<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-MAYORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY WIN GIVES COUNCILMAN LOCK ON BALTIMORE MAYORALTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ City Councilman Martin O'Malley, a 36-year-old
former prosecutor who has vowed to crack down on the city's
alarming wave of drug dealing and homicide, was elected Tuesday as
the Democratic mayoral nominee in a primary victory tantamount to
final election in this Democratic bastion.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley, who is white, won more than 50 percent of the vote in
defeating the two leading black candidates, Lawrence BellIII, the
City Council president, and Carl Stokes, a former councilman and
school board member. The two split much of the majority black vote
in this gritty, troubled city which, the candidates all emphasized,
has sadly missed out on the renaissance enjoyed by other major
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for diversity and a victory for
inclusiveness,'' O'Malley told a victory rally Tuesday night. All
about him, a happy throng of black and white political leaders
beamed at his strong showing among black voters and his
overwhelming margin of victory of close to 2-1 over Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to build a new Baltimore,'' O'Malley said as he
promised to work for ``those who dream of a new tomorrow for this
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Overtaking the field after a late decision to run, the
boyish-looking councilman prevailed in a raucous primary
competition. It featured 19 Democratic contenders, veiled charges
of racism and a political standoff that caused an 11th-hour shift
to the O'Malley banner by several leading black politicians. This
proved a critical blessing in a city that is 65 percent black and
90 percent Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   The vote meant that O'Malley, a tireless campaigner who visited
New York and other cities to underline Baltimore's deeply resistant
crime problems, is virtually certain to succeed Mayor Kurt Schmoke
in November as the city's 47th chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Elected and hailed 12 years ago as an urban visionary and the
city's first black mayor, Schmoke chose not to run again in the
face of Baltimore's continuing problems with middle-class flight,
crime, budget deficit and failing schools.
</P>
<P>
   The hopes of political and business leaders to draft Kweisi
Mfume, the former Baltimore congressman who is now the president of
the NAACP, as an overwhelming unity candidate failed when he
declined to run, and O'Malley entered a wide-open primary with no
clear leader until Tuesday night. The election turnout proved
strong, about 50 percent of the 294,000 registered voters in this
city of 675,000.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes, 49, finished second after several campaign stumbles,
including an erroneous claim of a college degree and an income tax
lien he had once settled. Bell saw his early front-runner status as
a 37-year-old leader of the black community fade in a series of
campaign gaffes including, at one point, his appeal for black votes
because ``I look like you.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican ballot, David Tufaro, 52, a developer and
lawyer, was the victorious mayoral nominee, defeating Carl Adair,
65, a public school teacher and Republican committeeman.
</P>
<P>
   With a virtual lock on the mayoralty in the November election,
the Democratic victor is expected to spend the next two months not
campaigning so much as appealing for unity and trying to heal the
civic wounds of the rugged primary contest. Voters faced a listless
bevy of candidates at first, 27 in all from both parties. The
Democratic candidates were winnowed to three main contenders by
Labor Day, with some bare-knuckled campaign tactics flashing about
the race.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley stuck doggedly to his anti-crime theme, asking why
Baltimore, which has more than 300 murders a year, could not enjoy
the same urban renaissance as New York and other rebounding cities.
In particular, he targeted the open-air drug markets as an affront
to the city and vowed a ``zero-tolerance'' criminal justice stance.
``We have to make our city safe,'' was his repeated message.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes, denouncing a ``zero-tolerance'' policy as basically
anti-minority, focused more on the failures in the city's schools,
which have the lowest test scores in the state. He promised smaller
class sizes and vowed to quickly generate renewal in the city's
neighborhoods, which lose about 1,000 working- and middle-class
residents each month to surrounding suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, a political tyro when he came up through neighborhood
organizations to win an underdog victory on the City Council and
then the council presidency, attacked O'Malley as a political
spoiler exploiting a divided black community. ``When he saw there
was a split vote, he leaped into the race,'' Bell said of O'Malley.
Their sharp-edged rivalry ended a once cooperative relationship on
the council in days when they were dubbed Batman and Robin for
their crime-fighting agenda.
</P>
<P>
   By early August, a group of black leaders led by a state General
Assembly delegate, Howard Rawlings, was disappointed by Bell and
Stokes as questions arose about their personal finances. The
leaders decided to cast their lot with O'Malley. ``It's not a
question of being the best black candidate or the best white
candidate,'' Rawlings announced, putting his record as a party
kingmaker on the line. ``O'Malley has a track record of empowering
black Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   After all the crossfire of the primary, O'Malley now has to
apply a fresh burst of resolve and energy to managing what the
departing Schmoke has wistfully dubbed ``the tale of the two
cities'' _ Baltimore's gleaming inner-harbor image of skyline
optimism and its back-street reality of deep neighborhood problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
