<SLUG> BC-GEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKFULLY, THESE ATHLETES COME ALONG ONLY ONCE A CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ESPN went to the expense the occasion deserved in
unveiling its list of the top 20 athletes of the 20th century on
Tuesday. Honorees were flown to New York for the ceremony, somebody
put on a record of dramatic orchestral music and lunch was served.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, this column is going to the expense the occasion
deserves in revealing its bottom 20 today. No airline tickets (our
honorees would miss the plane), no music (``Chopsticks'' is not
available on CD) and no meal (these guys might hurt themselves with
the forks.)
</P>
<P>
   Another difference between ESPN's top 20 and our bottom 20: They
consulted broadcasters, writers and sports scholars before making
their list. We asked the guy at the next desk.
</P>
<P>
   Arazi: ESPN was ridiculed for including three racehorses in its
top 100. But our list of the most hapless, star-crossed,
disappointing athletes would be incomplete without the overhyped
little colt from France who inspired Pimlico Race Course to build a
second press box to handle the Preakness media overflow. Arazi
finished eighth in the Kentucky Derby, never made it to Pimlico.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Benjamin: What he lacked in ability for the Clippers,
Lakers and six other teams, he made up for with lack of effort.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Brown: The often-injured (or so he thought) third baseman
begged out of the San Francisco Giants lineup one day because ``I
slept on my eye wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Buckner: We're listing them alphabetically. He also could
go under ``E.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Decker Slaney: Little Mary wailing in the arms of her
husband is the most pathetic sight in Olympic sports history.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Ford: Good football player, middling president, dangerous
golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Frazier: The heavyweight champion set the ``boxers are
athletes'' side of the argument back 10 years by nearly drowning in
``Superstars'' swimming competition.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gerkin: He went 0-12 _ despite a 3.62 ERA _ as a rookie
pitcher for the 1945 Philadelphia A's. But he wouldn't have made
our list if his name weren't Gerkin.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Kuiper: The anti-Aaron hit !ital!one home run in 3,379
at-bats for the Indians and Giants, and had a sense of humor about
it, posing for a trading-card photo with a splintered bat on his
shoulder. Had Kuiper played with the lively baseball of the '90s,
he might have hit two homers.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Lett: It must be the drugs: The Cowboys defensive lineman's
knack for committing more turnovers than he causes is all that
keeps earlier football boneheads Roy Riegels and Jim Marshall off
our list.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Merkle: As in ``Merkle's boner.'' The moral of the story is
that you should always touch second base, lest your name appear
alongside ``boner'' for the next 90 years.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Mendoza: The weak-hitting infielder is the namesake of the
``Mendoza line'' (.200, or .215 if you're going by his actual
career average). Now he's passing along his secrets to future
Angels as manager of Single-A Lake Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   Dan O'Brien: Commercialism and pole-vaulting at their worst. The
decathlete starred in those ``Dan and Dave'' shoe commercials
before the 1992 Olympics _ then failed to qualify for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   George Plimpton: Everybody on this list is a bad athlete in one
way or another. What sets Plimpton apart is the fact he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Powlus: The Notre Dame quarterback Beano Cook predicted
would win two Heisman Trophies fell two short. He was, after all,
no Gino Torretta.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ryun: Mary Decker with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry: ``You're wrong,'' Tom Lasorda told an
interviewer. ``Darryl Strawberry is not a dog. A dog is loyal and
runs hard after balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Marv Throneberry: The symbol of the 1962 Mets hit .244, led the
National League's first basemen with 17 errors, then held out for a
bigger contract. The Mets shipped him to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Wadkins: He and brother Lanny began the 1999 season with
21 PGA Tour victories between them. Lanny had 21 while Bobby was
winless in 702 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Wepner: The heavyweight known as ``the Bayonne Bleeder''
once said: ``I was 6-foot-1 when I started boxing, but with all the
uppercuts I'm up to 6-5.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN, too, gave out its list in alphabetical order: Hank Aaron,
Muhammad Ali, Jim Brown, Wilt Chamberlain, Ty Cobb, Babe Didrikson
Zaharias, Wayne Gretzky, Magic Johnson, Michael Jordan, Carl Lewis,
Joe Louis, Willie Mays, Martina Navratilova, Jack Nicklaus, Jesse
Owens, Jackie Robinson, Bill Russell, Babe Ruth, Jim Thorpe and Ted
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The exact ranking of the ESPN top 20 _ and the answer to ``Who's
No. 1?'' _ will be revealed as the network's weekly biographies
continue.
</P>
<P>
   As for our bottom 20, we have no plans to rank them. We've spent
just about long enough on them already.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
