<HEADER>
A2418 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-JOHNSON-     09-15 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-JOHNSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ The buzz began late last fall when Texas A&AMP;M
coach R.C. Slocum, who feels the same way about hyping players as
he does about using Grecian Formula, dropped the first bomb about
wide receiver Bethel Johnson.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnson was ineligible last season as an academic partial
qualifier, but Slocum had seen him enough in practice to say he had
a chance to be the best Aggies wide receiver in the 26 seasons
Slocum has been at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters checked and double-checked the tapes to make sure they
had heard Slocum correctly, talking this way about a player who had
yet to participate in a game. They had.
</P>
<P>
   During the spring and summer, Slocum said the Aggies were going
to be more proficient passing the ball. The reason, he said, was
that the receiving corps was the best he had ever had. The
implication was that Johnson, a 6-0, 190-pound ball of speed, would
make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   One game into his collegiate career, Johnson has done nothing to
dispel that enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   In the Aggies' season-opening 37-17 win over Louisiana Tech,
Johnson had four catches for 106 yards and one touchdown. He caught
bombs for 46 and 33 yards, turned a hitch-and-go pattern into a
15-yard gain, and leaped to grab a 12-yard touchdown pass in the
corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Johnson was not at full strength after suffering a
stress fracture in his foot during summer practice and then
straining his hamstring the week before the opener, he will be
worth watching when the Aggies host Tulsa on Saturday night in
their home opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did on the field what I had seen in practice,'' said
Slocum. ``He's the kind of receiver who can make a quarterback look
good. Quarterbacks love a guy who can turn a hitch pattern into 15
or 40 yards, a guy who can leap and make the great catch. He can
sky and get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Aggies quarterback Randy McCown, who also raved after watching
Johnson practice last season, concurs. McCown was 17-of-28 against
Louisiana Tech, setting career bests for completions and yardage
(252).
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to throw it right on the money for him to catch
it,'' said McCown. ``He's a lot like (Minnesota Vikings receiver)
Randy Moss in that he can go up and make the play. With that speed,
he (Johnson) is a tough guy to overthrow. You'd have to have a
stiff wind at your back.''
</P>
<P>
   The question that begs to be asked is why Johnson, who moved
from running back to wide receiver midway through his junior year
at Corsicana High School, elected to attend Texas A&AMP;M. Under
Slocum, the Aggies have built a reputation as a team that throws
only when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were recruiting me, they pretty much came to me
straight,'' he said. ``I knew that this wasn't a passing school,
but they were telling me that coach (Steve) Kragthorpe was the new
offensive coordinator, and he was the wide receivers coach, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I didn't want to go to A&AMP;M, because I just thought
they would run the ball. But then I got to thinking, `If he's the
wide receivers coach and the offensive coordinator, there's a
pretty good chance he's going to be passing the ball.'''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is at once brash and humble. He said he was disappointed
in his first-game effort against Louisiana Tech because ``after I
watched films, I thought the catches I made should have been
touchdowns. I know it's different from high school, but in high
school those were touchdowns. I hate falling down (being tackled)
after a catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has picked the role model of role models for wide
receivers _ San Francisco's Jerry Rice. The main reason, says
Johnson, is that Rice's work ethic is something he would like to
emulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got this Jerry Rice film, and I watch it like every other
day for inspiration,'' said Johnson. ``He practices real hard, and
sometimes I tend to be lazy. Then I start thinking about the film.
It's like, `Jerry Rice wouldn't do this.' He works extra hard to
stay a step ahead of everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where the Aggies believe Johnson will be in the weeks and
years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got big-play capabilities,'' said senior running back
Dante Hall. ``The way he was running past the defensive backs in
practice (last year) caught your attention. We couldn't wait for
him to do it in the game. Now, it's just a matter of execution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
