<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIES HIT DOTEL, BEAT METS, 7-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Bobby Valentine made it perfectly clear before this
game as to what he had advised his rookie starter, Octavio Dotel,
to do differently in his first outing in the nightmarish
environment of Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' Valentine said. ``I would not like to see him
change for the ballpark. You have to go with your strength.''
</P>
<P>
   That hands-off approach did not work for Dotel and the Mets
Tuesday night in a 7-2 loss to the Colorado Rockies. Dotel, whose
season has otherwise been so impressive that he is almost sure to
remain in the Mets' rotation when it is pared down for the final
two weeks of the season, was hit hard by the Rockies and victimized
by the thin air and remarkable carry of fly balls at the park. He
gave up six runs on seven hits _ there were consecutive home runs
that looked like routine fly balls by Vinny Castilla and Edgard
Clemente in the third and a total of six extra-base hits _ in only
three innings.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat could have been worse for the Mets. Cincinnati lost
to the Chicago Cubs, 4-3, so the Mets remained two and a half games
ahead of the Reds in the wild-card race. Meanwhile, the Mets
dropped a game and a half behind Atlanta in the National League
East, with the Braves playing later in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   This was not Dotel's worst start in his still brief tenure with
the Mets, although it ended a streak of seven consecutive winning
decisions for the right-hander. He was hit harder and had less
control against the Cubs at Wrigley Field in July. But in recent
starts, Dotel (7-2) had been superb. In his last three starts, he
had given up just five earned runs on 13 hits in 20 innings and
beaten two potential playoff opponents _ Arizona and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, he walked just two, but he left several pitches
up in the strike zone, prime territory for Colorado batters to put
the ball in the air and watch it fly. If there was any good to come
from this outing, it was that Dotel's early exit afforded Bobby
Jones to make his debut as a long reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who had a 3-3 record with a 5.81 earned run average this
season, had not pitched since May 22, when he began to suffer from
tendinitis in his right shoulder. He went on the disabled list, and
when he came off in August and began a rehabilitation assignment,
he was diagnosed with bursitis in the shoulder as well.
</P>
<P>
   There was gloomy talk that Jones might be finished for the
season to rest the shoulder and that if the pain persisted when he
tried to throw, he could need off-season surgery to clean out the
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he continued pain-free with his rehabilitation and was
activated in Los Angeles. Barring cataclysmic injuries to the
rotation, Jones will not be a starter again this season, a
situation he seems content with for now.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Jones gave a glimpse of the pitcher he could be
again next season. He had entered the game with a dismal record at
Coors, having allowed 25 earned runs in 24 1/3 innings here. But in
his first relief effort as a professional, he retired the side in
the fourth, allowed only a single in the fifth and did not give up
a run _ on Neifi Perez's second triple of the night, to drive in
Ben Petrick _ until the sixth, his final inning.
</P>
<P>
   In three innings, he allowed one run, three hits and no walks,
while striking out three.
</P>
<P>
   That was the best part of the game for the Mets in what was an
otherwise sleepy effort. Colorado's starter, Jamey Wright, had
spent the summer in Class AAA before being recalled Aug. 2. He shut
down the Mets on only three hits through six innings, assisted by a
third-inning pickoff of Rickey Henderson. Only three times did
Wright allow runners to get into scoring position before the
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets finally threatened in the seventh when Roger Cedeno
walked and later scored on a single by Luis Lopez, who had been
inserted in the bottom of the fourth at shortstop in place of Rey
Ordonez, who has gone 2 for 22 on this road trip. Jay Payton, who
pinch-hit for Jones and remained in the game, had singled and gone
to second on Lopez's hit.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Henderson came to the plate. The count went full
and the Mets seemed ready to continue the rally. But living
dangerously, Valentine sent the runners. Henderson struck out and
Petrick threw Payton out easily at third for an inning-ending
double play.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine recently said that he never gives up in a game. But
even he conceded Tuesday night. For the bottom of the eighth
inning, Valentine put in the Class AAA call-ups Melvin Mora at
second and Jorge Toca at first. Todd Pratt replaced Mike Piazza as
catcher. The infield had not one regular starter remaining, a sure
sign that Valentine was not counting on any late-game rallies by
his team.
</P>
</TEXT>
