<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2424 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-FLOYD-ART-2     09-15 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-FLOYD-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FLORIDA AND SOUTHEAST, UNCERTAINTY AND ANXIETY AS HURRICANE
APPROACHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 14th graf re traffic jam in Charleston, S.C.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(With HURRICANE-OUTLOOK and related stories) 
(mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRITT ISLAND, Fla. _ After days of worry and preparation, with
much of the state's eastern coast boarded up and deserted, people
here in Florida braced for the arrival Wednesday morning of massive
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as the hurricane's outer bands began to buffet the
state's east-central barrier islands after dark, forecasters were
still unsure if the deadly eye of the Category 4 storm would make
landfall, perhaps around Cape Canaveral, or if the storm center
would only skirt the state before turning north to threaten Georgia
and the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists said that, as they had cautiously forecast, Floyd
seemed to be turning more to the north, good news for Florida. But
even if the storm's eye, with winds of around 150 mph, did not come
ashore, meteorologists predicted that hurricane-force winds would
still extend into the state, strong enough to blow roofs off
houses, fell walls and topple trees.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, more than half a million people were on the move as
authorities ordered the evacuation of Savannah and low-lying
counties. In South Carolina, 800,000 people were ordered to leave
coastal areas, and even North Carolina declared a state of
emergency and urged residents of outlying islands to seek shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Max Mayfield, the deputy director of the National Hurricane
Center in Miami, said Tuesday night that the most recent prediction
put the direction of the storm more toward the north, making
landfall more likely in Georgia or the Carolinas. He also said that
the storm had weakened, but warned against making too much of that.
``It's the difference between being hit by a semi and being hit by
a freight train,'' Mayfield said.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, President Clinton on Tuesday issued an
unusual pre-emptive declaration of disaster for the state, even
before the first palm tree had been pushed down.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, James Witt, the federal official in charge of the
storm relief efforts, said Tuesday night that the exodus of
residents from the coastal areas was one of the largest evacuations
ever conducted in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why Clinton had declared Florida and Georgia disaster
areas even before the storm reached land, Witt said, ``The massive
evacuation is almost a disaster in itself,'' with its needs of
shelter, food and medical care for the thousands of people who left
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center in
Miami, warned that the northward jaunt of the storm probably came
too late to spare the east-central coast from what is still a
dangerous storm. One meteorologist predicted a ``weed-eater
effect'' as winds churn up the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd howled through the Bahamas Tuesday, knocking out power,
wrecking boats, knocking down trees and damaging houses, but damage
was not as bad as expected, according to e-mails from residents
there.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, more than 1 million people evacuated the east coast
on Monday and Tuesday, and as of Tuesday evening thousands were
still stranded in unmoving traffic on a variety of interstates and
toll roads. Interstate 4, Toll Road 528, U.S. 1 and other routes
were more like parking lots much of the day, as people fled inland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to get the hell out,'' said Stephen Collins, who lives on
Merritt Island, between Cape Canaveral and Cocoa Beach, as he
gassed up his car at a convenience store on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the store's manager, A.K. Patel, put up hurricane
shutters and prepared to leave. ``I've got two kids,'' he said.
``We're scared.''
</P>
<P>
   In Charleston, S.C., where memories remain vivid from Hurricane
Hugo, which devastated the South Carolina low country 10 years ago,
a mandatory evacuation turned into an unthinkable traffic debacle
as state officials waited until late Tuesday evening to open the
eastbound lane of Interstate 26 to westbound traffic. Although the
evacuation order came at midday, police did not reverse the
eastbound lane on the primary westbound escape route until after 10
p.m., leaving tens of thousands of cars at a standstill for hours.
</P>
<P>
   All along the central Florida coast, waves were already chewing
into the beaches and washing over sea walls, but as dark fell the
worst of the storm was still miles off shore.
</P>
<P>
   Most people were long gone, and towns up and down the beach were
quiet and boarded-up. A few people made last-minute runs to the few
open stores for essentials.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Rich is staying. After boarding up her own windows in
Melbourne, she made a trip to the store for provisions: a case of
Corona beer, a 12-pack of Pepsi and a carton of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how long we're going to be trapped,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not just highway traffic that snarled here. Floyd closed
most of the state's airports, leaving passengers stranded and
upsetting flight schedules around the country.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   State officials said that decisions made as early as Monday to
evacuate coastal areas were wise ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local governments did the right thing by asking for
evacuations early enough,'' said Gov. Jeb Bush. ``Floridians have
responded in the proper way.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than 1 million people ordered to evacuate their homes
in coastal Florida, hundreds of thousands spent the night inland
wherever they could find a bed. The more fortunate, and more
wealthy, filled hotel rooms in Orlando and other inland cities, and
some drove as far the west coast, to Naples, Fort Myers and the
Tampa Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands filled high school gymnasiums, auditoriums and
churches, spending a miserable night on the floor or in folding
chairs. In Belle Glade, about 40 miles west of Palm Beach, more
than 500 people packed the auditorium of Glades Central High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all by myself with my four kids, and I was scared,''
said Pearlie Hill, 33, who abandoned her mobile home in this mostly
poor farming community for the stronger walls of the school. ``We
had no safe place to be. We all learned in school about the 1928
hurricane, so hurricanes scare us around these parts.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, a hurricane crashed through Palm Beach County, flooded
the farm towns around Lake Okeechobee and killed nearly 2,000
people, most of them poor farm workers. Some 1,000 were buried in a
mass grave in a cemetery in Canal Point.
</P>
<P>
   Missoura Philpart, 49, brought her family of eight to the
shelter. ``My grandmama had to climb to the top of her roof when
that hurricane hit in 1928,'' she said. ``I was raised to fear
hurricanes.''
</P>
<P>
   To the east in Palm Beach County on Tuesday, the usually busy
Federal Highway was mostly quiet as the sun set and Floyd, finally,
began to blow into the state. The strip malls, their storefronts
covered over with plywood, were almost empty of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Loony, a mail carrier, tried to keep his Postal Service
jeep from being blown off the road by wind gusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we're the only ones who had to work today,''
Loony said, before moving on with his baskets of mail, a real-life
example of that old slogan about neither rain nor sleet nor dark of
night. He did not seem pleased.
</P>
<P>
   But others were looking ahead for the possible consequences and
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Witt, the director of the Federal Emergency
Management Agency, said that the cost of caring for the evacuated
people was going to be very great regardless of damage to the
coastal areas. One example he gave was the cost of calling up 2,000
members of the South Carolina National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   There were other costs that ordinarily do not come to mind, he
said, giving as an example warnings that he received from Southern
governors that ``they're right in the middle of harvesting cotton,
and it could have a devastating effect.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Boca Raton, as in other parts of Florida, the time for
preparation was past, and people hoped the forecasters' prediction
that the worst of the storm would go north of them, was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   As the night wore on, it looked as if that was exactly what had
happened, and people here were grateful that lashing rain and winds
of 70 mph were the worst they saw of Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, I had this awful pit in my stomach,'' said Charles
Miehz, a retiree who lives in Boca Raton. As he, and many others
here, had watched the massive storm creep across his television
screen, it seemed as if it would swallow the whole state. But, as
the worst of the storm passed farther north, he finally took a safe
breath.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same in Miami, where Tiffany Zadi, a student at the
University of Miami, stayed up late at her parents' house in Cutler
Ridge, praying that the storm would pass Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `Thank God,''' said Miss Zadi, who, along with her
parents, rode out Hurricane Andrew in their Cutler Ridge home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricane Andrew was a nightmare,'' she said. And Floyd seemed
so much bigger, so much more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane warning that went into effect Monday night in
Miami was lifted late Tuesday afternoon, allowing people to leave
emergency shelters and return to their homes. Mayor Alex Penelas
announced late Tuesday that schools and government offices would
reopen Wednesday, and that city services would resume normal
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   For some people, the best preparation they could think of was to
go for a swim. On Miami Beach's South Beach, a half-dozen hardy
souls dove into the waves at midday, while dozens of other braved a
hazy, gritty wind to watch them. John Tedesco, who lives in Miami
Beach, had already been there twice for nighttime swims.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a little bit of fear you're going to get pulled
out,'' he said. ``You got to know your limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Becker, Tedesco's girlfriend, knew hers. She stayed on
shore, watching him like a sailor's wife perched in the widow's
watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's nuts, I tell you,'' she said. ``He likes the rush of it.
And my heart stops.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, Juan Andrada stood and took it all in.
Bare-chested and with a leathery tan, he was almost meditative as
he beheld the ocean. For 30 years, he worked as a steward on cruise
ships, including the Queen Elizabeth II. He was happy just to watch
what he knew could be a wicked, unforgiving sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always an attraction to the sea,'' he said. ``I can
see what people don't know. I have respect for the sea. I'm not
going in it. I know the force of the sea. Other people don't. There
is wind and water. That is electricity. For me, this is a great
miracle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
