<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2428 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING-     09-15 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL WITH NEW LIMITS ON CAMPAIGN DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Updating and rewriting throughout to reflect House approval of
bill)   (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defying the Republican leadership, the House late
Tuesday night voted for the second year in a row to limit the
influence of money in politics and overhaul the way the nation's
political campaigns are financed.
</P>
<P>
   The 252-177 vote in favor of legislation sponsored by Reps.
Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass., was nearly
identical to last year's vote, as House members for both parties
complained that the money pouring into politics was fueling public
cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four Republicans split from their party to back the bill,
while 13 Democrats broke party lines to vote against it.
</P>
<P>
   But in a slap at Hillary Rodham Clinton, the House by a vote of
261-167 added to the bill a provision that would require the first
lady to reimburse the federal government for any transportation
costs she incurs in her expected Senate bid in New York. Forty-six
Democrats voted for the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over campaign financing now moves to the Senate,
where the bill to ban the unlimited and unregulated ``soft money''
donations to the national political parties drew a majority of 52
votes last year. But the legislation then died in a Republican-led
filibuster. Opponents have vowed to kill it once again when it
comes to the floor in October, and its proponents face an uphill
struggle in finding the extra votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that there are the votes to pass any bill this
year in the Senate,'' said Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles on
Tuesday. ``Right now, there's no consensus pulling together.''
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is volatile and Shays predicted that the
legislation could yet pass before the 106th Congress ends in 2000
if its Senate supporters are adamant. ``We are going to ask the
Senate to do what they did during the civil rights days,'' he said.
``We are going to ask the proponents of campaign finance to force
the opponents of campaign finance reform, a minority in the Senate,
to have to filibuster continually to prevent a fair vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on Tuesday clashed repeatedly over whether the influx
of money into campaigns was corrupting Congress or whether it was
essential to free political speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reach and influence of special interests have grown out of
control,'' said Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., one of numerous
Republicans to buck their leadership and support the bipartisan
bill. ``As a consequence, people believe their elected officials
are bought and paid for.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., insisted that the legislation could
not face constitutional muster. ``It tromps all over people's
individual First Amendment freedoms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton this week called upon the House to approve the
bipartisan bill, saying it would ``revitalize the political process
by curbing the role of special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The House debate came as a new campaign season was already well
underway and promising to be the most costly yet.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side of the presidential campaign, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, who has amassed an enormous $50 million campaign
fund, has already declared that he will not accept federal matching
funds. Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher, is also
forgoing federal funds. Those decisions leave both men unrestricted
by a $40 million spending limit that applies to candidates who
accept matching funds in the primaries, a cap that was a bulwark of
the post Watergate campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the chief Republican sponsor of the
Senate legislation to ban soft money, has put his crusade at the
center of his own uphill bid for the Republican presidential
nomination. He has called the current campaign system ``an
elaborate influence peddling scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Democrat Bill Bradley has pledged that he
would refuse soft money in 2000 if the Republicans would also do
so, saying big money is at the root of multiple problems in U.S.
politics. Vice President Al Gore supports legislation to ban soft
money.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan legislation would not raise the current
donation limit of $1,000 per candidate in the presidential race.
Instead, it would ban so-called ``soft money,'' the unlimited and
unregulated donations to political parties that both parties have
used to circumvent the limits on contributions to individual
candidates that were enacted in the wake of Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   It would also curb the increasingly popular practice by
independent advocacy groups of running advertisements that purport
to explain an issues but are thinly veiled campaign commercials
attacking or supporting a candidate. The bill would more strictly
regulate such advertisements in the 60 days before an election. And
it would raise the total limit on individual campaign contributions
from $25,000 to $30,000 each year.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The question of how to overhaul the campaign finance system took
on new resonance after the 1996 campaign, in which Clinton
aggressively used access to the White House to raise money. Both
parties found ways to use television commercials that stopped just
short of promoting a candidate to get around federal spending
limits. And the Democratic National Committee gave back several
million dollars in donations after disclosures that the money had
come from foreign nationals or was of questionable legality.
</P>
<P>
   But despite holding a series of high profile hearings into the
1996 abuses, the Republican leaders in Congress have staunchly
opposed the move to ban soft-money, arguing publicly that it would
weaken political parties and harm free speech.
</P>
<P>
   This summer in a closed door meeting for House Republicans,
party leaders were more blunt. Republicans said their party
chairman, Jim Nicholson, and Rep. Thomas Davis, R-Va., of Virginia,
who is head of the House Republicans' re-election effort, told
lawmakers that their party held a $39.9 million advantage in soft
money in the 1997-1998 election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Through a long day and into the night, House members argued over
the money chase that they have come to know so well.
</P>
<P>
   Shays insisted his legislation would close loopholes that had
come over time come to erode long-standing fund-raising
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about ending corrupt politics,'' he said, ''that's what
it's about. It has been against the law since 1907 for corporate
treasury money to be used in campaigns. But it happens. It's been
against the law since 1947 for union dues money to be used in
campaigns. But it's happening. It's been against the law since 1974
for foreign nationals to contribute to campaigns. But they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill said its restrictions on issue advocacy
infringed on the First Amendment. ``Free speech, particularly free
political speech, is a cherished right and shrine in the First
Amendment to our Constitution,'' said Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif.
``For democracy to flourish, a free people must be able to express
their political views without government restriction.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt accused the Republican
majority of being in the sway of special interests on issues
ranging from health care to tax cuts to gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all seen what being bound to big money from the
special interests has done to the Republican legislative agenda,''
Gephardt said. ``Republican leaders put the needs of powerful
lobbyists ahead of the average family and their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, for their part, charged that the issue advocacy
restrictions would particularly disadvantage conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan legislation approved by the House was pitted
against three rival bills and 10 amendments.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The first signs that Shays and Meehan would prevail came when
they handily defeated a series of amendments that they had called
``poison pills'' designed to splinter their ranks and weaken their
legislation. Among the defeated amendments were ones to raise
contribution limits and to exempt from regulation advertisements on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The House, however, did pass, several amendments, including one
that was all about the New York Senate race. Sponsored by Rep. John
Sweeney, R-N.Y., with Mrs. Clinton in mind, it would require ``a
candidate for election for federal office (other than a candidate
who holds federal office)'' to reimburse the government for federal
transportation used for campaign purposes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sweeney said his measure ``remedies an unfair advantage.'' But
Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., called the measure ``a mean-spirited
petty politically charged amendment.'' Democratic leaders said the
amendment would never become law and that they did not consider it
significant enough for their party to withdraw their support from
the overall bill.
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday night also defeated three rival campaign
finance measures that could have been used to trump the bipartisan
legislation. One would have eliminated all federal contributions
limits, eliminated public financing of campaigns and required
immediate disclosure of contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Another would have banned soft money donations to the national
political parties but not to the state parties. A third proposal
would have strengthened the powers of the Federal Election
Commission. Shays and Meehan were fighting it on grounds that its
passage and would supersede and thus kill their own measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
