<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2433 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-THREAT-HNS &LR;      09-15 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-THREAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS FLEE COASTS OF FLORIDA TO VIRGINIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
and TERRY KLIEWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Fla. _ Millions of people from Virginia to Florida
were ordered inland Tuesday as Hurricane Floyd, one of the
strongest and potentially most destructive storms to threaten the
United States in decades, bore down on the southeast Atlantic
coast.
</P>
<P>
   With winds pushing 140 mph and the storm a monstrous 600 miles
wide, authorities from the tip of the Florida peninsula to Cape
Charles, Va., urged coastal residents to evacuate. Clogged highways
and emptied towns up and down the seaboard indicated the warnings
were being heeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest evacuation that has ever been done in the
face of a hurricane,'' said Federal Emergency Management Agency
Director James Lee Witt. Estimates placed the number of people on
the move at 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   In both size and intensity, Floyd, a Category 4 hurricane, ranks
as one of the mightiest storms ever to threaten the coast of the
United States. Hurricane Andrew, which caused $25 billion in damage
and killed 40 people in South Florida in 1992, also was a Category
4 storm, but it was significantly smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters could not say with any certainty where or when Floyd
might make landfall, but computer models showed the storm running
parallel to the Florida coast Wednesday, with the eye a few miles
offshore, and a possible landfall later in the week in Georgia or
the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this thing parallels us, it could act like a weed-eater
going up the coast,'' Craig Fugate of the Florida Emergency
Operations Center told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   NASA meteorologists, wary of the threat to the space agency's
shuttle fleet parked in hangars at the coastal Kennedy Space
Center, predicted the eye of the storm would be 30 to 40 miles due
east of the center Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane-force winds extend up to 125 miles from the center of
the storm and tropical-storm-force winds reach out for at least 200
miles. A storm surge of 5-10 feet above normal tide was expected as
Floyd nears the Florida coast; higher levels could be expected if
it approaches the coasts of Georgia or South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the possibility of severe damage along the Florida
and Georgia shores, President Clinton ``declared an emergency
exists'' in those states and ordered federal aid ``to supplement
state and local recovery efforts,'' the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   And even before the storm hit, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush on Tuesday
requested $7 billion in federal disaster assistance for his state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was ending an overseas trip to New Zealand,
returned to Washington to ``oversee the federal response.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, preparations Tuesday concentrated on
evacuating people from the most vulnerable areas. Traffic slowed to
a crawl on Florida's major highways.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1.2 million coastal residents from Miami's northern
suburbs to Jacksonville vacated their homes and businesses. The
migration topped the previous high of 800,000 ordered during
Hurricane Elena in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are heeding the warning and moving out,'' said Janet
Dennis, a spokeswoman in the state's division of emergency
management in Tallahassee. ``Our highways are packed with folks
moving very slowly, but they are getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   The normal three-hour commute from Jacksonville to Tampa took
twice as long on Tuesday as rain began to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters favored a course that would bring the powerful storm
close to the central Florida shoreline before it curved toward
Georgia. But there was no guarantee the storm would not make
landfall in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general reaction from folks here who have dealt with a
number of hurricanes is that this is a particularly bad
situation,'' Dennis said. ``Whether it comes in or rolls up the
coast line, there will be awful damage. I can't really say which
will be worse or better.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, which looked Tuesday like it might be spared the
worst, people who had sought refuge in shelters began to drift
home, although a substantial number opted to remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going well in our shelters,'' Miami Mayor Alex
Penales said.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, authorities ordered 500,000 people to evacuate six
coastal counties. A similar order covered 800,000 people in South
Carolina, a week shy of the 10th anniversary of Hurricane Hugo's
destructive run there.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, residents were urged to evacuate outlying
islands on the Outer Banks, and Gov. Jim Hunt declared a state of
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of evacuees prompted the American Red Cross to open
163 shelters in the three states _ 64 in Florida, six in Georgia
and 93 in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to meet the needs of the evacuees and to
provide them with the care they need to ride out'' the storm, said
Dr. Bernadine Healy, president of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Healy said 70 emergency response vehicles have been deployed
from southeastern states to the Red Cross staging area in Atlanta.
Another 48 are on standby.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Healy, whose agency manages about half the nation's
blood supply, issued a plea for donors to replenish stocks that
normally decline after the Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will ensure that the Red Cross and other blood centers
have an adequate supply for hospitals should they receive an influx
of patients because of the hurricane,'' Healy said.
</P>
<P>
   In Savannah, Ga., officials ordered thousands of people to
evacuate the historic city. They expressed concern that the city,
with its antebellum mansions and mature oaks, would not fare well
from a direct hit.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere along the Eastern Seaboard, the U.S. military began
moving ships, aircraft and personnel out of Floyd's path.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Rear Adm. Craig Quigley said more than 4,000
National Guardsmen were assigned to help with the evacuation and to
provide security for areas abandoned by residents.
</P>
<P>
   NASA could only hope for the best at the Kennedy Space Center,
where forecasters said the storm could pass 30 miles to the east
with winds in excess of 130 mph. The seaside launch pads, at nine
feet above sea level, could be threatened by the storm surge. The
space agency's four shuttles and international space station
components worth hundreds of millions of dollars were secured in
hangars vulnerable to Category 4 winds. Eighty personnel were
prepared to ride out the storm at Kennedy. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Disney World, for the first time in its 28-year history, shut
its doors Tuesday and will not reopen until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
