<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2439 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-RONSTADT-AZR &LR;      09-15 1570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RONSTADT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINDA RON STADT, EMMY LOU HARRIS MAKE MAGIC ON RECORD, ON STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY RODGERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When the owners of two of popular music's most
distinctive female voices decided to finally record an album
together, they wound up in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ronstadt has deep roots in Tucson, and she had little
trouble luring close friend Emmylou Harris away from Nashville for
a five-week stay at the historic Arizona Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Transforming the library of one of the larger buildings at the
inn into a recording studio, the pair soaked up the atmosphere of
Tucson's oldest resort and crafted a magical album, Western Wall:
The Tucson Sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Inn is one of the last vestiges of what Tucson was
when I was a child growing up,'' said Ronstadt in a recent call
from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually stayed in the house that was built by the owner of
the inn ... (the part) that she built for herself, which is now
part of the inn which they rent out. It's a lovely house with seven
bedrooms and two stories and a nice library, which is where we
wound up singing.''
</P>
<P>
   While road veteran Harris and the session musicians stayed at
the central Tucson resort in September 1998, Ronstadt _ who is
raising her two adopted children in the city _ commuted from her
nearby home.
</P>
<P>
   The inn's homey surroundings had a calming effect on both
artists, who have recorded scores of albums since the late '60s _
many in traditional studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about being in a house (to record),'' Harris
said in a call, also from New York. ``There's something about the
`living room thing' that everybody talks about.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronstadt enjoyed curling up in the 1930 inn's library between
takes ``because they have a lot of good books, and I always read
when I'm recording.''
</P>
<P>
   In their remarkable recording careers and away from the studio,
Ronstadt and Harris have been studies in both parallel and
contrast.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to possessing striking voices and physical
presences, both helped blaze the trail for today's Sheryl Crows and
Sarah McLachlans by leading bands in the male-dominated music
industry of the '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Ronstadt and Harris have refused to be pigeonholed into musical
niches, instead challenging themselves with forays into new
territories.
</P>
<P>
   Their strong musical personalities helped forge a deep
friendship in the early '70s, when Ronstadt was recording wildly
popular rock albums and Harris was growing her country roots with
Gram Parsons and, later, her Hot Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to develop that sort of comrade thing that
happens when people are experiencing something that is (done by) a
relatively small part of the population,'' Harris recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't a whole lot of female singers going out there
and fronting bands. ... There's more now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think we're a strange breed in the fact that for the
most part we're interpreters in a kind of world of
singer-songwriters. And so we have a real appreciation for the song
and for finding songs.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two have developed starkly different approaches to
performing and touring as their careers progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pair's current tour to support Western Wall,
Ronstadt declares, ``I've basically quit performing. I didn't
announce it particularly _ I just decided I didn't want to do it
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Raising her children, ages 5 and 8, is clearly Ronstadt's
priority:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I just stay home, and I'm a mom. And I love it. It's
harder work than anything I ever did before, that's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel that there's just no room for negotiating here.
This is what I have to do. I don't think you can leave children and
have them turn out OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, meanwhile, has developed a passion for performing and
traveling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love performing, I love singing for people. I'd like to say
it's not an ego thing ... but just the process of connecting to
people with those songs. And, of course, I've always had fantastic
bands, and I love being around these people and hearing what they
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said her friend realized they'd need to tour in support
of Western Wall: ``She (Ronstadt) understands that you have to give
the record company a fighting chance and loves the fact it would be
the two of us together, and it would be fun _ that it's not just
being out there all on your own.''
</P>
<P>
   On their current concert tour, the two are performing the entire
album, as well as some hits from their Grammy-winning solo careers.
</P>
<P>
   Western Wall features an eclectic mix of songs by artists such
as Jackson Browne, Bruce Springsteen, Sinead O'Connor and Leonard
Cohen. Harris had a hand in writing three of the tracks, including
the offbeat single Sweet Spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to do a project together before we recorded the
last Trio record (with Dolly Parton) _ that was about six years
ago,'' Ronstadt recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmy had started out sending tapes to me and we started
talking about material. ... At some point, we decided to call Dolly
to see if she wanted to guest with us, and she said let's do
another Trio record.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that was the last thing that postponed our duet record. ...
So we waited until now, and then, oddly enough, as we started
planning this record, it became possible for the Trio record to
come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally said it's now or never _ we can't wait for the
planets to line up ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters, Ronstadt caught the flu and was hit by
laryngitis as the Tucson sessions got under way. Many of her vocals
were added late in the process, while Harris relished the chance to
do most of her singing live with four talented session musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Ronstadt _ who has ventured far from her country-rock roots to
explore Spanish music, Nelson Riddle-arranged standards and
operetta with Pirates of Penzance _ unexpectedly returned to her
early sound with the toe-tapping new number He Was Mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to craft a vocal that I hadn't used ... in years. I was
really surprised that it came in, but it did. It's something that I
kind of knew instinctively _ I think it's just from listening to so
many Merle Haggard records.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who charted new territory in 1995 with her complex
Wrecking Ball album, enjoyed creating a ``left-footed, slightly
twisted'' album with Ronstadt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet Spot is one of the oddest songs I've ever recorded _ and
I wrote it, with Jill (Cunniff of Luscious Jackson). But the whole
thing that Jill brought to it was so different than where I'm
coming from musically and rhythmically.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she enjoyed being close to home for the Western Wall
sessions, Ronstadt, 53, sounds disheartened when she talks about
her native state and the desert she loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a heartbreaking thing for me because, of course, the
developers have come in and just destroyed it. It's an area that
should never have a high population because it's desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very beautiful. As soon as you mow it down and put up
those horrible tinkertoy houses that they build. ... All they're
doing is building slums, because those houses are going to degrade
so fast in the desert.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronstadt adds, ``They're building in such a way that prevents
community. I live right in the middle of town. I didn't buy into
that suburban thing, never have. And there still is a community in
the center of town if we can just hold out against the City
Council, which is trying to put a freeway through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Municipal government in Tucson is just mind-bendingly
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, Ronstadt is bent on making sure that her children
don't grow up stupid. She has banned television and computers from
her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television and computers are destroying nuclear families,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even like to let them (children) go and see movies. I
think that the media has such an extraordinary influence. Children
are very impressionable, and I think we're developing a whole
generation of borderline personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody should take their televisions out and break
them. It's not enough to turn them off.''
</P>
<P>
   She later lightens up, laughing: ``They'll (her kids) probably
grow up to be ax murderers, but I don't have a television in my
house and they still get too much (at other people's homes).''
</P>
<P>
   For Harris, 52, a major concern is what she calls a loss of
originality on modern country radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that it's a shame, considering how much great
music there is out there, that the country format has become so
homogenized to the point that there's hardly anything recognizable
from where it started.
</P>
<P>
   ``And music should not stay the same. ... But certainly if you
have people like Gillian Welch and Lucinda Williams and Steve Earle
_ and even the Trio didn't get any airplay or very little.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil Young could be played on country radio _ Bruce
Springsteen, not to mention a lot of the younger artists that are
coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I always believe there's hope ... and you're not going to
stop the creative spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   As Harris looks ahead to a new solo album and Ronstadt prepares
to produce a record spotlighting glass instruments from the past
three centuries, their listeners no doubt hope that Western Wall
was not a once-in-a-lifetime experience. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Larry Rodgers can be reached at (602) 444-8043 or at
larry.rodgers(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
