<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES, DOWN BY 5, COME BACK TO BEAT TORONTO, 10-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The grieving began in the Yankees' dugout in the
seventh inning Tuesday night, after Toronto assumed a 6-1 lead.
Looks like another loss, some of them thought. There were glances
at the one-sided Boston result on the scoreboard. Looks as if the
Red Sox will gain another game in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few appreciative comments when Ricky Ledee made a
scrappy base-running play in the eighth inning. Way to hustle,
Ricky, with the rest unspoken: Way to hustle when we're getting
killed. But then Chuck Knoblauch walked and Derek Jeter singled and
soon the Yankees were back to believing anything is possible for
them, even the seemingly impossible. Bernie Williams capped the
five-run rally in the eighth with a game-tying grand slam, and Paul
O'Neill ripped a grand slam the very next inning and the Yankees
won, 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   That broke the Yankees' four-game losing streak and maintained
their three-and-a-half-game lead in the American League East;
Boston defeated Cleveland, 12-3.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Yankees tried playing down the significance of the
victory; no one feigned professional indifference.
</P>
<P>
   In two innings, the Yankees reversed their slide. And Williams
and O'Neill _ perhaps the team's most important hitters _ helping
to reverse their recent slumping ways as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the midst of a free fall,'' said David Cone, who
started and threw well for six innings, without run support. ``And
it was getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre called it ``the biggest win'' of the year,
``and you look at the smallest reason.''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about Ledee's hustle. The left fielder was on
first with one out in the eighth when Chili Davis bounced to second
baseman Homer Bush for what appeared to be an inning-ending double
play. Bush fielded the ball and intended to tag Ledee, but Ledee
stopped and retreated. Bush charged and Ledee dropped flat to the
turf; Bush swiped a tag at Ledee, missed and threw to first,
figuring the Blue Jays would have a play on Ledee at second. Carlos
Delgado, the Toronto first baseman, took the throw to retire Davis
_ two outs _ and fired to second for a tag play on Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   But Ledee dived safely into second, barely, keeping the inning
alive. No one on the field thought this would lead to anything.
Toronto had a five-run lead, Roy Halladay was pitching a great game
for the Blue Jays, the Yankees were beginning to look to Wednesday
to end their losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch battled Halladay, seven pitches, before drawing a
walk. Jeter singled through the middle, Ledee scoring, and the
Yankees _ who in recent days have been wallowing in their own
self-defeating frustration _ began to stir in their dugout. Jim
Fregosi, the Toronto manager, sensed this as well, and called on
Graeme Lloyd to pitch to O'Neill. Cone and Allen Watson watched on
television in the Yankees' clubhouse, each still consumed with
their unsuccessful appearances in the game, trading sob stories.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, the Yankees' right fielder, batting .201 against
left-handers, fought Lloyd, worked to put the ball in play, and
chopped a high bouncer in front of home plate. For an instant,
there was confusion between Lloyd and catcher Darrin Fletcher as to
who would make the play, and Fletcher stepped forward _ and dropped
the ball. Bases loaded, tying run coming to the plate. Lloyd was
out, and the hard-throwing Billy Koch was coming in.
</P>
<P>
   Williams stood in the on-deck circle, watching Koch warm up.
Williams had just one home run in his last 26 games, and he had
been feeling awful, as if he had let down his teammates. Koch threw
a fastball out of the strike zone, ball one. Williams stepped out
and concentrated: Koch had to throw a strike. Mariano Rivera
watched from the bullpen and said aloud: ``Come on, Bernie, he's
got to come to you. Hit it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch threw the fastball Williams expected, and Williams crushed
it, knowing instantly his slump was over, the ball sailing beyond
the wall in right field, a grand slam. Tie game. Cone and Watson
were yelling in the Yankees' clubhouse, the relievers were trading
high-fives in the bullpen. Tie score.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Bellinger ran hard on a ground ball to open the ninth
inning and reached first when Tony Fernandez threw high, and then
Bellinger took second on a passed ball. With one out, Knoblauch
rolled a ball toward the middle and beat the throw to first, with
one last burst at the bag. First and third and one out.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter drew a walk, loading the bases. Paul Spoljaric relieved
Koch, who immediately began screaming at the plate umpire, Laz
Diaz, angry about his interpretation of the strike zone, and Diaz
charged Koch; the two had to be separated. The Blue Jays were
coming apart, as the Yankees were coming together.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill had two homers in 135 at-bats against left-handed
pitchers this year. He wanted to put the ball in play, to deliver
the go-ahead run. Spoljaric threw him a breaking ball, O'Neill
turned on it, and immediately dropped his head as he moved to first
base. This is what O'Neill does when he knows he has hit a home
run.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Jeter jumped around happily. Other Yankees stepped out
of the dugout, screaming and clapping. Cone and Watson were yelling
again, and so were the relievers.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes to break out of a slump, Torre said before the
game, is one hit, one infield dribbler. Or, in the case of Williams
and O'Neill Tuesday night, in the case of the Yankees, a seemingly
meaningless bit of grit and a couple of grand slams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
