<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS15-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD OF STATE IS MINORITY, CENSUS SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   minority, the Census Bureau estimates in a report that depicts
the United States as an increasingly multiracial, multiethnic
society.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Hispanic population has grown by half since 1990,
surpassing 1 million in 1998, according to data being released
today. More than half the Hispanic growth occurred in Maricopa
County.
</P>
<P>
   Growth of the state's Black population was almost as fast, 47
percent, bringing Arizona's total to more than 169,000.
</P>
<P>
   And underscoring the rapid urbanization of Native Americans, who
make up the state's second-largest minority group, the Indian
population of Maricopa County last year ranked second in the
nation, just a few percentage points below that of Los Angeles
County.
</P>
<P>
   More than one in five of the state's 256,183 American Indians
now live in Maricopa County.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of Asians ranks them as the state's smallest
minority group, they are nearing a population of 100,000 statewide,
two-thirds of which is centered in Maricopa County.
</P>
<P>
   In percentage terms, Asians are the fastest-growing minority in
both the state (a 68.3 percent increase since 1990) and county
(75.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
   With Arizona's total of more than 1.56 million minorities
statewide, ramifications span a broad array of social, political
and economic fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make all citizens of Arizona aware of the positive
implications of this emerging diversity,'' said Jesus Trevino,
founding director of the 2-year-old Intergroup Relations Center at
Arizona State University in Tempe. The center brings people of
different backgrounds together to interact and learn more about one
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old way was to look at it as a problem. But we can use it
as an asset,'' Trevino said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more this population has success, the more the state of
Arizona will be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's minority concentration could well bring heightened
political clout to racial and ethnic groups, but the sheer numbers
are unlikely to translate rapidly into economic power, said Marvin
Perry, president of the Black Board of Directors Project in
Phoenix, which promotes diversity on corporate boards of directors
and policymaking bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``How well they participate in politics, not just in voting but
taking part at higher levels, should bring a heightened awareness
(of minorities),'' he said. ``But on the economic front, it will be
something a little bit more dicey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see them controlling major businesses in the near
future, but there probably will be an increase in minorities rising
to upper levels of corporate responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the minority population passed the 75 million mark
in 1998, meaning that more than one in four people is a minority.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities have increased at more than six times the rate of
non-Hispanic Whites, and the Census Bureau projects that by 2015,
the nation will reach the level at which Arizona finds itself
today: one-third minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an instructor in the College of Education, I think this
clearly has implications for teacher preparation,'' Trevino said.
Teachers must be given skills ``to work with students who are
different from them,'' he said. &QL; 
Ralph Romero, who administers federal grants for the state
Department of Education, pointed out that Arizona schools are
especially challenged because growth is stemming not just from
in-state residents and newcomers from other states, but from
foreign immigration as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are limited English-proficient students with special
requirements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The economic stability of the minority population is crucial to
the well-being of the state, several sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally those at lower income levels are at risk of failing
in school,'' Romero said. ``That's not to say that a Hispanic or
any other minority has any less of a capability to learn _ all have
the same capacity to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Leland Leonard, executive director of the Phoenix Indian Center,
said economic factors play the biggest role in bringing Indians to
the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of jobs on the reservations, contrasted with the booming
urban economy, has led to Maricopa County's gaining Indian
residents faster than either of the state's principal Indian
territories, Apache and Navajo counties.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nation's 10 counties with the highest Indian populations,
five are in Arizona. An estimated 54,415 Native Americans were
Maricopa County residents in 1998, making up 2 percent of the
county's population.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County, with 552,181 Hispanics, ranks ninth among U.S.
counties with the largest Hispanic populations.
</P>
<P>
   Just under one in five Maricopa County residents, or 19.8
percent, is Hispanic. Statewide, the proportion of Hispanics is
22.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For other minority groups, data show:
</P>
<P>
   Blacks, including Hispanic Blacks, total 169,191 or 3.6 percent
of the state. In Maricopa County, the number is 116,937, or 4.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Asians total 98,214, or 2.1 percent of the state. The county's
67,242 Asians make up 2.4 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Whites, including Hispanic Whites, total 4,145,043, or 88.8
percent of the state, and 2,545,481 or 91.4 percent of the county. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Republic writer Betty Reid contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
