<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO DELIVERS IN NINTH FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Minnesota Twins chose their poison and learned
that a dose of designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro can be lethal no
matter the percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Twins manager Tom Kelly elected to pitch to Palmeiro instead of
catcher Ivan Rodriguez with the game on the line in the top of the
ninth inning, and the left-handed hitter delivered a two-out,
two-run double to propel the Rangers to a 5-4 victory last night at
The Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one thing about our lineup,'' said manager Johnny
Oates, whose Rangers moved 6 1/2 games in front of second-place
Oakland in the American League West. ``Do you want to get shot? Do
you want to get stabbed? Do you want to get run over by a truck? Do
you want to get run over by a freight train?''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins opted for a '99 Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers appeared destined for a 4-3 loss. Twins right-hander
Hector Carrasco retired all six batters faced in the seventh and
eighth innings, but a leadoff walk to shortstop Royce Clayton set
the wheels in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly responded by summoning left-hander Eddie Guardado from the
bullpen for center fielder Tom Goodwin, the Rangers'
left-handed-hitting center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin advanced Clayton into scoring position with a sacrifice
bunt, but second baseman Mark McLemore _ who entered last night's
game hitting .141 (13-for-92) against left-handers this season _
hit a routine fly ball to right field for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly played the percentages from that point with right-hander
Mike Trombley available and warm in the bullpen. Kelly chose to
walk catcher Ivan Rodriguez intentionally with first base open and
let Guardado pitch to Palmeiro with the game on the line and the
winning run on first base instead of allowing Trombley pitch to
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is hitting .273 (6-for-22) against Trombley during his
career, with three doubles and one home run in his past 10 at-bats
against him. Palmeiro entered last night's game hitting .158
(3-for-19) with four strikeouts against Guardado.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics supported Kelly's decision, but the move
backfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I throw out all the percentages and all the matchups,'' said
Palmeiro, who drove Guardado's 1-0 pitch off the wall in
right-center field. ``I just take it personally. It's the right
decision for them, but I get pumped up for that.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro entered last night's game leading the major leagues
with a .380 batting average with men on base, and he provided his
club-record 19th game-winning run batted in this season.
</P>
<P>
   Those statistics suggest that Palmeiro can reach deep within and
find another gear when the occasion calls for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I do,'' he said. ``For some reason, I'm able to block
everything out, and everything seems to happen in slow motion for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Danny Kolb (2-1) earned the victory by retiring one
batter in relief, and closer John Wetteland recorded his
club-record 42nd save with a scoreless ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers _ who have won all 11 games from the Twins
this season _ will enter this afternoon's game with an opportunity
for their first-ever sweep of a season series.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
