u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     09-15 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-U.S.-DRUGS (Undated) _ With Colombia's government
buckling under guerrilla attacks, a thriving drug trade, and the
worst economy in decades, the Clinton administration has been
forced to reconsider its policies. By Tim Golden and Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Why Floyd is such a big storm, how
it is different from other hurricanes, and what forces are
determining its course. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Undated) _ The National Bioethics Advisory
Commission recommends that the government allow federal funds to be
used to support scientists who want to harvest embryonic stem cells
from human embryos. The research with the cells, which can give
rise to any kind of cell in the body, shows too much promise for
treating a range of diseases to hold it up, the commission says in
its report to the president. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FUELREGS-SUVS (Detroit) _ After heavy lobbying by the auto
industry, the Senate is expected on Wednesday to extend a
four-year-old ban preventing the Clinton administration from
reviewing a two-tier system of fuel economy regulations that allow
auto makers to produce large numbers of big, gas-guzzling sport
utility vehicles. Auto makers are moving forward with preparations
to take advantage of this system by introducing as many as two
dozen small and medium-sized car-based vehicles in the next few
years. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   MAYTAG-MARKETPLACE (Chicago) _ Were some investors just lucky,
or did they know something was awry last week at Maytag Corp.? By
David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CLEC-ACQUIRE _ Pssst, wanna buy a phone company? That is not
quite how Wall Street takeover pitches are made, but it captures
the gist of the calls that have gone out across the
telecommunications industry recently as at least a few competitive
local exchange carriers _ young communications companies trying to
compete against the Bells in local markets _ look to be acquired.
By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FEES-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The world's largest advertiser,
Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., plans major changes in how it pays the
agencies that create campaigns for its 300 household brands around
the world, like Cheer, Crest, Folgers, Ivory and Jif. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SACKLER-ASSESS (Washington) _ When the Smithsonian Institution
announced this month that a trove of Chinese art amassed over
nearly 60 years by an American collector, Dr. Paul Singer
(1904-1997), had been given to the Arthur M. Sackler Gallery here,
the details were rather staggering. It amounts to more than 5,000
objects, with a value estimated at $60 million, though, in fact, an
item-by-item assessment of the material is only just beginning. The
gift more than doubles the existing collection of the Sackler
Gallery, which was established in 1987 and constitutes, with the
neighboring Freer Gallery, the national museum of Asian art in the
United States. And in a stroke it transforms the Freer and the
Sackler into the largest repository for Chinese archaeological
material in North America. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on television. By Bill
Carter and Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
