<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETT OUT 8 GAMES FOR COWBOYS; CORYATT WON'T PLAY IN '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys will be without Leon Lett for eight
games, the penalty the NFL handed down yesterday for the Pro Bowl
defensive tackle violating the league's substance-abuse policy
again.
</P>
<P>
   Also, linebacker Quentin Coryatt, signed as a free agent in
April, will not play for the Cowboys this season. The former Texas
A&AMP;M star informed team officials yesterday that he has decided to
sit out this season because of chronic Achilles tendinitis and a
shoulder injury that required reconstructive surgery in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This double dose of bad news for the Cowboys defense came two
days after it allowed 504 yards and 35 points to the Washington
Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Lett, serving his third drug suspension in five seasons, is
eligible to play Nov. 14 against Green Bay. Lett, who is suspended
without pay, may return to practice Nov. 9, but until then, he
cannot associate with coaches or engage in any activities with
players at the Cowboys Valley Ranch training complex.
</P>
<P>
   NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue said Lett would draw a one-year
suspension if he violates the substance-abuse policy again.
</P>
<P>
   Lett has been on ``indefinite suspension'' since March after
violating terms of the league's substance-abuse policy. According
to a source, he did so at the Pro Bowl or in the days immediately
after the Feb. 7 game in Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   Lett is in Phase 3 of the NFL drug program, which requires him
to be tested three times a week, 52 weeks a year. This time, Lett's
violation required NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue to determine the
length of the suspension. After Lett's previous two violations, he
received a preset four-game suspension in 1995 and a preset
one-year suspension over the 1996 and 1997 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said
yesterday. ``I respect the commissioner's decision. I understand
the amount of deliberation involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue had said he would decide on Lett's suspension ``before
the first game of the season.'' Jones said he understood the change
in the time frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason why the commissioner took the amount of
time that he did is that this decision sets a standard for how he
wants to handle `indefinite suspensions' in the future,'' Jones
said. ``The program is progressive punishment, and I believe it was
a concern of the commissioner to follow a one-year suspension with
a lesser suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cowboys officials privately say that, except for his
February slip, Lett continues to follow the guidelines of his
aftercare treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon does not have a dependency or an addiction; I know
that,'' Jones said. ``That's why I continue to give him the benefit
of the doubt and not just continue wanting him on the team. I'm
familiar with all facts and aspects \Rof Lett's case\S, and I'm
just disappointed \Rwith the length of suspension\S. But I do
believe that if you have responsibility, you have to pay the price.
Leon has done that. We're all big boys ... Now we have to move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 20-minute phone call Monday, Jones tried a last-ditch
effort to influence, or at least inform, Tagliabue of Lett's
progress. But apparently there was no changing Tagliabue's mind
over what came down yesterday as the official two words: eight
games.
</P>
<P>
   A letter from Tagliabue was sent to Lett at his Dallas address
by registered mail yesterday. Lett chose not to appeal the latest
suspension. He could not be reached to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you this: Leon certainly regrets what has
happened,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said: ``Both \RLett and Coryatt\S are
good players, but I'm excited about the guys we have here. If and
when Leon is back, then we'll be excited about him, too. Mentally,
I was prepared for \RLett to be gone\S one season, one week. ... I
was prepared for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt, 29, had not practiced since the first week of training
camp. He was signed in April after being released in August 1998 by
Indianapolis, where he played for six seasons. He was the No. 2
pick overall in the 1992 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, the Cowboys received a roster exemption from the
NFL. Coryatt was put on the ``exempt, left squad list.'' He has
told Jones that he is willing to return his $1 million signing
bonus, which could be an indication he will retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the money with Quentin,'' Jones said. ``If it
was, I'd have a different approach to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will now put him on the ``retired list'' or waive
him at Coryatt's request or put him on ``reserve, left squad,''
which would keep him from playing for any NFL team this season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
