r s BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     09-15 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKE-UP CALL SENT TO LETT, COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leon Lett was slapped with an eight-week wake-up call yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   For his sake, let's hope he doesn't snore through it.
</P>
<P>
   According to Owner Jones, NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue wanted
to set a precedent for any future five-time violators of the
league's substance abuse policy. Tagliabue's message is a clear
one:
</P>
<P>
   Don't be a Leon.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as the Cowboys defense was concerned, the
commissioner could have been flagged for piling on. Add the news of
the Lett suspension atop the announcement that injury-riddled
linebacker Quentin Coryatt will not play this season, both coming
in the after wash of Sunday's 504-yard flogging in Washington, and
it has not been a bonny week for the Cowboys defenders.
</P>
<P>
   We knew they weren't going to be the bedrock of this Cowboys
team. We just didn't expect them to be a doormat.
</P>
<P>
   It would be rude to Redskins quarterback Brad Johnson to rank
what happened as one of the Cowboys' worst defensive performances
in the past eight seasons. Starting his first game for head coach
Norv Turner, Johnson threw for 382 yards, two touchdowns and was
never intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   He was rarely touched and only infrequently compelled to
scramble. Two of his best targets, Michael Westbrook and Albert
Connell, combined for nine catches and 296 yards, though the former
has been labeled as one of former GM Charley Casserly's drafting
mistakes and the latter has been shopped in possible trades.
</P>
<P>
   Lett might have helped. More accurately, he couldn't have hurt.
At least he could have been a stronger body to throw against the
109 rushing yards that Washington's Stephen Davis chugged for.
</P>
<P>
   But by now, the Cowboys defense knows the drill. Over the past
four seasons, Lett will have missed the equivalent of a full
season-and-a-half.
</P>
<P>
   In that same time, the Cowboys are a palpably ordinary 28-24
with only one victory in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   At what point does Owner Jones finally admit that Leon Lett
hurts this team, not helps it?
</P>
<P>
   He may have hurt it the most on last NFL Draft Day. For reasons
still unclear, Jones seemed convinced that Lett's latest suspension
would amount to no more than a wrist slap.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys never got a chance to pick defensive tackle Anthony
McFarland, snatched by Tampa Bay five picks in front of them. But
for some reason, they passed on every other true defensive tackle
for the remainder of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, we now see things like the grand experiment of moving
Alonzo Spellman inside for the first time in his NFL defensive line
career. The coaches pulled the plug on that midway in Sunday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Myers, meanwhile, was supposed to be the Cowboys' steal
of the 1998 draft. He has started only one regular-season game in
two seasons and didn't even suit up in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Without Lett, we also have come to realize what a mediocre
talent that tackle-mate Chad Hennings is.
</P>
<P>
   If a team can't consistently stop the run or pressure the
passer, it had better be prepared to score 41 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   With Lett gone and Deion Sanders still nursing The Mother of All
Toe Injuries, the only consistent playmaker on defense is safety
Darren Woodson. But there we go, pining for Leon again.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the Lett case has said that Leon's latest
indiscretion came at the Pro Bowl, which is coldly ironic in that
Lett's inconsistent play didn't merit a Pro Bowl trip in the first
place. It also brings up the curious question of why the NFL would
test for drugs at the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sad story, and yesterday was just another in a long list
of chapters. Jones reportedly tried on Monday to persuade the
commissioner to go lightly on his wayward defenseman. But Tagliabue
wanted to make five-time offender Leon an example.
</P>
<P>
   Five times Lett has violated the league's substance abuse
policy. So don't dump on the commissioner. The truly remarkable
thing about Lett's career is that through it all, he has remained
with the same team.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys stand by their man. Embarrassing, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Lett was injured in a preseason scrimmage. It should
have been a reminder to Owner Jones that Lett could vanish in a
blink. He had solid trade value in the summer of 1998, but the idea
was scoffed at because, as 20 or 30 emails rationalized to me,
``Leon is one of our best players.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider yesterday's announcement, therefore, a wakeup call, and
not just to Leon.
</P>
<P>
   Heard it?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
