<HEADLINE>
BROWN, DODGERS BEATEN BY EXPOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Brown's right arm won't be what keeps him
from winning 20 games for the second time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Nope. It appears the culprit will be the Los Angeles Dodgers'
offense. If you can call it that.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Brown had six remaining starts to win four games. He
since has allowed three earned runs in 17 innings _ and has two
losses to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Dodgers wasted another wonderful Brown outing by
getting one hit off Montreal right-hander Javier Vazquez in a 3-0
loss to the Expos at Dodger Stadium on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez, who had a 6.43 ERA on the road this season, struck out
a career-high 10 batters in winning for the first time in four
starts. He walked one. Vazquez, 23, is 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   The lone hit he allowed was a clean single to left by Mark
Grudzielanek to lead off the fourth. The Dodgers hit three balls
out of the infield after that.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (16-8) yielded two earned runs and struck out six in his
fifth complete game of the season. He allowed nine hits, but for
the sixth start didn't walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   In his last start, Brown allowed one earned run and struck out
seven in eight innings against the Mets. The Dodgers lost 3-1. They
had two hits, but none after the fourth inning. Mets starter Orel
Hershiser retired the last 15 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   The only inning the Dodgers had a baserunner was the fourth.
Grudzielanek led off with the single, stole second with one out and
advanced to third on a passed ball. But, as is the Dodgers' habit,
the meat of the order left Grudzielanek there. Gary Sheffield
walked but Eric Karros popped out to second and Raul Mondesi
grounded out to third.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez retired the first nine batters he faced. The
fourth-inning interlude also gave a three-batter break to another
string of mediocrity and disinterest from the Dodgers hitters that
saw Vazquez sit down 17 straight batters.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the offense, Brown could be two wins away from 20, a
mark he hasn't reached since going 21-11 for the Texas Rangers in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the Expos game with a 6-1 record and 1.62 ERA in his
past 10 starts, and he was 8-2 with a 2.01 ERA in his last 14
starts at Chavez Ravine.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike some of his latest outings, Brown wasn't overpowering
or particularly dazzling against Montreal. He was, however, very
effective.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos took a 1-0 lead in the fourth when Peter Bergeron
singled to lead off. Bergeron, traded to Montreal along with Wilton
Guerrero and Ted Lilly for Carlos Perez last season, scored on Jose
Vidro's double to the fence in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bergeron who struck again in the sixth as the Expos went
ahead 2-0. Bergeron singled with one out and moved to second on
Brown's errant pickoff attempt. Vidro's single to center put
Bergeron on third and he scored on Vladimir Guerrero's
fielder's-choice groundout.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' defense didn't help Brown in the ninth when the
Expos extended their lead to 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero led off with a line drive to center fielder Devon
White, who broke in on the ball, only to have it carry over his
head for a triple. Brad Fullmer then singled to left to score
Guerrero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
