<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED POLICY UNDERMINES EFFORTS OF AMERICAN WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Are you overworked? Some who study America's work
habits say you are if you're an average working person.
</P>
<P>
   The concern initially surfaced in the early '90s, when a Harvard
professor focused on the phenomenon in a book titled The Overworked
American. The thesis was then viewed as a good-news-bad-news
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that our harder working ways would allow us to
catch up with the performance results of Japanese superworkers. The
bad news was the depressing prospect of our transformation into a
society of joyless toilers.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Juliet Schor's book was published, however, the
Japanese juggernaut hit the wall and never recovered. Meanwhile,
the U.S. economy has boomed throughout this decade. If the
expansion lasts until next February, it will become the longest
period of uninterrupted growth in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   The price of this prosperity, though, has been longer hours with
the nose in close proximity to the grindstone, according to a
recent New York Times op-ed page article.
</P>
<P>
   A new study by the International Labor Organization, the article
noted, indicates that Americans have replaced the Japanese as the
superworkers of the world. American workers now put in 1,966 hours
of toil a year, which not only is 70 hours more than the Japanese,
the study noted, but also 350 more a year _ nearly nine 40-hour
weeks _ than their European counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the study's validity, there is a certain irony at work
because the reward for all this effort is a Federal Reserve effort
to neutralize the resulting economic growth by tightening monetary
policy. The thinking at the central bank seems to be that all this
hard work is producing a dangerous prosperity that threatens
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, if there is one, is that workers are translating
their good fortune into enthusiastic personal consumption, which is
the primary fuel for economic growth. Their quest for financial
security also is driving much of the demand for equity investments,
thereby pushing the stock market to record highs and raising Fed
fears of a ``bubble'' on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Is this what it's all about? If so, it's a cruel irony. In the
bad old days the underpaid and overworked proletariat got ground
into the dust with nothing to show for it except broken backs and
broken dreams. Nowadays, they share in the prosperity to a much
greater degree, but their ultimate reward is a regime that sees too
much prosperity as a curse rather than a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   American workers produce more value than any other on the
planet, and what do they get for the effort they expend to create
the highest standard of living in the world? They get a policy
rigged to undermine their efforts in the name of heading off an
inflationary threat that seems more phantom than real.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Schor says that if she were to write a sequel, she'd
call it The Even More Overworked American. Perhaps it would be
appropriate to insert the word ``underappreciated'' in there
someplace.
</P>
<P>
   If you're regretting not spending enough time with your family
while pondering such matters, here's something to keep in mind:
There's no known instance of anyone's dying words being, ``I wish
I'd spent more time at the office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-15 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEVER have so many been so captivated by sheet metal.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happens when a race becomes a race _ the kind
that captivates fans and enthralls players. And that's what
happened Tuesday night at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   A scoreboard came to life. A piece of metal was the messenger.
</P>
<P>
   It was 8:37 p.m. _ the fifth inning at the Astrodome _ and the
Astros were slicing through another round of woeful Philadelphia
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Another double-digit, batting-practice kind of victory was on
the way. It was only a matter of time before the Astros extended
the club record for consecutive wins, taking the streak to 12 with
Tuesday's 12-2 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   The real news was happening out behind left field, where the
heroes of the night _ guys named Scott Burford and Matt Johnson _
were gripping the hearts of 25,164 fans every time they reached for
a numbered slat of metal and slid it into the National League
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   When the box came open at 8:37 p.m., a gradual progression of
applause wafted across the Astrodome as a white ``2'' slid into the
Chicago Cubs' ninth-inning frame. The Cubs took a 4-1 lead over the
Cincinnati Reds with those two runs in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Some Astrodome fans stood and applauded as word spread, the
noise gradually getting louder and louder as fans pointed to the
outfield scoreboard. Astros players sitting on the bench noticed.
Players on the field, warming up for the inning to begin, noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught myself peeking out there a little more than usual,''
third baseman Ken Caminiti said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when a race becomes a race.
</P>
<P>
   With just 15 games remaining after this one and a 10-0 lead
against the Phillies on a school night, few fans left their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs cable when you have otherwise anonymous guys named
Burford and Johnson who can make your night or break your heart?
</P>
<P>
   This time things were looking good. What began as a three-game
Central Division edge over the Reds was looking to be four.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds had things well under control, even hitting a
two-run homer to help his cause. A six-run fourth had squished all
Phillies hopes.
</P>
<P>
   But then things started to look bad _ very bad _ and all too
familiar in this stretch run during which neither the Reds nor the
Astros have buckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating for them and frustrating for us,''
Astros second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``Both teams have been
winning. But one team is not going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 8:48 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Burford and Johnson slid a yellow-colored ``2'' into the board,
this time in the Reds' ninth-inning box. The yellow meant the
inning was still alive. The Reds were down 4-3 but still batting.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd groaned. That's what happens when a race becomes a
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked up there and figured the Reds were going to come
back and beat them,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``That's
just the way it's been going.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell, who with Biggio was pulled
early from this laugher in order to get some rest, went up the
tunnel behind the Astros' dugout as the game was safely in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans can't bear to watch such dramatics. Bags couldn't bear
not to, sneaking into the Astros' clubhouse for a moment to watch
the Reds' final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when a race becomes a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting crazy,'' Bagwell said. ``There's 15 games to go _
that says it all right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at 8:56 p.m., the ninth-inning scoreboard windows
opened again in left field. The final score was posted: Cubs 4,
Reds 3.
</P>
<P>
   A roar went up in the Astrodome. Caminiti looked over his
shoulder to the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, warming up for the sixth inning, didn't have to look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the crowd and figured what it was,'' he said.
``Everybody gets into it when it's crunch time.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what it became Tuesday night. When the Astros arrive at
the Dome tonight, there will be only 15 games remaining, and the
Reds will be four games back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four games is nothing,'' Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's better than three. And that's why even in a 10-run romp
you could feel the drama in the air _ and see it every time a metal
slat slid into place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
