r a BC-BOXER-DEATH-KAN &LR;      09-15 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXER-DEATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXER DIES, TWO DAYS AFTER BOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BOYCE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Friends and family of Randie Carver had
held out hope since Sunday night that the Kansas City boxer somehow
would recover from an injury to the left side of his brain.
</P>
<P>
   Through hours of bedside vigil at North Kansas City Hospital,
they prayed and sobbed and pleaded with Carver to fight his way
back from critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   So when the news came that Carver, 24, died at 10:30 a.m.
Tuesday _ apparently from injuries suffered in a supermiddleweight
title fight at Harrah's North Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel _ it was
the most devastating blow delivered all week.
</P>
<P>
   Carver's 23-year-old brother, Frankie, consoled another brother
who had broken down on his mother's shoulder. Barbara Carver, who
wore a T-shirt with the image of her son, sat with a friend outside
the hospital nearly four hours after he died, trying to come to
grips with the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and fellow boxers drifted in and out of the hospital all
day, many leaving in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my driving force,'' said Carver's trainer, George
Smith. ``I don't know what I'm going to do. He was my best
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at North Kansas City Hospital did not release the
cause of Carver's death.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Arnold, a neurosurgeon at the University of Kansas Medical
Center in Kansas City, Kan., who has treated sports-related head
injuries, said Carver's death most likely was caused by a blood
clot that formed after the boxer suffered blunt trauma to his head.
</P>
<P>
   Carver also could have suffered a tear in his brain, Arnold
said. A tear, particularly in his brain stem, also could lead to
death.
</P>
<P>
   When a boxer dies from injuries suffered in a fight, many
questions are asked. Should the bout have been stopped? Was Carver
healthy going into the bout? And above all, could his death have
been prevented?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this kid. I'd gladly trade places with him,'' promoter
Tony Holden said. ``I'm so numb, I'm not even comfortable defending
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Carver went into Sunday's fight against Kabary Salem as the
North America Boxing Federation supermiddleweight champion. He lost
in the 10th round of a scheduled 12-round fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime a boxer walks up those four steps, anything can
happen,'' said Peyton Sher, a boxing matchmaker for 54 years. ``I
don't know if there is anyone to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Carver understood the risk. On Saturday afternoon, he
talked about the respect he had for anyone willing to box.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of heart to get in the ring,'' Carver said.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime trainers such as LeRoy Green will never dispute that.
Green trained Carver for eight years as an amateur at the old Bell
Recreation Center in Kansas City, Kan. Sher knew Carver a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   Green and Sher watched the fight on television and noticed
something different about Carver right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't look like Randie Carver from the first round on,''
Sher said.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth round, in a brutal fight, Carver stopped moving
around. Holden and Smith attribute that to the numerous head butts
Carver received in the first three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You heard me yelling, `Stop the head butts,' '' Holden said.
``I think the one at the beginning of the fourth round really hurt
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Famed referee Richard Steele, who has worked 150 world title
fights, questioned how much damage a head butt could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, head butts cause cuts,'' said Steele, who
lives in Las Vegas. ``I don't think a head butt can cause brain
damage. Remember, the one who does the head butting is going to be
hurt also.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, Kansas City referee Danny Campbell looked
at tape of the fight. Campbell has refereed for 18 years and boxed
15 years before that.
</P>
<P>
   He said Salem did not head butt Carver enough even to be issued
a warning.
</P>
<P>
   By the fifth round, Campbell noticed Carver looked disoriented.
In the sixth round, when Salem barely pushed him, Carver fell
through the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he talked with Carver after each round.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said Carver looked exhausted in the eighth round.
Carver fell down once and was knocked down again on a light
straight left. In the ninth round, Carver could barely stand. And
in the 10th, when Salem actually missed on two punches, Carver fell
to the ground and could not return to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   As Carver rolled around, desperately trying to get up, it took
20 seconds before anyone reached him. Smith said professional
boxing rules prevented him from jumping into the ring before the
fight was officially stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Ross Strada said he thought Carver looked tired in the
late rounds but added that he couldn't stop the fight for that
reason. Ringside doctor Michael Poppa looked at Carver before the
10th round and declared him fit enough to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Steele said it was important for a referee to be neutral. Strada
has stated he considered Carver a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each referee who does a good job is not worried about who is
winning a fight,'' Steele said. ``When a kid is in trouble, you
can't have likes and dislikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a friend, you may think you are helping him but wind up
hurting him by letting the fight go too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Green and Campbell don't think what happened to Carver occurred
in the Salem bout but was an accumulation of seven bouts in the
last 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had tough fights back to back,'' Campbell said. ``I think
he's had too many rough fights.''
</P>
<P>
   It all started on Oct. 8, 1998, when Carver fought Mario
Iribarren to a tough 12-round draw. Carver's face was battered with
cuts around his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Carver then had two tune-up bouts before facing William ``Bo''
James at Harrah's on May 23. Carver won a 12-round decision to earn
the NABF supermiddleweight title. Again he left the ring with cuts
around the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Before facing Salem, Carver went eight rounds and won by
knockout on July 12 and returned to the ring on Aug. 8 for a
second-round knockout victory.
</P>
<P>
   Holden said that's a normal number of fights for a boxer. Still,
that's also a lot of potential for head trauma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any repetitive head trauma is dangerous,'' said Arnold.
``Boxers ought to have head gear the way bicycle riders and
football players have helmets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
