<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMING-MAINSTREAM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMING INDUSTRY STRIVES FOR MAINSTREAM ACCEPTANCE, PATRONAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ A photo of a man jogging along the picturesque
pathway in Kansas City's Richard L. Berkley Riverfront Park is
featured prominently in the American Gaming Association's first
Survey of Casino Entertainment, released Tuesday at the World
Gaming Congress.
</P>
<P>
   That might seem like an odd image to associate with gambling,
but it bolsters the industry's argument that casino taxes make such
public improvements possible.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that the average casino gambler is most likely
a white-collar worker who has attended college and makes
better-than-average money.
</P>
<P>
   It also reinforces the industry's conclusion that the gambling
industry has become just another part of life in many states, where
it provided 325,000 casino jobs and paid more than $2.5 billion in
state and local taxes last year.
</P>
<P>
   More than 23,000 gaming professionals and others are in Las
Vegas this week for the industry's largest annual trade show,
sponsored in part by the association, which is the industry's trade
group and national lobbying arm.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, association President and Chief
Executive Frank J. Fahrenkopf said the survey of 54,000 U.S.
households also showed that ``the American public wants legalized
gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become part of the mainstream culture,'' he said.
``We've become part of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found overwhelming public support _ more than 80
percent _ for the notion that casinos and other gambling
enterprises must take an active role in discouraging compulsive
gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   The industry survey, however, did not examine deeply the
increasingly studied question of why people gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Findings from another recent national study, analyzed in the
current issue of Public Perspective magazine, suggest that fewer
Americans are gambling for fun in the 1990s and that in the last 20
years substantially more of them are engaging in wagering simply
because they hope to win money.
</P>
<P>
   The association's survey, conducted by national polling firms,
found that U.S. casino customers':
</P>
<P>
   - Median household income is $46,000, compared with the national
average of $39,000.
</P>
<P>
   - Education level includes at least some college for 54 percent,
compared with the national average of 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   - Employment is 45 percent white-collar, 27 percent blue-collar
and 13 percent retirees, which roughly approximates the national
breakdown. In 1998, someone from 29 percent of all U.S. households
visited a casino, and on average Americans visit a casino once
every two months.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found widespread acceptance of casino gambling as
adult entertainment, with only 25 percent of Americans agreeing
with the statement that ``casino gambling is morally wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-two percent agreed with the statement that ``casino
gambling can be a fun night out.''
</P>
<P>
   But an analysis of other surveys, including two commissioned by
Congress in 1975 and last year, suggests that gambling is emerging
as a second vocation for some and as a get-rich-quick avocation for
others.
</P>
<P>
   The August-September issue of Public Perspective examined those
congressional studies and found that between 1975 and 1998 the
percentage of people who said they gambled to win money increased
from 44 percent to 66 percent, and the number who said they gambled
for the excitement or challenge of it dropped from 70 percent to 49
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that hard to believe,'' said Fahrenkopf, who had not
seen the analysis. ``That is just not supported by anything that I
have ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fahrenkopf also took issue with the methods of the 1998
congressional study, complaining that telephone survey findings
were mixed with random interviews of gamblers at U.S. casinos to
reach many of the conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   At the trade show this week, scores of the latest slot machines
and other player attractions are on display and for sale alongside
such mundane, back-of-the-house technology as cash- and
coin-counting machines and database software for casino managers.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities on hand range from retired Miami Dolphins head coach
Don Shula, who delivered Tuesday's inspirational opening address on
winning, to actress Barbara Eden and NASCAR superstar driver
Richard Petty, whose images grace this year's crop of new slot
machines from International Game Technology, the worldwide
industry's dominant game maker.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the stars of the show were Elvis Presley (or at least
his image) and Monopoly slots, now being played in many Missouri
casinos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
