<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FANS SURE THAT TAGLIABUE HATES THE COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, you have spoken. You're divided on Leon Lett. You're not
divided on Paul Tagliabue. You have matters of concern about the
Cowboys. You're thinking big picture, one miracle finish down, 15
games to go, plenty of time to get in your shots.
\Nsubheds:FIRST SHOT This commish is the pits! He acts as though
he's on drugs. How long does it take to say ``no games'' or two or
even four? What a real jerk! Only a ``no-game'' suspension can save
his reputation, and then how about an apology and a resignation?
Randy Phillips Austin
\Nsubheds:BUCKSHOT Randy, sit down, take a deep breath. Because
Lett was just slapped with an eight-game suspension. On second
thought, you don't need to be hearing words like slapped.
\Nsubheds:SECOND SHOT I am a faithful S-T reader, but I am sick of
the newspaper space wasted on ``poor'' Leon Lett. He has proved for
the third time that he has no regard for an organization that has
made him a multimillionaire. If the rest of us peons who work for a
living fail one drug or alcohol test at work, we are fired. Period.
I truly hope this is the last word on the subject. It is mine. Good
luck, Leon ... and goodbye. Lee in Bedford
\Nsubheds:BUCKSHOT Oops, it looks like somebody just gave Lett
another paragraph. Goodbye.
\Nsubheds:THIRD SHOT I still disagree with having Michael Irvin on
the sideline with the game on the line. I think you need to have
your best receiver on the field at all times. I wonder if Chan is
using this as a tactic to light a fire under Michael? John Minor
\Nsubheds:BUCKSHOT Bottom line, it worked at Washington. Irvin was
fresh to make two late-game touchdown catches. Few words of
explanation were needed afterward, but then Chan Gailey's MO has
always been more like a Bic than a blow torch. \Nsubheds:FOURTH
SHOT Jerry Jones still has his work cut out for him. The ``Mona
Lisa'' restoration project needs a major overhaul on defense. The
Cowboys have the worst defensive line in the NFL. Leon Lett and
Chad Hennings couldn't bull rush an 80-year-old man! I'm not even
going to discuss the secondary. That pathetic unit speaks for
itself! Paul Patterson
\Nsubheds:BUCKSHOT At times Sunday, the Cowboys' D-line and
secondary did seem joined at the hip. In fact, maybe that was
problem.
\Nsubheds:FIFTH SHOT How can a team jump offside four times in 10
snaps with the opponent marching toward a tying touchdown? Redskins
coach Norv Turner claims Mark Stepnoski ``rolls the ball before he
snaps it,'' thus suckering three defensive linemen to jump. I'll
bet you anything that the same commissioner who came up with the
Erik Williams Rule (hands to the face) and the Emmitt Smith Rule
(no taking helmets off after a good play) will now come up with the
Stepnoski Rule (no rolling the ball before snapping it). All it
will take is a resurgence of the Cowboys to get the commish to put
a stop to it. I think Tagliabue is drafting up the new rule as we
speak! J. Terrell
\Nsubheds:BUCKSHOT Hey, J.T., all the Cowboys have done so far is
beat the Chokeskins. Doesn't exactly qualify as a resurgence.
\Nsubheds:SIXTH SHOT Lost in the hoopla about Troy Aikman's
comeback win and gaudy numbers were three INTs, two of them on very
bad throws into coverage. Brandon Noble/Nathan Davis looked like
the best pair of defensive tackles we had, especially ``no-size''
Noble. When did 285 pounds become small anyway? And where was Peppi
Zellner? Don Phillips
\Nsubheds:BUCKSHOT Look for Zellner to get face-time Monday night.
Noble isn't small, just short. Now those three Aikman INTs looked
real small after the game.
Do you have a question? Cowboys writer Ray Buck answers your
e-mail. Send your questions to Buckshots at
rbuck\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
