<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2467 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-H     09-15 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
This week, Reds outfielder Dmitri Young suggested if the Astros
were going to win a third straight National League Central title
they would have to play .900 ball the rest of September.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be careful what you wish for, Dmitri. With 19 days left in the
regular season, the Astros show no signs of letting up.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds pitched seven solid innings and hit his first
homer of the season and Ricky Gutierrez tied a career high with
four hits Tuesday night as the Astros extended their club-record
winning streak to 12 games with a 12-2 pounding of the Philadelphia
Phillies at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   After matching victories with second-place Cincinnati for much
of the past two weeks, the Astros finally were able to widen their
lead over the Reds, who lost to the Chicago Cubs 4-3 on Tuesday.
The Astros hold a four-game lead in the NL Central with 15 games
left and are a half-game behind Atlanta in the race for the best
record in the majors. It's also the Astros' largest lead since a
4{-game advantage June 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are 12-1 in September, their only loss coming on the
first day of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been crazy, 12 straight wins,'' Astros first baseman Jeff
Bagwell said. ``The Reds are getting a little bit frustrated.
Hopefully that's good for us. Maybe they'll start pressing a little
bit. Both teams are a little frustrated. We win 11 in a row and
gain a half-game. They win 10 out of 11 and lose a half-game. It's
nice to finally pick up a game. If we keep playing the way we're
playing, we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Astros could do no wrong _ and the Phillies could
do nothing right in dropping their 11th game in a row, matching
their longest losing streak since 1997. Philadelphia has lost 18 of
its last 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds kept the Phillies off the scoreboard for five innings,
and the Phillies' pitching staff threw extended batting practice
that allowed the Astros to build a 10-run lead after four innings.
</P>
<P>
   In six games with the Phillies this season, the Astros have
outscored them 52-18. The Astros are averaging 7.4 runs per game
during their winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the race intensifies,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said of the expected down-to-the-wire finish with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds (16-11) turned in his third straight strong start,
allowing two runs and six hits over seven innings. He retired 10 of
the first 11 batters he faced, including eight in a row. He is 2-0
with a 1.27 ERA in three September starts.
</P>
<P>
   The righthander also helped his cause with a two-run homer in
the second inning, his first in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God August is over. Me and August have never gotten
along,'' Reynolds said of his 1-4 record and 4.17 ERA last month.
</P>
<P>
   Nine Astros scored, and 10 had at least one hit. Reynolds,
Daryle Ward, Carl Everett and Lance Berkman each had two RBIs. Bill
Spiers added a pair of singles, and Bagwell reached base safely in
all three of his plate appearances (two walks and a hit-by-pitch).
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez continued his tear with his second four-hit game in
the past week. He is batting .600 (12-for-20) during this six-game
homestand, which concludes tonight against the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   By the fifth inning, Dierker elected to rest many of his
every-day players.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies starter Paul Byrd (14-9) allowed seven runs and eight
hits in three-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took a 3-0 lead in the second on an RBI double to
left by Gutierrez and a two-run homer by Reynolds, his third career
homer and first since Sept. 8, 1996. Reynolds leads all
major-league pitchers this season with 14 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Everett had an RBI double in the third inning to give him 100
for the season, the first time in his career he has reached the
century mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros broke open the game with a six-run fourth. Craig
Biggio singled in a run, Spiers hit an RBI single off reliever
Billy Brewer, Everett had an RBI grounder, Ken Caminiti had an RBI
double, and Ward hit a two-run single. The Astros had six hits and
sent nine batters to the plate in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about the Phillies that brings out the big
inning in the Astros, who have scored nine, five and six runs
(twice) in an inning against Philadelphia this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We executed well,'' Biggio said. ``Shane pitched a good game
and helped his own cause with a two-run homer. The little things
turned out to be the big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia got on the scoreboard in the sixth inning when Doug
Glanville led off with a triple and Ron Gant followed with an RBI
single to left field. Pinch hitter Wendell Magee singled in a run.
</P>
<P>
   Berkman drove in the Astros' final two runs with a double in the
seventh inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
