<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ LOOKING TO HAVE A WINTER OF CONTENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Of all the things that contributed to Carlos
Perez's abysmal season _ to count them all would take the next few
days _ he goes back to something that never took place.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was embroiled in contract negotiations, Perez didn't
pitch last winter. He's not going to make the same mistake again.
</P>
<P>
   Perez said Tuesday he will pitch this winter in his native
Dominican Republic and will return to the pitcher he was before
this season. The left-hander also said he will return to the Los
Angeles Dodgers' starting rotation next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be better next year,'' Perez said. ``What a year. It's
bad. As soon as the season is over I'm just going to forget about
it. Your whole career, you're not going to go through it and not
have a bad year. This is my bad year. I'll be back next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad? OK, but disgusting, revolting, grotesque or nauseating are
apt descriptions, too. After all, when you sign a three-year, $15.5
million contract during the offseason, you're expected to win more
than two games.
</P>
<P>
   There were some people who thought Perez would have a better
season than teammate Ismael Valdes. But Perez, on the 60-day
disabled list after getting hit in the right leg with a line drive
in his last Triple-A outing, was brutal from his first start.
</P>
<P>
   He frustrated the club by going 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA before
being banished to Albuquerque. He infuriated Dodgers officials when
he missed a start in Montreal after mysteriously injuring his knee
the night before.
</P>
<P>
   But Perez, who was 33-35 with a 3.71 ERA in his first three
seasons, said it could have been different had in pitched in winter
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really hurt,'' Perez said. ``That was a mistake not to
pitch then. But I had to sign my contract. I didn't want to get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan is for Perez to return home Thursday (as long as
Hurricane Floyd cooperates) and return to the states in a week. He
will continue his rehab in Arizona with the Dodgers' instructional
club before pitching in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go through the winter working hard and be ready for next
season,'' Perez said. ``When you pitch there, it sets up everything
going to spring training. Your arm is in better shape.''
</P>
<P>
   If Perez doesn't pitch well in spring, the Dodgers have the
option of sending him to Albuquerque next season.
</P>
<P>
   Exclusive club: For everything that's gone wrong for Raul
Mondesi this season, the Dodgers' right fielder is just one homer
and one stolen base from becoming the first 30-30 player in the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi stole two bases in Monday's win against Montreal to
reach the precipice of one of baseball's most exclusive clubs. He's
the only Dodger to hit 30 homers and steal 30 bases in a season. He
did it in 1997, when he hit a career-high 30 homers (which he tied
last season) and stole a career-best 32 bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's who he is,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``Steal bases, hit the ball all over, throw people out, get his
uniform dirty. I'd like to see him locked into that mode.''
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Johnson said he'll bypass rookie Eric Gagne's next
scheduled start in Colorado. Instead, Valdes with pitch Friday
followed by Chan Ho Park and Kevin Brown.... For the second
consecutive game Eric Young didn't start at second base. Craig
Counsell got the call a night after Alex Cora started.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
