<HEADLINE>
FRESNO STATE, UCLA PLANNING A REUNION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Call it the Fresno Connection or the Fresno Farm
System, but there's no doubt UCLA has closer ties to Fresno State
than any team on its schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The ties start at the top. Bulldogs coach Pat Hill played for
UCLA coach Bob Toledo at Cal State-Riverside in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA running backs coach Kelly Skipper was an honorable-mention
All-American tailback at Fresno State in 1988. He was a graduate
assistant for two seasons, then a full-time assistant for seven
before joining Toledo's staff last year.
</P>
<P>
   Skipper's brother, Tim, is the Bulldogs' starting middle
linebacker. He was a first-team All-Western Athletic Conference
selection last year as a sophomore. He has 21 tackles in two games
this season.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA defensive tackles coach Jethro Franklin was a two-time
All-American (1986-87) at Fresno State who sacked Bruins
quarterback Troy Aikman four times in a 1987 game at the Rose Bowl.
Franklin was a Bulldogs assistant for eight years, then joined
Toledo's staff this spring.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bruins cornerback Ricky Manning Jr. is a Fresno
native who attended Edison High. He has several friends and former
teammates on the Bulldogs' roster.
</P>
<P>
   The connections should help UCLA prepare for Saturday's 7 p.m.
game at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to attack their schemes, and Jethro knows the defense
and Kelly knows the offense,'' Toledo said. ``You also attack
personnel, and we know it better than normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Origins of the platoon: Just as Toledo's talent-less years at
Pacific (1979-82) are the source of his recruiting zest, so too was
an Oregon experience the reason he platooned Drew Bennett and Cory
Paus for two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to get stuck without a (backup) quarterback,''
he said. ``When I was (offensive coordinator) at Oregon in 1988, we
were 6-1 when Bill Musgrave got hurt. We didn't win another game
after that. We didn't have a backup quarterback who could play.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer update: Receiver Danny Farmer will play this week despite
tweaking his sprained left ankle. However, Farmer is not at top
speed and hasn't regained his rhythm; he even dropped a touchdown
pass at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ankle isn't going to be healthy all year, and that's a
concern,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Showing promise: Reserve left tackle Bryce Bohlander, a true
freshman, will play 20 to 25 snaps each game unless injuries
dictate otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a heck of a player,'' Toledo said. ``It's shame he has to
play, but it may help him in the long run. He's very athletic, and
he's stronger than we thought he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting his kicks: Walk-on kicker Chris Griffith has made 3 of 3
field goals (33, 35 and 37 yards), and that's a pleasant surprise
for the Bruins considering the state of the kicking game when
training camp began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's improved tremendously over the last year,'' Toledo said.
``He was a walk-on and didn't have a strong leg. But he lifted
weights and got stronger. I'm very impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Perturbed about parking placards: Toledo on the media's response
to the disabled parking scandal:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to me what (the media) are trying to do to our
program. What are they trying to prove? Why don't they let it die?
The kids have been punished. They've suffered severely. To bring it
up again and again is absolutely absurd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
