<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR USC, RESPECTABILITY MEANS BEATING UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Questions may linger about just how good USC is
after beating lowly Hawaii, but offensive lineman Travis Claridge
doesn't think skeptics will get any more answers from Saturday's
opponent, San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Claridge doesn't expect the Trojans to silence doubters
until the end of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to have questions about the team until we
beat UCLA,'' Claridge said. ``No matter who we beat. No matter what
the score is. People will have questions until the end of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   USC is a 20{-point favorite against San Diego State, meaning the
Trojans will probably gain little national respect even if they win
by a large margin. But Claridge is not looking past the Aztecs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they'll still be a good test,'' Claridge said.
``They've got a good defensive line.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie out: Sophomore tailback Malaefou MacKenzie will miss
the San Diego State game after straining his hamstring Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just bad luck,' MacKenzie said. ``I did it on the last
play of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie was bothered by a sore hamstring during training camp,
in part because of stress he placed on the leg while trying to
recover from a season-ending knee injury that caused him to miss 12
games last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is he is in jeopardy of reinjuring the hamstring
and needs a week off,'' Hackett said. ``I'm not going to feel the
pressure of putting him in there.''
</P>
<P>
   With MacKenzie out, Frank Strong and Sultan McCullough become
USC's short-yardage tailbacks. That could be interesting because
Strong has two fumbles in only six carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to take care of the problem,'' Hackett said. ``I'd like
to tell you a coach can do something, or you can buy a machine. If
he has another fumble, my patience will wear thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawley gets the start: San Diego State will make a quarterback
change and start Jack Hawley of L.A. Harbor College instead of
Brian Russell against the Trojans. Hawley completed 9 of 19 passes
for 86 yards in a 38-10 loss to Illinois, while Russell completed 8
of 21 passes for 93 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Papadakis gets extra year: Tailback Petros Papadakis, who
suffered a broken foot in training camp, said he has been granted
an extra year by the NCAA and will complete his eligibility next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker shuffle: There's been more movement with the reserve
linebackers, and it's becoming harder and harder to keep track of
who plays what position.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Aaron Graham has switched from No.2 middle linebacker
to No.2 weakside linebacker behind Markus Steele. Freshman Troy
Polamalu has gone from No.2 weakside linebacker to No.2 strongside
linebacker behind Sultan Abdul-Malik.
</P>
<P>
   And sophomore Henry Wallace, who was moved to weakside
linebacker just three weeks ago, is back at middle linebacker
behind Zeke Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheed returns: Defensive end Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed will
play this week after serving a one-game suspension for academic
problems. Abdul-Shaheed will split time with Matt Childers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried about losing my spot,'' Abdul-Shaheed said.
``We're in a rotation. As long as I have an opportunity to compete
that's all that matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
