<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2478 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      09-15 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYER BAFFLES DEVIL RAYS; GRIFFEY CLUBS 45TH HOMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ It was blustery and wet Tuesday when the
Mariners left their hotel for Tropicana Field. Nobody was sure if
that was Florida being Florida, or if Hurricane Floyd was
approaching the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The storm's on everyone's mind, and everyone in their right
mind is going to think that way,'' left-hander Jamie Moyer said
after the Mariners had beaten the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, 5-1. ``I'm
not worried about it, but you have thoughts about it. Once you get
to the field, though, you go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   There were occasional high winds inside the dome Tuesday night,
and Moyer caused a lot of them. He struck out seven while pitching
his third complete game in seven starts, allowing a double, six
singles and a walk. The Devil Rays' only run was unearned, and
Moyer lowered his earned run average to a season-best 3.83 while
improving his record to 14-6.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr.'s two-run homer in the third inning, his
American League-leading 45th, gave Moyer all the runs he needed. It
was Griffey's third homer this year off Devil Rays starter Rolando
Arrojo, against whom he is 6-for-10 in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't pitch that bad,'' Griffey said. ``What did he give
up, four or five hits while he was in? (Four.) He just gave up one
low one and that was it. Other than that, he was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo was fine, but Moyer was brilliant _ and he finished with
a flourish.
</P>
<P>
   After getting Jose Guillen looking on an inside fastball, Moyer
fanned Aaron Ledesma with an outside changeup, 74 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners came out to congratulate Moyer, and Ledesma,
frustrated and baffled, flung his bat across the AstroTurf. It
skidded and landed by the first base coach's box.
</P>
<P>
   That's how hitters can react when Moyer is on.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ball's got a lot of movement; it's all over the place,''
said Ledesma, who was 0-for-4. ``It's tough to get a good swing on
a guy like that. He picks around the plate, and he's got some good
defense behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   The one run Moyer allowed came in the third inning. A single, a
stolen base and a throwing error by catcher Tom Lampkin put a
runner on third with two outs, and brought up the dangerous Jose
Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin rose for an intentional walk, and Moyer fired ball one.
In the M's dugout, manager Lou Piniella was confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where in the hell that intentional walk came
from,'' Piniella said. ``It didn't come from me. ... I've never
seen that in 30 years. I don't want to see it again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my fault,'' Moyer said. ``I probably overthought a
little bit too much. It wasn't that I didn't want to face him, it
was a matter of trying to be smart about it. Lou came out and said,
`What do you want to do?' I said it didn't really matter either
way, so let's face him.''
</P>
<P>
   On a 3-and-1 pitch, Canseco hit a bouncer between third and
short that never left the infield but went for a run-scoring
single. Moyer held the Rays to two singles the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching is location,'' said Lampkin, who doubled and scored
in the fourth. ``If that isn't evident by the way he pitches, I
don't know any better way to explain it. But he's the epitome of
`pitching-is-location.' Yeah, he's got a great changeup and a great
sinker, curveball and cutter. But he wins because of location, not
his pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Moyer is winning frequently. He is 6-1 with a 2.01
ERA in the second half, and has worked at least six innings in all
11 of his starts. Only once in those games has he allowed more than
three earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   That's a consistency few American League pitchers can match. To
Moyer, who started the year 1-4, it's about time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of bothered that I didn't have that consistency in
the first half,'' said Moyer, who had struggled by trying to be
more of a power pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to make a negative out of a positive, but I'm showing
myself today,'' he said. ``Not that I doubted that I could do it,
but it kind of bothers me that it's taken me so long to get into a
steady feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's victory followed the Mariners' four-game sweep by the
Baltimore Orioles, and came when the club was without its top two
setup relievers. Jose Paniagua has a mild groin strain, and Tom
Davey has minor tightness in his forearm.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners needed innings from their starter, and Moyer
provided.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of the series, Moyer presumably will count the
hours until the team's charter leaves for Seattle Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's play two more,'' he said, ``and get the heck out of
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
