u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK     09-15 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS MAY BE DONE AFTER BREAKING BIG TOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Mariners third baseman Russ Davis could
miss the rest of the season after X-rays before Tuesday's game
revealed a fracture of his left big toe.
</P>
<P>
   Davis fouled a pitch off the toe in his second at-bat in
Baltimore Monday night. He homered in his next at-bat and played
the whole game, but had X-rays as a precaution and the results
confirmed the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he'll play again,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
``Maybe he will, but it would be right at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis will have the toe re-examined in 10 days, and said he
hopes to play in the season's final week. He was surprised at the
extent of the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm able to walk around, and everything looks normal,'' said
Davis, who is hitting .245 with a career-high 21 homers. ``Just
playing a game at 100 percent and doing things up on my toes,
pushing off in the field with my weight on my toes, it's pretty
painful. But I never expected to have a crack in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella plans to give Charles Gipson an extended look at third
base as long as Davis is out. Gipson, who could fit in nicely as a
utility player, will play winter ball in Puerto Rico after the
season to work on his hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ABBOTT SKIPPED: Right-hander Paul Abbott will miss Wednesday
night's scheduled start in Tampa Bay with a groin injury suffered
Friday in Baltimore. Ken Cloude, who won his only start since being
recalled from Class AAA Tacoma Aug. 30, will pitch instead.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott was lifted after seven innings and just 96 pitches in his
last start, and the M's went on to lose a 4-3 lead and the game.
This is the first injury this season for Abbott, who has a history
of physical problems and has had groin injuries off and on for 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I absolutely had to pitch, I could,'' Abbott said. ``But
why put it in a situation where it might worsen it? It's hard to
miss a start, but it isn't my arm. It's just a strain that's going
to happen in the course of a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott will throw two bullpen sessions and get treatment before
his next start, which would fall next Monday against Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH FOR THE WINTER: Nearly a quarter of the Mariners' 40-man
roster will take part in winter ball this offseason. Besides
Gipson, pitchers Ken Cloude, Brett Hinchliffe, Sean Spencer and
Eric Weaver will play in Puerto Rico; outfielder Ozzie Timmons and
pitchers Ryan Franklin and Cam Smith will play in Venezuela; and
left-hander Jordan Zimmerman will pitch in the Arizona Fall League.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Raul Ibanez also may play winter ball, and though the
club would like to get infielder Carlos Guillen some at-bats _ if
only as a designated hitter _ in Venezuela, he still is recovering
from an April knee injury and has not been cleared to return.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Freddy Garcia (Venezuela) and Jose Paniagua (Dominican
Republic), who normally play in their respective home countries,
will rest this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Winter ball had one casualty for the M's last year, when Abbott
tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee covering
first base in Puerto Rico. But even sitting-on-the-couch winters
can be dangerous: early-'80s infielder Jamie Allen once hurt his
groin getting up off a couch.
</P>
<P>
   LINEUP SHUFFLE: The M's have used shortstop Alex Rodriguez as
their No. 4 hitter and Edgar Martinez in the No. 5 spot since the
end of July, but Piniella altered the lineup Tuesday. Rodriguez
returned to the No. 2 hole, in front of Ken Griffey Jr., and
Martinez moved to cleanup. Catcher Tom Lampkin batted fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to change it around, see if we can get on track
offensively a little bit,'' Piniella said. ``We haven't hit the
ball real well, so we'll shake things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the All-Star break, playing their home games at
pitcher-friendly Safeco Field and with fewer veteran hitters, the
Mariners have batted .254 with 70 home runs. They hit .284 with 151
homers in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA BASES: The New York Mets acquired minor league pitcher
Justin Dunning from the Mariners to complete the June 18 trade that
sent pitcher Allen Watson to Seattle for Mac Suzuki. Dunning had a
4-4 record with a 5.61 ERA and two saves this season for Seattle's
Class A Wisconsin club. ... The Mariners' game with Anaheim on
Sat., Sept. 25, will start at 6:05 p.m. ... Piniella, on his belief
that the Mariners never would have developed pitching had they
stayed in the Kingdome: ``It's like trying to develop altar boys in
a pool hall _ it just doesn't mix.'' ... Griffey had some fun with
the Devil Rays' mascot, named Raymond, who carried a bull's eye
around his neck and taunted Griffey playfully from the roof of a
center field restaurant. Griffey obliged by throwing three balls at
Raymond, hitting him in the ankle once. The skit was dubbed
``Tiffey With Griffey!'' on the scoreboard. ... Tuesday was the
12th anniversary of Martinez's first career hit, a triple off
Cleveland's Reggie Ritter. Just 12 of Martinez's other 1,540 hits
have been triples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
