<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2483 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     09-15 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL CRIES OUT FOR QB TO FILL ELWAY'S CLEATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Did anyone notice how freaked John Elway appeared
during the Monday Night Football game in which his former team
looked nothing like the two-time defending Super Bowl champs?
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying Denver's new quarterback, Brian Griese, tore
down everything Elway built during his
47-come-from-behind-victories reign. The kid was admirable.
</P>
<P>
   And no one is saying the Broncos are in the tank the way the
Bulls died the minute Michael Jordan packed up his patent leather
sneakers and took to the golf course and started those
long-distance telephone relationships with his cartoon friends.
</P>
<P>
   But seeing Elway in street clothes, unable to run the two-minute
offense and make things happen, was a serious dose of reality for
anyone whose ideal NFL scenario is that the guy behind center is a
guy who can take over a game and snatch a ``W'' out of the jaws of
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Elway may be happily retired, rich and ensconsed in his
post-football life as the ultimate Beer Man. (Did anyone notice
that Coors Banquet Beer has a higher alcohol content than Coors
Light?)
</P>
<P>
   But there is no getting past the fact that the NFL could still
be Elway's, considering the way he towers (in suit and tie) over
what's left of the league's quarterback club.
</P>
<P>
   These are the days in which a guy like Ryan Leaf should wake up
and feel the urge to kick himself, hard.
</P>
<P>
   To possess such a prototypical quarterback body _ not to mention
such a gargantuan signing bonus _ and to let it go to waste ...
especially when the NFL cries out for the heir apparents to an era
in which Elway, Dan Marino, Jim Kelly and Warren Moon lent the NFL
a strong-arme glamour that the league is eager to regain.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the season's first week did not provide a few choice
QBs the opportunity to take over during crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   Marino, who is on his last legs, may have had his best game of
the season. Certainly, the scene was ripe for his Hall of Fame
thievery.
</P>
<P>
   But more than Marino's throwback night, the stage was set in
Week 1 for the next generation to make a splash.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Jake Plummer, Tennessee's Steve McNair, New England's
Drew Bledsoe and Green Bay's Brett Favre each led his team to
come-from-behind wins last Sunday, thanks to last-minute drives
they orchestrated.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Troy Aikman again looked like the Cowboys QB of old.
Aikman led Dallas on a comeback run that erased a 21-point
Washington lead at the end of regulation. Then, thinking he was
going to hand off to Emmitt Smith, Washington was fooled when
Aikman dropped back and nailed a TD pass in overtime to win the NFC
East rivalry match.
</P>
<P>
   The big guys made big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those types of drives are storybook drives,'' Green Bay coach
Ray Rhodes said after Favre shook off the pain of a bruised thumb
to lead Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Favre, in tears after the game, engineered an 11-play, 82-yard
TD drive capped with a 1-yard pass to Jeff Thomason in the final
1:51 with no timeouts remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the types of drives the Favres, the (Joe) Montanas,
the Elways make,'' Rhodes said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe with the absence of Montana, Elway and possibly even Steve
Young _ who looked like Steve Old in the 49ers' train wreck against
Jacksonville _ it is Bledsoe who will make the strongest bid to
become a QB legend.
</P>
<P>
   With the Jets devastated by the loss of Vinny Testaverde and
hurt by a tipped pass by backup Rick Mirer (he of the poor judgment
school of passing), Bledsoe engineered a nifty drive in the
Patriots' win over New York.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:01 left, Bledsoe took the Pats from the Jets' 49-yard
line to their 1 with three seconds left _ just enough time for Adam
Vinatieri to kick the winning field goal. Over the course of the
day, Bledsoe completed 21 of 30 passes for 340 yards, making
Patriots coach Pete Carroll gloat that Bledsoe is back to top form
after injuring his finger last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe is in his seventh season _ a perfect time for him to
take advantage of his talent and experience. NFL observers will
watch with great interest to see if Bledsoe can make good on all
he's got going for him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Jacksonville, another Washington state-tied QB
continues to make his mark. Mark Brunell already has showed supreme
professionalism in guiding the Jags to the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   After these QBs, though, there are a lot of mere mortals in
charge of running NFL offenses this season.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's bad to watch scrappers like Jon Kitna try to
figure it all out in the face of hideous pressure.
</P>
<P>
   And not that there isn't redeeming value in watching likable
guys such as Doug Flutie to see if he can have another magical
season.
</P>
<P>
   And not that there isn't entertainment in tracking the progess
of big-ticket youngsters like Cleveland's Tim Couch, Indianapolis'
Peyton Manning or Chicago's Cade McNown, especially since the ranks
of the heir apparents to Elway's prototypical QB throne do not, at
this point, include a 6-foot-5, 240-pounder named Leaf, who should
be kicking himself.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2484 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BELMONT-REPORT-2TAKES     09-15 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-REPORT-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT ON BELMONT REVEALS WRONGDOING, INCOMPETENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff Writers Beth Barrett, David R. Baker and Dominic Berbeo
contributed to this story 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Exposing massive wrongdoing and a cancer of
incompetence at Los Angeles Unified's highest levels, an internal
audit of the Belmont Learning Center released Tuesday called for
criminal investigations, civil lawsuits and the possible dismissal
of many top officials.
</P>
<P>
   Don Mullinax, the district's inspector general, charged that
officials _ including Superintendent Ruben Zacarias, former school
boards and consultants _ are responsible for allowing the Belmont
Learning Center to be built on a potentially explosive oil and gas
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This culture developed a practice denying responsibility,
deflecting (rather than responding to) criticism, and defending
poorly planned and executed LAUSD actions with regard to Belmont,''
Mullinax wrote in the report on a $200 million project that may
never be completed.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-plus page report, supported by more than 6,000 pages of
evidence, concludes that former school boards were hindered by a
lack of experience in the development of school facilities and
consequently violated state laws in the approval of the nation's
costliest high school.
</P>
<P>
   Finding an absence of policy and procedures to protect the
public's health and safety, investigators recommended overhauling
the district's environmental and legal departments and revamping
its site selection process for schools.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax advised the district to sue several consultants,
including the district's top outside legal counsel, O'Melveny &AMP;
Myers; the lead architect, McLarand, Vasquez and Partners; and
possibly the project developer, Temple Beaudry Partners, led by
Kajima Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   O'Melveny and Myers and Temple Beaudry Partners issued
statements denying wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The report also asserts the state Department of Education and
Governor's Office of Planning and Development failed to adequately
supervise the $200 million project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results of our inquiry are very troubling,'' said
Mullinax, director of the LAUSD Internal Audit and Special
Investigations Unit.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the report is that the school board was repeatedly
misled. Mullinax said his investigators were continuously left
wondering who was in charge because of rampant finger pointing
among the many bureaucrats involved.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax recommended the district discipline, if not fire, nine
employees who ``personally failed to exercise proper management,
supervision, and/or professional execution of their assigned
responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential hit list, which includes the directors and former
directors of the district's facilities, and real estate,
environmental health and safety departments, is topped by Chief
Administrative Officer David Koch and Chief Legal Counsel Richard
K. Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Five former employees, including former Superintendent Sidney
Thompson and retired administrator Dominic Shambra, also were
singled out for blame. It was Shambra who was the driving force
behind the Belmont deal from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Turning his attention to the superintendent, Mullinax advised
the school board to remember ``Zacarias' failure to supervise the
Belmont project in a diligent, professional, and effective manner''
during his next performance evaluation, scheduled for January.
</P>
<P>
   After a five-hour meeting behind closed doors, school board
members issued a terse joint statement saying they had begun
discussions with outside legal advisers on how to proceed with the
recommendations. The statement, read by board President Genethia
Hayes, gave few details on what those steps might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the board, this detailed report, based on a substantial,
seven-month investigation, is the beginning of the process to take
corrective action that will safeguard the public trust in the LAUSD
and ensure fairness and accountability,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the rights of employees named in the report,
Hayes said, it would be ``inappropriate at this time for us to
comment further.''
</P>
<P>
   At the direction of the superintendent, all district employees
were forbidden to comment publicly on the findings. Zacarias'
office ``will be the only point of contact at this time for this
issue,'' said spokesman Erik Nasarenko.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from a prepared statement, Zacarias rejected the
report's criticism of his performance. ``Ironically, I want to note
that I was the first one to recommend the appointment of an
inspector general for this district.''
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias held open the possibility of disciplining or firing
district employees named by the probe. He refused to take any
questions from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, a longtime Belmont
critic, lauded the work of Mullinax and his staff and called for
terminations of the district employees named in the report.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: in the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to hit the ball right on the head,'' Wildman said.
``I would hope that the board and superintendent take this report
seriously. Many of the people named in the report are still working
for the district, and that in itself is criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax and his team of attorneys and investigators were
empowered in February by the school board to investigate how and
why the district decided to build an enormous school downtown atop
an oil field marred by explosive methane gas and other dangerous
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school district's problems are much deeper than this one
problem,'' Mullinax said. ``The real reform will come only when
there is a change in the culture, when there is meaningful action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to hold public officials to the highest
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Having spent $1.2million on his review, Mullinax said a second
report delving into financial matters relating to Belmont will be
issued late this year. The follow-up investigation will attempt to
sort out where the $123million spent on Belmont has gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to find out who was watching the checkbook,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mullinax, numerous district officials were slow in
cooperating with investigators, and some repeatedly refused to
comply with demands for documents.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan said he hopes the report will be used to
make needed changes at the school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, today will be the start of real change. We can no
longer tolerate business as unusual at the LAUSD, especially when
it comes to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a wake-up call to those who would protect the
status quo,'' Riordan said. ``The findings of this report symbolize
the dysfunctional, Byzantine culture that exists at the school
district.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who gave significant campaign contributions to the
reform slate that recently took control of the school board, said
the findings should not only be used for accountability but also to
support meaningful institutional changes at the district.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the school board placed the fate of Belmont into the
hands of a blue ribbon advisory commission. The eclectic group of
eight commissioners, led by former District Attorney Ira Reiner, is
conducting a breakneck review of the pollution-plagued project.
They are scheduled to release a report in late October.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Belmont Learning Complex can be finished in a manner
that achieves the twin goals of public safety and educational
excellence, it should go forward,'' the audit unit report said.
</P>
<P>
   County Supervisor Michael Antonovich, a longtime Belmont critic,
renewed his call for a county grand jury investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unconscionable that our community could tolerate the
district's culture of finger pointing, backside covering and buck
passing by top LAUSD staff that leaves even Mullinax, after an
exhaustive analysis of Belmont, asking, Who is in charge of this
project?''
</P>
<P>
   Antonovich said he will ask his colleagues to pass a resolution
calling on the LAUSD board to adopt the report's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Hayden, a Los Angeles Democrat who wrote legislation to
get Mullinax subpoena power that will be used in follow-up
investigations, questioned the strategy recommended in the report,
calling it a ``beheading and not a surgical change of structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayden argued that the $7 billion institution cries out for
institutional change. In particular, he said, the real estate and
acquisition branch needs to be separated from the educational
functions of the nation's second largest public school system.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he called the recommendation to consider getting
rid of top officials a ``breath of fresh air.'' Now, he said, the
board has to ensure that real change is made. ``Otherwise, who's to
say they won't build more Belmonts?''
</P>
<P>
   Angelo Bellomo, the top environmental consultant on the LAUSD's
recently formed School Safety Team, said the report was a
comprehensive look at the district's practices and could have a
positive effect on where the district goes from here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the whole truth is finally coming out,'' he said.
``This is the time. If we're going to make changes, this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
