<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX POUND INDIANS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-INDIANS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Red Sox fans are not likely to be massed, 10,000
strong, at Logan Airport when the weary sons of Jimy Williams
finally arrive home well after midnight Wednesday, the end of their
13-day criss-crossing of the continent finally at hand.
</P>
<P>
   But what these Sox have accomplished on this journey is no more
improbable, or less impressive, than what the Cardiac Kids of '67
did when they reeled off 10 in a row on the road and were hailed as
conquering heroes upon their return.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were two games ahead of the Oakland A's in the wild-card
race when this trip began in Seattle on Labor Day weekend. They
guaranteed themselves of being at least that far ahead when they
wake up Thursday morning by clobbering the Cleveland Indians, 12-3,
behind Ramon the Elder, reliever Derek Lowe, and a 16-hit attack
that featured Troy O'Leary's game-breaking three-run home run and
mocked any hint of battle fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Williams admitted the trip has taken its toll in one respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only problem I have is remembering my room number,'' he
said. ``I got on the bus back to the hotel Tuesday night and
couldn't remember my room number.''
</P>
<P>
   With the A's 13-6 losers to Baltimore Tuesday night and Pedro
the Younger _ who has never lost to the Indians _ set to follow his
brother Ramon Martinez to the mound for the trip finale Wednesday,
the Sox, now 8-3 in this trip/defining crucible, are in a position
to double their lead by the time they arrive home.
</P>
<P>
   With 17 games left, they lead the A's by three games for the
wild card while remaining 3 1/2 behind the Yankees in the AL East.
The Yankees essentially eliminated Toronto as a wild-card contender
by winning Tuesday night, 10-6, in a game they trailed, 6-2, with
two outs in the eighth. The Jays trail Boston by 6 1/2 games, seven
in the loss column.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys in here are aching and hurting,'' said Lowe, who
replaced Martinez with the Sox ahead, 7-3, with two on and two out
in the fifth, then retired all 10 Indians he faced to gain credit
for the win. ``You've got to put that aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when courage and the will to win kicks in, and we have
a lot of it in here. You can't ever stop. Our goal is to win the
World Series, which means there's a month and a half left. You have
to prepare yourself physically and mentally to keep pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who was all but dismissed as a helping hand 12 days
ago, when he pitched just three innings and was dropped from the
rotation one day later, came within one out of recording his first
win in more than 15 months Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ramon Martinez I saw today is the Ramon Martinez I know,''
said Jose Offerman, who was a Dodger teammate during Martinez's
glory days and helped his good friend and fellow Dominican Tuesday
night with four hits, two runs, an RBI, and a stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who was pitching only because Pat Rapp was home where
his wife is struggling with a difficult pregnancy, was lifted him
for Lowe after he walked two straight batters, raising his pitch
count to 94.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez may yet prove to be the saving grace for a rotation
that changes from minute to minute (When Williams was asked before
the game what the state of his rotation was, he responded with
Jimywocky: ``It's in Ohio, and Friday it will be in Boston.'')
</P>
<P>
   Could Martinez &AMP; Martinez be double trouble for the American
League down the stretch? Ramon broke into a broad smile at the
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother, he's going tomorrow,'' he said. ``I got a chance,
an opportunity to win a game last night. I hope I get another
chance, and I'm going to try and do better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, meanwhile, teed off on Dwight Gooden, who may have
pitched his last game as an Indian. There was widespread
speculation that Gooden, who has had a bad shoulder and is now 3-4
with a 6.38 ERA, is about to be released. In eight career starts
against the Sox, he's 0-5 with an 8.36 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon homered for the second straight night, this time with
Wilton Veras on board in the third with the first of his three
hits. The diminished Doc was dismissed with the Sox ahead, 4-2, in
the fifth after issuing an intentional walk to Nomar Garciaparra
with Reggie Jefferson on second. Offerman had tried to score on
Jefferson's hit, but was erased at the plate when third-base coach
Wendell Kim sent him home, even though charging center fielder
Kenny Lofton already had the ball when Offerman reached third.
</P>
<P>
   Indians manager Mike Hargrove brought in a lefty, Mark Langston,
to face O'Leary. But O'Leary bailed out Kim and crossed up Hargrove
by hitting a 1-and-0 pitch for his 27th home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just part of baseball, you know,'' said O'Leary, who
also singled home a run in the seventh for his first four-RBI night
of the season, giving him 99. ``You're always going to try to go
with the odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Has he changed those odds with his performance this season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't changed anything,'' said O'Leary, who over the
weekend attributed his home run off the foul pole in Yankee Stadium
to the ``luck of the Irish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who over the weekend clinched their season series
against the Yankees, the first-place team in the AL East, did the
same Wednesday night against the Indians, whom they have beaten six
times in nine meetings. Battle fatigue? Offerman shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where we're playing, we're in a position where we
have to win some games,'' he said. ``And that's exactly what we're
doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
