<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-SUPERINTENDENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUSD SUPERINTENDENT SAYS HE MET OBLIGATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff Writer Beth Barrett contributed to this story 
BY DAVID R. BAKER AND GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Superintendent Ruben Zacarias rejected an
internal audit's finding that his leadership of the nation's second
largest school district contributed to problems plaguing the
Belmont Learning Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can in no way agree with the report's assertion that I
failed to supervise the Belmont project in a diligent, professional
and effective manner,'' Zacarias said.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from a prepared statement, Zacarias _ his voice hushed
by a recent bout of laryngitis _ said he would implement the
report's recommendations and deal with its call for severe
discipline, including possible dismissal, of nine subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   But he argued he fulfilled his own obligations, saying he
immediately took steps to gain control of Belmont _ a $200 million
school construction project _ after taking office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent said he quickly disbanded the Office of
Planning and Development branch overseeing the project and
appointed a chief administrative officer to run the business side
of the district, including school construction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Zacarias said he spearheaded efforts to create an
environmental safety team to provide ``quality technical advice on
environmental matters at Belmont'' and mandated no new school would
be built without approval from the state Department of Toxic
Substances Control.
</P>
<P>
   Don Mullinax, the district's top investigator, included Zacarias
on a list of 15 former and current Los Angeles Unified School
District employees who failed to ``exercise proper management'' in
regard to Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax advised the school board to consider Zacarias' role in
the scandal during his job review, which is scheduled for January.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias held open the possibility of disciplining, possibly
firing, district employees for their performance on Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I have not as yet had the opportunity to thoroughly
study the document, I am taking the report's finding and
recommendations very seriously and plan to respond in an
expeditious, forthright and appropriate manner,'' Zacarias said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles, a frequent LAUSD critic,
defended Zacarias, saying the superintendent deserved credit for
starting the very process that led to Tuesday's report criticizing
his own performance.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than rush to demand Zacarias' ouster, Hayden said he
wanted to hear the superintendent's side of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to give him a chance to explain himself,'' Hayden
said ``If he gets up there and says he was part of the previous
administrations but he supports reform and he embraces this report,
why should we fire him?''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
