<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BO     09-15 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON MARTINEZ PITCHES IN
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-INDIANS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Does this look like a winning pitcher line to you?
</P>
<P>
   4 2/3 3 3 3 4 5
</P>
<P>
   It sure did to Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, he was the winning pitcher,'' declared the Red Sox
mentor, who had to make a painful decision to lift comebacking
Ramon Martinez with one out standing between him and his first
official major league victory in well over a year.
</P>
<P>
   But on these 1999 Boston Red Sox, individual goals are secondary
to the Big Picture. What mattered was that the Sox trampled
Cleveland by a 12-3 score Tuesday night at Jacobs Field, raising
their road trip record to 8-3 with the World's Best Pitcher
awaiting his regular turn Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big stat night for the Olde Towne Team. Jose Offerman
was 4 for 4 and on base five times. Troy O'Leary had a big
three-run homer and four runs batted in, leaving him one shy of his
first 100-ribbie season. Wilton Veras again proved himself
oblivious to the pressure of a two-tiered major league pennant race
with three hits. Trot Nixon, the apple of his teacher's eye
(``Trot's doing fine,'' beamed Williams. ``Trot's a good player''),
knocked out his 13th homer of the season. Derek Lowe set down all
10 Indians he faced.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hollywood story was the starting pitcher. Ramon Martinez
earned the gratitude and admiration of his manager and teammates by
giving a pitching-strapped staff a chance to win a big ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   The elegant Dominican embarked on this road trip with no
guarantees he would pitch again the rest of the season. Williams
had handed him the ball Sept. 2 (five hits and four earned runs in
three-plus innings against Kansas City), but the skipper had no
apparent intention of giving him another start until circumstances
got so bad that he almost had no choice. This was supposed to be
Pat Rapp's turn, but he was back in Louisiana. Kent Mercker was
unavailable because of torn rib cartilage. Williams no longer feels
comfortable with Mark Portugal, although he did feel daring enough
to allow the veteran an opportunity to pitch the ninth inning with
a nine-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Martinez had a conversation back in Seattle, at
which time the skipper told the hurler that he really didn't know
when, or if, he would be calling on him. The Martinez response was
to go out and work his slender butt off, and this made a tremendous
impression on his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never told me I wouldn't get another start,'' Martinez
reported. ``He just told me it was a difficult situation, and I do
understand that we are in a pennant race and it is very difficult
for him to take a chance with me. But I never stopped working. I
worked hard every day, hoping I would get that chance, and I wanted
to take advantage of that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was one pitch and one dropped throw away from blanking
the mighty Cleveland Indians. He sailed through the first three
innings nicely, the only hit being a first-inning two-out double by
Roberto Alomar. With a man on first and two away in the fourth, he
made his one mistake, a fastball that was supposed to be in but
hung out over the plate. Jim Thome feasts on those type of errors.
He knocked the ball over the dead center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez deserved a better fate in the fifth, too. Sandy Alomar
led off with a shot into the left-field corner. O'Leary, an
underrated outfielder, played the carom perfectly and then uncorked
a throw that had Alomar beaten at second. But Offerman dropped the
throw. A ground ball to first moved Alomar over, and he scored on
an Omar Vizquel sacrifice fly. Martinez walked Robby Alomar,
bringing Williams to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was going to give me one more batter,'' explained
Martinez, whose pitch count was heading into the 90s by that point.
But I couldn't get that guy out.''
</P>
<P>
   He got ahead of David Justice, 0-and-2, but the wily veteran
wound up working him for a walk. Williams didn't want to take any
chances with what was then a 7-3 lead, so he replaced Martinez with
Lowe, whose sinker completely dominated the Indians for the next 3
1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The W would have been nice, but it wouldn't have made Martinez
any better than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really pitched great,'' lauded Williams. ``It meant a lot
to our ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had better control tonight than in the first game,''
Martinez said. ``I felt relaxed. I don't even feel I had surgery. I
was relaxed. I just wanted to go out there and throw strikes, and
that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   He stuck with two pitches, his fastball and his changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had late life and late movement on both of them,'' said
Jason Varitek, who was catching the former LA 20-game winner for
the first time. ``With the one exception, when he missed, he was
off the plate or in. It was fun to catch him. He's a pure
professional in every way. You can see he's been pitching for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   He did exactly what Williams said he'd do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to seeing Ramon pitch tonight,'' the
mentor was saying before the game. ``I think he's gonna pitch a
good game.''
</P>
<P>
   As aware as Williams was of what the performance meant to
Martinez personally, what it ultimately meant was one more victory
for the Boston Red Sox. Williams deals with issues one day at a
time, as a local radio guy discovered when he asked Williams about
the possibility of Martinez being on the postseason roster, and
thus facing the Indians three weeks hence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play tomorrow,'' he said. ``That's all I can tell you.
We've got a scheduled game tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's got another Martinez going. As Jimy himself might say,
you can bet he was planning on sleepin' good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
