<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2516 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BELMONT-CULTURE-2TAKE     09-15 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-CULTURE-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT BLASTS LAUSD'S CULTURE OF LYING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Belmont Learning Center scandal is
symptomatic of a pervasive culture of lying, finger pointing, power
games, disregard for the law and wholesale shirking of
responsibility that permeates top management of the nation's
second-largest school district, the Mullinax report concluded
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Los Angeles Unified School District has tolerated
repeated violations of policies and procedures without calling
employees to account, disciplining them or even mentioning
employees by name, said Don Mullinax, director of the district's
internal audit and special investigations unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was ever held responsible or accountable for their
actions,'' he said. ``A report would read, `A procedure was not
followed, next time follow the procedure.' No names were ever
mentioned, no one was held accountable, no discipline was given
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping today that will change, but it's not going to
happen overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   The report validated what many critics have said is at the heart
of the district's failures in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we've been saying about the school district for
two decades,'' said Day Higuchi, president of United Teachers Los
Angeles. ``It speaks to a culture that's been in place for 30 years
or more. Now the people who should be accountable need to act. The
culture is about to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax, LAUSD's inspector general, launched his investigation
seven months ago, amid growing evidence that environmental problems
caused by old oil wells and widespread presence of explosive
methane gas at the Belmont site posed serious health hazards.
</P>
<P>
   His mission was to determine how the district decided to locate
what would be the nation's most expensive high school at $200
million without proper safety precautions, and to assign
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The former Senate investigator said he studied past district
documents regarding policies and practices covering several years
and interviewed 65 officials extensively.
</P>
<P>
   What he learned, he said, was that from a succession of school
boards and superintendents, the LAUSD evolved a culture that
allowed on-top managers to avoid all responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a general failure to demand professionalism from
district staff who in turn failed to properly oversee their
employees and outside consultants.
</P>
<P>
   The report said former school boards generally operated under
``rudderless'' policies for Belmont in terms of acquisition,
development and evaluation of environmental risks at the school.
</P>
<P>
   The boards ``tolerated a culture remarkably indifferent to
compliance . . . This culture developed a practice of denying
responsibility, deflecting (rather than responding to) criticism,
and defending poorly planned and executed LAUSD actions with regard
to Belmont,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Absent scrutiny from the top, LAUSD staff became so
undisciplined that ``turf rivalry and internal bickering'' became
so commonplace that they no longer were able to exercise their
responsibilities, including the oversight of consultants, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   As the district staff became increasingly cavalier, they
``misled'' the board on such vital issues as the environmental
risks associated with Belmont, even failing to warn board members
they might be in danger of violating _ and in some cases already
had _ state environmental and other laws.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax said the LAUSD's culture of ``denial and deflection''
was able to thrive, because no one ever demanded that anyone step
forward and take responsibility for projects, most notably Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax said that after 65 interviews and reviewing thousands
of documents it remains almost impossible today to know who
actually should have been responsible _ let alone who was
responsible _ for Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all said they were coordinators,'' Mullinax. ``They
pointed fingers. Hardly anyone took responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The LAUSD's habit of stonewalling remains so strong that at
least one official waited months before turning over documents, and
Mullinax said he's not convinced the LAUSD has fully complied with
the document requests even yet.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Roger Friermuth, a project manager
within the Project Management and Construction branch, did not
provide 11 boxes of documents to investigators until Aug. 10,
though they had been requested in March. Friermuth supplied one box
of materials in April, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   Friermuth did not return calls for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends Friermuth be disciplined up to
termination, saying he failed to require the developer, Temple
Beaudry Partners LLC, to properly design and install a methane
barrier system beneath Belmont and also failed to obtain the proper
environmental assessment of excavated and removed contaminated
soil.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT PAGE)
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: contaminated soil.
</P>
<P>
   Friermuth told investigators he had ``no say'' in the design and
construction of the facility and that he was ``not responsible''
for the environmental assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax said the district's lack of forthcomingness is
``endemic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a school district that does not want to cooperate,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   An extensive log contained in the report reveals how difficult
the document acquisition process was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defensive and uncooperative behavior of some senior staff
within the district coupled with the hesitancy of many staffers to
release Belmont-related documents or cooperate with the
investigation made the internal auditor's job of ferreting out the
truth all the more arduous and time-consuming,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax said the district has been resistant to change for
years, but said even the most entrenched cultures can be changed.
He said that requires both consideration of the disciplinary
recommendations and more far-reaching structural changes
recommended in the report.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the employment of senior managers to be held
responsible for school facilities and environmental compliance, as
well as an independent counsel to the school board. That attorney
would give the board advice apart from that now provided by General
Counsel Richard Mason. The report said it had probable cause to
believe Mason failed to make sure the board did not violate state
environmental laws, failed to supervise outside counsel and failed
to cooperate with the investigation. Mason declined comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a first step in restoring accountability and
credibility in the school district,'' Mullinax said. ``The report
is to the board. It's up to them to take action.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
