r a BC-DISNEY-HALL-LADN     09-15 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-HALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY CONCERT HALL APPROVED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Facing criticism that Los Angeles County would
subsidize the center to the tune of $12 million a year, county
supervisors gave final approval Tuesday to the downtown Walt Disney
Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We the taxpayers are going to pay an additional $12 million a
year for 25 years for this,'' said Supervisor Gloria Molina. ``The
net county cost will be close to $550 million during the 65-year
life of this contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Supervisors voted 5-0 to approve final legal
documents related to the construction of the $18 million Cal Arts
Theater and the $231 million Walt Disney Concert Hall, the home of
the Los Angeles Philharmonic Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Although the concert hall and theater construction costs are
financed through donations raised by Disney, the county is
responsible for the maintenance of the center and parking garage.
The largest maintenance costs will include those for utilities,
security and ushers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now confirmed that the county is also responsible for
maintaining the exclusive `Founders Room', a lounge within the hall
that only those patrons who have contributed over $35,000 can
enjoy,'' Molina said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Molina proposed a motion that would continue
approval of the concert hall until the supervisors agreed on
finding funding to expand the Los Angeles County/USC Medical
Center, which is seeking to build a satellite hospital with either
60 or 125 beds in Baldwin Park.
</P>
<P>
   But no one would second her motion.
</P>
<P>
   She said she voted for the concert hall because she has always
supported it.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky said the subsidy was justified
because the public will be enriched by the concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Disney Concert Hall is going to be the premier
philharmonic hall in the world,'' Yaroslavsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the cultural side, this is a very valuable asset for the
community,'' said Disney Hall board Chairman Bill Siart. ``On the
economic side, it's going to be an economic boom for Los Angeles in
terms of sales tax revenue and attendance fees paid to the
county.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction permits for the center are expected to be issued
this month.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 0222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
