<HEADLINE>
VAN NUYS AIRPORT TAKES OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAN NUYS _ Van Nuys Airport generated $1.23 billion in economic
activity last year, up 30 percent from 1991, and supported more
than 10,000 jobs, according to a report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Keys to the facility's growth have been the improvement of the
Southern California economy and the rising use of corporate jets,
leading to an 8 percent rise in takeoffs and landings to 551,622 in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, the economy has been very good in Southern
California since the recession, and the airport and aviation
industries have done very well,'' said airport Manager Jens Rivera.
``The airport's close proximity to city business centers makes it a
natural choice of major business users.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by Wilbur Smith Associates, found $191.8
million in direct economic impact at or near the airport led by
$63.2 million for aircraft operators, $41.5 million for aircraft
services, $38.7 million for corporate operators and $18.8 million
for air taxis and charters.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed indirect impact of $96 million from the
312,700 visitors to the facility; multiplier revenue for
aviation-related businesses totaled $499.3 million, from money
originally generated through the airport; and nonaviation
multiplier revenue of $276.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this shows is the economic significance of the airport
beyond its actual margins,'' said Robert Rodine, airport committee
chairman for the Mid Valley Chamber of Commerce and a member of the
airport's citizens advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the job growth came in the aviation sector with a 22
percent jump to 6,584 jobs; nonaviation jobs edged up 3 percent to
3,443. The report noted that even though the number of total
aircraft based at Van Nuys has decreased, the rise in corporate
jets has spurred economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jet aircraft typically require 4 to 10 (or more) people
employed in a full-time capacity to fly, service and administer the
aircraft,'' the report said. ``These jobs are typically high-paying
skilled positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Williams, a homeowner living three miles from the airport
and a member of an appointed task force on airport noise, said the
report was inadequate because it does not address the issue of the
reduced value of real estate due to aircraft noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has been looking at the financial impact of airport
noise on property owners,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also said the report shows there is plenty of demand
for business at the airport so that the louder Stage 2 jets, built
before 1983, could be banned from the airport without economic
hardship. The airport commission decided in July to allow Stage 2
jets already stationed at Van Nuys to remain there.
</P>
<P>
   The report was presented this week at the start of public
hearings at the airport on the issue of aircraft noise and the
facility's operating variance, which allows aircraft to exceed
standards in some areas. The administrative law judge conducting
the hearings will make a recommendation to the state Department of
Transportation, which issues such variances.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes on the heels of a move by Los Angeles World
Airports, which runs the Van Nuys facility, to set aside $15
million for soundproofing 150 homes and 900 apartments near the
airport. The work is expected to start next summer.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
