<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SHUT DOWN BY ANOTHER NOBODY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At least the Los Angeles Dodgers didn't get no-hit
by Eric Milton.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they got one-hit by 23-year-old Montreal right-hander
Javier Vazquez in another ugly footnote to an even uglier season.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez struck out a career-high 10 and retired the last 17
Dodgers as the Expos won 3-0 Tuesday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' only hit was a clean single between shortstop and
third by Mark Grudzielanek to lead off the fourth. Two batters
later Vazquez walked Gary Sheffield but got out of the inning by
retiring Eric Karros and Raul Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only inning in which the Dodgers had a baserunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cy Young out there,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Johnson should know. The Dodgers have turned their share
of mediocre opposing pitchers into reasonable facsimiles of
baseball's winningest pitcher. Losing to pitchers with inferior
statistics is now commonplace on a team that continues to follow
disturbing trends.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez (8-7) entered the night with a 5.41 ERA. On the road, he
was 3-4 with a 7.33 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez mixed his fastball with his curve and changeup to look
as seasoned as his counterpart, Dodgers ace Kevin Brown, who, as it
happens, is the last pitcher to one-hit the Dodgers. Brown did it
July 16, 1997, when he was pitching the Florida Marlins toward the
World Series (which is far from where the Dodgers will be next
month).
</P>
<P>
   ``I had good location with my fastball, had a good curve and a
good changeup,'' Vazquez said. ``That doesn't happen often, when
you have all your pitches working.''
</P>
<P>
   It does, however, seem to happen more regularly than one would
expect when the Dodgers are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek lined out to second baseman Jose Vidro to start the
bottom of the first. Vidro then ranged behind second to retire
Craig Counsell on a grounder for the second out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But other than Grudzielanek's single off a Vazquez changeup in
the fourth, there weren't any difficult plays. Just difficult play
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty good pitch (to Grudzielanek in the fourth),''
Vazquez said. ``He did a good job of staying with it. It was
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez's domination puts Brown (16-8) in a must-win situation
in his last four starts if he's to reach the 20-win mark for the
second time in his career. But the way the Dodgers' offense tends
to disappear, don't hold your breath until you turn Dodger blue for
that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   In his last start, Brown allowed one earned run and struck out
seven in eight innings against the Mets. The Dodgers lost 3-1 and
had two hits, but none after the fourth inning. Mets starter Orel
Hershiser retired the last 15 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   A nice outing, but done one better by Vazquez, who threw 111
pitches and barely broke a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the game he didn't have it and he got by with his
fastball,'' Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley said. ``In the fourth,
fifth inning, he found his curveball. It seemed like his fastball
wasn't the greatest, but he had the equalizer working with his
curveball and changeup. Makes your fastball a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado pitcher John Thomson (1-7, 7.95 ERA) could be in for
the experience of a lifetime. He opposes Brown at Coors Field on
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
