<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCRHON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG THIEVES, NOTHING IS SACRED
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hang onto your valuables, folks, because the bad
guys are getting more desperate, or more creative.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, thieves made off with priceless bells from two
San Francisco churches.
</P>
<P>
   Now someone has ripped off the barber pole hanging over the
entrance of the Exchange Barber Shop on Pine Street in the
Financial District.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed up for work Monday morning and the pole was gone,''
says shop owner Ken Connell.
</P>
<P>
   The Exchange opened in 1926, and the pole had hung there for at
least 50 years. Connell had it reconditioned recently.
</P>
<P>
   A new pole costs about $650; the old ones are valuable antiques.
Connell is offering a $200 reward.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional red, white and blue swirly barber poles, Connell
notes, are symbolic of the time when barbers, who were also
blood-letters, hung their bloody towels to dry outside their shops.
``Though  &UR; I've  &LR; never done that,'' Connell says.
</P>
<P>
   THE ASHES of Joe DiMaggio Jr., who died August 7 of an asthma
attack at age 57, will be scattered over the bay Wednesday by a few
family members.
</P>
<P>
   Joey D, as his friends called him, was the only child of the
Yankee Clipper. And it's hard to say who had the tougher end of the
strange father-son relationship. For sure, that relationship was a
burden to both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Joe died March 8, a wealthy, dignified and deity-like American
hero and noted recluse. Joey D died in poverty, a Yale-educated man
who lived for a time in a freight container in Antioch, worked
occasionally in a scrapyard and not long ago was ticketed for
riding a bicycle while under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe lay dying in a Florida hospital, Joey D never visited.
He said later he would have come in an instant if his father had
asked for him. Friends say Joe felt he shouldn't have to invite his
son to his deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a disappointment to each other,'' says Sam Spear, a
Bay Area racetrack exec who was good friends with Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Neither father nor son could comprehend the other's demons. They
were never close, probably never played catch. Joe never came to
Joey's high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   To the end, Joey called his dad ``Sir.'' Family insiders say Joe
was jealous of Joey's closeness to his mother, Dorothy Arnold, and
to Marilyn Monroe, Joe's second wife.
</P>
<P>
   Sam tells of driving Joe around the backstreets of Martinez on
more than one occasion, searching for Joey, trying to make a
connection.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Joe died, Joey D dug out an old Joe DiMaggio bat
and took some cuts on the porch of his trailer in Pittsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, by now maybe the Clipper and his kid have it all
sorted out.
</P>
<P>
   GOOFY EUPHEMISMS, Corporate Division: If you wish to discuss
your AT&AMP;T Cable (TV) Services bill in the East Bay, Shirley
Hockings has discovered, you are connected to an ``Entertainment
Consultant,'' and who couldn't use one of those?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; So, what should I do right now _ Watch the ``Late Show'' &LR; 
 &UR; re-run, play Yahtzee with my cat, or go look for a hooker? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   And CellularOne's phone jockeys are called Customer Care, so
give 'em a call if you need a billing adjustment or a pedicure.
</P>
<P>
   IT MUST BE TOUGH being rich and trying to figure out how to
unload all that money.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-based CityAuction auctioned off U.S. Open goodies
for charity over the weekend. A pair of oversized tennis balls
scribblegraphed by Open players went for $10,442, and a racket Pete
Sampras used in winning the '96 Open went for $33,722.
</P>
<P>
   And ... the Four Seasons Hotel in New York is quoting a starting
price for single rooms _ $840.
</P>
<P>
   I'm impressed. I've stayed in hotels that I could've bought for
$840, cockroaches included.
</P>
<P>
   HEY YOU: Confidential to Mystery Caller: Don't do it, I can't
afford to lose a reader. And I want to know if I was right about
``Bowfinger.''
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BIZ: Headline in Marin Independent Journal: ``Two years
after her death, Diana's memory fades.''
</P>
<P>
   And Terry Gordan says, ``I'll bet that by now her reflexes are
pretty well shot, too.''
</P>
<P>
   PEACE POETS: Four San Francisco poets _ Marc Joseph, James Kass,
Biko Eisen-Martin and Jason Mateo _ are just back from southern
Bosnia, where they were trying to spread peace as part of a
movement called ``Youth Against War.''
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone should be against war, it's youth, which
traditionally does most of the dying in wars.
</P>
<P>
   The S.F. poets led poetry workshops for young Bosnians,
Croatians and Albanians _ ``To give them an outlet for expressing
their truths,'' says Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Poetry diplomacy? Look, I don't understand it, but it's got to
be better than whatever people over there have been trying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 0341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
