<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-DONORS-SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DONORS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIQUE STUDY LOOKS AT BUSH DONORS, SHOWS FEW WORKING WOMEN ON 
 LIST
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two-thirds of recent donors to the campaign of GOP presidential
hopeful George W. Bush are men, but women _ particularly homemakers
_ have been the more generous contributors.
</P>
<P>
   That is the finding of a new computer analysis of Bush's newly
released campaign data by programmers at a Silicon Valley startup
company.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Bush's campaign became the first to post daily donor
information on his Internet website _ an innovation praised by
campaign finance watchdogs and technology buffs alike.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrating how instantaneously Silicon Valley and its
fast-evolving innovations can affect the political scene, all
41,000 files of Bush's donor list were immediately put under the
microscope by programmers at Palo Alto, Calif.-based Inxight
Software.
</P>
<P>
   Using the company's new software program called Table Lens, the
programmers began chopping, shuffling and charting the July and
August donation data to illustrate exactly what it could show about
Bush and the people who give to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see lots of patterns very quickly,'' said Steve
Bernstein, director of marketing at Inxight. Among the firm's
findings:
</P>
<P>
   -- Two-thirds of Bush's donors are men, but the average donation
is higher for women.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Homemakers'' represent 5 percent of Bush's donors and write
the biggest checks. Their median donation: $1,000, or the maximum
legal amount for the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they are part of wealthy couples who donate to the
max,'' said Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   -- One in 4 donors to Bush's campaign in July and August had
given the legal maximum. But some got carried away entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 600 people gave donations during July and August that
put them over the legal limit _ and of those over the limit,
three-fourths are at least double the legal limit,'' the analysis
said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fifteen percent of the donors were retired, and they gave a
median donation of $50.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said the way Bush's Web site posted the data was
surprisingly amateurish and difficult to analyze.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Bush) donor data isn't all one big file _ it actually
started out in 18 little files, each of which you had to
download,'' said Bernstein. ``One of their files is a broken link.
You can't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's common on amateur Web sites, but for such a prominent
Web site on which they got so much coverage, they should have been
a lot more careful,'' Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Inxight CEO Robert P. Lee was quick to praise the Bush
campaign for making the data accessible, and he said he hopes the
company's analysis will help people make sense of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need an easier way to analyze this massive and
ever-growing amount of data.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm's charting of the Bush donor information can be viewed
at  &UR; www.inxight.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 0342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
