r a BC-MENTALILL-ELDERLY-SFC     09-15 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTALILL-ELDERLY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG RISE PREDICTED IN MENTAL ILLNESS AMONG ELDERLY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ``unprecedented explosion'' in psychiatric problems among the
elderly is about to hit the country, and the U.S. medical system is
woefully unprepared, a panel of psychiatric health specialists
warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Boomers start reaching retirement age in 2011, the experts
noted, signaling a new generation of geriatric mental health issues
involving such problems as substance abuse, late-onset
schizophrenia, anxiety disorders and depression.
</P>
<P>
   A projected 15 million cases of psychiatric disorders, triple
the current caseload, are expected among those age 65 and older by
the time the post-war demographic wave crests in 2030.
</P>
<P>
   The health system already serves mentally ill older adults
poorly, according to a national ``consensus statement'' on the
problem, issued Tuesday by an 11-member panel in the Archives of
General Psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   Authors called for a long-term research and treatment plan to
cope with ``the upcoming crisis in geriatric mental health.'' They
forecast a 275 percent jump in psychiatrically ill elderly from
1970 to 2030, versus only a 67 percent increase in comparable cases
among those ages 30-44.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mental illness in the elderly is underdiagnosed and
undertreated,'' said lead author Dr. Dilip Jeste, director of
geriatric psychiatry at the University of California at San Diego.
``If we do nothing about it, the cost will be social disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel outlined a 15- to 25-year plan to retool medical
schools and health providers to deal with psychiatric problems
expected to beset aging Baby Boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Even detecting such conditions is fraught with difficulty among
older people because of gaps in research and age-biased diagnostic
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of our current perspective is based on studies of young
adults,'' the panel noted.
</P>
<P>
   Projections of a large increase in geriatric mental illness
follow other recent studies showing a relatively high incidence of
mental health disorders among those born during the post-World War
II boom. Factors include greater willingness to seek help, less
family support and higher risk of alcoholism and substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Drug problems were cited as a particularly telling example of
the aging face of mental health care.
</P>
<P>
   Use of illicit substances has rarely been considered much of a
problem before among the elderly. In the latest
government-sponsored studies, fewer than 0.1 percent of people
older than age 65 had used an illicit drug within the prior month,
compared with 3.5 percent of those ages 18 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   But that may start to change as survivors of the drug culture
spawned in the '60s and '70s reach old age. One recent study in the
journal Psychiatric Services, which Jeste co-authored, said
demographics alone dictate a steady rise in recreational drug use
and related problems among the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The latest cross-generational data on drug-taking behavior
``suggest that some Baby Boomers have continued to use illicit
drugs as they age,'' the study noted, ``and due to their sheer
numbers we can expect larger numbers of current drug users to reach
age 65 and potentially impact treatment programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides illicit-drug use and alcohol problems, older people also
are vulnerable to problems caused by prescription medications _
problems that often show themselves in the form of psychiatric
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often overlooked,'' said Doug Hennig, a geriatric social
worker and founder of a new Web site  &UR; (www.agenet.com) &LR;  aimed at
aging adults and care givers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of health issues are going to have to be dealt with in
terms appropriate for this age group, including the mental health
issue,'' Hennig said.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding dementia, which is usually due to Alzheimer's and
affects about 10 percent of the elderly, current estimates show
that 13 percent of those over age 65 meet the standard criteria for
having a psychiatric disorder.
</P>
<P>
   That is ``a serious underestimation,'' according to Jeste and
his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, drawn from leading institutions across the country
including the National Institute of Mental Health, noted that
social stigma tends to discourage people from seeking treatment,
while current diagnostic methods tend to be skewed toward younger
people.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the experts said, many psychiatric conditions are
gauged in terms of their impact on work lives and other criteria
that become less appropriate as the population ages. The panel also
noted ``pervasive ageism'' among caregivers, citing one survey that
found only 35 percent of primary care internists felt confident
prescribing anti-depressants to elderly patients, while
three-quarters considered depression ``understandable,'' and hence
not worth treating, for people 65 and older.
</P>
<P>
   When all the complicating factors are taken into account, the
new consensus statement concluded that nearly 20 percent of today's
elderly have ``serious psychopathologic symptoms,'' not counting
those with delirium and other disorders considered secondary to
general medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   That number is expected to rise to nearly 22 percent as the
population ages. Besides more problems overall, the experts
envision higher proportions of patients in need of long-term care
because of earlier diagnoses of psychiatric conditions and
decreased mortality from physical illness.
</P>
<P>
   The panel called for a 15- to 25-year research agenda, a push to
train more psychiatrists and psychologists specializing in serving
an older population, fewer health-plan restrictions on prescription
drugs and outpatient services and ``a reduced social stigma against
the elderly mentally ill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
