<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 03:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SEGA-SEGA_SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEGA-SEGA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Despite Glitch, Sales Strong for Dreamcast 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Stein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Despite a potentially devastating software glitch, Sega's new
Dreamcast video gaming system is racking up impressive sales at
retail outlets across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sega of America in San Francisco said $132 million in revenue
was generated from the sale of 372,000 Dreamcast systems since the
product first went on the market on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The figures include sales of the 19 games that can be used with
the Dreamcast system. Sega officials said for each $199 Dreamcast
system sold, consumers are buying about three games.
</P>
<P>
   The only hitch last week occurred when consumers complained that
some Dreamcast games simply did not work with the new console. Sega
officials admitted that a small portion of its games were hit with
a manufacturing problem.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company was quick to point out the Dreamcast
console was unaffected, industry observers said the problem could
be more serious and affect the operation of many more games than
the company claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bellfield, director of marketing communications at Sega,
said the company expects to sell an additional 100 million
Dreamcast units by the end of this weekend. He said Sega's
distribution channel will be tapped out after that, but the company
expects to ship new consoles to retail stores by the end of
September or early October.
</P>
<P>
   Sega officials are pleased with the sales response so far,
especially in light of the disastrous launch of its Saturn system
four years ago. That gaming console sorely disappointed customers
and game developers with its high sticker price and buggy
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturn debacle caused Sega to see its share of the U.S.
gaming market fall from about 50 percent four years ago to about 1
percent today. Sega expects its market share to rise dramatically
thanks to the release of Dreamcast, although the current software
glitch could dampen those expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Sega's Bellfield said less than 1 percent of all games in the
latest release were defective and that the company was encouraging
customers to return those games to retailers for a refund or
exchange. ``If this was really a serious problem, we would not have
seen the kind of sales we have so far.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Funk, editorial director for gaming magazines Electronic
Gaming Monthly and Expert Gamer, thinks the software glitch _ which
affects the Blue Stinger, Sonic Adventure, Hydro Thunder and Ready
2 Rumble games _ may be more serious than Sega has stated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just judging from reader e-mails, I'd say about 5 to 10
percent of those games are defective,'' he said. He adds that one
of his co-workers had to return five copies of Sonic Adventure
before he got one that worked.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential impediment to future Dreamcast sales is the
launch of Sony's next-generation PlayStation system in the U.S. for
Christmas in the year 2000. Sony gave consumers a sneak preview of
the upcoming system, know as PlayStation2, at a trade show in Tokyo
this week. ``The system looks outstanding,'' said Funk. ``Sony is
on target with its release date and has lined up a number of
software developers.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe some consumers may hold off buying Dreamcast
and wait for PlayStation2.
</P>
<P>
   Sega remains optimistic. Company officials said they expect to
sell one million Dreamcast units by the end of the year, and
generate half a billion dollars in sales for hardware and software.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Saito, manager of the Toys R Us store on San
Francisco's Geary Street said demand is still strong for Dreamcast.
``We sold out our 200 consoles pretty much the first day,'' she
said. ``We're expecting our next shipment in early October and
already have a bunch of people on our waiting list.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
