<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 03:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2539 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PG&AMP;E-PG&AMP;E_SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PG&AMP;E-PG&AMP;E </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 PG&AMP;E to Auction Dams Off
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Kenneth Howe &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
PG&AMP;E Corp. said yesterday it will auction off its vast
hydroelectric resources. The move comes less than two days after
failing to persuade the Legislature to allow it to transfer its
$3.3 billion system to an unregulated subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The decision could potentially allow bidders to acquire all or
some of PG&AMP;E's crown jewels, an inventory that includes 68 power
plants and 94 dams on 16 rivers that produces enough electricity to
power 4 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   However, PG&AMP;E's widely expected decision, disclosed in a
Securities and Exchange Commission filing, was greeted with some
skepticism in many quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to see a fair auction, but I don't think they've
really given up their desire to transfer their hydropower hydro &LR; 
power  &LR; to a separate subsidiary,'' said Steven Kelly, policy
director for the Independent Energy Producers, a trade association
for more than 50 electricity producers in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having failed to convince the Legislature to let it transfer
the assets, PG&AMP;E had to follow up on its threat to auction off the
system,'' noted Nettie Hoge, executive director of The Utility
Reform Network, a San Francisco consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics think that PG&AMP;E may use the prospect of an auction to
prod the Legislature to reconsider the issue when it reconvenes in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout PG&AMP;E's nearly six-month battle in the Legislature to
shift its hydroelectric resources to a separate subsidiary, the
utility company said if it were not permitted to make the move it
would auction off the dams. It used that prospect in an attempt to
forge some agreement on the contentious transfer issue.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E's proposal would have affected the price consumers and
industry pay for electric power. That's because the proceeds from
the sale would go toward paying down some of PG&AMP;E's debts, which
arose from investments in nuclear power plants and power contracts
in the 1980s. Those debts are being paid by consumers through a
surcharge on their monthly electricity bills, an amount that is as
much as 40 percent of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But PG&AMP;E's proposal would also have affected the fate of 140,000
acres of Northern California forestland; critical water flows for
fish in numerous river systems; and as well as  &LR; the amount of water
to be used by farmers and country water districts.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the move would allow PG&AMP;E to secure control of the
system for far less than it is worth, then charge higher rates on
the hydroelectric power it produced.
</P>
<P>
   Having failed in the Legislature, PG&AMP;E's first step in an
auction would be for it to file with the California Public
Utilities Commission. A spokesman for the company said the utility
is likely to take that step but had not yet filed and offered no
timetable for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   But an auction is unlikely to happen anytime soon. Experts noted
that the PUC would have to hash over the same issues with which the
Legislature wrestled: how to balance the concerns of rate payers,
environmentalists, farmers, recreational users and others and avoid
giving any one company excessive market power over such a huge
amount of generating power.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's possible the Legislature will take up the issue
again when it reconvenes in January. ``It's hard to image the
Legislature and the governor giving up control of this issue that
affects so many constituents,'' said Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
