<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 03:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2540 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EBAY-EBAY_SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-EBAY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Murderer Puts Art Up for Auction on eBay
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Authorities have disclosed that a serial killer imprisoned in New
York State has been selling art, poetry and autographs to dealers
for resale on the eBay Internet auction site.
</P>
<P>
   Prison authorities this week revoked the art privileges of
Arthur Shawcross, 54, convicted of murdering 11 prostitutes in the
Rochester, N.Y., area. The authorities said that Shawcross _ who
was paid by the dealers with clothing rather than cash _ violated
state regulations prohibiting prisoners from operating businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Two Shawcross items _ a poem and a set of autographed index
cards _ are still for sale on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Shawcross is not the only serial killer whose handiwork is for
sale on San Jose's eBay _ not by a long shot. Just about every
high-profile serial killer of the past three decades is
represented.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes Richard Ramirez, the Southern California
``nightstalker''; Albert DeSalvo, the Boston strangler; John Wayne
Gacy, who killed young boys in Illinois; Ted Bundy, who specialized
in killing college girls; David Berkowitz, New York's ``Son of
Sam'' killer; Jeffrey Dahmer, the Milwaukee cannibal _ and many
more.
</P>
<P>
   In almost all cases, the items are limited to autographs or
letters. Artistic efforts, such as Shawcross', are few and far
between.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether any of the killers are offering their
wares directly or through a representative. Sellers of merchandise
on eBay are identifiable only by pseudonymous screen names.
</P>
<P>
   It also is unclear in many cases where the sellers got the
merchandise _ directly from the serial killers or from other
sources, such as collectors.
</P>
<P>
   A poem by Shawcross now offered on eBay is described as dating
back to 1993. The bidding had reached $18.50 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   A set of six index cards that Shawcross autographed is said to
have been collected by ``a female serial killer groupie.'' It has
attracted bids as high as $16.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer with the most serial-killer mementos for sale is
identified only as ``cc.'' The dealer did not respond to an
e-mailed request for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of EBAY15 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  You don't even have to be a serial killer to make it to eBay. An
autograph from Richard Allen Davis, killer of Petaluma schoolgirl
Polly Klaas, is being hawked for a minimum bid of $9.99. There were
no bidders as of yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Pursglove, a spokesman for eBay, said the company makes
``no moral judgments'' about the merchandise sold on its Web site.
If a serial killer's autograph is being sold by a private
individual who is entitled to sell it, eBay will not intervene, he
remarked.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added that if the merchandise was obtained in a way
that ``violates laws or prison regulations,'' eBay will ``shut the
auction down.''
</P>
<P>
   Pursglove said eBay's lawyers had been unable to get a
``definite'' statement about whether the two Shawcross items
displayed on the auction site are there in violation of any laws or
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   James Flateau, a spokesman for the New York prison system, said
Shawcross did not violate the state's Son of Sam law, which
prevents convicted criminals from profiting directly from their
crimes _ for example, with books or paid interviews about the
crimes themselves. The artwork, poetry and other merchandise did
not refer to the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republican New York state Sen. Michael Nozzolio said
the Son of Sam law should be broadened to prevent any moneymaking
activities by inmates. He said Shawcross was able to sell his
merchandise ``because of his crime.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 0345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
