A2541 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROW-GROW_SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Informational Internet Sites  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 
 
Q: What are the some of the new Internet sites that provide useful
information for entrepreneurs?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Web sites are popping up like porcinis, but not all of them are
palatable. There's a lot of information but often it is not
pertinent. And the site may have a hidden agenda, such as selling
you products or services or extracting personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there is an increasing array of useful sites. Here
are a few of the newcomers:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Allbizdepot.com _ This Milpitas company launched its Web site
(www.allbizdepot.com) a week ago to offer free resources to
entrepreneurs. Its list of and connections to government resources
_ from federal agencies to the smallest California counties _ is
terrific.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it has the most comprehensive nationwide
directory of business-to-business services with thousands of links.
It also lets members download software and business forms for free,
post their own Web page and job listings and take advantage of
discounts on products and services offered by its online business
partners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Allbusiness.com _ This San Francisco startup will launch its Web
site (www.allbusiness.com) this month. Started by Netscape veterans
and backed by Technology Crossover Ventures and other VC firms,
this company also intends to be the leading Web destination for
entrepreneurs looking for business information, services and
products.
</P>
<P>
   A bunch of other companies such as Bigstep.com and Onvia also
are striving to be the first stop for entrepreneurs wading into
e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _Silicon Valley Bank _ The institution has launched a great
information site for high-tech startups (esource.svb.com). The only
problem is that you have to be a customer of the bank or a prospect
to access the information, which includes tips on recruiting,
employee benefits, space planning and real estate rental and
vacancy rates in the Bay Area and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Some other useful small business Web sites with excellent links
to online resources are www.workingsolo.com, which also answers
startup questions and publishes a free monthly newsletter, and
Krislyn's Strictly Business Sites at
sites.krislyn.com/smallbiz.htm.
</P>
<P>
   If you like to do your own online hunting, two of my favorite
new search engines are Google (www.google.com) and LookSmart
(www.looksmart.com). The former, developed by Stanford graduate
students, uses sophisticated text-matching techniques to find pages
that are both important and relevant to your search so you don't
have to sift through so much junk. LookSmart of San Francisco has a
200-person editorial staff to cull and categorize the best sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 0345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 03:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2542 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROW-GROW_SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
