<HEADER>
A2746 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-GOLAN-ARABS-$ADV19-CO     09-15 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLAN-ARABS-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARABS IN THE GOLAN HEIGHTS CALL FOR SYRIAN RETURN ISRAELI
OCCUPIED LAND
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-GOLAN-$ADV19.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Majdal Shams is a town in
the most northeastern point of the Golan Heights about a mile from
the Syrian border.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Sept. 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAJDAL SHAMS, Golan Heights _ The land is governed by Israel,
but Syrian President Hafez Assad carries the day in Afif Mahmoud's
barber shop.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian leader stares down from a portrait photograph on the
wall. Pictured nearby is the late Egyptian President Gamel Abdel
Nasser, the champion of Arab defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are our leaders,'' said barber Mahmoud, 60. ``Everybody
here feels Syrian, not just me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Israelis consider whether to include the Golan Heights in
a peace offering to Syria, Mahmoud is among thousands of Golan
Arabs who say they are anxious for the day when Syria will again be
in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Syria used to use the Golan Heights to stage artillery attacks
on Israeli towns below. Israel conquered the plateau in 1967,
leading to the flight of tens of thousands of Syrians who lived
here.
</P>
<P>
   Now, new Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak promises to resolve
Israel's disputes and the aging Assad is reportedly anxious to get
the Golan back.
</P>
<P>
   About 16,000 Arabs live there, in separate towns from the 17,000
Israelis who have come to the Golan since 1967. Half the Arabs live
in this mountain-top town of Majdal Shams, just about a mile from
the Syrian border.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Arabs here are Druze, a secretive offshoot of Islam.
They are not as wealthy as their Jewish neighbors, but apparently
in better condition than Palestinians in the West Bank and The Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Palestinians under Israeli occupation, Golan Arabs
seem less openly bitter, perhaps because they have long expected to
someday return to Syrian control.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the occupation is barely visible here, but that it
pains them emotionally. The vast majority refuse Israeli
citizenship and those who take it are often ostracized.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis often say that the Druze in the Golan express support
for Syria only out of fear that Syrian security forces will someday
control the region. But, the Druze seem convincing.
</P>
<P>
   They say they are aware that Syria is dominated by a network of
secret police and has tight controls on everything from fax
machines to cellular telephones. They know, also, of Syria's sickly
socialist economy.
</P>
<P>
   But they say they will never feel like first-class citizens in
the Jewish state and they would rather be in Syria, where many have
relatives, despite its restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can take everything, even my cellular telephone,'' says
Talae Abu Akd, a 21-year-old Druze in jeans and black T-shirt,
while having a falafel sandwich. ``But, I'll be in my country. I
just want to feel better and see my family. Everything else is not
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Most long to see relatives in Syria and several hundred each
year are allowed to go to colleges there. They call relatives by
telephone or shout to them through megaphones on the border.
</P>
<P>
   They complain that Israel has confiscated most of their land and
appoints their municipal leaders.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In a bookstore stocked with school texts and Ninja Turtle
backpacks, owner Sakr Kang Abu Saleh gestures to his 12-year-old
son, Hilal, to explain the loyalty to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy in Israel is not equal. We don't have the same
democracy as others,'' he says. ``What I would call democracy is
when my son grows up in his own country and can be what anyone can
be, like a pilot or a government minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Those jobs in Israel almost never go to Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Saleh hopes merchants like him will be key intermediaries
between the Israeli and Syrian economies. At home, though, he makes
his choice known with the Syrian flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make clear to our children that that is our
country,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
