<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-$ADV19-C     09-15 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI SETTLERS IN THE GOLAN HEIGHTS KNOW THE END IS NEARING
 &HT;    725&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With GOLAN-ARABS-$ADV19.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Sept. 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIBBUTZ METZAR, Golan Heights _ Peace in the Middle East may
require Israelis to give up their peaceful lives in this plateau of
farmlands and war memorials.
</P>
<P>
   At this small communal farm, children are safe to run the
grounds alone, the air is clear and the water pure.
</P>
<P>
   But, there are reminders that this is disputed land. The stucco
duplexes are clustered around stone bomb shelters. A minefield is
nearby and Syria, the nation that wants this land back, looms just
across a valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to stay in the Golan, but we know it's not
realistic,'' says Rivka Dadon, 28, sitting with friends around a
picnic table. ``It's not fair, but if they tell me to go I will
go.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more, Israelis like Dadon see the political forces
turning against them and the homes they love.
</P>
<P>
   New Prime Minister Ehud Barak has vowed to make peace and Syrian
President Hafez Assad is said to be aging and eager for a deal.
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright this month came to the
region to try to start direct talks between them. U.S. officials
have hinted that the Golan will likely be the price for a deal with
Assad.
</P>
<P>
   The Golan Heights is a plateau graced with crop lands and
vineyards, but scarred by abandoned Syrian villages and Israeli war
memorials of twisted scrap metal.
</P>
<P>
   From this strategic high ground, Syria used to shell Israeli
towns below. Israel captured it in the 1967 war and held it in the
1973 war. As small as Rhode Island, the Golan saw more than 6,000
Syrians and almost 900 Israelis fall in just a few days of
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   About 17,000 Israelis live their now. Many came for the rural
serenity and the free land Israel offered as an enticement to
settle there. On rolling landscapes reminiscent of the American
West, they grow fruit, make popular dry wines and host thousands of
tourists from central Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Golan is also a land that tens of thousands _ estimates
range from 40,000 to 100,000 _ of Syrians fled during the fighting
in 1967. About 16,000 live there now.
</P>
<P>
   Most refuse Israeli citizenship and complain that Israelis now
inhabit and farm their family estates.
</P>
<P>
   While Israel claims the Golan Heights as part of Israel, the
United States, along with most of the world, considers it occupied
territory.
</P>
<P>
   But, there seems to be a mandate for peace. Even most Golan
residents voted for Barak knowing that he might withdraw from the
land where they've made their home.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show most Israelis clearly oppose a full withdrawal while
a majority might favor a partial pullback. However, if put to them
in a referendum as part of a deal with Syria _ as Barak promises _
Israelis would likely vote to hand over the land.
</P>
<P>
   Golan activists say that would be a tragedy. They say the land
provides Israel with security and much of its water supply. Others
counter that those concerns can be worked out with international
peacekeepers and a water treaty.
</P>
<P>
   To the chagrin of Golan residents, the Israeli attachment to the
region seems to be wavering as Israel tries to settle disputes with
its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my country left me,'' Ronen Maroni, 28, who bought
a house in the Golan just 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israelis have another front on their minds. The Golan is
seen as the key to ending Israel's unpopular 17-year war in
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israel occupies southern Lebanon to protect its border from the
Hezbollah guerrillas there. Syria controls Lebanon and it is
expected _ but not certain _ that Assad would rein in Hezbollah if
he could finally recover the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   The equation is simple for one of the Golan's pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear that making peace and staying in the Golan is
just not practical,'' says Yoav Tsur, who came here 20 years ago
and helps run electric-generating wind turbines. Golan landmarks,
they tower like giant pinwheels near the Syrian border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself first an Israeli and second a Golan
resident,'' says Tsur, 44. ``I have to do what is best for my
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Most residents disagree with Tsur, even refusing to talk about
whether they would accept possible government compensation to leave
their land.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Israel leaves the Golan Heights, the Arabs in a few years
can destroy the whole country,'' says Sammy Bar Lev, mayor of
Qatzrin, the Golan's biggest town.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can and here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A residents' committee is running a publicity campaign to hammer
home that point to their fellow Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The residents' case is based on distrust of Assad and is helped
by the Syrian president's demand that peace talks cannot start
until Israel agrees in principle to return the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all kinds of solutions once the two sides are
interested in a real peace,'' Avi Zeira, head of the Golan
Residents Committee, said. ``Syria is not interested in real
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But, outsiders say a safe deal can be made.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent trip to Jerusalem, U.S. Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.,
who has met with Assad several times since the mid-1980s, called
the security and water supply concerns ``details'' that can be
solved.
</P>
<P>
   The question, Specter said, is whether Israel is ready to part
with the land.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Israelis are split _ even within their own families.
</P>
<P>
   While Rivka Dadon, the Kibbutz Metzar kindergarten teacher, is
resigned to the prospect of a sad departure, her husband, named
Golan, is digging in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll get me out over my dead body,'' he says. ``We fought
on this land too much and lost too many soldiers to leave this
place.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
