<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2764 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN16-COX     09-15 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gimme that ol' time politics _ keep church and state separate
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Twoscore years ago voters debated whether the
United States was ready to elect the first Roman Catholic
president.
</P>
<P>
   John Fitzgerald Kennedy had good looks, charm, wit,
intelligence, a good education and a hero's war record, not to
mention a charming wife and a firm grasp of foreign and domestic
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy was a Catholic. Many Americans worried that Kennedy
might allow his personal religious beliefs to influence
presidential decisions made on behalf of the nation. Would the
Vatican call the shots in the White House?
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy understood these concerns. He addressed the issue
head-on. He respected the requirement to separate church and state
and would maintain that separation if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, 1999 presidential candidates feel the need to wear
their personal religious beliefs on their sleeves as a sign to
voters that their religion will indeed influence presidential
decisions they would make on behalf of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dylan was right. The times, they are a-changin' _ for the
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are not reluctant to show off their religious
credentials. Jimmy Carter, a Southern Baptist, talked about being
born again and admitted that he lusted in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton, also a Southern Baptist, welcomes photo ops of him
in church or carrying a Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore went so far as to set up a White House interview with
religion writers so they could spread the word about his religious
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last onescore years Republicans became the party most
eager to put their personal religious convictions on public
display.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan changed American politics when he made a quid pro
quo pact with America's religious right, a fervid assortment of
faiths that includes televangelists, evangelicals and traditional
religious conservatives who oppose Roe vs. Wade and abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Republican Party has become the bully pulpit for
evangelical religious beliefs with right-to-life a central dogma.
</P>
<P>
   Now Republican presidential candidate Pat Buchanan is
threatening to leave the Grand Old Party and take the religious
right and the right-to-lifers with him. He hints at running for
president in Ross Perot's Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders are begging Buchanan to stay put. They fear
he will take enough votes with him to open the White House door for
another Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Republican leaders should send Buchanan a bouquet of
going-away flowers and tell him to not let the door hit him or his
Pitchfork Brigade in their backsides on their way out.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's conversion would ruin the Reform Party. But that's a
small price to pay if he siphons off into one high-octane container
all those voters who want to merge religion and state by
establishing their own religious tests as qualifications to hold
public office in America.
</P>
<P>
   Although he talks like a born-again evangelical fundamentalist,
Buchanan is an inflexible Roman Catholic who, unlike presidential
candidate Kennedy 40 years ago, desperately wants to combine church
and state in the White House and throughout government.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan and the religious right want to shape government to
reflect their religious views, which means conservative Christian.
Buchanan displays reflexive hostility toward Jews and others of
non-Christian beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The religious right picks up disproportionate power when it
attaches itself to a mainstream political party and dictates
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Public servants should follow President Kennedy's example _
don't wave religious flags for personal gain. Respect the need keep
church and state separate.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
