<HEADER>
A2767 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CRIDERCOLUMN16-C     09-15 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CRIDERCOLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kitty Crider's food column
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ SING YOUR WAY TO A BETTER DIET: I've been
jammin' on the way to work. Rap, hip-hop, swing, disco, marches,
pop _ you name it. Now, the lyrics, well, those are something else:
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrots, pumpkin, spinach and tomatoes;
</P>
<P>
   ``Broccoli, asparagus and sweet potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cantaloupe, watermelon, mangos, hey!
</P>
<P>
   ``All are sources of Vitamin A''
</P>
<P>
   This catchy collection of fruit and veggie tunes promotes the
National Cancer Institute's message of five to nine servings of
such a day. This free, fun cassette is really well done. ``Jammin'
5 A Day Songs'' tout the benefits of Vitamins C and A, fiber,
broccoli, bananas, salad, phytochemicals and exercise in 10 lively
tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Geared toward elementary-age children and performed in part by
them, it is an educational program developed by Dole, as in the
pineapple/banana people. ``Jammin' 5 A Day '' can be ordered free
from www.dole5aday.com. And to Dole's credit there is no mention of
the company's name in the songs.
</P>
<P>
   However, we have a quibble with the tape's promotion of bananas
as ``loaded'' with Vitamin C. That's a stretch, say dietitians. A
banana does have 10 milligrams, or about 15 percent of our daily
requirement, of Vitamin C. But, it's hardly in the same class as an
orange, which has 60-80 mg., or 100 percent. The government,
however, is more lenient. Read on.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S A GOOD SOURCE?: A box of Keebler's Grahams arrived
recently. ``Now a good source of calcium,'' the label proclaimed
boldly. This is good; most women don't get enough calcium. I turn
to the nutrition label and find the grahams provide 10 percent of
the daily requirement. Isn't that low for something deemed a
``good'' source?
</P>
<P>
   That's a legal claim, says Dallas dietitian Barbara Gollman, a
spokeswoman for the American Dietetics Association. According to
government rules, a product that provides 10 percent to 19 percent
of a daily value can be called a good source. A product with 20
percent can be labeled ``high.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep that in mind as you see more and more nutritional claims.
</P>
<P>
   PARA SU FAMILIA: That's the name of a new line of cereals that
General Mills is marketing to the Hispanic population. The four
varieties are Frosted Corn Flakes, Frutis, Cinnamon Corn Stars and
Raisin Bran. The cereals, which have only half the sugar of some
leading sweetened varieties, are fortified with calcium, iron and
folic acid.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING TO THE AIR: Seven of the city's leading chefs will give
live demonstrations Saturday on KLRU (Channel 18, Austin cable 9)
from 1 to 6 p.m. Tune in to catch in action: Stewart Scruggs of
Brio Vista, David Garrido of Jeffrey's, Charles Mayes of Cafe
Josie, Rebecca Rather of Rather Sweet, Jeff Blank and Jay Moore of
Hudson's and Roger Mollet of Central Market.
</P>
<P>
   BIGGER THAN BAGELS: Tortillas have surpassed other ethnic breads
such as croissants, English muffins, bagels, pita, etc., in
popularity and show no signs of decline. Maybe it's all those
tacos, enchiladas and wraps. In 1998, Americans consumed 75 billion
tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Items for this column are drawn from wire reports, mail,
personal observation and comments from readers. To pass on a
suggestion, contact Kitty Crider at the Austin American-Statesman,
P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas, 78767.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
