<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2768 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-ONIONRECIPIES16-     09-15 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ONIONRECIPIES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Onion varieties steal the limelight
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In most recipes shallots are minced as a seasoning, but in this
recipe they are the star of the show. Roasted with balsamic
vinegar, they are so seductively sweet that I could eat more than
my share.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe calls for half shallots and half cipollini, but if
you can't find those Italian onions, just double the number of
shallots. Look for large, individual shallots rather than the
smaller ones which are sold in a clump.
</P>
<P>
   If you're willing to eat them out of hand like roasted garlic,
just pull off the papery outer skin and don't bother with peeling
them. But for a finer presentation, peel before roasting.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED SHALLOTS AND CIPOLLINI
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   8 large shallots
</P>
<P>
   8 cipollini onions
</P>
<P>
   1 4-inch sprig fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   2 4-inch sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fine sea salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Clean the shallots and cipollini by removing papery skins. Trim
the stems and root ends with a paring knife but don't cut too
deeply. Make a small crosscut at the root end. Place the bulbs in a
shallow casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the rosemary and thyme leaves from their stems, then
place in a blender or food processor with the oil, vinegar, water,
salt and pepper. Blend at high speed 3 to 5 minutes, until
combined. Pour the mixture over the shallots and cipollini and toss
with a spoon to coat well. Roast, stirring occasionally, for about
40 minutes, until they can be easily pierced with the tip of a
sharp knife.
</P>
<P>
   Serve these with roast pork or chicken or grilled fish, spooning
the extra juices over the meat.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe is from the Onion Harvest Cookbook by Barbara Ciletti
(Taunton, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   I won't lie to you. Peeling pearl onions is not something you
want to do on a regular basis. But this recipe using them makes a
big batch that will last a while.
</P>
<P>
   The neat thing about Martini Magic mixture of pearl onions and
olives soaked in vermouth is that you can dispense with the
vermouth when making a martini (or Gibson). Just plop them in the
glass.
</P>
<P>
   As cookbook author Jesse Ziff Cool says,``All you have to do is
ice the gin, kick off your shoes and remember how good life can be
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   MARTINI MAGIC
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 quart
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cold water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 basket small red or white pearl onions, about 15 to 25
</P>
<P>
   Ice water
</P>
<P>
   1 10-ounce jar pimiento-stuffed green olives, drained
</P>
<P>
   Dry vermouth
</P>
<P>
   1 fresh, hot red chile pepper (optional)
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan over high heat bring the water to a boil.
Meanwhile trim the root ends of the onions. Have a large bowl of
ice water ready.
</P>
<P>
   Drop the trimmed onions into the boiling water for about 5
minutes. You want the onions to be cooked but still have some
crunch. Drain and transfer to the ice water. When cool, drain and
peel. If fate is with you, you can squeeze the root end of the
onion and it will pop out of its peel.
</P>
<P>
   Sterilize a quart jar with a tight-fitting lid. Then layer the
onions, olives and lemon rind in the jar. Add vermouth to cover
completely and slip in the chile pepper if you want to spice up
your martinis. Cover and refrigerate overnight before using. The
mixture will keep for weeks in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   When making a martini use a vermouth soaked olive, onion or
lemon rind strip in place of a splash of vermouth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipe from Onions, a Country Garden Cookbook, by Jesse Ziff
Cool. His recipe also called for slivered lemon peel mixed with the
onions and olive.
</P>
<P>
   Although sweet cipollini would be the onion of choice in Italy,
pearl onions can be used in this.
</P>
<P>
   Serve as a side dish with roast pork or turkey.
</P>
<P>
   CIPOLLINI STEWED IN OLIVE OIL
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds cipollini, peeled and lightly trimmed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cipollini and olive oil in a small, heavy casserole.
Dilute the tomato paste in 1/2 cup warm water and add it to the
pot. Season with salt and pepper to taste. Cover and simmer slowly,
stirring occasionally, for 45 minutes, until the cipollini are
tender and the sauce has thickened slightly. Serve hot or at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipe from The Four Seasons of Italian Cooking by A.J.
Battifarano and Alan Richardson (TimeLife, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
