<HEADER>
A2769 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-ONIONS16-COX     09-15 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ONIONS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Undersized onions pack an impressive taste wallop
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you don't know a shallot from a scallion. A cipollini _
pronounce that chee-poh-LEE-nee _ sounds like a New York drink. And
a boiler might be something they toss down in a boomtown bar.
</P>
<P>
   They are the other onions, the little ones that Old World home
cooks and sophisticated chefs use to add flavor to everything from
stews to martinis.
</P>
<P>
   As the season shifts from produce that is fresh and green _ as
in the green onions known as scallions _ these little onions with
their papery skin deserve a place in the market basket.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that garden variety cooking onions may cost less
than $1 for a 3-pound bag, shallots ring in as a luxury. They may
come three to a little net bag for $1.49, or in bulk at $4.89 a
pound. But for cooks, they offer the sweetness of onions combined
with the depth of garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Cipollini are new to the American market, but not to Italian
cooks who braise the squat little onions in olive oil and tomatoes
or glaze them with a sweet balsamic sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl onions, on the other hand, have been around as long as
your grandmother and are savored as a seasonal specialty.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying box tells what to look for and how to handle
these other onions.
</P>
<P>
   ONION BOX
</P>
<P>
   SHALLOTS: _ The elegant and refined cousin in the onion family,
these little bulbs grow singly or, like garlic, in clusters. The
variety usually sold at supermarkets here are pink-skinned. They're
a bit harsh when tasted raw, but once cooked, shallots have a
delicate but pronounced onion flavor. French cooks rely on them,
tucking them into dishes such as coq au vin and making the shallot
essential to classic sauces such as beurre blanc _ the butter/wine
sauce _ and marchand de vin, the red wine steak sauce. Minced
shallots cook quickly. Avoid browning or they may taste a little
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   PEARL ONIONS: _ Because these 1-inch onions have been a
traditional staple on the Thanksgiving table _ inevitably creamed
in the fashion of yesteryear _ they are widely available this time
of year. The white ones are more common, but now red and yellow
ones are available as well. An assortment of colors makes for a
prettier dish.
</P>
<P>
   These mild little onions are used whole. First, they must be
peeled, and the easiest way to do that is to blanch them in boiling
water for 1 minute, then plunge into cold water for a quick chill.
When they're peeled, trim off any root fibers and cut a small X in
the root end before cooking.
</P>
<P>
   BOILING ONIONS: _ It's size that determines what these onions
are called, and they must be golf-ball sized. Look for them in
16-ounce net bags, at a price of $1.89. They're a good choice for
stews.
</P>
<P>
   CIPOLLINI: _ Found only occasionally in Dayton supermarkets and
farm markets. They are shipped by Frieda, the exotic produce
supplier in California, so look for the company's signature purple
label. Cipollini are sweeter than our yellow boiler onions, smaller
than our regular onions but larger than little pearl onions. An
acceptable substitute is a large shallot, peeled and used whole.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2772 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA16-COX     09-15 1932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Photos by HA LAM / Cox News Service
 &HT;    Roy Perez, left, and Leeman Schmidt drag embers Monday to the
new Kreuz Market
 &HT;    BARB2
 &HT;    Evelyn Schmidt, left, owner Rick Schmidt, Danny Buckner and
Jimmy Franks cut a ribbon of butcher paper marking the opening.
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA: Kreuz Market savors new digs, old flavor
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.)
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCKHART, Texas _ How to move a 99 3/4-year-old barbecue joint,
in case you ever have to, in three easy steps:
</P>
<P>
   1. Do something winningly goofy and symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   It's this past ``Ash Monday,'' around 10 in the morning, and a
parade likely without precedent is about to commence. It starts at
the old Kreuz Market, which stands uncharacteristically dark and
empty. Present are Kreuz owner Rick Schmidt, sons Leeman and Keith
Schmidt, mutton-chopped pit boss Roy Perez, wives and assorted
media. They're here to move the fire from the old place to the new
Kreuz Market a quarter-mile north up the road.
</P>
<P>
   A reasonable person might be moved to ask: Huh? Can somebody get
these people a match?
</P>
<P>
   To which the owner might reply, You from up north or something?
Lighting the fire with matches is not the Kreuz Market way, and we
have to go back just shy of a hundred years to explain why. Let's
just say for now that this is a special fire that's been burning
for a hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Schmidt and Perez each hook the handle of the silver
barrelful of ash and smoldering embers and drag it through the
fabled old dining hall _ the one that used to have knives chained
to the tables _ through the front door and into the insistent
midmorning sun. They're met by an escort of no fewer than four
police cars and some 11 members of the media, including a crew of
four from CBS's ``48 Hours'' They walk briskly, purposefully (which
is pretty much how this bunch does everything) down the street,
past the Caldwell County courthouse and the antique shops. They
walk past the bank and the Chevy dealer, and people come out to
holler and wave at them, Roy and Keith, then Roy and Leeman, with
Rick Schmidt and his wife, Evelyn, following carrying long-handled
shovels. Rick's asked what he's doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking the fire from the old original Kreuz to the new
original Kreuz,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   They haul the fire in the back door of the vast new restaurant,
where a couple of dozen friends, family and well-wishers are
waiting. Roy Perez positions a pair of post oak logs. Rick Schmidt
puts three shovelfuls of embers between them, adds some bark, fans
the embers with a flattened IBC brand root beer carton, says, to
himself as much as anybody, ``There she goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Applause.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why people are applauding: In the summer of 1900, Charles
Kreuz Sr. purchased part of a lot and opened a grocery and barbecue
business. Over the decades the barbecue overtook the grocery, and
in recent years Kreuz Market operated as a butcher shop and
barbecue restaurant. Edgar ``Smitty'' Schmidt took over in 1948 and
sold out to his sons, Rick and Don (the latter now retired) in the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years the joint's reputation grew, and it came to be
regarded as the best barbecue in Texas. A large part of the old
dump's appeal was its dogged adherence to primitive tradition: no
plates (unless you count brown butcher paper), no forks, no spoons,
no traditional side dishes, no escape from the smoke while waiting
in line, and anybody who asked for barbecue sauce was shot on the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   The post oak fire burning in the pits became central to that
devotion to tradition. Roy Perez would come in every morning before
dawn, get a shovelful of embers from the previous day's fire out of
a metal bucket, add some kindling and get the new day's fire
roaring. So it could be said _ and it was _ that the fire at Kreuz
Market had never gone out for over almost a hundred years. Because,
even if it might not be technically true, it makes for a very good
story.
</P>
<P>
   And the smoldering embers also became a too-obvious metaphor for
a tenant-landlord conflict. And when some unfortunate things
happened that forced Kreuz Market to move from the building it had
inhabited for a century, Rick Schmidt knew he'd have to take
everything he could from the old place to the new place, and
nobody's sure now exactly whose idea the fire thing was, but Roy
was its champion. Three little words, they decided, apply to this
fire, our fire:
</P>
<P>
   Does. Not. Convey.
</P>
<P>
   2. Don't make a big deal out of your last day _ let others do it
for you.
</P>
<P>
   Back up to the week before ``Ash Monday'' _ the last smoky gasp
for the old original Kreuz Market. Call it, to appropriate a phrase
from one of the faithful who couldn't be there, The Last Temptation
of Kreuz.
</P>
<P>
   Folks have been calling, sometimes at the rate of 10 or 15 an
hour, every day, arranging to come pay their respects. Business has
been up by 50 percent or more all week, and by 11 a.m. one morning
there's a line out the door of the old brick joint into the gravel
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Which is nothing unusual for a Saturday at Kreuz Market. But the
nostalgia on this day is thicker than the smoke. And the smoke _
let's just say the wind is doing tricky things and the smoke gets
so bad sometimes even members of the faithful are wondering if a
little change is such a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If y'all hurry up you'll get your picture on the tee-vee,''
says John Butler of Austin, Texas, who just wanted to look around.
</P>
<P>
   The ``48 Hours'' crew is the TV presence. Austin filmmaker Ken
Lewin is here, too, shooting footage to make his short film on
Kreuz Market into an hour-long documentary. (Alas, he will run out
of film, which means money, on ``Ash Monday.'')
</P>
<P>
   You never saw so many people taking pictures of their lunch.
Flash bulbs are going off with a frequency that makes you wonder if
George W. Bush is somewhere in the room talking about cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Then the unthinkable happens. A group of four is eating with _
fraud! scandal! _ paper plates, knives and forks. Commanded to
explain this breach of protocol, a woman who identifies herself as
Adela Acosta of San Antonio, Texas, says cheerfully, ``That was my
idea. I'd been here several times and knew they didn't have any. So
I brought my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman in the party, shamed and humiliated, refuses to be
identified or quoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see that,'' says Leeman Schmidt. ``They're the same people
who sneak barbecue sauce in their purses.''
</P>
<P>
   They came from Lubbock. They came from Houston. They came from
Dallas and Fort Worth, just to say they were here, you know, when.
Victor Torres, who went to high school, even came from Chicago,
although the trip had a dual purpose _ he's also got a daughter
here.
</P>
<P>
   They're all talking about how their entire families would come
in for barbecue. They ask each other, `What generation Kreuz Market
customer are you?' It's clear that although the building and the
business were owned privately, all of Texas held emotional stock in
Kreuz Market.
</P>
<P>
   What happened was this: When Smitty died, he gave the building
to his daughter, now Nina Sells. Rick and Don, and then just Rick,
paid rent to Nina. The lease came up for renewal, and Rick and Nina
couldn't come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   And in a couple of weeks, if the plan comes off, Nina, her
husband Jim Sells and her son John Fullilove will open Smitty's
Market in the old Kreuz building.
</P>
<P>
   Same menu. Same dearth of amenities. Same meatus operandi.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always wanted what was mine,'' Rick Schmidt says, watching
the endless procession of barbecue pilgrims from his favorite spot
for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   A man who flew in from Dallas tells Rick Schmidt it won't be the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much money you want to bet?'' Rick shoots back, not
exactly smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Later he'll say that kind of talk makes him a little mad. He
knows it'll be the same because he's not changing anything. It's a
myth that these hallowed pits impart their smoky goodness through
decades of seasoning they have to be rebuilt every eight or 10
years. (The new ones, however, should last a long time.) One of the
first things Rick Schmidt did many months ago, when he knew the
market was on the brink of big change, was have an exact replica of
his biggest pit built. He burned it for a while, put on a brisket
and a shoulder, cooked them around five hours, put some beer on ice
and had the local barbecue intelligentsia in to pronounce judgment.
</P>
<P>
   These were old boys not apt to sugar-coat anything, and they
were skeptical to the extreme. And they ate that barbecue and said,
``Damn, Rick, it tastes like it come from downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Cut the ribbon and get ready for Y2Kreuz.
</P>
<P>
   And on the fourth day, it rose again.
</P>
<P>
   It's now Sept. 1. You can tell because it's carved in stone, or
maybe poured concrete, next to the front door of the new,
23,000-square-foot Kreuz Market for the new millennium:
</P>
<P>
   Kreuz Market
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 1, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Owners
</P>
<P>
   Rick and Evelyn Schmidt
</P>
<P>
   Contractor
</P>
<P>
   Buckner Builders Inc.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 people wait outside on the new parking lot, which still
has that new parking lot smell. The banker's here, a couple of
cops, family and friends and merchants and even Johnny Frizell, a
much-loved character who worked in the old place for 34 years
before he broke his hip and had to go into a home.
</P>
<P>
   The bow and ribbon stretched across the front entrance are made
of butcher paper, and Rick Schmidt's fixing to go at them with a
carving knife. But a few words seem appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done one of these before _ what do you do?'' he
jokes. ``I hope I don't do another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, mostly it's big _ almost triple the capacity of the old
joint, which in theory could hold up to 250 carnivores ``if
everybody sat real friendly, cheek to cheek,'' Rick Schmidt liked
to say. The ceiling in the main serving and dining room here rises
more than 30 feet, keeping heat and smoke away from diners and the
crew. The look is utilitarian and not fancy _ lots of unfinished
wood and corrugated metal. The signs are faux-old, yellowed and
cracked and brand new. Nonetheless, the place avoids the Forced
Rustic aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Schmidt looks a little ragged, but the place is ready to
go. The furniture _ including wooden chairs with the Kreuz logo _
have arrived. Little paper boats of the Kreuz spice rub are on the
tables, as are bottles of Hill Country Fare Louisiana hot sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Graham is the first customer. This happens spontaneously _
just minutes before he'd said it wouldn't be him. But nobody else
wanted to be first, so there he was, getting his usual shoulder
slice from Ella Townes, behind the counter as always.
</P>
<P>
   Well? ``Well, the first piece is just as good as the last
piece,'' he says as the new Kreuz Market celebrates its 10th minute
of business. ``I reckon I'll be here every day. At least once.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Frizell is impressed, too, except for the fact that
``they got these damn fans. We didn't have any fans. Still, you get
some smoke so you know where you been.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go all over the United States and you won't find a
barbecue place like this,'' he says. ``I bet you won't.''
</P>
<P>
   By lunchtime, the crew is up to its eyeballs in business.
</P>
<P>
   Beach writes for the Austin (Texas) American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
