<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2773 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-TAKE     09-15 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take one of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him: q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that Puerto Rico had two islandwide
votes on the issue of statehood vs. independence, one in '93 and
the other in '98. What were the results?
</P>
<P>
   A: What the article reported was that islandwide votes on
statehood were pushed through in 1993 and 1998 by Gov. Pedro
Rossello, the most ardent statehood advocate ever elected there.
</P>
<P>
   But Puerto Ricans also voted on that issue in July 1967, with
four-time Gov. Luis Munoz Marin backing commonwealth status. Voters
had three choices: remaining a U.S. commonwealth; statehood; or
independence. In that plebiscite, 60.5 percent voted to retain
commonwealth status; 39 percent for statehood; and less than 1
percent for independence. The vote for independence wasn't
considered a true indication of support, however, because many
groups favoring independence boycotted the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1993, residents again voted in favor of retaining
Puerto Rico's commonwealth status, but by a narrower margin. The
tally: 48.4 percent for commonwealth; 46.2 percent for statehood;
4.4 percent for independence.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, voters had five choices: statehood;
commonwealth; independence; free association; and ``none of the
above.'' Once again statehood was rejected. The last option
actually received just over 50 percent of the nonbinding vote.
Statehood was favored by 46.5 percent. Independence won 2.5
percent, while commonwealth status and free association each won
less than 1 percent. The Popular Democratic Party had urged its
voters to choose ``none of the above'' as an expression of their
desire to retain the status quo, even though that was to retain the
commonwealth status. Party leaders objected to the wording of the
commonwealth option, which it said made the territory sound like a
colony.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I can't find any information about Fort Delaware, a northern
prison during the Civil War. Can you tell me anything about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Built on Pea Patch Island in the Delaware River, near
Delaware City, the fort housed political and naval prisoners from
the beginning of the war. According to the Historical Times
Illustrated Encyclopedia of the Civil War, it was this prison,
above all others, that captives dreaded. Brig. Gen. Albin Schoepf,
the fort's commandant, was called ``General Terror'' by his
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival in 1861 of 2,000 Confederate soldiers, shed
barracks were provided inside the wall surrounding the fort, on
ground several feet below the river's high-water mark. Dikes kept
water from washing over the ground, but it was damp and cold in
winter. After Fort Delaware was designated a permanent prison depot
and thousands more began arriving, new barracks were built, with
enough to house 5,000 prisoners completed by spring 1863.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, 12,500 Confederate prisoners were housed at the
fort, creating conditions so dangerously overcrowded that even the
Union surgeon general complained. In September 1863, of the 7,000
prisoners still at Fort Delaware, 331 died. In October, smallpox
broke out and the suffering and death increased. The last
Confederates weren't released until mid-July 1865.
</P>
<P>
   A major renovation of the fort that will allow visitors to stay
overnight in re-created Union officers' quarters is under way, but
no target date has been set, a park spokeswoman told Q&AMP;A. More
information: Fort Delaware State Park, 45 Clinton St., Delaware
City, DE 19706; 302-834-7941.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many houses have been built worldwide since the Habitat
for Humanity program began?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since its founding in September 1976, Habitat for Humanity
International has built and rehabilitated some 80,000 houses, with
the number changing every week.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported recently on various strong earthquakes, but
nothing was said about the one that occurred in Guatemala in the
'70s that claimed more than 25,000 lives. What about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The earlier report responded to a question asking about the
strongest earthquakes ever recorded. All were of magnitudes topping
8 on the Richter scale. The quake that struck Guatemala on Feb. 4,
1976, while undeniably devastating, measured a magnitude of 7.5,
according to World Almanac. It caused 22,778 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that Monica Lewinsky is selling handbags over the
Internet. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The former White House intern's line of handbags, marketed as
``Made especially for you by Monica,'' can be ordered through her
Internet site _ www.therealmonicainc.com _ and cost between $70 and
$130 each.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky said she took up knitting and sewing ``as the only way
to stay sane'' when she was more or less trapped in her Washington
apartment last year, forbidden by prosecutors to talk to anyone by
phone or e-mail. ``I went back to something I did in high school,
which was designing and sewing,'' she said in an interview with The
Associated Press. ``It's been nourishing for me emotionally to work
with colors and different fabrics.'' After she made her first
handbag, she said, all her friends wanted one, and the business was
born.
</P>
<P>
   A dollar from each bag will go toward various charities,
Lewinsky says, with the remainder of her profits going toward
paying off the debts she incurred from President Clinton's
impeachment scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really excites me is that this has nothing to do with the
president,'' she said in a report published in October's Marie
Claire magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My granddaughter, who is 13, lost her Social Security card.
How can she have it replaced?
</P>
<P>
   A: An application for a replacement card can be requested by
calling 1-800-772-1213. The applicant must present either original
or certified copies of documents proving her identity. Page 2 of
the application lists examples of acceptable documents.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of Johnny Carson? He was reported to have had
a heart attack, but I haven't seen anything since.
</P>
<P>
   A: Carson underwent successful quadruple heart bypass surgery in
March at St. John's Health Center in Santa Monica, Calif. Three
weeks later he returned to his Malibu, Calif., home, with a
spokesman proclaiming th-- t the 73-year-old entertainer was
``doing great.'' Although tabloids reported that his health was
declining, he dismissed such a thought with this statement:
``They'll print anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The entertainer, who said he quit smoking more than seven years
ago, is now back on the Los Angeles social circuit and was well
enough to attend a recent tennis tournament there. He and his wife,
Alex, also were seen dining recently at Mr. Chow, a Los Angeles
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Carson attributes his rapid recovery to years of sensible eating
and lots of tennis.
</P>
<P>
   (End take 1 of two takes)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
