<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2778 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-COOKING-FEARLESSLY16-     09-15 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING-FEARLESSLY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kitchen daredevils having too much fun with very hot things
 &HT;    (EDS: WITH SIDEBAR _ FEARLESS-RECIPES16-COX. Photos available.)
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Call them culinary pyromaniacs. Daredevils in
the kitchen. Jeff Blank and Jay Moore have set their chefs' hats on
fire more than a dozen times. They toss rattlesnake into the
skillet on a regular basis. They delight in roasting peppers with
the same kind of 6-foot flamethrower that Texas ranchers use to
burn the spines off prickly pear cactus for their cattle's
consumption. (And they just happen to know that if you turn the
propane bottle upside -down, the flame thrower will spit fire an
impressive 18 feet.)
</P>
<P>
   These guys are having entirely too much fun.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but it's just beginning, they insist.
</P>
<P>
   A flamboyant duo, Blank and Moore are the owner and executive
chef at Hudson's on the Bend, a 15-year-old restaurant in a
converted limestone house. They are also partners in the Hudson's
on the Bend Cooking School, as well as a line of sauces bearing the
restaurant name, a new book called ``Cooking Fearlessly,'' a
fast-paced video by the same title that will threaten Emeril, and
weekly televised food segments which will debut Monday in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Don't even pause to take a breath. These guys are rocking.
</P>
<P>
   With a 10-year history as a team, they act like brothers, egging
each other on, helping each other out, cracking up with laughter,
smarting off. It's all in the name of Texas food, good times and
good eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not fun, we don't do it. And it's all fun,'' says
Blank. Oh, sure, they get hot in the kitchen, they get pressured on
a packed restaurant night, they have dinner crises.
</P>
<P>
   But, says Moore, ``By us having fun back here (in the kitchen),
that enables us to lighten the stress load and put more of it out.
When it becomes work, I will say, `Adios.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Not much chance of that any time soon. The ``two crazy guys at
Hudson's who will cook anything'' are out to persuade the rest of
us to jump fearlessly into the fire with them. Cooking fearlessly,
their motto, is about wild techniques, bold flavors, trusting your
instincts, breaking the rules, using your hands, ``cookin' with a
boogie back beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Saute an African lion? Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Take the shaker top off the bottle of Tabasco and pour a slug in
the orange ginger barbecue sauce? You betcha.
</P>
<P>
   Sneak two kinds of chiles into the brownie dessert? Absolutely.
``Put down your Prozac and pop a pepper,'' they quip.
</P>
<P>
   But lest you think these two fellas are totally out of control,
let us assure you that their hearty, big-portioned, bold-flavored
food _dishes like venison backstrap stuffed with smoked lobster in
a pool of guava sour cherry sauce _ consistently earn them spots on
the lists of the top restaurants in the area. And they have won
notice nationally as well: in The New York Times, Cooking Light,
Men's Journal, Chef's Magazine, Field &AMP; Stream and PBS' ``Best
Chefs of the West'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the Central Texas influences of Mexican, German,
Czech, cowboy and hunter cooking, they've earned their fame and
name:
</P>
<P>
   For their meat _ both wild game and tame. (Their reputation is
that they will cook anything once, even lion, kangaroo, zebra.)
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys could cook a horseshoe and make it delicious,''
says CBS news anchor and frequent Hudson's diner Dan Rather in the
foreword of their new book.
</P>
<P>
   For adventurous smoking, both planned _ like their trademark
smoked shrimp, avocado and goat cheese quesadillas _ and unplanned
_ like the time they fired up their 12-foot stone smokehouse with
too much gusto to cook a leg of antelope and the roof caught fire.
When it happened, they were being interviewed by a New York Times
writer, and the staff hurriedly put out the fire while Moore and
Blank tried to distract the reporter in the kitchen and keep her
from looking out the window. As the story goes, the antelope turned
out great, the article was a success, and the smokehouse got a
makeover.
</P>
<P>
   For growing their own herbs, edible flowers and greens long
before it was fashionable. And, these days, their garden is 14
-feet up in the air, on a rooftop to which they fearlessly climb
when they need a sprig of cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   These may sound like the antics of a couple of college kids, but
both are family men and seasoned chefs. Blank and his wife, Shanny
Lott, married eight years, have three children, 24, 21 and 19.
Moore, married to Kristi for 14 years, has two sons, 6 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   Blank, 49, is a self-taught chef who owned The Wineskin
Restaurant in Aspen, Colo., before opening Hudson's in 1984. Moore,
40, is a graduate of the Culinary Institute of America with a
passion for Tabasco and sauces. He is the one credited with
refining the restaurant's sauces into a gourmet line that they hand
pack and sell through mail order and specialty stores in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago the two fellas began teaching monthly cooking
classes at the restaurant on Sunday mornings. Last year, after
Blank and his wife completed their unique straw-bale home on Lake
Travis, with both indoor and outdoor teaching kitchens, the classes
were moved there. The monthly classes (one on a Sunday morning and
one on a Thursday evening) frequently sell out weeks in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The fun and camaraderie of teaching the classes begat ``Cooking
Fearlessly,'' a 25-minute TV pilot of food and music.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with Deborah Harter of California, the partner of their
videographer, they opted to write a cookbook telling the history of
Hudson's, their cooking philosophies (both serious and irreverent),
recipes, anecdotes, techniques, quotes, musical suggestions, the
cooking school and promotion for their bottled sauces. They also
divulge for the first time the recipes for the most popular of
these sauces: the orange ginger barbecue, the tomatillo white
chocolate, bourbon vanilla praline, mango jalapeno, champagne herb
vinegar and guava sour cherry.
</P>
<P>
   Blank's wife, an artist, did a series of chef paintings for the
chapter dividers. Local food photographer Laurie Smith recorded
their cooking, food and antics with her camera. The result is a
self-published book that is a riot of color and photos, reflecting
the fun behind the food.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, everyone was laughing so hard in the flaming
toques shoot that they didn't knock the hats off quite fast enough
in one frame and the guys' hair singed a bit. Later that day, when
Blank went down to the bank to get a loan for the cookbook
production, the president commented that he smelled burned hair.
</P>
<P>
   Blank shrugged it off. ``Oh, we were lighting our hats on
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Which prompted the bank officer to comment, ``You were setting
yourselves on fire and you expect me to lend you money?''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the fiery duo got the loan and now the book,
``Cooking Fearlessly'' ($32.95). National release will be in
November.
</P>
<P>
   There is more on their plates. This month an Austin television
news show will begin running weekly food segments, featuring Blank
and Moore.
</P>
<P>
   None of that scares these guys. But what does have this fearless
duo just a little nervous is an appearance on the Food Network's
``Ready. Set . Cook!'' to be shot Sept. 26, for which they will be
given a mystery bag of groceries to cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if they give me taro root or octopus?'' muses Blank.
</P>
<P>
   No worry. Smoke it, pour the Tabasco to it, cover it in
tomatillo white chocolate sauce, light it. If they can't figure out
something, they know how to create interesting distractions and put
on a good show.
</P>
<P>
   But they admit there is one area of their showmanship they might
refine. This business about setting their toques on fire is giving
them bad hair days. So they've got the co-author's boyfriend
designing remote-controlled chef's hats that light up, something
that would look kind of flashy on TV. If it works out, they just
might give their matches a rest. Good news for their banker.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Crider writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kcrider(AT)statesmancom
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
