<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2780 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FEARLESS-RECIPES16-CO     09-15 1579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEARLESS-RECIPES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WARNING: Techniques and recipes not for the unadventurous
 &HT;    (EDS: Sidebar/recipies to COOKING-FEARLESSLY16-COX. With
photos.)
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In-Your-Face Grilling
</P>
<P>
   Watch some of these chefs in open kitchens cook and you might
see them touching steaks and other meats with their fingers as they
grill. They are practicing the touch method of doneness, checking
not only the temperature of the meat but the firmness of the
muscle. As the meat cooks, moisture is reduced and the muscle
becomes firmer.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it takes a little experience, but try this face-testing
technique as you grill:
</P>
<P>
   Rare
</P>
<P>
   Touch your cheek, with a straight face (no smiling or it will be
overdone). The temperature of the steak will be between 110-120
degrees, and it will have a cool red center.
</P>
<P>
   Medium rare
</P>
<P>
   Touch your chin, still poker-faced.The internal temperature will
be 120-130 degrees, and the steak will have a warm, red center.
</P>
<P>
   Medium
</P>
<P>
   Touch the end of your nose. This is the texture of a medium
steak, with an internal temperature of 140-155 and a hot pink
center.
</P>
<P>
   Medium-well
</P>
<P>
   Touch your forehead, the area just above the bridge of your
nose.The internal temp will be 155-160, and and the steak will have
a thin line of hot pinkness in the center.
</P>
<P>
   Well-done
</P>
<P>
   Touch the bottom of your shoe. That's well done, with an
internal temp of 180 degrees and visually no pink. (However even a
well-done piece of meat should have some juice; it's not beef
jerky.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Blank and Jay Moore, who like their steaks between chin
and nose
</P>
<P>
   Smoked Shrimp and Flounder en Papillote
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle of chardonnay
</P>
<P>
   2 sheets parchment paper or foil, 16-by-12 inches (for the bag)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons shallots, minced (can substitute onion, leeks,
celery or jicama)
</P>
<P>
   2 flounder fillets, 5-6 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   6 shrimp (21-25 per pound size)
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lime zest
</P>
<P>
   1 roasted poblano, julienned
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Put in baking sheet to preheat.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce wine in a small saucepan to 1/2 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Cut a large heart out of the parchment paper (Fold the paper in
half and cut half a heart shape, away from the fold). Repeat with
the other sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Butter the inside of each sheet thoroughly. Slightly off center
on the paper, sprinkle garlic and shallots.
</P>
<P>
   Top each parchment heart with flounder, shrimp, herbs, zest and
poblano, divided equally. Splash with reduced wine. Season each
with salt and pepper. Top with remaining butter.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the bottom, fold the edges over themselves (kind of
like folding a note in high school) sealing the entire paper bag.
One trick we sometimes use is to puff with a straw at one end of
the bag to make sure it inflates, then hold it closed with a paper
clip.
</P>
<P>
   Place on pre-heated baking sheet. Place in 350-degree oven for
9-10 minutes. Serve immediately. Serves 2.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipes from 'Cooking Fearlessly'
</P>
<P>
   This is also a wonderful marinade for babyback ribs, portobello
mushrooms, chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Rib Eye Steak
</P>
<P>
   6 rib eye steaks, 14-16 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Shiner Bock marinade:
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce Shiner Bock, or your local or homemade dark beer
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   4 shakes Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red onion, diced fine
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 limes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coarse brown mustard (Creole is good)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except salt. Salt in the marinade draws
too much moisture from the meat over an extended time. Pour over
steaks and marinate from 4 hours to overnight. (Marinate the steaks
in an airtight plastic bag the day before grilling to achieve the
optimum flavor.)
</P>
<P>
   Cook the steaks over medium-high heat about 4 minutes each side
for medium rare to medium. (See ``In-Your-Face Grilling.'') Season
with salt to taste after cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   Ancho Chile Bock Beer Smashers
</P>
<P>
   5-6 ancho chile peppers, pureed
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds Idaho potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound sweet butter, cubed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bottle Shiner Bock beer, or any big, malty beer
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Soak ancho chiles in water to cover until soft. Remove stems,
ribs and seeds. Puree with 1/2 cup water in a blender to yield 1/2
cup ancho puree.
</P>
<P>
   Peel and boil Idaho potatoes and sweet potatoes until tender.
Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Warm the beer, cream and butter to slightly above room
temperature. Cold milk and cold butter cause the starch in the
potatoes to seize up, which is the main cause of glutinous mash
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Whip the Idaho and sweet potatoes together with electric mixer.
Add cream, chunks of butter one at a time, ancho puree, beer and
salt. Adjust salt flavor and keep warm until served. Serves 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   These reheat well with a little more butter added.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Heat Brownies
</P>
<P>
   6 cascabel or ancho peppers
</P>
<P>
   10 oz. semi-sweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 cups unsalted cashews
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dried cherries
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Lightly coat 9-inch-square cake pan
with butter and dust with flour. Shake out extra flour.
</P>
<P>
   Submerge peppers in hot water in a bowl to rehydrate. Cover bowl
with plastic wrap and let stand for approximately 15 minutes. Drain
and remove seeds.
</P>
<P>
   In a double boiler, melt chocolate and butter over water at a
low simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Sift flour, cocoa, cayenne pepper, baking powder and salt
together and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put seeded cascabel peppers in a blender and puree until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Place eggs, sugar and vanilla in a mixing bowl. Mix at high
speed until slightly thick, approximately 2 minutes. Add
chocolate-butter mixture and pepper blend to mixer bowl along with
eggs and sugar. Beat on medium high for 1 1/2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Next, add sifted ingredients and mix for one minute on medium
speed. Add sour cream and mix on medium speed for 30 seconds. Fold
in cashews and dried cherries. Pour into cake pan. Place in
preheated oven and bake for 45-55 minutes. Remove and cool for 20
minutes. Makes 10-12 big brownies. Best if served warm with
homemade ice cream and fudge sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Our corn pudding recipe is the restaurant's most requested
recipe _ bar none. We wish it were an original, but we cannot tell
a lie. It has been Jeff's mother's holiday standby for as long as
anyone can remember. She isn't sure where she found it, but thinks
it came from one of those innumerable Junior League cookbooks. At
any rate, we have changed it so many times over the years, we
suppose now it is more original than when we started. We like ours
a little on the spicy side, so we add cayenne and poblano peppers
along with the sweet mild peppers.
</P>
<P>
   You can make the batter the day before and store it in a bowl in
the refrigerator. Just give it a whisk before putting it in a
greased and floured casserole dish at baking time. This recipe is
so sturdy you can bake it early and hold it in a warm oven or in a
chafing dish.
</P>
<P>
   Corn Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Dry mix:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Wet mix:
</P>
<P>
   6 whole eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 stick of butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can cream-style corn
</P>
<P>
   Veggie mix:
</P>
<P>
   1 medium poblano pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 Anaheim pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh cut corn
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Combine all dry ingredients in a
bowl. Mix well and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a second bowl, whisk the eggs until blended, then add melted
butter, cream and cream-style corn.
</P>
<P>
   Blend the dry ingredients into the wet ingredients using a wire
whisk.
</P>
<P>
   Clean all three peppers, discarding the seeds and stems. Dice
into 1/4-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Add fresh cut corn kernels and the diced peppers to the mixing
bowl. Blend together.
</P>
<P>
   Coat a medium-size 9-inch-square casserole dish with butter or
light vegetable oil and dust with flour. Add the mix to the
casserole dish. The depth can vary from 1 inch to 2 inches. If the
mix is only 1 inch deep it will cook 5 to 10 minutes faster.
</P>
<P>
   Place in a preheated oven at 350 degrees and bake for 40 minutes
or until it is golden brown and firm.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   Our corn pudding recipe is the restaurant's most requested
recipe _ bar none. We wish it were an original, but we cannot tell
a lie. It has been Jeff's mother's holiday standby for as long as
anyone can remember. She isn't sure where she found it, but thinks
it came from one of those innumerable Junior League cookbooks. At
any rate, we have changed it so many times over the years, we
suppose now it is more original than when we started. You can make
the batter the day before and store it in a bowl in the
refrigerator. Just give it a whisk before putting it in a greased
and floured casserole dish at baking time. This recipe is so sturdy
you can bake it early and hold it on warm or in a chafing dish.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
