<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2 takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: A recent article mentioned Newton Minow's description of
television as a ``vast wasteland.'' When and where did he say that,
and can you give me some additional context?
</P>
<P>
   A: Minow, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission at
the time, made his now-famous statement on May 9, 1961, in a speech
before 2,000 delegates to the National Association of Broadcasters
convention in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   While saying he did not intend ``to idly observe this
squandering of the public's airwaves,'' he added a further
indictment of TV as ``a procession of game shows, violence,
audience participation shows, formula comedies about totally
unbelievable families, blood and thunder, mayhem, violence, sadism,
murder, Western badmen, Western goodmen, private eyes, gangsters,
more violence, and cartoons. And, endlessly, commercials, many
screaming, cajoling and offending. And most of all, boredom.'' He
explained later that the remark wasn't meant so much as a total
indictment of everything on TV as it was a way of explaining that,
in his opinion, TV wasn't realizing its potential for good. Minow,
a Democrat appointed by President Kennedy, was a little-known
bureacrat until he became a media darling _ in media other than TV,
that is _ for his comments. He quit the FCC two years later to go
back to law, saying he was making the move for financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was vacationing in California at Lake Tahoe, I was
told that it is one of the deepest lakes in the United States. If
it isn't the deepest one, what is?
</P>
<P>
   A: At its deepest point, Lake Tahoe goes 1,640 feet down.
Oregon's Crater Lake tops it _ or should we say bottoms it _ at
1,932 feet at its greatest depth.
</P>
<P>
   Neither U.S. lake comes close to the world record holder, Baikal
in Russia, which in places is 5,371 feet (1.02 miles) deep.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Jerry Lewis' latest telethon received pledges of more than
$53 million. When was his first telethon, and what amount was
pledged then?
</P>
<P>
   A: His first telethon to benefit the Muscular Dystrophy
Association, on Labor Day weekend in 1966, raised more than $1
million in pledges. It was broadcast by only one station, in New
York. This year's broadcast was shown on about 200 stations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the Institute for Policy Studies? It was mentioned in
a recent article reporting on several staff members of the U.S.
House of Representatives who were visiting Iraq, contrary to the
wishes of the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Institute describes itself as ``the only multi-issue
progressive think tank in Washington,'' saying it operates four
programs: global economy; paths for the 21st century; sustainable
communities, and peace and security.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based organization's Web site _ www.ips-dc.org _
goes on to say that ``at a time when other think tanks celebrate
the virtues of unrestrained greed, unlimited wealth, and
unregulated markets, IPS is striving to create a more responsible
society, one built around the values of justice, nonviolence,
sustainability and decency.''
</P>
<P>
   The article you mention, by the way, made it clear that the
White House was not pleased about the visit of the congressional
staff members. It went on to say that the five got around a U.S.
ban on travel to Iraq by carrying special papers with their
passports for recording their entry and departure. None of the five
was willing to speak with reporters in Iraq or Jordan, the article
stated.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported on both a Fox news broadcast and on MSNBC
that Louis Freeh was not the FBI director at the time of the
burning of the Branch Davidian compound in Waco, Texas. Can you
confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's correct: Freeh was not the FBI director at the time.
The fire that killed many members of the sect occurred on April 19,
1993, when William Sessions headed the bureau. Sessions gave up the
post at the request of President Clinton and on July 19, 1993, was
replaced by Floyd Clarke, whose title was acting director. Freeh
was named the agency's director on Sept. 1, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the design on the left side of the back of a $1
bill, showing a pyramid, an eye, and some Latin words, represent?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Bureau of Engraving and Printing explains that the Latin
words above the pyramid, Annuit Coeptis, mean ``He has favored our
undertakings.'' The Latin phrase beneath the pyramid, Novus ordo
seclorum, means ``new order of the ages.'' The eye represents the
eye of Providence, and a light around it illustrates ``spiritual
above material.'' The pyramid is unfinished, signifying that this
country needs to grow and build.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Lance Armstrong recently won the Tour de France as part of a
bicycle team sponsored by the U.S. Postal Service. Did the Postal
Service pay the team's expenses? How does it justify spending money
that way?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Postal Service is one of about 20 team sponsors, said
USPS spokeswoman Margot Myers. All the money from all the sponsors
is pooled to cover all the team's activities throughout the year,
paying for salaries, travel expenses, equipment and any other
expenses the team incurs. Some sponsors, such as USPS, pay money
only; others offer in-kind support, such as providing helmets or
other equipment; and still others provide a combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Srvice views its sponsorship of the team strictly as
a business proposition, Myers explained. The USPS has a marketing
and sales development group that oversees this project, with an
annual sales goal that must be met in order to justify continuing
the sponsorship. For example, the group will make a pitch to a
company involved in cycling to use direct mail as part of its
advertising mix, or to use the Postal Service to fill some of its
orders. ``The idea is that we're able to generate enough additional
revenue in sales related to the sponsorship to more than cover the
cost of the sponsorship,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the reason for Peter Jennings' extended absence from
ABC World News Tonight?
</P>
<P>
   A: He was on a four-week vacation, said ABC publicist Eileen
Murphy. He was back on the air starting Sept.7.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will a house with a metal frame and metal roof that is
properly grounded to a copper rod about 2 feet in the ground be
protected from lightning?
</P>
<P>
   A: Factors involved in a building's susceptibility to lightning
damage include its height in relation to other structures in the
area, the proximity of large trees, and the materials used to build
the structure. In the structure you described, you should properly
bond all metal parts and provide adequate grounding to ensure that
any lightning strike would be conducted safely to the ground.
Adequate grounding requires at least two ground rods at opposite
corners of the building driven no less than 10 feet into the
ground. They should be installed by an experienced person licensed
to do such work.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners can get additional information from the Lightning
Protection Institute, 3335 N. Arlington Heights Road, Suite E,
Arlington Heights, IL 60004 (1-800-488-6864); or online at
www.lightning.org
</P>
<P>
   End take 2 of two takes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
