<HEADLINE>
$9.4 BILLION DEAL BETWEEN MOTOROLA AND GENERAL INSTRUMENT IN 
WORKS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID BARBOZA AND LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Motorola Inc., long a dominant player in the
semiconductor and cellular telephone markets, may be carving out a
new niche for itself in home entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   By negotiating to acquire the General Instrument Corp., the
leading maker of cable set-top boxes, Motorola is trying to be a
leader in merging voice, data and video applications and funneling
them directly into homes through one broadband cable device,
according to people close to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, consumers could soon be equipped with a cable
television set-top box offering a variety of multimedia
applications, everything from telephone service and high-definition
television to high-speed Internet access and interactive video
games.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Motorola and General Instrument refused to comment
Monday on such a merger, which was reported in The Wall Street
Journal and The Los Angeles Times. But people close to the talks
said that as early as this week Motorola was expected to agree to
trade about six-tenths of a share of its stock for one share of
General Instrument, which would value the deal at $9.4 billion,
based on Monday's Motorola stock price.
</P>
<P>
   But initial reaction to the combination was negative as
investors sent the stock of both companies tumbling Monday on the
New York Stock Exchange. Shares of Motorola, which is based in
Schaumburg, Ill., fell $8.25, or 8.5 percent, to $90.375, and
shares of General Instrument, which is based in Horsham, Pa.,
dropped $2.8125, or 5.4 percent, to $49.6875.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors in General Instrument apparently considered the
price Motorola was offering as too low, while some Motorola
shareholders apparently thought it too high, fearing the
acquisition could dilute earnings in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow the two companies said that even if
Motorola's earnings were hurt in the early stages of the merger,
the deal would eventually reap huge benefits by positioning the
company in the fast-converging market of cable television and
telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger makes a lot of sense for Motorola,'' said Kenneth
Leon, an analyst at ABN Amro. ``This is clearly the direction
Motorola wants to go in: they've been desperately looking for
another high-growth business, and digital boxes open up
opportunities for new features and services.''
</P>
<P>
   The move by Motorola comes as the world of media,
telecommunications and cable properties is being redrawn. Just last
week, Viacom Inc. agreed to acquire CBS Inc. That deal would create
the world's second-largest media company after Time-Warner Inc. And
over the last two years, AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest telephone
company, has transformed itself into the nation's leading provider
of cable television by swallowing up companies like
Telecommunications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts say leading telecommunications, cable and
media companies are scrambling to find partners in the expectation
that many of the technologies will converge. Wireless phones,
televisions, video games and other devices will no longer have
distinct voice, data and video applications. They will be one _ or
at least linked through cable and wireless ports that can deliver
high-quality video and audio.
</P>
<P>
   ``A major focus for them is broadband technology,'' Mona Eraiba,
an analyst at Gruntal &AMP; Company, said of the prospective
Motorola-General Instrument deal. ``There are going to be set-top
boxes with cable modems and satellite technology. This is really a
chance to deploy the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola is already the leading maker of cable modems, which can
deliver cable programming into the personal computer. Now, analysts
say, the company can combine that technology and its ability to
feed data into a set-top box and cable infrastructure devised by
General Instrument that delivers everything from interactive video
to electronic commerce capacities. Some analysts predict that new
set-top boxes will be equipped with pay-per-view access and a slot
through which a credit card could be swiped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at an inflexion point, everything is moving very fast,''
Ms. Eraiba said. ``And the set-top boxes sit at the crossroads of
many technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola is now racing to that crossroads. After stumbling badly
because of a slowdown in Asia and a decline in the sales of
cellular telephones, Motorola has moved aggressively to return to
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the company has made sharp cuts in its work
force, upgraded its cellular handsets in a booming cellular
marketplace and moved quickly to beef up its software development
and to position itself in the Internet and home entertainment
markets.
</P>
<P>
   It has made agreements with Cisco Systems and Sun Microsystems
Inc. to begin developing a ``wireless Internet'' network. The
company has also invested heavily in Teledesic LLC to produce
satellites to create an ``Internet in the sky'' system.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Motorola have rocketed more than 50 percent in the
past year, despite a troublesome investment in Iridium LLC, a
satellite telephone service now in Chapter 11 bankruptcy. Still,
company executives say Motorola is reaching into homes with cable
modems, set-top boxes and high-definition television sets, with
gentle whispers about the new buzzword on Wall Street: convergence.
</P>
<P>
   ``With set-top boxes they would have a control center that
delivers bytes the same way your electric company is delivering
watts,'' said Eric Buck, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette. ``The big picture is that broadband pipes are going to
win out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-13-99 2142EDT &QL;
</P>
