<SLUG> BC-CPT-MAC-REPORT14-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Graphics world gets new tool 
By Charles Haddad  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They came expecting a new enhanced iMac, but what the
audience of publishers and graphic designers got instead was the
surprise announcement of a new computer built for them.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Steve Jobs, the mercurial interim chief executive of Apple,
had done it again. He used the recent Seybold trade show in San
Francisco to unveil a new development in his company's technology:
a new microprocessor chip called the G4.
</P>
<P>
   The chip offers computing speeds up to 500 megahertz. Jobs calls
this microprocessor the ``first supercomputer on a chip.''
</P>
<P>
   The speed of a chip in megahertz is not the total measure of how
fast the chip performs. The technical performance specifications of
this chip are nearly three times faster than those of the Pentium
III microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   The G4 is so fast, in part, because it includes something called
the ``velocity engine.'' It can perform multiple operations and is
especially good at handling streaming media such as video and
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Such an improvement is especially important to graphic
designers, who increasingly find themselves working with multimedia
projects like Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Apple's new G4 Power Macs are designed for this
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   To further enhance the appeal of the G4 to designers, Apple also
released at Seybold a new 22-inch, flat screen monitor. Some of
those who have used this monitor, called Apple Cinema Display, have
called its sharpness ``stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   The G4 will be available in two versions. Keeping them straight
can be a little confusing, given that they both carry the same
moniker, but here goes.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the two G4s is essentially a souped-up version of
Apple's current blue-and-white desktop machine, the G3. What's new
is the G4 microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the speed of the G4 will be 400 mhz, with more
powerful versions arriving in October. It will sell for $1,600, the
same price as the top of the line G3.
</P>
<P>
   The second version of the G4, dubbed Sawtooth, will include a
redesign of the motherboard, which is the central nervous system of
any computer.
</P>
<P>
   The redesign will add several improvements, including faster
hard drives, ports and wireless networking technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Sawtooth model, however, is not expected to ship until
November. It will sell between $2,400 and $6,500, depending on the
speed of the microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   While the G4s are more powerful than what most consumers need,
the model is important to Apple, anchoring the support of the
design and publishing industry, which long has been the company's
biggest supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
