 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
New biz magazine looks at entrepreneurs &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta has a new local business magazine, and it's
called Catalyst. The magazine's debut issue features a lead article
about five young entrepreneurs the writer says are shaping ``a new
Atlanta.'' The five are Andrea Arena, founder and president of 2
Places at 1 Time; Jeff Levy, founder of eHatchery; Alan Daniels,
chairman of RealEstate.com; Alexis Abramson, founder of Mature
Mart; and Tom Noonan, president of Internet Security Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Catalyst also features an article that asks whether Atlanta is
the Silicon Valley of the South. Not quite, the article concludes,
arguing that the city still lacks the name-brand companies, capital
and talent to claim the mantle.
</P>
<P>
   If you're stuck in a Nintendo game, unable to move to the next
level, you might want to check out the September issue of Nintendo
Power. This magazine, as you may guess from the name, features
nothing but stories about how to win games on Game Boy, Super
Nintendo and Nintendo 64. The current issue features tips on how to
play Gauntlet Legends, Gex 3, Re-Volt and Shadow Man. You'll also
find tips on color Game Boy titles such as Tarzan, Looney Tunes and
Deja Vu.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Both Intuit and Microsoft, the leading makers of personal
finance software, have announced new versions of their programs.
Microsoft's Money 2000 now offers a guided interview that helps you
set up the program and organize your finances. Lots of new ``what
if'' calculators also let you figure out things such as how much
you need to save to finance a child's college education. Money is
available only for Windows-based computers.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit's Quicken 2000 has similar features. In addition, it has
added an insight tool that lets you see in place, at one time, a
complete picture of your personal finances. Quicken is available
for both Macs and PCs.
</P>
<P>
   IN PRINT
</P>
<P>
   Now that school is back in session, it's time to consider
something artful. There's a new artsy magazine called Terrain. It's
a quarterly publication featuring essays, poetry and articles about
subjects ranging from rivers to the suburbs. You'll find this site
at www.terrain.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-13-99 1145EDT &QL;
</P>
