<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-REPORT14-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Mad air travelers get ticking
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to air travel, there is a lot to be
ticked about: runway delays, coach seating that feels more like
steerage and, perhaps especially, the use of the word ``deplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a site, www.ticked.com, to serve as your caustic
mouthpiece. The site is a collection of consumer-friendly,
anti-corporate rants about anything and everything annoying about
travel. It's Ralph Nader and Dennis Miller with a little Don
Rickles tossed in to put an edge on things.
</P>
<P>
   A recent ChrisCrossings column answered a question from a reader
who wondered when airlines were going to quit squeezing more seats
into the business and first-class areas and cramping the folks in
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree the economy-class passengers are flying like sardines.
I base that conclusion on the ever-shrinking distance between seats
... (which) has shrunk from about 33 inches to about 30 inches. But
there are other passenger comfort issues, such as reduced seat
width, overall quality and diminished air supply that all make for
a claustrophobic traveling experience. But passengers aren't
behaving very well either. A well-publicized string of ``air rage''
incidents has plagued the airline business for the last few years.
Reversing the air rage problem is easy: Just release passengers
from the vise grip that is economy class.''
</P>
<P>
   The site is free. It was created by Christopher Elliott, an
Annapolis, Md.-based free-lance travel writer who writes a column
called the Crabby Traveler for ABCNews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Site helps you become your dog's best friend
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you know someone who keeps a dog chained in the back
yard and rarely walks it. It's enough to make you wonder why the
dog was gotten in the first place, as a companion or a furrier,
more politically correct lawn jockey?
</P>
<P>
   A thoughtful Web site, www.howtoloveyourdog.com, tries to remove
some of the mystery from dog ownership and prevent decent people
from becoming bad owners.
</P>
<P>
   The site is aimed at children, trying to catch potential dog
owners before bad habits form.
</P>
<P>
   It was created by Janet Wall, a former San Diego elementary
schoolteacher. Wall decided to take lesson plans she designed to
teach students kindness, commitment and responsibility and apply
them to dog-raising.
</P>
<P>
   The advice is designed to cover a dog's life, from ``A New Dog''
through ``Losing Dogs,'' with ``What They Cost,'' ``What They
Need'' and ``Where They Come From,'' in between.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking on ``A New Dog'' gives you an idea of the thoroughness
of the site.
</P>
<P>
   She points out several of the downsides of dog ownership,
mentioning that dogs can: get big, bark a lot, chew furniture, shed
and get sick on the rug.
</P>
<P>
   Wall also lists several questions that anyone considering dog
ownership should ask, including:
</P>
<P>
   Am I responsible?
</P>
<P>
   Am I kind and gentle?
</P>
<P>
   Do I have the extra time to spend with a dog?
</P>
<P>
   Do I want to spend 10 to 15 years with a dog?
</P>
<P>
   Does everyone in your house want one?
</P>
<P>
   Whitney to show art of 20th century America
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, Intel and New York's Whitney Museum of
American Art are launching the second half of an online version of
a museum tour.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.artmuseum.net, features paintings from the
Whitney's The American Century: Art &AMP; Culture 1900-2000 exhibit.
The online tour will feature works from 1950 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   The first part opened in April and it featured more than 100
objects on display at the Whitney. The part starting Sept. 26
features another 100 works and includes archival documents, images
and historical information about the era. The combined exhibit will
be online for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
