<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-APPLE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 AT THE SOURCE: Heirlooms of the Orchard   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SEBASTAPOL, Calif. _  When it comes to enthusiasm for apples,
Johnny Appleseed has nothing on Stan Devoto. When this Sonoma
County grower describes his Gravensteins, Winesaps, Spitzenburgs,
Galas and Arkansas Blacks, you can almost feel the tart spritz of a
tree-ripened apple in your mouth and smell the heady aroma of an
apple crisp bubbling toward sweet perfection in the oven.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Devoto, a one-time home builder, and his wife, Susan, moved
to Sebastopol two decades ago they bought property that was filled
with apple trees. Susan Devoto enrolled in community college
classes to learn how to grow and care for apples, and the couple
leased additional acreage. In short order, builder Devoto had
become farmer Devoto.
</P>
<P>
   That was when the Gravenstein _ which reportedly traces its
lineage to Northern Italy _ ruled supreme in Sonoma County. In the
1960s, says Devoto, there were about 12,000 acres of apple orchards
in western Sonoma County alone (Devoto cultivated as many as 60).
Today, acreage is down to 4,000; the Devotos grow heirloom and
antique apples on 15 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The decline, Devoto says, can be traced to changes in lifestyles
and economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cans anymore, and few people make applesauce or bake
pies'' _ preparations to which the Gravenstein is uniquely suited,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   On the economic side, the equation is fairly fundamental.
Gravensteins are fickle, with many trees yielding good harvests
only every other year. The same land planted to wine grapes can
bring in 21/2 to six times as much money. The initial investment in
growing grapes may be high, but in the long run that's where the
profit is.
</P>
<P>
   The Devotos haven't joined the stampede. Instead, they have
developed a thriving business in cut flowers, which subsidizes the
apples.
</P>
<P>
   Devoto sends his apple and flower harvests to 12 farmers'
markets around the Bay Area, including San Francisco's Ferry Plaza,
San Rafael and St. Helena. These markets, along with some specialty
stores like Berkeley's Monterey Market and restaurants that
appreciate locally grown fruit with distinct qualities and flavors,
guarantee the survival of old varieties like the Gravenstein.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of commercial produce distribution, these classics
would surely face extinction, Devoto believes. They cannot be
harvested under-ripe _ as most large-scale crops are _ but are
hand-picked at their peak. That's what makes them deliciously
special _ and too perishable for the mass market that demands long
shelf life. Gravensteins, like most heirloom apples, start to
soften after a week.
</P>
<P>
   Devoto likes to explain these things to customers at the
farmers' markets he attends, often accompanied by one of his three
daughters, aged 9, 11 and 15.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven-year-old Jolie is ``the most into apples'' and might just
follow in her parents' footsteps. Her dad says she bakes a fine
apple crisp and, showing early business acumen, often sells some of
it to workers on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether they end up with farming careers or choose
other pursuits, Devoto says farm life with its seasonal cycles and
dependence on nature creates a healthy environment for growing up.
And it enables him to be an active father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I start early,'' Devoto says of his work day, ``and I try to
knock off by 4:30. During the week, I don't miss any of the girls'
soccer games.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; An Orchard and Its Heirlooms &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Heirlooms are fragile. That applies to old and unusual fruit just
as much as it does to fine old furniture or china.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Devoto, who grows as many as 65 kinds of heirloom and
unusual apples on 15 acres in Sebastopol, can explain both why this
kind of apple _ Winesap, Gravenstein, Arkansas Black, Spitzenburg
(Thomas Jefferson's favorite) and Hawaiian (an apple with a flavor
resembling tropical fruit, developed in Sebastopol 50 years ago) _
has become rare, and why it's a fruit to be treasured.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastopol, he says, has the best growing conditions an apple
could encounter. The coastal climate with its cool nights and foggy
mornings, followed by warm afternoons, lets the apple mature at a
leisurely pace. Devoto does not have to irrigate his orchards _
another factor that contributes to the intense flavor and what he
considers the unsurpassed texture of these apples.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most supermarket varieties, Devoto's apples are not
picked until they are truly ripe. They can't be stored very long
before they get soft, so they don't fit the mantra of mass
marketers: shelf life, shelf life, shelf life. What's more, they
may have a few marks or look a little gnarled. Some of them are,
admits Devoto, cosmetically challenged.
</P>
<P>
   But _ ah _ the taste. ``I eat 10 apples a day,'' the grower
admits with a chuckle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
