<HEADER>
A2852 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-ONLINE-HIGHSCHOOL     09-15 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONLINE-HIGHSCHOOLS-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    No more teachers...or classrooms...or hallways....
 &HT;    By Joanne Huist Smith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Schools in Ohio are virtually changing.
</P>
<P>
   Classrooms in Warren and Hamilton counties will move out of the
traditional school setting into homes, businesses, libraries _
anywhere there's a computer that has Internet access with the
start-up this week of a Virtual Learning Academy in Ohio. For the
first time in the state, it's possible to take high school courses
online.
</P>
<P>
   Other counties, including Montgomery County, are expected to
join in quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This educational delivery system can break down time and
distance barriers that have kept people out of the classroom,''
said John Boggess, superintendent of the Miami Valley Career
Technology Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults can take classes to enhance their jobs, students can
get special intervention for proficiency tests or take classes not
offered at their school.''
</P>
<P>
   Via the Internet, students learn from the best libraries,
museums, and information archives in the world, said Greg Berry,
president of The Citadel Group International, based in Maryland.
Citadel developed the learning academy and was hired to make sure
the lessons meet Ohio Department of Education standards, Berry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many courses are enhanced by graphics, stereo sounds and
multimedia pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The courses are set up so students can move at their own pace,
but still receive guidance from a teacher who is either at an area
school or available by e-mail or telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe you cannot substitute the face-to-face time with a
teacher. That element has to be incorporated into any kind of
learning,'' said Clifford A. Migal, president of the Great Oaks
Institute of Technology and Career Development, the joint
vocational school that serves, Hamilton, Highland, and Clermont
Counties.
</P>
<P>
   The academy includes two components: Learning Springs: On-line
curriculum for students grades five to 12. In Ohio, the fee runs
about $165 per student for unlimited access to a library of 80
courses that include basic education classes, proficiency
intervention and electives such as foreign languages. Adult
Learning: more than 600 courses that range from personal
development to computer classes to electrical schematics. Fees run
$150 per course with up to six months to complete. There's no
traditional start of the school year so students can sign up and
get started at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges offer courses on-line, but only three states _ New
York, Georgia and South Carolina _ offer Internet study. Citadel
has contracts with about 6,000 individual school districts to
provide coursework in some fashion on-line.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio will tap into virtual classes through an initiative of the
Ohio Association of Joint Vocational School Superintendents. The
association voted in August to secure rights to the Citaldel's
curriculum in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw an opportunity for public education to use virtual
learning as a tool in a viably financial way,'' said Vince
Roessner, superintendent of the Warren County Career Center. ``If
we don't deliver this, somebody else will and they may not be as
altruistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Roessner and Migal volunteered to test the program for adults
and high school students in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Great Oaks got the head start with virtual classes offered to
161 students over the summer. Of those students, two failed, two
dropped the courses and 157 passed. About 83 percent of the
students got a C or better, Migel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a group who had already failed the class
once. You bring them back with a new delivery option and 157 out of
161 complete the class,'' Migel said. ``That's phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Great Oaks and Warren County career centers will begin to
offer virtual classes to adults in October. Roessner said virtual
high school classes should be on-line by the end of the year.
Credit from the classes counts toward a high school diploma and
would show up on a student's transcript no differently than if the
student went to school to pass the class.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County hopes to roll out adult programs in January,
Boggess said. The Greene County Career Center is investigating the
on-line courses but has no definite plan to start them,
Superintendent Marsha Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very interested in learning more,'' Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Contact the Warren County Career Center (513) 932-5677 or visit
the website at http://members.xoom.com/citadelgroup The Virtual
Learning Academy targets:
</P>
<P>
   Students who are at risk for dropping out due to low academic
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Students prevented from participating in regular classes due to
suspension/expulsion
</P>
<P>
   Students away from school for extended periods of time due to
illness or incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   Regular students who need additional time time to meet required
learning objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Students desiring courses (including honors) not offered locally
or those desiring to accelerate learning.
</P>
<P>
   Adults or students who previously dropped out and want to obtain
a GED or high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wants to take classes to improve their employability.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Huist Smith writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-13-99 2155EDT &QL;
</P>
