<HEADER>
A2854 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKING-SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 1893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 THE WORKING COOK: Prepared Food Shortcuts Allow for Even
Speedier  Cooking  By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Bay Area grocery stores are making it possible for
us to cook quickly without having to resort to frozen or heavily
processed foods. With all of the freshly prepared foods _ fresh
salsa, cleaned and deveined shrimp, prewashed salad mixes and
smoked tofu, just to name a few _ why not take advantage?
<P>
   However, some pre-prepared foods are better than others. Many
commercial pestos, for instance, have lost their fresh herbal
flavor by the time you get them.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to find the best products. Pasta Etc. brand pesto,
made in Sonoma, has no cheese or oil and is flavored with miso.
That may not sound like pesto at all, but its bright basil flavor
works very well in this week's Fast &AMP; Fresh recipe.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe is simple but elegant enough for a dinner party
because of the way it looks _ luscious pink salmon atop golden
couscous, accented with green basil sauce. Quick pan-frying gives
the fillets a crisp crust and moist interior, and the pesto sauce,
mixed with lemon juice, cuts through the richness of the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Another excellent prepared product is achiote paste. Widely used
in Mexico's Yucatan region, this seasoning base is made of ground
annatto seeds, spices, vinegar and sometimes garlic. Mixed with oil
and additional seasonings, achiote is an instant marinade that
gives intense flavor and an appealing saffron-red color to meat and
fish.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's 30-minute recipe, chicken breasts are marinated
in achiote, then quickly broiled. The chicken is placed on top of a
salad of crisp jicama and arugula dressed with lime juice and a
touch of cayenne, bringing the vibrant marinade to life.
</P>
<P>
   Like all lasagnas, the Now &AMP; Later recipe, Lentil and Butternut
Squash Lasagna, involves many steps. But it's worth every minute
you spend behind the stove.
</P>
<P>
   A vegetarian dish created by my non-meat-eating friend
Elisabeth, the lasagna brings together butternut squash, roasted
until creamy, with firm French lentils and intensely sweet
caramelized onions. A rich b &LR; e &LR; chamel sauce makes the layers float
on top of each other like clouds.
</P>
<P>
   When making a many-stepped recipe like Lentil and Butternut
Squash Lasagna, do all the prep work ahead of time. Chop the
vegetables and herbs, measure the liquids and grate the cheese
before you start cooking. Being organized allows you to cook many
things at once instead of trying to chop while minding something on
the stove.
</P>
<P>
   If you like, break up the preparation by cooking the b &LR; e &LR; chamel
and vegetables ahead of time, then layering the lasagna the next
day. To reheat b &LR; e &LR; chamel, add a bit more milk and heat it slowly,
stirring constantly. Do not allow it to boil.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; PAN-FRIED SALMON FILLETS WITH LEMON PESTO &AMP; COUSCOUS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons prepared pesto sauce (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 (10-ounce) package instant couscous
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons + 1 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 boned skinless salmon fillets, 5 to 6 ounces each and 1-inch
thick
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 lemon wedges
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   If possible, let the pesto sit at room temperature for 20
minutes before beginning preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the pesto sauce and lemon juice. Set aside at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the couscous according to package directions, adding 1/2
teaspoon salt and 1 teaspoon olive oil to the cooking water. Keep
warm while while you prepare the salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Season the salmon fillets on both sides with salt and pepper.
Heat a large nonstick skillet until quite hot. Add 1 tablespoon of
the olive oil and heat until almost smoking. Cook 2 salmon fillets
flesh-side down over medium-high heat until crispy on the bottom,
about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the fillets and cook an additional 2 minutes. The fish
should be tender in the middle and crispy outside. Remove the
fillets from the pan and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining 1 tablespoon olive oil to the pan and repeat
with the 2 remaining fillets.
</P>
<P>
   Fluff the couscous with a fork. Serve the salmon on a bed of
couscous, dressed with the lemon-pesto sauce and garnished with
lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Pasta Etc. pesto sauce (made in Sonoma), which has no
cheese or oil, works well in this recipe because it cuts through
the richness of the salmon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 695 calories, &LR;   &LR; 39 g protein, 54 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 36 g fat (7 g saturated), 97 mg cholesterol, 418 mg
sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ACHIOTE-MARINATED CHICKEN BREASTS WITH JICAMA SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons achiote paste (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless, skinless chicken half-beasts
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 to 2 limes
</P>
<P>
   1 medium jicama
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch arugula or other bitter greens
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the achiote paste, cumin, the 11/2 teaspoons salt
and the vegetable oil. Coat the chicken in this mixture and set
aside at room temperature for a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape off any large chunks of marinade from the chicken
breasts. Place breasts on a foil-lined pan and cook directly under
the broiler until done, 7-15 minutes, depending on thickness. Check
for doneness by slicing through thickest part of one breast. If you
see any pinkness, continue cooking another minute or so. When done,
remove chicken from the oven and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cayenne pepper, sugar, juice of 1 lime and salt to
taste in a small bowl. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the jicama in half, then stand each half on its flat end and
trim off the skin with a sharp knife. Cut the halves into 1/4-inch
slices, then stack them and cut them again into long julienne.
</P>
<P>
   Trim off and discard the woody stem ends from the bunch of
arugula and coarsely chop the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the jicama and arugula in a bowl and toss with the
dressing. The jicama should have a kick of cayenne and tart lime;
add more if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, slice each chicken breast crosswise into 4 large
pieces. Place the salad on a large platter and arrange the chicken
pieces on top. Serve with warm tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; You can find bricks of achiote paste in Latin American
markets or in supermarkets with large Hispanic sections.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Variation:  &LR; These chicken breasts are delicious on the grill,
or use a grill pan to get a smoky flavor and grill marks. You can
pump up the flavor of the marinade by adding minced garlic, some
fresh orange juice or a dash of tequila. The salad is even more
succulent with the addition of orange segments.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING  &LR; ( &LR; The calories and other nutrients absorbed from &LR; 
 &LR; marinades vary and are difficult to estimate. Variables include &LR; 
 &LR; the type of food, marinating time and amount of surface area. &LR; 
 &LR; Therefore, the marinade is not included in this recipe &LR; ):  &LR; 175 &LR; 
 &LR; calories, &LR;   &LR; 28 g protein, 11 g carbohydrate, 2 g fat (0 &LR; 
 &LR; saturated), 68 mg cholesterol, 84 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; NOW &AMP; LATER dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; LENTIL &AMP; SQUASH LASAGNA WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   18 sheets lasagna (about 1 pound)
</P>
<P>
   Bechamel Sauce (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   The Vegetables
</P>
<P>
   7 pounds butternut squash
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   8 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon thyme leaves, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   The Lentils
</P>
<P>
   21/4 cups French green lentils (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 celery stalks, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Instrustions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the vegetables:  &LR; Preheat the oven to 375 degrees. Line
large baking sheets with foil or parchment. Halve the butternut
squash. Discard seeds. Brush the exposed halves with 2 tablespoons
of the olive oil and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Place the squash halves cut-sides up on the baking sheets. Bake
until the thickest part of the squash is tender when pierced with
the tip of a sharp knife, about 30 minutes. Do not let it get
completely soft. Remove from oven and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   When cool, scoop out the flesh into a bowl. Chunk into small
pieces and season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 2 tablespoons olive oil in a large nonstick
saute pan. Add the sliced onions and cook over medium-high heat,
stirring often, for about 10 minutes. Add the garlic and thyme and
continue to cook until the onions are golden brown and very sweet,
15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The lentils:  &LR; While the squash is roasting, place the lentils
in a small saucepan with the celery, carrot, onion, bay leaf and
salt. Add enough water to cover the vegetables completely. Bring to
a boil, then simmer until the lentils are completely tender, 15 to
20 minutes. Remove the vegetables and bay leaves, strain out any
liquid and adjust the seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The lasagna:  &LR; Cook the lasagna noodles in a large pot of
boiling salted water until al dente. Drain, then spread out to dry
on a baking sheet so the noodles won't stick to each other.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Mix together the squash,
lentils, caramelized onion and half of the bechamel sauce. Divide
this mixture into 3 equal parts.
</P>
<P>
   Place one third of the vegetable mixture on the bottom of an
oversized lasagna pan (or use an 8 x 8-inch pan plus a 9 x 13-inch
pan). Sprinkle with 1/3 cup of the Parmesan. Cover with a layer of
lasagna noodles. You may have to trim the noodles to make them fit
in the pan(s).
</P>
<P>
   Repeat the layers two more times. Spread the remaining bechamel
on top of the last pasta layer. Cover the sauce with the remaining
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until heated through and golden brown on top, 20 to 25
minutes. Let rest 10 minutes before cutting and serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; French green lentils are available in upscale
supermarkets and specialty stores. Do not substitute any other
lentils, which become mushy when cooked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 595 calories, &LR;   &LR; 26 g protein, 85 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 19 g fat (9 g saturated), 40 mg cholesterol, 310 mg
sodium, 11 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BECHAMEL SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   This recipe makes just enough sauce for the Lentil and Squash
Lasagna.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1/2 onion
</P>
<P>
   1 whole clove
</P>
<P>
   6 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   Pinch nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the bay leaf on the outside of the onion half, then pierce
it with the clove to attach. Add this piquet and the milk to a
small saucepan. Reduce over medium-low heat for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the milk is reducing, make the roux. Melt the butter in a
heavy-bottomed saute pan over low heat. Slowly incorporate the
flour, stirring constantly. Continue stirring over low heat for 4
to 5 minutes. Remove from the heat. Strain the milk and discard the
onion pique.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the milk into the roux a little at a time. Bring to a
simmer and cook 15 minutes over very low heat, stirring often. Stir
in the nutmeg and season with salt and white pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Set aside at room temperature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
