<SLUG> BC-BOOKPARIS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: Add a Touch of France to the Table   By Stephen Baker 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  It's a popular notion that Parisians dine on foie
gras and truffles every night, but Michael Roberts sets the record
straight with his new book, ``Parisian Home Cooking: Conversations,
Recipes and Tips From the Cooks and Food Merchants of Paris.''
<P>
   Roberts, who attended the Ecole Superieure de Cuisine
Jean-Ferrandi in France before opening Trumps restaurant in Los
Angeles, has spent long periods of time in Paris and knows it well.
</P>
<P>
   He demystifies French cooking by pointing out that while the
French rely on fresh ingredients they're not necessarily luxurious
ones. French home cooks might spend more time preparing food than
their American counterparts but their typical dishes are generally
fairly easy to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is an excellent storyteller and his descriptions of the
markets, people and cityscapes enliven the 175 recipes. The
anecdotes also point out the central role food plays in French
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' friends and professional colleagues in France
contributed the recipes and the accompanying _ and jealously
guarded _  &LR; astuces &LR; . These tricks of the trade help make the
recipes accessible and also highlight tips and techniques to make
them special.
</P>
<P>
   However, some recipes do require hard-to-find ingredients and
this can be a drawback since Roberts does not suggest alternatives.
Even though the Bay Area is a hotbed of gourmet foodstuffs and
produce, searching for the likes of veal top round and striped bass
fillets can be challenging.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, recipes like Eggs Poached in Tarragon
Cream _ which features a wonderful combination of flavors and
textures _ and Bibb Lettuce with Chicken Livers and Gizzards _
which turned me into a fan of the earthy-tasting innards _ are
excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the recipes showcase the French flair with thrifty cuts
of meat, such as chicken livers, and with lesser-used vegetables
like turnips. With Roberts' help, Americans can bring this flair
and other secrets of Parisian home cooking to their own tables.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Parisian Home Cooking: Conversations, Recipes and Tips From &LR; 
 &LR; the Cooks and Food Merchants of Paris,'' by Michael Roberts &LR; 
 &LR; (William Morrow and Co.; 335 pages; $25). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BIBB LETTUCE WITH CHICKEN LIVERS &AMP; GIZZARDS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound chicken gizzards
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brandy
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound chicken livers
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh thyme leaves or dried
</P>
<P>
   12 peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   3 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, peeled
</P>
<P>
   About 1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   16 garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons aged red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh tarragon (do not use dried)
</P>
<P>
   2 heads Bibb lettuce, washed, dried and leaves torn
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   One day in advance, rinse the gizzards. Lay them flat on a work
surface, silverskin down. Beginning in the center, remove as much
silverskin as you can easily, cutting each gizzard in half. Place
the gizzards in a small bowl, mix with half the salt and half the
brandy, and place in the refrigerator for 12 to 18 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the livers and trim them of any green or discolored bits.
Place in another bowl with the remaining salt and brandy and place
in the refrigerator for 12 to 18 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, tie up the thyme, peppercorns, bay leaves and
cloves in a square of cheesecloth and place in a heavy 1-quart
casserole. Halve the onion from tip to stem, lay it flat, and slice
it lengthwise. Add the onion to the casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Drain and rinse the gizzards; discard the marinade. Add the
gizzards to the casserole, add enough oil to cover, and place the
casserole, covered, in the oven. Turn the oven on to 325 degrees
and cook for 11/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Drain and rinse the livers; discard the marinade. Add the livers
and garlic to the casserole and cook for an additional 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Strain out the gizzards, livers, onion and garlic and allow the
cooking fat to drip off. Discard the herb packet. Reserve the
cooking fat. Allow everything to cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Stir the mustard, vinegar and tarragon together in a salad bowl.
Whisk in about 3 tablespoons of the reserved fat. Place the lettuce
in the bowl and add the gizzard and liver mixture. Toss the salad
at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING &LR;  ( &LR; The calories and other nutrients absorbed from &LR; 
 &LR; marinades vary and are difficult to estimate. Variables include &LR; 
 &LR; the type of food, marinating time and amount of surface area. &LR; 
 &LR; Therefore, the marinade is not included in this analysis. &LR; ) &UR; : &LR; 
 &LR; 315 calories, &LR;   &LR; 36 g protein, 14 g carbohydrate, 16 g fat (3 g &LR; 
 &LR; saturated), 414 mg cholesterol, 142 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
