<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 BAY AREA CLASSICS: Duo Revives Drewes Brothers   Stephen Baker  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Hop on a Muni J car, get off at 29th and Church
streets in the heart of Noe Valley and you'll spot shoppers
meandering in and out of Drewes Brothers Meats.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 110-year-old Drewes, along with Star Bakery across the
street, anchors a lively block-long business district. The
neighborhood is home to majestic St. Paul's Catholic Church,
renowned for the 1991 &UR;  &LR; film, ``Sister Act,'' starring Whoopi
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   But last fall, the community lost Drewes _ temporarily, that is.
</P>
<P>
   On October 15, owners Dave and Teri McCarroll closed the butcher
shop, which had shared space with Stellings, a video and mailbox
rental operation. The counters were cleared, the antique clock was
removed from the wall and the butcher sign was taken out of the
window. Stellings remained open under the proprietorship of Cecila
De Leon.
</P>
<P>
   But the block wasn't the same without Drewes, De Leon says.
Disappointed customers kept coming into Stellings and asking about
Drewes' disappearance. Soon, a sheet of butcher paper appeared on
the front of the building, filled with shoppers' pleas to reopen
the store.
</P>
<P>
   They got their way. Within two weeks, the butcher shop was open
again, run by former employees Isaac and Josh Epple.
</P>
<P>
   The Epples, who had worked at Drewes for years _ Isaac started
as a window-washer at the age of 16 _ wanted to reopen the
business, and building landlord Phil Tomasello gave them the
chance. Drewes was back, with ``Brothers'' added to acknowledge the
new owners' relation and the original Drewes, who were brothers as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The Epples also kept much of what made Drewes popular in the
first place _ the signature stuffed pork chops made with fresh
herbs, onions, garlic and sourdough breadcrumbs, and the house-made
meat loaf mix.
</P>
<P>
   Drewes also continues to carry salads, deli meats and cheeses,
sausages and a good selection of seafood, along with all the
butcher-counter staples &LR;   &LR; and free-range poultry.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers have added rotisserie chicken to their offerings,
and in the future plan to add entire take-out dinners and some
French wines to accompany them.
</P>
<P>
   The Epples feel a sense of place and purpose in bringing Drewes
back to the neighborhood. ``I like the homey atmosphere best . . . &LR; 
 &LR; I know probably 80 percent of the customers that come through the
door,'' Isaac says.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the bustle of daily activity, those customers return
often. As this Noe Valley community can attest, sometimes you don't
know what you've got until it's gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
