<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 WINE POTPOURRI: Washington Defines `Reserve'  &HT;       
 By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  California may be the nation's leader in terms of
wineries and wine production, but it lags behind Washington as a
pro-active state in getting some wine-related things done.
<P>
   For years, the wine industry has not been able to come up with a
consensus on the definition of ``reserve'' on a wine label and the
federal government has avoided writing a legal definition. But now,
the Washington Wine Commission, under the newly established
Washington Wine Quality Alliance (WWQA), has provided the nation's
first definition for Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the 2000 vintage, the word Reserve can only appear
on the label of 10 percent of a Washington winery's total
production or on 3,000 cases of the particular variety, whichever
is greater. In addition, any Reserve wine must be made up entirely
of grapes grown in the state of Washington. This move by the WWZA
is pro-consumer because it provides information to help wine-buyers
make informed purchases.
</P>
<P>
   WWQA members have also agreed to phase out the use of generic
wine terms like Bordeaux, Burgundy, Chablis and Champagne, a move
that shows confidence in the quality of local wines without relying
on foreign names to make the sale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pinot Chardonnay
</P>
<P>
   The big buzz in wine circles is the discovery by University of
California at Davis grape sleuths that Chardonnay and 15 other
grape varieties are related to an obscure French grape called
Gouais as well as to the prestigious Pinot Noir. DNA fingerprinting
made the discovery possible.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean we can go back to calling America's favorite
white wine Pinot Chardonnay? That was the term many wine people
used for the grape and the wine until Chardonnay started its rise
to stardom in the 1970s. But back then, experts said the Chardonnay
grape wasn't part of the Pinot family. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Q &AMP; A &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Janne Mahan of Menlo Park wants to know where to purchase
1995 Signorello Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   A: Signorello reports the wine is mostly sold out, but
Andronico's may still carry some. Or, call Linda at Signorello,
(707) 255-5990, for more help.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few weeks ago, a reader asked about the availability of
Barbera Blanc, a blush-type wine made from the Barbera grape.
</P>
<P>
   A: Readers have informed Potpourri that a Barbera Blanc called
Imbianco is available for $9.50 at Viansa Winery, 25200 Arnold
Drive in Sonoma and at Viansa's Lo Spuntino tasting room on the
square in Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Vintage 1999 has been one to watch closely since little has gone
according to schedule. Until recently, cool temperatures have kept
winemakers and grape growers in the vineyards to check for
ripeness.
</P>
<P>
   The stage that occurs just before a grape is fully ripe is
called veraison. At this stage the grapes are a good size and
weight and growers often use laboratory analysis to determine if
they're about ready to pick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Wine Events &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ This year's KRCB On-Air Wine Auction, from 7-10:30 p.m.
tomorrow through Saturday, is one for the serious wine collector.
An anonymous donor has given more than 100 bottles of rare
California and French wines to the offerings. For more information,
contact KRCB-TV 22 at (800) 287-2722.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Benziger Family Winery will hold a 1999 Harvest Dinner and
Wine Celebration at the winery, 1883 London Ranch Road in Glen
Ellen on September 24 starting at 6 p.m. Chef John Toulze of The
Girl and the Fig restaurant in Sonoma County has created the menu.
Seating is $125 per person and can be reserved by calling (800)
989-8890.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
