<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Campbell's Is Tops For Minestrone Soup  &HT;        By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  For a quick lunch or dinner, canned soup can be a
lifesaver. The number of soups available take up row after row on
supermarket shelves, which means just about every soup imaginable
can be purchased in a can.
<P>
   Today's panel tasted six canned minestrones, as well as one
minestrone in a jar. We did not include any soups labled low-fat or
nonfat, though many of the soups were naturally low in fat.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the soups were concentrates and required the addition of
water. All were heated according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   The panel liked a couple of the soups, but found most of them to
be bland and watery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Campbell's Home Cookin' &LR;  (19 ounces, $1.89-$2.09 at many
supermarkets) took top honors. All panelists commented on the good
texture of the pasta and vegetables. One panelist thought the soup
was too oily, but another described it as a ``nice, clean soup.''
One would buy it, and four might.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's also took second place with  &UR; Campbell's Simply &LR; 
 &UR; Home &LR;  (24 ounces, $2.69 at many supermarkets), which comes in a
jar. Three panelists liked the ratio of vegetables and pasta to
broth, and one described it as ``tasting home cooked.'' But many
found the soup overly spiced with fennel or anise (the label does
not list which herbs and spices are used). One would buy it, two
might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the rest was  &UR; Progresso &LR;  (19 ounces, $1.99-$2.79 at
many supermarkets). Three panelists described it as bland, but most
liked the mixture of vegetables and beans. One panelist thought the
soup had a nice herbal quality, but another thought the herbs
tasted stale. One would buy it, two might buy it, and two would
not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Riviera &LR;  (19 ounces, $1.69 at many supermarkets) came in
fourth. All of the panelists commented that this very thick soup
had little in common with traditional minestrone. Some said it more
closely resembled split pea soup. However, four panelists liked the
flavor even if the texture was too starchy. One would buy it, one
might buy it, and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Pomi, Campbell's regular and Walnut Acres,
but they scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Roland
Passot chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in
Larkspur and Menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and
Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
