<HEADLINE>
COOKIES POSE A NEW THREAT TO PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two quarters you handed over for this paper won't cover my
salary. It's the advertisements that really pay the freight at a
newspaper. So I'm sympathetic to Internet companies looking for new
ways to earn ad revenues for their Web sites. Still, one must draw
a line somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite technology news Web sites is marred by a
series of wretched ads for some benighted electronics firm. The ads
feature dismal-looking women displayed in what are supposed to be
come-hither poses.
</P>
<P>
   Weary of wincing at the sight of them, I downloaded free
software (Windows and Unix only) to solve the problem. Internet
Junkbuster (www.junkbuster.com) can filter out many on-line
annoyances. It's not as simple to use as commercial filtering
products like SurfWatch or Cyber Patrol, but the price was
unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   Having installed the Junkbuster, it was easy to block unwanted
ads. By clicking on one of them with the right-side mouse button,
and then clicking on the word ``properties,'' I got the Web address
of the ads. By typing this into Junkbuster, I ensured that the
nasty images would trouble me no more. All I see is a blank space
where the grimy photos used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Other ads on the page are not affected. But after chatting with
Jason Catlett, creator of Internet Junkbuster, I began wondering if
I should block many more ads. It's not the photos that trouble me _
it's the cookies.
</P>
<P>
   You remember cookies _ the little bits of data left on your hard
drive by some of the Web sites you visit. Cookies enable you to log
on to many sites only once. Next visit, the site finds the cookie
on your hard drive and logs you in. Cookies make Web surfing
simpler, but Catlett sees them as a threat to privacy.
</P>
<P>
   I generally scoff at such paranoia. Cookies can only be read by
the company that gave them to you, and they only contain personal
data if you provide it. For instance, Yahoo's cookie identifies me
because I willingly gave the information to Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   But Catlett warned me that it's not that simple any more.
Consider firms like DoubleClick Inc. and 24/7 Media Inc. These are
firms that display many of the ads you see on popular Web sites.
These sites put cookies on your computer whenever they flash an ad
on your screen. These cookies are checked whenever you visit
another site with a DoubleClick or 24/7 ad. The ad company now
knows which sites you've visited and which ads you've seen. That
helps them decide which ad to show you the next time you visit a
site.
</P>
<P>
   This is old news. And in its original form, it posed no threat
to privacy, because the advertiser's cookies identified you as a
number. DoubleClick or 24/7 didn't know your name, address, phone
number, or e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   But soon they will. Ever buy a product and register it over the
Internet? Then there's a good chance your name and address are on
file with 24/7. The firm has an arrangement with Intelliquest
Information Group Inc., the company that handles most on-line
registrations. Intelliquest puts a cookie on your computer when you
register your latest purchase. Then the company shares the cookie
and your personal data with 24/7. Starting early next year,
whenever you visit a Web site with a 24/7 ad, the company will know
you're there. Visit enough 24/7 sites, and the firm can compile a
dossier on your comings and goings. DoubleClick plans to introduce
a similar feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just gives us the ability to profile groups of people,''
says 24/7 chief executive David Moore, ``so we're showing diaper
ads to women and, say, football ads to men.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore says consumers must grant permission for his firm to
create a profile. He said users can contact 24/7 and have their
names removed from the database. Moore said 24/7 will not sell data
to other firms. Besides, he added, ``the folks who have really
strong feelings about privacy are few and far between.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm one of them. Maybe 24/7 will behave itself, but we have only
its word for it. European nations have data privacy laws. But in
America, firms can pretty much do as they like.
</P>
<P>
   Firms like 24/7 and DoubleClick think they can make millions
from consumers' personal data. Well, they'll get no help from me.
I've contacted both companies and opted out of their databases. If
I were really paranoid, I'd use Internet Junkbuster to block all
ads sent from the two companies. But I won't. After all, these guys
have to make a living too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(E-mail Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-09-99 1318EDT &QL;
</P>
