<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM PARTY GAIN WOULD BE GOP GAIN, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All these Republicans who are in a dither because Pat Buchanan
is talking about leaving their party need to get a grip. Instead of
begging Buchanan to stay and stewing about what will happen if he
goes, Republicans should be helping him pack.
</P>
<P>
   Ridding itself of Buchanan and the divisive mentality he
represents can only help the Grand Old Party in its efforts to
recapture the presidency in the 2000 election. Buchanan's
departure, in fact, would be a perfect example of addition by
subtraction.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan is a colorful character. He has some ideas that are
interesting, and even a few that are worthwhile. But he can never
escape his well-earned public image as a champion of intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   It's an image that he earned over the years as a commentator in
the media and as a political operative in the administrations of
Presidents Nixon and Reagan _ and that he cemented forever when he
stood before the 1992 Republican Convention and sounded the call to
arms for a cultural and religious war against all those who dare to
disagree with his views on an array of social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Democrat Ronald Reagan used to explain his switch to
Republicanism by saying, ``I didn't leave the Democratic Party; it
left me.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan could say the same about the Republican Party, and he'd
be correct. The party did leave him _ and the party is better off
for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The on-again/off-again host of CNN's ``Crossfire'' has been at
odds with his party for years. He may as well make the split
official.
</P>
<P>
   He not only damaged President Bush's 1992 re-election campaign
by turning that year's GOP convention into a virtual hatefest, but
a mere four years later Buchanan wounded Bob Dole's candidacy by
winning the New Hampshire primary. The defeat made Dole a sitting
duck for subsequent attacks by Steve Forbes _ attacks that
undoubtedly erased any chance that Dole might have had to upset
Bill Clinton in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   With friends like Pat Buchanan, the Republican Party doesn't
need enemies.
</P>
<P>
   So why don't the Republicans just tell Buchanan, ``See you
later'' or ``Don't let the door hit ya,'' or ``Don't call us, we'll
call you''?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the Grand Old Party lives in fear of the ghost of
Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans _ some of them, anyway _ are absolutely convinced
that Perot's independent candidacy in 1992 cost Bush the election
and put Clinton in the White House. The truth is, Perot siphoned
votes almost equally from Bush and Clinton; for all practical
purposes, he was not a factor in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   But it drives Republicans crazy to think that their president
just plain lost the election to the likes of Slick Willie Clinton;
it evidently eases the pain to imagine that this alien force known
as Perot somehow disrupted the natural order of things.
</P>
<P>
   And now, irony of ironies, the longtime Republican Buchanan is
thinking of bolting to the Reform Party _ a political organization
that had its roots in Perot's independent presidential campaign in
'92. If Buchanan becomes the Reform Party's presidential nominee in
2000, many Perot-haunted Republicans fear, he could seal the
election for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released this week showed Buchanan winning just 6 percent
of the vote in a three-way contest with Republican front-runner
George W. Bush and likely Democratic nominee Al Gore. And I'm
guessing that 6 percent is a considerable overstatement of
Buchanan's potential support.
</P>
<P>
   If the wishful thinkers who have embraced the Reform Party _ and
who fantasize that this half-baked organization can become a
serious player in American politics _ want to crown Pat Buchanan as
their standard-bearer, well, I say they are welcome to him. They
deserve each other.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is indisputable. Any damage that Buchanan might
do to the Republicans in the 2000 election would be inconsequential
when compared to the enormous increase in credibility and
respectability that would accrue to the GOP by eliminating such a
high-profile troublemaker from its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
