<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
Sept. 16. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD: Lead poisoning of children always has been a problem in
Kansas City, but it's only been in the past couple of years that
health authorities have taken a really aggressive approach to
prevention. Armed with federal grant money, new equipment and
tougher laws, hundreds more children now are being tested, and
dozens of homes are being cleaned of lead. Health authorities have
had to work at changing attitudes of doctors, who didn't think lead
was still a problem. And they have had to seek out and train
contractors to do the remediation work. In some Kansas City zip
codes, as many as 26 percent of kids tested have high blood lead
levels, which can reduce IQ and cause learning disabilities, high
blood pressure and kidney damage. Graphics. Photos. Alan Bavley.
44.
</P>
<P>
   ABORT: The Missouri General Assembly convenes at noon today to
consider bills vetoed by Gov. Mel Carnahan. Thousands of protesters
on both sides of the abortion issue are expected for rallies before
the session begins. Will Sentell and Kit Wagar. 30.
</P>
<P>
   FAR: Four days after Michael L. Farris cut off his electronic
monitor Independence police stopped him on a routine check. They
let Farris go because they did not know that he had cut his
monitor. In fact, it took state probation officials nearly a month
to notify court officials about Farris' disappearance. In the
meantime, Farris allegedly strangled an elderly Kansas City woman
to death. We'll ask the family as well as state and local officials
to respond to this discovery. Trisha Howard and Joe Lambe. 15-20.
</P>
<P>
   BACH: You've seen the billboards around town. And admit it,
ladies, you're just a little intrigued: ``Wealthy, Sophisticated
Gentleman Searching for Ms. Right. Call 967-1100.'' It's one of
several such billboards in the Kansas City metro area, but good
luck trying to contact the guy directly. But is he wealthy? Is he
sophisticated? Does this approach really work? We set an Eligible
Bachelor to track one down. Matt Stearns. 19. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: An Indian couple and their 8-year-old daughter are
bicycling around the world to promote nonviolence, the sharing of
resources and love and peace. We find out why they're doing this.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   SHER: The Ray County sheriff accused of harassing men and women
in his department filed a lawsuit and settled with a local hospital
a few years ago, claiming heart surgery complications caused him to
suffer brain damage. We'll see how Ray County commissioners and
residents feel about having a sheriff with mental problems. Benita
Williams. 20. Photo
</P>
<P>
   HOG: Sierra Club releases a report Wednesday blasting Missouri
officials for giving so many tax breaks and other economic
incentives to corporate pig farms and then forcing them to clean up
environmental damage. State officials involved say the economic
benefits outweigh the problems. Michael Mansur. 16.
</P>
<P>
   HAIR. Scofflaws at the Renaissance Festival have been brought to
justice; the Kansas Board of Cosmetology shut down the festival's
hair weavers last weekend because they didn't have the proper
licenses. John L. Petterson. 15
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   GLEN _ A rural Missouri banker who had a longrunning battle with
the FDIC has sued a UMB affiliate in Springfield that started it
all. But the real battle, once again, is between the banker and the
FDIC. By Charles R.T. Crumpley
</P>
<P>
   NGISC _ More from the American Gaming Association study,
including comments on a new gaming impact study under way. By Rick
Alm
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   CHIEFS. Tony Gonzalez looks as if he could play Sunday against
the Broncos. That's the good news from Arrowhead. The bad news is
Dave Szott isn't looking too healthy. Adam Teicher. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   GYM. Coverage of men's prelims at World Team Trials. Howard
Richman. Photos. STAFF ART
</P>
<P>
   KSFT. Quincy Morgan caught a 63-yard touchdown pass from
Jonathan Beasley aginst Temple, picking right up for the absence of
big-play receiver Darnell McDonald now in the NFL. Kent Pulliam.
15-17.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Anaheim at Kansas City, 7:05 p.m. Dick Kaegel. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   CARVER. News folo on boxer Randie Carver. David Boyce. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   MUFT. Julian Jones will get, on average, about two hours of
sleep per night this week. That's normal, for Jones, who has been a
chronic insomiac for years. But although just a junior, he is the
guy who has to call the formations for the secondary and in Western
Michigan's passing attack faces the ultimate test of his MU career.
18-22. Mike DeArmond. Photos.
</P>
