<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SOUTH-FOOTE16-COX     09-15 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-FOOTE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHELBY FOOTE EXPLAINS THE SOUTH TO CAPITOL HILL
 &HT;    Duplication alert: Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle
categories
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over a breakfast of bagels and bran muffins, with
nary a grit nor biscuit in sight, Shelby Foote was educating a
Capitol Hill audience about the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having lost a war, we've known a tragedy that other Americans
have not experienced, certainly not until Vietnam,'' explained
Foote in the Mississippi drawl that narrated Ken Burns' PBS
documentary on the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have gained from it (is) a true sense of tragedy which
I think accounts, in part, for the dominance of Southern writers in
the history of American literature, particularly in this century,
since Mark Twain.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote, perhaps the world's best-known Southern historian, was
the first in a series of speakers who will address congressional
audiences on regionalism in the American culture at the behest of
William Ferris, chairman of the National Endowment for the
Humanities (NEH). Ferris is seeking federal funding for the
creation of ten regional humanities centers to ``nurture the
roots'' of Southerners, New Englanders, Westerners and other
American geographic groups who share a sense of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes Bill, we'll try to get you a little more money,'' said
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, a Republican who hails from
Mississippi, as do Ferris and Foote.
</P>
<P>
   In the basement of the U.S. Capitol and later at NEH
headquarters on Pennsylvania Avenue, Foote spoke of regional shame
and redemption, of race and roots and family, of how he ``will be
eternally grateful to God Almighty for letting me be born and
raised in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of the three-volume classic ``The Civil War: A
Narrative'' and five novels, including ``Shiloh,'' Foote grew up in
Greenville, Miss. In this Delta town, he said, there were ``about
as many people writing books as reading them.'' His closest friend
for over 60 years was the late novelist Walker Percy. Foote now
lives in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memphis has always been the capital of the Mississippi Delta
even though it is in Tennessee,'' said Foote.
</P>
<P>
   In the Delta, ``you can see forever, until the land rolls out of
sight. It is as flat as a pool table with topsoil 40 feet deep,''
he recounted. ``It is a place where farming is the main thing and
it is thought to be good to hold on to land.''
</P>
<P>
   In his boyhood, he said, ``Old men were not willing to turn
management of the plantation over to their sons. 'Those crazy fools
would would lose it.' As a result, you had 70-year-old men sending
45-year-old men out for cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what they did to their sons. What they did to their
sons-in-law you just won't believe,'' he said. ``But no Delta girl
ever left home. When she got married, she brought her husband back
with her. She couldn't live away from the Delta, couldn't
breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Storytelling and love of the language are Southern traits, of
course, but Foote said it is history rather than drawls or overalls
or pick-up trucks that defines the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``We carry a burden,'' he said. ``We wouldn't be what we are if
we hadn't been what we were.''
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of slavery may always haunt the region, he reckoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South has sins on its soul that it will never be able to
get clear of, but so has the nation,'' said Foote. He said
emancipation was handled sinfully bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told 4 million people 'You're free. Hit the road','' he
said, providing no preparation or assistance for coping with a new
life.
</P>
<P>
   But he said a stronger nation was forged from the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War is an example of good coming out of evil,
strength coming out of suffering. The American Civil War is when
this country became this country. The Revolution made us an
independent nation. The Civil War decided what kind of country we
were going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And losing that war did a lot to create the cultural South.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to know why the South is so interested in the
Civil War,'' he said. ``I've been in about 50 fist fights in my
life. And the ones I have the most vivid memories of are the ones I
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ``instantaneous communications'' of television, radio
and the Internet, there has been a ``homogenization'' of the
American culture that has lessened regional differences, Foote
said. But the South retains some distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something of the code of the Southern gentlemen has survived
and differentiates us,'' he said. Southern children still say ``Yes
sir'' and ``No ma'am'' to grown-ups. Cars still pull to the side of
the road to let a funeral procession pass. Manners matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southerners can be insulted. With some Easterners, it's
impossible,'' said Foote, describing Yankee conversations that
would have concluded with an invitation to step outside if
Southerners were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good society where people can go around cursing
each other with impunity,'' he explained. ``There ought to be some
risk involved.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, he agrees that the South is probably more violent than
other regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds a certain verve to life, but I'm not sure it's worth
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of people from other regions has diluted Southerness,
he said. ``Atlanta is about as Northern as it is Southern. Florida
is Northern.''
</P>
<P>
   But the South is famous for hospitality -- at least to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a stranger, you're welcomed in a sort of distant
way'' while the homefolks size you up, he said. ``If they like you,
intimacies develop. If they don't like you, the Southern deep
freeze sets in.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
