<HEADER>
A2912 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HURRICANE-PREDICTIONS     09-15 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-PREDICTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FORECASTERS HAD WARNED OF A BUSY HURRICANE SEASON THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A grim forecast of hurricane disaster, made by a controversial
meteorologist and a federal emergency official earlier this year,
appears to be coming true as Hurricane Floyd rolls along the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, William Gray of Colorado State University has
racked up an impressive reputation as a hurricane forecaster. And
his forecast for 1999 _ that it would be a worse-than-normal
hurricane year _ certainly resembles the season now unfolding as
Hurricane Floyd bears down on the southeastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   Conceivably, ``Floyd could be `The Big One' in the hurricane
community,'' said a leading expert on the societal impact of
hurricanes, Roger A. Pielke Jr. of the National Center for
Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo., late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   East Coasters can't say they weren't warned. On June 13, James
Lee Witt, director of the Federal Emergency Management Agency,
while addressing the Annual Conference of Mayors in New Orleans,
urged them to prepare for an especially bad hurricane year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your obligation to your communities who bear the brunt
of disaster, to a nation who bears the cost of helping you rebuild
and, just as much, to yourselves, leaders whose ambitions for your
administration could be overtaken by a single storm,'' Lee warned
in his speech. He based his concerns on forecasters' expectations
of an especially severe hurricane year.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1998, Gray forecast four major Atlantic hurricanes for
the autumn of 1999. He based the forecast on global weather trends
that have, in the past, been correlated with increased hurricane
activity, among them the continued La Nina conditions in the
Pacific, weakened high-altitude winds and the position of the jet
stream.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane forecasters including Gray, now a media celebrity who
couldn't be reached Tuesday, have gained confidence in recent years
in their ability to forecast seasonal hurricane incidence.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason is the discovery of an apparent close link
between El Nino and La Nina years in the Pacific and hurricanes in
the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are still trying to understand the precise links
between weather in the two oceans. They suspect that Atlantic
hurricanes tend to be fewer in El Nino years _ years when Pacific
waters are unusually warm _ partly because those years also bring
strong, high-altitude easterly winds. Those winds blow apart
tropical storms before they expand into hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Partly for this reason, Atlantic hurricanes are fewer in number
_ according to theory, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, those same high-altitude winds are weaker during La
Nina years, when Pacific waters are cooler. Hence, in theory, more
Atlantic hurricanes grow to full size during a La Nina year, as
Floyd has done this year.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced that Gray has a crystal ball for
hurricane forecasting. One is Kevin Trenberth, a noted
climatologist at the Boulder research center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of what he's (Gray) done is good, and some of it is
rather questionable,'' Trenberth said. ``He's a seat-of-the-pants
meteorologist, (but) he's not a good (weather) statistician. . .
.The general consensus in the (scientific) community (is) that some
of the things Bill Gray (does) are in the realm of art rather than
science.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Gray's forecasts are valid or just lucky guesses,
improved hurricane forecasting is essential partly because a
super-hurricane could cause cataclysmic damage.
</P>
<P>
   In a research paper published last year, Pielke, of the National
Center for Atmospheric Research, and colleagues ``made the comment
that it's just a matter of time before the nation sees a $50
billion (damage-causing) hurricane,'' he recalled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a $50 billion hurricane, you need two things: a
tremendously powerful storm, and . . . the storm to make landfall
in a populated area. With Floyd out there, we have _ potentially _
those ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane that wrought $50 billion in damage, or worse, could
seriously damage the U.S. insurance industry. It might also have
ripple effects on the rest of the U.S. or world economy.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Hurricane Hugo in 1989, ``no hurricane had resulted in
claims in excess of $1 billion,'' Loretta Worters of the Insurance
Information Institute in New York said Tuesday. Then along came
Hugo, which caused $4.2 billion in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Worters said, ``Before Hurricane Andrew struck south
Florida in August 1992, many experts thought the worst possible
windstorm would cause no more than about $8 billion (damage).'' Yet
Andrew was close to about $16 billion. The resulting damage claims
forced numerous insurance firms into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   And if a hurricane hit a major metropolitan area such as Miami,
damage claims could exceed $50 billion, Worters added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
