<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2913 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i BC-CHINA-PANDAS-$ADV19-C     09-15 2386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PANDAS-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INNOCENT PANDAS CAVORT WHILE POLITICOS DEBATE THEIR FATE
 &HT;    1600&AMP;ADDS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With PANDAS-HERITAGE-$ADV19.
 &HT;    For Use Sun, Sept. 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENGDU, China _ Will it be a love legend of the new millennium,
or a case of affections thwarted by geopolitical manipulation,
menacing illness or even the curse of incest?
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like themes in a weepy Chinese opera.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tune in to the tube or hike to the local bookstore to
find the outcome of this melodramatic tale.
</P>
<P>
   Keep your eyes on Zoo Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Those outrageously cuddly fur balls, the panda cubs Lun Lun and
Yang Yang, are innocently nuzzling each other and ambling around
their mini-forest in this southwest China research base, blissfully
ignorant that politicians and scientists have hung their future in
suspended animation.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the panda pair that Zoo Atlanta holds clouded hope
of receiving on Oct. 7 has become a saga entwining power politics
with conflicting codes of conservation and the fragility of the
panda itself.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the pandas will go, whether they will stay, whether they
can mate, all are open-ended questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The over-arching problem is nothing more or less than the
fencing our two governments have been going through regarding
Kosovo, regarding Tibet, regarding Taiwan, regarding missiles in
North Korea,'' zoo director Terry Maple acknowledged in a telephone
interview from Atlanta. ``These are serious political issues.''
</P>
<P>
   They are serious enough that the Chinese government has not yet
given the actual go-ahead for the two pandas to be loaned to Zoo
Atlanta under the 10-year agreement of ``intentions'' signed by
officials of the zoo and of the China Association of Zoological
Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Final approval could come any day. Or never.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it will be very quickly processed. Maybe it will go
very, very slowly,'' said Xie Zhong, secretary general of the China
association in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Another Chinese government spokesman, who refused to give his
name, warned not to expect word until after the Oct. 1 celebration
of China's 50th anniversary of the revolution, an event consuming
the attentions of officials countrywide.
</P>
<P>
   China's Byzantine bureaucracy requires endorsements of panda
loans by the Ministries of Construction, Forestry and Foreign
Affairs, which then must jointly petition the State Council, the
counterpart of a president's cabinet in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Premier Zhu Rongji himself must sign off on the deal is
an issue of semantics, because the ultimate approval is a decision
of international political consequence made at the highest levels
of China's governing elite.
</P>
<P>
   And that merely underscores the importance of the delightful
rolly-polly creatures whose sad-looking eyes and deceptively clumsy
gait have endeared them to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the panda is considered a national treasure. Abroad, this
endangered species is a symbol of the harm humankind has done to
its environment and must repair before nature's clock ticks
premature closure on preservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   A more crass filter produces a somewhat different view: to the
Chinese, the panda is better than gold as a piece of barter, while
foreigners see dollar signs in those poignant black eyes that will
pull in ticket receipts to support conservation, research or other
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wants a piece of the panda, and the Chinese government
manipulates that desire to the hilt.
</P>
<P>
   That said, things nonetheless are looking up for Atlanta.
Eventually, at least.
</P>
<P>
   Maple of the Atlanta zoo is convinced final approval is only a
matter of time, although he doesn't guarantee the United Parcel
Service plane ready to ferry the two-year-old bundles of spunk will
take off for America as scheduled in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a little optimism rising because of the trade talks,''
he said, referring to the negotiations on China's painfully long
endeavor to enter the World Trade Organization. After a cordial
meeting last weekend at a New Zealand conference, China's President
Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Bill Clinton ordered their
negotiators to press ahead, a development viewed as a positive turn
in badly deteriorated relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pandas could be a very positive thing for relations
between the countries. That's the way I hope it will turn out,''
Maple said.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the pandas do board UPS's Boeing 767 painted _ how
else? _ with the visage of a panda, Zoo Atlanta will continue its
cooperative project with the Chengdu Research Base of Giant Panda
Breeding, the place Lun Lun and Yang Yang were born and now romp.
The cooperation will include a generous infusion of dollars from
Atlanta to the Chengdu base _ $1
</P>
<P>
   million a year for the 10 years of the panda loan.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantans will do behavioral research here and in Atlanta,
recording the interactions of pandas on an almost daily basis from
the day of their birth. They began watching Lun Lun and Yang Yang,
among others, two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Things still may not proceed precisely as Zoo Atlanta once
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Yang Yang has been feeling poorly. And that is not
at all unusual for pandas. They look big and strong, but actually
suffer physical problems ranging from a minuscule birth weight of
five or six ounces _ they essentially are born before fully
physically developed _ to a perpetually delicate digestive system.
</P>
<P>
   The latter results from the fact that early in their three
million-year history pandas used to be carnivores. They pioneered
modern health trends by adopting a vegetarian diet, but their
bodies never made the switchover to properly process their almost
exclusively bamboo meals.
</P>
<P>
   In the wild, they may eat an average of 40 kilograms (88 pounds)
of bamboo shoots a day, but most of it passes right through their
bodies in an average of 150 droppings rather than being digested.
</P>
<P>
   With so much focus on the survival of newborns, people tend to
forget that rough-and-tumble pre-adolescents like Yang Yang also
are vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the sub-adult the survival rate is very low,'' said Zhang
Hemin, director of another Chinese panda breeding center in the
forested mountains northeast of here. He cautioned that they need
close attention, but was confident they can be reared to vigorous
adulthood. Interviewed at his center in the Wolong Nature Reserve,
Zhang proudly said his place has 100
</P>
<P>
   percent survival of pandas that manage to reach six months of
age.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Yang's illness was indeed a digestive problem that kept him
sidelined for more than two weeks in August and so far, in
September. He spent most of the time sprawled like a sack of
potatoes in his barred cage in the gray concrete sub-adult house
here at the Chengdu research base, suffering from diarrhea and lack
of appetite.
</P>
<P>
   American Sarah Bexell, a zoologist and education specialist from
the Atlanta Zoo who has been working here on the research project,
lamented one day during Yang Yang's illness that the staff could
hardly tempt him even with fresh bamboo shoots they collected from
the mist-shrouded grounds of this leafy, wet research center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chewed it up and then spit it out. He didn't swallow more
than three mouthfuls,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't worried about it (potential illness) until Yang Yang
got so sick. They are vulnerable animals. When you watch them you
can't believe it because they are so big and rolly-polly and
playful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   A Zoo Atlanta nutritionist and veterinarian have been consulting
long-distance on the case, and antibiotic shots got him well enough
for daily yard work-outs early last week.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Yang's female companion Lun Lun was evidently bummed out
about his absence from the play yard, despite the fact that a pair
of twins around the same age kept her company. Zoo Atlanta also is
monitoring the twin pandas as part of the behavioral study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lun Lun has been pining for him,'' Bexell said. ``The first
few days after Yang Yang was separated from the group, Lun Lun
spent a lot of time wanting to get back to him. It's what we call
'door directed behavior.'''
</P>
<P>
   She referred to the tendency of all three animals, Lun Lun and
the twins, to frequently sidle up toward the building where Yang
Yang was at rest, rather than wander around the wooded yard where
they climb the jungle gym, slosh around water pools or clamber down
a four-foot incline to the empty concrete moat where they
invariably fall asleep.
</P>
<P>
   On the one day Yang Yang did come out to play, Lun Lun ignored
him for 15 or 20 minutes, until a keeper running around the
enclosure with her guided Lun Lun over to her playmate who was
belly-up on the jungle gym.
</P>
<P>
   Lun Lun boosted herself up the logs, and the two proceeded to
nuzzle and spar and, well, apparently communicate. That is, until
they got a bit too rambunctious and Lun Lun tumbled to the ground.
She ultimately headed for the moat, and Yang Yang finally followed
her there for a companionable snooze.
</P>
<P>
   Such sociable interaction transfixes humans, but diminishes as
pandas reach adulthood, when they aggressively bark and bleat at
each other and often must be separated. By the time they are
sexually mature at the age of five or six, they may tolerate each
other only at Lun Lun's once-yearly mating time.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta researchers will have some crucial decisions to make
before the pair reaches panda adolescence _ with the help of a
panda paternity test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two pandas are both sub-adults, both two years old,'' said
Yu Jianqiu (pronounced, ``You Jee-en chyou''), deputy director of
the Chengdu research base. ``Maybe we can breed them there. We
chose these two pandas because they can breed, because their
families are separate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Also maybe we can get money from Atlanta to help us get more
equipment here for research of diseases and for reproductive and
genetic research.''
</P>
<P>
   The money part is a pretty sure thing. The breeding is not.
</P>
<P>
   Yu does not admit the possibility, but Atlanta zoo personnel
suspect that Lun Lun and Yang Yang may be too closely related to
mate without causing the genetic consequences of in-breeding. In
fact, they may share the same father.
</P>
<P>
   When Yu hauled out China's ``Stud Book'' that chronicles which
pandas have sired which, where and when, he looked surprised to
find that Yang Yang was not listed. The book stopped at the
beginning of September, 1997, and Yang Yang was born September 9 of
that year.
</P>
<P>
   With the troubling question-mark over Yang Yang's parentage, Zoo
Atlanta has trained staff and docents not to tell visitors that
mating the pair is a sure thing, according to Bexell, who
co-authored the education program.
</P>
<P>
   Director Maple acknowledged DNA testing eventually will
determine the relatedness of Yang Yang and Lun Lun. Although
researchers chose these two pandas because they are compatible and
it seemed mating ``was an option,'' he said the discovery of the
potential barrier will not block Atlanta's research program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one sense it is important in that we want these two to
become breeders. Whatever we do in managing them, in watching them
and other animals we're observing in Chengdu, we want to understand
better the process by which pandas become socialized and become
appropriate breeders and appropriate parents,'' he said. ``But we
didn't acquire them just to breed them. We acquired them to study
them.''
</P>
<P>
   If this pair is returned to China to breed with more genetically
appropriate pandas, Maple said he assumes Atlanta would receive a
replacement pair to breed and to study.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the panda program in essence is in perpetuity,'' he
said. ``We want to be in China as long as we're doing good there.
And we want to continue to observe and study pandas.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Getting this far has been a 13-year crusade for Maple, one he
said began when former President Jimmy Carter told China's late
leader Deng Xiaoping in 1986 that Atlanta would love to exhibit a
panda or two.
</P>
<P>
   The quest was interrupted by a ferocious international
controversy begun a few years later when Western conservation
groups balked at China's rent-a-panda policy of grabbing up
animals, sometimes from the wild, to loan to Western zoos happy to
pay six-figure prices for three-month to six-month visits that
would draw millions of visitors and multi-millions of
</P>
<P>
   dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic then was hot and heavy despite the March 15, 1984,
declaration of the panda as an endangered species. A mere 1,000
pandas are estimated living in the wild, and about another 100 are
in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it had only been in 1936 that the panda won western
hearts with its first public appearance in America. The panda
supply line was severed once the revolutionary government took over
China in 1949 and quickly cracked down on panda hunting and export.
It used the animal only as a goodwill ambassador to friendly
governments.
</P>
<P>
   So when China opened up again to the world and made its first
short-term loan for a fee in 1984, western zoos clamored for more
pandas. And they got them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 the World Wildlife Fund-U.S. filed suit to stop the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service from granting import permits until it
adopted regulations designed to protect the vulnerable panda.
Conservationists wanted to discourage the taking of pandas from the
wild by allowing only the import of captive-bred animals, and to
force American zoos to do more than simply
</P>
<P>
   put the creatures on display for big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Only after a decade were the regulations finished, and Atlanta
became the first zoo to get an import permit by complying with new
federal demands requiring top-of-the-line physical conditions,
scientific research and contributions to environmental protection
in China.
</P>
<P>
   With luck and continued perseverance, Lun Lun and Yang Yang will
get to Atlanta. And they may even mate and produce little giant
pandas.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be surprised if, by then, they aren't speaking to each
other any more.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
