<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2914 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i BC-PANDAS-HERITAGE-$ADV1     09-15 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANDAS-HERITAGE-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FINDING PANDA PAPA NO EASY TASK
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With CHINA-PANDAS-$ADV19.
 &HT;    For Use Sun, Sept. 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENGDU, China _ If there's anything trickier than making panda
babies, it's tracking panda papas.
</P>
<P>
   Is Yang Yang's dad Lan Lan or Lin Lan?
</P>
<P>
   Or some other male panda whose seed may have been frozen in a
sperm bank for several years?
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, how come Yang Yang's keepers insist on calling
him Jiu Jiu?
</P>
<P>
   The researchers of Zoo Atlanta would love to know his pedigree.
But because of a Chinese panda breeding phenomenon inelegantly
referred to as a ``cocktail,'' Yang Yang and Lun Lun could be
half-sibs _ or just good friends.
</P>
<P>
   To start with, Yang Yang, the male of the pair, is not listed in
the ``Stud Book'' that traces giant panda lineage. The book stops
about a week or so before his birth on Sept. 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Yang was born here at the Chengdu Research Base for Giant
Panda Breeding, so there is no doubt about his mother. She is Ya
Ya. And her lineage is illustrious, including her renowned
grandmother Mei Mei, who produced so many offspring that the
Chinese designated her the ``hero mother'' and gave her a special
posthumous exhibit in the museum here.
</P>
<P>
   The complication is that Ya Ya not only mated naturally that
spring before Yang Yang arrived _ at the tiny size of 173 grams, or
6 ounces _ but that she also was artificially inseminated with what
Western zoologists call a ``semen cocktail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We did artificial insemination with several different males,''
acknowledged Yu Jianqiu, (pronounced, ``You Jee-en chyou''), deputy
director of the research base.
</P>
<P>
   Yu said he didn't think it possible that among the sperm donors
was Lin Lan, whose sperm has been identified as producing Lun Lun,
the female of the young panda pair Atlanta wants to borrow for the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't say why it's not possible, but just not.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Snyder, head of Zoo Atlanta's panda research, said in an
e-mail message that she managed to track down Ya Ya's natural mate,
a male called Lan Lan, and she thinks she has traced one donor for
the artificial insemination. But that doesn't solve the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese practice multiple breeding attempts in an effort to
produce multiple offspring or at least one solid pairing of egg and
sperm. And they have improved the pandas' poor breeding record.
</P>
<P>
   But with only about 100 pandas in captivity, around half of them
males and many too young to breed yet, the pool of available sperm
isn't huge. That is why Western wildlife experts prevailed upon the
Chinese to create the ``Stud Book'' that they hope will prevent
breeding of closely related pandas.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously there are glitches even with the book, though DNA
testing will identify genetic heritage before any mating in Atlanta
could take place.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion is the profusion of names some pandas
accumulate. Officially they get numbers, but also usually are named
in the zoos or research centers where they are born.
</P>
<P>
   The may get additional names, if a well-to-do Chinese or
foreigner decides to ``adopt'' one and pay $5,000 or so for a least
a year's upkeep. For that, the donor gets a brass plaque and the
privilege of naming the animal.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Yang, for example, was first named Jiu Jiu (pronounced,
``Jyo Jyo'') by his keepers. Holland's Province of Friesland,
Chamber of Commerce of Friesland and Van Hall Institute ``adopted''
him at the age of one and named him Yang Yang.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, the Chinese keepers still call him Jiu Jiu.
</P>
<P>
   They also call Lun Lun by her original name, Hua Hua. She was
adopted by a Taiwanese rock star Su Huilun, who modestly applied
the last part of her own monicker to the panda.
</P>
<P>
   The critical factor in tracking a panda's ancestry is knowing
that original name, or even better, the animal's number.
</P>
<P>
   Lun Lun, for example is in the ``Stud Book,'' but you won't find
Lun Lun listed.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Hua Hua. Or if you're really in the know, find 452.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
