<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-2-TAKES-     09-15 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-2-TAKES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD A BATTLER SINCE BOYHOOD IN PUERTO RICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUPEY ALTO, Puerto Rico _ The lush vegetation that threatens to
overwhelm the shanty houses it is growing between fools you at
first, the way a fighter can when he feints one way before
delivering a crushing blow from another angle.
</P>
<P>
   You take a look around at the small homes, many of them
dilapidated, and it is clear that poverty lives here between the
plant life. But there is no sign at first of the kind of grinding
despair or fermenting danger that is the breeding ground of great
boxers.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty is as necessary a component in the creation of a
champion prizefighter as a sharp jab, quick reflexes, or a brave
heart. There have been exceptions, such as Gene Tunney, but they
are rare. The rule says you don't find fighters in Beverly Hills
unless they're committing a burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing is the harshest of sports, and so it seems to demand a
hard upbringing to weather it. Men fight because they have no other
choice. They fight because that is what they have known from the
time they were small boys trying to make their way through hard
places. In comparison to the streets they walk in their daily
lives, the boxing ring seems a safe haven, so they go there intent
on destroying another man's will almost without realizing the
danger of the undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   But in this neighborhood not far outside San Juan, where the
humidity and unemployment are high, there are few outward signs of
such a life. There is no high-rise feel of a big-city housing
project. No sense that danger is lurking not far beneath the
surface calm.
</P>
<P>
   Then the police officer standing in front of Felix Trinidad's
old school steps out of a guard shack wearing a bulletproof vest
and removes all doubt about where the International Boxing
Federation welterweight champion of the world learned to fight.
</P>
<P>
   He learned here, in the streets of Cupey Alto, where there are
drugs and guns and violence, just as there are in East Los Angeles,
the neighborhood that spawned the great challenge of Trinidad's
life, Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad will face that challenge Saturday night when he fights
the World Boxing Council champion in Las Vegas to unify the
welterweight title. That night, perhaps the two best fighters in
the world will meet, a fire raging inside each like flames licking
up dry timber. It is a fire born in East Los Angeles and here in
Cupey Alto, where the school guard wears a bulletproof vest to
greet a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tito came here, his father could already see his son had
something, like a raw diamond,'' recalls Carmen Carratini, who
taught young Felix ``Tito'' Trinidad social studies and history in
the seventh grade. ``I tell all my students they can be great, like
a doctor or a lawyer, but Tito began to know he'd be great early.
There was a smell. A look. A feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time Tito won the title, I went to the airport to
greet him. It was so emotional. I love Tito! In this town, Cupey,
we are close. I have lost 22 of my students (to street violence or
drugs). This is a place that has problems, like so many places. I
lost my own child a month ago to a motorcycle accident. It is sad,
but I think God is so good to me to give me a student like Tito.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all so glad a son of Puerto Rico is making the best of
it. That night with Oscar, it will be like a son making history.
You can teach history, but Tito will be in sports history. Never
before has a newspaper come here looking for the story of one of my
students. That is a gift from God.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many folks in Cupey Alto make history, nor do reporters
often come to the Juan Antonio Corretjer School for their stories.
Life here is too hard for that. There is no time for dreaming when
you're slipping on a bulletproof vest to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   Or when you're passing by one on your way to school.
</P>
<P>
   But Felix ``Tito'' Trinidad was always different. He dreamed and
his father dreamed with him, and now all of Cupey Alto is dreaming.
Dreaming of how they will dance in the streets when he comes home
with all the title belts, dance all the way from the airport in San
Juan to Tito's mother's house up on the hill, where the boy was
born to a man who dreamed of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Felix Trinidad, the father of the champion, was once a
featherweight fighter himself. He made no name in the world of
boxing, but he learned to use his fists early, and although he
would feed his family by building swimming pools, that was not his
trade. The trade he would pass on to his son was working with his
hands in another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything his father did, the son wanted to do the same
thing,'' Carratini recalls. ``He wanted to build swimming pools and
make them as good as his father's.''
</P>
<P>
   Tito Trinidad may have been content had he done that, but his
father had other plans for his son's hands. Those hands were to
strike out at the world, to take its measure. Those hands were made
to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very early in his amateur career, you could see he was
different,'' Don Felix says, pride and acceptance of fate in his
voice. ``Tito had a lot of stamina. A lot of courage. And very good
skills, even as a boy. He started very young.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad started the way so many boxers do, before he knew any
better. He started before some other sport could take him away from
boxing because he wanted to be with his father, and his father
wanted to be in a gym. So the boy followed the man to the hardest
place there is in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson once said of prizefighting, ``You play sports, but
you don't play boxing. Who goes to the playground to fight?'' The
fact is, only fighters do, and only a few are blessed to fight like
Tito Trinidad. Often, like him, they fight that way from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first fight was when he was 10, so he was almost always
the youngest,'' his father explains. ``He was just like you see him
now. Somebody knocked him down, he got up and knocked them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a champion at 80 pounds, 95 pounds, 100 pounds, 119
pounds, 126 pounds, 132 pounds. He was always the champion. He was
11 when he won his first championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The father could dream big dreams because of that, and the son
has lived them, winning 35 straight fights and the IBF welterweight
title as a professional. As he grew tall and thin in the sun, the
boy kept fighting without complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the streets or at school, like so many others. Only where
it counted. Only in tiny gyms, inside roped-off squares where his
father was always at his side to encourage him.
</P>
<P>
   But the father was smart. He pushed, but not too hard. He
cajoled, but not too often. Along the way he convinced him of his
greatness without demanding he show it too often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard him once say he didn't want to fight,'' the
father insists. ``He was never under any pressure. You have to
remember, Tito only had 57 amateur fights (51-6). No 200-300 fights
like some kids. I let him go along. I didn't push him. I was very
conscious that if you push him to the extreme, it could go, as you
say, and he could lose interest.''
</P>
<P>
   But the boy never lost interest in his father's dream. Instead,
he made it his own. Up on the hill, at the end of a winding road
where the family farm had been, he grew up believing he would make
history, just as his father said.
</P>
<P>
   Never once did he waver. Never once did he rebel. Instead he
fell in love with long runs and putting his hands in other boy's
faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father fought (Salvador) Sanchez once in Texas,'' says
Juan Gomez, Trinidad's cousin and the caretaker of the hill where
now ``12 or 14'' of Trinidad's family members live, scattered in
houses he has paid for. ``That's a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   As he speaks, Gomez stands in front of a sturdy stucco house
Tito remodeled for him that sits yards away from a second house
under construction. Down the hill sits another, and 10 yards away
is another.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
