<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2933 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MEDIA-CABAL-BOS &LR;      09-15 1739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-CABAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S AN ERA OF MASSIVE MASS MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When Viacom and CBS announced a $37.7 billion merger last
week, some analysts saw it as a career-capping triumph for master
deal maker Sumner Redstone, the 76-year-old Boston-born cinema
entrepreneur turned media magnate.
</P>
<P>
   But others saw the deal as an alarming escalation of a trend in
which Redstone is joining a very small clique of corporate titans _
including News Corp.'s Rupert Murdoch, Disney-ABC's Michael Eisner,
and Gerald Levin of Time Warner _ who control a huge fraction of
everything Americans hear, see and read in the mass media.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by recent Federal Communications Commission moves relaxing
cross-ownership restrictions, US media companies are rapidly
concentrating ownership over television networks, movie studios, TV
and radio stations and cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   The Viacom-CBS deal, announced Tuesday, creates a global
conglomerate with nearly $20 billion in annual revenues from CBS,
Paramount Pictures, the Simon &AMP; Schuster publishing house, the
Infinity Broadcasting radio network, cable channels including MTV
and Nickelodeon, and the country's biggest billboard business _ not
to mention five amusement parks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ``is simply the latest example of a tendency toward
monopoly control of the entire culture by a very small group of
very large corporations,'' said Mark Crispin Miller, a New York
University media professor and head of the Project on Media
Ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an undemocratic development. The whole media system is
enthralled to moneyed interests in a way that is unprecedented,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   While it is difficult to calculate an exact number, industry
analysts agree that the overwhelming majority of everything
Americans see on television over the course of a week is now
developed by six or seven huge companies, some of which are likely
to continue merging.
</P>
<P>
   Just four companies alone _ Time Warner, Walt Disney Co., News
Corp. and Viacom-CBS if combined _ control the following
entertainment and news outlets:
</P>
<P>
   ABC, CBS, Fox News, ESPN, Turner Broadcasting, Sky Broadcasting,
Star TV of Asia, Warner Bros., the WB television network, the UPN
network, Paramount Pictures, Walt Disney Studios, 20th Century Fox,
Time-Life magazines, The New York Post, The Times of London; book
publishers HarperCollins, Simon &AMP; Schuster and Hyperion; and the
Warner music labels.
</P>
<P>
   The question that is challenging to answer is whether this is
necessarily a bad or alarming thing.
</P>
<P>
   From a business standpoint, the CBS-Viacom combination was
widely hailed as a brilliant move, bringing together two strong,
rich companies that fill each other's weak spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our union will be king,'' declared Redstone, who continues to
maintain a Newton residence. ``We will be global leaders in every
facet of the media and entertainment industry, financially strong
from day one, with an enviable stable of global brands'' and huge
opportunities to cross-promote each division's offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some media magnates who are known to have a political
agenda, Redstone is seen chiefly as an investor and promoter who
believes that ``content is king'' but does not have a strong
preference for what the content should be.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS-Viacom deal could be seen as a symptom of a media
nuclear-arms race spawned by changing viewer habits.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thistle, a former Boston television news director who now
runs the broadcast journalism program at Boston University, noted
that networks have been under intense pressure to join bigger
companies and get into cable ventures because their viewership has
steadily eroded.
</P>
<P>
   By way of example, Thistle noted that last Tuesday night at 9:30
p.m., more than 65 percent of Greater Boston households watching TV
were tuned in to something other than a station affiliated with the
big three national networks, Fox, UPN or WB. The Nielsen ratings
numbers do not account for some untold additional number of people
who five years ago might have been watching TV but were up surfing
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional prime-time audience is nowhere to be found,''
said Thistle.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, combinations like CBS-Viacom, Disney-ABC and
Time-Warner-Turner could be seen not so much as efforts to dominate
the flow of electronic information, but as defensive moves to keep
a critical share of a steadily more atomized television and
entertainment audience.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage of Viacom and CBS, bringing together a national
network with a company that has a big studio presence, has
parallels to ABC's teaming up with Disney's network, creating an
arsenal of programming for both ABC and The History Channel on
cable.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, all three of the old-line networks have made major moves
into owning cable networks as a way to hold on to viewers, fewer
and fewer of whom tune in over the air.
</P>
<P>
   And amid the cacophony of media outlets crying out for
attention, for CBS-Viacom to have a radio outlet and 210,000 US
billboards to promote its movies, news and television shows becomes
a crucial tool to break through to an mass audience besieged by
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that makes it hard to judge the impact of corporate
control of entertainment and, perhaps more importantly, news is
that, literally, most of us do not know what we are missing.
Observers have some reasonable theories but are generally hard-put
to say what news stories have not been aired because of
profit-minded conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   A survey commissioned by Miller's group, run by well-regarded
pollster Celinda Lake, found last December that 64 percent of
Americans surveyed think that consolidated ownership of TV networks
has ``some or a great deal of effect'' on the variety and type of
programming shown, although the question did not get into the
nature of that effect.
</P>
<P>
   One example cited was a decision by ABC News ``20/20'' producers
last year not to pursue an investigation of child molestation and
lax security at amusement parks, including Walt Disney World, the
flagship property of ABC's corporate parent. But ABC sources have
said the story had shaky sources, and it was an ABC producer who
unilaterally made the decision not to drop it _ perhaps to avoid
angering Disney bosses, but not because of direct orders.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hewitt, the veteran executive producer of CBS's ``60
Minutes,'' told The New York Times last week that except for a 1995
decision not to broadcast an interview with a tobacco company
whistleblower that could have led to a costly lawsuit, ``I've never
seen us knuckle under to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller said he thinks the media have fallen down pursuing
one of the major stories of our time _ the concentration of
capitalist power in not just media but finance, defense contracting
and industry.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many media critics have said television networks
provided only spotty coverage of the congressional debate over the
1996 Telecommunications act, focusing chiefly on its impact on
telephone and cable service while largely ignoring its provisions
to give TV station owners digital spectrum airwave space worth up
to $70 billion, much of it usable for non-TV communications
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The only big national network that is not now part of a media
conglomerate, NBC, is owned by a different kind of powerful
multinational business empire: General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't hearing the news about the big conglomerate
ownership,'' Miller said. ``Advertising-driven media tend to be
noncontroversial and tend not to be offensive to moneyed
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   But Solveig Singleton of the Cato Institute, a
libertarian-oriented Washington think tank, said, ``Government
control of the media or media conglomerates is still a much bigger
threat to people's liberty than the media conglomerates are.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Singleton added, ``In some cases it may be very important
to have a big, powerful company to expose something like corruption
at the highest levels of government.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing availability of information over the Internet, now
used by 40 million Americans, represents ``this enormous bottom-up
phenomenon. There are very low barriers to getting into the public
comment business. The really important thing is to keep that market
as open as possible rather than to say, `OK, big is bad, so if you
are big, we are going to restrict and regulate you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   However, veteran public television journalist Bill Moyers, in a
recent PBS special called ``Free Speech for Sale,'' said the First
Amendment does mean ``government can't keep you from getting your
two cents into the public debate. But what the framers of our
government didn't reckon with is that two cents doesn't buy you
much free speech these days . . . If you really want to be heard
today, we're talking big money.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS News president Andrew Heyward said despite the shrinking
number of corporate owners, television viewers today enjoy an
unprecedented diversity in programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more different kinds of news and information
available to viewers than there ever were before,'' Heyward said.
``Even in the so-called golden days of network news, there were
huge areas of life that were being woefully undercovered, like the
women's movement. I think there was a very narrow definition of
what was considered news.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that newspaper ownership has been
consolidated on a scale somewhat comparable to TV channels and
production studios; The Boston Globe joined The New York Times Co.
in 1993, which also includes 21 smaller newspapers and a magazine
group. National chains such as Gannett, Knight-Ridder and
Scripps-Howard control hundreds of US newspapers, most of which
have no local competition.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Edward J. Markey, the Massachusetts Democrat
who is the ranking minority member of the House telecommunications
subcommittee, has vigorously opposed recent FCC moves he says will
dilute the long-enshrined principle of diverse, local ownership of
media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``These mergers are like nuns: They don't travel alone. I am
sure you are going to see three or four more of these huge
megacombinations happen,'' Markey said, adding with a laugh:
``Eventually it will all get bought by AT&AMP;T, and then it will all
get bought by Microsoft, and then all of us in America will be
working for the same company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
