<HEADER>
A2938 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     09-15 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CUPEY ALTO, Puerto Rico: ... is another.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Gomez surveys the property, pointing here and there, he tells
a visitor who is living where.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's four over there and four in there and four down
there,'' he says. ``Big family. The land belonged to his
grandparents. If a relative is struggling somewhere, they come here
and we make room for them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a compound of Trinidads, and in the center stands a house
now twice as big as it used to be. It is the house where Doris
Trinidad, Tito's mother, lives, the same house where the boy grew
up to become a champion.
</P>
<P>
   Here . . . long before that house had a satellite dish beside it
big enough to bring in a NASA broadcast. Here . . . long before a
bigger house had been built around the old shell. Here . . . on
what has become hallowed ground in Puerto Rico, the boy grew to be
a man by running down that hill and through the lush green.
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, running in the heat. Running and throwing his
fists and hearing of the night his father fought the great Sanchez
and never asking why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I been here 27 years, and Tito is 26,'' Gomez says, making
clear he has the proper perspective to speak on the subject of his
cousin. ``He always got up on his own (to run). He was always ready
in the morning. Nobody had to wake him up. His father never had
problems with him. Tito always liked cross-country. He liked to
dance and ride horses. But since the first day he started fighting,
he never hesitated for one moment.''
</P>
<P>
   He never hesitated, so by the night he stopped Angel Romero in
Miramar with a blinding flurry of punches in the second round on
May 10, 1990, Felix Trinidad's fate was sealed.
</P>
<P>
   For good or ill, he was a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Trinidad returned to Puerto Rico after defending his title
against Pernell Whitaker in February, he was a conquering hero.
Although Whitaker had grown old since the night De La Hoya whipped
him two years earlier, he was still the great Whitaker to the
people of Puerto Rico, and their man had beaten him easily, as he
had so many before.
</P>
<P>
   He had not knocked out Whitaker, but he had beaten him soundly
and set the stage for the showdown that will define the career not
only of Trinidad but also of De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   It is their moment, a moment being talked about as the greatest
welterweight confrontation since Sugar Ray Leonard faced Thomas
Hearns 20 years ago. Perhaps it will be, but on this day Felix
Trinidad is far from the confrontation to come.
</P>
<P>
   He is sitting in a beautifully appointed villa overlooking the
ocean at the Wyndham El Conquistador Resort &AMP; Country Club in
Fajardo, a beachfront town an hour from San Juan. It is here that
he and his father came to prepare for De La Hoya. Here where he is
surrounded not with the poverty that spawns most fighters but by
the wretched excess they dream of.
</P>
<P>
   Up the side of a mountain climbs a cable car that takes hotel
guests from their rooms to a pool and the ocean below. In front of
him is a private marina, where a boat owned by the hotel will take
you to a private island owned by the hotel where sun worshippers
can bathe nude.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from Cupey Alto, not in miles but in life's realities.
Few of Trinidad's neighbors ever come to a place like this unless
it is to go to work. In a sense, that is why he is here, too.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad's father cut a deal with the Wyndham Hotels &AMP; Resorts
people that had his son train at several of their properties before
landing here. Always the workouts were private, but the people
would line up 100 yards away after he was done to have a picture
taken or get an autograph from an athlete many on the island
compare to Puerto Rico's greatest athletic legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone puts my son next to Roberto Clemente, that is a
great honor,'' Don Felix says. ``He was one of the best
representatives of Puerto Rico.''
</P>
<P>
   With that honor comes the pressure to fulfill it, however. Few
people here even consider the possibility that Trinidad might
return home without De La Hoya's WBC belt, so he fights not merely
for himself and his father's dream but for all Puerto Ricans.
</P>
<P>
   This Trinidad understands, promising at a large press gathering
in Fajardo that he will dispense with De La Hoya in six rounds.
That no one else has come close to doing that in De La Hoya's 31
straight victories means little to him because this fight is
against the hero of an island and the savior of a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think Oscar has a chance with Tito?'' asks Gilberto Luna
after spending a day taking people to the gym where Trinidad
usually trains in Bayamon _ a gym that is named after the great
champion Wilfredo Gomez. ``Forget about it. There will be a big
party here when he comes home. It will last a week.''
</P>
<P>
   That belief is everywhere, even in the minds of the father and
the son. As the latter stands in front of his villa on the evening
when he is scheduled to head to Las Vegas, he looks at the brown
heavy bag hanging by a chain 15 yards from the ocean and laughs at
De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   On it is painted white letters, and in the middle is a large
white shape. As you get closer, it is clear what the shape is.
</P>
<P>
   It is a chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Above it is written Oscar ``Chicken'' De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   On the dusty back window of the van Trinidad is about to get
into, someone has scribbled, ``Chicken De La Hoya.''
</P>
<P>
   The nickname, coined by a New York sportswriter with an ax to
grind with De La Hoya's promoter, Bob Arum, is everywhere around
Trinidad. Few believe it, though. Maybe even Trinidad doesn't. But
it has become fuel for the flame that began in Cupey Alto 26 years
ago and drove a young boy to become a champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how they call him the last few months,'' Trinidad says
when asked if he truly believes his opponent is afraid. ``At one
time he acted like a chicken. He didn't want this fight. We'll see
how he acts Sept. 18.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad says this through a translator, even though he has
studied English for a year and understands far more than he lets
on. He is wary of people he believes are in De La Hoya's corner but
is safe in the belief that his people are all behind him.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a burden to carry, he says, but one to be joyous
about. When Sept. 18 comes, he will carry that burden with the
strength of his people behind him, and he will prove that his
critics and even his promoter were wrong about him. He will show
then that his father was right about the rough diamond he sent
Carmen Carratini 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of my career, (promoter) Don King didn't
recognize my worth,'' the fighter says. ``Don King never got me the
recognition I deserved worldwide, like De La Hoya got. That is the
luck of promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping back then to sign autographs for a half-dozen hotel
workers who have politely waited for more than a half-hour and then
to have his picture taken, another Tito Trinidad reveals himself
for just a moment.
</P>
<P>
   He is in a fighting pose now, throwing phony punches for a
photographer, when he suddenly unleashes a blinding barrage. His
hands move, but you can barely see them. They come like a hard
rain. Then he looks at a reporter and throws one last flurry,
saying with an assassin's grin on his face, ``No mas, Golden Boy!''
</P>
<P>
   It is then you see he is like Cupey Alto. He fools you at first
with his soft voice and shy smile, but he comes from a place where
school guards wear bulletproof vests. A place where fighters grow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
