<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEEP-FARMER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S LEARNING FROM THE LAMBS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT BARRINGTON, Mass. _ Lila Berle and her crew of two _ a
teenage boy who has been trimming brush from fences and a man who
is the only full-time employee on the sheep farm _ have just picked
up lunch from the North Egremont post office and deli.
Uncharacteristically (it takes too much time), Berle suggests
driving up to the top of a hill and picnicking under a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Below, the scene can take your breath away. In the midday sun,
sheep are napping under the shade of trees. The tractors are lined
up, their hoods just poking out of a barn. There isn't a thing out
of place. Berle likes order, and she's been working on it since she
bought the rundown, bankrupt farm nine years ago. Some trees were
removed and some planted. A silo came down. One barn was renovated
and another is in process. And all the ugly old repairs, like
aluminum sheeting on one side of a corral, have been pulled off.
</P>
<P>
   Berle, who hardly ever sits still, seems almost peaceful. And
then she spots something below and the calm is gone. She grabs a
shovel out of the back of her SUV, heads down the hill, and starts
digging. She returns with a weedy-looking burdock plant and tosses
it into the bushes. ``These are a scourge,'' she says. ``I'm a bear
about these.'' Burdock, she explains, gets tangled in sheep's wool,
and she prides herself on ``beautiful, clean wool.''
</P>
<P>
   Lila Berle, 62, was born to farming. She and her family own vast
tracts of protected land in the Berkshires, though none where sheep
graze. People out here say that her family's land is some of the
most beautiful acreage in the state. But when Berle saw this
defunct dairy farm, overgrown and badly in need of a cash infusion,
she decided to buy it, fix it up, raise sheep, and bale her own
hay. She named it Stonehedge. Five hundred Rambouillet (some
crossed with Romneys and Border Leicester) graze on 300 acres. The
lamb goes to New York to specialty butchers; the wool is sold to
one of the fussiest wool shops in the region. Berle works from 7
a.m. until sundown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will not find any person who knows sheep like she does,''
says George Wislocki, president of the Berkshire Natural Resource
Council in Pittsfield. ``If anyone can make money at sheep farming,
it would be Lila.''
</P>
<P>
   Add a level of energy not often found in women half her age.
Once lunch is over, Berle seems antsy. She has taken too much time.
She hops on a tractor and goes whipping around her fields for an
hour and a half, leaving 24 round bales of fresh hay in her wake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a ball,'' she says. ``I love the land and I love
the animals. I'm extremely passionate about it. There's something
rhythmic about farming. In the summer, haying and dealing with
lambs, crops to keep, mothers to feed. You learn a lot about life
and death _ about patience. You never know what the challenge will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Old friends like what they see. ``Lila came into her own,'' says
Wislocki, who has known her some 30 years. ``She knows who she is,
and she's very pleased to be that person.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheep farm suits her, says Laurie Norton Moffatt, director
of the Norman Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge. ``She lives it, she
breathes it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moffatt says that Berle hays the museum's 25 acres twice a year.
``Our visitors are absolutely enthralled. And they have no idea who
she is. She likes it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The lady on the tractor, it turns out, was a Rockwell board
member for 7 years and president for another 10 during its move to
new premises. Berle has been, over the years, deeply involved in
many aspects of the Berkshire community, its arts, its land, its
churches, and its schools.
</P>
<P>
   The sheep farm is different. It's all hers. She insists it isn't
physically taxing. Running Stonehedge takes time and a certain
passion. ``I want to inspire other women to do this,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Which she will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lila Wilde Berle bought her first four animals in 1984 when she
was raising meat for her own table. By the time she was 50, she had
quite a few, she says.
</P>
<P>
   She was raised at High Lawn Farm in Lenox, one of the largest
dairy farms in the area, known internationally for its Jersey cows.
Since both of Berle's parents, Colonel H. George and Marjorie Field
Wilde, died within the last few years, High Lawn is now managed for
the Wilde family heirs. Wilde won agriculture breeding awards for
his Jerseys. Berle's mother, granddaughter of William D. and Emily
Vanderbilt Sloane (the furniture merchant whose family owned W. &AMP;
J. Sloane) could simply look at a cow and see if something was
wrong, says Berle.
</P>
<P>
   After Smith College ('58), Lila Wilde married Peter A. A. Berle.
Peter Berle is former commissioner of environment for New York
State, headed the National Audubon Society for 10 years, and is now
host and creative director of the ``Environment Show'' on Northeast
Public Radio. He farms part time, raising Angus cows for beef. This
year, says his wife, ``he made 50 bales of hay.''
</P>
<P>
   But who's counting?
</P>
<P>
   The Berles raised four children, and the job brought Lila
immense satisfaction. ``It's the most rewarding thing I've ever
done,'' she says. ``I have seven grandchildren, who I just love, so
I'm very blessed.'' All are young, and when they visit, they play
with the sheep. One Berle daughter, Beatrice, went into farming;
she raises organic vegetables and goats for cheese in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a family who has always challenged itself,'' says
Wislocki, the Resource Council president. Lila Berle ``comes from
race horses. She knows she works hard, but that's what she believes
it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Wislocki says that the sheep farm is unusually efficient. By
frost, Berle will have collected 850 bales of fresh hay to feed the
animals, plus another 5,000 smaller rectangular bales of dried hay.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
