<HEADER>
A2942 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-SHEEP-FARMER-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     09-15 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEEP-FARMER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 GREAT BARRINGTON, Mass.: ... dried hay.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The drought didn't affect her because it rained at the critical
moment. While others around lost crops, Berle says, ``this is the
best hay crop in years.'' So good that she'll hardly need grain for
the animals, which is what she's aiming for. Grass-fed lamb is
quite different from grain fed. Grass-fed is leaner, firmer, tender
but not fatty. Like sheep in some regions of France, Berle's nibble
wild thyme in the summer and watercress in the spring, but she
can't detect either perfume or pepper in the meat.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't use hormones, additives, or antibiotics, so she has
market possibilities all over the Berkshires. Instead, she sells
about 80 percent of the sheep to Greek and Lebanese specialty
markets in New York each spring. Spring lambs weigh about 40 to 50
pounds (regular weight is twice that). They go whole to market,
where they're often bought to spit-roast over a wood fire for the
Orthodox Easter celebration. The remaining sheep grow to full size,
and they go to auction or they're slaughtered and butchered into
standard cuts, which Berle sells from her freezer to private
customers.
</P>
<P>
   She delivers her wool to Green Mountain Spinnery in Putney, Vt.,
which is known for its top-quality wool. ``We refuse any wool that
has burdock, hay, or chaff,'' says the Spinnery's Donna Coughlin.
``You can't get a good price for wool unless it's clean.''
</P>
<P>
   So Lila Berle will rid her land of burdock if she has to pull
the plants out one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Which she does.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fresh round bales of hay Berle has made this afternoon are
wrapped in white plastic within hours of being cut. The giant white
drums, stored for winter at the edge of the fields, look, from a
distance, like mounds of melting snow. Closer, they have the
pleasant smell of a beer brewery.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh hay bales are more common in Europe than they are here.
``The sun hasn't taken the nutrients out,'' says Berle. Called
haylage, to distinguish them from silage (they don't require a
silo), these bales are simply fodder whose air has been pressed
out. Once wrapped in plastic for storage, the hay goes through a
slight fermentation process _ that's what causes the beer aroma _
that prevents it from spoiling.
</P>
<P>
   Berle collects grass for haylage in a German Deutz Fahr baler
hooked onto the back of her tractor. As she drives around, the drum
on the baler picks up the grass and packs it until nothing more
will fit. Berle stops the tractor and the machine continues to
work, first tying the bale, then releasing it onto the field. The
wet bales are picked up by Joel DeGaramo, who lives and works on
the farm. DeGaramo follows Berle with a wrapping machine attached
to his tractor, which lifts up a bale and tosses it around in the
back while a large roll of opaque white plastic winds around it,
forming three layers. It looks like a ball of yarn being rewound.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means I can put out a heck of a lot of grass without
barns,'' says Berle, who has poured money into shoring up
dilapidated barns.
</P>
<P>
   She brings a visitor around to one side of the long pen where a
couple of dozen wildly woolly sheep have stuck their noses into the
side of a bale of fresh hay. ``Look, it's so delicious. The lambs
love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Berle holds her hand out to one of the two Maremmas who guard
the sheep. These dogs, she explains, have been bred for centuries
in Italy to protect sheep from wolves.
</P>
<P>
   The others watch a flock in a pasture a mile away. Those dogs
won't let her near them, she says. ``But it's much better to have
them not friendly. They're working dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes at night DeGaramo hears the dogs barking and knows
they're at work. Coyotes are nearby, and there are other dangers.
``A lot of animals coexist here,'' says Berle. ``There are deer,
baby foxes, lots of rabbits this year. We love the deer, but they
eat my clover.''
</P>
<P>
   A fox with three pups got three of Berle's small sheep, and
Berle didn't do anything about stopping her. Pressed about it, she
admits that it's a weakness of being a woman _ and a mother. She
allowed the mother fox to get some food for her babies.
</P>
<P>
   Berle doesn't trot out this soft side very often, but her
mothering instincts are often called into play. She pulled a weak
lamb out of the flock and took two playmates with it, so the weak
one could become strong without feeling isolated. Weak lambs are
prey not only for coyotes but for the Maremma puppies as well,
explains Berle. ``The younger animals don't flock up,'' says Berle.
The young guard dogs don't want them around.
</P>
<P>
   Several grandchildren are arriving soon, and Berle has to leave.
Before she gets down from the tractor, she wants to empty the baler
into the upper field to feed the sheep some fresh hay. She calls
down and offers the visitor a ride. ``Plenty of room,'' she shouts.
</P>
<P>
   No, there's not. But Berle is burning to show off her view of
the world, which is worth the bumpy ride. ``It's so empowering.
When I first got on a tractor, I understood why men run them all
day. They're so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   She bumps along the road until the sheep are in view. ``You get
up here and you can do anything,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And she has.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
