<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MCDONALDS-MAKEOVER &LR;      09-15 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONALDS-MAKEOVER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDONALD'S TOUTS FASTER COOKING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a McDonald's in Boston general manager Vijay Selhi inspects
$40,000 worth of new computerized cooking equipment _ equipment
McDonald's hopes will change perceptions that its food is something
relished only by omnivorous 12-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Gone from the restaurant are the bins where once Quarter
Pounders languished under heat lamps. Instead there are video
screens that track orders and high-tech toasters that can brown a
sesame-seed bun in 12 seconds, 43 seconds faster than a
conventional toaster.
</P>
<P>
   While customers at the drive-through window can verify an order
on a new video screen, most changes, aside from a new paint job,
may not be immediately visible.
</P>
<P>
   But what customers should experience is a better burger as
behind-the-scenes automation frees employees to lavish more care on
preparing food.
</P>
<P>
   Burgers used to be ``mass produced,'' says Selhi's boss, Bob
King, owner of six McDonald's franchises. Now meals are ``hot and
fresh and cooked the way a customer wants.''
</P>
<P>
   From the mid-1950s to the mid-1980s, McDonald's ruled fast food,
a category it virtually created. But now the 44-year-old
Illinois-based chain of more than 25,000 restaurants worldwide is
in the midst of a middle-age makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to defend their turf against intensifying competition
while adjusting to changing consumer tastes, McDonald's restaurants
are spending an average of $85,000 apiece on improvements designed
to result in a higher quality meal.
</P>
<P>
   Toasting buns in 12 seconds may not sound like a big deal, but
all the incremental fine-tunings add up to ``one of the most
significant change in McDonald's history,'' says Sid Boorstein,
owner of four McDonald's franchises.
</P>
<P>
   A drive down just about any main drag in America shows how much
tougher competition has gotten in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   For openers, there are the Golden Arch rivals, such as Burger
King and Wendy's. Together, the three chains operate about 25,000
hamburger stands in the United States, meaning market saturation
has the potential to slow growth.
</P>
<P>
   Competition also comes from new sources. With salad bars and
takeout meals, more and more supermarkets are trying to take a bite
out of America's fast-food dollar.
</P>
<P>
   And in New England, McDonald's franchisees face a unique
challenge with big breakfast competition here from Randolph,
Mass.-based Dunkin' Donuts. For many McDonald's franchisees in
other parts of the country, breakfast can be the most lucrative
meal.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case in Boston. But with the new cooking system,
McDonald's franchisees can be more aggressive at breakfast. Among
other things, the system can support a larger menu, including a
recently launched line of bagel sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   As competition has gotten tougher, consumer tastes have changed.
Some folks eschew fast food entirely for more healthful fare, and
diehard trenchermen have become even more demanding.
</P>
<P>
   No longer satisfied with just burgers and fries, fast-food fans
want better service, better quality, and more menu choices _ and
they want it right away.
</P>
<P>
   This desire for even faster fast food may explain why purchases
made at the drive-through window often account for 60 percent of
sales at many McDonald's restaurants, says Boorstein, who also
chairs a cooperative of franchise owners who operate 315
McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's has always been fast. It's the quality that's been at
issue. Two years ago, McDonald's sought to dispel perceptions of
its mediocre food by introducing new computerized cooking systems
that mean each meal is ``made for you.''
</P>
<P>
   (With roughly 13,000 domestic restaurants, it took time for the
``made-to-you'' changes to be rolled out nationwide; the changes
are just about completed.)
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, a single cook prepared McDonald's burgers, then
kept them hot in a bin. If a cook overestimated the pace of
business, food had to be thrown away.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new system, burgers are crafted by a team of sous
chefs. Cooked meat is kept hot in a heating cabinet, but a sandwich
isn't assembled until an order is placed.
</P>
<P>
   For McDonald's, the new system reduces waste and improves profit
margins, franchisee King says. For the customer, the new system is
intended to yield an ``individualized'' sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want extra onions and no pickles?'' King says. ``The
system has the flexibility to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-food purists might detect similarities to Burger King's
flame-broiled credo of ``have it your way.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing ideas is nothing new in the fast-food business, says
Ron Paul, president of Technomic Inc., a restaurant consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burger King does one thing, and McDonald's has to respond, and
vice versa,'' Paul says.
</P>
<P>
   The early read on the ``made-for-you'' program has been
positive. For its most recent quarter, McDonald's Corp. said
profits were up 45 percent largely because of increases in overseas
sales. But domestic cost-cutting was also a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Made-for-you'' has been a ``good success'' for US McDonald's
franchisees in other parts of the country, Paul says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a competitive necessity because the bar keeps
getting raised,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive pressures may be why Burger King Corp., the
Miami-based division of Diageo PLC, recently announced its own
makeover, which includes a new logo and a revamped kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new kitchen will take us well beyond the `have it your
way' concept,'' says Burger King spokeswoman Kim Miller.
</P>
<P>
   For McDonald's, talking about better Big Macs is one thing;
convincing adults that the quality has improved is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the cooperative of McDonald's franchisees has
increased its advertising budget to $18 million from $14 million.
Created by Boston ad agency Arnold Communications, the campaign for
the cooperative has the theme of ``You get more for your money
because McDonald's treats you right.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest ads in that campaign talk up ``outrageous values''
and ``every day deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoting 39-cent hamburgers on Wednesdays and 49-cent
cheeseburgers on Sundays, the ads look to drive traffic to the
restaurants so customers can experience the ``made-for-you''
changes for themselves. The hope is that customers will be
sufficiently pleased to make many return visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real breakthrough for us,'' says Boorstein, who
adds: ``If a customer hasn't been to a McDonald's lately, they
haven't been to a McDonald's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
