<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SWITCH-BILLIONAIRE-AR     09-15 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWITCH-BILLIONAIRE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS AREN'T THE ONLY MEASURE OF HIS JACKPOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Madonna is not exactly complaining that Lucent
Technologies has made him, on paper at least, a near-billionaire by
offering to buy his small high-tech company for more than $1.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that a sense of mission _ not money _ is what
has propelled him and his colleagues at Excel Switching Corp., a
Hyannis, Mass. maker of versatile telecommunications equipment that
nine years ago numbered only a dozen people. Then, they worked over
an auto-body shop, trying to ignore paint fumes as they wrote
software.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna is the latest of several Massachusetts entrepreneurs who
have hit what some now call ``the Lucent jackpot'' _ when the
concept a little company has perfected proves so compelling a giant
eager to protect its dominance comes visiting with offers of
hundreds of millions of dollars in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Tuesday's closing price, Madonna stands to get $1.02
billion in Lucent stock when the Excel deal closes, perhaps before
year's end. Virtually all of his 460 employees own Excel stock as
well, and some stand to reap mini-fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   But Madonna is far more eager to talk about his corner of the
Internet world than he is about stock options. In a new age of
overnight Internet millionaires, Madonna stands as a comparatively
rare example of someone who did it, so to speak, the hard way.
Madonna has labored for more than a decade to build a company that
actually makes money ($27 million net income on $123 million sales
last year), rather than months pumping up a concept. Finally, Excel
became irresistible to New Jersey-baed Lucent, the world's biggest
telecommunications equipment manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who knows him knows he deserves this,'' said Matt
Trask, a software executive. ``He's the hardest working guy I know.
I think he's probably seen by a lot of people in the Cape (Cod)
high-tech community as something of a god now.''
</P>
<P>
   To the extent Madonna is pleased with the Lucent deal _ a big
part of him and his family wishes they could all go back to
obscurity _ it is because he sees Lucent as a kind of platform to
reach the whole world with a radically new approach to building
devices for people and machines to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excel is very much on a mission of changing an industry,''
Madonna, 39, said as he took a break from a Boston meeting with
software writers who develop new uses for Excel's so-called
open-platform, programmable switches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often said we were dancing with the elephants out there,''
Madonna said of the challenge of competing with some of the world's
biggest and richest telecommunications equipment companies,
including Lucent, Northern Telecom, Siemens, Alcatel and Ericsson.
``Now we're harnessing one of the elephants and riding it.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the company has more than 200 customers in 70
countries. ``To get into the mainstream, we believe we could have
done it as stand-alone, but it would have taken longer,'' said
Madonna, adding that ``to have that red circle, the Lucent logo on
our products, can go a very long way'' in increasing market
credibility and attracting new customers. (It is undecided whether
the Excel name will continue to be used after the deal closes,
which could be as soon as December.)
</P>
<P>
   Excel is one of a half-dozen Massachusetts companies Lucent has
moved to buy over the past year as it tries to stay at the leading
edge of the dizzying world of Internet communication.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to some recent Lucent acquisitions, however, Excel is a
graybeard. In June Lucent made a $900 million bid for Nexabit, a
company with zero revenues but well-developed plans to sell 1
billion-bit-per-second data switches. Two years ago Lucent grabbed
high-speed switch maker Prominet of Marlborough, Mass. for $200
million just seven weeks after it shipped its first product and 20
months after its founding.
</P>
<P>
   Excel's impact on telecommunications can be compared to the
impact personal computers had on computing 15 years ago. Until
recently, companies buying telephone switches have had to buy the
equivalent of preprogrammed mainframe computers from giants like
Lucent and Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   Excel builds smaller, flexible devices that, like personal
computers, can be programmed to perform a vast array of functions
or resold by companies such as Motorola and QualComm as part of
customized telecom packages.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing its bid for Excel, Lucent officials said they are
convinced ``open platform'' switching is a wave of the future, a $5
billion market by 2003. Analysts contend Lucent feared it risked
becoming a doomed dinosaur like Digital Equipment or Data General
if it ignored the trend away from jumbo mainframe-like switches.
</P>
<P>
   By selling use-as-you-want switches, Excel has also spawned a
thriving business for programmers and companies like Priority Call
Management and Converse that use Excel products in advanced
voice-mail and other services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of the concept that the world is full of smart
people'' who will dream up new uses for telecommunications switches
that a giant company might be slow to realize, Madonna said. For
example, Excel's products are being used to develop systems that
allow people to use their wireless phone as an extension of their
home phone, or transmit text messages synthesized into speech.
</P>
<P>
   One other key advantage of Excel products is what is called
``scaleability.'' Instead of buying the electronic equivalent of a
hangar from Lucent, a start-up company offering local or
long-distance service or prepaid calling cards can buy a few sheds
_ and add more as business grows.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna, who grew up in what he describes as a ``blue-collar''
background in New Britain, Conn., graduated from the University of
Connecticut with a degree in biomedical engineering.
</P>
<P>
   He went to work for a Cambridge, Mass. company designing what
was in the early 1980s the world's largest CAT scan medical device,
but always felt that ``I wanted to work for a startup company.'' In
1984 he joined LanTel, a company in Orleans, Mass.with a dozen
employees developing office telephone switches.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the company moved to Marlborough, Mass., then went out
of business _ leaving Madonna at age 28 jobless, but ready to found
Excel. It started operations in early 1988 with a half-dozen people
in 500 square feet of space over an auto-body shop in Southborough,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the cheapest place I could find to rent,'' Madonna
said. ``It wasn't bad if they weren't painting cars while you were
trying to write software.'' The company's sales quickly reached
millions of dollars a year, helped by 1988 federal deregulation
moves allowing Baby Bells to sell voice mail and other premium
services.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna always wanted to get back to the Cape, and in 1990 found
space over a Chinese restaurant in Sagamore Beach. ``Instead of
smelling paint fumes, like we did in Southborough, we were smelling
egg rolls,'' said Madonna, who frequently slept at the office
during back-to-back seven-day workweeks.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, the company had grown to where it needed new
space in Hyannis for its now 400 employees, plus another 60 in
sales and development offices in New Hampshire, Orlando, Fla.,
Dallas, Tokyo, and Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The company went public in November 1997, not because it needed
cash _ it had tens of millions in the bank _ but to raise its
public and Wall Street visibility given its location well off the
high-tech beaten path.
</P>
<P>
   Excel's manufacturing and development offices do not immediately
suggest a billion-dollar business. The nondescript Independence
Park site might as well be in a South Carolina industrial park as
on the Cape Cod of salty-air fame; Excel's neighbors on
Perseverance Way include Jeff Bacon Auto Service, Bourque Heating &AMP;
Cooling, an awning shop and a sand quarry.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucent deal has been greeted with pride by Madonna's
colleagues in the fledgling but fast-growing high-tech community,
who see the Lucent deal validating the image some promote of the
Cape as ``the Silicon Sandbar.''
</P>
<P>
   Trask, the president of Communica, a 50-person software firm
that also runs the CapeCod.com Web information site, said,
``There's a sense that Bob has once again shown us the way. He's
the poster boy for the region.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
