u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-15 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARCOURT GENERAL'S SMITH GOING OUT ON A LOW NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Smith, the tough-as-nails leader of Harcourt General
Inc. for three decades, will likely make his last public appearance
before shareholders as the company's chief executive this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 74, created a family fortune worth more than $800 million
and huge wealth for investors who bought into companies he has run
over many years. Harcourt General shares have outpaced the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500, sometimes by wild margins, over a long stretch
beginning in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who shares Smith's famously hard-nosed focus on stock
values would be unhappy with Newton, Mass.-based Harcourt General
and other related companies over the past three years. It's not the
blaze of glory every executive hopes to go out on.
</P>
<P>
   Consider how the stock market has boomed since September 1996, a
period in which the S&AMP;P 500 soared by 108 percent and the Nasdaq
stock index gained 145 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt General stock has actually gone down in value during
that same period, generating a total-return loss of 14.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One of Harcourt General's biggest assets, its 53.9 percent
interest in pricey retailer Neiman Marcus Group Inc., has fared
even worse. The publicly traded Neiman Marcus stock has slumped by
32 percent during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of GCX Cos., the General Cinema movie theater and venture
capital business spun out of Harcourt General in 1993 but still run
by the Smiths, are down 10 percent in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Now Smith, who will continue as Harcourt General's chairman,
plans to step down as the company's chief executive in six weeks
and make way for, literally, the next generation. Smith's son,
Robert Smith, and his son-in-law, Brian Knez, will take over as
co-CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   At a special meeting Harcourt General asked shareholders to back
a plan that will yet again reshape the interests of a company that
has a history of changing businesses like a corporate chameleon
(remember the bottling business?).
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone approves.
</P>
<P>
   A proxy analysis firm that advises institutional investors has
recommended shareholders vote against a proposal that would
increase Harcourt General's pool of authorized shares. The reason:
The company's relative stock performance over the last three years
wasn't good enough to justify it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, they came very close,'' said Ed Seaton, an
analyst at Institutional Shareholder Services who recommended
voting against the proposal. ``You have to draw a line in the sand
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But the company has tied the authorization to a plan to spin off
its Neiman Marcus stake to Harcourt shareholders. No increased
stock authorization, no Neiman Marcus spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt General has painted the two tactics as part of a larger
strategy to make the company's stock a pure investment in the
publishing business. Once separated from any retailing interests,
Harcourt General wants to be able to issue more stock to fund
acquisitions or raise cash with the aim of building up its
publishing ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives believe Harcourt General stock is paying the
price for two recent cash acquisitions that have watered down
recent profits, paying $854 million for National Education Corp. in
1997 and $416 million last October for Moseby Inc., a professional
health science publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through a period where we've made two very
significant additions and indicated they would be dilutive to
earnings in the near term,'' said spokesman Peter Farwell. ``I
think we've paid the price for it in the stock market. But we're
convinced it was the right thing to do for the company in the long
term.''
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus is another problem. The stock has been nothing
special for a long while now and recent sales numbers have been a
big disappointment. Our question: If you can't sell really
expensive stuff to rich people in this economy, when exactly can
you make it happen?
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, we just got our hands on the Neiman Marcus
Christmas catalog the other day. Among the highlights: a song
written and performed for you by tuxedoed bandleader Peter Duchin
($35,000); a 181-carat diamond necklace ($450,000); and a Boeing
business jet ($35,250,000). There's a save-the-rainforest option
($35 per acre) for anyone feeling too guilty.
</P>
<P>
   GCX Cos., though no longer a part of Harcourt General, is a
publicly traded company with many of the same old shareholders.
After the Smiths, mutual fund manager Mario Gabelli is the biggest
investor, owning nearly 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The problem at GCX: Revenues from its movie business have been
stagnant or even declining despite international expansion. Its
unusual business model, investing the cash in venture capital
deals, is interesting but unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   One investment in its stable, Internet retailer
Mothernature.com, is in registration to go public and could be a
big hit.
</P>
<P>
   But right now, Harcourt's plan to focus on publishing and its
new generation of Smiths are what shareholders are counting on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has a chief economist. So does BankBoston. And when the
two banks finally merge, there will be room for only one chief
economist.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday Fleet announced the job would go to Wayne Ayers, who
currently holds the position at BankBoston. Nicholas Perna of Fleet
will leave to write and teach.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers, 52, has been with BankBoston for 21 years, nearly 10 as
chief economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a bigger challenge,'' said Ayers, who will now be
responsible for tracking the economies of New York and New Jersey
as well as New England.
</P>
<P>
   Perna said he took himself out of the running for the top job
voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I have been thinking about for some time,''
he said. Perna said he has no specific plans but envisages writing
articles and possibly books about economic subjects.
</P>
<P>
   A likable fellow with a rare ability to translate economics into
simple English, Perna will be missed, especially by journalists
scrambling to make sense of difficult economic stories on deadline.
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
