<HEADLINE>
ONE FAMILY'S PRECIOUS HEIRLOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEPPERELL, Mass. _ From where Carl Hills is standing, on his
120-acre farm here, he's at the edge of an acre-and-a-half field of
tomatoes with fruit-heavy rows of apple trees behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take them out this winter,'' says Hills.
</P>
<P>
   No, not the tomatoes, but the apple trees.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, he says, the tomato field will be rotated into corn
next spring, but the apple trees will just be ``pushed over'' and
hauled away _ and the land where they are now probably put into
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   It is not on some Long Island truck farm where this is to
happen, but an old New England apple orchard, which the Hills
family took over from the Kimball brothers (keeping the name,
Kimball's Fruit Farm) a generation ago. It sits high on a ridge of
apple country land that straddles the Massachusetts-New Hampshire
border, with a clear view northwest to the Monadnock Range.
</P>
<P>
   But these are not your big, red, juicy hybrid tomatoes, Big Boy,
Beefsteak, and the rest. What Hills will be tearing out his apple
trees for are ``heirlooms,'' old tomato varieties with distinctive
tastes and exotic names like Black Prince and Green Zebra, Mortgage
Lifter, and Arkansas Traveler.
</P>
<P>
   Hauled into town, 300 to 400 pounds' worth at a time, the
heirlooms fetch $1.60 a pound at the nine farmers' markets in and
around Boston that Hills or his wife, Marie, or his two sisters,
Wendy and Sheri, have staffed every week this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the 10-pound boxes that Hills delivers in the early
mornings to wholesale ``commission men'' for $15 end up going for
$25 a box to pricey restaurants in the city.
</P>
<P>
   And those prices, Hills says, ``aren't holding people back.''
</P>
<P>
   The best-sellers by far are the Green Zebras, a three-ounce
fruit that ripens to an amber-green with darker green stripes,
which the seed catalogs describe as ``sweet yet zingy.'' ``I can't
grow enough of them,'' Hills says.
</P>
<P>
   Other good sellers _ and attention-getters _ are the Black
Prince, originally grown in Siberia; the Brandywine, a large
reddish fruit originally developed by Amish farmers; and the Yellow
Peach, whose fuzzy skin somewhat resembles that of a peach.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening on Hills's farm is part of a growing national
trend, according to Jaime Gooch, managing editor of American
Vegetable Grower, where heirloom tomatoes were the cover story in
the August issue.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend triggered, Gooch says in a telephone interview from
Willoughby, Ohio, ``by the consolidation of the food industry.''
With supermarket mergers, Gooch says, ``it's becoming harder for
the smaller growers to get their produce into the supermarkets, so
they're focusing on niche markets.''
</P>
<P>
   And in that general niche-market trend, Gooch says, ``heirlooms
are a big thing, because a lot of consumers aren't happy with what
they're finding on supermarket shelves'' _ the tomatoes picked
green in California and Florida ``and blasted with ethylene gas to
ripen them.''
</P>
<P>
   And once shoppers see a colorful array of heirloom tomatoes,
Gooch says, ``they go nuts for them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carl Hills's father, Harold, who is now 79, took over the farm
from the Kimball brothers when Carl was a teenager. Tacked up now
on the wall inside the farmstand, out on Route 122 just before
Pepperell turns into Hollis, N. H., is a faded snapshot of a
half-dozen long-haired teenagers, shirtless and smiling broadly
into the sun. Carl Hills, now 43, is in the middle, and they were
the farm crew one summer back in the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   What Hills remembers from those summers is how the crew
manhandled as many as 600 bushel boxes of apples every day during
the height of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the crew is five young men from Jamaica who live in a
dormitory up over the farmstand. On a good dark-to-dark day, three
or four times a week, they will pick up to 1,500 pounds of
heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   Hills did two years at the University of Connecticut's
agriculture school and came back to work the farm _ as an apple and
fruit farm _ for his father.
</P>
<P>
   But when he took over the farm on his own nine years ago, Hills
says, ``I told my dad, no way I'm going to take over the farm on
that basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was he thinking that there might be something else, but
it was increasingly apparent that there wasn't much of a future in
apples.
</P>
<P>
   Already there was competition from the year-round season in
Washington State and a looming threat from China, which is now
dumping apple juice concentrate on the American market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Hills says, ``we have to beg wholesalers to take our
apples,'' especially in a bumper-crop year like this one, when the
trees are so laden with fruit that ``if we'd had a wet summer, we'd
have a lot of broken limbs.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was after the Hillses started going to farmers' markets
that he discovered the niche market of heirloom tomatoes, along
with a market for new and unusual varieties of apples like Ginger
Gold and Elstar, which Hills is planting now _ and won't be tearing
out this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We listened to what people were asking for,'' Hills says, and
looked at what other farmers were selling.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hillses, particularly Carl's wife, Marie, work hard to
promote their niche product at the farmers' markets. At the markets
Marie Hills staffs, like Sunday's at the Charles Hotel in Harvard
Square, she'll eagerly explain the particular qualities of the
various varieties and perhaps hand a sample to a wavering customer.
</P>
<P>
   If the journey from traditional apples to heirloom tomatoes
rightly begins in the field _ the field next to the rows of apple
trees that will come out this winter _ it properly ends at the old
apple-packing house behind Hills's farm stand.
</P>
<P>
   Hills remembers coming in there as a child with his mother, when
she used to bake doughnuts to sell to the dozens of local women who
sorted and packed apples in the late fall chill.
</P>
<P>
   The only reminder of those days is the plugged-up opening for
the old wooden stove, which never warmed the room enough to let the
women take their coats off.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are large wooden pallets on the floor on which are
laid out, by color and variety, the previous day's heirloom
picking.
</P>
<P>
   And they're laid out that way, Hills explains, so that in the
late afternoon on days before he'll be heading into Boston, ``I can
make up real eye-catching boxes'' _ those 10-pound open-faced boxes
of heirlooms, destined to catch the eyes of restaurant chefs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
