<HEADLINE>
ORTHODOX CHURCH BARS PAPAL VISIT TO GREECE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a sign of ecumenical tension, leaders of the Greek Orthodox
Church last week ruled out a pilgrimage to Greece by Pope John Paul
II until the Roman Catholic pontiff apologizes and offers penance
for centuries of antagonism between Orthodox and Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope can come to Greece as a head of state but not as a
religious leader,'' Metropolitan Kallinkos, spokesman for the Holy
Synod of the Greek Orthodox Church, said after a meeting of church
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope cannot visit Greece as the head of the Catholic
Church before asking forgiveness and doing penance for the
interventions by the church in the Orthodox world from the epoch of
the crusades until today,'' Kallinkos said.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul, in a letter published in June, expressed his desire
to visit Greece as part of trips to biblical sites in various
nations to mark the start of the third millennium.
</P>
<P>
   In Greece, the pontiff sought to recall the New Testament
account of St. Paul's sermon on the Areopagus that symbolizes the
whole of humanity's encounter with the gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Greek Orthodox leaders rejected the pope's idea of a visit as
soon as the letter was published and formalized their opposition
last week. But the Vatican and the Greek government are striving to
avoid a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Edward Cassidy, president of the Pontifical Council for
Promoting Christian Unity, who was in Greece last week to attend a
religious symposium, said John Paul had not yet asked to visit
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope does not desire to come to Greece soon,'' Cassidy
said. ``It is a desire for the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said John Paul ``will be
welcome in Greece like every head of state,'' but added that he did
not want to interfere in ecclesiastical matters.
</P>
<P>
   But the Roman Catholic archbishop of Athens said the controversy
has hurt ecumenical efforts. ``The criticisms of a visit by the
pope have set back dialogue between Catholics and Orthodox by 10
years,'' said Archbishop Nikos Foscolo.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in the Greek Orthodox Church said they want John Paul to
apologize for the schism of 1050 that divided the Orthodox and
Roman churches; the Crusades, which led to the conquest and sacking
of Constantinople in 1204; and the Council of Lyons in 1274, which
unsuccessfully attempted to unite the Greek and Roman churches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --``See You at the Pole,'' the annual event in which young
people gather to pray for their schools, has been expanded this
year to include activities by adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``See You at the Pole'' will be held Sept. 15. Millions of
students are expected to pray at their schools at 7 a.m. local
time. While the event is aimed at public school students, others
can participate.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., have
heightened interest in the event this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there's more of a need felt by people in the
church to pray for our schools, to pray for our children,'' said
Doug Clark, director of field ministries for the National Network
of Youth Ministries, a San Diego-based organization that has helped
coordinate ``See You at the Pole.''
</P>
<P>
   This year adults will be involved, the Sunday before the event,
with a ``Challenge 2000 Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's setting aside services on the weekend before `See You at
the Pole' to pray for students and teachers to represent God
faithfully on the campus throughout the year,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   --Greek Orthodox churches across the country took up a special
collection at liturgies to help victims of Tuesday's earthquake in
Greece that killed dozens of people and left thousands homeless.
``I appeal to you now as beloved spiritual children: please lift up
your voices in prayer and open your hearts in love at this time for
our brothers and sisters in Athens in their hour of need,'' Bishop
George of New Jersey, archiepiscopal vicar for the Greek Orthodox
Archdiocese of America, wrote in a letter to the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   --Religious leaders of various faiths will be part of a
delegation of about 80 Massachusetts immigrants who will travel to
Washington on Friday to lobby Congress to support bills to soften
the effects of 1996 legislation that curtailed government benefits
for immigrants. The delegation is organized by the Massachusetts
Immigrant and Refugee Advocacy Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   --The Women's Ordination Conference, a progressive Roman
Catholic group based in Fairfax, Va., has released a national study
focusing on women who feel called to the priesthood. The Vatican
has said repeatedly that the priesthood is closed to women because
Jesus chose only men as his apostles. But Rome's stance has angered
many liberal Catholics, particularly in Western Europe and the
United States, who believe the church's position is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego Ribadeneira,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
