<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROTTING OUT OLD STEREOTYPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just before the US Open final between Martina Hingis and Serena
Williams, CBS's John McEnroe said: ``The Williams sisters are so
(itals)physically gifted(unitals). I mean particularly Serena, who
is just absolutely incredible to me. I mean I never, ever seen a
17-year-old girl, to be honest, I've rarely seen a 17-year-old guy
on the tennis circuit who looks as (itals)strong(unitals) as she
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's a very imposing task for Hingis. And what she
(Hingis) has done is (itals)worked hard and get herself(unitals)
stronger physically. She's incredible in the sense that she's a
step or two ahead of almost other human beings on the tennis court.
She sees things that most people don't, that virtually no one sees.
She's like a (itals)chessmaster(unitals) out there. She's a step or
two in front of what you're (itals)thinking(unitals) she's going to
come up with. She comes up with angles that are almost
unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe's colleague, Mary Carillo, added that Hingis, ``had to
get physically fitter because, she's so bright as John's been
saying, but you (itals)can't coach(unitals) someone to be four
inches taller.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus the stage was set, not just just between Williams and
Hingis, two young stars, but also for whether this would be another
disgusting display of racist stereotyping. It seemed that listeners
were doomed to hear that Williams was an uncoachable, born Amazon
while Hingis was the physically deficient but bright and
hard-working chessmaster.
</P>
<P>
   An hour and a half later, Serena Williams not only won the
championship, but respect for her hard work and brains.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the seventh seed in the tournament, defeated the
top-seeded and world's top-ranked woman, Hingis, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4).
Williams said afterward, ``I was really mentally tough out there. I
wouldn't give in to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams's deft placement of deep shots to the corners, and
crosscourt winners made believers out of the broadcasters. It is
important to note that her tough mind was not developed at preteen,
white-run tennis camps and the lonely, myopic junior circuit
littered with burnouts. It was developed at home by parents Richard
and Oracene, who kept Serena and her sister Venus away from the
pressure cooker until their mid-teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought I was a fool,'' Richard Williams said. ``But I
wanted them to get their education and know their history. Those
girls believe in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the match started, McEnroe, Carillo, and Bill Macatee began
believing that Serena Williams was more than just shoulders to die
for. Early in the first set, she hit the ball so well that McEnroe,
Carillo and Bill Macatee started talking about how ``confident''
she looked.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the first set, they began talking about her
``maturity.'' Noting how Williams had frozen Hingis with several
aces with a strategic placing of serves, Carillo said, Williams
``goes for for the 115s (115 mile-per-hour serves) largely down the
middle of the court where the net's 6 inches lower. Smart.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe said Williams played ``very intelligently, so far.''
This was a more conditional credit for intelligence, which hardly
compares to Hingis being called ``bright'' as a permanent state.
But at least McEnroe displayed a learning curve about Williams even
as he said Williams was ``learning quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   In a tense second set, the broadcasters were remarkable for
comments that did not distinguish between the two players. When
Williams played well, she ``hustled'' was ``very smart'' and had
``great technique.'' If she played poorly, she had ``lots of
nerves'' or was ``feeling the pressure.'' If Hingis played well,
she was ``very, very smart,'' ``dug deep'' or was ``plugging
away.'' If Hingis played poorly, she was ``not in charge,'' ``not
imposing herself'' or ``stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   Oracene Williams said ``In tennis, you have to have a head.
Anything mental will get to you.'' As Serena Williams went up 3-1
in the tie-breaker, McEnroe recognized for a last and critical time
that Williams indeed had a head. ``It appears Serena has weathered
the storm (itals)mentally(unitals). She's positive again. She's
(itals)forgotten(unitals) about it (an earlier, blown chance to win
the match).
</P>
<P>
   As Williams held the title trophy, she never received the
permanent attributes of intelligence that Hingis received. Nor was
Hingis ever described as ``physically gifted,'' even though it
should be obvious that the world's top player has to have
world-class reflexes. The broadcasters never mentioned, as did a
New York Times editorial, that Hingis, just like the Williams
sisters, hits her ground strokes with ``incredible power.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the match's end, Williams was no longer merely a born,
bronze Amazon. She was smart, hustled, displayed great technique,
and was a mental fighter. Given how sports broadcasters have in the
past degraded black athletes by praising only their physical gifts,
this was a pleasant advance. McEnroe, Carillo, and Macatee lost the
first part of their broadcast on stereotypes. But they rallied to a
second-set tiebreaker. Time will tell if they can win the second
set, weathering the storm of racist assumptions to tell us that
Serena Williams, like Hingis, is ``bright.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
