<HEADLINE>
JOSE MARIA OLAZABAL: COUNTER PUNCHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ This has been a breakthrough year for Jose
Maria Olazabal, but he knows it could have been much better if he
hadn't carried the concept to such literal extremes.
</P>
<P>
   In April, he put the capstone on one of the most remarkable
comebacks in the history of sports _ never mind just golf _ when he
captured his second Masters title, his first since it appeared he
might never walk again.
</P>
<P>
   But in June, Olazabal made himself eligible for yet another
comeback when he celebrated a first-round 75 in the US Open at
Pinehurst by smashing a wall in his hotel room and fracturing his
right hand. He missed the cut in the first four tournaments he
played after his latest convalescence _ the British Open, the Dutch
Open, the Buick Open, and the PGA Championship _ and he qualified
for his sixth European Ryder Cup berth largely on the strength of
April's storybook performance.
</P>
<P>
   Ever candid, Olazabal readily acknowledges that embarrassment
must share the centerfold with exhilaration in his 1999 yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great in the sense that I won a major event,'' he
says. ``But if you take that away, the second half of the year,
I've really struggled. I made a stupid mistake, and I've paid the
price for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Olazabal believes he is fully recovered (``the doctor said
it would take 6-8 weeks''), and he's optimistic again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some good tournaments left where I can
hopefully do better,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The big one is the Ryder Cup. At 33, Olazabal will be one of a
handful of veterans upon whom captain Mark James will rely against
the United States Sept. 24-26 at The Country Club in Brookline. So
as reckless and ridiculous as his latest ordeal may have been, it's
a snap compared with what he endured before _ and thought he might
have to endure for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat like this year, 1994 was an out-of-control elevator
ride for Olazabal. That April, he reached his career zenith when he
held off Tom Lehman down the stretch to win the Masters. While the
route to that grail wasn't as inspiring as this one, it was close
in implausibility.
</P>
<P>
   The son and grandson of greenskeepers, Olazabal had grown up
along the San Sebastien golf course in Fuenterrabia, Spain, where
he still lives. Despite his proximity to a 7,000-yard classroom,
Olazabal could find only one tutor. Himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, golf was not very popular in Spain,'' he says.
``The members only came on weekends. The rest of the time, I had
the whole course to myself. I learned the game on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   It took him a while to get started. He was all of 2 years old
when he first picked up a club, and at the advanced age of 5, he
made a major adjustment in his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played lefthanded when I began,'' he says. ``Then I switched
to righthanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise move. Olazabal developed into a junior prodigy, turned pro
at 19, and the following year, became a mainstay on the European
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   His game and fame went international with his Augusta triumph,
but before 1994 was done, he began experiencing something that can
be rather inconvenient for a golfer. He had trouble walking the
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw different doctors,'' he says. ``The situation got worse
and worse. I got a Ryder invitation in 1995, but I turned it down
because I wasn't physically fit.''
</P>
<P>
   That qualified as peak condition compared with the following
year, when Olazabal missed the entire season and golf became a
distant second priority to mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reached the point where I couldn't walk at all,'' he says.
``I figured that I was done, that I'd never have a chance to play
again.''
</P>
<P>
   He would have been happy for a chance to get out of bed again
when he finally consulted a Munich physician, Hans-Wilhelm
Muller-Wohlfahrt, who diagnosed the problem: rheumatoid
polyarthritis in both feet.
</P>
<P>
   It was debilitating but not incurable. Olazabal began working
with Muller-Wohlfahrt in September 1996, and by the following
February, he was back walking 18 holes a day for pay, in the Dubai
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still wasn't 100 percent,'' he says, ``but it was a start.''
</P>
<P>
   The culmination came this past April, and even his
self-inflicted setback can't tarnish his green jacket. He has
always placed intense emphasis on the Ryder Cup, and he helped
Europe retain it two years ago, but he can't help having a slightly
different perspective on the Brookline matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very sad if we lost,'' he says. ``But for me,
winning the Masters again was a major achievement. Nothing can top
that.''
</P>
<P>
   If he wins a third, at least he probably won't have to worry
about an excruciating aftermath. He's just about run out of
extremities to hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
