<HEADLINE>
CHINESE ARCHAEOLOGY EXHIBIT TO DISPLAY SOME 200 OBJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL CRAIG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A replica set of 65 ancient bells will ring Sept.
19 when a new exhibition of more than 200 archaeological treasures
from China opens at the National Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Golden Age of Chinese Archaeology'' is billed as a sequel
to the spectacular exhibition of Chinese archaeological discoveries
at the gallery 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That show resulted from the establishment of diplomatic
relations between the United States and China; the current
exhibition comes as signs from both nations point to a relaxation
of recent tensions.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, sponsored by the Eastman Kodak Co., will be at
the Gallery until Jan. 2. It will then be moved to the Museum of
Fine Arts in Houston for display from Feb. 13 through May 7, 2000,
and to The Asian Art Museum of San Francisco from June 17 through
Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The objects exhibited include 165 discovered since 1973 in tombs
and buried troves, selected by the guest curator for the
exhibition, Dr. Xiaoneng Yang of the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in
Kansas City, in cooperation with Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the exhibited objects _ which have never been
shown outside of China _ illustrate the achievements of Chinese
culture from 5000 B.C. to the tenth century A.D.
</P>
<P>
   They have demonstrated to scholars that Chinese civilization
advanced through a gradual blending of regional cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The works exhibited here represent great achievements in
Chinese archaeology,'' said Earl A. Powell III, National Gallery
director. ``The study of these works has made possible the
reconstruction in far greater detail than ever before the cultural
meaning of ancient works of art in their own time.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is arranged in historical sequence and includes
sculpture, ritual objects, furniture, coffins, textiles and
decorative objects made of clay, jade, stone, bamboo, ivory,
lacquer, gold, silver, bronze, glass and silk.
</P>
<P>
   Pictographs on two of the earliest ceramics are believed to be
forerunners of later Chinese writing.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more striking objects include sinister masks and a
standing figure from the 1300-1100 B.C. period, jade burial suits,
and six life-sized warriors from the 7,000-strong terra-cotta army
discovered in 1974 in the third century B.C. tomb of the ``first
emperor,'' Qin Shi Hwangdi.
</P>
<P>
   A strange, cranelike figure with deer antlers is one of a number
of prominent items from the fifth century B.C. tomb of the Marquis
Yi of Zeng, a small state south of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
   The bronze bells that will formally open the exhibit are
replicas of a set found in his tomb. Twelve Chinese musicians will
play traditional music on them and on other instruments from that
period in performances on Sept. 17 and 18, as well as at the
opening.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery's East Building is at Fourth Street and
Constitution Avenue in downtown Washington. It is open Monday
through Saturday from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. and on Sundays from 11 a.m.
to 6 p.m. Admission is free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
