<SLUG> BC-WOM-BUTCHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSAN BUTCHER: WIFE, MOTHER _ SLED-DOG RACER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ever a woman paid homage to her passion and purpose, musher
Susan Butcher did it when she named her newborn daughter after a
favorite dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned everything together,'' said Butcher of Tekla, the
beloved husky who was one of the first dogs she lovingly acquired
after arriving in Alaska in 1975 and going on to become a four-time
winner of the grueling 1,049-mile Iditarod dogsled race.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Butcher is learning everything anew with her
preschool daughter Margaretha Tekla, a lively 4-year-old known by
her middle name who is taking lessons in beadwork from an
Athabascan Indian and thinks everyone in the world has 100 dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is definitely living the childhood I wish I would have
lived,'' said Butcher, now 44, in a telephone interview from
Fairbanks, ``but I am absolutely positive she is not going to be a
dog musher. I'm expecting her to be as different from me as I am
different from my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Butcher was raised in Cambridge, Mass., attending
Buckingham Browne &AMP; Nichols School and knowing her way around
Harvard Square, it was always the country that sang to her heart
and animals that touched her soul. (As a first grader she wrote an
essay highlighted by the unambiguous phrase ``I hate the city.'')
First it was summers in Maine, where she could run with her
mixed-breed dog, Cabee; later, doing carpentry and farm work in
Nova Scotia; then on to a brief stint of veterinarian studies at
Colorado State University and finally, perhaps inevitably, on to
wide-open Alaska, where she has been living in spartan simplicity
for 25 years. No lines at the supermarket, no wailing sirens on
city streets, and if she's stuck behind two or three cars at a
stoplight in Fairbanks ``it's like, oh man, the traffic is heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those 25 years have been spent in Eureka, which is not
really a town but more like a few cabins near a river of the same
name about 150 road miles northeast of Fairbanks. In 1985, Butcher
married David Monson, a fellow dog sledder; they, along with Tekla,
still live there much of the year in a one-room, 15-by-19-square
foot cabin with no running water or electricity, eating their meals
in a separate cabin nearby because it's so small.
</P>
<P>
   In what is partly a concession to their daughter's needs, Monson
and Butcher recently built a house in Fairbanks _ complete with
kitchen, to Tekla's amazement _ in which they plan to live about
half the year when Tekla reaches school age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the schooling I'm worried about, it's the
socialization,'' said Butcher, pointing out there are ``zero
children'' in Eureka.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few other changes since Tekla was born, too.
Butcher, who competed in her first brutal Anchorage-to-Nome
Iditarod in 1978, set a record in 1990 when she finished in 11
days, 1 hour, 53 minutes and 23 seconds. In between, she became the
only person to win three years in a row with victories in 1986,
1987 and 1988; altogether she finished 15 times in the top 10. She
last attempted the race in 1994, the year before Tekla was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be a good mother and be a good Iditarod racer at the
same time, not to a young child,'' she stated flatly.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Butcher's legendary devotion to her dogs, and the
energy and single-mindedness it took to train them, 14 to 16 hours
a day, seven days a week, to run 1000-plus miles through the brutal
Alaskan wilderness, is not unlike that of a mother preparing her
child for the rigors of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just with the dogs 24 hours a day; the relationship you
have with them is just so intense,'' said Butcher of her Iditarod
years. ``To anybody's vision, looking at what I do now with the
dogs would say it's very intense, but I know the difference. Now
it's a job, concentrating training into eight hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Iditarod aside, Butcher has not disappeared from competitive
mushing. She still races at least 10 times a year in events from 10
to 500 miles (``shorter stuff,'' she calls it), and still raises
dogs at their Trail Breaker Kennels. And when Tekla is a little
older, Butcher plans to once again hit the trail that made her
famous; the trail on which a moose in 1985 attacked her team,
killing two of her dogs and knocking her out of the race; the trail
on which a musher is lucky to get two hours of sleep a day for two
weeks in temperatures that commonly plummet to 50 below.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much want to go back to it,'' she said. ``I miss it a
lot. All this other stuff is fun, but it's just playing around.
(During the Iditarod), you almost become one with (your dogs).
They're your workmates, your pets, your everything. It's something
almost indescribable to someone who hasn't experience what happens
during a race. You're depending on them, they're depending on you.
For your lives. You understand that, and they do, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Butcher was affecting other lives as well, blazing trails as
metaphorical as they were physical, but she thought little and
talked less about it at the time. She wanted to be accepted as a
musher, period.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the time it was happening I didn't look at it at all
and didn't think it was necessary to look at it at all,'' she
recalled. ``I was very aware that I was a woman and that this was a
big thing for women, but I didn't want to be given any special
treatment. I just wanted to be viewed as a musher.''
</P>
<P>
   She remembers once complaining to a girlfriend about how tired
she was of all the problems. Of course you're exhausted, the friend
said; you're opening doors on a daily basis. ``I went, oh,'' said
Butcher. ``I wasn't able to think of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she has a daughter, who already mushes with her own two-dog
team and speaks to them like a pro. (``She's very direct with
them,'' said Butcher. ``I crack up to hear her use my authoritative
voice with the dogs.'') And what she wants for her is not really so
different than what she wanted for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a moment that it wasn't a labor of love,'' she
said of the exhausting, often solitary years she spent readying her
dogs to race. ``That's my biggest dream for her, that she find her
passion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(On Wednesday, Sept. 15, Susan Butcher received the 1999 Pioneer
Award from the New England Women's Fund at its second-annual New
England Women's Sports Award Reception in Boston. In addition to
announcing the second class of inductees into its Hall of Fame, the
organization also honored sports reporter Lesley Visser with its
Media Award, Laurie Flutie with its Philanthropy Award and the New
England Blizzard basketball team with its New England Today Award.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
