<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2966 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     09-15 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLTS' MORA PRAISES BLEDSOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jim Mora finished looking at the tapes, he joined the Drew
Bledsoe bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as good as anyone in the league right now,'' said Mora,
the head coach of the Indianapolis Colts, who will be in Foxborough
Sunday trying to defend the Patriots' wide-open passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's young and at the peak of his game,'' Mora continued.
``The other quarterbacks (mentioned as being among the best) are
older and not as good as they used to be. This guy is making every
throw. I'm really impressed with the way he responds in clutch
situations. And he shows such great leadership on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put him together with the talent they have at wide
receiver and you have an exceptional pass game. It's one that can
eat up yardage in big chunks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts had a big win of their own Sunday, beating the highly
regarded Bills at home, 31-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a very good game and Buffalo did not play the way
they can play,'' said Mora. ``We are better as a team than we were
a year ago, but we are still not there yet. We have the makings of
a good team in the future if we can keep all of our key players,
but right now I still think all of the other teams in the division
have the edge on us.
</P>
<P>
   ``This division is the best in football, and I think everyone
has to be impressed with what Miami did Monday night. When you beat
Denver in Denver, the way they did, when Denver hadn't lost at home
in something like 24 games, then that is impressive. They are
probably the team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Mora's offense was playing better at the end of last year when
rookie Peyton Manning started to get a second look at some teams.
Manning has continued to progress and in a couple of years he and
Bledsoe may be hyped as the two best passers in the game. Manning
is helped this season by the addition of running back Edgerrin
James, the Colts' first pick in the draft, and a better defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where we have made the most progress,'' said Mora. ``On
defense. I brought in Vic Fangio to be my defensive coordinator and
he has done a fine job. We're much more aggressive on defense than
we have been. Then we picked up some players in free agency on the
defensive side who were better than the ones we were playing with a
year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest surprise in the upset of the Bills was Doug
Flutie being sacked five times. Flutie was sacked just 12 times in
13 games last year, so the Colts' new defense has the capability of
rushing the passer better than it did a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bills running back Thurman Thomas was hurt on the first play of
the game when he jumped to catch a high pass from Flutie and was
rocked by cornerback Ty Poole. Thomas was hit head-on in the ribs,
bruising his kidney, and is out six weeks. Flutie apologized to him
after the game for throwing such a poor pass and exposing him to
injury. Thomas said he never saw Poole coming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of the hurricane off the east coast of Florida, the
Dolphins had to land in Fort Myers, on the west coast of the state,
at 6 a.m. following their big win over Denver Monday night, then
take a two-hour bus ride back to Miami. Coach Jimmy Johnson gave
the players the day off Tuesday, and most of them used it to
prepare their homes for the storm. Johnson himself headed for
nearby Williams Island, where he has his boat docked, to remove
anything of value from it. Rookie Rob Konrad, of Syracuse and North
Andover, did a good job for the Dolphins, catching a touchdown
pass, running well inside tackle when he had the chance, and
blocking for the tailbacks. ``All in all, considering it was my
first game, I was pleased,'' said Konrad, who was hunkered down in
his apartment waiting out the hurricane. ``I was very nervous
before the game. I looked at game film in our hotel during the
afternoon, and that made me more nervous. Maybe I should have
watched TV and relaxed. But when I got to the pregame warmup, I
started to feel better. The atmosphere was electric. Monday night
football. Retiring John Elway's jersey. All during the week, Dan
(Marino) was telling me to stay calm and stay patient. He said the
same thing in the game. I caught that touchdown pass in the first
half and that was great. They blitzed two defensive backs, and one
covered me coming out of the backfield. After I caught the ball and
turned around, there was no one there and I started to prance. When
I got to the end zone, I gave it a big-time spike. I waited a long
time for that. We weren't allowed to do that at Syracuse.'' Konrad
gave himself a grade of ``B to B minus'' for the game. It had to be
a wonderful start to his NFL career. Beating the defending
champions on their home field in your first game. It doesn't get
much better than that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denver linebacker Bill Romanowski said the Miami running game
was the difference. ``A year ago when we beat them (in the
playoffs), they couldn't run the ball on us. This game they did.''
Miami overpowered Denver at the line of scrimmage. The Broncos set
their defense to stop the passing of Marino but had to adjust when
Miami consistently moved the ball on the ground. Then Marino hurt
Denver with play-action passing, which also reduced the pass rush.
Marino's ability to get rid of the ball quickly under pressure
stymied any hope the Broncos had of blitzing him successfully . . .
Some Dolphins left Denver with the impression that Terrell Davis is
injured more than the Broncos are letting on. Davis hurt his
shoulder in preseason and reportedly had two MRIs. Davis carried
the ball just 19 times for 61 yards, and when Miami had built a
substantial lead early in the fourth period, coach Mike Shanahan
took Davis out of the game. Denver is not the same team when Davis,
the best runner in the league, is not controlling things on the
ground . . . The Jets' situation is even worse than it appears.
Starting quarterback Vinny Testaverde is gone for the season. So is
No. 2 runner Leon Johnson, who spelled Curtis Martin in certain
situations and returned punts. Pro Bowl receiver Wayne Chrebet
won't be back for at least five weeks. Nose tackle Jason Ferguson,
their best defensive lineman, is out six weeks with ankle and knee
injuries. And they still don't know when tight end Eric Green, who
hurt his neck Sunday, will be able to play.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
