<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 443 -- Sept. 15, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. ALMODOVAR AND HIS WOMEN When Pedro Almodovar learned that the
Hollywood Madam, Heidi Fleiss, once employed a prostitute who went
by the name of Norma Jean Almodovar, he was amused. (And before
that, the woman worked for the police.) Only in Almodovar's
strangely ordered universe would a cop-turned-whore seem honest.
Nearly all of Almodovar's films since his 1980 feature debut are
populated with transsexuals, porn stars, drag queens,
sadomasochists and drug addicts. It's the unconventional subject
matter - freaky characters, sex, drugs - that has helped ensure the
success of his movies in the United States. By Jonathan Van Meter.
From The New York Times Magazine. 1,800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
WHAT'S DOING IN HONOLULU While autumn is the low season for travel
to Honolulu - the wallflower period of the year - savvy travelers
await the benefits lurking in the aftermath of the frenzied summer.
This is also the time when the Aloha Festivals sweep the islands
with more than 300 events, from parades to a Royal Ball. By Jocelyn
Fujii. From The New York Times Way To Go! 1,800 words + photos +
map. _____________________________________________________________
3. HAIR AND NAIL SALONS MAY SPREAD DEADLY VIRUSES Nail and hair
salons may be a source of blood-borne as well as other infectious
diseases. There is good evidence that standard disinfection isn't
doing the trick and razors, nail files, scissors, tatoo needles and
body piercing instruments are risk factors for transmitting
hepatitis B and C and HIV. By Charles Downey. 1,150 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
PORTRAIT OF GOETHE On the 250th anniversary of Goethe's birth, does
this legendary literary figure have anything to offer us? An
indulgent attitude to past errors, a sane optimism and an
un-Teutonic worldliness. By John Armstrong. From Prospect Magazine.
(N/A U.K.) 4,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
HEMINGWAY'S BRIDGE On Ernest Hemingway's centenary, Richard Barry
goes in search of the bridge in Spain that Robert Jordan blew up in
``For Whom the Bell Tolls.'' Was it fact or fiction? From Prospect
Magazine. (N/A U.K.) 1,500 words.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   6. FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   (a) DESIGNER DRUG : A designer drug that shuts down a gene
associated with cancer protection may make cancer treatment easier
to tolerate. 400 words.
</P>
<P>
   (b) CANCER RISKS : Different ways of portraying risks among
scientists, journalists and environmentalists lead to much of the
public confusion over their chances of developing cancer, according
to one expert. 400 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo 19h00 BST,
Sept. 15)
</P>
<P>
   (a) INSIDE COCAINE ADDICTIONS Drug addicts trying hard to break
their addiction can take comfort from new lines of work showing
that it is not weakness of resolve that makes cracking the habit so
tough - it is their genes. By Henry Gee. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   (b) HOW PRIONS GET PLEATED Creutzfeld-Jacob disease in humans
and BSE in cows occurs when a normal protein, 'prion protein,'
somehow folds abnormally - but what causes this prion pleating? By
Valerie Depraetere. 400 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Australia, New Zealand, Brazil)
</P>
<P>
   (a) The Bigger Picture : Flying could be child's play with a
head-up display that taps in pilots' peripheral vision. Its
inventors say that the display could do away with conventional
instrument panels altogether.
</P>
<P>
   (b) It's A Pig's Life : Pig-to-human transplants have the
potential to reverse the worldwide shortfall of 180,000 organs. But
even if the remaining scientific hurdles are cleared, patients may
face social exile as a precondition for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   (c) Pure And Clear : Genetically modified bacteria are the
latest weapon in the battle against mercury pollution. The bugs
soak up toxic metal from contaminated water and could also clean up
industrial waste. 500 words.
_____________________________________________________________
