<P>
   In connection with Hurricane Floyd, The New York Times News
Service plans these stories:
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-RDP (Dateline to kum) _ Ledeall: Hurricane Floyd moves
closer to the Southeast, sending wind-whipped rain through
Florida's deserted streets and leaving coastal residents from
Georgia to Virginia bracing for a more severe thrashing. The
storm's eye was expected to continue to swirl over the Atlantic
before hitting land Thursday near Wilmington, N.C. In a weakened
form, it could still complicate the lives of residents all the way
up to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-FLORIDA (Jacksonville, Fla.) _ Florida averts disaster
and newscasters are left talking about blowing palm trees. By Rick
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-FEMA (Washington) _ The federal emergency management
team faces its gravest test in this massive hurricane. By Irvin
Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-BEACHES (Undated) _ Development along the North
Carolina beaches has made evacuation a much more involved and
time-consuming process. By Cornelia Dean.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-BAHAMAS (Nassau, Bahamas) _ What the hurricane wrought
in the one place it has struck land so far. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NJ (Dateline to kum, N.J.) _ On the New Jersey coast,
preparations and fears for Floyd's possible visit. By Paul
Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY (New York) _ New York City and the surrounding
region brace for possible heavy flooding. By David W. Chen.
</P>
