</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Consumer prices rose moderately again in
August as roaring domestic consumption continued to put only faint
pressure on prices. The Labor Department reported that the Consumer
Price Index rose 0.3 percent for the second consecutive month,
matching forecasts. Excluding a 2.7 percent jump in energy costs
and a 0.2 percent increase in food prices, the CPI came in below
expectations, rising 0.1 percent during August. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   YEN-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column: The dollar
is falling against the yen. What does it mean for the United States
economy, and Japan's? By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   HEINZ-BESTFOODS (Undated) _ Folo reports that H.J. Heinz and
Bestfoods are in merger talks. Bestfoods issues a statement saying
that it is not holding ``significant acquisition or combination
discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONES-911 (Washington) _ The FCC is requiring all makers of
cell phones to install global satellite or other technology that
will enable emergency rescue teams to pinpoint within about 300
meters anyone dialing 911. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-TALKS (Detroit) _ Monitoring the progress of the auto
negotiations: Talks between the UAW and DaimlerChrysler continue;
wildcat strikes at five DaimlerChrysler plants on Tuesday night
have ended. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-VISIO (Undated) _ Microsoft plans to buy Visio Corp.,
a maker of technical drawing software and Powerpoint competitor,
for $1.3 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-GENERAL (Chicago) _ Motorola Inc., as expected, agrees
to buy General Instrument in a stock deal valued at about $11
billion. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:45 p.m., stocks were slightly lower.
The Dow Jones industrial average was down 15 points, the S&AMP;P 500
down 6 points and the Nasdaq composite index down 32 points. The
30-year bond was priced to yield 6.11 percent. European markets
were lower, with London down 1.09 percent and Frankfurt down 0.26
percent. Hong Kong stocks fell 2.71 percent. The Tokyo market was
closed in observance of a national holiday, Respect for the Aged
Day. The dollar stood at 104.2 yen and at 1.0380 euro. By Robert D.
Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
