<HEADER>
A2994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-SPOT-BJT16-COX     09-15 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, Sept. 16,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE FLOYD
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-MAIN _ Main news story on Hurricane Floyd. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/ FLOYD-COAST _ Scene wrap of what is happening along the coast
that doesn't make the main. Is Tybee Island near Savannah under
water, as suggested was possible? How's the lighthouse at St.
Simons? Did the storm surge rush up the Savannah River and
rechristen River Street? (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-EVACUATE _ Will there be another wave of evacuations
today? How are road conditions? Stories of strife or heroes
emerging? Will those who stopped in middle Georgia shelters on
Tuesday try to head farther north. May wrap scenes from shelters.
(Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-FORECAST _ Short box on what kind of weather follows this
storm as the clean up begins. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-HOSPITALS _ As Savannah and environs clear out, hospital
patients are being moved, too. From neonatal cases (which went to
the Medical College of Georgia) to the elderly, patients are being
sent north and west from coastal Georgia. Augusta hospitals are
overwhelmed. And, one of the problems is that staff from the other
hospitals do not come with the patients. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-INSURANCE _ Tips on reporting storm damage, dealing with
your insurance company, etc. (Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-SHELTERS _ Early indications are that the Red Cross and
GEMA didn't match up too well on getting the shelters stocked and
opened before people got there. Problems were especially apparent
in middle Georgia, from Macon to Dublin. (Jones/Osinski, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-FLA _ The storm. Even though Hurricane Floyd essentially
missed Florida, it triggered what may be the biggest evacuation in
history. Hundreds of thousands fled _ and are still fleeing -_ in
Florida, Georgia and the Carolinas, where they are braced for
impact expected Thursday morning. It's still a monster storm and
whatever it hits will be hurt. In Tallahassee, emergency managers
say they pretty much knew yesterday afternoon that it wouldn't hit
Florida, but they didn't want to call back hundreds of thousands
jamming I-10 and other highways and send them back because what if
it wobbled back left? The agony of when to leave and when not to
leave strikes again. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-FLADAMAGE16 Wrap of the damage. Beach erosion, property
damage, death, destruction? Start right away assessing damage to
public and private property; going out with inspectors. How about
all those big Boca homes going up in Delray Beach. Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-FLAECONOMY _ What was the economic impact of the storm,
everything from Home Depot's increased sales, full hotels, etc.
(SSmith, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-INTERNET _ ATLANTA _A look at how the internet has evolved
into a more sophisticated emergency tool with each disaster.
Mention various websites and check how email traffic and chat room
talk has increased. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VETO _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and congressional
leaders plan a large, elaborate ceremony Thursday to veto the GOP
tax-cut plan. The event likely is only the first of several vetoes
in coming weeks, and illustrates how the power of the pen is
putting Clinton, a year ago seemingly in danger of imminent removal
from office, in position to once again best Congress in a battle
over tax and spending policy. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RILEY-EDUCATION _ WASHINGTON - Education Secretary Richard Riley
delivers his annual ``state of education'' address Wednesday at a
National Press Club luncheon. lede uncertain. (Mollison, Cox News
Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   TESTS-LATINOS _ WASHINGTON - Some states and school districts
that use high-stakes tests to decide whether students can advance
to a higher grade or graduate from high school use them in a way
that discriminates against Latino students who are still learning
English, according to a report released and discussed here
Wednesday by Clinton's official Presidential Commission on
Educational Excellence for Hispanic Americans. The report is said
to identify ``unacceptable practices'' and offer ``guidance for
effective policies.'' (Mollison, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-BUSINESS _ WASHINGTON _ A day after the State Department on
Wednesday issues its list of countries that travelers should avoid
because of Y2K concerns, a look at what the list means for
Americans working abroad and business travel. (Geewax, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial catyegories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   STRAY911 _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Like many people who want a prompt
response, Jay T. McCarty added a 911 after his phone number on the
page he sent his girlfriend near dawn on Aug. 29. The three digits
somehow resulted in a phone call to the Palm Beach Police
Department. Officers arriving at the ground-floor Hammon Avenue
apartment from which McCarty had called found McCarty with crack
pipes and other drug paraphernalia, as well as a 12-gauge shotgun
and .22-caliber rifle, both loaded. (Schusler, Palm Beach Daily
News).
</P>
<P>
   GHB _ ATLANTA _ Teens use gamma hydroxybutyrate (GHB) as a party
drug. GHB developed as an anesthetic but never approved for use in
U.S. It was being sold to weightlifters in 80s and 90s as a muscle
booster and sleep aid til FDA banned sales. Chemists changed a few
components to slip through the law, and substances with same active
ingredients still available, or its easily cooked at home thanks to
availability of chemicals and internet instructions. Common
overdoses, including a recent one in alpharetta where a 17-year-old
girl went into respiratory arrest after sipping some while hanging
out with friends. they got the substance at a health food store,
where it is being sold still as a solvent and labeled ``not for
human consumption. FDA says they have trouble controlling the
substance because it is not illegal to make or sell, only to sell
it as a drug or food supplement. If it's labeled as a solvent, you
can buy and sell all you want. (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED..
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   UN-SUPPORT _ One of the goals of Ted Turner's U.N. Foundation is
to build more support for the United Nations. That may not be an
easy task. The U.N. is under fire in some circles in America, which
is already far behind in its dues payments. And the Clinton
administration has often seemed to circumvent the organization. As
the U.N. General Assembly begins a new session and a new U.S.
ambassador begins his duties, we talk with Atlanta-based experts
about the issues confronting the organization and what is needed to
rebuild support. (Graham/Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
