<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, Sept. 16:
</P>
<P>
   GIANT-CANE (Undated) _ Nobody can remember the exact moment the
giant cane, Arundo donax, went from being a nuisance to a state of
emergency, but the day it lifted up a bridge in Norco, Calif.,
might do for starters. The magnificent, 30-foot plant has been used
for everything from fencing by the Spanish conquerors to an
ornamental garden grass. But over 20 years, it has muscled out the
native cottonwoods and willows that once thrived along the banks of
the Santa Ana. Slurping up nutrients pouring into the river from
seven tertiary sewer plants, arundo can grow 7 inches a day. By
Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TREE-STUDIOS (Chicago) _ Barton Faist is a soft-spoken artist
who is battling to save his studio and home here in Tree Studios, a
wondrous amalgam of gables, carved heads, stained-glass windows and
chiseled aphorisms, a project dreamt up by a turn-of-the-century
philanthropist for struggling artists. The owners have been trying
for 17 years to sell the increasingly valuable property to
developers. This week, fearing the result of this relentless clash
of new and old, the World Monuments Fund named Tree Studios one of
the world's 100 most endangered places, right next to Machu Picchu
in Peru and the Valley of the Kings near Luxor, Egypt. By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-LIGHTSHOW (London) _ It's called Excessive Sensual
Indulgence, Isabella Blow said, gleefully cranking up the
electronic sequencer that regulates the pulsating fountain-shaped
light sculpture in the Vampire Room of her new house in London's
Waterloo. By day, nothing about the conventional Georgian facade of
the former artisan's cottage Ms. Blow shares with her husband,
Detmar Blow, an art dealer, prepares visitors for the blazing
modernity of the interior nor the eccentricity of its inhabitants.
By night, however, passers-by are often startled by the merrily
demented light show emanating from the curtainless ground-floor
windows, creating the impression that the house is throbbing with
pleasure. By Christopher Mason.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BOULEY-DANUBE (New York) _ Tastefulness is not something David
Bouley is used to worrying about. On the plate, it hasn't been a
problem for the chef and owner of the four-star Bouley Bakery. But
Bouley is standing in the vestibule of his new 3,800 square foot
restaurant, Danube, worried about the Brazilian granite that he
thinks look like Gustav Klimt paintings, the 3,000 copper leaves
that canopy the gold-leafed ceiling like the Secessionists' dome in
Vienna and every other detail of the $1.8 million dollar
establishment, opening here on Monday. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   NARROW-SEATS (Boston) _ When the Boston Red Sox announced the
long awaited and highly controversial plan to replace venerable
Fenway Park, the team made much of the deficiencies of the old
ballpark. At the top of the list, the most criticized feature of
the old stadium, was the narrow seats. ``In our surveys, seating
was the largest single issue for fans who come to more than three
games a year,'' said Kathryn St. John, a spokeswoman for the Red
Sox. ``When the park was full, people were literally overflowing
their seats.'' In the new stadium, fans will enjoy an 18- or
19-inch seat instead of a 14- or 15-inch one. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
