<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-PRESIDENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD PRESIDENT TO STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Saying it is time for a ``season of refreshment
and renewal,'' Stanford University President Gerhard Casper
announced his resignation as head of one of the top universities in
the nation after seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work of the university is work that cannot be done unless
it is continuously reconsidered,'' Casper said in a statement. ``I
believe it is about time to bring fresh perspectives to bear on the
president's office.''
</P>
<P>
   Casper, 61, announced his decision to step down next summer at a
Tuesday meeting of department chairs. The constitutional law
scholar said he will leave his position in August to take a
sabbatical and then return to Stanford to teach undergraduate
classes. The university's Board of Trustees will appoint a search
committee to choose Casper's successor.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been credited with a number of accomplishments
during his tenure, Casper announced his retirement amid criticism
over the problem-plagued merger of Stanford's teaching hospital
with UCSF hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   When the hospital system's top two officials resigned last
month, Casper joined UC President Richard Atkinson in asking their
staffs to come up with a plan to restructure the 2-year-old UCSF
Stanford Health Care system by Oct. 1. The joint venture predicts
losses of $60 million for this year.
</P>
<P>
   UC Regent Frank Clark, who opposed the merger, said he was
``absolutely overwhelmed and shocked'' by Casper's resignation.
Clark said he has the highest respect for Casper, who he said was
never a vociferous supporter of the merger before the Board of
Regents.
</P>
<P>
   Casper barely addressed the merger issue in his resignation
statement, but he vowed to devote much of his last year as
president to Stanford's relationship with UCSF ``in the expectation
that shortly we will determine our future course.''
</P>
<P>
   Casper leaves Stanford under considerably less scrutiny than his
predecessor, Donald Kennedy, who resigned in 1991 amid embarrassing
allegations that the university had overbilled the federal
government by as much as $300 million for carrying out research
projects. University officials denied the overbilling but paid back
some of the money.
</P>
<P>
   When he became Stanford's ninth president in 1992, Casper
immediately set out to repair its reputation. He pushed the Justice
Department to conclude its two- year investigation and sought ways
to wean the university from government research grants.
</P>
<P>
   Turning his attention to the campus, he oversaw the repair and
retrofit of buildings that were damaged or threatened by the 1989
Loma Prieta earthquake and focused on developing new guidance
programs to help undergraduates and students applying to the
university.
</P>
<P>
   Casper's call for a re-examination of the undergraduate program
shortly after he took office sparked considerable debate and led to
a crackdown on grade inflation, tougher language requirements and
more stringent science requirements for many students.
</P>
<P>
   Before arriving at Stanford, Casper was provost at the
University of Chicago from 1989 to 1992. From 1979 to 1987, he was
dean of its law school. He had joined Chicago's Law School faculty
in 1966 after two years as an assistant professor of political
science at UC- Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Casper earned $375,622 in salary and benefits last year, placing
him 10th overall among the nation's university presidents,
according to the Stanford Daily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
