<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRIEST-SUED-HNS &LR;      09-15 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-SUED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC DIOCESE SUES DEFROCKED PRIEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service)  
 c.1999 ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco has filed
suit against Monsignor Patrick O'Shea, a defrocked Roman Catholic
priest who has also been accused of molesting altar boys and other
children.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accused O'Shea _ former pastor of Holy Name of Jesus
Church _ of embezzlement and fraud and demanded the return of a
quarter-million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   During a 16-year span, O'Shea, 66, ``engaged in a continuous and
sophisticated fraudulent scheme of embezzlement and conversion of .
. . funds,'' the suit alleged.
</P>
<P>
   O'Shea would open ostensibly legitimate church bank accounts,
then channel money to his own use, buying property and paying debts
while falsifying financial reports to the archdiocese, the suit
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, which accused O'Shea of stealing nearly $252,000,
was filed last week in San Francisco Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   In its suit, the archdiocese said that O'Shea last year formed a
``restitution trust'' which calls for the assets, totaling
$187,000, to go to the local church when he dies. The archdiocese
wants to attach the funds of the trust which it said ``serves as an
acknowledgement of O'Shea's indebtedness.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit also demanded an accounting and repayment of all money
owed by O'Shea, who was ordained in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese's suit said ``there is substantial danger'' that
O'Shea might revoke the trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   O'Shea's civil attorney, Joseph O'Sullivan, said the lawsuit is
barred by the three-year statute of limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are alleging that in 1995 they believed there was a
conversion of funds. They have to act within three years,''
O'Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the primary motivation for the church's suit was to gain
access to the trust fund. ``The trust fund says if, in fact,
Monsignor O'Shea (were) found to be criminally liable, there would
be money to cover it . . . Now the church is trying to circumvent
the criminal process,'' O'Sullivan said. ``They are trying to use
this lawsuit as the vehicle to take the money.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco attorney John Christian, who is representing the
church in the lawsuit, declined comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   O'Shea was permanently stripped of his priestly duties in 1995,
following numerous allegations that the had sexually molested boys.
In 1996, the San Francisco district attorney's office charged him
with 11 counts of grand theft and filing false tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   In the criminal complaint, prosecutors alleged that O'Shea
diverted money into at least eight secret accounts in three San
Francisco banks. The money was allegedly used to maintain a home in
Indian Wells, an expensive community near Palm Springs, Calif., and
in property at Lake Berryessa in Solano County, as well as for
other personal uses.
</P>
<P>
   Those charges are pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1447EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
