<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3048 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-JEDEDIAHPURDY-BOOK-2n     09-15 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEDEDIAHPURDY-BOOK-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: being cynical. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Harvard, the Times story notes, Purdy was outraged at the
freshman class custom of sitting together for a showing of ``Love
Story'' and shouting insults at the characters onscreen. How could
anyone make light of the lead character's cancer, Purdy wanted to
know. How could such disrespect for human suffering exist? It
evidently never crossed his mind that fellow freshmen were mocking
a very bad movie, not a disease.
</P>
<P>
   That is part of the reason ``For Common Things'' fails as real
philosophy. It is, instead, wordy prattle dispensed by someone who
wants to tell the common herd how to change without ever sharing,
even momentarily, the herd's perspective. How can Jedediah know
what they think when, by his own admission, he did his best not to
interact with them?
</P>
<P>
   The other reason Purdy falls short is that, although he decries
the derivativeness of politicians and TV show preachers, he does
exactly what he doesn't want them doing. There is nothing unique
about a political candidate or an ambitious philosopher stating the
obvious: The world is in bad shape, and it could be better. This
basic theme harks back to, say, George Wallace in 1968 asking
dissatisfied taxpayers to ``send a message'' to Washington's
``pointy-headed bureaucrats'' without ever explaining why electing
George Wallace president would be a message effective enough to
bring about positive change.
</P>
<P>
   Purdy asks us to make a bad world better by caring more but
doesn't demonstrate how caring more can be translated into specific
action. Oh, there are generalizations: Compassion, he notes, is not
feeling sorry for someone, but trying to help someone. But help
how, Jed? Details are nice.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Knopf's publicity campaign, and a lot of the praise
generated in positive reviews about ``For Common Things,'' focus on
Purdy's age. It is true; few 24-year-olds could write such a book,
let alone demonstrate the vocabulary and reading habits of Jedediah
Purdy. If his philosophy fails, then his youth ought to be enough
to place him beyond critical contempt, some seem to believe.
</P>
<P>
   But the unsubtle message is that no young man has ever achieved
such literary/philosophic heights before, and that's simply not
true. In precosity Purdy is among the elite but is not the elite's
one-man roster. William F. Buckley, the conservative to whom Purdy
has (so far) most often been compared, wrote ``God and Man at
Yale'' when he was 26 and founded the prestigious National Review
magazine just a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   Purdy isn't the youngest college student to write and publish a
book that got national attention. James Simon Kunen was 19 when
``The Strawberry Statement'' chronicled his role in the Columbia
University student riots of 1968, when Kunen was an 18-year-old
freshman. Windy, condescending and painfully sincere, ``The
Strawberry Statement'' was turned into a very bad movie, but Kunen
couldn't be blamed for that. He has since written a couple of other
near-forgotten books, and recently wrote some articles for
Newsweek. But he didn't change the world, although he made clear in
``The Strawberry Statement'' that this was his intention.
</P>
<P>
   Purdy isn't even the youngest Harvard ex to make a literary
impression. Cotton Mather was admitted to Harvard at the ripe old
age of 12, and subsequently, ``The Oxford Companion to American
Literature'' notes, ``was justifiably considered a prig by his
fellows.''
</P>
<P>
   Post-graduation, Mather became an author and minister. By the
time he was Purdy's age, he was churning out titles like ``Relating
to Witchcraft and Possessions,'' with his chief message that
Americans must abandon modern hedonism and return to the simpler
moral values of their forefathers. Mather ended up delighting at
the Salem witch trials _ unsurprising, since he entered Harvard in
1675.
</P>
<P>
   So, with ``For Common Things,'' Jedediah Purdy proves he is not
unique, either as a philosopher or child prodigy. He is, in fact,
derivative.
</P>
<P>
   There's irony in that, but also potential _ which shouldn't be
ignored, even though ``For Common Things'' makes you want to chide
the kid rather than shake his hand. ``For Common Things'' is
obviously sincere, written by a young person who is intellectually
gifted. With a little more experience in the real world, Purdy may
have something of value to offer besides the pleasant, not terribly
unique wish that we would all work together and build a better
society.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
