<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3049 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-JEDEDIAHPURDY-BOOK-10     09-15 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEDEDIAHPURDY-BOOK-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURDY-OTHERS) 
24-YEAR-OLD AUTHOR TELLS US TO SHED OUR IRONIC ATTITUDE AND
CALLOUSNESS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by JEDEDIAH PURDY-INTERVIEW and JEDEDIAH(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jedediah Purdy is the stuff legends are made of _ and marketing
campaigns, too.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years old, first home-schooled by farmer-parents in
West Virginia and then whisked off to Harvard via the tony Exeter
prep school, young Jed, as he's affectionately called by relatives
and publicists, snagged a book contract with Alfred A. Knopf, one
of the more prestigious publishers.
</P>
<P>
   In between Harvard matriculation and his current enrollment at
Yale, where he's studying ``law, environment and values,'' Jed
churned out a 207-page book titled ``For Common Things: Irony,
Trust and Commitment in America Today.'' The author fervently hopes
in his copious introduction that the book will ``turn our attention
to essential and neglected things,'' namely losing the irony that
separates us emotionally from commitment to making our world a
better place.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Common Things'' has engendered uncommon response: The New
York Times Magazine recently devoted a four-page spread to Jed and
his book; all the prestigious magazines and newspapers are
reviewing it, albeit arriving at mixed opinions. (''Inspiring'' is
the positive, minority opinion; ``pompous'' is the negative
majority verdict, with ``overwritten college term paper'' a close
second.) Jed either has been or will be seen on network morning
talk shows, with a good dollop of appearances on the best cable
programs.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks on store shelves, the book has met uneven sales,
too. Purdy's appearances on TV spiked Internet sales _ ``For Common
Things'' hovers between Nos. 135 and 150 on amazon.com's bestseller
list, with a high around 35 _ but walk-in store shoppers don't seem
as enthusiastic. An informal check of three major Fort Worth area
bookstores last week indicated that they have collectively sold
fewer than a dozen copies.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the irony of Jedediah Purdy writing a book decrying
marketing schlock and then having himself and his book become the
center of a national marketing campaign, it is possible _
necessary, really _ to decide how, its near-overwhelming
earnestness aside, ``For Common Things'' really measures up as the
philosophy it purports to be. Both praise for and attacks on ``For
Common Things'' center on two specific issues: its theme and its
author. Theme, of course, ought to be most important, though
Jed-bashers prefer calling him names to weighing what he wants to
tell the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, ``For Uncommon Things'' is a call for readers to stop
distancing themselves from commitment _ emotional, social,
political. For many reasons, Purdy argues, we've learned that ``not
caring'' is the best way to protect ourselves from disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are skeptical, ironic, and inclined to an impoverished
self-reliance,'' he writes in an early chapter. ``At the same time,
we want to give up the ironist's jaded independence and believe
that we are not alone, that we can find moral communities, clear
obligations and even miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdy's most obvious failing is overuse of an impressive
vocabulary. Many very intelligent people go through their entire
lives without once using the word ``jejune;'' Purdy includes it in
the first paragraph of his book. ``(Jejune,'' by the way, means
``dull'' or ``ordinary.'') He writes not with engaging rhythm, but
with an annoying habit of overselling his ideas. Where one media
example of social commitment to irony would do _ yes, Jed,
``Seinfeld'' was a signal that not all was well with America _ he
can't help tossing in many more examples, potty-mouth TV cartoon
``South Park'' included.
</P>
<P>
   Purdy also likes to recall his idyllic childhood; eager to raise
their children away from modern society, his parents moved to the
West Virginia hills in 1974 ``to pick out a small corner of the
world and make it sane,'' according to their son. He and his sister
were taught without specific subjects and lesson plans, encouraged
to jump into adult conversations and learn from the low-key world
around them.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Jed did have to try high school, and it didn't work.
He admits he was unprepared for teen-age society. When, in ``For
Common Things,'' Purdy describes the cynic as someone who stays
home from parties while thinking he is better than those who
decided to go, it's impossible not to imagine Jed doing just that,
turning down an invitation and staying home, while all the other
kids laughed and danced and drank beer on the sly. But Jed, of
course, wouldn't say he was being cynical.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
