<HEADER>
A3067 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-15 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT WORK, BEING ADAPTABLE IS CRUCIAL TO SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an old joke about two campers who notice a bear slowly
approaching. While they're watching the bear, one of the men grabs
his tennis shoes and begins putting them on.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing that for?'' his friend asks. ``No tennis
shoes in the world are going to let you run faster than a bear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to run faster than the bear,'' he replies. ``I
just have to run faster than you.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know how someone becomes a star at work, think
about the man in the tennis shoes. He isn't necessarily faster or
smarter than his friend (now known as Bear Chow). He's just more
adaptable.
</P>
<P>
   Most workers are like Bear Chow, and think that being a star is
like trying to outrun a bear. They think you either have to have
incredible skills or work long hours, sacrificing your life for the
sake or work. Or they believe they are already stars _ and get a
real jolt when the layoff notices arrive.
</P>
<P>
   But a couple of recent books _ Robert Kelley's ``''How to be a
Star at Work'' and ``First Hired, Last Fired,'' by Robert M.
Bramson and Susan J. Bramson _ say that although top performers
certainly have good technical skills, they owe most of their
success to smart work habits.
</P>
<P>
   They also make it clear that it's about focusing on the right
issues, not spending your life in the office. In researching their
book, the Bramsons found that none of the people identified by
bosses as ``indispensable'' worked particularly long hours unless
special circumstances required it.
</P>
<P>
   Here are five qualities that help to separate the best workers
from everyone else:
</P>
<P>
   _ Understanding other people's perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   The camper with the tennis shoes looked at the situation from
the bear's perspective, and saw that the faster runner would become
the less-desirable entree.
</P>
<P>
   Mediocre bosses overlook this. They hand down decisions without
understanding how they will make subordinates' lives more
difficult, limiting the chance that workers will buy into the
program.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing can happen with top managers. They will
thoroughly analyze a plan among themselves but not even think about
getting ideas from rank-and-filers. Or, if they do talk with
subordinates, they'll be concerned with getting their point across,
not listening to other perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   People who work hard tend to think they're wonderful workers.
But think about your boss's perspective: Is there anything that
makes you better than the other 25 people who have similar jobs?
Has the boss made it clear that you stand out, either through words
or choice assignments?
</P>
<P>
   Suppose the boss gets an angry call and passes it on to you. A
lot of workers might solve the caller's problem, but the best ones
know that it probably doesn't end there. If you were the boss,
wouldn't you want to know that the problem had been resolved? If it
appeared that you screwed up, but you really didn't, shouldn't the
boss know that? And if you did screw up, shouldn't you apologize?
</P>
<P>
   The same thing is true for bosses. When you learn something,
think about whether it would make other people's lives easier if
you told them right away. One particularly bad habit bosses can get
into is to say something like this on a Friday: ``I want everybody
in the office at 10 a.m. Monday. There are some serious problems we
need to discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   What you've done is ruin everybody's weekend. You know what the
problems are, but the workers don't _ and everyone who cares tends
to personalize these things.
</P>
<P>
   If a subordinate offers an idea, respond to it. If you
stonewall, it's true that the proposal will slowly fade away _ but
so will your employee's respect. E-mail makes courtesy easy. Take
10 seconds and write: ``I'll get back to you on that next week.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Thinking like an owner.
</P>
<P>
   Many tasks don't fit neatly into anyone's responsibilities, but
they have to get done. Find the ones that are crucial and offer to
do them.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of workers will be tempted to say, ``That's not my job.''
</P>
<P>
   They're right. But the best workers _ the ones who get promoted,
the ones who survive layoffs, the ones who get snatched up by other
companies _ take on added responsibilities, discarding lesser
duties if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   If you never get chosen for high-profile assignments, identify
important tasks that no one else is handling and offer to do them.
If you perform well, you'll raise your profile.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking like an owner also means paying attention to the costs
of a project. If something appears to be wasting a lot of time and
money, say so. Your boss may not realize it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Meeting deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Most people turn in work by the assigned time, but the best
workers stand out because they do it early, again seeing things
through other people's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you have something due Oct. 15, which your boss then has
to process for a Nov. 1 deadline. If you were the boss, wouldn't
you want it a week or two early if possible? If there were
complications, wouldn't you want to know as early as possible so
you could assign more staff? What bosses want is pretty basic: Do
the assignment well and turn it in on time. Top workers do that,
but they provide something extra: peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   If you're the boss and you handed that Oct. 15 assignment to a
top worker back in April, you have several months of not worrying
about it. You know that the bases will be covered, that you'll get
periodic updates to reassure you (even if they're just brief e-mail
messages) and that you won't get a rude surprise on Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Helping others effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Top performers will help peers to learn, but they won't do
others' work for them. They're most helpful to people who have
tried to do as much as they can before they ask for help.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapting and learning.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be afraid of changes and technological advancements, and
move quickly to use new items effectively. Top workers even come up
with new ways the tools can help them.
</P>
<P>
   Mediocre workers won't think beyond the company's training
program. If they see others using new technology, they won't bother
thinking about whether the same item might help them as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
