<SLUG> BC-JEDEDIAHPURDY-OTHERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHER EARLY GENIUSES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies JEDEDIAH PURDY-BOOK) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jedediah Purdy isn't the only young writer/philosopher to make a
literary impact. His contemporaries in age, if not generation,
include:
</P>
<P>
   Aristophanes, born about 445 B.C., was a playwright in Athens.
His plays poked fun at government and society. ``The Clouds,''
written when he was about 23, and ``Lysistrata,'' written when he
was 34, are still studied and performed.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton Mather, born in Colonial America in 1663, became
Harvard's youngest freshman when he was 12. After graduation, he
became a minister and author, using both professions to decry the
decline of morality and urging more conservative lifestyles. He
wrote more than 450 books, essays, poems and published sermons and
was said by his enemies to be unwilling to believe anyone had the
right to disagree with him.
</P>
<P>
   Few realize that Edgar Allan Poe was a writing prodigy. His
first collection of poetry was published when Poe was 22. He had
written most of his famous verse and horror novels and short
stories by his mid-30s. Good thing; he died at 40.
</P>
<P>
   William F. Buckley published ``God and Man at Yale'' when he was
26; he founded the ``National Review'' at age 30 and went on to
become perhaps the best-known spokesman for conservative politics
during the 1960s and '70s. His recent books have all been mediocre
spy novels, mostly involving the now-defunct Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Naked and the Dead,'' based on Norman Mailer's World War
II experiences, made him a celebrity author in 1948 at age 25.
Mailer won two subsequent Pulitzer Prizes, for ``The Armies of the
Night'' and ``The Executioner's Song.'' Among all the boy-prodigy
authors, he has had perhaps the longest and most prominent career.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bond wrote several philosophic tracts that formed the
basis for the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, or SNCC,
in 1960; Bond was 20 at the time. At 25, the African-American
leader was elected to the Georgia State Assembly, only to have his
election invalidated because he opposed the Vietnam War. He was
later reinstated. Undaunted, Bond ran for the same seat and won
again; this time, a Supreme Court ruling forced the Georgia
assembly to allow him to serve. Bond made more history in 1968,
when he was nominated for vice president at the Democratic National
Convention. Before delegates voted, Bond noted that, at age 28, he
was constitutionally ineligible for the office (35 is the minimum).
Bond now serves as chairman of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   As an 18-year-old freshman at Columbia University, James Simon
Kunen participated in the 1968 student protests. At 19, he
published a book about them titled ``The Strawberry Statement,''
which concluded with the dramatic promise that, ``one of these days
I may fight in earnest and altogether so I won't have to fight
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
