A3092 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-JEDEDIAHPURDY-INTERVI     09-15 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEDEDIAHPURDY-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AT THE FUTURE, THROUGH JED'S EYES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies JEDEDIAH PURDY-BOOK) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pausing for a quick interview between law classes at Yale,
24-year-old Jedediah _ ``Just `Jed' ''_ Purdy seems polite,
well-spoken and just a little bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Response to my book, `For Common Things,' makes me feel very
peculiar,'' Purdy admits in a phone interview. ``The reason one
writes a book is because of a point to be made, to have something
worth saying. I imagined people sitting down with it, giving the
book some time as a set of ideas to be considered, not paying any
particular attention to the person who wrote it. Perhaps I was
being naive in this.''
</P>
<P>
   As reviews of ``For Common Things'' find their way to the
apartment Purdy shares in New Haven with two fellow students, he is
struck by the words in them devoted to his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``My book is clearly, very openly, a young man's book,
reflective of a sense of urgency about what to do with a life,''
Purdy says. ``Certainly, it is a perspective that comes from being
in one's early 20s, considering the directions gone so far in a
life, and the directions where a life may next go. But to focus on
my age is, I believe, catching the book at a wrong angle. What I
have attempted to describe are not virtues or deeds I personally
have accomplished, or even to present my own convictions as
exemplary. Rather, I am describing what I have seen in other lives,
described by other writing and in scenes of public engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   After a short pause to pose for photographs for another
interview _ a pause of perhaps five seconds for which Purdy spends
the better part of two additional minutes apologizing profusely _
he also responds to criticism that ``For Common Things'' is simply
the yammering of an inexperienced boy trying to talk about issues
he isn't old enough to know much, if anything, about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that in some ways my book invites that
response,'' Purdy says. ``It is, of course, a personal book, but my
aim is to explore some ways we can develop from personal experience
something that evolves beyond the idiosyncratic. And, of course,
portions of the book dealing with political skepticism and the
whole tone of the current popular culture are areas where a young
person can characterize modern texture as well as anyone of any
other age.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdy doesn't intend ``For Common Things'' to be his last book,
although he doesn't expect writing to occupy all his post-Yale
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of myself exclusively as a writer, though
whether I ever practice law is unclear,'' he says. ``My view of the
rest of my life is that it won't turn on how much of this current
notoriety stays with me. And I think of this first book as a
preface to future works that will be not so much exploration of
ideas on a large scale as they will be topical, more concrete _ the
city as an element of American culture, for instance, or work in
America and the difference between those who think it is an
entitlement to have interesting careers vs. those who work so that
one day they won't have to work anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a writer or lawyer, as a celebrity or nonentity, Purdy
never intends to sit back and let the world go along without his
input.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view,'' he says, ``I hope to be engaged in
public issues for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
