<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSE-HIP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISE A GLASS TO ROSE _ YOUNG, SPIRITED AND SUDDENLY HIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When your most fashionable friend pours you a glass of pink wine
one of these warm afternoons, don't assume she's lost her mind. If
she's hip, that's not a white zinfandel she's wielding.
</P>
<P>
   She has probably selected one of the dry, full-bodied ross from
the south of France that are so popular among chic hosts and
hostesses on the East Coast. And if she's in the know like those
stylish denizens of the Hamptons, she's having fits trying to
convince her friends that she hasn't geeked out.
</P>
<P>
   As Food &AMP; Wine reported this summer, novelist Jay McInerney
loves serving ross from Provence and Bandol, such as the Domaine
Tempier, to his summering guests in the Hamptons. But he admits
that he has to reassure them that ``it's actually really cool'' to
drink ross.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, ross are a tough sell elsewhere. Ask somebody
who knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like a ros on a warm day _ it's refreshing,'' said
Bernard Tronche, who said he orders a case from Provence each year
for his Fort Worth, Texas, restaurant, Saint-Emilion. ``But it
doesn't sell that well. Sometimes a customer orders it, meaning
white zinfandel, and is surprised to not get a sweet wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tronche enjoys having a pizza with his ros, which is a
young and spirited wine, it's also a nice companion for
bolder-flavored foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were in Aspen, we had a wonderful ros with spicy Asian
food,'' said Darryl Beeson, who is the cellar master at the Mansion
on Turtle Creek in Dallas. ``What I like about it is that you can
throw an ice cube in your ros and not feel like you're committing a
sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most ross found in these parts are those from Provence
or from Languedoc-Roussillon, the region just west of Provence,
there are plenty of others from Spain, Italy and Greece. Even some
American producers, such as Joseph Phelps in the Napa Valley, make
a ros that is definitely not the sweet blush that is sort of known
as wine for beginners.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like a touch of pink, here are some ross to check out.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau d'Aqueria Tavel: paler pink and strong flavored, this
bone-dry wine from the southern Rhone region is blended from
grenache and syrah grapes; it hints of tangy cherry and goes nicely
with herbed, grilled fish, pasta laced with aioli, bouillabaise,
ratatouille and couscous. About $15.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Phelps Vin du Mistral Grenache Ros '96: The California
producer of famed (and costly) Insignia red wines makes a very nice
refreshing, dry ros. About $10.
</P>
<P>
   Fortant '97: This French white merlot is an easygoing
bestseller. Less than $10.
</P>
<P>
   Vendages de Soleil '97: Another French favorite, this comes in a
gorgeous bottle that looks as though it was hand-painted. Less than
$10.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Grande Cassagne Costieres de Nimes '98: Tasting of red
berries, cherry and mint, this round and fruity wine has a ripe,
smooth finish. Serve it with antipasti, crudites, pates, grilled
salmon, Caesar salad and hamburgers. Less than $10.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
