<HEADER>
A3098 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     09-15 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDY IS DANDY, EVEN IN CAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madeline Armstrong of Hurst, Texas, saw our request for a cake
made with Milky Way candy bars and sent along this version.
</P>
<P>
   MILKY WAY CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 20
</P>
<P>
   6 (1.9-ounce) Milky Way bars
</P>
<P>
   1 cup margarine, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Slowly melt candy bars with 1/2 cup margarine. Set aside. Cream
sugar with the remaining margarine. Add eggs and blend. Add the dry
ingredients, which have been sifted together, alternately with the
buttermilk. Add the melted bars and margarine mixture. Blend. Stir
in pecans. Bake in greased and floured tube pan at 325 degrees for
1 hour and 10 minutes or until done. Cool on rack.
</P>
<P>
   Frosting:
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup margarine
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce package semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1 cup marshmallow cream
</P>
<P>
   Cook sugar, milk and margarine to soft ball stage. Remove from
heat and add chocolate chips and marshmallow cream. Stir until
melted. Spread on cake.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 567 calories, 25 grams fat, 84
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 50 milligrams cholesterol,
290 milligrams sodium, 40 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Bragging rights: And since we're already on board the calorie
train, here's a recipe for something else sinful. This recipe is
from Ann Hodgman's delightful ``Beat This!'' (Chapters, $12.95). Do
note that these brownies must be made six hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   THE VERY BEST BROWNIES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 9
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces best-quality semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces best-quality unsweetened chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup miniature chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Butter an 8-inch-square pan.
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, beat sugar, eggs and salt for 15 minutes. This is
much easier if you own a stand-up mixer and can roam around the
kitchen straightening up while the mixture beats. If all you've got
is a hand mixer, however, plan on having a book in your other hand.
Just check the bowl once in a while to make sure the egg mixture
isn't migrating out onto your counter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, melt the semisweet and unsweetened chocolates and
butter in a double boiler over a very low flame. When mixture is
about three-quarters melted, take it off the heat and stir until
chocolates and butter are completely melted and the mixture is
smooth. Cool to lukewarm (don't rush this) and fold gently into the
sugar-egg mixture. Fold in flour, vanilla and finally the chocolate
chips.
</P>
<P>
   Spread mixture in prepared pan and set it in middle of the oven.
Bake for 20 minutes if you like your brownies custardy. If you like
them a little drier, bake for 30 minutes. They'll still be nice and
creamy. Cool on rack for 6 hours and cut into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per brownie: 438 calories, 29 grams fat, 48
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 98 milligrams cholesterol, 50
milligrams sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Star-Telegram, Box
1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1555EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0186 </DOCNO>
