<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3107 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-DRACULA16-COX     09-15 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-DRACULA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kronos, Glass in black, white
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those brand-name vanguardists, foxy chamber group Kronos Quartet
and minimalist/pop composer Philip Glass, tag-team the silent
cinema on their latest collaboration: a score for Todd Browning's
1931 horror classic, ``Dracula.'' Packaged with the menacing visage
of Bela Lugosi glaring from the CD's cardboard slipcover, the
project immediately piques your curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Glass, who is frequently linked to such fellow '60s-identified,
repetition-minded, rock 'n' roll-friendly composers Steve Reich and
Terry Riley, has a virtual second career as a soundtrack guy. His
credits include unconventional documentaries like ``The Thin Blue
Line'' and ``Koyaanisqatsi,'' epics like Martin Scorsese's
``Kundun'' and even the B-movie slasher ``Candyman'' (which he
disowns, sort of). Half the time, his work sounds cheesy and
blithely recycled; but when it's inspired, a Glass score flaunts a
multifaceted opulence, its hypnotic insistence pulling you through
the surface into a hall of mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dracula'' is good Glass. His keyboard-based music translates
with appealing simplicity to string quartet, especially one as
well-recorded as the Kronos, which plays these 26 short pieces
(from 43 seconds to nearly five minutes) with a crisp elegance.
Maybe it's the brevity of the segments or the desire to complement
those shadowy black-and-white images, but the composer's signature
repetitions never get, you know, repetitious. Neither does it
succumb to heavy-handed drama, stroking romantic touchstones
without evoking the same old gloom and doom from the tomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dracula''
</P>
<P>
   Kronos Quartet/Philip Glass. Nonesuch. 26 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1604EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS16-COX     09-15 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Judith Green and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Na Please''
</P>
<P>
   Ol' Dirty Bastard. Elektra. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   And now, rap listeners, we return you to another episode of Ol'
Dirty Bastard. Last we saw him, ODB, Big Baby Jesus _ or whatever
he was calling himself _ was running his mouth at the 1998 Grammy
Awards, running from the cops or running up a number of women
accusing him of shirking child support. And as reckless as this
member of the Wu-Tang Clan is in his personal life, he is on his
second solo album. Stumbling through often incoherent boasts and
verbal assaults, the equal-opportunity offender somehow manages to
stay upright enough to make fun of singers who ad-lib (``Good
Morning Heartache''), smart enough to include danceable production
(``Recognize'') and interesting enough to keep you tuning in _
albeit warily _ to hear what he'll wreck next.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   ``prokofiev bartok webern barber''
</P>
<P>
   Garrick Ohlsson, piano. Arabesque. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Known as an interpreter of romantic music, American pianist
Garrick Ohlsson also has a gift for mainstream contemporary
repertory (though, regrettably, he rarely plays it in public). The
melodic ease and harmonic clarity of his Chopin and Schubert are
just as apparent in this exquisite recording. He plays the
meditative first movement of Prokofiev's Sonata No. 8 and the
intricate fingerwork of Samuel Barber's 1949 sonata with equal
thoughtfulness and skill. As for Bartok's ``Three Studies,'' Op.
18, and Anton Webern's ``Variationen fur Klavier,'' Op. 27, these
sketches have the transparency of early Debussy preludes. The tiny
middle variation of Webern (``Sehr schnell,'' very fast) lasts
exactly 38 seconds: a dragonfly of a piece, gone almost before it's
here.
</P>
<P>
   _Judith Green
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TRIP-HOP
</P>
<P>
   ``Juxtapose''
</P>
<P>
   Tricky with DJ Muggs and Grease. Island. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   There are artists who spend a career trying to equal a
remarkable debut, and Tricky is among them. 1995's ``Maxinquaye''
was a dark, moody masterpiece that sprang from the Bristol,
England, trip-hop underground with a stunning display of raw
talent. Tricky has never again reached the mark set by it.
``Juxtapose'' doesn't change that, but it still outstrips most of
the competition. Previous releases flirted with psychedelia, but
that tendency gets free rein here. ``Contradictive'' and ``She
Said,'' among other tracks, call to mind Echo and the Bunnymen and
even Smashing Pumpkins. The steady throb of hip-hop is still there,
but we get more trip and less hop. The metallic thrum of ``Hot Like
a Sauna'' even flirts with Kid Rock/Limp Bizkit-type sonics. One
other caveat: At just under 36 minutes, this is considerably
shorter than your average full-price CD.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Judith Green and Shane Harrison write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
