<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3110 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS16-COX     09-15 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Steve Murray, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Last Days'' (PG-13) _ James Moll's Oscar-winning
documentary uses simplicity to underscore the horrors of the Nazi
Holocaust. It focuses on five survivors of Germany's decision to
exterminate as many Hungarian Jews as possible late in the war,
when Hitler logically should have been channeling all resources to
his troops. It's a portrait of hatred at its most irrational. The
survivors tell stories of courage and loss with a
matter-of-factness that makes the horrors of genocide
heartbreakingly personal. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cookie's Fortune'' (PG-13) _ A delicious, deep-fried riff
from director Robert Altman. Set in small-town Mississippi, this
comic character study kicks off when busybody Glenn Close tries to
cover up her aunt's (Patricia Neal's) suicide, leading to
misunderstandings that shake up the lives of the locals, including
Charles S. Dutton, Julianne Moore, Liv Tyler and Chris O'Donnell.
Altman spoons a rich Southern flavor over his scenes, celebrating
yet ever so gently mocking his characters' eccentricities. Grade:
B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Forces of Nature'' (PG-13) _ Opposites attract as
strait-laced Ben Affleck heads to his Savannah wedding, accompanied
by free-spirited Sandra Bullock. Like ``My Best Friend's Wedding,''
it's a savvy blend of romantic-comedy formula and wise 1990s
updates. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Three Seasons'' (PG-13) _ The winner of three awards at
Sundance and further distinguished as the first U.S. film shot in
Vietnam since the war, this tenderly appealing pastiche interweaves
several obliquely connected stories while catching a country in
transition between a conflicted past and an uncertain future.
Reminiscent of Italian neo-realism, the movie may be narratively
facile, but it's visually and emotionally rich. With subtitles.
Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``God Said `Ha'!'' (PG-13) _ A one-woman autobiographical show
with ``Saturday Night Live'' alumna Julia Sweeney talking about her
brother's cancer, her parents and her own illness. Lacking special
effects or sex scenes, and with death as its undeniable subtext,
it's definitely a grown-up film. And it proves that laughter is
indeed the best medicine. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Jill Vejnoska
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Yellow Submarine'' (G) _ As a cultural artifact, it's a
blast. As a movie, it's a bomb. Available for the first time in 11
years, the digitally restored Beatles oddity is a showcase for some
psychedlic strangeness and swell tunes (largely culled from ``Sgt.
Pepper's''), mired in a nonsensical fantasy plot. The animation
plays like a series of inferior Peter Max posters forced to move;
that's a plus or minus, depending on your own personal groove, man.
(VHS, $19.98; DVD $29.98.) Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Children of Heaven'' (unrated) _ You can see this
Oscar-nominated movie (for foreign language film) intent on
divining all sorts of hidden messages in its tale of abject
poverty, scary authority figures and other aspects of Iranian life.
But then you'd miss seeing a simpler, much more delightful story
about two little children and their quest for one pair of shoes.
The ending is by turns touching, heartbreaking and hilarious.
Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Jill Vejnoska
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Jill Vejnoska write
for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
