<HEADER>
A3112 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-PERKINS-TV-COLUMN-TEX     09-15 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERKINS-TV-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS, CAMERA, CENSOR! HERE COMES `ACTION'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although he's playing a character with no character and starring
in a comedy in which language is lewd, offensive, sexual, racist,
homophobic or merely bleeped out, Jay Mohr and his much-hyped
half-hour comedy, ``Action,'' have created one of the early
pleasures of the new TV season.
</P>
<P>
   I say this with the full knowledge that this is the kind of
television that could very well doom us all.
</P>
<P>
   Shot with the quick-cut sensibilities of a music video and the
broadcast standards of late-night cable, ``Action'' arrives at a
time when network TV finds that its only recourse in the audience
war against the freewheeling cable competitors is to arm itself
with the same artillery.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Jimmy Smits put it succinctly the other day while
cruising the red carpet during the pre-Emmy festivities, ``Get
edgier, get crazier, go over the line.''
</P>
<P>
   He must have gotten a peek at Thursday's pilot episode of Fox's
``Action,'' which does all that and tosses in a scene in which a
limo drags a hooker several blocks, then dislodges her onto the
red-carpet entrance of a movie premiere, her skirt up, legs
spread-eagled, the camera zeroing in.
</P>
<P>
   Says Mohr's Peter Dragon, who's more concerned with the flashing
cameras than a no-name prostitute: ``Don't die, hooker, please
don't die, this is a Christmas movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter is the protagonist here, a Xanax-popping, hotheaded
Hollywood producer who is Mohr's Jerry Maguire character had he
ascended into the film industry and gotten hooked on amphetamines.
He is unscrupulous and heartless, a purveyor of the filth that
pervades Hollywood, which is ironic and even comical considering
that he's about to do the same number on us on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Peter's specialty is the sort of big-budget action picture that
might be titled ``Slow Torture II: It Still Hurts'' unless he
decides to call it ``Slow Torture II: Now It's Unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   He has an ex-wife married to a tyrannical boss, the studio head,
who is gay and is legendary for being well-endowed physically. Most
of Peter's time is spent barking orders into his cell phone,
walkingandtalkinglikethis, and treating everyone below him like a
gooey something on the bottom of his $200 shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can come to the premiere,'' Peter snaps into his cell
phone as he strides into his office suite. ``She can come to the
post-premiere party. But she cannot come to the post-premiere
party-party. Whaddaya mean, why? Because she's ugly!''
</P>
<P>
   Illeana Douglas is Wendy Ward, a former child star turned
cocaine addict turned prostitute turned Peter's creative
consultant, which, in this rather pretentious, sleazy world, could
very well happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a date?'' Wendy asks Peter, who is bent over the
sidewalk, halfway out his limo, when they first meet. Peter: ``I'm
gonna puke on you.'' Wendy: ``Gee. I don't think I have a price for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot more in this vein, most of it howlingly funny,
based on situations that are morally appalling, but taken as a
package, create a racy and entertaining spoof of Hollywood
deal-making.
</P>
<P>
   Action is executive-produced by Chris Thompson, who wrote for
HBO's ``The Larry Sanders Show,'' the other cable series that was
all tension, cynicism and profound shallowness _ just the way you
imagine Hollywood life would be, except funnier.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike that on ``Larry Sanders,'' the humor isn't hermetic.
You'll get all the jokes even if you've never set foot in Los
Angeles, although you'll probably laugh louder if you subscribe to
Daily Variety.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sanders, ``Action'' will take advantage of stars playing
themselves _ Keanu Reeves appears in the pilot, attending the movie
premiere of ``Slow Torture,'' asking Peter why Wendy has her hands
down his pants. Purrs Wendy: ``I'm a big fan of yours.'' Purrs
Keanu: ``I'm getting to be a big fan of yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter, by the way, is flanked by Stuart (Jack Plotnick), his
sidekick of a production president and typical Hollywood yes-man.
Buddy Hackett plays Peter's uncle and chauffeur, and perhaps the
only person he remotely respects, unless you count Georgia (Sara
Paxton) his pre-teen daughter, who lives with her mother (Cindy
Ambuehl) and the gay studio boss.
</P>
<P>
   The series, originally conceived for cable (HBO passed), has
drawn a considerable amount of attention by allowing Peter to utter
bleeped-out obscenities. Not that you don't know what he's saying.
Take the scene where he rips into an underling upset over losing
his ``Employee of the Month'' parking space: ``I will continue to
park any (bleep) place I want,'' Peter informs him, ``because I'm
the (bleep) employee of the century!''
</P>
<P>
   Profanity, or the semblance of such, isn't needed to give Action
irreverence or realism. So let's hope it's a device that becomes
relegated to the same every-now-and-then status of a posterior
sighting on ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bleeped profanity aside, I like the idea that ``Action'' will
have an infinite number of ways to deconstruct the film business
and that it will come through the eyes of Peter, who looks as if
he'll convey the shadings of insecurity and bottled-up rage that
made Larry Sanders such a prickly, complicated, glorious character.
</P>
<P>
   To say that ``Action'' is so far the most fearless half-hour of
comedy this season wouldn't be off target _ just suspect at a time
when we must question whether Smits' solution of network TV being
``edgier, crazier, going more over the line'' will be worth what we
get in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1604EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3113 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE16-COX     09-15 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wake up with stress-free breakfast
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have known forever that breakfast is the most important meal
of the day. Why is it, then, that for many it is the meal we put
the least thought into? Day after day the same soggy cereals,
sugary doughnuts, Pop-Tarts and fast food are eaten on the run ...
and we are done with it.
</P>
<P>
   But breakfast is also a quality-of-life meal. Besides being
nutritionally vital, breakfast sets the tone for the day. If
breakfast time at your house is usually rushed _ filled with
stress, tensions and distractions _ maybe it's time to take a good,
hard look at your morning dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every day can be a Norman Rockwell painting; but
by doing a little readjusting here and a tad of rethinking there,
you can add a chunk of quality time and other remarkable benefits
to your family's life.
</P>
<P>
   A study done last year by Massachusetts General Hospital took
100 kids from the third through eighth grades who usually didn't
eat breakfast for one reason or another and gave them a chance to
eat a free, nutritionally sound (although not very imaginative)
breakfast for four months. The kids were tracked to see how often
they ate the breakfasts. At the end of the test period, the kids
who ate the breakfast often saw improvements in their math grades.
(Researchers couldn't figure out why the boost showed in math and
not other subjects.) The kids also claimed that their feelings of
anxiety and depression decreased. On top of that, teachers and
parents reported that tardiness, absenteeism and hyperactivity
dropped among the breakfast eaters.
</P>
<P>
   We can only imagine what would happen if, instead of moping to
the breakfast table to face yet another predictable bowl of cereal
or a doughnut, your family was met with an eye-opening, tasty and
imaginative morning meal.
</P>
<P>
   It can be done with surprisingly little effort by budgeting just
15 minutes in the evening and 15 minutes in the morning to plan and
prepare this most important meal.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is a good place to look to help you get started
revamping your breakfast routine.
</P>
<P>
   For pure motivation, start by looking at some fabulous breakfast
dishes. And where better to start than with what bed-and-breakfast
inns across the country are serving their pampered guests? For
original, tempting recipes _ like Pineapple French Toast With
Ambrosia Salsa and Artichoke Heart Strata _ check these B&AMP;B sites:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.flinthills.com/(tilde)atway/recipes
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  bedandbreakfast.com/recipes/breakfast.asp
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.victoria.to/recipes.bed.breakfast.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.bbchannel.com/index3.asp
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.travelguides.com/bandb/recipes/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.cs.cmu.edu/(tilde)mjw/recipes/misc/breakfast-coll.html
</P>
<P>
   For more ideas of the pleasures that can await you at the
breakfast table, dive into some of the more than 300 recipes at
SOAR
</P>
<P>
   .Berkeley.EDU/recipes/breakfast. There are recipes for breakfast
kebabs and quiches, casseroles, parfaits, burritos, chimichangas
and focaccia. There is even a breakfast lasagna. Also included are
imaginative variations on French toast, pancakes, crepes, omelets,
grits and hash.
</P>
<P>
   How-to sites
</P>
<P>
   Now that you are sufficiently inspired, here are some sites to
help you get it done.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Stressless Breakfasts,'' an article by Lynn Nelson at
busycooks.About.com/library/weekly/aa083099.htm is loaded with good
info and related links. There are tips on freezing everything from
pancakes to breakfast casseroles to French toast and even hot
cereal. She also suggests that you may want to start breakfast the
night before in a crockpot, and she includes a recipe for an apple
granola cobbler. Other topics are Breakfast on the Run and
Breakfast in a Glass.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Breakfast tips provided by iVillage at www.ivillage.com
</P>
<P>
   /food/features/quicktips/articles/0,5370,17474,00.htm include
preparing a salad of fresh and dried fruits to serve throughout the
week and a breakfast ``pizza'' using leftover or frozen pancakes or
waffles topped with yogurt and fresh fruit and drizzled with maple
syrup.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keeping your pantry stocked for particularly rushed mornings
is just one of the tips at ``Morning Blast'' at
www.thriveonline.com
</P>
<P>
   /shape/countdown/countdown.food.week2.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Breakfast recipes tailored specifically to children with
attention deficit disorder can be found at www.additudemag.com
</P>
<P>
   /breakfastrecipesforaddkids.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast on the run
</P>
<P>
   If things are so rushed you simply must eat on the run, instead
of grabbing a doughnut, why not whip up a power drink or smoothie?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you have only three minutes to prepare breakfast, check out
the yogurt smoothie at www.chap.com/ezine/issue1/recipe1.htm for a
fast breakfast with nutritional punch.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hamilton Beach at www.hambeach.com/special/fun.html shaves two
minutes off that with a one-minute smoothie, and offers other
kid-tested breakfast shakes including one with peanut butter. They
suggest putting the shakes into commuter cups or ``sippy cups'' on
particularly hurried days.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure to check the Apricot Smoothie, Mango Milk Shake and
Triple Fruit Yogurt Shake at Country Living at www.homearts.com
</P>
<P>
   /hl/articles/00powf1.htm
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast Burritos
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15-20 minutes, including bacon
</P>
<P>
   Burritos for breakfast? Why not _ especially if they are quickly
filled with scrambled eggs, bacon and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   6 strips bacon
</P>
<P>
   6 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   6 (10-inch) flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup salsa
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (4 ounces) shredded Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet, fry bacon until crisp. Drain on paper towels.
Crumble and set aside. In a small bowl, lightly beat eggs, milk,
salt and pepper. Melt butter in a nonstick skillet over medium
heat. Add eggs and cook, stirring, until set. Wrap tortillas in
damp paper towels. Microwave on high 30 seconds to soften.
</P>
<P>
   Spread each tortilla with 2 tablespoons salsa. Spoon one-sixth
of the eggs on lower half of each tortilla. Sprinkle with bacon and
cheese. Roll up, tucking in sides as you roll. Place, seam side
down, in a single layer in a microwavable dish. Cover with damp
paper towels. Microwave on high 1 to 1 1/2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with additional salsa, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Per burrito: 436 calories, 25 grams protein, 22 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 32 grams carbohydrates, 360
milligrams cholesterol, 1,122 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
