r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP16-COX     09-15 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peanut Butter Bars that melt in your mouth
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if you're not back in a classroom, the very thought of
cranking a pencil sharpener and smelling a box of newly opened
crayons may be enough to revive fond back-to-school memories.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Stribling of McDonough (Ga.) wrote to say she would
appreciate a recipe for Peanut Butter Bars like those she enjoyed
in the early 1980s when she attended a Fulton County elementary
school.
</P>
<P>
   Her plea was answered by Betty Sheldon of Covington (Ga.), who
said she got this recipe from the dietitian at Rowland Elementary
School in DeKalb County (Ga.) when her children attended in the
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   The bars are easy to make and freeze well.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Peanut
</P>
<P>
   Butter Bars
</P>
<P>
   Makes 42 bars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the bars:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups rolled oats (quick or old-fashioned, not instant)
</P>
<P>
   For the icing:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (4 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, cream sugars and butter until smooth and
fluffy. Add eggs and mix well. Add peanut butter, soda, salt and
vanilla. Stir in flour and oats. Spread in a greased 11-by-14-inch
jellyroll pan. Bake 20 to 25 minutes, until edges just begin to
turn golden. Do not overcook. Cut into squares while still warm,
then immediately spread on icing.
</P>
<P>
   For the icing: In a mixing bowl, combine sugar, peanut butter
and enough evaporated milk to make icing of thin spreading
consistency. Spread on bars with a spatula, then let cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Per bar: 161 calories, 3 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 38), 23 grams carbohydrates, 28 milligrams
cholesterol, 117 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cynthia Montgomery of Tucker (Ga.) is looking for a recipe
before the holidays for oyster dressing or stuffing. She had some
at a friend's family's in Tennessee years ago and would like to
make some this year. It is made with bread, not corn bread, she
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mary Rose asks via voicemail if anyone has a recipe for a
mandarin orange cake like one a co-worker, who has since moved
away, used to bake. It had three orange-flavored, light layers,
filled with a light frosting made of either whipped cream or cream
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tessie Knighton of Stone Mountain (Ga.) is searching for two
cake recipes. Mile-High Buttermilk Cake has three layers, lemon
filling and fluffy frosting, all topped with more lemon filling.
The Earthquake Cake has a layer of toasted pecans in the bottom of
a pan. Batter is poured on, then a cream cheese mixture is poured
through the center. ``It is to die for,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting the column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to
</P>
<P>
   Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone
number.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
