<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3116 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION1     09-15 2062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOPPING DESTINATION: Thomasville
 &HT;    City of Roses thrives on hospitality, ingenuity
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOMASVILLE, Ga. _ In this historic southwest Georgia town of
20,000, the streets are paved with red bricks instead of gold.
</P>
<P>
   But that simply adds to the charm of its vibrant Victorian
downtown, which boasts about 100 authentically restored shops and
galleries. Businesses run the gamut, from Neel's 101-year-old
department store to Grapevines &AMP; Good Times, a four-month-old
boutique that sells invitations, gifts and collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   If you wander into Thomas Drug Store, you can walk on the
original 1857 blue-and-white tile floor and buy a block of camphor
($1.29) that Thomasville women put in their silver chests to retard
tarnish on the family silver. Or you can buy a diamond at Jerger
Johnson Jewelers while admiring their polished wood jewelry cases
dating to 1857. And when you're ready for a break, duck into Izzo's
Pharmacy, whose owners use a 75-year-old hand press to make yummy
burgers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to soaking up history on your shopping foray, you'll
be treated to top-notch service in each store and have your
purchases gift-wrapped for free. And don't worry about parking.
There's plenty on the streets _ and it's free, too.
</P>
<P>
   Thomasville, also known as the City of Roses, was named a Main
Street City in 1982. The goal of this program is to provide
economic development within the context of historic preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a problem that most towns would love,'' said Sharlene
Celaya, the executive director of Thomasville Tourism. ``I have a
list of five owners who want to move to Broad (the main shopping
street), but there are no vacancies. Most of our stores are locally
owned by second- and third-generation residents and young people
are coming back to their hometown to open more.''
</P>
<P>
   Holly Lybrook, the co-owner of Hollybrook, a chic furniture and
home accessories shop, is originally from Thomasville. She lived in
Richmond for 20 years with her husband Drew but moved back 3 1/2
years ago to open the shop. ``I always wanted to come home,''
Lybrook said. ``I love the friendliness of the people and the
pretty downtown. My husband, who is from Richmond, also wanted to
move to Thomasville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are lucky. Local residents support us as well as visitors
from Valdosta (Ga.), Albany (Ga.), Bainbridge (Ga.), Moultrie
(Ga.), even Tallahassee (Fla.).''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday afternoon, former Atlanta resident Dinorah
Hall, who now lives in Albany (Ga.), was shopping at Lybrook's
shop. ``I find more unique, yet affordable, items here than at the
Atlanta Decorative Arts Center,'' said Hall, who is director of the
James H. Hall Eye Center in Albany. ``Plus, everyone in Thomasville
makes me feel so comfortable when I'm shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantans also like to shop in town. Ted Turner and wife Jane
Fonda own Avalon, a plantation in northern Florida, and shoppers on
Broad Street often rub elbows with Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   A local wag once remarked that ``Thomasville was built on
Northern ingenuity and Southern hospitality.'' Maybe so. Founded in
1824, the town received its charter in 1831 and became a part of
Thomas County.
</P>
<P>
   After the Civil War, wealthy northerners and socialites traveled
to Thomasville by train, where it ended its run. Situated 330 feet
above sea level, the town was fairly free of lowland marshes that
bred mosquitoes carrying yellow fever and malaria. Thus, it became
known as a fashionable winter resort. Northeast and Midwest
industrialists built homes, also known as ``cottages,'' in town, or
plantations in the fertile lands. By 1906, however, the railroad
expanded to Palm Beach and Miami, leaving Thomasville and
surrounding counties with a heritage of beautiful homes and
plantations.
</P>
<P>
   Today, these graceful places _ most are still privately owned _
attract a bounty of visitors and hunters. Quail hunting is a
favorite sport. The 4,500-acre Woodhaven plantation in nearby
Coolidge is owned by Atlantan Charlie Loudermilk, founder and
chairman of Aaron Rents. It's said to be the inspiration for the
fictional quail plantation Turpmtine in Tom Wolfe's novel ``A Man
in Full.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-75 south to Tifton (Exit 18). Go right,
which brings you to a stop sign. Turn left and you will see the
sign for U.S. 319 south. After it crosses Ga. 19, U.S. 319 south is
also known as Jackson Street, which takes you straight into
Thomasville. About a four-hour drive from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most shops open 9 a.m.-5:30 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Free parking on Broad Street and side streets. Also,
two municipal lots are on Crawford Street behind the stores facing
Broad Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Stores are generally accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Public restrooms in the Thomasville Welcome Center,
135 N. Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-800-704-2350.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1884 Paxton House: You can't miss this elegant two-story
bed-and breadfast on Remington Avenue, which is painted a deep blue
and trimmed in white with a wonderful wraparound porch. Innkeeper
Susie Sherrod, a retired army nurse, has restored this Victorian
beauty and filled it with antiques, crystal and dolls collected
from her trips abroad. The nine rooms/suites have private baths,
TV, phones and air conditioning. And guests also have use of the
hot tub and lap pool. There's even a tiny gift shop on site filled
with trinkets made by the owner. Don't miss the gourmet breakfast.
On a recent morning, Sherrod served eggs Benedict, fresh fruit and
her famous homemade banana nut bread. After this repast, you can
take off the calories by walking the four blocks to the shopping
district. Smoke-free rooms are $99-$250. No children under 12. 445
Remington Ave. 912-226-5197. www.1884paxtonhouseinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Also recommended: Some of these bed-and-breakfasts are within
easy walking distance of downtown; others require a short drive:
Wright House, 415 Fletcher St. 912-225-9922; Evans House, 725 S.
Hansell St. 912-226-1343; Fast Turtle Inn, Route 2, Box 118-B,
Pavo. 912-859-2775; Serendipity Cottage, 339 E. Jefferson St.
912-226-8111 or 1-800-383-7377.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Even shoppers have to eat. At lunch, head for The Horse and
Buggy, 123 N. Broad St. (912-225-9600), located in the renovated
1916 Upchurch Building, which has been everything from a billiard
parlor to various retails shops. The sleek interior features a
buggy filled with flowers and a contemporary Southern menu. For
starters, try collard soup, a blend of the leafy greens, country
ham and mixed veggies ($2.50 a cup). If you eat eggs, the western
omelet is a must ($6.95). 11 a.m.-3 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Other dining spots to try: Neel's Lunch on the Mezzanine, 101 N.
Broad St. (912-226-5431, Ext. 17). Located in the oldest store in
town, this small cafe serves a variety of sandwiches, including ham
or turkey, chicken salad, pimento cheese and peanut butter and
jelly ($1.25-$3.25). For a cool drink, opt for a lemonade ($1), an
iced cappuccino ($1.50) or a cherry Coke ($1.25). The Billiard
Academy, 121 S. Broad St. (912-226-9981). Step up to the walk-up
window and order a hot dog all the way _ chili, mustard and onions
($1). Chips are 50 cents, a beer, $1.75. Then play a friendly game
of pool. 8 a.m.-9 p.m. Mondays-Fridays; 8 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Splurge on dinner and make a reservation at Melhana, the Grand
Plantation Resort, 301 Showboat Lane (912-226-2290;
1-888-920-3030). Developed in the late 1800s by industrialist
Howard Melville Hanna, and recently restored, you will eat in a
pale pink house surrounded by formal English gardens. Appetizers
might include fried green tomatoes ($8.95) or creamed crab on toast
points ($8.95) followed by a blue cheese apple salad ($7.95). Main
courses choices: pan roasted grouper ($26.95), grilled double lamp
chops ($29.95) or Florida red snapper ($25.95). 6-10 p.m. every
night. Jackets required for men.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   Plan to be in Thomasville for ``Art on the Bricks'' from 10
a.m.-4 p.m. Oct. 2 if you love art. Held on brick-paved Broad
Street, artists from around the southeast will sell paintings,
pottery, jewelry, wood carvings and sculptures. Festivities also
include food tastings and musical entertainment. Free. Information:
912-227-7020.
</P>
<P>
