<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3117 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-EGYPT16-COX     09-15 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-EGYPT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One impressive, earnest `Prince'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt'' (PG)
</P>
<P>
   The powers that be at DreamWorks talked to everyone from
evangelists to ministers to rabbis to Muslim theologians to make
sure the world's major religions found nothing overtly offensive
about this animated musical epic. About the only person they didn't
contact was the ghost of Cecil B. De Mille. Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   He could have told them he'd already done this movie.
Unquestionably impressive, ``The Prince of Egypt'' can't help but
summon echoes of De Mille's ``The Ten Commandments.'' It has the
same awesome visuals, the same cast-of-thousands scale, the same
insistently reverential approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prince'' tells of the Hebrew people's liberation from slavery
in Egypt. All the big scenes are here: Moses in the bulrushes; his
run-of-the-palace coming of age; his discovery of his true
birthright; his being summoned by God to lead the Israelites out of
bondage; the 10 plagues. A huge amount of care has been lavished on
this movie, and it shows, from the spectacular animation to the
spectacular voice talent: Val Kilmer, Ralph Fiennes, Jeff Goldblum,
Michelle Pfeiffer, Sandra Bullock, Patrick Stewart and Steve
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But is ``Prince'' the sort of animated classic that will be
embraced? Not really. It can't escape a kind of squeaky-clean
Sunday-school-lesson aura. It's visually impressive. And just a bit
too kosher. It probably could have used a little ham. ($26.99
video, $34.99 DVD.)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT16-COX     09-15 0192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spotlight on Sandra Bullock (``Forces of Nature'')
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Speed'' (1994; R) _ Applies pedal to metal, keeps bus from
going boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``While You Were Sleeping'' (1995; PG) _ Saves guy from muggers,
falls for him while he's in a coma, masquerades as fiancee _ oops.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Time to Kill'' (1996; R) _ Steaming up the screen as Matthew
McConaughey's legal support in this Deep South John Grisham
adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practical Magic'' (1998; PG-13) _ Getting witchy with sis
Nicole Kidman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope Floats'' (1998; PG-13) _ Getting dumped, moving home and
finding love again with Harry Connick Jr.
</P>
<P>
   THE VIDEO COLLECTOR
</P>
<P>
   Notable videos now on sale
</P>
<P>
   Kids: ``10 Years of Thomas the Tank Engine &AMP; Friends Collector's
Edition,'' $12.98.
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic: ``Avalanche: The White Death,'' $19.98.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage TV: ``The Avengers '66 Collection,'' two sets, each with
three episodes: VHS $29.95, DVD $44.95.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
