r l BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE16-COX     09-15 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can't find it? We did
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTANTA _ Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to
help you locate it. But due to the volume of mail, we cannot track
down every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the
column will receive a blue and cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag.
Write us at Buyer's Edge Find It, Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at
buyersedge(at)ajc.com (please include name, city you live in and
daytime phone number); or call
</P>
<P>
   404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently visited Boston and drank the best-flavored tea
I've ever tasted. It was brewed from Sir Thomas Lipton tea bags.
I've looked in several stores in the Atlanta area since I've been
back, but they seem to be unavailable. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _Dottie Richey, Dunwoody, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Another tea request: When we have catered lunches at work, the
caterer always brings Sir Thomas Lipton herbal teas. They are much
better than teas I find at the store. Where can I find them?
</P>
<P>
   _William K. Wilson, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: We've bagged that tea. According to a company representative,
the Sir Thomas Lipton line of teas is sold only to hotels, motels,
cruise ships and other food professionals. However, Lipton makes
these teas available to the public via its Products by Mail
Program. Included are flavored tea bags (raspberry, honey and
lemon, orange and spice, blackberry, mint and amaretto) as well as
herbal tea bags (including chamomile, golden honey lemon,
peppermint, orange, lemon soother and cinnamon apple). A box
contains 24 bags, and a six-box case is $8.86 plus $4.88 shipping
or $13.74. Send a check or money order to: Lipton Products by Mail,
P.O. Box 3000, Grand Rapids, MN 55745-3000. Information:
</P>
<P>
   1-800-697-7897.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please help us find pencil clips that slip onto wooden
pencils. These allow one to ``clip'' a pencil to a pocket, etc.
They used to be available at Emory University in the bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   _Dennis Taylor and
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Taylor, Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Another clip request: For years, I've been unable to find pencil
clips _ those little metal things that slip over six-sided pencils
so you can clip them onto pockets. Have they been declared lethal
or something? If not, where can I find them?
</P>
<P>
   _The Rev. James E.
</P>
<P>
   Hacke, Griffin
</P>
<P>
   A: Clipping right along, we found your silver-colored pencil
gizmos at Artlite Office Supplies &AMP; Pens, 1851 Piedmont Road N.E.
(404-875-7271). Each one is 29 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Seems as if I've been searching forever for a small
4-by-2-inch nylon ``shoe wallet'' in which you can carry ID and
coins. It attaches to the laces on a running shoe. I am quite sure
I purchased the last one here in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _Vic Bond, Lawrenceville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: No one will pick your pocket when you wear a ``shoe pocket''
on your running shoes. It attaches via a hook and loop tape
fastener and comes with or without a piece of reflective tape. We
found this handy item for $5 at two places: Fleet Feet Sports,
Sandy Springs Plaza, 6221 Roswell Road N.E. (404-255-3338) and at
Phidippides, two locations: 220 Sandy Springs Circle N.W.
(404-255-6149) and 1544 Piedmont Ave. N.E. (404-875-4268).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Scott's Liquid Gold ``Touch of Scent'' wall
dispenser refill.
</P>
<P>
   _Helen B. Darsey, Avondale Estates, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Every room will be as fresh as a spring day with a Touch of
Scent Air Freshener in the Potpourri scent. According to the
manufacturer, ``one touch is all you need for a long-lasting
fragrance.'' Each refill is $2.19. We found our 2.5-ounce can at
Drug Emporium, 2953 N. Druid Hills Road N.E. (404-636-6108). If you
don't have a dispenser, call for an order form at 1-800-227-8111.
Or visit Scott's Web site, www.touch-of-scent.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in finding utz potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   _Lance Baden, Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Since 1921, the family of Salie and Bill Utz has been making
and selling potato chips in Hanover, Pa. At first, Salie made the
chips in a small house behind their home and Bill delivered them.
In 1936, they started using an automatic potato chip cooker, which
could produce 300 pounds of chips per hour. Today, the company
turns out more than 12,000 chips per hour in such flavors as
regular, crab, salt and vinegar, sour cream and onion. You've had
trouble finding the chips because they are sold only in
Northeastern and North Central states. However, you can get your
fix of utz chips by ordering them via mail at 1-800-367-7629, Ext.
138. Or visit the Web site, www.utzsnacks.com. An 11-ounce bag
retails for $2.49. Utz also produces pretzels, popcorn and
decorative cans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johonson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
