</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's the likely effect of these worries on the stock market
during the next several months? In each case, at the moment, the
risk is all on the downside.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is already reflected in the prices of financial
assets; the bad news is just starting to get factored in. In
situations like that, investors tend to sell at the first sign of
real or imagined trouble.
</P>
<P>
   During May and June, that led to an over-sold market as
investors marked down everything. That was followed by a July
rally. And in early August, stocks and bonds took another tumble.
</P>
<P>
   Expect more of the same: lots of action without much direction. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Jim Jubak is senior markets
editor at Microsoft's MoneyCentral _ www.Moneycentral.msn.com.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
