<HEADLINE>
`ACTION' COULD BE THE TV SEASON'S FUNNIEST OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fall season's most hyped show is also the most controversial
and perhaps even the funniest. The bleeping bleeps can say whatever
they want, ``Action'' is not only a bracing tonic for television,
it's a searing sendup of Hollywood movies, the people behind them
and, ultimately, all of us. So what if it accomplishes all of that
by swearing at and skewering anything in its path?
</P>
<P>
   The show is damn funny. Period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action,'' which debuts Thursday evening, was originally
developed for HBO, and it contains all the hallmarks of pay-cable
freedom: swearing, anti-P.C. sentiments and the kind of hip insider
punch lines that say, ``If you don't get it, go watch CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fox has smartly bleeped out the swear words instead of
rewriting them into some kind of soft acceptable alternative, and
the network has otherwise left this series untouched _ one of the
smartest moves it has made in some time.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, what will the audience think? Will people like
the abrasive, unlikable main character, will they tolerate the
everybody-knows-what-you're-saying bleep-outs, and will they get
all the industry humor?
</P>
<P>
   Let's put this bluntly: If you think a cameo involving Keanu
Reeves having sex _ no, not that kind _ in a theater, or perhaps
the best O.J. Simpson gag in ages is just plain bad taste, you're
going to hate this show.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you appreciate razor-sharp humor, biting
social commentary and gratuitous anger and swearing, well, settle
into the sofa, you daring viewer, and get a load of what could be
the season's finest offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action'' stars stand-up comic Jay Mohr (he was the obnoxious
sports agent in ``Jerry Maguire'') as the obnoxious and brutally
frank movie producer Peter Dragon, whose specialty is empty-headed
action movies that have made his parent studio a billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   When Dragon drives onto the studio lot and parks in the spot of
Manny Sanchez, cafeteria worker, who was just awarded that space as
employee of the month, he points out _ in one of the best rants
you'll ever see this side of Dennis Miller _ that he's ``employee
of the (bleeping) century!'' and can park wherever he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Illeana Douglas (``Grace of My Heart'') plays Wendy Ward, a
child star turned Hollywood prostitute who ends up being Dragon's
best evaluator of talent, someone who really knows the pulse of the
nation and won't suck up to him the way his other employees do.
</P>
<P>
   When she's the only one who will tell him the truth _ that his
latest $150 million action picture is a flop _ Dragon's president
of production says, ``She's a whore?'' To which Dragon says, ``No,
she's a prostitute. You're my whore.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Hackett makes a comeback as Dragon's Uncle Lonnie, the
security guard/chauffeur for Dragonfire Films. Believe it or not,
it's fairly inspired casting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action'' is the product of executive producer Chris Thompson
(``The Larry Sanders Show,'' ``The Naked Truth'') and movie
producer Joel Silver (``The Matrix,'' ``Lethal Weapon'). They have
jammed so many industry jokes in the show it's like a poisonous
Valentine to Hollywood. And they make no attempt to explain things.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Dragon's mean and powerful studio boss Bob (Lee
Arenberg) has people in Hollywood scrambling to guess whom he's
modeled after, and several people who may or may not be the model
have already stepped forward to say they are flattered despite his
evilness.
</P>
<P>
   That he's a dead ringer, visually, for Barry Diller may be lost
on 80 percent of the viewers, but Thompson and Silver don't care.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should they. ``Action'' has enough universal themes _ greed,
meanness, Hollywood stupidity, entertainment and, deep down, a big
heart _ that a lot of viewers can glom onto it despite the inside-
baseball approach. Besides, with Silver in tow, the show is
expected to have celebrity cameos every week. That they have Reeves
in the pilot is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and a word on that pilot: ``Action'' is a half-hour sitcom,
but Fox, sensing the building hype, has expanded the premiere to
one hour, but didn't have the final product ready to preview. All
of the 30-minute pilot sent to critics will appear Thursday,
however, and you can rest assured that if the other half is as
funny, you'll be shifting your viewing habits pretty quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Goodman can be reached by e-mail (goodmanexaminer.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
