<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D.BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. If Windows 98 Second Edition requires at least a 486
processor, why do computer makers offer that operating system but
processors at 366, 400 and 450? A. Advertisements for computer
systems are full of confusing numbers and abbreviations. The
confusion in this case is between model numbers and chip-speed
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``486'' you might see in system requirements refers to the
model number for the Intel 80486 microprocessor. The 486, highly
popular with home users in the early 1990s, was the fastest chip
available until Intel introduced the Pentium family of
microprocessors in 1993. The Pentium chip has been through several
generations and is now up to the Pentium III. Other companies, like
Advanced Micro Devices, also manufacture Intel-compatible chips for
PC's.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers you saw in the recent advertisement (366, 400 and
450) were referring to the different clock rates of these newer
microprocessors. The clock rate is the speed at which a
microprocessor can execute instructions, and it is usually measured
in megahertz. Some old 486 chips have a clock rate of 33 megahertz,
but the new Pentium III (or competing brand) chips have clock rates
of 600 MHz, and even faster speeds will be coming along.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I use Windows 98 and my computer screen flickers a lot. What
I can do?
</P>
<P>
   A. You might try changing the refresh rate of your screen to a
different setting. (The refresh rate is how many times your
computer redraws the screen per second.)
</P>
<P>
   Go to the Start menu, then to Settings and Control Panel.
Double-click on Display; in Display Properties, click the Settings
tab. Click on Advanced, then on the Adapter tab to see refresh rate
options, including the Optimal choice for your system. Lowering the
Desktop area setting (also in the Display control panel) could give
you more refresh rate choices.
</P>
<P>
   You might also try calling the makers of your video card and
monitor, or visiting their Web sites for technical support
information. You may be able to download updated device drivers for
your hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3148 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-CHILE-MAGAZINE-TEX     09-15 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-MAGAZINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHILE PEPPER' MAGAZINE SEEKS JUST THE RIGHT BLEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DICK REAVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard enough for magazines to make money, but a bimonthly
magazine about ... peppers? Can a title published in Fort Worth,
Texas, by two men with nothing in common except middle age and,
again, peppers, succeed?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, say ``Chile Pepper'' publisher Joel Gregory and
editor Robb Walsh. They will be unique because their audience is
unique: Of the magazine's 60,000 readers, 70 percent are male.
``Chile Pepper,'' Walsh says, ``is the only cooking magazine in the
country with a predominantly male readership.''
</P>
<P>
   The editor-publisher team plans to turn that difference, like
the differences between the two of them, into an advantage. They
intend to establish grilling and barbecuing as parts of the
magazine's franchise, because outdoor sauces are often spicy _ and
because outdoor cooking is a male favorite. Adopting the prophet's
role, Gregory declares that ``Chile Pepper could become to hot and
spicy foods and outdoor cooking what `Cigar Aficionado' is to
tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Gregory, 51 _ he of the deep-throated drawl _ is a
Fort Worth native, the former pastor of Gambrell Street and Travis
Avenue Baptist churches. For a while, he was also pastor and heir
apparent to W.A. Criswell at First Baptist Church of Dallas. Walsh,
46, from New England and Austin, describes himself as a ``former
hippie'' _ with emphasis on ``hippie,'' not ``former.'' The
contrast between the publisher and editor is apparent even at a
glance: Gregory wears somber Sunday suits and a Rolex. Walsh wears
a mulitcolored Lego watch, no tie and no socks.
</P>
<P>
   Their journal of hot and spicy foods was founded in Albuquerque,
N.M., in 1987. Its first editor, David Dewitt, a New Mexico radio
personality and show promoter, appealed to the eccentricities of
``chileheads'' with articles that carried titles such as
``Armadillo Tamales and Other Delights.'' But he inspired some of
the gastronomy network's talent: Walsh wrote his first magazine
article for Chile Pepper in 1991, an apt piece, ``Confessions of a
Hot Sauce Smuggler.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite management changes, chile fanciers didn't abandon the
magazine. ``We have an extremely loyal readership,'' Gregory says,
pointing to reams of lengthy surveys that subscribers have mailed
to the editors. The magazine has about 40,000 subscribers. To
attract female readers, Gregory and Walsh will pursue the kind of
articles on light and healthful fare that have made ``Cooking
Light'' _ with a circulation of 1.6 million, the largest of the
foodzines _ a hit with women.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest transition for the magazine has to be the
unlikely pairing of the preacher and the hippie. After leaving
Dallas and the daily ministry in 1992, Gregory returned to Fort
Worth to sell cemetery plots and operate a clinic for preachers in
need of sermon seasoning. In 1994, he penned ``Too Great a
Temptation,'' an autobiography of his rise and fall at First
Baptist in Dallas. The book was published by the Summit Group, a
Fort Worth publishing house. Early the next year, when Summit spun
off a magazine firm, the Magnolia Media Group, Gregory entered the
company's ranks as a manager, even giving the new firm its name, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   As an editor and publisher at MMG, which produces a half-dozen
niche and regional titles, including ``Fort Worth'' magazine and
``Pet Life,'' Gregory shepherded ``Chile Pepper'' to press.
Gregory, who says that he has always been a fan of picante fare,
soon began looking for a way to make a name for himself as an
owner-publisher. A former member of his Dallas flock, insurance
magnate Karl Singer, and his sometimes partner, Fort Worth investor
James Goldsmith, came to his aid, and in May the
money-and-Scriptures men bought ``Chile Pepper'' from MMG.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory quickly discovered that ``I was wearing too many hats,''
and decided to hire an editor. When Walsh heard about the opening,
he wasn't sure that he wanted to apply. Austin had been his home
since 1970, when he moved there for college. He was also wary of
Gregory's biblical reputation, and his free-lancing career was in
fine shape, if such a thing is possible. In 1995, his book about
Jamaican fare had been published, followed in 1998 by ``Nuevo
Tex-Mex.'' In February, a book with Reata chef Grady Spears, ``A
Cowboy in the Kitchen,'' had been released. He ran the the Austin
Chronicle Hot Sauce Festival, which Walsh began in 1991 ``because
some people get a buzz from eating chiles,'' and he was a
contributor to National Public Radio's ``Weekend Edition.'' Perhaps
most important, he had just won, for the second time, the James
Beard Journalism Award, ``something like the Academy Awards of the
food business.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh was a bit intrigued by the idea of returning to a magazine
for which he once wrote, and once the contract was completed in
August, Walsh moved into the Fairmount historical neighborhood _
and quickly became enamored of the mag's town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fort Worth'' he says, ``is the Texas that I moved here to live
in in 1970.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways,'' Walsh says, ``the old `Chile Pepper' was a
lifestyle magazine. Under MMG, it became more of a cooking
magazine. I want a marriage of both.''
</P>
<P>
   The wedding of features and readers that Walsh and Gregory plan
to solemnize is not entirely implausible, nor is ``Chile Pepper's''
Fort Worth location a great disadvantage, peers in the magazine
trade say. DeWitt says that in the years since the publication was
born, ``the magazine and chiles have both gone mainstream. Walsh
will give back to the magazine some of the edge that it originally
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Davis, executive editor at ``Cooking Light'' _ published in
Birmingham, Ala. _ observes that ``chile peppers are being
appreciated across more of the United States, thanks probably to
demographic changes such as the expansion of the Latino and Asian
population, and also the fact that people travel more and hear more
through the various media, including new ideas about food and
cooking.'' But tying lifestyle to recipes won't be easy, he
advises, and the magazine's immediate need, he says, is to improve
its editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   The next issue, on sale in October, won't show the full teamwork
of Gregory and Walsh; readers will have to wait until January for
that. With that in mind, ``Cooking Light's'' Davis, a former Austin
resident, recalls the days of a defunct but much-missed Austin
hangout, ``Maybe Gregory and Walsh could use the old Raw Deal sign
as a motto: `It'll be better next time.' '' (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDRV/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
