<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BATTLE AGAINST MOLD AND MILDEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people think of mold and mildew as minor household
annoyances that can be dealt with by spraying with a bathroom
cleaner. This is effective for small patches of mold, but it's not
sufficient to deal with larger infestations, which can become a
serious health hazard. Some environmental inspectors estimate that
at least 10 percent of the houses in the United States have enough
mold contamination to make the occupants sick.
</P>
<P>
   Mold and mildew are common names for a variety of species of
filamentous fungi _ microscopic stalk-like plants that grown on
substances of plant or animal origin, like paper or leather. The
stalks, called mycelium, support the fruit, or spores. Collectively
these plants may look fuzzy; others may look slimy. Both stalks and
spores present some health hazard, but spores are the bigger threat
because they break away from the stalk and become airborne, where
they can easily be inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   They need two things to grow: organic nutrients (paper,
cellulose, dust from the skin or even oil from a fingerprint) and
moisture. They can grow at temperatures between 32 and 95 degrees
Fahrenheit, but most species thrive at common household
temperatures. The moisture may be in the form of water or
moisture-laden air with a relative humidity above 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When the mold digests the organic nutrients, it grows and
releases volatile organic substances like aldehydes, alcohols and
ketones. As these compounds evaporate, they give off the musty odor
that is characteristic of mold and mildew. If the temperature
drops, or the moisture dries up, the mold may stop growing and
become dormant until conditions change and favor renewed feeding
and reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Most homeowners believe that as long as they do not see visible
signs of mold, that is patches of green, blue, or black
discoloration on surfaces, their environment is free of
contamination. What they don't realize, however, is that large
accumulations of mold may be growing in areas that they cannot see,
like air ducts, remote attic or basement spaces, or wall cavities.
Left to multiply, these infestations may produce enough organic
compounds to cause allergic reactions, sickness and, in extreme
cases, death (a possibility with infants).
</P>
<P>
   The only tools you need to look for mold are a strong flashlight
and your nose. The flashlight will help you to see in dark corners
and recesses throughout the house. Your nose will help you detect
the musty odor that means mold is present. You may not be able to
see mold in enclosed areas, but you can often detect it because the
odor-laden spores will drift out through an electrical outlet or
crack in the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Because attic air is generally dry and hot, it might seem an
unlikely place for mildew growth, and, in most cases, it is.
However, a leak in the roof can add enough moisture to allow a mold
colony to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Pay particular attention to air-conditioning systems and
dehumidifiers because they pull water out of the air where it
condenses on cool surfaces. This condensed water can be enough to
nourish a mold colony.
</P>
<P>
   When you discover a light infestation of mold sediment, cleanup
is simple You can spray the area with a bleach solution _ one ounce
of ammonia-free detergent, one quart of household bleach and three
quarts of water _ and wipe clean.
</P>
<P>
   But for heavy concentrations of mold, you will have to take more
precautions. First set up a fan so it blows fresh air in your
direction. Then don goggles, a high-efficiency particulate
air-purifying respirator equipped with a chlorine cartridge and
rubber gloves. Spray the bleach solution on the mold. Use clean
cloths and clear water to wipe the area clean.
</P>
<P>
   Discard the cloths in double plastic bags and dump the rinse
water down the toilet. When the area is dry, vacuum it to remove
residual spores and particles. Do not, however, use an ordinary
household vacuum, which can stir up the spores and circulate them
in the air. Use a high-efficiency particulate air-purifying vacuum
(this can be rented) and go over the entire area.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to clean mildew and mold off porous surfaces
like wallpaper or fabric. It is usually better to remove these
materials and dispose of them in double plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   Removing heavy concentrations of mold from air and heating ducts
is a job for a professional. Consult with a contractor certified by
the National Air Duct Cleaners Association. The contractor will
seal the ducts to keep the mold from spreading through the house,
then use compressed air, high-efficiency particulate air-purifying
vacuums and duct whips to remove it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
