<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3160 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-FUTURE-HOUSE-NYT &LR;      09-15 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FUTURE-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO WINDOWS ON THE WORLD FOR THE DIGITAL HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget bricks and sheetrock. Get past the notion of computer
monitors and television sets. Someday the outside and inside of
your home may consist of liquid crystal displays that function as
walls, windows and multimedia portals.
</P>
<P>
   That's the future of domestic space as envisioned by Hariri &AMP;
Hariri, an architectural firm in New York City known for its
experimental designs.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the firm's most recent conceptual designs, huge
passive LCD screens take the place of walls and windows. When
turned on, the screens act as computer or video monitors,
displaying images, video, text or any other digitized information.
When turned off, the screens are transparent and look like
floor-to-ceiling windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this the building block of the future,'' said Mojgan
Hariri, an Iranian-born architect who co-founded Hariri &AMP; Hariri
with her sister, Gisue. Such blocks, Mojgan Hariri said, could be
prefabricated, off-the-shelf products that people might someday buy
at a place like the Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   A conceptual home based on their vision, which they call the
Digital House, is on display through Oct. 5 at the Museum of Modern
Art in New York. Visitors to a larger MOMA exhibit called the
Un-Private House can see a two-foot model of the house as well as
an animated videotaped rendering of how it might look and feel to
walk through such a space.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday afternoon, more than a dozen people were
gazing with amazement and skepticism at the scenes played out
before them.
</P>
<P>
   The video, for example, shows a person cooking dinner according
to directions given by a restaurant chef who had appeared on the
LCD screen in front of the kitchen counter. In a hallway, music and
video flash from a wall. In the living room, family members gather
to talk with friends who are not physically present but are
displayed in front of the sofa, larger than life.
</P>
<P>
   The architects envision people being able to unplug themselves
from such interactivity, too. When the screens are turned off,
``you can see beyond and through to nature,'' Mojgan Hariri said.
``It is that flexibility that we are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   They came up with the Digital House concept a year ago for an
article in House Beautiful magazine. Since then, Mojgan Hariri
said, ``a few people have come forward and want to build the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   But the technology is not quite as advanced as she and her
sister would like. Liquid crystal displays that can switch from
opaque to clear already exist, but images are projected onto the
screens. Hariri &AMP; Hariri are waiting for screens that are as smart
as computers, that essentially have no need for projectors. They do
not want designs to be hampered by the logistics of hiding
projectors in walls and ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   The two sisters have talked to manufacturers like Philips and
Samsung about such a concept. ``Everyone is enthusiastic about the
possibilities of it,'' Mojgan Hariri said. ``But right now, they
are so busy they cannot even catch up with themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The hitch might revolve around more than simply a lack of time.
Display technology has inherent limitations, said Paul Semenza,
director of market analysis for Stanford Resources, a
market-research company that specializes in display technology.
Today's active displays, which are known as direct-view displays,
must include tubes or grids to provide color and definition. The
apparatus is hardly transparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Displays have a function of producing images, and that is
contradictory to using this as a window onto the world,'' Semenza
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another barrier may be cost. Considering the cost of flat-panel
televisions, Ms. Hariri imagines that a screen as large as 4 feet
by 8 feet _ a size that she imagines as a useful building block _
would most likely cost between $10,000 and $15,000 today. And
that's not even taking into account the technology required to turn
the screens into windows.
</P>
<P>
   But she adds: ``It's like anything else. I'll bet in two years,
the price of these screens will come down to $2,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Terence Riley, the curator of the MOMA exhibit, dismisses the
talk of technological limitation, calling it ``short-term''
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house is already an increasingly media-driven
environment,'' Riley said. ``This is a logical conclusion of what
is already a commonplace situation in the typical house.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley suggested that the technological building block that
architects would use might not even be the LCD but some other
technology. ``But the desire for these things is so great _ these
facades that can give information,'' he said, ``that I do think it
is eventually going to become possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
