<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV03-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., OCT. 3, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The rural house we recently moved into has no smoke alarms
and we would like to install as many as needed. Where should we
locate them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some local codes require one in each bedroom, but most people
install one outside the door of each bedroom or sleeping area. Do
not install them more than about 10 or 12 feet away from the
bedroom door, and don't place them in the kitchen, furnace room or
workshop where many false alarms (due to fumes, etc.) can occur.
Also, place them at least 10 or 12 inches away from wall and
ceiling corners as shown here, but make sure they are at least
three feet away from open windows and cold air or return duct
openings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to paint the front of my dishwasher to help
spruce up my kitchen. What kind of paint do you think I should use?
</P>
<P>
   A: The toughest paint would be a two-part epoxy paint, but you
can also use any good grade of alkyd enamel. If you do decide to
use an epoxy, bear in mind that careful and thorough preparation of
the surface is essential _ so read and follow directions carefully.
Even with an alkyd you have to clean and sand the surface before
painting, but in general this type of paint is more ``forgiving''
than an epoxy if you are not as thorough in the preparation of the
old surface.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My house is on a busy street with lots of traffic, so noise
is always a problem during the day and early evening hours. The
windows have only a single pane of glass, so I am wondering if I
can reduce the noise by installing storm windows over each window,
or by replacing the old ones with new double-pane windows. Which do
you think would offer the best chance of noise reduction and be
most economical?
</P>
<P>
   A: Storm sash would certainly cost a lot less and if properly
installed (with good caulking around the frames) they would
probably help reduce noise just as much as replacing the existing
windows with more expensive new double-pane models.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to install a large whole-house attic fan to help cool
the house during the summer after the sun goes down, but I am
confused about how and where the fan should be installed. Should I
lay it horizontally over the opening in the upstairs ceiling and
directly over the louvers on the attic floor to permit the fan to
draw air up from below, or should I install the fan vertically
against one of the end walls in the attic?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although both methods are used, installing the fan
horizontally over the ceiling louvers is easier and often more
effective as there is less chance of drawing hot air in from
outside if the attic is not really airtight (often impossible in
attics that have openings around the eaves for venting
condensation). However, you will also have to install louvered
openings at each end of the attic so that the exhausted air can
escape easily to the outside. These openings must have a total
unobstructed area that is at least 10 percent larger than the fan's
ceiling opening.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``SMOKE DETECTOR PLACEMENT'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Smoke detectors should be installed at least 12 inches
away from each corner, whether on the ceiling or wall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
