<HEADER>
A3176 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VOYNICH-NYT &LR;      09-15 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VOYNICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T READ IT? YOU CAN LOOK AT THE PICTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn.)   (af)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alien life forms! Hidden messages! Secret formulas! Naked women!
</P>
<P>
   That's not what one would expect from a European manuscript that
appears to be about 400 years old. But this 7-by-10-inch, 234-page
parchment book in the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library at
Yale University has all that and more.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Voynich manuscript after Wilfred M. Voynich, a book
dealer who bought it in 1912 and tried for many years to unlock its
secrets, the book is a Holy Grail of sorts for cryptographers, as
well as other devotees of the unusual.
</P>
<P>
   So what is this book about? That's a good question. What does it
say? Nobody knows. It has never been read, because no one can
translate it.
</P>
<P>
   You can try reading it yourself, or at least see the pictures,
at www.geocities.com/Athens/Delphi/8389/voygal1.htm. An extensive
commentary on the manuscript, including its history and a summary
of theories as to its origin, is at www.voynich.nu, a site by Rene
Zandbergen, who is engaged in a European project to try to crack
its code.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, I don't think that anyone believes the MS to contain
any historical secrets, but it is regrettable that this has been
used as an excuse to stop funding its research,'' Zandbergen wrote
by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Describing its appeal to code-breakers, he wrote: ``Some of the
greatest brains in cryptography of the 20th century have been
baffled by someone from the Middle Ages.'' He likened it to a high
school football team devising a game plan that baffles the Miami
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Students are fairly sure of a few facts: The manuscript existed
by the early 1600s, and was owned by various people in the court of
King Rudolph II of Bohemia (1552-1612) in Prague. Rudolph, who was
also Holy Roman Emperor, was an eccentric who was fascinated with
the occult, and attracted numerous scholars, pseudo-scientists and
mystics.
</P>
<P>
   A faint signature in the manuscript has been identified as that
of Jacobus Horcicki de Tepenecz, Rudolph's doctor, herbalist and
alchemist. The manuscript passed to another Bohemian court
physician, Johannes Marci of Prague, who gave it in about 1665 to
the Rev. Athanasius Kircher, a Jesuit scientist and mathematician
who was an expert on codes.
</P>
<P>
   Then it went to an Italian monastery, where it remained until
Voynich bought it. A letter enclosed with the manuscript, from
Marci to Kircher in Rome, states that Rudolph had paid 600 ducats
for it.
</P>
<P>
   It is lavishly illustrated with detailed plants and flowers,
none of which match any known plant. Some have human faces. There
are astrological symbols and drawings galore, which remain a
mystery. And adorning many of the flowers, buildings and other
drawings are tiny nude figures.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge is the writing. The manuscript's estimated
250,000 characters are in no known alphabet. They are arranged in
groups like words, and certainly look like a language, but no one
has ever conclusively translated a single page.
</P>
<P>
   The Voynich is the most studied medieval manuscript in the
Beinecke Library, attracting several hundred academics a year and a
good many more amateur scholars. It also attracts devotees who tend
to be passionate about their theories.
</P>
<P>
   The Beinecke sells microfilm and prints of the manuscript, and
is on line at www.library.yale.edu/beinecke.
</P>
<P>
   Serious academic students tend to be from the fields of
mathematics, statistics and linguistics. Some of the most dedicated
Voynich cryptographers have worked for the Army or the National
Security Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manuscript itself seems to have the attraction of a
poisonous flower,'' William R. Bennett Jr., emeritus professor of
engineering and applied science at Yale and a Voynich expert, wrote
by e-mail. ``Quite a few people have wasted the final decades of
their lives trying to decipher it and reacting to the numerous
pictures in it as if it were some kind of medieval Rorschach test.
Good luck, but be careful!''
</P>
<P>
   People have suggested that the manuscript is a heretical tract
by Isis followers, or an astronomical thesis by Roger Bacon, the
13th-century Franciscan, or an almanac, or an alchemist's guide, or
a secret list of herbal remedies.
</P>
<P>
   A widespread opinion is that the manuscript was created to
separate Rudolph from his ducats, and that much of the writing (but
not necessarily all) is gibberish.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best guess is that the manuscript was a deliberate hoax,''
Bennett wrote, naming John Dee, an English mathematician and
astrologer at Rudolph's court, as the likely suspect. ``I suppose
he argued that it contained the secret of eternal life, wanted a
high price for his efforts, and didn't want to create anything that
could be deciphered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
