<HEADER>
A3177 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TESTS-LATINOS-0916-CO     09-15 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTS-LATINOS-0916-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LATINOS WORRY THAT THEIR CHILDREN FACE UNFAIR TESTS
 &HT;    300&AMP;add
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of thousands of children who are still
learning English are being harmed by the invalid use of some
standardized tests that measure progress in public school reforms,
the Presidential Advisory Commission on Educational Excellence for
Hispanic Americans reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Office of Civil rights should investigate the use of
tests with Hispanic students, especially English language
learners,'' recommended the 21-member commission, which was formed
by President Clinton six years ago. It also called upon the federal
government to fund more research into how to avoid bias in tests
administered to Hispanic students.
</P>
<P>
   ``State policies often require that Hispanic students be
assessed in English with tests they may not even understand, or
with alternative but less rigorous tests in Spanish, whether or not
they are receiving instruction in that language,'' said the
commission's report. ``Neither approach produces accurate
information about student learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet children with low scores on those tests risk being denied
promotion to the next grade or a regular high school diploma, the
commission said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many states exempt Spanish-speaking students
from tests intended to discover which schools or districts need
outside intervention or extra resources to get up to par. So those
schools don't get the extra help their students need in order to
master the English language and other subjects, the commission
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in high-stakes tests, and of course there are valid
tests,'' said the commission's chair, Ana ``Cha'' Margarita Guzman,
executive vice president of Austin Community College in Texas.
``However, the stakes need to be high for the school districts and
the schools _ not for the children.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The commission singled out Texas as an example of a state that
for the most part uses valid tests correctly in measuring
educational results. But it argued that the educational needs of
some some students may be neglected during the ``grace period'' in
which they are exempt from assessment tests until their English
skills are improved.
</P>
<P>
   In California, tests designed to diagnose learning problems are
instead being used improperly as a measure of language proficiency,
said a commission member, Sonia Hernandez, deputy superintendent of
the California Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has the opposite problem, where districts sometimes use
``tests that do not assess the students' content knowledge, but
assess their language fluency,'' said another commissioner, Erlina
Paize Archuleta of the Colorado Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   While elementary school students in Colorado can take tests in
their native language, funds haven't been made available to develop
similar tests for middle or high school students, she said.
</P>
<P>
   About half the nation's school districts have some students
learning English as a second language. Seven out of 10 are from
Spanish-speaking families, the commission said. Most of the Spanish
speakers live in California, Texas, New York, Florida or Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The commission recently began work on a state-by-state analysis
of the use of high-stakes tests. Its preliminary research showed:
</P>
<P>
   -- Nearly 20 states have adopted reforms in which graduation or
promotions to the next grade can depend completely or in part on
tests the children may not understand. For example, math tests can
contain word problems that pose trouble to youngsters who are not
native to the language of the test.
</P>
<P>
   -- In 40 of the 49 states that use tests of students to learn
which schools need intervention or extra resources, students with
limited English proficiency are exempted from all or some of the
key tests.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said that Texas and North Carolina are the only
states in which minority and disadvantaged children are rapidly
closing the gap between their performance and those of other
students on statewide exams. Texas, Oregon and Minnesota were
singled out as states that have made great progress in developing
``fair and accurate'' standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
