r l BC-DIANEREHM-VOICE-TEX     09-15 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANEREHM-VOICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK SHOW HOST FIGHTS TO KEEP HER VOICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Diane Rehm loses her voice, 700,000 people know it _ almost
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   She hesitates, strains and struggles to get the words out.
Listening to her over the radio, you can't help but feel her
distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strangled hoarseness fills my voice with tremors and makes
me sound like a very old woman,'' Rehm says. ``It's very
frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   And she never knows when it might happen.
</P>
<P>
   This week, her voice is strong and pleasant. It doesn't sound
like the typical radio-talk-show voice, if only because it is more
respectful and less sarcastic and flippant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had six Botox injections, and my voice is quite strong,''
she says in a telephone visit. ``I will go as long as I can without
another. When I need another, believe me, I'll know it. I'll hear
it on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been five weeks since Rehm's last injection with Botox,
the brand name for the purified botulinum toxin that doctors at
Johns Hopkins Outpatient Center periodically inject directly into
her vocal cords to relax them and prevent them from clamping
together so tightly as to prevent the flow of speech.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a cough and slight tremor in Rehm's voice seven
years ago was finally diagnosed about 18 months ago as ``spasmodic
dysphonia,'' a type of dystonia or involuntary muscle spasm that
interferes with speech.
</P>
<P>
   The cause is still unknown and there is no cure, but there are
several treatments, including Botox and a drug used to control
epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two weeks after her first Botox injection, Rehm
had no voice. It took five weeks for her voice to come back enough
to resume her popular radio talk show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't lose my voice at all, this last time,'' she says.
``It got very weak and breathy, but I never lost my voice
completely. I'm very lucky. I have no real side effects from the
botulinum. There have been people taking it as long as 15 years
without long-term side effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehm timed her last injection so she would have three weeks to
get her voice back before leaving on a tour two weeks ago to
promote her new book, ``Finding My Voice.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, an autobiography, chronicles Rehm's traumatic
childhood and her quest to find her voice, figuratively and
literally, as a Washington talk-show host.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes referred to as the female voice of public radio, Rehm,
who will turn 63 on Tuesday, says she never expected to have a
career.
</P>
<P>
   She was 37 with less than a year of college when she volunteered
in 1973 to work on ``The Home Show,'' a program at American
University's radio station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would marry and have children and be a wife and
mother, but I never expected any type of career. It was so
unexpected and late in life, out of the blue, an aberration _ young
Arab girl with no college education volunteers to work at radio
station,'' Rehm says.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 20 years, she has conducted live interviews with
Al Gore, Hillary Clinton, Gen. Colin Powell, Archbishop Desmond
Tutu, novelist John Grisham, actresses Liv Ullman, Audrey Hepburn
and Lauren Bacall, and hundreds of other politicians, writers and
movie stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``What causes the switchboard to light up and brings people to
radio is dealing with serious subjects that really concern
listeners, no matter who your guest is,'' Rehm says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to treat each guest and each caller with respect _
bring light instead of heat to each subject, no matter what you are
talking about or who you are talking with. That's what brings
people to radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the presidential campaign is over, Rehm would like to
talk to each candidate, and she believes she will get the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to hear each one's tone of voice, how he or she
interacts with listeners. I want to hear how they respond to
listeners' questions. I'm not interested in hammering away at them,
but in hearing how they sound as human beings,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, I would like to talk to the president before he leaves
office. I would like the chance to sit down for an hour's true
conversation with listeners one-on-one, our listeners around the
country _ no screening out.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rehm has some other plans. Roger Mudd will be the
host for a black-tie gala Tuesday to celebrate Rehm's birthday and
the 20th anniversary of ``The Diane Rehm Show'' and to raise money
for American University's radio program. First lady Hillary Clinton
is the honorary chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of my career, my voice meant everything, but I was
able to say, `If this is God's will, I have had a wonderful career
for which I can be very thankful,' '' Rehm says. ``I pray a lot for
healing and strength, but I am one of the lucky ones. If it's never
any better than this, and I have to continue the injections, I can
live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the various forms of dystonia, including
spasmodic dysphonia, call the Dystonia Medical Research Foundation
at (800) 377-3978 or the National Spasmodic Dysphonia Association
at (800) 795-6732.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDRV/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
