<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3189 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VERTICAL-MOUSE-2T     09-15 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VERTICAL-MOUSE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN A MOUSE THAT ROARS CAN SIT ON THE SIDELINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas, N.C., Ohio)   (af)  
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Build a better mousetrap, and the world will beat a path to your
door. It stands to reason that the time-worn adage about innovation
and capitalist reward would apply to better mice as well, at least
of the computer variety.
</P>
<P>
   By that measure, the vertical mouse, which resembles a gamer's
joystick, ought to be poised for commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, The International Journal of Human-Computer
Interaction, a respected quarterly, published a study that said
switching to the odd-looking mouse had reduced the pain suffered by
computer users in their hands, arms and necks and also trimmed the
number of workdays lost to sick leave.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the past is any guide, the Anir Vertical mouse, also
known as Dr. Mouse, faces an uphill struggle, and its producer,
Animax International of Norway, will not be minting a fortune
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Industry history, economics and human nature resist an insurgent
product unless it promises a huge improvement in price or
performance or some other benefit. Economists call the forces
favoring the incumbent product ``lock-in'' and describe the steep
hurdle faced by an innovative newcomer as high ``switching costs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, it's the brain that is the real lock-in _ people's
habits are so difficult to change,'' said Hal Varian, an economist
at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ergonomic computer keyboards and mice have
found it frustratingly difficult to make major inroads. As many as
20 percent of the nation's 150 million computer users, especially
those working on their machines for four hours or more a day, are
considered by experts to be at risk of suffering repetitive stress
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Most ergonomic products try to reduce the strain of computer
work by putting the hands in a more natural position _ tilted with
the thumbs raised somewhat instead of having the hands splayed
flat, as they are when typing on a conventional keyboard or when
manipulating a standard mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful ergonomic product by far has been the
Microsoft Natural Keyboard, a wave-shaped, split keyboard that
raises the thumbs and separates the hands. Indeed, Microsoft's
hardware unit _ which produces mainly keyboards, mice and joysticks
_ is a quiet success story within the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a success story that contradicts the repeated claim
of the company's critics that Microsoft owes its success to the
inherent and unfair edge it enjoys because of its industry-standard
Windows operating system. Microsoft has no natural advantage in
hardware other than a well-known brand and deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rick Thompson, vice president of the hardware unit, said the
Natural Keyboard, introduced in 1994, did not take the market by
storm, as he had hoped. Today, roughly 120 million PCs are shipped
worldwide each year, nearly all of them with flat keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called aftermarket for replacement or enhanced keyboards
is about 3 million, and one in five of those have an ergonomic
design. In the ergonomic keyboard niche, Microsoft holds an
estimated two-thirds of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``You simply can't cause most people to change from the standard
design even if your product is better,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's sense that the best product does not always win in
the marketplace is contradicted, however, by two economists who
have sided with Microsoft in its antitrust battle with the
government. Stanley J. Liebowitz, a professor of managerial
economics at the University of Texas at Dallas, and Stephen E.
Margolis, a professor of economics at North Carolina State
University, argue in their new book, ``Winners, Losers and
Microsoft: Competition and Antitrust in High Technology''
(Independent Institute) that the best products do come out on top.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They say the importance of economic lock-in and switching costs
are vastly exaggerated, and that Microsoft's dominates the PC
software market thanks to hard work and superior business acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Liebowitz and Margolis are known for their shrewd critique of a
classic story about the success of a second-best product _ the
Qwerty keyboard layout, which became the standard design in the
1880s when it was used in vocational schools to teach touch-typing.
Later designs, notably the Dvorak keyboard, were said to allow
faster typing, but they never caught on. But Liebowitz and Margolis
concluded that August Dvorak had inflated his claims for his
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Liebowitz and Margolis have a bit more trouble explaining
away the leading modern example of what is often said to be a
second-best winner, Microsoft's DOS and, later, Windows, which
mimicked the look of Apple's Macintosh operating system, which was
introduced in 1984. They dismiss the Mac's several-year lead over
Windows, until recently, in ease of use as merely superior
``elegance'' _ not a real consideration, economically, they
suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it remains to be seen whether an innovation like the
vertical mouse can overcome the daunting challenges it faces.
</P>
<P>
   The field study just reported seems encouraging. It was
conducted by Dr. Arne Aaras, coordinator of health medical services
in Norway for Alcatel, the European telecommunications company, and
two assistants over six months.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at 69 computer users; it measured pain by using
questionnaires. Pain levels dropped 30 percent to 50 percent.
Alcatel and the Norwegian government financed the study.
</P>
<P>
   Other ergonomic experts are impressed. Marvin Dainoff, director
of the Center for Ergonomic Research at Miami University in Ohio,
called the study powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the hurdles of habit and price are high. Researchers say
that it takes a day or so to learn how to use the vertical mouse
and that performance drops slightly.
</P>
<P>
   And the Anir Vertical mouse costs $50. ``Anything that knocks up
the price of a system is very tough to sell,'' said Neal Taslitz,
president of Humantouch Products.
</P>
<P>
   Mouse experts at Microsoft have not ruled out a vertical design,
but they are skeptical. ``You have to take account of the social
context in which a product will be used,'' said Edie Adams,
ergonomics manager of the company's hardware unit. ``A vertical
mouse would take a lot of motivation on the buyer's part.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Getting information into a handheld device has become easier
because handwriting recognition software has improved. But a
keyboard is still the preferred method for entering lots of text.
Keyboards for handheld devices are available, but until now, none
have been the size of a regular keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   A new company, Think Outside, in Solana Beach, Calif., announced
this week a folding keyboard called the Stowaway, for handheld
devices. Folded, the unit is about the size of a Palm III or the
new Handspring Visor and fits, though a little tightly, in a shirt
pocket. It opens up, like an accordion, into a full-size keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Oldort, Think Outside's chief executive and inventor of the
keyboard, said that the need for such a keyboard for the millions
of handheld devices in use was obvious. ``It's like the missing
piece of a puzzle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the keyboard won't be available until the holiday buying
season, Palm Computing has already committed to putting its name on
a version of it. Versions will be available for the Visor at the
same time and a Windows CE version will be available the first of
the year. The unit is expected to sell for less than $100.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
