<HEADLINE>
REPAIR KIT AVAILABLE FOR RECALLED INFANT CAR SEATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I own a Cosco infant car seat. Which ones were affected by
the recent safety recall? _ M.P., Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   A: In July, Cosco recalled Arriva and Turnabout infant car
seat/carriers that were made from March 1995 to September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Arriva seats with the following model numbers are being
recalled: 02-665, 02729, 02-731, 02-732, 02-733, 02-751, 02-756 and
02-757.
</P>
<P>
   Turnabout seats with these numbers are being recalled: 02-758,
02-759, 02-760, 02-761, 02-762, 02-763, 02-764, 02-765 and 02-667.
</P>
<P>
   The seats can unexpectedly become unlocked when used as an
infant carrier, causing a child to fall out. There have been 29
reports of children being injured, according to the Consumer
Product Safety Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Until you receive a free repair kit from Cosco, you should not
use these seats as infant carriers. To request a kit or more
information, call the company at (800) 221-6736.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My son is a huge fan of the Bigfoot monster truck. Is there a
club he can join? _ E.L.D., Bedford, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The Bigfoot International Fan Club costs $9.99 for a
three-year membership. Members receive five 8-by-10 photos,
postcards, a newsletter and a birthday surprise.
</P>
<P>
   To join, write to Bigfoot 4X4, 6311 N. Lindbergh Blvd., Dept.
SK, Hazelwood, MO 63042-2876.
</P>
<P>
   The original Bigfoot is a modified 1974 Ford F250 Pickup that
stands 10 feet 6 inches high and weighs 11,000 pounds. Bob Chandler
began modifying it in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   There's an official Bigfoot World Wide Web site at
www.bigfoot4x4.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that the actor Chuck Connors played Major League
baseball briefly. What were his stats like? _ S.G., via the
Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Connors played one game for the Brooklyn Dodgers in 1949 and
66 games for the Chicago Cubs in 1951, according to ``Total
Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed first baseman hit .238 in 202 at-bats, with two
home runs, 18 runs batted in and four stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Connors, who died in 1992 at age 71, also played basketball for
the Boston Celtics. In 1946, the first home game in team history
was delayed for an hour because the 6-foot-5 Connors broke a wooden
backboard with a pre-game dunk.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
