<HEADER>
A3258 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-OUTER-COX     09-15 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-OUTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outer Banks braces for another storm
 &HT;    By Cindi Courbat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CURRITUCK, N.C. _ With the clean-up from Hurricane Dennis still
under way, North Carolina's Outer Banks waited for an even bigger,
and potentially more dangerous, hurricane today.
</P>
<P>
   Packing 155 mph winds, Floyd bypassed Florida on Tuesday and, as
of early Wednesday evening, was headed straight for the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   By 7 a.m. Wednesday, Currituck County issued a mandatory
evacuation for its off-road north beaches _ joining other
oceanfront communities from Florida to Virginia where an estimated
two million people have already fled their homes.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m., a mandatory evacuation order was also put into
effect for Currituck's low-lying areas, including Knotts Island and
Gibbs Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Weather Service flood prediction models indicate storm surge of
eight to 10 feet in the Currituck Sound, Lambertson added. There is
a high potential for flooding in all of the low-lying areas
adjacent to the Sound, he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Vann, fire chief at Corova Beach, said about 70 families _
mostly tourists _ had left the area by noon and the rest were
expected to leave by 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting real good response,'' Vann said. ``Fire and
rescue workers have been calling and going door-to-door in an
effort to get everyone off the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Vann said the north gate leading through the Back Bay Refuge
into Virginia Beach, Va., has been open all day, and would remain
open as long as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Dyer, owner of Karichele Realty in Corolla, said
Wednesday that about 300 short-term renters have evacuated the
north beaches over the past 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about 30 houses in the four-wheel drive area _ each
with an average of ten tenants,'' Dyer said. ``We expect everyone
to be gone from there by nightfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyer said the evacuation process is going more smoothly for
Floyd than it did two weeks ago when Hurricane Dennis threatened
the coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem better prepared and more willing to leave (than
they were for Dennis),'' she said. ``It still isn't clear where
they can go _ but they seem willing to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The back gate leads only to Virginia's beaches _ so that isn't a
final solution for those who have been evacuated from Currituck,
Vann said. Most evacuees will have to drive much further north or
west to reach safety, he said. Dyer said she has been advising
tenants to head as far north as Richmond and as far west as Raleigh
to escape danger, and to find alternative shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being told that every motel room in North Carolina is
already booked,'' Lambertson reported.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of available motels and shelters poses a serious
problem for many beach residents, Currituck County Commissioner
Ernie Bowden said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's right to force people to evacuate without
providing a nearby shelter for them to go to,'' he said. ``I have
voiced this opinion to local officials for many years _ and I don't
know why they refuse to open Knotts Island and other local schools
to use as shelters.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bowden, many older people and indigents are being
forced to stay in their homes _ even through mandatory evacuations
_ simply because they can't afford to drive two or three hours away
and then pay for motel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were up to me, I'd open up every school in Currituck
County to use as a shelter _ but I am just one voice on a board
that is opposed to that idea,'' Bowden said. ``They say they don't
want the liability of opening a shelter but the truth is they
assume liability every time they use the school for civic
activities _ and they are assuming a greater liability by leaving
these people out here in the storm with no where to go and no way
to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
