<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3260 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     09-15 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZER, PAGER, TOY, PHONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a Palm!
</P>
<P>
   It's a Phone!
</P>
<P>
   It's a Game!
</P>
<P>
   It slices, it dices, it shreds and makes radish rosettes, just
by changing the blade. It sews buttons on your shirt, catches big
fish, takes out even the toughest stains, and fits in your pocket.
It removes unsightly blemishes, never needs sharpening, and alerts
the authorities in case you fall down and can't get up. But wait!
There's more ...
</P>
<P>
   Aficionados of late-night television advertising are familiar
with consumer devices that promise to perform 101 different tasks,
just by turning a knob or switching an attachment.
</P>
<P>
   The palm-size computer world is about to be treated to similar
claims, in the form of a new and very promising little personal
digital assistant called the Visor, made by a new company called
Handspring Inc. The company said it would begin taking orders for
the Visor at its web site (www.handspring.com) any day now, for
delivery in October and November. The new product will not be in
retail stores until early next year. Prices range from $149 to
$249, depending on the model.
</P>
<P>
   The Visor is promising on several levels. On its most
fundamental level, it is a fully compatible, slightly smaller and
less expensive clone of the palm-size computer now sold by the 3Com
Corp.'s Palm Computing division. The Visor was created by the same
people who invented the original Palm Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The Visor uses the Palm OS operating system, which allows it to
take advantage of the thousands of home-made and commercial
applications written for the Palm Pilot. It weighs a little more
than 5 ounces, is about the size of a pack of playing cards, runs
for weeks on a pair of AAA batteries, and has the same infrared
capabilities as the Palm, enabling people to ``beam'' their contact
information to one another wirelessly.
</P>
<P>
   But even more promising is a little slot on the back of the
Visor, called the Springboard slot, which allows the user to plug
in a variety of matchbook-sized modules that perform specialized
tasks. Depending on the module that is inserted, the Visor can
slice, dice and otherwise process data in a variety of interesting
ways, and transform itself into a seemingly endless variety of
tools. It is sort of a Swiss Army pocket computer.
</P>
<P>
   Handspring executives said a number of Springboard modules would
be offered in coming months, including wireless phones and voice
recorders (the Visor has a tiny built-in microphone), data and fax
modems, MP3 music players, one-way and two-way pagers, graphing
calculators, bar-code readers, Global Positioning System units,
games, and even heart monitors and scientific probes.
</P>
<P>
   One minute the Visor is a language translator; the next, with a
headset, it becomes a portable digital music player or a cell
phone. Snap in the right module, and it draws a map to the nearest
gas station or ATM machine, calls up stock quotes, and checks your
V-mail (voice mail) and e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, however, the Visor's slot is full of promise, and
not much else. The only module that Handspring made available for
testing before its formal debut this week was the Tiger Woods PGA
Tour Golf card ($29.95). I suppose one could argue that it is
productivity software, in that Woods is a well-known efficiency
expert known for getting around a golf course with an economy of
effort. But some sticklers would call it a game.
</P>
<P>
   Handspring says that some 20 Springboard modules and accessories
will be available by the end of this year. The big challenge will
be to get more major hardware and software companies to support the
Springboard technology.
</P>
<P>
   The way the slot works is almost as interesting as the potential
applications for it. One of the charms of the Palm Pilot, compared
to rival devices, is its simplicity. Hit the power button and it
turns on, without churning through a boot-up process. The same is
true for the Handspring modules that slide into the Visor's slot.
</P>
<P>
   Each module is expected to be self-contained, with everything
needed to simply plug in and launch. The user will not have to load
any diskettes or CD-ROM drivers, nor issue any commands to launch
or shut down the software. When the application is no longer
needed, the user just pops out the module and plugs in something
else. Compared to other versatile devices like the Windows CE-based
PDA's, the Visor is a snap to use.
</P>
<P>
   There are three different versions of the Visor. The most
popular model is likely to be the basic Visor ($179). It comes with
2 megabytes of RAM, which is sufficient to hold thousands of
addresses, several years' worth of appointments and to-do items,
and far more e-mail messages than one ought to be carrying around
in one's pocket. It also comes with a cradle that connects to the
USB port of any desktop or laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   The USB connection is very smart, and an order of magnitude
faster than the serial port connections used by the original Palm
Pilot. Most newer computers come with a USB port or two, but people
with older computers can order a serial connector for the Visor.
</P>
<P>
   The version I tested was the Visor Deluxe ($249), which includes
8MB of RAM. Handspring says this is enough space to store 12,000
addresses, 10 years worth of appointments, 6,000 to-do items, 6,000
memos and 400 e-mail messages. This seems like a lot of to-dos,
even compared to the list of chores my wife hands me each weekend,
and I have yet to meet the poor wretch who actually needs instant
access to 6,000 memos.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the practical use for all that added memory is for Palm
OS software applications that the user can transfer into the Visor
through a desktop computer. Loading a lot of downloaded games will
eat up memory, for example. Or, larger businesses may want more
memory for custom applications like technical manuals or product
data bases. The memory requirements are reduced somewhat by the
ability of Springboard modules to take care of their own memory
needs without drawing on the Visor's built-in RAM.
</P>
<P>
   The Visor Deluxe comes in a clear case or in a choice of three
translucent colors (what a concept!) or black-gray. It also has a
leather carrying case.
</P>
<P>
   The third model is the Visor Solo ($149), which comes without
the synchronization cradle and cable needed to connect to a PC.
About the only reason I can think of to buy one of these is if the
household already has another Visor and does not need two cradles.
</P>
<P>
   Handspring said the Visor and Visor Deluxe models would not be
shipped until October, although the company says it will soon be
taking orders (and money) at its Web site  &UR; (www.handspring.com &LR; .
The Visor Solo will not be shipped until November, the company
said. The delayed shipping date, along with the initial paucity of
plug-in modules and the fact that the Visor is not available in
retail stores, all combine to force Handspring's early customers to
take a leap of faith based on the impressive track record of the
original Palm Pilot developers.
</P>
<P>
   The Visor works smoothly with both Windows and Macintosh
computers, and swaps data with leading contact management programs
including Microsoft Outlook.
</P>
<P>
   The 3Com Corp., meanwhile, disclosed plans this week to spin off
the Palm Computing division as a separate company. Such a move
could free the Palm team from the gravitational drag of the larger
computer networking company and perhaps lead to more aggressive
pricing and product design.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely rumored that 3Com is also preparing some changes
for its own line of Palm Pilot computers, including price
reductions across its product line and even the addition of a
variety of translucent colors (what will they think of next?). The
company has also said it is on schedule to begin selling its
innovative Palm VII computer nationwide this fall. The Palm VII,
which until now has been available only in the New York City area,
allows the user to send and receive e-mail by radio and download
information like stock quotes and sports scores clipped from World
Wide Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   As always, competition benefits the consumer. The least
expensive Palm model today, the Palm IIIe, was introduced just last
month with a list price of $229. To remain competitive with the new
$179 Handspring Visor, which matches and surpasses the IIIe in
features, 3Com will have to cut the price by at least $50.
</P>
<P>
   The Handspring Visor really, really works _ just like a Palm
Pilot. It costs less and does more, at least in theory, although in
my tests it was unable to make julienne fries, remove lint or slice
a ripe tomato.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-TREE-STUDIOS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-15 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREE-STUDIOS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAINST DEVELOPERS, CHICAGO ARTISTS BATTLE THE CLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Barton Faist is sick of the uncertainty of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken a toll,'' said Faist, a soft-spoken artist who is
battling to save his studio and home here in Tree Studios, a
wondrous amalgam of gables, carved heads, stained-glass windows and
chiseled aphorisms, a project dreamt up by a turn-of-the-century
philanthropist for struggling artists _ like Faist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Faist, 44, paced as he recited war stories of 17 years of
fighting his landlords, the Shriners, who are trying to sell the
increasingly valuable property to developers. For most of those
years, the developers have had another dream: razing all those
gables and mottos to build the New Chicago, another glossy, glassy
apartment tower to add to the city's rapidly expanding collection.
</P>
<P>
   This week, fearing the result of this relentless clash of new
and old, the World Monuments Fund named Tree Studios one of the
world's 100 most endangered places, right next to Machu Picchu in
Peru and the Valley of the Kings near Luxor, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Why is a charming but down-at-the-heels artists' enclave in the
heart of Chicago deserving of such attention? ``Because the threat
is so immediate,'' Bonnie Burnham, the fund's president, said.
``People may not think of Tree Studios as one of the world's
undying treasures, like Machu Picchu, but it has an extremely
interesting history.'' John Singer Sargent is said to have painted
in the courtyard; Frank Lloyd Wright visited his disciples here; J.
Allen St. John illustrated the Tarzan books here; at different
times Burgess Meredith and Peter Falk, then struggling artists,
struggled here before finding their true calling.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the fate of the compound, created in 1894 by Judge
Lambert Tree and the oldest such artists' enclave in the country,
is in limbo. The city, in cooperation with the Shriners, who have
owned it since 1959, has imposed a nine-month moratorium on just
about anything having to do with Tree Studios and the Shriners'
1913 Medinah Temple, which together take up the full block on State
Street between Ontario and Ohio Streets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a contentious hearing in 1997, the City Council, which can
vote down any landmark designation, thwarted the recommendation of
the Commission on Chicago Landmarks to designate all of Tree
Studios and listed only the front facade and the roof line on State
Street. Anyone buying the property could have legally ripped down
the Moorish Medinah Temple and most of Tree Studios.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half after the City Council's action and just as
the Shriners were ready to talk with developers, the local
alderman, who had backed the studios' vastly reduced landmark
designation, proposed new hearings to include the rest of the
complex. The Shriners threatened to sue. But even as they rattled
the legal saber, they signed an agreement with Steven Fifield, a
Chicago developer, to sell the block for $21 million. He quickly
drew up d plans to gut Tree Studios and tear down Medinah Temple to
build a tall tower and parking garage. At that point, Mayor Richard
M. Daley announced that the Medinah Temple should be saved, too.
Fifield threw up his hands: if he had to save both the studios and
the temple, he said, the property was worth a lot less than $21
million.
</P>
<P>
   So all parties have agreed to the moratorium: no demolition, no
lawsuits and no landmark attempts.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Fifield, in an interview, explained his newest plan
for the block. If he has to save the temple, where Daley saw the
Shriners' Circus as a child, he wants to build a 38-story rental
tower in the middle of it. And he wants to sell the city on a
package of special tax incentives that would effectively pay him
back a good chunk of the $21 million he will still give the
Shriners for the land and buildings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the Tree Studios? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To avert another attempt at landmark designation, the developer
said he would save the exteriors and the courtyard but made no
promises for the interior, much of which still has its original
stained glass and fireplaces trimmed with handmade tile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, Faist and his fellow artists will have to go.
``They've known that from the beginning,'' Fifield said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the courtyard this week, water splashed from the original
stone fountain, and little-girl-pink impatiens flowed from
terra-cotta urns. All was serene in George Sotos' drawing studio,
where five skeletons dangled in the late summer breeze. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sotos, a tall man with a George Carlin ponytail, says he pays
about $1,450 a month for his double-width ground-floor space, where
he teaches 85 students a week; another two dozen drift in on
Saturday for life-drawing workshops. He lives down the hall, near
Carl and Lucille James, who have lived there since 1952. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James, a sturdy 80, is a painter and illustrator whose work
appears in the extensive show of Tree Studios artists _ past and
present _ at the Chicago Cultural Center through Sept. 26.
``There's been a tremendous change in the neighborhood since we
came,'' Mrs. James, 72, said. ``It used to be silent; now it's
Disney World.'' She was referring to the Disney Quest store that
opened this summer a block away.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner, James said, ``there's a high-rise condo going
up, and we hear it's sold out before they put a shovel in the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Fifield said that the other developers _ at least
three bid similar amounts for the Shriners' block _ were willing to
pay so much.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, Paul Barber, the business administrator of the
Shriners, said he didn't know who would end up with the property _
or what they would do with it. ``Hey, we're a fraternal
organization that cares for crippled kids,'' he said. ``Our sole
goal is to liquidate the asset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
