<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Sept. 16, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A weakening Hurricane Floyd will bring gales and flooding rains
to most of the Middle Atlantic region Thursday. The center of the
storm will likely pass from eastern North Carolina this morning to
near southern New Jersey Thursday night. Given this path, many
coastal locations on the east side of the hurricane will experience
sustained winds between 40 and 50 mph with gusts to 75 mph or
higher. Very rough seas and tides between 5 and 8 feet above normal
will cause serious beach erosion. Rainfall of 3 to 5 inches will be
common from Virginia to eastern New England resulting in widespread
urban flooding. Gusty winds west of the storm track will reach 40
mph at times.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will be brighter and tranquil with much lower
humidity. Brisk winds in the Carolinas will diminish by afternoon.
Some clouds will return to south Florida as sea breezes occur. High
pressure cresting over the Middle West will promote sunshine and
pleasantly cool weather from the northern Mississippi Valley to the
Tennessee Valley. Morning readings will be in the 40s as far south
as the Ohio River.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and showers will persist over the western Plains and
southern Rockies due to a sluggish disturbance near the Four
Corners. The dull conditions will shift into Nebraska and the
southern Dakotas later Thursday. Sunny skies and very warm air will
cover the interior Northwest. The Southwest will be bright and
seasonable, except for thundershowers in the mountains and fog
along the Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Storm Surge
</P>
<P>
   Land is where hurricanes sometimes go to die. At landfall,
however, hurricanes are very dangerous. As a hurricane approaches
the coast, water is pushed toward land on the storm's right-forward
flank by fierce onshore winds. Because of the shallowing bottom,
water being shoved ashore piles up, causing an abnormal rise in
ocean level. Called the storm surge, this sudden rise can reach
heights as high as 30 feet. Battering waves ride atop the surge.
This wall of water can flatten houses and small-story buildings.
Storm surges swell when they occur at the time of normal high
tides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
