<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3281 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-TETRIS-ART-2TAKES     09-15 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TETRIS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CREATOR OF TETRIS LOOKS FOR NEW WAYS TO DAZZLE AND BEGUILE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., N.Y., Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ever there was a common touchstone of cyberculture it is the
engaging little computer game known as Tetris. This first truly
cross-platform, cross-generational, cross-the-sexes digital
diversion is, some 15 years after its birth, still drawing players
to all manner of computers _ from desktops to electronic organizers
_ to play it.
</P>
<P>
   And, 15 years later, people within the gaming industry are still
drawn to the creator of Tetris, Alexey Pajitnov, 44. That suits him
fine. Making games, playing them and discussing how much fun they
are to make and play have been a large part of his life since he
was a clever boy growing up in his native Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   There was very little to do for entertainment, he recalls, in
what was then the Soviet Union. So, he occupied himself mostly by
solving complex, mathematical puzzles on paper. He soon graduated
to solving three-dimensional puzzles like Rubik's Cubes. ``I loved
them all,'' Pajitnov said in a heavy Russian accent that makes him
sound more like a cosmonaut than an American-based game designer.
</P>
<P>
   But his creation of Tetris in the mid-1980s has made Pajitnov, a
man with a boyishly round face framed with a full beard, a
celebrity in game circles and somewhat beyond.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the birthplace of the Sony Gameboy, the hand-held game
device that helped to sell more than 30 million copies of Tetris,
Pajitnov is hounded by autograph seekers. In professional game
conferences around the world he is often regarded as a living
legend, a sort of stocky, Jedi master of computer code and game
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He created what I still think is the single most addictive
game ever made,'' said Cliff Bleszinski, the lead game designer for
Epic, a computer game company based in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Pajitnov is hoping to strike gold again with a new game on
CD-ROM called Pandora's Box. The game, which is being released this
month by Microsoft, is a collection of 10 visually dazzling puzzle
types with more than 350 individual variations.
</P>
<P>
   The puzzles are connected in a plot line that carries the player
around the world restoring order wrecked by seven tricksters
released from Pandora's box. The game is rooted, Pajitnov says, in
his time-tested theme: players instinctive urge to replace chaos
with order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he thinks about the customer, and how they approach
the game, and what they are going to get out of it, he almost seems
like a psychologist,'' said Ed Fries, the general manager of the
Microsoft game group. ``He's in your head and he is thinking about
what he is going to do to make this game compelling to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Pajitnov's approach to computer games is certainly not
accidental. By the time he was 14, Pajitnov, whose mother was a
journalist and whose father was a philosopher, writer and political
dissident, had fallen into the mind-whirling embrace of advanced
mathematics and strategy games. The former he studied hard; the
latter he explored gleefully.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a master's of science degree in applied mathematics
from the Moscow Institute of Aviation and did post-graduate work at
the Academy of Science Computer Center in Moscow. All the while he
continued to play games, even designing some to test the computers
at the center, where he also worked as a programmer in speech
recognition, artificial intelligence and computer-assisted design.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of his heady research, Pajitnov decided that he was
more interested in ``bringing the computer to people, directly,''
as he put it. At first, he said, he tried to find ways of using the
computer to help unlock psychological processes. Nothing really
came to fruition, but he gained an extraordinary understanding of
the psyche, he said, a kind of engineer's insight into human
behavior. ``That kind of helped,'' he said, in deciding what he
would do next.
</P>
<P>
   In about two weeks in 1984 he wrote the primary computer code
that would become Tetris. He recalled that he could have written it
more quickly, but he found the game so compelling, even in its
embryonic stages, that he kept playing rough versions, telling
himself that he was ``testing it.'' After many more refinements,
the game finally made it to the West in 1988 by way of a Hungarian
programming consortium.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The following year the game earned four Excellence in Software
Awards, the computer game equivalent to the Oscars from the
Software Publishers Association. Since then, the game has sold some
50-million copies in many variations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tetris is one of the few games that has transcended the casual
gamer and the hard-core gamer,'' Bleszinski said. It is widely
believed that even the occupants of the Russian space station Mir
passed some of their idle hours circling high above Earth playing
Tetris.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about being recognized as the creator of one of the
world's most popular computer games, Pajitnov paused and spoke
slowly. ``The first time it is agreeable, but the hundredth time?''
His voice trailed off as he shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   Tetris is very unusual in that it is widely played by women, a
distinction in a computer game universe that is often mapped by the
tastes and habits of male players. ``There is just something about
it that is so appealing,'' said Linda Helin, the general manager of
XS New York, a game arcade and cyber cafe in Times Square. ``I
still play it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pajitnov said he is not surprised. ``Tetris is very
nonviolent,'' he said. ``Women don't feel bad that this is some
kind of stupid male activity.'' ``And Tetris is a kind of game
which helps you order the world. You fight against chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it is very politically correct, but that's what
women prefer to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pajitnov was still living in the Soviet Union when he developed
the game and so was unable to cash in on the wild success of
Tetris. Under communism, he explained, he was prohibited from
personally profiting from his work. The rights to his game were
given up to the state for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently, years after he emigrated to the United States in
1991, have the rights to the game reverted to him. ``I'm getting
some royalties,'' he said beneath his breath, conceding that the
game's economic life is all but over. ``I'm losing my humor sense
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; He'd much rather talk about games than the fortune that got
away. ``I am always thinking about how he will be puzzled,''
Pajitnov said of potential players, ``how he will be intrigued, how
he will figure it out and how to fool him.''
</P>
<P>
   Central to his method of creating computer-based puzzles is to
try to create those that will interest and hold his attention. Then
he ``simplifies, simplifies, simplifies, simplifies until it is
understandable.'' His reason for this, he said, is simple: ``It's a
lot of frustration when you are just confused on how to operate the
puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   After running his own company in the Soviet Union in the late
1980s, and working for others in the United States, Pajitnov
created a string of relatively successful games like El-Fish,
Welltris and Hatris. In 1996 he joined Microsoft as its first game
designer.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is one of 10 game designers nestled in offices on one
of Microsoft's campuses just outside Seattle. His second-floor
office is comfortable, he said, overlooking the Microsoft cafeteria
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever skills I have I use,'' Pajitnov, who is married and
the father of two sons, said of his work for Microsoft. Dismissing
his star status, he shrugged and said, ``I'm a working person.''
</P>
<P>
   And now he is making the media rounds around the country to talk
about his latest project, Pandora's Box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal it to give you a good time, a relaxing time,''
he said as he mouse-clicked his way through one of the new game's
puzzles that requires players to restore the famous form of Rodin's
``Thinker'' from globs of 3-D pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself, I love this kind of puzzle,'' he said with an impish
grin. ``It is kind of meditative stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
