<SLUG> BC-DADS'-WORLD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE YOU A TRUE FAMILY MAN? HERE'S A TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listen up, fathers. Before you take the following test to
determine just how domesticated, wife-dependent and child-addicted
you have become, you must understand the Paula Nicholas theory.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Nicholas, 30, is a beautiful single woman who lives in
Mississippi. She sells pharmaceuticals. Often, when she is
contemplating dating a gentleman, she will take him to a certain
type of restaurant known as a ``bar.'' Once there, she will put
money in a jukebox and play a song or songs by '80s ``Tiger Beat''
and ``General Hospital'' star Rick Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Most men would wince at that. Rick Springfield, in generic male
terms, is a ``goober.'' He sang sappy power ballads about how he
wished he had Jessie's girl, wondering aloud where he could find a
woman like that. He said that he would get excited by a woman
because there was heaven in her eyes tonight, noting that the fire
within him was ignited and love was burning bright. You get the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   The catch: Nicholas deemed a man worthy of her companionship
only if he enjoyed the music of Mr. Springfield. Her theory,
delivered in a slow, thick drawl: ``Any man who would admit to
liking Rick Springfield is comfortable with who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   That theory can be applied to family men, too. If you want to
know how comfortable a man is with his role as husband, father,
handler of all business familial, then have him take the following
``when the wife and kids are outta town'' test. As with the Rick
Springfield test, the intuition to give the manly answer will,
ironically, be counted against you. (For future biographers, it
should be noted that I created the following quiz this past weekend
while my wife and child were visiting relatives.)
</P>
<P>
   ``All answers on a scale of 1 to 10 _ 10 being exactly like
something you would do, 1 meaning you would never act that way.''
</P>
<P>
   1. After four days of being alone in the house, you begin to
wish your wife was back in town so that you'd have clean underwear
again. That is until, on day five, you discover a load of whites in
the dryer that had been there the entire time.
</P>
<P>
   2. At six o'clock every day, you stare at the phone, waiting for
the daily call that comes from your daughter when she and Mom
arrive home. When you remember that the call won't come, you wonder
what that weird empty feeling is inside you, deciding it must just
be that you're hungry.
</P>
<P>
   3. After five days of Ultimate Bacon Double Cheeseburgers from
Jack-in-the-Box for dinner, you begin to wonder whether your
returning wife will still love ``the new you'' who can't seem to
button your trousers anymore.
</P>
<P>
   4. You find yourself watching hours of Cartoon Network and
Nickelodeon when at home, so that you and your daughter can discuss
the tomfoolery of Johnny Bravo and the Rugrats when she returns.
</P>
<P>
   5. On your night out with the guys, you act appropriately
collegiate. Except that you bring your cell phone so that, once you
steal away to the restroom, you can make a long-distance call to
make sure that the wife and munchkin are indeed planning on
returning soon.
</P>
<P>
   6. You stay up far too late watching veg TV every night, leaving
far too many lights on, because for the first time, you think your
daughter may be right about those ``scary nighttime noises in my
room.''
</P>
<P>
   7. You remember, for the first time in a long time, that even
though the grass always seems greener, you hated being single.
HATED it.
</P>
<P>
   8. You start to wonder why you spend so much time at work,
wondering if somehow you could quit to spend time with your wife
and child every minute of every day, yet still afford the
sport-utility wagon.
</P>
<P>
   9. While eating candy and playing PlayStation in the swim trunks
that are substituting for your underwear, you realize that if your
wife left you, you would fall apart so fast you'd be a recurring
guest on ``Jerry Springer'' within a month.
</P>
<P>
   10. You decide to publicly declare your transmogrification from
``normal guy'' to ``whipped family man'' in the hopes that your
wife and child will take pity on you and never leave again, except
perhaps during Cowboys games.
</P>
<P>
   (Scoring: 90-100, welcome to my world; 75-90, I'll see you at
the PTA meeting; 60-75, put down the remote and attend a soccer
game, please; 50-60, did you think this whole family thing
through?; below 50, why are you reading a section called Family
Day?)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
