<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER16-COX     09-15 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS REP FIGHTING SCHOOL PRAYER AMENDMENT
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Chet Edwards, D -Texas, said Wednesday he
would once again lead the fight against a school prayer
constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting government into our religious and prayer life was a
bad idea when Madison and Jefferson rejected it over 200 years ago
... and it is a bad idea today,'' Edwards said, at a Capitol Hill
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was among the leading opponents to a similar measure
last year that fell short of the two-thirds majority needed for
passage, the first House vote on a school prayer amendment in 27
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla., who authored last year's amendment,
is also renewing his role. He introduced a new measure Wednesday
that would ``secure the people's right to acknowledge God according
to the dictates of conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed by 57 co-sponsors, most of them Republican, the amendment
added: ``The people's right to pray and to recognize their
religious beliefs, heritage or traditions on public property,
including schools, shall not be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argue that more prayer would help deter violence in
schools and that legislation is needed to reverse more than 30
years of court decisions which have resulted in an atmosphere
intolerant of religion.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said that the effort is based on a myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could be further from the truth,'' he said. ``God and
prayers are alive and well in our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments were echoed by leaders of religious and civil
liberties groups that joined Edwards at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are prayer clubs, there are Bible groups,'' said Oliver
Thomas, who sits on a special council for religious liberty at the
National Council of Churches of Christ. He said that no child is
denied the right to pray as long as they do not disrupt school
events or infringe on the rights of others.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also say that the amendment would be divisive _
pitting religions against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each school district there would be a fight like you can't
imagine over which religion or religions would be acknowledged and
promoted in schools,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups represented at the press conference included the
National Council of Jewish Women, the Baptist Joint Committee on
Public Affairs, the American Jewish Committee and the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   This year's debate over school prayer is likely to repeat as a
political hot button issue.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Christian Coalition supported the amendment by
distributing hundreds of thousands of church bulletins and
targeting 50 congressional districts with phone calls, radio ads
and 150,000 postcards -- some accusing congressional opponents,
including Edwards, of religious bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said he is surprised that those on the political right
support government intervention in something as private as
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political conservatives, who do not trust our government to
educate our children and regulate our businesses, should be the
first to distrust government getting involved in something as
personal and sacrosanct as our religious faith and prayers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
