<HEADER>
A3303 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-HOMEWORK-MUSTHAVES-TE     09-15 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEWORK-MUSTHAVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO HELP THE KIDS BUCKLE DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's officially homework season. No more summer slacking, no
more first-of-school light workloads. It's time to get down to
business, whip out the sharpened No. 2 pencils _ or turn on the
computer _ and do some real work. Here, some of the best ideas,
products and resources for getting out from under that pile of
work:
</P>
<P>
   1. Start with basic organizers. Organize your study area with
two stationery musts: a calendar and an assignment book. Keep a
calendar by your child's homework area to keep track of projects
and long-term assignments. (That science fair can sneak up on you
if you don't see it approaching, circled in red.) Consider mounting
a reusable two-month or three-month wipe-off calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Your child will also need a totable form of date-tracking: an
assignment book. They're crucial. Assignment notebooks come in all
forms, from the cheap and simple spiral notebook styles to the
personal organizers with leather covers and refillable pages. The
key is to get into the habit of writing down homework assignments.
Remembering the homework assignment is half the battle. Well,
almost.
</P>
<P>
   2. Get a CD-ROM Encyclopedia. Remember when ``encyclopedia''
meant a collection of heavy books that cost hundreds if not
thousands of dollars and were outdated within a few years? No more.
These days, encyclopedias come on CD-ROM and go for less than $100.
</P>
<P>
   The just-released Microsoft Encarta Reference Suite 2000
contains four major CD-ROM reference guides: the encyclopedia, the
Encarta Interactive World Atlas, the Encarta World English
Dictionary and Encarta Online Deluxe, an online version of the
encyclopedia. The set of four costs about $65 after a company
rebate _ the deluxe encyclopedia by itself is about $40 after the
rebate. One caveat: The Microsoft Encarta products run only on
Windows. A Mac version of the encyclopedia has been produced in
years past, but it's not known if one will be made for the 2000
edition.
</P>
<P>
   3. Turn to online homework helpers. There's more to the Internet
than junk e-mail and advertising; it's probably the fastest,
easiest way to get information children might need to complete
homework assignments. Try these two exceptional Web sites that
specialize in getting students the homework help they need:
</P>
<P>
   The www.homeworkcentral.com site lets students pinpoint the
information they need by helping them narrow down their topics. The
site is divided into age groups, and the search engine is designed
to serve academic purposes. For instance, if you type in ``George
Washington,'' you'll get information about the first president _
not a list of every site with the word ``George'' or ``Washington''
in it.
</P>
<P>
   The www.schoolwork.org site offers numerous topic categories,
then provides a fairly comprehensive list of Web sites that contain
specialized information about each topic.
</P>
<P>
   4. Keep those papers in place. There's always that book that
won't stay open or that piece of paper that keeps disappearing.
Eliminate frustration with products that keep flyaways in place.
Try an adjustable bookstand that props up your textbook _ and keeps
it open to the right page; The Container Store has a version for
$35. Or use a book weight that'll weigh down the page you need.
Levenger's Web site (www.levenger.com) offers really nice leather
book weights for $17.99 _ or find a cheaper one at bookstores or
office supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   5. Provide practical inspiration. Sometimes the work gets done
faster when the right tools are also fun to look at. Hence the
Pokmon Study Kit, based on the Japanese animation game that has
taken over the lives of everybody younger than 12. These little
desk-supply packs (ruler, eraser, pencil sharpener, pencil pouch)
cost less than $5 at toy stores that carry Pokmon products; we
found them at Kay Bee Toys in Fort Worth's Hulen Mall. Or spring
for the Deluxe Desktop Set, which includes a Jigglypuff tape
dispenser, a Bulbasaur pencil sharpener, a Poliwhirl tape measure
and a Pikachu stapler; it goes for about $10. Not a bad investment
if it helps get the homework done.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
