<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3319 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     09-15 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOVERED MATISSE WINDS UP IN LAS VEGAS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recovered a few months ago by the family from whom it was
confiscated by the Nazis in 1941,  &UR; Henri Matisse &LR; 's 1924
``Odalisque'' has landed at  &UR; Steve Wynn &LR; 's Bellagio in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Rosenbergs lived in Paris, where they collected art and
owned a gallery. Their Matisse was sold in the '50s by the Knoedler
gallery in New York, to  &UR; Virginia  &LR; and  &UR; Prentice Bloedel &LR; , who knew
nothing about its past. The Bloedels donated it in 1991 to the
Seattle Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, after the painting was mentioned in a book about Nazi
art looting, the Rosenberg heirs sued the museum. A B'nai B'rith
Holocaust Art Restitution Project affirmed that the painting
belonged to the Rosenbergs, and the museum returned it.
 &UR; Elaine Rosenberg  &LR; told the New York Times that her late
father-in-law would have rejoiced. ``His children are finally
coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported that the
work, which has been valued at more than $2 million, was bought
within two months by Wynn, who won't say what he paid for it. It is
on display at the gallery at Wynn's Bellagio hotel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mimi Gates &LR;  of the Seattle museum told the Seattle newspaper
that the family wasn't interested in working out a deal to allow
the Matisse to remain in the Seattle museum, which is suing the
Knoedler gallery on grounds that it illegally sold the painting to
the Bloedel family.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Wynn's statement of the gallery's purpose, on the Bellagio
Web site, is to make available ``works that have long been hidden
from public view in private collections,'' apparently including
this work that had been in a museum.  &UR; Barbra Streisand &LR; , who was at
the Bellagio Saturday attending ``O,'' the water-based Cirque du
Soleil show, was treated to a private tour of the art collection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Faced with a roar from angry protectors of the Miss America
image, pageant organizers backed away from the report early this
week that they would allow divorced and formerly pregnant women to
compete. They said they were reconsidering the decision.
</P>
<P>
   _ Point Richmond conceptual artist  &UR; Nicolino &LR;  had planned to
string bras across the Grand Canyon, but he didn't raise enough
money (there was also a small question of getting permission).
Writes the artist this week:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking of selling off 40,000 bras, one at a time, in
vending machines. ... Got to issue a public apology to all those
bra donors for stooping to this level.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Rose Barrett &LR;  appreciates the honesty in a sponsoring
announcement she heard this week on KQED radio: The program had
been brought to listeners by United Airlines, whose new
economy-plus class features ``3 to 5 inches of legroom.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Pamela Helsey  &LR; reports that  &UR; Gwyneth Paltrow  &LR; _ who is not
making a movie in San Francisco, says the film commission _ has
been seen in the last few days ``at all the cool places,''
including Tokyo GoGo on 16th and Valencia. Remember  &UR; Mick Jagger &LR; 
at the Slanted Door, just around the corner? The Mission District
rules.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUTH IN THE EYE OF THE BIOGRAPHER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At a party  &UR; Roselyne Swig &LR;  tossed in San Francisco on Tuesday
night for  &UR; Christopher Ogden &LR; , author of ``Legacy: A Biography of
 &UR; Moses  &LR; &AMP;  &UR; Walter Annenberg &LR; '' (Little, Brown; $29.95), Ogden, an
experienced biographer, contrasted a few of his subjects:
</P>
<P>
   Despite philanthropist and ambassador Walter's reluctance at
first to talk about his father, who made a somewhat tainted fortune
by publishing racing forms and went to jail in the '30s for tax
evasion, Ogden was granted full access to records and complete
control over the text.
</P>
<P>
   While Ogden was at work on an earlier authorized book about
Pamela Harriman, ``Life of the Party,'' the Democrat femme fatale
came to suspect that the biography would be less than adoring. She
pulled out of the deal, legal wrangling ensued over notes already
gathered, and Ogden went on to complete the biography _ which
wasn't half as critical as &UR; Sally Bedell Smith &LR; 's later ``Reflected
Glory'' _ without her help.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can confide in her and trust her. ... Elizabeth is someone
who loves me, really loves me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Michael Jackson about Elizabeth Taylor in the October issue
of Talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is part of my heart. We would do anything for each other.
... He is magic. And I think all truly magical people have to have
that genuine eccentricity.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Elizabeth Taylor about Michael Jackson, ibid.
</P>
</TEXT>
