<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-ACTION16-COX     09-15 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ACTION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fox takes `Action' against cable sitcoms
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox's ``Action'' is the most audacious debut of the season. It's
being called a ``bridge'' show between the networks and cable, but
it's more like a gangplank into a future where the only difference
between the two is whether the four-letter words are bleeped.
</P>
<P>
   They're literally bleeped here, and for good reason. Movie
producer Peter Dragon, played to snarky, snakey perfection by
bad-boy-next-door Jay Mohr (``Jerry McGuire''), makes his
outrageous entrance into American living rooms by speeding through
a studio's streets, flipping off Steven Spielberg (``geek!''), then
pulling into a parking spot reserved for the employee of the month.
</P>
<P>
   When the award-winning commissary worker objects, Dragon turns
on him with an asp's smile and asks if he got the award for not
urinating in the commissary's Cobb salads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if I was you, I would pee in the Cobb salads,'' Dragon
says in his deadly deadpan. ``In fact, I would pee in every
(bleeping) Cobb salad every (bleeping) day so every one of those
(bleepers) in the commissary would have a little (bleeping) taste
of Peter Dragon.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a soliloquy on ``Action,'' a show you'll love if you
don't hate it, and hate if you don't love it. It's an insidery
sendup of Hollywood; a self-loathing mirror on our media culture.
It's a world where cell phones are an evolutionary advance on the
human anatomy and insincerity is more prized than the truth. It
lets us feel wink-wink knowing about the Hollywood machinery that
suckers us every time.
</P>
<P>
   When Dragon's head of production mistakenly buys the wrong
script, he offers, ``We've bought crappy scripts before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that was on purpose!'' Dragon snaps back.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the gaps between clever exchanges are extended with the
broadest, Fox-est filler: pratfalling hookers, penis jokes _ ``The
Player'' meets ``Married... with Children.'' Much of it unreels
like an in-house roast of the company brass: lots funnier if you're
in on the jokes. If your bathroom reading is ``Entertainment
Weekly,'' maybe you'll cut it.
</P>
<P>
   Mohr is delicious as Dragon. He sets up tent inside his
bloodless character with such vacant glee that you'd run to hug him
if you didn't know he bites.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the cast seems emboldened by his toxic oxygen.
Illeana Douglas (``Message in a Bottle,'' ``To Die For''), plays
child star-turned-prostitute Wendy Ward, a hooker not with a heart
of gold, but with an eye for the blockbuster script. Jack Plotnick
plays production head and Dragon sychophant Stuart Glazer (``Is she
your whore?'' he asks Dragon of Wendy. ``No, Stuart,'' Dragon tells
him. ``She's my prostitute. You're my whore''). And Buddy Hackett
hacks his way wonderfully though his role as Dragon's lackey uncle
Lonnie.
</P>
<P>
   Guests show up to lampoon themselves: Keanu Reeves in the
premier, Salma Hayak in the episode that follows immediately after,
Cameron Diaz later in the season.
</P>
<P>
   It all sort of works as much as it all sort of doesn't. It's too
bad a network like Fox doesn't have the confidence yet _ or doesn't
trust its audience enough _ to simply be good and be done with it.
That's the real difference between the networks and cable.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Dragon would say, brimming with hide-skinning cynicism,
``Welcome to the magical world of motion pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Action''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight on WAGA at 9 and 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
