<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HEDWIG-SHEEDY-ART-2TA     09-15 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDWIG-SHEEDY-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLY SHEEDY REPLACES A MALE ACTOR AS THE GENDER-BENDING STAR OF
`HEDWIG'
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hedwig Schmidt is about to undergo a sex change.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be the first time, of course. Anyone who has seen
``Hedwig and the Angry Inch,'' the long-running off-Broadway
musical, knows that a botched sex change is just one of the
problems facing the world-weary drag queen Hedwig Schmidt, who
describes herself as the ``internationally ignored song stylist.''
</P>
<P>
   The character, created by John Cameron Mitchell and the composer
Stephen Trask, demands a mix of wit, wistfulness and vocal
firepower in a 90-minute monologue spiced with 10 rock songs. And
ever since the show opened at the Jane Street Theater in February
1998, the role has always been played by male actors, each of whom
has donned the character's gravity-proof blond wig, arch German
accent and industrial-strength makeup to create the image of an
individual caught midway between the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, the musical's gender bending will take a curious
new turn, when a woman, Ally Sheedy, takes over the role.
</P>
<P>
   It is a risky move for both performer and production. For the
producers, casting a woman in a role that trades so heavily in
gender confusion means playing with the script's double-entendres
and humor, not to mention the loyalties of the show's devoted
following.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I talk to about it, when I tell them, their eyes kind
of go out of focus,'' Mitchell said. ``They're trying to grasp the
idea. Some people say that's not a good idea, to have a woman; some
people think it's wonderful.'' He emphasized that while the actor's
gender is changing, the character remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the word leaked out in late July that Ms. Sheedy
was taking over, Mitchell posted an open letter to Hedwig fans on
the show's Web site, explaining how he had met and cast Ms. Sheedy.
``She'll need to feel welcome to go where she needs to go in this
part,'' Mitchell concluded. ``And I hope you'll all be there for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Ms. Sheedy, whose career as a Brat Pack ingenue gave way
to a sustained professional slump in the late 1980s, the role means
putting her newfound reputation as a serious actress, and her
untested voice, to the test.
</P>
<P>
   How does she feel?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's essentially me onstage with a mike for 90 minutes,'' Ms.
Sheedy said recently over a cup of coffee before heading to a voice
rehearsal. ``Now I'm in the terrifying reality of having to do the
show.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While popular and critical reaction to Ms. Sheedy remains to be
seen, what is certain is that Ms. Sheedy's take on the character is
bound to differ from those of her predecessors: Mitchell, Michael
Cerveris and currently, Kevin Cahoon.
</P>
<P>
   First off, there's a new wig: gone are the feathered sides in
favor of a look that the wig designer Mike Potter described as
``Sally Struthers meets Chaka Khan in a tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got dreads, crimps, spiral, curls and braids,'' he said.
``It's like all hairdos in one.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Vocally, some key changes in songs have been made to suit Ms.
Sheedy's voice, and she has also dropped some of the ad-libs she
feels aren't working for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing her as straight as possible to begin with,'' Ms.
Sheedy said. ``And seeing how it goes over.''
</P>
<P>
   The choreography has also been stripped somewhat, too, allowing
her to explore what Trask called the ``rock 'n' roll survivor'' in
Hedwig. ``It's going to be less glam and more punk, less European
and more American, more New York, less London,'' Trask said. ``You
can imagine this Hedwig had a heroin problem at one point.''
</P>
<P>
   That alone would not make Hedwig a huge stretch for Ms. Sheedy.
After all, it was only last year that she won plaudits for playing
a heroin-addicted photographer in the independent film ``High
Art,'' a role that won her the Best Actress Award from the National
Society of Film Critics and several other groups. Other juicy roles
have followed, including that of a perpetually lonely production
designer in ``Sugar Town,'' directed by Allison Anders and Kurt
Voss, which opens Friday, and a slightly unhinged blind date in the
romantic comedy ``I'll Take You There,'' which was screened this
month at the Telluride Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The roles, and good reviews, have been a sweet vindication. A
Manhattan native, Ms. Sheedy had a career as a teen-age actress in
New York and fame in Hollywood in her 20s before suddenly finding
herself unable to win decent roles. She was eventually dropped by
her agent at the William Morris Agency and considered quitting
acting altogether. Shortly after that, she read the script for
``High Art'' and was so eager to play the role that she called the
director, Lisa Cholodenko, herself.
</P>
<P>
   Now 37, Ms. Sheedy displays much of the goofy charm _ she uses
the word ``like'' a lot _ and twinkling looks that scored with
teen-age boys in '80s movies like ``The Breakfast Club'' and
``WarGames.''
</P>
<P>
   She is married to David Lindsay, an actor she met during her
last stage appearance, a production of ``Advice From a
Caterpillar,'' by Douglas Carter Beane, in 1991. They have a
5-year-old daughter, Rebecca.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy, who has been open about her battles with bulimia and
prescription drugs, still shows flashes of bitterness about what
she describes as the ``acceptable version of female'' that prevails
in Hollywood, which she feels shut her out of many roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that I fit neatly into the particular definition
of femininity,'' said the actress, lean and slim-hipped, adding
with a puckish smile: ``I think there's something kind of
androgynous about me, and I kind of like it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that androgyny and an aura of having endured trial by
fire that first appealed to Mitchell. He said he felt it was a
perfect fit. ``There's anger and irony and world-weariness about
Ally's own life that infuses Hedwig all the time,'' he said. ``In
many ways, she is Hedwig. She's been through hell and back again
and she's not shy about saying so.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was in January, between screenings at the Sundance Film
Festival, that Mitchell and Ms. Sheedy first met and began to
discuss the possibility of her taking on Hedwig. Mitchell showed
Ms. Sheedy a videotape of the show; Ms. Sheedy's response was
immediate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'd really love to do a show like that,''' she
recalled. ``And near the end of the festival he said, `You know I
really want a woman to do the show. Do you want to do it?'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy wanted the part but was not certain that she had the
vocal range for the score, which swings from punk to twangy country
to anthemic glam rock. ``It's such a new experience for me, because
it's something I haven't really tackled,'' she said of singing.
``It's a completely fortunate coincidence they like my voice,
because my voice is odd.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Trask said he wasn't completely convinced that Ms. Sheedy could
do it, either. ``I was totally prepared to say, `It's really nice
to meet you, but I don't think that it's going to work out,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   What Trask found, however, was a voice that fell somewhere
between the punk stylings of Patti Smith and the folk sound of
Natalie Merchant. He decided that every song could work with Ms.
Sheedy's voice and that in some cases the switch would allow him to
strip some songs back down to their original form.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a song, `Sugar Daddy,' which has a kind of a Vegas
feel the way John performed it,'' he said. ``I'd never intended it
like that. So I'm kind of excited to see it returned to a looser,
less revved-up feel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hedwig'' follows the story of a sexually confused, glam
rock-loving East Berliner who agrees to marry an American GI _ and
have a sex change _ in order to cross over to the West. Neither the
operation nor the marriage is a success, however, leaving Hedwig
living in a Kansas trailer park, where she plays mentor (and lover)
to a young Springsteen type named Tommy Gnosis. Apart from the
occasional grunt from the band or Hedwig's long-suffering husband,
Yitzak, the job of keeping the audience's attention is all
Hedwig's.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Perfecting that mix of song styles and character takes work. Ms.
Sheedy has been rehearsing five days a week with a voice coach, as
well as putting in daily sessions with Trask, the composer, and a
personal acting coach. To create a more masculine look, she has
trimmed her hair short and has been working out to build muscles in
her arms and shoulders. Her script, in a blue binder, is marked
with notes to herself on the character and decorated with a
Polaroid of herself and Mitchell, each in costume as Hedwig.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything has gone smoothly; her debut was originally
scheduled for this past Monday, but was rescheduled for next week
to make up for rehearsals lost when Ms. Sheedy had to travel to
Telluride. ``I went under serious duress,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gender gap, Ms. Sheedy says she feels a deep
connection to the role of Hedwig.
</P>
<P>
   ``She makes sense to me emotionally,'' she said. ``The fact that
she once had a penis that got cut off is just not presenting itself
as an obstacle to me.'' She adds with a laugh: ``I guess this is
what happens when you grow up on the Upper West Side.''
</P>
<P>
   She says the role also resonates with the life of her mother,
Charlotte Sheedy. The elder Ms. Sheedy, a literary agent in
Manhattan, divorced Ms. Sheedy's father in the early 1970s and
began a long-term relationship with another woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the other parts of Hedwig I understand is the search
for spiritual completion, which is something that I actually
watched firsthand my mother go through,'' Ms. Sheedy said. ``It's a
really long journey from thinking you're supposed to be one way and
then being brave enough to say, `What I actually am is something
else.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Ms. Sheedy is finding her inspiration for the role,
Trask and Mitchell say they are confident that she is up to task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a reinvention of Hedwig,'' Trask said. ``But in
the end, we think the feeling is going to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell added: ``I guess historically, drag queens were
imitating movie stars and luminaries. It's kind of nice to have a
movie star imitating a drag queen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
