<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALN VICTIMS DEMAND EXPLANATION FOR CLINTON'S CLEMENCY DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two victims of FALN bombings, joined by two former
FBI agents who investigated the terrorist group, on Wednesday
condemned President Clinton's offer of clemency to 16 Puerto Rican
militants and demanded that the president explain his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Pascarella, a former New York City police officer who was
injured in a December 1981 FALN bombing, told a Senate panel he
could not understand why Clinton would grant any ``clemency request
with American blood on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The FALN gave me a life sentence when one of their bombs blew
off part of my leg, destroyed the hearing in one of my ears, badly
scarred my other leg and damaged my eyesight, and I want to know
why President Clinton feels that their sentence should be less
severe than mine,'' Pascarella told the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   William Newhall, who said he lost three friends and was severely
injured in the January 1975 bombing of Fraunces Tavern in New York
City, told the hearing that Clinton's decision was an ``affront''
to the families of those who died in FALN bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends' children grew up without their fathers, while
their wives were left to grieve and raise their families alone,''
Newhall said as he worked to hold back tears.
</P>
<P>
   Former FBI Special Agent Richard Hahn, who investigated FALN
attacks from 1975 to 1987, told the committee that the president's
decision sends a ``frightening message'' to terrorists that the
United States is not serious about protecting its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Wofford, a former FBI special agent who worked on FALN
cases from 1974 to 1980, said he feared the president's granting of
clemency might hurt current law enforcement efforts against the
FALN organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very difficult to get captured FALN members
to cooperate and give information about the group since they know
that their sentences could be shortened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the testimony of the Pascarella and Newhall, the
committee's chairman, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, became visibly
angry at the refusal of White House officials to testify before
Congress on the president's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick and tired of being stiffed by this administration
when I ask for information that we have a right to see,'' said
Hatch. The chairman is well known for his calm demeanor and courtly
manners but he repeatedly stopped himself in mid-sentence to regain
his composure as he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he will subpoena administration officials to testify
about Clinton's decision to grant clemency to the Puerto Rican
militants.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Justice Department blocked Neil Gallagher,
assistant director for the FBI's National Security Division, from
testifying at a separate Senate hearing on the clemency issue.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining its decision not to allow Gallagher to appear before
the committee, the Justice Department said in a statement that
there were constitutional questions about whether it would be
appropriate for FBI officials to testify because the power to grant
clemency is the president's exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, labeling that explanation as ``pathetic,'' said he would
ask his committee to subpoena Gallagher and officials from the
Justice Department and the White House to force them to appear
before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This committee cannot stand to be snubbed by the White
House,'' he said. ``The only thing we're asking for is that the
administration explain to us and the American people why it made a
decision that almost nobody understands or agrees with.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's threat came a day after the Senate voted 95 to 2 in
favor of a resolution calling the clemency decision ``deplorable.''
The House passed a similar measure last week with 311 to 41 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The votes on the president's decision have no actual impact on
the clemency granted to the Puerto Rican militants since Congress
has no constitutional authority to overturn the offers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 FALN members offered clemency, which required them to
renounce violence, 14 accepted and two declined.
</P>
<P>
   None of those granted clemency by Clinton was directly linked to
bombings that caused injuries or fatalities, a point the president
has cited in explaining his decision.
</P>
<P>
   However, at Wednesday's hearing, Hahn noted that some of the
released militants had been caught building bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men helped build the bombs, transport the bombs and plan
attacks, so don't tell me they had nothing to do with FALN
bombings,'' Hahn said.
</P>
<P>
   The FALN was linked to 130 bombings that killed six people and
maimed dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said the president's decision
``has undermined the country's doctrine that it will find
terrorists, hunt them down and punish them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., a long-time Clinton supporter,
said: ``As I have said, the burden of proof is on the
administration to prove why clemency should be granted. I have
repeatedly requested information on these cases. I have been given
no such information.''
</P>
<P>
   The president has said politics played no role in his clemency
decision and that he was swayed in large part by the lengthy terms
_ nearly 20 years in several cases _ already served by the FALN
members.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans and members of the law enforcement community
have accused Clinton of offering clemency to help his wife's
all-but-announced Senate candidacy from New York, home to some 1.3
million Puerto Ricans eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
   However, the issue has turned into a headache for the first
lady. Mrs. Clinton first came out against the clemency offer,
angering many of New York's Puerto Rican leaders. Then last week
she explained that she should have consulted more with Latino
leaders before reaching a decision.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
