<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAITT-CONCERT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDLY TRIO KICKS TOUR INTO GEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bruce Hornsby and David Lindley supplied some
extraordinary musicianship, Shawn Colvin and Jackson Browne the
introspection, and Bonnie Raitt the rock as the veteran performers'
concert tour hit the Greek Theatre on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In their own personal hootenanny, Raitt and cohorts have been
performing together for the past three weeks as kind of an ad-hoc
band. Each of them is spotlighted at times throughout the evening
but usually with at least one of the others joining in on harmony
or in accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   The results, as you might guess, are uneven. Sometimes it works
quite well, such as on Colvin's hit ``Sunny Came Home,'' an
intimate number that benefits from strong backing, but there are
other times when numbers lack focus and the addition of another
voice or instrument seems extraneous.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately it's Raitt's energy that fuels the evening. After
30 years in the business, she's got as much kick _ maybe more _ as
she ever has. And songs like ``Are You Ready for a Thing Called
Love'' and ``Let's Give Them Something to Talk About'' had the
house rocking.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt did most of the talking, too, showing off her bawdy sense
of humor when she ended a solo she was dueting on with Lindley and
cracked, ``That's the first time I ever finished before a man.''
</P>
<P>
   While not as outgoing as Raitt, the others weren't slouches
musically. Hornsby showed off some wild piano licks, and Lindley
was his usual amazing self, excelling on a multitude of different
string instruments throughout the evening.
</P>
<P>
   While Colvin is an accomplished songwriter, most of her material
is suited to more intimate places than the Greek, which was sold
out. Browne, who has had a longer career and is a Southern
California fixture, fared better. His songs like ``The Pretender''
or ``Barricades of Heaven'' maintain their intimacy even with
expansive arrangements. And Browne can kick it into gear, too, as
he _ joined by the others _ proved on the final number before the
encore, ``Running on Empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best thing about the evening, though, was watching
how these longtime performers clearly have fun making music after
all these years. That in itself is inspirational. If the rest of us
could just enjoy our jobs that much. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
