   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Sept. 19,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-POP-MUSIC (Undated) _ During ``Not Lookin,''' a new duet
with her former beau, the urban love man K-Ci Hailey, Mary J. Blige
demonstrates how to stop a man cold. The song, from Ms. Blige's new
album, ``Mary,'' pits a woman seeking true affection against a man
out for pure pleasure. Throughout the 1990s, most discussions of
women's increased power in pop have focused on alternative-rock
transgressors like Tori Amos and Courtney Love or the songbirds of
Sarah McLachlan's Lilith Fair. Rhythm-and-blues artists sold albums
but were rarely viewed as culture shapers. Now, though, with
mainstream rock again becoming a male bastion, it is clear whose
music matters within the continuing emergence of women as equal
players in contemporary music. By Ann Powers. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY-NIGHT-LIVE (Undated) _ Nothing in popular culture can
be hip for 25 years. The culture turns over far too many times.
Icons become relics; objects of obsession become objects of
nostalgia. So what are we to make of ``Saturday Night Live''? The
one-time groundbreaking, precedent-setting, establishment-tweaking
comedy sketch show begins a decidedly well-established 25th season
on NBC next week, to be celebrated by a two-and-a-half-hour
prime-time special next Sunday night. Longevity is certainly not in
itself a claim on pop cultural relevance. Other shows have been on
longer but are in no danger of being labeled hip (e.g., ``The Price
Is Right''). But, apparently in defiance of both time and show
business convention, ``SNL'' begins a 25th year still the most
pervasive influence on the art of comedy in contemporary culture.
By Bill Carter. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIGULA-FILM (Undated) _ This month, the re-release of a movie
that became infamous in 1980 for going too far will go even further
_ about 12 minutes further, according to its producer, Bob Guccione
of Penthouse magazine. ``Caligula,'' called by Newsweek ``a
two-and-one-half hour cavalcade of depravity,'' will now run nearly
two-and-three-quarters hours. The movie opened Friday in New York.
By Ted Loos. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   JAKOB-THE-LIAR-FILM (Paris) _ ``Jakob the Liar,'' directed by
Peter Kassovitz and starring Robin Williams as the reluctant hero
Jakob Heym, opens in New York on Friday. The film, based on a 1969
novel by Jurek Becker, tells of a Jewish cafe owner who uses lies
to bring hope to a Polish wartime ghetto. By Alan Riding. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHABBY-BLACK-DANCE (New York) _ ``I'm supposed to look like a
disheveled, disgruntled old geisha,'' Beverly Blossom said
cheerfully, dressed in a long golden kimono and top hat and
sprawled in a convenient folding chair in a midtown rehearsal
studio. Next she swept across the floor in a bargain-basement black
satin Balenciaga cloak and thrift-shop gold dress, a toy monkey
drooping from her hand. Then, with the donning of another, slightly
shredded costume, she became both an aging beauty and a
bottom-patting old gigolo drawn together in a bittersweet tango.
``Who (italics)is(end italics) she?'' a visitor to the studio
whispered, eyes wide, as Ms. Blossom glided through the dizzying
array of characters she will portray in ``Dances in Shabby Black,''
a retrospective program on Friday and Saturday at the Context
Studio, a small black-box theater on the Lower East Side. By
Jennifer Dunning. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   DOWNSIZING-MUSICALS (subslug) (New York) _ The dancing corkscrew
will still be there, as will the singing whisk and the graceful
cheese grater. But there may be slightly fewer spinning plates and
spatulas when ``Beauty and the Beast'' reopens at the Lunt-Fontanne
Theater on Nov. 12. By Robin Pogrebin. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OHNESORG-MUSIC (Cologne, Germany) _ Franz Xaver Ohnesorg, 51, a
Bavarian, who has held various administrative position in Munich,
will become the executive and artistic director of Carnegie Hall.
By James R. Oestreich. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NINE-INCH-NAILS-ALBUM (New York) _ Trent Reznor can smile now.
``Everyone has this impression of me that I'm morose,'' he
complained. An interviewer pointed out that the albums he had made
as Nine Inch Nails were saturated in despair. ``Point taken,'' he
said. Reznor was caffeinated and voluble as he sat in a midtown
hotel room where he was doing interviews, sipping what was clearly
not his first cup of coffee and explaining how five years went by
between ``The Downward Spiral'' and Nine Inch Nails' new album,
``The Fragile.'' By Jon Pareles. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UN-PRIVATE-HOUSE-ART (New York) _ Modern life is long, modern
art is short. That's why art keeps getting better all the time. If
you don't like it now, just stick around for a while. Eventually,
something likable is bound to turn up. It's a pleasure to report,
for example, that the Museum of Modern Art's architecture and
design department is back on track after several lackluster
seasons. ``The Un-Private House,'' a current show has been a
popular as well as a critical success. The exhibition of 26 recent
residential designs will run through Oct. By Herbert Muschamp.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
