<HEADER>
A3393 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-WTO-PROTEST-SPI &LR;      09-15 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-PROTEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUCKUS SOCIETY `IN TRAINING' TO DISRUPT WTO SUMMIT IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They call it the perfect protest: a city snarled. Traffic tied
up. Banners hang from buildings. Protesters have chained themselves
to trees.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the The Ruckus Society, which teaches these things, which
espouses these methods, which really wants to disrupt life in
Seattle when the World Trade Organization meets here later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Ruckus Society will be at the Pragtri Farm just
outside of Arlington, Wash., to teach 160 activists from around the
world how to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   The society, based in Berkeley, Calif, promotes its weeklong
workshop as a camp. Instead it is a training ground for what could
be the nation's largest protest in 20 years. Protesters from
Florida, Vermont, Minnesota and Oregon are expected to attend the
camp, which started Wednesday. So are protesters from Canada and
England.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle police and federal agencies have set up a task force to
deal with the planned protests. The city's SWAT team will be on
alert, police said; specific security plans have not been released.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters and a police line make good visual images _ and
that's what the Ruckus Society says its training is all about: It
wants protesters to get their messages across, but it doesn't want
them to get hurt doing it. .
</P>
<P>
   The WTO conference will be held in Seattle Nov. 29 through Dec.
3. It will bring about 5,000 delegates from around the world to
discuss, among other things, trade and tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Westlund, communications director for the Rainforest Action
Network, which is co-sponsoring the camp at the Pragtri Farm, is
glad to see delegates from around the world will come together
during the WTO conference.
</P>
<P>
   But he's concerned, too, about the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good thing,'' Westlund said of the WTO conference.
``It's good to see an acknowledgment that the world is one, linked
ecoysystem.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we're going to globalize, we need to have environmental
laws, we need to have laws that protect people. We gotta get it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Forcing the delegates from 150 nations to ``get it right'' is
the overarching theme of The Ruckus Society's camp. Its official
title, ``Globalize This!'' was coined by John Sellers, The Ruckus
Society's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Courses include how to reconnoiter areas for protests; how to
blockade objects and streets; how to perform effective political
theater; and how to coordinate massive, non-violent movements of
humans against an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The camp also marks a departure further into the politics of
protest for the 5-year-old group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new lease for us,'' said Sellers, a Greenpeace
veteran. ``This is the first time we've done a camp with a totally
concrete political target in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we've always tried to depoliticize the camps. Now
we'll be able to do a lot more livewire classes, with everything
focused on distilling the same basic message.''
</P>
<P>
   That message?
</P>
<P>
   The WTO is a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers calls this camp ``advanced camp.'' The only applications
accepted, he said, were for progressive, experienced protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people are planning on making their feelings
known,'' said Westlund, of the Rainforest Action Network. ``But
we're focused on getting our message across in a non-violent way.
</P>
<P>
   That means climbing buildings, creating mass civil disturbances
and performing skits that demonize the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be doing an expanded technology bit of things _ digital
activism, like online security, encryption, building the perfect
Web site against WTO,'' Sellers said. ``We'll be doing advanced
media classes. We won't have mandatory climbing workshops like
we've done at some of our other camps, but we'll have it so that
people can climb pretty much anytime they want at the workshops.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be an advanced ropes course at the farm, Sellers
said, and a two-story steel structure for people to practice
climbing buildings _ which is designed to help them better display
their banners made of rip-stop nylon.
</P>
<P>
   The society's climbing expertise has been on display in Seattle
before.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, nine society trainers dangled from the Aurora Bridge
for 48 hours to block a fishing trawler from leaving Lake Union.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers was at the Aurora Bridge that day, though not dangling
from it; he was providing site security for the others. In 1998,
Sellers and three other activists climbed to the top of a
construction crane in downtown Houston and opened a giant banner
that read ``Houston, We Have a Problem _ Stop New Oil
Exploration.''
</P>
<P>
   The WTO conference, which focuses on global trade, has given the
group, and protesting in general, a much-needed boost.
Municipalities have become much stricter about citing people for
civil disobedience, Sellers says, and that's made it tougher to
find people willing to get a message across.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things are heating up right now,'' Sellers says. ``The
media is champing at the bit to go and report this kind of news.
There's no Monica Lewinsky, story, no O.J. Simpson story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
