<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-NEGLECTED-THEATERS     09-15 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEGLECTED-THEATERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY'S NEGLECTED THEATERS ARE NOW IN DEMAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
By ROBIN POGREBIN    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For 12 years, the 74-year-old Biltmore Theater has
stood dark and lifeless, blackened by fire damage, crumbling with
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Now with Times Square suddenly prime real estate and theaters in
increasingly great demand, people are fighting over the 948-seat
house, at 261 W. 47th St.
</P>
<P>
   The battle, between a real estate developer, who says he wants
to restore and book the theater, and the Nederlander Organization,
which says it may try to more than double the house's size so that
it can accommodate musicals, has cast a light on some of Broadway's
most beautiful and neglected jewel boxes: the small, two-balcony
theaters, mostly on the less popular east side of Broadway, that
have fallen into disuse.
</P>
<P>
   Theater operators, who had considered these properties obsolete
money losers, and real estate interests are now vying over at least
three of the theaters, suggesting that a recent trickle of serious,
straight drama on Broadway could lead to a busier future for houses
like the Biltmore, Belasco, Cort and Lyceum. Yet the strengthening
real estate market in Manhattan could threaten the theaters as
never before.
</P>
<P>
   There is new interest in the Lyceum Theater on West 45th Street,
which has been dark 70 percent of the time over the last 12 years,
according to a report by Richard Frankel, one of several Broadway
producers interested in putting a tourist attraction in the
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to a number of successful plays in smaller theaters,
including last season's ``Blue Room'' at the Cort on West 48th
Street, Shubert Organization chairman Gerald Schoenfeld, said,
``All of this bodes well for the future.'' He once campaigned
unsuccessfully against designating the theaters as city landmarks,
arguing that theater owners should receive tax breaks or other
compensation for the burden of operating under landmark status.
</P>
<P>
   Jed Bernstein, president of the League of American Theaters and
Producers, said: ``Do we have a new paradigm? I don't think anybody
knows the answer to that. This season if you had a telephone booth
you could book it if it had a fire exit.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Broadway theaters are booked to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over the Biltmore involves all the issues that are
likely to shape the theaters' future.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Moinian, a real estate developer, said he wanted to
restore the Biltmore and build a 43-story residential hotel next to
it. He is suing the Nederlanders, the prominent theater owners,
arguing that the organization improperly terminated his contract to
purchase the property because real estate values had tripled since
1997, when he arranged to buy the property for $14.4 million. They
now believe that the Biltmore can fetch a higher price, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   The Nederlanders have moved to dismiss Moinian's complaint on
the grounds that he failed to show up for the real estate closing
last April, thereby defaulting on the deal. The theater owners are
considering transforming the Biltmore into an 1,800-seat theater as
they shop it to other prospective buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Biltmore's interior became a city landmark in 1987, as did
the interiors of five other Broadway theaters, meaning that any
changes made for a production, like taking out rows of seats to
expand the stage, must be reversed after the show closes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the options they're considering is rehabilitation of
the interior and exterior in compliance with landmark
regulations,'' said Howard Rubenstein, a spokesman for the
Nederlanders, in reference to the Biltmore. ``They will either sell
it or rent it or retain it. They're looking at all three options.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Judge Herman Cahn of state Supreme Court in Manhattan
heard arguments in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for the Biltmore are sharply different than they
were in the 1980s, when all of Broadway's theater owners fought
landmark designation for theaters that they did not see as
economically viable. These small theaters are difficult to book
because many people do not want to sit in a second balcony and
producers need a certain seating capacity to earn a return on their
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Larger theaters like the Gershwin, the Majestic and the Marquis
each have about 1,600 seats and only one balcony. And some
theaters, like the Helen Hayes, rarely use their second balconies.
</P>
<P>
   Can theater owners be blamed for wanting to update these small
houses or get rid of them? ``Most of these buildings are
approaching 100 years old, and you can't just recreate them
easily,'' Bernstein said. ``By the same token, you can't remodel
them easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's really hard for theater owners to grapple with the
problem. There is no other business I can think of where the owners
of the factories are still operating with the same plant as they
were 100 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s theater owners struggled to fill seats
because of the economic downturn, and some sought to unload their
properties. In 1991, for example, the Nederlanders sold the Mark
Hellinger theater to the Times Square Church. About three years
later, the Shubert Organization agreed to install a community court
in the Longacre Theater for three years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Biltmore is not the only house of its size that is suddenly
coveted. Two blocks down, a fight is raging over the fate of the
foundering Lyceum on 45th Street. Several producers want to open an
hourlong show geared toward tourists, ``The Spirit of Broadway,''
which would run several times a day. But Schoenfeld contends that
the production is not a legitimate theatrical attraction and does
not belong in the Lyceum.
</P>
<P>
   Although he called the Lyceum a money-losing liability when he
sold the Lyceum's air rights to Bertelsmann AG, the German media
company, Schoenfeld nevertheless said: ``We're not interested in
doing anything other than preserving these theaters for the
presentation of legitimate theatrical attractions.''
</P>
<P>
   Another developer holds a similar option at the Belasco, a
Shubert theater.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent demand for Broadway houses of almost any
size, many people in the theater district say the Biltmore-sized
theaters do not have much of a long-term future.
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Landesman, the president of Jujamcyn Theaters, which owns
the two-balcony Walter Kerr Theater, said he believed that the
demand would change with the economy. ``The future of the
two-balcony playhouse is still extremely grim right now,''
Landesman said. ``There's a theater shortage and booking backlog,
but it's not going to last. We've been through these cycles
before.'
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Landesman said, he does not consider the Walter
Kerr newly valuable property. ``If I can get a good price, I would
take it,'' he said ``It's tough to book.''
</P>
<P>
   The Biltmore, home of ``Barefoot in the Park,'' ``Hair'' and
``My Sister Eileen,'' was built in 1925. Designed by Herbert J.
Krapp and developed by Irwin Chanin, the neo-classical theater
needs extensive repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Moinian said he originally intended to turn the Biltmore into a
lobby for the adjacent high rise he planned to build on the east
side of Eighth Avenue between 47th Street and 48th Street, which he
would call the Biltmore. But because of the theater's landmark
interior, Moinian said the city's Landmarks Preservation Commission
informed him that such plans would be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Moinian said he proceeded with plans to restore the theater.
Unable to locate the original blueprints, Moinian hired an
architectural firm, Issac &AMP; Stern, that recreated the plans from
scratch. He then hired the architectural firm Li Saltzman, which
specializes in restoration. The plans were submitted to the
Landmarks Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Rosen Deutsch, the chief of staff for the landmarks
commission, said, ``When we heard about the litigation, it was
decided we would wait to hear the outcome on ownership before any
permits were issued.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
