<HEADER>
A3399 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KELSO-COLUMN16-COX     09-15 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    End of Tukky's adventure tears at boy's heart, father's walletBy
John Kelso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ The good news is that
<TEXT>
Tukky, the Hebrew-speaking African gray parrot, has been found and
is back speaking Hebrew in its own cage in Northwest Austin.
<P>
   The bad news is that the kid who took it in wants one of these
high-dollar birds for himself. And his dad says that will set him
back a couple of grand.
</P>
<P>
   But what the heck? He's a chiropractor.
</P>
<P>
   After reading about Michelle Perris-Moscona's lost bird, Tukky,
in this column Sunday morning, Dr. Jay Morgan, who lives about two
miles from Perris-Moscona as the parrot flies, realized that the
bird his family took in was, indeed, slightly conversant in Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   So on Sunday, Morgan and his son, Casey, 12, returned the bird
after some grieving by the boy. Casey, a bird enthusiast who had
wanted an African gray parrot for quite some time, thought his
prayers had been answered when the bird showed up next door
unexpectedly and he got to take it home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had been bugging us just like a Chinese water drip torture
to get an African gray,'' Jay Morgan said. ``If you sneak into his
room at night, you can hear him praying on his knees to God to get
him one.''
</P>
<P>
   This bird yarn began Sept. 2 when Tukky, the Hebrew word for
parrot, flew away from Perris-Moscona's deck. She lives on Cat
Mountain with her husband, Jerry, and son, Ronny, 13. The bird
learned to say a few phrases in Hebrew from listening to the family
chat in the living room. Michelle and Jerry hail from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgans live on top of Shepherd Mountain, overlooking Loop
360 and the Pennybacker Bridge _ a couple of hills over from the
Moscona family. The Morgans have a cockatoo named Gumbo. This is
high-end territory, and no one out here in these large homes keeps
chickens unless they are wrapped in cellophane.
</P>
<P>
   Around 7:30 last Saturday night, the Morgans' next-door neighbor
called the Morgans to report that a bird had run into the
neighbor's back window and stunned itself. The neighbor figured the
bird was Gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   But when young Casey found out the bird was an African gray
parrot, he rushed next door to apply for custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't even get off the phone, and my son is like ringing
their doorbell,'' Jay Morgan said. ``It was like he was aglow. He
was absolutely ecstatic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Morgans took the bird in, not knowing who owned it.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sunday morning, Jay Morgan picked up my column and started
reading about a missing Hebrew-speaking parrot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm (thinking), `No way, it can't be the same bird, and the
article says, `Mimics cell phones,''' he recalled. ``About the time
I read that, the bird goes, `(insert cell phone noise here).'''
</P>
<P>
   He read on. ``Person lost it from West Austin. I'm going, `Bad
sign,''' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the dagger through the heart: ``And then I read further,
and it says it speaks Hebrew,'' Morgan said. ``So I go over to the
cage I have him in, and I go, `Tukky,' and he goes, `Tukky,' and I
go, `Oh-oh, we're dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said approaching his son about returning the bird was
tough duty. ``So my wife and I go in his bedroom, and I say, `Son,
we've found the owner of the bird.' Casey goes, `There's no
possible way,' and I said, `Son, go speak Hebrew to him.' And he
says, 'What's Hebrew?'''
</P>
<P>
   Casey came around to see things his father's way. ``I said,
'Casey, we have to do the right thing here,''' Morgan said. So on
Sunday, Jerry Moscona picked up Tukky. And no, the Morgans did not
accept the $250 reward.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Perris-Moscona is glad to have her bird back. Jay
Morgan is pleased about that, too, although he says the incident
will lighten his wallet. He figures he has to get Casey an African
gray parrot, which costs considerably more than a $7 duck from
Callahan's General Store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure this woman over on Cat Mountain is going to cost me
about a grand for a bird and another grand for a cage,'' Morgan
joked. ``I have no choice. We kind of hope he (Casey) forgets, but
we figure the chances of that are about the same as flying in the
space shuttle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
