<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-STAGEHANDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEDERLANDER NEGOTIATES ITS OWN STAGEHAND PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Breaking ranks with Broadway's other major theater
owners, officials of the Nederlander Organization have reached a
separate agreement with the stagehands' union.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Local One of the International Alliance of Theatrical
Stage Employees ratified the new contract Sunday, said Tony
DePaulo, the theater business manager for the union.
</P>
<P>
   The Nederlanders' move was a departure from the most common
labor strategy of theater owners, who let the League of American
Theaters and Producers, a trade organization, represent their
interests in negotiation sessions with the unions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain the rationale for making their own deal, the
Nederlander official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said, ``Sometimes you just don't feel like being part of a massive
committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The current contract between the League and Local One expired
July 31. The new, five-year agreement between the Nederlanders and
Local One includes an annual 3 to 3.5 percent increase in pay along
with title and category upgrades for some production stagehands,
said DePaulo. He said stagehands' salaries under the previous
contract ranged from $944 to $1,270 per week, with benefits and
pension payments.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the Nederlanders received concessions from the
union on work rules for house electricians and other backstage
workers as well as the use of film stock shot during performances.
``I think it's a very progressive deal,'' DePaulo said. ``It
reflects the 1990s rather than the 1940s.''
</P>
<P>
   The league and the other two major Broadway theater owners, the
Shubert Organization and Jujamcyn Theaters, are to begin their
negotiations with the union Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nederlanders are the first major theater owner to directly
seek their own deal with a union, although corporate producers like
Disney, with hits like ``Beauty and the Beast'' and ``The Lion
King,'' and Livent, producer of the musical ``Ragtime,'' have
negotiated their own deals. The Nederlanders own eight theaters
outright and half of the Palace Theater.
</P>
<P>
   According to the league's by-laws, members are allowed a
one-time exception from the collective bargaining negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Kylie Robertson, a spokeswoman for the league, said the league
had no comment on the deal. ``The league was not involved in this
issue,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BIZMAGS16-COX     09-15 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retirement of execs forcing new strategies
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ American corporations face a growing challenge: the
loss of management talent through retirement as the population
ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there aren't enough young workers to fill the gap,''
Business Week (Sept. 20) reports. ``So companies are tapping the
vast resources of their older workers'' by scrapping age limits and
creating ``bridge periods'' or transitions between full-time work
and retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are already adopting defensive strategies. Chevron
conducts ``demographic audits'' to pinpoint skill shortages.
Monsanto and Prudential use retirees as temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
   Pro sport nightmares
</P>
<P>
   They're talented, rich and famous, and they get to play ball for
a living. But off the playing field or court, pro athletes face a
host of trials and tribulations, says P.O.V. (October). The
problems include career-ending injuries, losing seasons and fans
who become foes with one missed foul shot or field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stripped of celebrity's sheen, their motivations and
sacrifices seem not just unenviable but even a little mundane,''
the magazine says of the pro athlete's lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy 3 Sticks' return
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta native James D. Robinson III didn't retire to the golf
course after being forced out as American Express CEO six years
ago, as so many ex-chief executives might have done.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes (Sept. 20) says he relied on his AmEx connections and
multiple board memberships _ including Coca-Cola _ to build a
successful investment advisory firm specializing in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ``Jimmy 3 Sticks'' by the New York press, Robinson is
chairman of Violy, Byorum &AMP; Partners, which has put together $5
billion in deals in the last four years, Forbes says.
</P>
<P>
   The market's art
</P>
<P>
   Computerized stock market certificates may be more efficient
than traditional shares of stock, but they will never replace the
quality of those old-fashioned certificates with pictorial artwork
good enough to frame.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune (Sept. 27) provides a look at some of the finely
engraved stock market certificates via excerpts from a new book,
``The Art of the Market.''
</P>
<P>
   A share of stock is technically a bill of sale, proof of part
ownership in a corporation. But the certificate may outlast the
company and become valuable as art.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ The September/October issue of Competitive Edge, one of
several Atlanta-based business publications, looks at the
importance of cultural differences for companies engaged in global
business. ``The fastest state-of-the-art technology will not help
you make sales if the cultures of foreign customers cause them to
misinterpret your communications,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Privately owned companies are behind much of the state's
growth, Georgia Trend (September) says in its annual report on
Georgia's largest private firms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
