u w BC-PUERTO-RICO-BOMBING-H     09-15 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-RICO-BOMBING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR OF PUERTO RICO COMES TO THE RESCUE OF THE FIRST LADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The governor of Puerto Rico enlisted in the New
York Senate campaign of First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on
Wednesday in a move that could bolster Puerto Rico's drive to evict
the U.S. Navy from a target range on the island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Gov. Pedro Rossello said his political support for
the first lady's pending campaign for the New York Senate seat was
not conditioned on her support for Navy withdrawal from Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically offering my help in her campaign for the U.S.
Senate and my views on issues that pertain to Puerto Rico,''
Rossello said before meeting Mrs. Clinton at the White House. He
said the first lady ``would be an exceptional senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossello, during a round of meetings on Capitol Hill, won a
commitment from Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, chairman of the
Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee, to introduce
legislation to transfer Navy-owned land on Vieques to the
government of Puerto Rico. The committee has jurisdiction over U.S.
territories such as Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski's legislation would turn 22,000 acres of Navy-owned
land on Vieques over to the government of Puerto Rico within 60
days of Rossello submitting a land use plan to the White House and
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello said he will continue his five-month campaign to
persuade President Clinton and Congress to permanently end target
practice on Vieques in the aftermath of a Marine Corps' bombing
mishap in April that killed a Puerto Rican security guard and
injured four others.
</P>
<P>
   Ending target practice and turning the land over to Puerto Rico
is ``a question of fairness,'' Rossello said. Live-fire training on
an island inhabited by civilians would ``not be happening in any
other territory that is a state,'' Rossello added.
</P>
<P>
   Target practice has been suspended since April, a step that Navy
maintains could imperil the combat readiness of Atlantic-based Navy
and Marine units.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello said he has asked Vice President Al Gore to persuade
Clinton to order the Navy to withdraw from Vieques, located eight
miles east of the main island of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``has been very supportive and has expressed to President
Clinton his desire that the Navy look for other alternatives other
than Vieques,'' said Rossello, a two-term governor of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello met with Mrs. Clinton after meeting with Murkowski and
other lawmakers on Capitol Hill. A special Pentagon review panel
continues to prepare a recommendation for the White House on the
Navy's future use of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Puerto Rico and allies in Congress want the
president to order a permanent end to live-fire training that has
been going on the island since 1941, as well as Navy turnover of
two thirds of the island territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy contends the 899-acre live fire impact area, an 11,000
acre maneuver area and an 8,000 acre ammunition depot provide the
opportunity for integrated land, air and sea combat training that
cannot be duplicated anywhere else on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that the president as commander in chief will be able
to see the broad panorama and he will be able to make a decision
that's in the interests of the American citizens who live on
Vieques,'' Rossello said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 9,300 civilians live on the island that was seized along
with Puerto Rico by the United States in the Spanish American War
in 1898.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rossello could be an important campaign asset if Mrs. Clinton
runs for the Senate seat of retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., particularly as she tries to recover from a misstep on a
White House clemency offer to imprisoned Puerto Rican nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton urged the president to rescind the clemency offer
three weeks after extending leniency, only to have most of the
Puerto Rican nationalists accept the deal a few days later. Puerto
Rican politicians in New York accused the first lady of a flip flop
that imperils their support for her Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But Rossello said Mrs. Clinton's ``intervention was a catalyst''
to forcing the imprisoned nationalists to reach a decision to
accept White House conditions for clemency, adding that the
question is now ``a closed issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossello's support could be crucial in New York City, where
Clinton's expected rival, Republican New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, carried 43 percent of the Hispanic vote in the New York
City mayoral race in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics, including Puerto Ricans, made up 20 percent of the
New York City vote in that election.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics, including New York state's 1.3 million Puerto Ricans,
were an important source of support last year for then-Rep. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., in his ouster of veteran Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y. Schumer won 82 percent of the Hispanic vote statewide in a
contest in which Hispanics represented 6 percent of the statewide
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
