<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   2 More Robot Kits From Lego Mindstorms &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lego Mindstorms may have managed to capture the market of
pre-teen-age boys (and their fathers) with its line of buildable,
programmable Lego robots introduced last fall. This year, the
company wants to give 9-year-olds, too, a reason to pester their
parents for Legos. And they won't even need a PC.
</P>
<P>
   Two new products _ the Robotics Discovery Kit and the Droid
Developer Kit _ are showing up in stores this month. The droid kit,
which features white, blue and silver-colored pieces, enables
children to recreate and program the robots of ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery set is more colorful. Models made with its pieces
can perform up to 3,000 behaviors like chirping, rolling forward
and, to provide that element of security all 9-year-olds need,
firing a harmless rubber dart as soon as they sense bright light.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's product required children to assemble their robots,
create their programming instructions on computers and then
download the programs into their creations. The new sets do not
require traditional computers at all; they come with palm-size
microcomputers that can be programmed by pressing buttons on their
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the learning here is for kids to understand the
process of invention,'' said John Dion, a Lego Mindstorms
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Lego is still making some assumptions about the
technical skills of its clientele: to read the droid kit's building
instructions, you must have a computer with a CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of shag carpets, beware: The discovery set comes with 387
easily lost plastic pieces, and the droid kit has nearly 700. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Guernsey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Watching Hurricane Floyd Without Even Getting Wet &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most captivating witnesses to Hurricane Floyd are
not wearing TV-network-issue windbreakers. In Jensen Beach, Fla.,
Webcams atop a Holiday Inn
(www.video-monitoring.com/martin/pan/pan.htm) provided a panoramic
view of the storm's passage over the state's south coast.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the county, three people covered a Linux computer
in plastic and left it running while they sought higher ground. The
machine, equipped with a Webcam and a T-1 line, survived
Wednesday's onslaught, recording the progress of the surf as it
crashed its way up to the house. Their Web page received more than
470,000 hits in 24 hours (z.treco.net/greg).
</P>
<P>
   _ Bruce Headlam &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sun's New Network Strategy Is to Aim to Simplify Things &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the battle to rid personal computing of needless complexity,
Sun Microsystems recently announced a new network computing
technology.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the Sun Ray 1 appears to be an ultrathin,
high-tech desktop computer with a flat-panel monitor and a central
processing unit no larger than a closed novel. Upon closer
examination, the Sun Ray 1 is what Sun executives like to call an
appliance. All the real computing is done over a powerful,
high-speed network, much the way a telephone is an appliance linked
to a complex network that the user never sees.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Ray 1 does not store applications like word processing
and spreadsheet programs on the desktop, as conventional PCs do.
Everything is on a network. Users insert a special card to gain
access to the network and their files. With the card, users can
also get to their work on any Sun Ray 1 on the network, freeing
them from having to be at a particular desk.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Ray 1 is not available for home use yet. The first
markets for the Sun Ray 1 are, among others, customer management
systems like call centers and help desks; education, including
libraries and school administration, and government and financial
services. But when broadband service, like digital subscriber
lines, becomes more widely available, the Sun Ray 1 could migrate
into the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is a technology that can make use of the bandwidth
that is coming available,'' said George Banman, a vice president
and general manager for information applications. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A New Player Can Decipher MP3 Music Files on CDs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an uncommon merger of competing technologies, Pine
Technology, a company based in Hong Kong, says it has found a way
to combine the best of MP3 music and CD players.
</P>
<P>
   The device, called a D' Music CD Player SM-200C, looks much like
any other portable CD player and can play regular CDs. Its chief
advantage, said Brian Hamilton, the vice president for sales and
marketing at Pine Technology USA, is that the player can also read
and decode music in the MP3 format, something regular CD players
can't do.
</P>
<P>
   That means that rather than read MP3 music stored on chips
(usually no more than a hour) in MP3 players, the D' Music CD
player reads MP3 compressed music stored on compact disks, which
can hold more than 100 songs and hours of music.
</P>
<P>
   The catch, and it may be considerable for many consumers, is
getting the MP3 music onto to CDs. That requires another device, a
CD writer, something that most computer owners must add to their
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Hamliton said the $299 player (three times the cost
of a conventional CD player and about $100 more than most MP3
players) represented a significant step forward for Web-wired music
lovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing today is just the start of a lot of
fantastic things to come in the next year or so,'' he said. The
player will go on sale this fall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michel Marriott &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giving Books Away Online While Hard Copies Are Sold &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those who argue about the virtues of paperbacks versus
electronic books, Byron Preiss has a new question: Why not enjoy
both? Preiss is the president of Ibooks, which opened its doors on
the Web this week. Ibooks, at www.ibooksinc.com, publishes
paperback and hardback books even as it gives them away in
electronic form.
</P>
<P>
   For the next few weeks, people can download the first chapters
of the books from the Web. After Oct. 1, visitors will have free
access to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Guernsey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medical Guide From Harvard Has an Online Supplement &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Simon &AMP; Schuster releases the Harvard Medical Family Health
Guide, a 1,300-page book, next month, it will have its own
anti-aging prescription: a Web site to provide updates on the text
chapters as they arise.
</P>
<P>
   The guide, which will sell for $29.95, features information on
how to navigate managed health care and on how all the major
biological systems work.
</P>
<P>
   It also has sections on the diseases and disorders associated
with each system.
</P>
<P>
   Access to the site (www.health.harvard.edu/fhm) can be viewed
now and is not limited to owners of the Family Health Guide. The
site is designed to supplement the book's core material.
</P>
<P>
   The guide and the site, edited by Harvard Medical School faculty
members, are designed to improve the quality of communication
between doctors and patients, said Dr. Anthony Kamaroff, editor in
chief of the Harvard Medical Family Heath Guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time patients have with their doctors is shrinking,''
Kamaroff said. ``So we want to give the patient a thorough idea of
what questions the doctor is likely to ask, to help them prepare
ahead for when they're in the doctor's office.''
</P>
<P>
   The site has interactive features designed to make it easier to
understand some of the complex charts in the book, Kamaroff said.
The 165 symptom charts, for example, are laid out in the book as
logic trees, but they can be navigated on line by answering a
sequence of yes or no questions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Catherine Greenman
</P>
</TEXT>
