<HEADLINE>
`ACTION' AN INTELLIGENT COMEDY WITH AN ADULT SLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lights! Camera! Ask the kids to leave the room!
</P>
<P>
   And then get ready for some ``Action.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that kind. Not on the screen, anyway. While ``Action'' the
TV show might be indelicate and coarse, we're persuaded that it
does have some standards. For instance, there is no frontal nudity
in Thursday night's premiere. Well, there is a
penis-mightier-than-the-sordid scene when a studio boss steps out
of the shower to confront our crude antihero, Peter Dragon. (Yup,
his name is Peter Dragon.) But the camera stays focused squarely on
the only Peter that won't get Fox arrested.
</P>
<P>
   At least not this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action'' is as earthy as a landfill, and there are many who
will complain that's where it belongs. The language is raw (the
really off-color stuff is bleeped but no less recognizable), and
there's so much sexual inuendo that it almost comes out the other
endo, right onto the cable converter. But, unlike other sitcoms,
which use sex because there seems to be a manual somewhere that
says sexual situations are inherently funny, ``Action'' uses sex
because it's inherently believable.
</P>
<P>
   And as a satire of the movie industry, ``Action'' is delectable.
Think of all those things a Boy Scout is supposed to be _
courteous, kind, clean, reverent, morally straight _ and now think
of the opposite. That's ``Action'': fearless, creative and as
offensive as a commercial network dares to be.
</P>
<P>
   If ribaldry is not your scene, no need to go in search of
``Action.'' But if intelligent comedy with an adult slant doesn't
make you dive under the bed, ``Action'' may be the best thing to
hit Thursday nights since ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that it's not on NBC. You've got a clicker, no? Look
under the sofa, next to the dusty sock. There. Now click over to
Fox and meet Peter and Wendy.
</P>
<P>
   Peter is a golden-boy producer for Dragonfire Films. Wendy is a
former child star who turned to prostitution when the nose candy
gave her a big nasal cavity and a lousy attitude. They meet by
accident and strike an unlikely partnership that makes Wendy
Peter's confidante and de facto script consultant. (Though his last
few films _ ``Uzi Easter,'' ``Carnival of Daggers,'' ``Dead and
Spit On in Oakland'' _ have earned billions worldwide, Peter
wouldn't know good writing from a good grocery list.)
</P>
<P>
   The series bears some resemblance to the current Albert Brooks
film, ``The Muse.'' Like Brooks' screenwriter character, Peter
Dragon is in danger of falling off the Hollywood A-list because his
current movie, ``Slow Torture,'' is a dud. Catching Wendy's fur
coat in the door of his limo may be a stroke of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night Live'' alumnus Jay Mohr, who played the sleazy
agent in ``Jerry Maguire,'' is completely despicable as Peter
Dragon. That's a good thing, although Peter is so unlikable he's
hard to root for. But studio boss Bob Gianopolis (Lee Arenberg) is
even worse _ he stole Peter's wife, even though he's gay _ which
may give Peter just enough underdog status to win us over.
</P>
<P>
   If not, there's always Wendy Ward, played with unbridled panache
by Illeana Douglas. Wendy can be as blunt and brash as Peter, but
where Peter's glass of diet spite is half empty, Wendy's glass of
Jolt never needs refilling. She's also smarter than a roomful of
movie moguls and knows what most of them look like with their pants
down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, no spoof of Hollywood is complete without celebrity
walk-ons. Thursday night's 9 o'clock premiere features Keanu Reeves
sitting down; a second episode in the show's regular 9:30 time slot
Thursday night has Salma Hayek. Next week we get Steve Garvey (hey,
they can't all be A-list), and the week after that it's Sandra
Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Action'' will succeed on irreverence and a willingness to
pillory with shotgun randomness. The Jewish power structure in
Tinseltown gets its share of zingers, but ``Action'' is likely to
offend every interest group long before the wrap party. After
Thursday night, Christians, homosexuals, O.J. Simpson supporters,
peasants in Calcutta and employees of the month may want to warm up
their letter-writing arms.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ``Action'' isn't without its touching moments. It's
Christmastime in the first episode when Peter, not knowing what to
get Wendy, gives her an envelope stuffed with cash.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously touched, Wendy says, ``But I didn't get you
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter demurs, but Wendy persists: ``I could call my girlfriend
Tracy and we could fool around together while you watch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's so sweet,'' Peter says.
</P>
<P>
   To which Wendy replies: ``Well, 'tis the season.''
</P>
<P>
   'Tis also the season for more than three dozen new series on the
networks, and ``Action'' may be one of the best. It's racy. It's
vulgar. And it's very funny.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, there's no laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   Action. Half-hour comedy series satirizing the movie industry.
Starring Jay Mohr, Illeana Douglas and Buddy Hackett. Two-episode
season premiere Thursday night on Fox. Show moves to 9:30 p.m. next
Thursday. Parental guideline rating: TV-MA.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
