<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROSSINI-OPERA-REVIEW-     09-15 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSSINI-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VIAGGIO A REIMS': LONG-LOST ROSSINI OPERA RESURRECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (editors: production notres at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Having warmed up the New York State Theater with
returning productions of ``Madama Butterfly'' and ``The Magic
Flute'' over the weekend, the New York City Opera offered its first
new production of the season, Rossini's ``Viaggio a Reims,'' on
Tuesday evening. The performance was treated, for some reason, as
the official opening of the season, which is to say that it was
followed by a dinner for patrons, and included a 30-minute tribute
to Beverly Sills after the intermission, honoring the 45th
anniversary of her debut with the company.
</P>
<P>
   For admirers of the bel canto style, it was also an occasion to
celebrate the City Opera's tradition of exploring rarities,
neglected works and unusual editions of familiar operas.
``Viaggio,'' after all, is an odd duck. As Rossini's last opera in
Italian, it holds a pivotal place in his works list; yet it was
also the very definition of an occasional work, meant to celebrate
a specific public event, the coronation of King Charles X of France
in 1825. Rossini, apparently considering the work of no further
use, withdrew it and cannibalized it in other works.
</P>
<P>
   The score was lost until the mid-1970s, when some of the
orchestral parts were found in Paris. Other materials were
discovered in Vienna and Rome, and the work had its first modern
staging in 1984. But it wasn't until 1992 that the final piece, a
chorus that begins the finale, turned up in the manuscript
collection of the New York Public Library. So although there is a
fine recording of the work, conducted by Claudio Abbado on the Sony
Classical label, ``Viaggio'' is a new world for most listeners.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of charm, cleverness and demands for vocal acrobatics,
``Viaggio'' has a lot to offer, even for a listener who usually
finds Rossini easily resistible. The story is slight but amusing. A
band of travelers is stuck at a hotel awaiting transportation to
Reims, where the coronation is to take place. When horses prove
unavailable, they decide to take part in the celebrations in Paris
instead, but before they leave, each traveler _ all the important
European powers of the time are represented _ offers a tribute to
the new king, sung in the appropriate national style.
</P>
<P>
   Political allegories are plentiful (program book essays by
musicologists Philip Gossett and Janet Johnson offer a key for
modern listeners), but so is Rossinian comic froth, including a
patter song and pairs of lovers at cross purposes. Because a starry
cast had assembled in Paris for the coronation and was available to
Rossini, he wrote no fewer than 10 principal roles, making for a
nearly nonstop stream of ambitiously florid arias and challenging
ensembles. This may also have been one reason Rossini withdrew the
work: its potential casting problems were immense.
</P>
<P>
   The City Opera has assembled a cast that was surprisingly
comfortable not only with Rossini's vocal acrobatics, but with the
embellishments supplied by Gossett, an expert in this style. That
isn't to say that everyone was of equal power and artistry. Indeed,
whatever the qualities of the company's new electronic enhancement
system _ and to these ears the house sounded much as it always has
_ it is by no means an equalizer of talents.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most outstanding singer in the production is Camilla
Tilling, a Swedish soprano who was making her company debut as
Corinna, a poet who sings two exquisite arias (one of them
offstage) with harp accompaniment, and represents Italy in the
multinational assembly of travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tilling's voice has a graceful, limpid quality that floated
nicely through the house. She also has the dramatic instincts to
create a character that reflects the qualities Rossini wrote into
her arias, serenity and independence.
</P>
<P>
   Notable as well were Mary Dunleavy, who gave a powerful,
clear-toned performance as the coltish French Countess of
Folleville, and Sally Wolf, who sang with both energy and subtlety
as Madame Cortese, the owner of the Hotel of the Golden Lily. Paula
Rasmussen's dark-hued mezzo-soprano suited the role of Marquise
Melibea, who, representing Poland, has an opportunity for both
reflection and, in her duet with the Russian Count Libenskof (sung
ably and sometimes colorfully by Jeffrey Francis), temperamental
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The men in the cast had a hard time measuring up to the women.
Monte Jaffe sang Don Profondo's patter song with the requisite
drive, but his timbre was dry and colorless. Kevin Glavin was also
a bit woolly sounding as the German Baron Trombonok, but he acted
and sang the role with considerable comic verve. Roberto Scaltriti
portrayed the English Lord Sidney amusingly, but with muffled
diction. Barry Banks gave a nicely agile performance as the failed
French lothario, and Dean Ely's account of Don Alvaro's final aria
had exactly the right Iberian flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Moyer's sets _ a tiled hallway and a swimming pool room,
both in mint green _ were simple and uncluttered, and effectively
lighted by Mark McCullough. Anna Oliver's costumes reflected the
ornateness of the period. James Robinson directed the large cast
deftly. Doug Varone choreographed the dance in the finale. And the
orchestra, conducted by George Manahan, sounded splendid.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `IL VIAGGIO A REIMS'
</P>
<P>
   Opera in three acts by Gioachino Rossini, libretto by Luigi
Balocchi after Madam de Stael's novel ``Corinne, ou l'Italie'';
conductor, George Manahan; directed by James Robinson; choreography
by Doug Varone; sets by Allen Moyer; costumes by Anna Oliver;
lighting by Mark McCullough. At the New York City Opera.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kathryn Honan-Carter (Maddalena), Peter Strummer (Don
Prudenzio), Kenneth Floyd (Antonio), Sally Wolf (Madame Cortese),
Mary Dunleavy (Countess of Folleville), Leah Creek (Modestina),
Benjamin Brecher (Don Luigino), David Ossenfort (Zefirino), Kevin
Glavin (Baron Trombonok), Paula Rasmussen (Marquise Melibea),
Jeffrey Francis (Count Libenskof), Dean Ely (Don Alvaro), Monte
Jaffe (Don Profondo), Roberto Scaltriti (Lord Sidney), Camilla
Tilling (Corinna), Barry Banks (Cavalier Belfiore) and John
Lankston (Gelsomino).
</P>
</TEXT>
