<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3418 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FLOYD-0916-COX     09-15 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-0916-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT GUIDES A HURRICANE?
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Several days before Hurricane Floyd began turning
northward, forecasters with the National Weather Service were
predicting with some confidence that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Some even felt confident the storm's right-hand turn, or
``recurve'' in the language of meteorologists, would happen just as
it neared the east coast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday afternoon, as Floyd headed toward its expected
South Carolina landfall, forecasters were saying - again with
confidence - that Hurricane Gert would turn northward and miss the
United States altogether.
</P>
<P>
   As computing power and a variety of weather monitoring
techniques have rapidly improved in the past few decades, the
ability to ``model'' the conditions surrounding a hurricane and
predict where it will go have improved rapidly, said Herb White, a
meteorologist with the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have better input data and vastly improved computing
power,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Computer ``models'' -- which combined readings from thousands of
weather balloons with hurricane-hunter aircraft information
gathered in the eye of Floyd and data from satellites, ships at
sea, even commercial aircraft -- would easily predict that a low
pressure ``trough'' moving eastward across the United States would
deflect Floyd northward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricanes move westward from an area just off the coast of
Africa primarily because the prevailing winds in the tropics are
east-to-west,'' explained Peter Ray, chairman of the meteorology
department at Florida State University in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   The storms are like corks spinning in a stream of water, he
said. And for all their power, the stream of water is more
powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The winds that circulated practically unnoticed around the
continental-scale low pressure zone contained enough energy to
carry the spinning cork northward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front was much bigger than the hurricane,'' he noted,
``and the winds that surrounded it extended over the whole
north-south extent of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened with Floyd was a question of timing, Ray added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the front was moving across the United States and that
the winds around that front would tend to deflect the hurricane to
the north.''
</P>
<P>
   The only question was how fast Floyd moved toward the Florida
coast and how fast the low pressure front moved to meet it. A
difference of a day would have determined whether Floyd recurved
northward before it reached the coast or made landfall in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Less clearly understood are how the circumstances immediately
surrounding a hurricane and swirling above it converge to define
its intensity.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic example in recent years was Hurricane Andrew,
which on Aug. 19, 1992 was a tropical storm that was so weak
hurricane-hunter aircraft had trouble finding its eye.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, it crashed into the southern tip of Florida, a
Category 4 hurricane, the second most powerful kind of storm known.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the last few years have meteorologists begun to explore
the mysterious reaches of the upper atmosphere, where gigantic
cyclones can destroy a hurricane or convert a lazy tropical storm
into a killer.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1996, when the government put a $43 million Gulfstream jet
equipped with weather monitoring gear into service, hurricane
hunter planes had a ceiling of about 25,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   They flew into hurricanes and released ``dropsondes,''
instruments that measured such weather forecasting staples as
humidity, temperature and pressure as they fell through the storm.
</P>
<P>
   When the radioed results were analyzed, meteorologists could
piece together a fairly accurate picture of what was happening in
the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Above 25,000 feet, however, was a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping its ``dropsondes'' from altitudes as high as 40,000
feet, the Gulfstream is rapidly filling in this data and and
meteorologists are learning much about conditions at the top of a
hurricane, where the rising winds that swirl around its eye spread
out and move away.
</P>
<P>
   Huge cyclones that swirl just beneath the stratosphere may have
a lot to do with whether a hurricane remains upright and grows in
strength and intensity or starts to tilt and sag, researchers
think.
</P>
<P>
   A better understanding of the interplay between the surface
level storm and the cyclones above it could greatly improve the
forecasting not only of its path but also its intensity, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
