u w BC-CENSUS-2000-HNS &LR;      09-15 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD CAMPAIGN LAUNCHED TO INCREASE HISPANIC PARTICIPATION IN 2000
CENSUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congressional board and a Houston councilman
launched an advertising campaign Wednesday to increase Hispanic
participation in the 2000 Census, saying the video blitz would
prevent a repeat of the 1990 U.S. population count that missed many
Latinos and other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston, assailed the U.S. Census
Monitoring Board's effort as a disingenuous attempt by the
Republican-led Congress to appear sympathetic to minorities
uncounted in the 1990 Census. If Republicans and the board were
sincere, Green said, they would support President Clinton's
proposal to use statistical data to help account for minorities
that Census Bureau personnel will inevitably miss next year.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Councilman John Castillo joined the monitoring board in
releasing the video at a Capitol Hill news conference. The tape,
recorded last month in Houston, features city and community leaders
as well as residents encouraging Hispanics to return their census
questionnaires next year in order to prevent a repeat of the 1990
count.
</P>
<P>
   That count of the U.S. population, the most recent, missed 8
million people, according to the Census Bureau. The 1990 census in
Texas undercounted Hispanics by 5.4 percent, compared with 3.9
percent for blacks and 2.6 percent for non-Hispanic whites and
Asians, the bureau reported.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's total estimated undercount of 3.9 percent, or 875,333
Hispanic residents, that year was the highest of any major city,
while Texas' 2.8 percent was second to New Mexico. The Texas
undercount cost the state about $1 billion in federal assistance,
Green has said.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutionally mandated census is conducted every 10 years
to determine how the 435 seats in the House of Representatives will
be apportioned among the 50 states. The federal government also
surveys the population at other times to determine how federal
money should be allocated.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent an undercount next year, Clinton had proposed using a
statistical formula to complement the traditional head count of the
U.S. population. But the Supreme Court struck down the president's
proposal in January as a violation of the federal Census Act's
mandate that the decennial census be a head count, a decision
endorsed by the monitoring board, a congressional agency.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high court's ruling and over Republican objections,
Clinton has vowed to go forward with plans to conduct a second
census that would include statistical data. That second count would
be used to determine the social-welfare needs of each state but
would not go toward the calculation of House seats.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo said the video, to be sent to nearly 1,000 Hispanic
leaders and communities nationwide, will encourage Latinos to
participate in the 2000 Census by alleviating many of their
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the tape debunks rumors that information disclosed
on the census questionnaire will be shared with the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, the councilman added.
</P>
<P>
   The video is a montage of interviews the board produced when its
representatives visited the Houston area with Castillo last month,
seeking ways to increase Hispanic participation in the census.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, in announcing the release of the video, said Green's
concerns about partisanship are unfounded. The board is trying to
mount a ``grass-roots'' effort to ensure that the traditionally
missed Hispanics are counted, the councilman said.
</P>
<P>
   J. Kenneth Blackwell, co-chairman of the monitoring board,
joined Castillo by telephone from Ohio and echoed the councilman on
the importance of Hispanics responding to the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Latinos and Hispanics represent one of the fastest
growing communities in our society and have much to gain in being
fully counted in the 2000 Census,'' Blackwell said. ``This is about
counting people. It's not about Republican or Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   But Green was not convinced, citing the monitoring board's
outspoken opposition to Clinton's effort to use statistics to
complement the traditional head count of the U.S. population. Green
said the board's vocal denunciation of the president's proposal
undermines minorities' faith in the census and discourages their
participation.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who represents a largely Hispanic district, has denounced
the Supreme Court's decision and said another miscount of Houston's
population would cost the city much-needed federal assistance for
social programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in defending the statistical sampling proposal, has
said he expects only 67 percent of the U.S. population to return
completed census questionnaires that will be mailed nationwide next
year. Under Clinton's plan, the population would be divided into
census tracts of about 4,000 people that have ``homogenous
population characteristics, economic status and living
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau agents then would visit a randomly selected sample
of the housing units that did not submit census forms. The sample's
population numbers and characteristics would be added based on the
statistical results.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
