<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF NEW DREAMCAST GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sept. 9, Sega launched its new,
gonna-take-ya-to-the-next-level home video-game system, Dreamcast
($199). Here's a quick look at four of the key titles:
</P>
<P>
   Sonic Adventure: Well, as Sega promised, Sonic's latest
run-and-pick-up-the-gold-coins journey is fast. And colorful. And
fun. But does Sonic Adventure ($49, all ages) break vid-game ground
like Nintendo's Mario 64? Not really.
</P>
<P>
   Sonic Adventure is more of an evolution than a revolution, a
spiffed-up, souped-up upgrade that features remarkable speed and
blinding colors _ but little else.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you'd want much else. Sonic games have always been more
about fast-paced action than Mario-type adventure. And on that
level, Sonic Adventure is a major success: Sonic races through a
whole new world, a brightly colored Oz-land filled with double-loop
tracks, underwater worlds and mountainous regions. You've never
played a Sonic game like this before.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Stinger: This game, however, has been around a long time
and was more fun when it was called Resident Evil. Blue Stinger
($49, age 17 and up) is the Dreamcast's version of RE, a horror
movie come to life in which the player must shoot to kill or run
like ... well, really fast.
</P>
<P>
   Story line: Guy hero gets stuck on an island that's infested
with mutants. Your goal: Like Metallica says, kill 'em all. One
interesting thing: You can use limbs from dead monsters to battle
live ones.
</P>
<P>
   The coolness stops there. The rest of the game is brainless,
grisly gore and nonstop bad language _ definitely not a kid game,
or a good one, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   NFL 2K: Here is a great game. NFL 2K ($49, all ages) has got to
be the best football game out there _ for any system. Period.
Frighteningly realistic graphics, all the teams and stadiums,
custom plays, precise, uncomplicated control _ forget Sonic. Buy
this instead.
</P>
<P>
   Soul Calibur: From Street Fighter to Virtua Fighter, Sega has
always had major luck with transforming arcade fighting games into
killer home video games _ and Soul Calibur ($49, age 13 and up)
carries on that tradition.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the medieval-themed SC so impressive _ besides the
superb graphics _ is the little bits of realism; for instance, the
game takes weapon weight into account. If this is the kind of stuff
Dreamcast is gonna be doing, its future definitely looks promising.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0292 </DOCNO>
