A3422 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-TEX     09-15 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS LAUNCH PUSH FOR SCHOOL PRAYER AMENDMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Declaring that the time has come to ``kneel down
for America,'' House Republicans launched their latest effort to
pass a constitutional amendment for school prayer Wednesday with a
foot-stomping, hand-waving revival meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas, GOP conservatives
gathered at a church near the Capitol to celebrate the
reintroduction of a school prayer amendment that the last Congress
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would expressly permit, but not require, school
prayer. It would also permit posting the Ten Commandments and other
religious teachings in government buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a nation must take a stand for authority and against
disorder. And, as we all know, the highest authority is God,''
House Republican Whip Tom DeLay of Texas said from the pulpit of
Bible Way Temple. ``In the battle for our culture, we all need to
understand that you cannot just stand up for America, you need to
kneel down for America.''
</P>
<P>
   But DeLay and other top Republicans conceded that the
constitutional amendment is doomed to defeat. Although the House
supported the proposal in a 224-203 vote last year, the outcome was
56 votes short of the two-thirds majority needed for a
constitutional change. It never came to a vote in the Senate, where
support is even weaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is to vote, have a national debate, so the
American people can see who's with `em and who's agin `em,'' DeLay
said. ``If you give up just because it won't pass, nothing will
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics accused Republican leaders of pandering to Christian
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Existing law protects a student's right to pray, say grace
before meals, read religious literature during free time and even
form after-school Bible clubs. Not only is this proposal dangerous,
it's unnecessary,'' said Barry Lynn, executive director of Citizens
United for Separation of Church and State.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative outlook did not dampen the enthusiasm of the
amendment's backers, who rallied behind the slogan ``America Come
Back To God.'' About 300 amendment supporters gathered at the
church after rains from Hurricane Floyd canceled plans for a show
of support on the Capitol steps.
</P>
<P>
   Church groups delivered petitions with more than 1 million
signatures endorsing school prayer. The event's organizers included
William J. Murray, the evangelist son of famed atheist Madalyn
Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Christians, and we just really want the Bible and
prayer back in schools,'' said Epifanio Rebollo, part of a
delegation of supporters who traveled to Washington from New York
for the rally. ``The founders of this government were Christians.
They strongly believed in the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the church, supporters jumped from their seats, waved their
hands and shouted ``Hallelujah'' in response to lawmakers'
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our laws should at every turn be a complement to, and
encouragement for, those laws of the Lord God Almighty,'' Armey
told his audience.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay drew the strongest response by outlining his vision of a
culture war in U.S. schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now only tolerance is taught, especially tolerance for what is
dangerous and immoral,'' DeLay said. ``God is not allowed in our
schools, but everything opposed to God is.'' Ron Hutcheson, (202)
383-6101 rhutcheson\Nkrwashington.com (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
