<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CISNEROS-WITNESS-HNS &LR;      09-15 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-WITNESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINDA JONES, KEY WITNESS IN CISNEROS CASE, MAY BE FREED SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ~WASHINGTON _ Linda Jones, the government's chief witness in the
conspiracy case against former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros,
could be released from federal custody as early as this week, a
prosecutor for Independent Counsel David Barrett told a federal
judge Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get this over with as quickly as possible,''
prosecutor Lawrence Scalise told U.S. District Judge Stanley
Sporkin.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, 52, pleaded guilty last week to a single misdemeanor
of lying to the FBI about $250,000 he paid Jones following their
extramarital affair. Cisneros agreed to a $10,000 fine but received
no jail time or probation.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Barrett, who spent more than $9 million on the
investigation, dropped 18 felony counts against Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who became caught up in a separate federal investigation,
pleaded guilty to 28 felony counts that included bank fraud. She
received a 42-month prison sentence from U.S. District Judge Sam
Cummins in Lubbock, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed to testify against Cisneros in exchange for a
reduction in her sentence. Her attorney, Sam Ogan, a public
defender in Dallas, said Barrett has proposed that Jones, who has
been in custody for 18 months, now be released with ``time
served.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister and brother-in-law, Patsy and Allen Wooten, also have
pleaded guilty to charges brought by Barrett. Scalise said Barrett
has recommended a $2,500 fine for the Wootens.
</P>
<P>
   Ogan said the reduction recommendation for Jones is before
Cummins.
</P>
<P>
   An extramarital affair between Cisneros and Jones, also known as
Linda Medlar, became public in 1988 when he was mayor of San
Antonio. Years later, when he was nominated to head the Department
of Housing and Urban Development, Jones feared she would lose a
secret financial arrangement with Cisneros, who had reconciled with
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   To protect that arrangement, Jones began secretly recording
Cisneros's telephone calls to her.
</P>
<P>
   She later made the tapes public and claimed Cisneros lied to FBI
agents about the amount he paid her. The FBI was conducting a
background investigation into his HUD nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sporkin signaled Wednesday that he would reject a
motion filed by the A.H. Belo Corp. seeking access to 26 of the
tapes of Cisneros and Jones that the prosecution was ready to use
as evidence in his trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the horse dies, you're supposed to get off of it,''
Sporkin told attorneys for Belo, the parent corporation of KENS-TV
in San Antonio and the Dallas Morning News.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lynch, a Belo lawyer, argued that tapes and their
transcripts became judicial record and pivotal to Sporkin's
pre-trial rulings on admissibility. Those rulings led to the plea
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros' lawyers strongly opposed their release, and Barrett's
prosecutors said the evidence should be kept from public
disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes contain intimate conversations between Jones and
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin said part of the plea agreement includes the protection
of Cisneros' private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over with,'' Sporkin told the Belo attorneys. ``Let Mr.
Cisneros live his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is currently the president of the Spanish-language
television network Univision in Los Angeles. He continues to own a
home in San Antonio with his wife, Mary Alice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
