u w BC-NASA-BUDGET-HNS &LR;      09-15 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL APPROVES $13.6 BILLION NASA BUDGET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Senate appropriations subcommittee approved a
$13.6 billion budget for NASA next year, virtually restoring nearly
$1 billion in cuts that were made by the House in the agency's 2000
spending request.
</P>
<P>
   Although some NASA funding still is in danger, the agency's
budget is expected to survive intact once House and Senate members
complete negotiations on year 2000 spending issues.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration of funding followed an intense lobbying effort
by Texas Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison. She won assurances from Sen.
Kit Bond, R-Mo., who chairs the appropriations subcommittee on
independent agencies, that NASA would be funded in line with
President Clinton's request for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison said Bond agreed that cutting $1 billion from the
NASA's budget next year would jeopardize not only the international
space station project, but a number of other science missions now
under way at the agency, including a study on human survivability
during long-term space travel, and development and production of
drugs and other materials in zero gravity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't cut $1 billion without warning from a highly
technical program and still meet the space program's important
goals,'' Hutchison said. ``A strong space program furthers the
national interest by advancing the frontiers of science in such
disciplines as physics, electronics and health care.''
</P>
<P>
   The NASA funding is part of a larger spending measure covering
the departments of veterans affairs, housing and urban development,
and independent federal agencies. When the House passed its version
of the VA-HUD measure last week, it eliminated more than $925
million in NASA funding. The reduction drew complaints from a
number of House members, especially those representing Texas and
Maryland, where NASA centers employ thousands.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, called restoration of
the NASA funding in the Senate bill ``good news'' and vowed to use
his leadership influence to keep the agency's budget intact during
House-Senate negotiations over the final VA-HUD measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the House and Senate come together to negotiate, NASA
will be restored to full funding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
