<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3430 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VISOR-ART-2TAKES-     09-15 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VISOR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH VISOR, THE IDEA WAS TO PLEASE ALL THE PEOPLE ALL THE TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Hawkins, the engineer who brought the Palm Pilot to the
world in 1996, is seated in his Spartan new office, pondering the
question of how he came upon the idea of putting a Game Boy-like
slot in the back of the Visor, the new palm-size omni-gadget from
Hawkins' new company, Handspring.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said that for a short time after he and his partner,
Donna Dubinsky, left their jobs at the Palm Computing division of
3Com Corp. to strike out on their own, they had not been sure about
just what they were doing. ``We weren't building anything,'' he
recalled. ``We had two desks and a houseplant.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one day, Hawkins had what he describes as ``a high moment,
when I said, `That's it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote all this down in my notebook,'' he said, ``and once I
got going, it all flowed right out, and I made a model. The whole
thing was done in a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, 14 months after inspiration struck Hawkins,
Handspring introduced the $179 Visor, a Palm look-alike whose
add-on cartridges, or modules, will eventually turn it into, among
other things, a wireless modem, a cell phone, an MP3 player, a
two-way pager or a game machine.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, a new palm-size computer might receive passing
attention in the consumer marketplace, which is already bursting
with personal digital assistants, or PDAs, and with cell phones
with built-in address books and calendars.
</P>
<P>
   But the Visor is the creation of Hawkins, Ms. Dubinsky and Ed
Colligan, the same trio who created the Palm Pilot, the first such
device to succeed where others had fallen flat. For that reason,
their new company has attracted an unusually high level of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins had not planned to do this. Before starting Handspring
with Ms. Dubinsky in the summer of 1998, he had scaled back to
working part-time at Palm Computing. In fact, Hawkins, an energetic
42-year-old engineer, had diverted his attention almost entirely to
another longtime interest: neurobiology. He was working on a book
about how the brain works.
</P>
<P>
   After what Ms. Dubinsky, 44, describes as ``many, many, many,
many months of conversation,'' Hawkins grew increasingly interested
in what kind of palm-size device he would be able to design if
given complete autonomy. In July 1998, both he and Ms. Dubinsky
resigned from 3Com and set up shop in Palo Alto, Calif., as J.D.
Technology. Within a month, they were joined by Colligan, who had
been Palm Computing's vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Handspring seemed blessed. Just a few weeks
after leaving Palm, Ms. Dubinsky and Hawkins signed a licensing
agreement with the company, which gave them the right to use the
Palm operating system in their own product. This meant that
whatever they built would work with the thousands of applications
already available for the Palm device. And while they had found it
hard to raise money for their original company, they were now flush
with offers from venture capitalists eager to see them duplicate
Palm's success.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said that the Palm's major drawback had always been the
device's inability to accommodate added hardware with ease.
</P>
<P>
   On the day he sketched out the Visor, Hawkins, who keeps
meticulous notes in a slim hardbound journal, sat down and listed
the kinds of devices people might want to add to a handheld device:
ROM cards for games and content, a memory expansion card, one- and
two-way pagers, a cell phone, a Global Positioning System receiver,
a wireless modem, an MP3 music player, a digital camera.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said he constantly bought electronic gadgets and took
them apart. One that he had dissected was the Nintendo Game Boy,
which has a slot in back for slipping game cartridges in and out. A
slot on his own product seemed an obvious solution.
</P>
<P>
   At dinner one night, Hawkins' 10-year-old daughter, Kate, came
up with the name for the main device: Visor, which is shortened
from ``advisor.'' The idea to call the expansion slot Springboard
was Colligan's.
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneurial team knew that the modules must be extremely
easy to use to be appealing. Indeed, when a Springboard module is
snapped in, it shows instantly on the screen. ``Users don't even
know what's going on,'' Hawkins said. ``They don't even know
they're installing anything.'' And when a module is taken out, it
leaves no trace of its presence.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said that both the Game Boy and the Visor emphasized
simplicity and longevity. ``I have held up the Game Boy at meetings
here as an example,'' he said. ``I remind people that we're
designing something that will be used for 10 years and more. A game
you bought eight years ago will play in a modern Game Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   But that, Hawkins said, is where the similarities end. He sees
the Visor as far more versatile than the Game Boy. ``The Game Boy
is a very limited user experience,'' he said. ``It doesn't do
anything unless you put a cartridge in, and if you take it out in
the middle of a game, it crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubinsky said she and her partners had seen little need for
market research. ``We felt we understood the marketplace pretty
well,'' she said. ``After all, we invented the product and the
category.''
</P>
<P>
   The company did conduct a few focus groups on ``some of the easy
things,'' Ms. Dubinsky said, like prices, memory and colors. (The
$249 Deluxe Visor has eight megabytes of memory, compared with the
two megabytes in the $179 Visor basic model. While the standard
color is black, the deluxe model also comes in a clear case or in
transparent blue, green or yellow.)
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Handspring got in touch with 20 or so
third-party developers to see if they would be interested in
creating some of the add-on devices on Hawkins' list. The response,
Hawkins said, was even more enthusiastic than he had hoped. Two MP3
modules are coming out soon, and Handspring is working with several
manufacturers on a cell phone module. Prices for the modules will
range from about $20 for a game to $250 for a cell phone or MP3
player.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Springboard slot in the back of the Visor is one feature
that had no market testing. ``You can't test the concept of a
slot,'' Ms. Dubinsky said. ``It's too major.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ms. Dubinsky said, she and her colleagues relied on ``a
general sense out there from people that they wanted to combine
devices, but no one had yet come up with a good way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest issue for Hawkins was price. Just as he had worked
hard to build the original Palm Pilot for $300 in 1996, he was
determined to keep the Visor's cost to $150. Such a price, he and
Ms. Dubinsky argued, would attract a younger and less affluent
crowd than today's Palm customers. Palm's most popular product is
the $449 Palm V, whose sleek anodized aluminum housing has made it
a de rigueur accessory for the professional set.
</P>
<P>
   But if he was to keep the price low, Hawkins knew that he would
have to sacrifice stylishness and settle on inexpensive plastic
housing for the Visor, and on triple-A batteries instead of the
rechargeable lithium-ion battery found in the Palm V.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as three weeks ago, the company was still trying to
figure out ways to keep the price at $150. At the last minute, it
decided to set that as the price for the no-frills Visor Solo unit,
a basic Visor without a cradle or software for synchronizing data
with a desktop computer. To cut distribution costs, it decided to
sell the Solo only on the Web (www.handspring.com), at least at
first. The basic Visor and the deluxe model will start being
shipped in October, while the Solo will start going out in
November.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The last word on design details was given to Hawkins, who holds
the unambiguous title of chief product officer. And details
mattered greatly to Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   One detail was the stylus, which is stored in a sleeve on the
side of the device. ``Every time I do a new product, I dread the
stylus,'' he said. ``I've never been able to get it right. On the
original Palm Pilot, it was a nightmare. They either got too loose
and fell out or were too tight and wouldn't come out.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Visor, Hawkins decided to put a tiny piece of foam
inside the sleeve so the stylus would slide in and out smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Is he happy with this solution? ``I won't know until I have
100,000 units in the field for a year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The display was easier. Technical advances have improved
displays in general, Hawkins said. The quality of the Visor's
display is somewhere between that of the original, rather fuzzy
Palm Pilot and the display of the crystal-clear Palm V. When a
visitor set her three-year-old Palm Pilot on Hawkins' desk to
remind him of the original display, he seemed appalled, as if he
had just been shown a picture of himself as a teen-ager in a Nehru
jacket. ``This looks like a joke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' he said, looking genuinely embarrassed.
``Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   In designing the Visor, Hawkins decided early on to put a small
microphone in each unit, which added a dollar to the cost but
opened the door for add-on devices like cell phones and voice
recorders.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins immodestly predicts a huge market for Visor modules. ``I
believe there will be hundreds and eventually thousands of things
that plug into the Springboard slot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone shares his optimism. In creating such a product,
Handspring's founders are betting that consumers will want one
device with multiple functions rather than owning one for each
purpose _ having a cell phone, pager, organizer and MP3 player, for
example. History suggests that they are mistaken. Exhibit A: the
Sony Walkman. Exhibit B: the Palm organizer itself. Both products
are beloved because they perform one function extremely well.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by a market research firm, Forrester Research,
found that although PDAs are in 3.6 million households in the
United States, people use them primarily for managing calendars and
to-do lists and not for more complex tasks like e-mail retrieval.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want a combination device,'' said Ken Dulaney,
vice president of mobile computing at the Gartner Group, another
market research firm. ``Every time you try to get a computer to do
many things, it ends up doing none of them well. Combination
PDA-cell phones are going to fail miserably.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The PDQ phone is the ugliest thing I've ever seen,'' Dulaney
said, referring to Qualcomm's 10-ounce, cell phone-cum-Palm
organizer, which will sell for $500 to $800, depending on subsidies
from carriers. ``Nobody wants that thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to such criticism, Ms. Dubinsky said she believed
that many people would buy the Visor simply as an organizer and
nothing else. Others, she said, may buy it to run a specific
module. One goal, she said, is to have Visors in widespread use in
high schools and colleges. ``Why shouldn't students all have a
little handheld computer that they can learn languages on, do math,
science, programming and all kinds of other stuff?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, executives at Palm have nothing but kudos for their
new competitor. Mark Bercow, a vice president at Palm, called the
Visor ``cool.'' But privately, Palm executives have done some
hand-wringing over the Visor's low price. Palm is likely to lower
the list price of its Palm IIIe before the end of the year, to
around $199 from $229.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins still plans to finish his book on neuroscience, but he
said the temptation to interrupt the project to take another pass
at building the perfect palm-size device was irresistible. ``Every
time I do one,'' he said, ``I think, `OK, it's a little closer.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
