<HEADLINE>
BIRD `DEFINITELY' DONE AS COACH AFTER THIS SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Indiana Pacers president Donnie Walsh brushed
aside speculation about the status of his head coach by saying
Larry Bird had never said, ``flat out,'' this would be his final
season.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Bird said it Wednesday, more than once, and without
equivocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely is,'' Bird said, responding to one of many
questions about his plans during a two-hour-plus interview session
with television and radio reporters to hype his new book, ``Bird
Watching: On Playing and Coaching The Game I Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be my last year,'' he said. ``I signed a three-year
deal. I've always thought three years for a coach was long
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are hoping Bird remains with the franchise in a
front-office capacity, perhaps succeeding Walsh as president. Bird
said he was uncertain about his future, adding, ``I'll wait until
next summer. Yes, I'll be bored again. But I signed a three-year
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to drive home the point, Bird said he could not even get
excited about the potential of Al Harrington or Jonathan Bender,
high schoolers drafted by the Pacers in the first round of the last
two drafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't draft two high school kids,'' he said. ``If you're
coaching for three years, you don't want too many high school
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird's publicity people picked an unusual method to hype the
book. Bird, making his only promotional appearance, sat in a studio
in Fort Myers, Fla., and was interviewed in 10-minute-or-less
sessions solely by members of the electronic media. He looked like
he was in a dentist's chair awaiting a root canal. ``You gotta do
some of it,'' he said by way of explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were print reporters not ``invited'' to participate,
Bird's people also did not make transcripts available.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the questions dealt with Bird's revelation in the book
that he has a heart condition, atrial fibrillation, which was
diagnosed only after he sought medical help after he retired from
playing. He did say, however, that he experienced the symptoms
while working out during the summer, while still with the Celtics,
but was unaware of what condition he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought it was fatigue, or working out too hard, or
overdoing it,'' he said. ``It didn't last long and it was always
gone when I woke up the next morning. I never had it while I was
playing (during the season).''
</P>
<P>
   Bird also was asked about his claim that Rick Pitino offered him
a job as an assistant coach prior to Bird's departure to Indiana.
Pitino has emphatically said no such offer ever was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I seen it,'' Bird said. ``I hear he doesn't see
it that way. Whatever. That's fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
