<HEADLINE>
CHARLES MRAZ, RENOWNED BEEKEEPER, LED VENOM THEORY; 94 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A funeral will be held Thursday for Charles Mraz, a nationally
known beekeeper and owner of New England's largest apiary who died
Monday at his home in Middlebury, Vt. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mraz was born in New York City. He moved to Middlebury, Vt.,
in 1928 and established Champlain Valley Apiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 70 years, Mr. Mraz became world-renowned for his
work as a beekeeper. He traveled to South and Central America,
Europe, Asia, and the Middle East as a consultant on beekeeping
methods and technology.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the American Beekeeping Federation recognized Mr. Mraz
among the five most distinguished beekeepers in the country for
advances in commercial beekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   A pioneer of the bee venom theory, the use of bee stings to
treat auto-immune diseases, Mr. Mraz established the standard of
purity for dried whole venom for the Food and Drug Administration
and was a supplier of venom to pharmaceutical companies and
independent researchers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he recounted his experiences with the bee venom theory
in his book ``Health and The Honey Bee.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mraz was a founding member and executive director of the
American Apitherapy Society, a nonprofit organization dedicated to
the medical use of bee products.
</P>
<P>
   An avid gardener and organic farmer, he was also president and
board member of the National Food and Farming Association, the
precursor of the Northern Organic Farming Association.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mraz also served as Middlebury water commissioner and on the
Cemetery Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He was a longtime contributor to the Rotary, Masons, and
Shriners in Middlebury.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mraz leaves his wife, Pamela; two sons, Charles of Destin,
Fla., and William of Middlebury; three daughters, Marna Ehrech of
Shelburne, Vt., Laurie Zwaan of Exeter, N.H., and Michelle of
Burlington, Vt.; several stepchildren; 13 grandchildren, and 7
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral will be held at 10 a.m. at St. Stephen's Episcopal
Church on the Middlebury Green. Burial will be in Middlebury
Cemetery.
</P>
</TEXT>
