<HEADER>
A3440 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAPAN-COURT-MUSIC-NYT     09-15 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-COURT-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: EX-COURT MUSICIAN NOW COURTS THE JAPANESE PUBLIC
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ At first glance, it is hard to imagine that Hideki Togi
was once a court musician in the Japanese Imperial Palace,
elaborately costumed and performing gagaku, a genre of ceremonial
music that has a thousand-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is his youth, long black hair, cowboy boots, or the
soothing, hip rhythms from his latest album that mask Togi's
legacy: His family has performed gagaku before a continuous
succession of Japanese emperors and aristocrats dating back to the
Nara period (710-794).
</P>
<P>
   But listen carefully to his music or attend one of his concerts,
and it becomes quite evident that although Togi resigned from the
Imperial Ensemble three years ago, he is keeping the gagaku
tradition alive and making it more accessible to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   In his Western-style compositions, Togi blends the haunting,
mystical tones of gagaku with the latest contemporary sounds and
beats, all played on a mix of ancient instruments, synthesizers,
cellos, electric guitars and bass.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a subtle fusion of New Age music that is both
yearning and uplifting, searching and defined, foreign yet
familiar, but immensely popular in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Togi knows various types of music, including pop, he
must be capturing many fans,'' said Motoko Sekiya, a music critic.
``Healing music is quite popular today, and Mr. Togi's music has
that kind of feeling. These must be factors that make his music
accessible. And it doesn't hurt that he's handsome, too.''
</P>
<P>
   While other contemporary Japanese composers like Maki Ishii and
Toru Takemitsu have incorporated gagaku into their music in the
past, Togi has taken the music in a new direction, to much critical
and popular acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old musician has been widely praised in Japan for
expanding the appeal of gagaku, which is one of the world's oldest
systematic forms of music with definite orchestration.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, Togi has released five albums that have
sold hundreds of thousands of copies. His latest compact disk,
``From Asia,'' appeared in March on Toshiba-EMI, which says it is
selling well.
</P>
<P>
   His music has become so popular that he has appeared on
television programs and in commercials and done a stint as a
celebrity panelist on a game show. Togi composed an easy-listening
tune for a Suntory pekoe tea commercial, in which he appears
dressed in kimono and holding canned tea with his gagaku music
playing in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started writing my own compositions, it was not my
intention to combine modern music with the ancient tradition as
means of popularizing gagaku,'' Togi said in a recent interview in
his home studio in Tokyo. ``I was just expressing what's inside me
musically. But if the result promotes gagaku, then I am happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Togi said his music was greatly influenced by his childhood,
which he spent living abroad, in Thailand and Mexico, where his
father worked for a trading company.
</P>
<P>
   ``At home my father listened to classical music and my mother
liked film music and operas,'' Togi said. ``But at the
international schools I attended I was exposed to jazz, pop and
rock. I really liked the Beatles.''
</P>
<P>
   Togi returned to Japan for high school and, upon graduation,
with some encouragement from his maternal grandfather, whose family
lineage consisted of court musicians, he entered the music division
of the Imperial Household. After seven years of intense study, in
which he learned to play several ancient instruments and to sing
and dance traditional music, he became a member of the Imperial
Ensemble, which is still restricted to men who are descendants of
court musicians. His instrument of choice is the hichiriki, a
double-reed pipe with nine finger holes that resembles an oboe.
</P>
<P>
   Togi also learned to play the cello because modern-day gagaku
musicians are required to play Western music to entertain visitors
of state from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   Togi says that while most Japanese have heard the word gagaku,
which literally means ``elegant music,'' few really understand what
the music is about, and many consider it too stiff and formal.
</P>
<P>
   There are three basic wind instruments in gagaku: the hichiriki,
the sho (a mouth organ made of 17 bamboo pipes) and the ryuteki (a
bamboo traverse flute with seven finger holes). These three wind
instruments play the main melody in gagaku, and they symbolize
heaven, sky and earth.
</P>
<P>
   Togi said that every note in gagaku contained significance. For
example, a single tone can represent a color, a season or even
something as unusual as a human internal organ. A spring note is
cheerful and warm while an autumn sound is more sorrowful.
</P>
<P>
   Togi said he resigned from the Imperial Ensemble to have greater
freedom to explore his own music at his own pace. ``As a member of
the Imperial Ensemble,'' he said, ``I was a civil servant, and my
hours were set from 9 to 5, and there were a lot of ceremonial
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a composer, there are days when the music comes very well
and days when it doesn't,'' he said. ``I wanted to have my own pace
of practicing, training and research that would allow the music to
flow more naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Togi said that his decision to leave the ensemble was not easy
and that it was very rare for court musicians to step down. He
noted that about one person in 100 years does so, mainly because
becoming a member is so arduous.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Togi's former colleagues at the Imperial Household have
publicly criticized his work, calling it laughable. Some gagaku
masters dismiss as invalid any efforts to write new gagaku
compositions or to combine the genre with Western instruments or
even to perform it outside the Imperial Household.
</P>
<P>
   ``The masters at the Imperial Household and my former colleagues
see me as an opponent, and they are very critical of what I'm
doing,'' Togi said. ``But my music has provided many people with
the opportunity to know Japanese gagaku. If the Imperial Household
sees this as problematic, then it's a small thing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Togi's prominence in Japan's music world was underscored
recently at a gala concert in Tokyo featuring some the country's
most noted opera, classical and jazz musicians. After performing a
medley of gagaku, Japanese and classical music on the hichiriki
accompanied by the Tokyo Philharmonic, Togi, who was clad in a
traditional costume, received the warmest applause of any other
performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed him the best because his music spoke to my soul,''
said Noriko Oikawa, a high school teacher. ``He was the only
performer who did something authentically Japanese.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
