<HEADLINE>
SPANISH TRANSLATION ERROR JEOPARDIZES TEXAS BALLOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM BOWER and CARMINA DANINI  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A translator's error has created a major headache
for election officials across Texas, and it could cost Bexar County
taxpayers $91,000 to fix.
</P>
<P>
   The problem stems from an incorrect Spanish translation of
Proposition 15, which is a constitutional amendment ``permitting
spouses to agree to convert separate property to community
property.''
</P>
<P>
   The original translation in Spanish, which appears on Texas
ballots, permits spouses ``to agree to convert separate property to
the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Secretary of State's Office, which printed the
ballots, issued an urgent notice Tuesday to officials across the
state, warning that the error is forcing the correction and
recertification of ballots for the Nov. 2 election.
</P>
<P>
   In Bexar County, 400,000 ballots already have been printed based
on a certification of the ballot language by the secretary of state
on Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Bexar County Clerk Gerry Rickhoff told county commissioners
Tuesday the mix-up could cost the county up to $91,000 if the
ballots must be reprinted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means we either have to resticker 400,000 ballots or
reprint them at a cost of $91,000,'' Rickhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Counties bear the cost of reprinting ballots because the state
doesn't have authority to assume liability, Ann McGeehan, deputy
assistant secretary of state, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Bexar County Judge Cyndi Krier said the county should look into
a third option of having poll workers hand out fliers with the
corrected language along with the ballots.
</P>
<P>
   McGeehan said local election officials could opt to have their
ballots reprinted or could purchase stickers with the corrected
language and affix them to each ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The translation was done by a person who's federally certified
to work as a translator in federal court, McGeehan said. The same
translator, who has yet to be paid, also did the translation for
the 1977 constitutional amendment election.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there had been any translation errors in the Spanish
version of the ballot for that election, McGeehan replied: ``Not
that we're aware.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
