<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV17-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARASODA GIVES SARATOGA UNFAIR ADVANTAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Friday, Sept. 17)  
(rk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rivalry between Sarasota (Fla.) and Saratoga (N.Y.) has
taken an ugly turn.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's true that I'm the one who started the rivalry and
there are probably only two or three people in either city who are
dimly aware of it, but it's a rivalry that has taken an ugly turn
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   I am speaking, specifically, of a new soft drink being marketed
in upstate New York called Sarasoda.
</P>
<P>
   Created by John and Carolyn Davis of PJ's Bar-B-Q in Saratoga
Springs, Sarasoda is said to be made with loganberries, which the
Davises claim is some sort of cross between a blackberry and a red
raspberry. However, if you read the fine print at the top of the
label, you'll see the words ``Contains 0 Percent Fruit Juice.''
</P>
<P>
   I am not a trained food critic or nutrition expert ``per se,''
so I suppose it is possible that Sarasoda could have several
bushels of ``loganberries'' squished into each 20-ounce bottle and
still, technically, contain 0 percent fruit juice.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, that in itself is not enough to turn ugly the
rivalry between Sarasota (Fla.) and Saratoga (N.Y.), such as it is.
</P>
<P>
   As a Professional Journalist I try to be objective, particularly
if it involves eating or drinking something I am pretty sure I am
not going to like. So I had my wife and 13-year-old son do a taste
test of Sarasoda, which comes in two flavors: Loganberry Flavored
Drink and Loganberry-Lemonade Flavored Drink. Both (the drinks; not
my wife and son) are noncarbonated.
</P>
<P>
   My wife took a sip of Loganberry Sarasoda and made the kind of
face I saw her make once before when she was doing laundry and
unwisely put her hand into the pocket of the boy's jeans.
</P>
<P>
   When she resumed breathing, she described Sarasoda as
``sickeningly sweet,'' quite a strong opinion from a woman who
considers mocha fudge chocolate cake to be one of the world's major
religions.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, needless to say, judged Sarasoda to be wonderful,
comparing the flavor to the liquid in those little edible wax
bottles that I dimly remember from my childhood.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who finds black coffee too sweet, I was
understandably reluctant to sample Sarasoda myself. Would my teeth
fall out? Would my face collapse upon itself like that unfortunate
fellow in the beer commercial? Would I get the sudden urge to
wander off into the woods to smoke and cuss like those annoying
young people in ``The Blair Witch Project?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, nothing remotely like that happened, though I did,
after taking a sip from each bottle, have this irresistible urge to
wash and vacuum my car, mow the yard and re-shingle the roof.
Whether it was the colorful label that accounted for this or the
high-fructose corn syrup, I can't really say. But I must admit I
felt strangely ... energized.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly why Sarasoda represents such an ugly turn in
the Sarasota/Saratoga rivalry. Although the Davises winter in
Sarasota, their concoction, Sarasoda, is available only in upstate
New York. While people living in Saratoga Springs and surrounding
areas are busy washing their cars and re-shingling their houses, we
Sarasoda-denied slobs of Sarasota continue to have trouble
summoning the energy to operate the remote control or chew our
oatmeal.
</P>
<P>
   There is more to life than high-fructose corn syrup, I realize,
and Sarasota has a lot of things going for it that Saratoga does
not, though I am much too tired to recall what those things might
be right at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Another swig or two of Sarasoda might be just the thing to jog
my memory.
</P>
<P>
   And give me the energy to clean out the garage.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
