<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-FLORIDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOYD LEAVES FLORIDIANS WONDERING WHAT MIGHT HAVE BEEN 
</HEADLINE>
 (With HURRICANE-RDP, HURRICANE-BEACHES, HURRICANE-BAHAMAS) 
(nk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITUSVILLE, Fla. _ The roundhouse punch that Hurricane Floyd was
supposed to deliver to Florida was more like a love tap, and while
most people in this vastly relieved state thanked God and luck, a
few, like Chad Fish, were almost disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The storm, four times the size and just as strong as the killer
Hurricane Andrew that laid waste to South Florida in 1992, had
threatened to ruin miles of coastline and be the event of the
18-year-old Fish's young life here in Titusville, a city of 42,000
people on Florida's east-central coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had hit us ... ,'' he said whimsically as he watched a
soft, harmless rain fall outside the Ramada Inn in this
still-deserted, boarded-up city Wednesday afternoon. But just as
forecasters had predicted, the hurricane turned north before its
eye and most powerful winds made landfall in Florida, and the
damage it left on land was more like a strong summer thunderstorm
than a murderous storm.
</P>
<P>
   More than a million people evacuated Florida's east coast on
Monday and Tuesday _ part of the largest evacuation in the nation's
history _ in shaky anticipation. Never had a storm so great come so
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see it, in a way,'' said Fish, who lives in
Titusville with his mother. Chances are, he said, it will never
happen again.
</P>
<P>
   While rescue workers stood by on the eastern side of the state,
rescue was seldom needed _ although a drunken man did stagger into
the surf in Daytona Beach and had to be fished out, complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Winds, estimated at up to 140 mph near the eye of the storm,
were a fraction of that on the coast, where hurricane-force winds
simply did not penetrate. ``Nothing in the way of massive damage at
all,'' said Don Pride, a spokesman for the Florida Insurance
Commission. ``It appears that Florida has dodged the bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   In Daytona, the hurricane's strong waves knocked down a wooden
pier, a sentimental spot for residents. The wind tore a roof off a
palm reader's house a few miles away, and damaged a church. It
pushed down trees _ but not many _ and downed power lines all along
the east-central coast, which had seemed to be the most likely
place for a landfall or serious damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had God's hand on us,'' said George Schultz, a maintenance
man in Titusville.
</P>
<P>
   The storm ripped awnings, knocked down a billboard, blew some
aluminum siding into power poles in Brevard County and, here and
there, toppled the aluminum roofs over gas pump islands, which
sometimes fall in hard rain. The wind also almost knocked down
several television reporters who insisted on standing on beaches
during the height of the storm to show viewers that it was, indeed,
windy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been spared,'' said Mel Martinez, county executive of
Orange County, which had expected hurricane-force winds earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Kelly, a spokeswoman for the Florida Emergency
Operations Center, said Wednesday that the state was still
assessing damage and had no figures yet, but county officials up
and down the east-central coast said most of the damage they saw
was minor.
</P>
<P>
   Even mobile homes, which almost melt in hurricane-force winds,
residents here said, came through the winds mostly intact.
</P>
<P>
   Power losses were mostly spotty. Ms. Kelly said some 240,000
households were left without power as of Wednesday. However, more
power losses were expected as the storm skirted the coast at
Jacksonville and moved north off Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Beach erosion, from elevated tides, was one of the most
noticeable impacts of the storm, but even that, residents said, was
less than feared.
</P>
<P>
   In Cape Canaveral, four space shuttles, valued at $2 billion
each and housed in hangars at the Kennedy Space Center, were
apparently not damaged, said NASA spokesman George Diller. Nearby,
at the Cape Canaveral Air Station, four rockets _ valued at more
than $600 million _ were left on the launching pads as the storm
neared, but they, too, were apparently not damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney World near Orlando, which was closed on Tuesday for
the first time in the park's 28-year history, was to reopen on
Thursday. ``Very minimal damage,'' said Renee Callahan, a
spokeswoman for the park.
</P>
<P>
   As the storm left the Florida coast, hundreds of thousands of
people who had left their homes for shelters and hotel rooms inland
headed back to their coastal homes, and most of them were relieved
when they got there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very fortunate,'' said Nell Deberry, who works at the
Ramada Inn in Titusville.
</P>
<P>
   While there was some mild grumbling about the mandatory
evacuations _ actually a misnomer, because many people ignored the
order from emergency management officials and stayed home _ most
people here seemed satisfied that the state handled the crisis
well. Most said it just made sense to flee.
</P>
<P>
   As the winds began to blow on Tuesday, William R. Davis knelt in
front of the walkway at Melbourne High School in Melbourne, one of
three shelters in that city that were mostly packed. The
62-year-old Davis knows hurricanes. He has been dodging them all
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old-time commercial fisherman, a shrimper,'' he said,
sucking on an unfiltered Camel. ``I've been out at sea when it blew
your pants off with your legs crossed. I've got sense enough to get
out of it now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
