<HEADER>
A3448 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV23-     09-15 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `LOOK' WORKS ON CHILDREN OF ALL AGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Sept. 23)  
(lh) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of my commands to my two children are issued at the back
of their heads, from another room or tossed over my shoulder while
I'm driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't do that to your sister!'' ``Put the ketchup back in the
refrigerator!'' ``Don't dump out the crayons unless you're planning
on picking them all up again!'' ``Quit sitting on the dog!''
``Don't step on the Etch-a-Sketch!''
</P>
<P>
   As my exasperation level is reached, the commands get louder and
more threatening.
</P>
<P>
   And then I am was reminded, by an article in a parenting
magazine, about The Look.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the one your mom and dad perfected. My mother, lips
drawn tight, could look across the supermarket and cut me down with
a glance.
</P>
<P>
   The look that made you freeze mid-sentence, mid-action, and
reconsider your whole plan.
</P>
<P>
   It's the calm born of confidence and control. The way a really
good first-grade teacher quiets a class of rowdy 6- and 7-year-olds
with a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the irony: To capture attention, do almost nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Don't yell. Don't threaten. Don't lecture. Don't plead. Don't
repeat something 54 times.
</P>
<P>
   Say it once, low, calm and (you hope) effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, of course, is in how you say it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an art to doing nothing, (and) that can turn you into
an immovable pillar of strength,'' writes Chris Ravashiere
Medvescek, a journalist and conflict-resolution mediator, in
Parents magazine.
</P>
<P>
   So what is The Look?
</P>
<P>
   It's an absolutely committed and relaxed, full-body
communication that says to your child, ``I mean business.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoulders facing front, body bent toward the child, hands behind
back, steady gaze and eyes locked on their face. ``And absolutely,
positively no hint of a smile,'' adds Medvescek, a mother of three.
</P>
<P>
   It's not important what you're really thinking. What's important
is that on the outside, you are not amused, you are not angry and
you are not distracted.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit, it works amazingly well. I'd never noticed how
rarely I even had eye contact with my children while I was trying
to communicate a serious consequence to them, or how often I was
trying to do chores or something else at the same time I was
reading them the riot act.
</P>
<P>
   To kids, distraction means they have gained the advantage. After
all, you'll be on to something else in a few seconds ... and so
will they.
</P>
<P>
   But The Look doesn't go away until there is compliance.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing makes kids more uncomfortable than an extended Look.
They want to make it go away, and the quickest and easiest way to
do that is obedience. Right then.
</P>
<P>
   Time outs, being sent to their room, getting so mad you have to
leave the room, even spankings, are easier than tolerating The Look
for a few minutes. From The Look, escape is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   And no one's talking about a seething glare, or a contemptuous
sneer. It's the very neutral nature of The Look that makes it so
effective.
</P>
<P>
   You may need to call their name _ again, in a neutral tone _ to
give them The Look. Your child may say, ``What? What are you
looking at?'' or ``NOOOO, it's not fair; it's not my turn.'' This
is an attempt to engage you in conversation. Don't give in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' says Medvescek, ``I imagine that I am a scientist
observing a life form in a laboratory. `How interesting,' I think.
`Notice how the species attempts to escape an uncomfortable
situation by making high-pitched sounds.'''
</P>
<P>
   Just stand there and do nothing. You may need to reiterate your
request. But make sure The Look doesn't waver.
</P>
<P>
   I once saw my 92-year-old grandmother give my 66-year-old mother
The Look.
</P>
<P>
   It still worked.
</P>
<P>
   So you can add that to the many advantages of developing The
Look: Apparently, there aren't any age limits, and once you've got
it, you never lose it.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
