u a BC-NC-TIRE-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      09-15 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-TIRE-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT REACHED TO END NEARLY YEARLONG STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For five days short of a full year, 1,450 workers at the
Continental General Tire factory in Charlotte, N.C., have been on
strike in what has been one of the largest and longest strikes ever
in a state known for being unfriendly to unions.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, the union, the United Steelworkers of America,
announced a tentative contract, and many workers were rejoicing
that after a painful year they had achieved their bargaining goals.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed six-year contract, the workers' pensions,
which have been far lower than those at other unionized tire
plants, will climb to the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely happy,'' said Linda Hatchell, who helps insert
steel belts into the tires. ``The main thing in my view is we
finally earned the company's respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The walkout, which began last Sept. 20, was unusual not only in
its length but in how the strikers hung together _ just 15 union
members crossed the picket line during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get by these last 12 months, people were living off of
their savings,'' said Mark Cieslikowski, a quality assurance
technician and a member of the union's nine-person bargaining team.
``There were people who took second and third jobs. Some had other
income from their wives. It ran the whole gamut, but we made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hatchell, for instance, worked at a video casino earning the
minimum wage of $5.15 an hour, far less than the $17.50-an-hour
average at the tire plant, one of Charlotte's largest employers.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Hollnagel, a company spokesman, said he could not comment,
other than to say, ``We are happy with the settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Tensions escalated last fall when Continental hired hundreds of
permanent replacement workers, and strikers stood outside the
factory, calling them scabs. All told, 900 replacement workers were
used, with the company saying that production was 60 percent of the
33,000 tires a day produced before the strike. The union insisted
that production was far lower and that the decreased output
pressured Continental to settle.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company threatened to keep all the replacement
workers and not let all the strikers back, the agreement calls for
rehiring within six months all strikers who want to return. Until
they are recalled, workers are to receive 80 percent of their
regular pay. The workers are to vote on the agreement this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers said the strike was caused by bad blood stemming
from the 1995 contract, in which the union had agreed to
concessions aimed at lifting the plant out of a prolonged slump.
The concessions included a wage freeze and acceptance of pensions
and cost-of-living increases below the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say management promised to raise the workers
back to the industry average once the plant became profitable. But
Continental workers said they felt compelled to strike when the
company, now profitable again, balked at raising their pensions and
cost-of-living adjustments to the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things we gave away in 1995, they wouldn't give us back,''
said Cieslikowski. ``We were expecting certain positive things to
happen when they started making a profit. We started asking,
`Where's our share?' and, lo and behold, it wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   The union took numerous steps to pressure Continental, a German
company which is the world's fourth-largest tire maker. It
organized protests at German consulates and persuaded workers at a
Continental plant in South Africa to stage a two-hour sympathy
strike. It hired a financial consultant to write a report saying
that Continental was making a financial mistake to let the strike
continue.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the steelworkers got churches and other unions to
contribute food to tide the workers over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solidarity of this membership made this contract happen,
and it was well worth the fight,'' said Robert Griffin, an
electrician at the plant.
</P>
</TEXT>
