<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-VETO-0916-COX     09-15 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VETO-0916-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, RETURNING THURSDAY, IS SET TO VETO GOP TAX AND SPENDING
PLANS
 &HT;    700&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    EDS: Clinton is en route back to Washington and scheduled to
land at 1 a.m. ET Thursday morning.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Back in the White House Thursday after a weeklong
Pacific swing, President Clinton is braced for an all-out partisan
fight over the heart and soul of national politics: federal taxes
and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was expected to veto the whopping $792 billion
Republican tax cut legislation as early as Thursday, effectively
killing prospects for the plan that was sent to the White House by
Congress on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That could be only the beginning. Clinton has threatened to
wield his veto power another half dozen times over the next two
weeks, after drawing a line in the sand over the Republican's
proposed tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is dead on arrival at the White House,'' Vice President
Al Gore said Wednesday on Capitol Hill. ``It is not going anywhere.
It's going to be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hurricane Floyd menacing the East Coast, Gore said the
Republican tax cut ``would be kind of like an economic hurricane
wreaking havoc on America's economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were quick to cast the White House as the champion
of big government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, maybe this is a difference in philosophy,''
said House Majority Leader Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. ''Maybe we do
believe that the American people should have some control over the
money they make...(or) bureaucrats will spend your money for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The next battleground is spending. Clinton's senior aides have
already threatened to veto more than half of the 13 appropriations
bills Congress must send to the president's desk by Oct. 1, the
start of the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriations bills govern about one third of all federal
spending. The rest is so-called mandatory spending for such
purposes as the federal insurance programs Social Security,
Medicare and Medicaid and transportation funding guided by revenues
earmarked for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Gridlock between the White House and Congress over
appropriations bills forced a temporary shutdown in the federal
government in 1995. Legislators and administration officials both
claim they want to avoid a repeat in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tough negotiations lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his foes on Capitol Hill are tens of billions of
dollars apart over how to spend the proposed $1.8 trillion budget
for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to work with them,'' said Gore. ``We extend the
hand of bipartisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other hand, though, is the veto pen, which Clinton has
vowed to use.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the White House has argued that spending
proposals by the Republican-controlled Congress badly underfund a
broad range of Clinton's initiatives, from hiring additional police
and storing nuclear weapons fuel to supporting Mideast peace
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans counter that Clinton's spending proposals would
break bipartisan budget agreements and eat into the projected
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the economy continues to grow at slightly more than 2
percent a year, the federal government is projected to take in $3
trillion more than it spends over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of that surplus would come from payments into the
Social Security worker retirement insurance program. Both Democrats
and Republicans have proposed plans they say would dedicate that
money to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is over the remaining $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Congress passed a bill that would give
$792 billion back to taxpayers _ through an across-the-board 10
percent cut in income taxes; tax credits for education savings
plans; wiping out the so-called ``marriage penalty'' by increasing
income tax deductions for couples, and other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed a much smaller_ $250 billion over ten years
_ tax cut, targeting lower-income workers and families. He would
use the bulk of the rest to expand a broad range of domestic and
international programs, to shore up Medicare, the federal health
insurance program, and to provide prescription drug subsidies for
low income households.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond dollars and cents, there are high political stakes.
Democrats and Republicans are using the tax and spending debate to
frame their positions in advance of the 2000 presidential and
congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans portrayed their proposed tax cut as emblematic of
their party principles. When it comes to government spending, they
say, less is more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget surplus doesn't belong to the federal government.
It belongs to the American workers who earned that money with their
sweat and ingenuity,'' House Republican Conference Chairman J.C.
Watts, Jr., R-Okla., said in a prepared statement. ``This is their
money. They deserve to have it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed a much smaller tax cut of $250 billion over
ten years. It would target lower-income workers and families.
</P>
<P>
   He has said, though, that the Republican plan would starve
needed programs while putting a balanced budget at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats rallied around Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to say unequivocally we will support the
president's plan to veto the Republican tax cut because it's the
right thing to do today, tomorrow, any time a tax cut like that is
proposed,'' Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told
reporters Wednesday at a Capitol Hill news conference. ``We're
asking our Republican colleagues to work with us to pass a
responsible budget that moves this country forward, not backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, though, White House officials were girding for a long
and drawn out partisan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a running battle that we've had since Day One of this
administration,'' a White House official said privately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is are we going to stay on the course of fiscal
responsibility and prudent investment in the American people...or
abandon it for a reckless tax cut and harsh cuts in education and
other critical priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
