<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-NEWENGLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLANDERS, WITH AN EYE TO THE SOUTH, PREPARE FOR FLOYD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As Hurricane Floyd tormented the Carolinas, New
England braced for its stubborn fury Wednesday, preparing for
punishing rains and the winds of a still-dangerous storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this thing glides a little to the east, it could zoom up
Buzzards Bay as a Category 2 hurricane,'' said Peter Judge, a
spokesman for the Massachusetts Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``From one end of the state to the other, something awful could
come out of this thing,'' he said. ``Hopefully, it won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Regional weather forecasters said Floyd's punch, once it reaches
this region, could range from tropical-storm wind gusts of up to 70
miles per hour, to a Category 2 hurricane with winds of at least 96
miles per hour, if the storm hugs the East Coast and regains
strength.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's center is expected to arrive here late Thursday or
early Friday. Late Wednesday the National Weather Service issued a
tropical storm watch from Plymouth southward.
</P>
<P>
   The meteorological menace _ still hundreds of miles away _
forced fishermen in Chatham to move their boats to protected waters
and prompted coastal homeowners to place tentative orders with
local lumber suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a large supply of plywood and waferboard that is
standing by in case things break bad,'' said Jim Kalife, manager of
Fairhaven Lumber near Buzzards Bay. ``No one is panicking, but they
want to know if we'll have 10 to 15 sheets available for them and
we're reassuring them that they don't have to grab it too early.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm's unpredictable path gave authorities no choice but to
activate emergency operations centers. Even under the rosiest of
scenarios, they said, Massachusetts will endure high winds, heavy
rains and possible flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heading toward New England. We will have the effects of
Floyd _ that's a certainty,'' said Glenn Field of the National
Weather Service. ``The only question is how strong the winds will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   From northwest Connecticut to Nantucket, Field said, emergency
officials are being told to get ready for a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of emphasis on Georgia and South
Carolina,'' the weather service's warning coordination
meteorologist said. ``But it's possible that it will just make a
grazing landfall in South Carolina and we would be the second stop.
It's not the Hurricane of '38 by any stretch of the imagination,
but a hurricane is a possibility here.''
</P>
<P>
   The September 1938 storm, one of the century's most violent,
killed 600 people and caused massive damage throughout New England.
</P>
<P>
   The USS Constitution was secured in its berth in the Charlestown
Navy Yard, and at The Country Club in Brookline, where the Ryder
Cup matches begin next week, workers secured about 70 tents that
have been erected near the golf course for corporations that have
payed up to $350,000 to host parties for major customers and
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been strapping them down, and we've taken some extra
precautions to make sure that nothing is damaged,'' said Barton G.
Weiss, president of the company constructing the tents. ``We're
very confident. These are not tents in the normal sense of the
word, they are really more like structures. They are pretty solidly
grounded, with good foundations.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardware stores and harbormasters reported moderate business
Wednesday as home and boat owners for the most part adopted a
wait-and-see approach to a storm that threatened coastal Florida
before veering north toward the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   By early Wednesday afternoon, Floyd's fury was unmistakable as
far north as Cape Cod. Swimmers and small water craft were warned
away from the ocean waters. And forecasters watched to see whether
Floyd tracked inland or glanced off the Outer Banks of North
Carolina and took aim at New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it just skirts the Outer Banks, it's not going to lose a
lot of punch,'' Field said, who pegged Floyd's arrival here for
very late Thursday or early Friday morning. ``If the storm moves
over eastern North Carolina and then back out to sea toward New
England, we could be looking at a Category 1 Hurricane and it's not
out of the question that we could have a weak Category 2 hurricane
on our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Field said the last Category 2 hurricane to strike this region
was Hurricane Bob in August 1991, which killed 18 people and caused
$1.5 billion in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's rainfall is expected to average at least 3 to 5
inches across the region with some pockets of heavier rains
measuring 6 inches or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with an inland track, we're going to get a lot of
flooding rain and winds gusts up around possibly hurricane force,''
Field said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gregg Krupa of the Globe Staff and Globe Correspondent Hollis
Engley contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
