<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM PAPERBACK ROMANCES TO BEST-SELLING NOVELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the focus and chatter in book publishing have been on the
Harry Potter phenomenon, another great success story has been
quietly burgeoning. A small group of women who started out writing
paperback category romances have emerged as the true power in
hard-cover escapist fiction.
</P>
<P>
   These women went from writing romances to romantic suspense
novels to pure suspense with just a touch of romance. In the
process they leaped right over the glitz and sex of the likes of
Judith Krantz and Jackie Collins, and book by book are taking over
the best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Sandra Brown, Iris Johansen, Nora Roberts, Tami
Hoag, Tess Gerritsen, Catherine Coulter and Barbara Delinsky. All
of them have been able to summon their faithful romance-novel
readers to better, more complex books as they themselves have grown
as writers. Most of their writing is now character-driven fiction
that is tough-minded, often violent and does not cater to the
insensate. All are prolific; by year's end, Ms. Roberts, for
instance, will have published 133 novels. They typically have large
backlists going back to their romance-novel days, which makes them
endlessly profitable for their publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Nita Taublib, deputy publisher of Bantam Dell, who edits Ms.
Johansen, said that ``each of her books grows by leaps and bounds''
in its quality and complexity. The same is generally true of her
competitors. Equally interesting, as these women became more
sophisticated writers, their fans became more demanding readers, so
while some readers dropped by the wayside as the authors moved
forward, most followed and remained fans.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taublib says that their current work is not so different
from that of such best-selling novelists as Patricia Cornwall or
Mary Higgins Clark, although their careers indeed are, since Ms.
Cornwall and Ms. Clark started at the top of the publishing ladder
with intricate hardcover thrillers, not paperback romances.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, practically every type of writing is more complex
than the romance category, which has a rudimentary formula: woman
and man meet, fall in love, have problem, overcome problem, live
together happily ever after _ angst and ecstasy in no more than
60,000 words, or about 200 mass paperback pages.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown, who has written 60 novels, 38 of them best-sellers,
said that ``after about 45 romances I had reached a plateau, and I
wanted to move on,'' adding that from the start her goal ``was to
write more mainstream books.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of my books now as suspense novels, usually with a
love story incorporated,'' she said. ``They're absolutely a lot
harder to write than romances; they take more plotting and real
character development. Each book is a stretch for me, and I try
something interesting each time that males will like as well as
women.'' Ms. Brown's latest novel, ``The Alibi'' (Warner Books),
will be No. 4 on the New York Times hardcover fiction best-seller
list on Sept. 26 (this weekend it's No. 1, a first for any of her
books, but for Sept. 26 the three Harry Potter books top it) and
last year's hardcover, ``Unspeakable,'' will be No. 6 on the Sept.
26 paperback list. About 455,000 copies of ``The Alibi'' have
already been shipped to bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johansen describes her career of writing best sellers as a
natural progression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love romance, happy endings and all, but as I continued to
write I wanted to grow,'' she said. ``My plots became more and more
complicated. There's lots of romance in my suspense stories, but
the emphasis is on suspense, not romance.''
</P>
<P>
   Her latest novel, ``The Killing Game'' (Bantam Books), will be
her first to make the hardcover best-seller list of The Times; it
will be No. 11 on Sept. 26. It features Eve Duncan, a forensic
sculptor, who will pop up now and again in her future novels,
though not in all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to make all my books very strongly character-driven,''
she said. ``They have complicated plots, but my purpose is to make
the reader really feel for the characters. I would say the majority
of my readers are women, but the last few books drew letters from
quite a few men too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johansen started writing what she called ``single title
historicals,'' for Bantam's Loveswept line of short romances, which
included a trilogy about a family and a statue that started in the
Renaissance and continued during the French Revolution and then in
contemporary times. ``I was not aware at the time that I was headed
that way, but the story happened to go in that direction, toward
the contemporary'' and this, she said, started her thinking in a
new direction.
</P>
<P>
   So she started writing more complex mass market paperbacks. In
1996 she published her first hardcover, ``The Ugly Duckling''
(Bantam), which included murder, plastic surgery, international
intrigue and revenge _ all the romance delectables woven into a
thriller.
</P>
<P>
   However one feels about the suspense novels with a jot of
romance that these women produce, these writers are the real
engines driving the book world. Each writes with great frequency;
all have a large backlist that is republished and repackaged over
and over, and often millions of fans. And it's the fans who make
them, since these authors' books are seldom reviewed and their
success comes from word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   One could suppose, from their work, that these women had
something else in common: That they were first and foremost readers
who then became writers. And perhaps that's what's most interesting
about them. It's rather like a weekend hacker molding herself into
a tennis pro and winning Wimbledon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
