<HEADLINE>
IODINE RADIATION ANTIDOTE AT CENTER OF N-POWER CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It's just a little pill, taken after a nuclear
accident to prevent a common type of radiation poisoning. But the
very existence of potassium iodide has caused big controversy in
the long war over nuclear power, symbolizing the worst thing that
could happen at a reactor.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday a Massachusetts panel on radiation issues will consider
whether to stockpile potassium iodide pills in schools, hospitals
and other buildings near the Seabrook, Pilgrim and Vermont Yankee
nuclear plants to be handed out to the public in the event of a
significant radiation release.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear industry officials oppose distributing the pills, saying
they distract from what people should really do during a major
accident: leave.
</P>
<P>
   But nuclear critics say the industry is mainly afraid of the
public relations black eye they could get from closets of potassium
iodide at schools or on drugstore shelves. The pills, they argue,
saved children's lives during the Chernobyl accident in 1986,
prompting European nations to stock up years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nuclear industry doesn't want'' potassium iodide pills.
``It reminds people that accidents can happen,'' said Peter Crane,
a Nuclear Regulatory Commission lawyer who, on his own time, has
led the fight for the pills for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   However, after years of bureaucratic stalemate, the tide seems
to be turning in Crane's favor. Last summer, New Hampshire
officials decided to make potassium iodide available at drugstores
near Seabrook, and Maine called for storing the pills near Maine
Yankee nuclear plant in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Department of Public Health has long declined
to keep public stockpiles of potassium iodide, but officials said
Wednesday they could change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still open. I want to hear all of the materials
available,'' said Robert Hallisey, director of the department's
Radiation Protection Program.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing before the Governor's Advisory Council on Radiation
Protection is part of a national reexamination of a nuclear safety
issue that dates to the 1979 accident at the Three Mile Island
nuclear plant in Pennsylvania. Then, federal officials looked in
vain for potassium iodide pills to hand out, finally convincing a
company to manufacture a batch.
</P>
<P>
   Potassium iodide is no cure-all, but, if swallowed soon after
radiation exposure, it prevents radioactive iodine from
concentrating in the thyroid glands, a part of the body where
growing children are highly vulnerable. The Polish government
distributed millions of the pills during the Chernobyl accident in
neighboring Russia, which researchers say helped lower the rate of
thyroid cancers for years afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The usefulness of potassium iodide ``is the major public health
lesson learned from Chernobyl and everybody knows it,'' said NRC's
Crane, who will testify at the hearing. ``And yet the NRC did not
change policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear industry officials counter that potassium iodide has a
relatively short shelf life before it needs to be replaced, and a
small percentage of people have an allergic reaction to the pills.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, argues David Tarantino, spokesman for Pilgrim
nuclear power plant in Plymouth, the pills may give people a false
sense of security during an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``While potassium iodide is effective in terms of the thyroid,
it doesn't do anything for overall radiation exposure and there is
some concern that people might think it was some kind of a silver
bullet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, NRC officials argued that potassium iodide
wasn't worth the cost, and that the money would be better spent on
improving emergency evacuation plans. The Massachusetts Department
of Public Health agreed, setting aside pills only for emergency
workers and people who can't be moved easily.
</P>
<P>
   But NRC commissioners, responding to an appeal from Crane, had a
change of heart in 1998. Noting that the pills had helped reduce
illness after Chernobyl, the NRC called on states to consider a
public supply and even offered to foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Massachusetts Department of Public Health officials
rejected the NRC offer, but that drew sharp criticism from
anti-nuclear activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are deep concerns within the environmental and public
health communities that the Department of Public Health is way too
cozy with . . . the operators of Pilgrim. Their footdragging on
this is further evidence,'' said Rob Sargent of the Massachusetts
Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   In response, DPH asked the Advisory Council on Radiation
Protection to reconsider the issue and pledged to follow its
advice. ``We'd be awful foolish not to listen to their advice after
we asked for it,'' said the state's Hallisey.
</P>
<P>
   Activists say they will get a chance to knock down old industry
arguments against the pills, showing that they are cheap and potent
for 10 years in storage, and no more dangerous than cough syrup
containing potassium iodide.
</P>
<P>
   If the council sides with them, DPH will then determine how best
to distribute the pills in Massachusetts communities within 10
miles of Pilgrim, Seabrook in New Hampshire and Vermont Yankee. The
plan could include both stockpiles as well as store availability
for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrim's Tarantino said plant officials ultimately could adapt
to a requirement to provide potassium iodide pills, although they
wouldn't like it. ``From a public relations standpoint, it would
probably be another item where people would see concern'' about the
safety of nuclear power, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
