<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LYNYRD-SKYNYRD-NYTR &LR;      09-15 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNYRD-SKYNYRD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYNYRD SKYNYRD CARRIES ON, BUT FORGETTING IS IMPOSSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL DeYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 20 years after the fuse was snuffed on Lynyrd
Skynyrd's skyrocketing career, the band has revived, rebuilt,
recommitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be foolish to let it pass us by, if you think about
it,'' says Leon Wilkeson, who has played bass in Lynyrd Skynyrd
since 1971. ``How blessed we are, given second and third chances.
How many groups do you know of that are given blessings like
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Begun in Jacksonville, Fla., by boyhood pals Ronnie Van Zant,
Gary Rossington and Allen Collins, Lynyrd Skynyrd created a pungent
distillation of good-old-boy Southern Rock and bratty,
take-no-prisoners songcraft: At its best, the band was like a
bastard child of the Allman Brothers and the Rolling Stones. It
rocked, but it sure wasn't dumb. No way.
</P>
<P>
   When their chartered plane ran out of gas and crashed into a
Mississippi swamp on Oct. 20, 1977, Lynyrd Skynyrd was crushed,
seemingly beyond repair: Van Zant, the group's leader, frontman and
main creative force, was killed, along with guitarist Steve Gaines
and backup singer Cassie Gaines, Steve's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkeson, Rossington (lead guitar) and Billy Powell (keyboards)
survived the crash _ just barely. Allen Collins died of pneumonia
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just extremely lucky, and we've seriously, honestly
tried to have kept the best attitude that we should have, every
time we hit that stage,'' Wilkeson says. ``I think we can honestly
say we try and play each show like it's the last.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every thing that I do great, he's responsible for,'' Wilkeson
explains, referring to Van Zant. ``And I feel like I can say that
on behalf of the rest of the members who worked with him. He was an
inspiration for everyone around him.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Rhode Island, Leon Wilkeson was working at an ice
cream plant in Jacksonville when he met Donnie Van Zant, one of
Ronnie's younger brothers. Wilkeson auditioned for, and got, a gig
in Van Zant's band the Collegiates, which would later become .38
Special and score a few hits of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Van Zant's band was called My Backyard, then The One
Percent, then Leonard Skinner, after the high school gym teacher
who got Rossington expelled because of his long hair. Finally, for
no reason other than it looked cool on paper, Lynyrd Skynyrd.
</P>
<P>
   Skynyrd signed with MCA Records in 1973. Leon Wilkeson was on
bass from the first session onward, and as the records got better,
the band's reputation grew: ``Free Bird,'' ``Gimme Three Steps,''
``Was I Right or Wrong,'' ``Sweet Home Alabama,'' ``Simple Man,''
``What's Your Name.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossington, Collins and Van Zant wrote the music _ but the
words, those belonged solely to Ronnie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the gift,'' Wilkeson says. ``Absolutely. One of the
strangest things about him in that area was that he never wrote
down lyrics. As strange as that may seem. When asked, he said he
figured if it had to be written down, it wasn't worth keeping. It's
shuddering to think about all the ideas he let slip into the
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Right out of the gate, they were treated like rock stars,
opening the Who's massive ``Quadrophenia'' tour in the winter of
'73.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a blast, absolutely,'' Wilkeson says. ``One of the best
parts about touring with the Who was that they were just so polite
and gracious to us. Ronnie got the inspiration then that every
opening act that ever performed for us, from then on, we gave them
everything they wanted and treated them the same way the Who did
us. Because we appreciated how important that was, how helpful and
everything. The Who really took care of us and treated us right.''
</P>
<P>
   The band opened a European tour for the Stones, and by '77 was a
major headlining act. The sixth Lynyrd Skynyrd album, ``Street
Survivors,'' had been out less than a week when the plane went
down.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 20 people who survived the crash, Wilkeson was the most
severely injured, suffering a broken jaw, a crushed chest and
massive internal bleeding. He was dead on arrival at the hospital,
and was revived twice on the operating table.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of physical and spiritual healing that we all
had to go through.'' he says. ``It took a long time to figure out
what to do. We all got together and kind of agreed to lay the name
to rest, out of consideration of the band members that passed away
in the crash.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, most of the musicians came together as the
Rossington-Collins Band, and when Rossington left to start a new
group with his wife, they made an album as the Allen Collins Band.
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the 10th anniversary of the accident, the band
launched The Lynyrd Skynyrd Tribute Tour in 1987. Johnny Van Zant,
brother of Ronnie and Donnie, was in the lead singer's slot, and he
still occupies that space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through kind of an eerie period when we started the
Tribute Tour,'' says Wilkeson. ``There were kind of eerie and
pleasant spiritual moments where the presence of Ronnie was always
felt onstage ... and Steve, and Allen, and Cassie. It's a
must-needed feeling for me, personally, that I welcome and like to
have. On account of the loss and how about I miss them since that
happened and all.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's Lynyrd Skynyrd makes an album every couple of years _
1994's ``Endangered Species'' was a critically lauded acoustic set
_ and tours to enthusiastic crowds. Currently, the band includes
Rick Medlocke, the founder of Blackfoot, Outlaws co-founder Hughie
Thomasson and drummer Michael Cartellone.
</P>
<P>
   The music is still fine, and the band still rocks. And even
though a lot of sand has fallen through the hourglass, no one
forgets the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, something that tragic and painful never
completely goes away,'' Wileson says. ``It's all in the way that
you handle your personal thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life goes on _ to everything, there is a season, turn turn
turn. Time to be sad, time to be glad.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
