<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3468 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     09-15 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS, LIKE REPUBLICANS, SHOULD BE WARY OF A BUCHANAN BID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 19)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some Democrats may be jubilant at the possibility
of Patrick Buchanan seeking the presidency on the Reform Party
ticket and presumably siphoning votes away from the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative commentator's call for a return to the old
fundamentalist policies of strong nationalism and protectionism,
coupled with an adamant stand against abortion and immigration, is
one that presumably could wean other conservatives away from a
centrist candidate such as George W. Bush, John McCain or Elizabeth
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   America would face disaster if it were to follow his xenophobic
policies and retreat to the isolationism and high tariffs of
yesteryear. But his message could have a powerful influence on
voters, especially blue-collar workers and union members who
normally vote Democratic but feel left behind as the great global
express has soared to record economic heights.
</P>
<P>
   Before Democrats get carried away with euphoria, therefore, they
should study the political history of the 20th century and the
impact that third parties have had on presidential elections. A
split in one party's ranks does not always spell disaster for that
party's presidential aspirant.
</P>
<P>
   The four most memorable elections in which third-party
candidates played significant roles were those of 1912, 1948, 1968
and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In 1912 Theodore Roosevelt, a former Republican president and
the most popular political figure of his time, bolted the GOP when
he was denied its nomination and ran as the Progressive Party
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   His action split the GOP wide open. William Howard Taft, the
affable Republican incumbent, was badly beaten in his quest for a
second term, and Woodrow Wilson, the progressive Democratic
governor of New Jersey, was elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson won nearly 42 percent of the popular vote, Roosevelt 27
percent, Taft 23 percent and Socialist Eugene Debs 6 percent
</P>
<P>
   That is the kind of scenario Democrats would like to see
replayed with Buchanan in the Roosevelt role and Bush as a
latter-day Taft. Democrats can envision their own nominee, whether
he's Al Gore or Bill Bradley, walking away with the election while
Buchanan and Bush split the Republican vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1948 campaign, with two major defections from the
Democrats, ended quite differently.
</P>
<P>
   The embattled presidential candidate was incumbent Harry Truman,
who was considered a sure loser by political leaders and the news
media. New York Gov. Thomas E. Dewey, as the GOP standard bearer,
was seen as a sure winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats faced two problems that seemed insurmountable. One
was Henry A. Wallace and the other was Strom Thurmond.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who had been jettisoned as vice president in 1944 and
replaced by Truman as Franklin D. Roosevelt's running mate, became
the presidential candidate of the Progressive Party. A caustic
critic of Truman's tough policy of communist containment, Wallace
appeared certain to win the votes of liberals who were disenchanted
with the president and wanted better relations with Moscow. Wallace
was endorsed by the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the philosophical spectrum, Strom Thurmond,
then the 45-year-old Democratic governor of South Carolina, ran as
the nominee of the States' Rights Democrats, known colloquially as
the Dixiecrats. He did well with anti-civil rights voters in
southern states and, in fact, carried Alabama, Louisiana,
Mississippi and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But the defections of Wallace and Thurmond may have helped
rather than hurt Truman. First, the Wallace campaign bolstered
Truman's image as a stalwart opponent of Soviet expansionism and
mitigated Republican assertions that the president was soft on
communism.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the Thurmond campaign, which followed a walkout of 35
southern delegates from the Democratic National Convention after it
adopted a strong civil rights plank, helped Truman win the votes of
African Americans and northern white liberals.
</P>
<P>
   The end result was that on Election Day Truman won, and the
Democratic Party picked up 75 seats in the House and nine in the
Senate, regaining control of both houses. Wallace got almost as
many votes as Thurmond, but they were spread around the country
rather than being concentrated in one region. He did not carry a
single state but probably prevented Truman from winning New York.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968 George Wallace, the anti-integrationist Democratic
governor of Alabama, stirred things up with a campaign that
appealed not just to segregationist southerners but to white
workers, most of whom were Democrats disenchanted with their party
and angry over student uprisings against America's stance in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace had a field day attacking ``pointy-headed liberals'' and
the political establishment. His appeal was such that in some areas
organized labor leaders had to twist arms to prevent members from
voting for Wallace rather than the Democratic nominee, Vice
President Hubert Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP standard-bearer, Richard Nixon, meanwhile had adopted a
``southern strategy'' aimed at winning votes in the traditionally
Democratic south. As his running mate, Nixon chose Maryland Gov.
Spiro Agnew, whose only claim to fame was his rigid law-and-order
stance against black demonstrators following the death of civil
rights leader Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 73 million popular ballots cast that year, Nixon beat
Humphrey by a mere 510,000 votes. But Wallace mustered nearly 10
million votes and took five southern states as the American
Independent Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey believed he might have won without Wallace as the third
party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 Ross Perot, the dynamic Texas billionaire, made his
political debut and won more than 19 million votes, compared with
43 million for Bill Clinton and 38 million for George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Perot's candidacy may have tipped the political scales in favor
of Clinton because his stands on trade and other issues, like those
of Buchanan, appealed to the Republican right wing.
</P>
<P>
   If Buchanan wins his uphill fight to head the Reform Party
ticket, he will greatly increase the drama of the campaign. He also
may influence the final outcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
