<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top executive to head both TNT, TBS
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting is consolidating control of its
popular TBS and TNT channels under one top executive as part of a
strategy to make them distinct from each other.
</P>
<P>
   Overseeing both channels will be Bradley J. Siegel, a veteran
programmer who is now president of TNT and Turner Classic Movies.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel will take on the new title of president of general
entertainment networks. As such he will serve as part of a team
including Turner Broadcasting President Steven Heyer and Chairman
Terence F. McGuirk to reposition TBS.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel's new job is important because TBS and TNT are in an
elite group of cable channels that are almost universally available
in every cable household. TBS is available in 78 million homes and
TNT in 76 million.
</P>
<P>
   All entertainment channels, other than the animated ones, will
now report to Siegel. Betty Cohen, president of Cartoon Network
Worldwide, keeps control of the animated channels. Her
responsibilities include Cartoon Network, Boomerang and a new
animation studio under construction in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``TBS Superstation and Turner South (a brand-new channel being
launched in October) are well-positioned for Brad to craft the
strong identities that he has for TNT and Turner Classic Movies,''
said Heyer.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel's promotion comes one day after TBS President William
Burke was promoted to the job of building parent company Time
Warner's news and information presence on the Internet. In this
job, Burke will work out of Turner Broadcasting's Techwood campus
and hold the title of chief executive of news and information for
Time Warner Digital Media.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past two years, we have been working to develop a
separate programming approach with each channel,'' says McGuirk.
``The repositioning of these networks is still in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel will push that process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past several years, the two have become similar,''
says Siegel. ``We both carry the NBA, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   TNT's position is clear, says Siegel, but TBS' image has become
muddied with expansion. It will be part of his job during the next
couple of months to chart a new course for TBS. He doesn't know yet
what that course will be. The station currently carries old movies,
reruns and a mix of sporting events, including the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``One person is needed to make the decision about what program
goes on each channel,'' says Siegel. He will be that person.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel stressed that his admittedly shallow critique of TBS is
not a criticism of Burke, a friend and ally. ``Bill did a great job
reviving the channel.'' Under Burke's reign TBS improved ratings
and viewership.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel joined Turner Broadcasting in 1993 as executive vice
president of TNT. He was promoted to president of the channel, with
responsibility added for Turner Classic Movies about a year later.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, TNT has changed its content and marketing.
Launched primarily as a movie channel, relying heavily on the
company's MGM library, TNT now features a much broader and more
contemporary selection of shows.
</P>
<P>
   The old movies were moved to Turner Classic Movies, and TNT now
showcases newer films, such as ``Austin Powers,'' ``Top Gun'' and
``L.A. Confidential.'' It also features reruns of top network shows
such as ``E.R.,'' ``Law and Order'' and ``In the Heat of the
Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Siegel has broadened TNT's programming to include
sporting and music events.
</P>
<P>
   Today, TNT often leads the industry in viewership among adults
during prime time on cable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
