 Wednesday, Sept. 15, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service has filed the following for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis
or Susie McBee at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
 (EDS: Adds HURRICANE-CAROLINES, HURRICANE-FLORIDA, JASPER-TRIAL,
BBN-ASTROS-FBN-COWBOYS, TRANSLATION-ERROR and CISNEROS-WITNESS.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-CAROLINAS (Charleston, S.C.) _ Florida lucks out as
storm skirts the coast, but Carolinas are scrambling for their
brush with Hurricane Floyd, which is only slightly weakening but
veering northeast, a good sign. Latest estimate is Wilmington,
N.C., area for most likely landfall Thursday morning. By TONY
FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-FLORIDA (Melbourne, Fla.) _ After the largest
evacuation in the state's history and much scrambling to prepare
for ``the big one'' Florida residents, including NASA and Disney,
awakened to a few downed trees and power outages Wednesday. By
TERRY KLIEWER.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Bryan, Texas) _ Prosecutors said they will
introduce DNA evidence today to tie a second white supremacist to
the slaying of a black East Texas man, dragged to his death and
dismembered while chained to a pickup truck last year. By PATTY
REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-LEADERS (New York) _ High-level Venezuelan leaders are
on a four-day mission in the United States to convince the American
people that their oil-rich nation of 23 million is getting its act
together and emerging from months of political strife. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   TRANSLATION-ERROR (San Antonio) _ A translator's error has
created a major headache for election officials across Texas, and
it could cost Bexar County taxpayers $91,000 to fix. The problem
stems from an incorrect Spanish translation of Proposition 15,
which is a constitutional amendment ``permitting spouses to agree
to convert separate property to community property.'' The original
translation in Spanish, which appears on Texas ballots, permits
spouses ``to agree to convert separate property to the community.''
By TOM BOWER and CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENCY-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Visably angry at the White
House's refusal to tell Congress why President Clinton granted
clemency to 12 Puerto Rican militants, Senate Judiciary Committee
Chairman Orrin Hatch vows to subpoena administration officials to
testify on the controversy. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTO-RICO-BOMBING (Washington) _ Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro
Rossello enlisted in the New York Senate campaign of First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton Wednesday, a move that may bolster Puerto
Rico's bid to evict the U.S. Navy from a target range on the island
of Vieques. Rossello also won a commitment from Senate Energy
Committee Chairman Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, to introduce
legislation to transfer Navy-owned land on Vieques to the
government of Puerto Rico. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-WITNESS (Washington) _ Linda Jones, the government's
chief witness in the conspiracy case against former Housing
Secretary Henry Cisneros, could be released from federal custody as
early as this week, a prosecutor for Independent Counsel David
Barrett told a federal judge Wednesday. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
