<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-QUACKENBUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUBERT G. QUACKENBUSH, AT 77; WAS ALL-STAR BRUINS DEFENSEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA MASSEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hubert George ``Bill'' Quackenbush, a former Boston Bruins
defenseman and Hall of Famer who once went 132 consecutive games
without a penalty, died Sunday in Pennsylvania from complications
of Alzheimer's disease. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Toronto, Mr. Quackenbush entered the minor leagues
shortly after graduating from Western Tech High School in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Detroit Red Wings in 1942, where he played for six
years before signing on with the Boston Bruins in 1949. He played
seven seasons with the Bruins, retiring in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   During his 13 years with the National Hockey League, Mr.
Quackenbush was named five times to All-Star teams _ to the first
team in 1948, 1949, and 1951, and to the second team in 1947 and
1953.
</P>
<P>
   In 774 NHL games, he collected a mere 95 minutes in penalties,
and during 1947-1949 he played 132 consecutive games without a
penalty, making him the least penalized defenseman in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he played so many years at an all-star level
with so few penalties says a lot about him,'' Mr. Quackenbush's son
Bruce said Wednesday. ``His style of play was unique, and he showed
that you could be successful without spending half the game in the
penalty box. That's hard to find in hockey these days.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1949 Mr. Quackenbush was awarded the Lady Byng Trophy, an
annual award given to the NHL player who best combines
``sportsmanship and gentlemanly conduct with a high standard of
playing ability.'' He was the first defenseman, and one of only two
in history, to win the Lady Byng.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 he was inducted into the NHL Hall of Fame, hailed as
``one of the most effective rushing defensemen in the game as well
as an excellant checker. Not a thumping hitter, his main attribute
was an ability to break up the rush without pounding an opponent
into the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the NHL, Mr. Quackenbush received an associate
degree in engineering from Northeastern University in 1962. He then
worked as a marketing representative for several civil engineering
firms in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967 he began coaching hockey and men's and women's golf at
Princeton University, a position he held until 1985. During that
time, he led the men's golf team to five Ivy League titles and the
women to three.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a couple of decades Dad was involved as a coach and a
teacher, something he was very focused on and proud of,'' Bruce
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Quackenbush lived in Lawrenceville, N.J., and was a member
of the Springdale Golf Club in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Joan Kalloch Quackenbush; three sons, Bruce
and Scott of Greenwich, Conn., and Todd of Pennington, N.J.; two
brothers, Ted of Toronto and Max of Halifax; and seven
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service is scheduled for Oct. 3 at 2 p.m. in the
Lawrenceville School Chapel in New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
