u f BC-CONTINENTAL-BANGOR-BO     09-15 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTINENTAL-BANGOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTINENTAL TO DROP SERVICE TO BANGOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Continental Airlines is planning to shut down its
service to Bangor, Maine, Oct. 30, diminishing the capacity of the
international airport and raising broad questions about the impact
of airline deregulation in rural parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The move infuriated both Maine senators, who issued a joint
statement saying they were ``appalled by Continental's decision''
and immediately demanded a Senate hearing on the matter.
Representative John Baldacci, a Maine Democrat, also announced he
would hold a hearing at Bangor International Airport next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastating,'' said Senator Olympia Snowe, a Maine
Republican. ``It's a significant loss to the airport. We've seen
this pattern in many parts of the country, and it's really having a
significant effect. It certainly is not right or fair. Airlines
depend on taxpayer dollars, public subsidies, the FAA as an agency
and airspace. It's a serious issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline currently runs two flights each weekday from Bangor
to Newark, with the capacity for 46 passengers on each turbo-prop
plane. But according to officials at Continental Express, ``the
system performance was relatively low'' in comparison to other
airports, forcing the company to close it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a true business decision,'' said Michele King, a
spokeswoman for Continental Express, the regional subsidiary fully
owned by Continental Airlines. ``It's a weak market for us. We're
disappointed as well, but we had to make this business decision. It
just makes the most sense to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12 employees of Continental now working at the Bangor
airport will be offered jobs at other airports, King said. She
declined to specify how full the flights to Bangor were on average.
But members of the Maine congressional delegation _ who learned
about the service termination on Tuesday, at the same time as
Continental employees _ said they were under the impression that
the flights were routinely as much as 70 percent full.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Express president David Siegel informed the senators
about stopping the service at a meeting scheduled to express ``good
news and bad news,'' said Dave Lackey, a spokesman for Snowe. The
good news was that Continental hoped to add two daily flights
between Columbus, Ohio, and Portland, Maine, starting on May 2,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the bad news had an immediate impact. Bob Ziegelaar, the
airport director at Bangor for nearly a decade, said he understood
why the congressional delegation was upset. ``They're right,'' he
said. ``Major carriers in this country are abandoning the smaller
airports, and there aren't regional carriers to take their place.
Airports like Bangor are being caught in the middle, because the
major carriers went out and the new ones can't come in because they
don't have the equipment, and the major carriers are fighting
them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Zeigelaar said the airport was already
negotiating with other carriers who hoped to take Continental's
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll overcome this. We're already talking to a couple of
operators,'' he said. And the new carriers, he pointed out, would
operate much larger regional jets. ``So there is a silver lining,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
