<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BOMBS-POLITICS     09-15 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMBS-POLITICS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW BOMBINGS RAISE MORE QUESTIONS ABOUT YELTSIN'S HOLD ON
POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (With RUSSIA-BOMBS)  
(nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Bombs are exploding in the middle of the night, in the
middle of the capital, killing families in their sleep. Generals
have boasted of victory in a war in the northern Caucasus, only to
be humiliated by thousands of Islamic militants who are striking
behind their backs. And international inquiries have cast new
suspicions overfinancial institutions, as well as members of
President Boris Yeltsin's family.
</P>
<P>
   How Yeltsin will react to the disasters and other problems that
are accumulating in his last year in office is unclear. Political
experts have given up predicting the next step of a leader
generally scorned by the population and isolated by a political
elite that is fleeing in droves from his once powerful tutelage.
</P>
<P>
   For days, rumors have swept Moscow that the Kremlin is again
preparing to do something. The speculation includes a declaration
of a state of emergency, or a ``special regime,'' to an
announcement by Yeltsin that he will resign 10 months ahead of
schedule in an attempt to give the advantage to his chosen
successor, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin. Other possibilities
include another round of dismissals of top presidential staff
members.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the blast on Monday, which killed more than 120
people in an apartment building on Kashirskoye Highway, top
officials have repeatedly insisted that the government has no plans
to introduce a state of emergency that, some fear, could lead to a
postponement of parliamentary and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   As Putin told parliament on Tuesday, Russia lacks an adequate
up-to-date law for imposing such emergency rule. And many political
observers said they thought that the central authorities were too
weak to impose the controls that such a move would entail.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that Yeltsin may retire early continue to circulate.
Analysts say they believed that the idea had been seriously
discussed in the Kremlin as a strategy to propel Putin into power
where he could watch over Yeltsin family interests. A month after
Yeltsin named him as heir apparent, Putin appeared in polls to
trail all possible presidential contenders, with a popularity
rating of 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But as Russia's situation goes from bad to worse, a consensus
has emerged that runs across society and across the political
spectrum: Yeltsin's time has run out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Yeltsin left today, it would be better for the people and
political parties, and it would be better for him, too,'' Yegor
Stroyev, chairman of the upper house of parliament, the Federation
Council, said in a recent interview. ``His attempt to hold onto
power or to stay there by installing his own man will create
enormous tension in society.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Stroyev, a former Communist who has been Yeltsin's
tactical ally in recent years, would not have made such a
statement. But since then, the country has undergone a severe
financial crisis that has sunk more of its people into poverty, a
regular turnover of governments and domestic scandals that have in
the last month spilled onto the international scene.
</P>
<P>
   The open-ended war in the Caucasus has come to Moscow with a
wave of what officials say are surely terrorist attacks, attributed
to Islamic guerrilla leaders whose operations in Dagestan have made
a mockery of the Kremlin's earlier claim of victory.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bombing in Moscow, the fourth in Russia in two weeks,
propelled Yeltsin into action. He summoned top security officials
to his office Monday, and since then he has reportedly been keeping
close track of the investigation and the security measures ordered
in Moscow and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the nation tries to steady itself for the
possibility of further attacks, Moscow newspapers expressed doubts
about the adequacy of the government's preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``After asking whether another terrorist act can be averted, the
key question is whether the executive power controls the country as
a whole,'' said Nezavismiya Gazeta, a Moscow newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya, the rebel republic where the guerrillas have made
their base, long ago slipped out of Moscow's control. The heirs of
the once-feared KGB network have proved incapable of anticipating
violence, even when it strikes at the heart of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Stroyev attributed the weakness of the central authority to a
flawed Constitution, drafted by Yeltsin in 1993, that gave him the
illusion of power, but none of its instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, he received enormous rights,'' Stroyev said
in an interview in the central city of Orel, where he is governor.
``But on the other hand, he was absolutely deprived of power over
the country. He may discharge his chief of staff and the prime
minister, but no one else. His power does not extend further than
the Kremlin walls. Nobody needs such a system of power. If it
remains, we will lose Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   For the seven years of his presidency, Yeltsin's power, illusory
or not, was enough to hold rivals in check. His instincts were also
acute enough to throw the challengers off guard, as he played his
favorite game of balancing different interest groups against one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as his status diminishes, and his opponents, including
former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Mayor Yuri Luzhkov of
Moscow, openly challenge his authority, reports of corruption in
his closest entourage have been met with a wearied yawn by many
politicians, among them Yeltsin's fiercest critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that in Russia there is terrible corruption, at all
levels,'' Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of the liberal opposition party
Yabloko, said in an interview last weekend. ``What difference does
it make what went on in Yeltsin's back yard?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Stroyev showed the same indifference to reports of bribery and
kickbacks given to members of `the Family,' a term now used to
describe Yeltsin's inner circle. The reportsarose from an
investigation, conducted with the help of Swiss authorities, into
the Mabetex Project Engineering Group of Lugano, Switzerland, a
company that has won several lucrative Kremlin contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even I, chairman of the Federation Council, am not interested
in what is going in the Kremlin,'' Stroyev said. ``I don't care
about the Family or its decisions. I know that they will not take
any decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The international dimension of the scandals, which now include
an investigation into suspicions that multiple billions of dollars
in Russian money had been flushed through accounts at the Bank of
New York, are also seen here as a sign that the Western world, too,
has had enough of the Yeltsin era.
</P>
<P>
   In Yavlinsky's view, Western frustration and disgust with
corruption in the government and its highhanded treatment of
foreign investors and creditors peaked in August 1998, but was for
months kept muffled as banks and international agencies struggled
to retrieve at least some of the money that they had lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then and there it became clear to me that this cannot be
forgiven for long,'' Yavlinksy said. ``Sooner or later, it had to
explode. And it happened this summer. It happened because everyone
is sick and tired of the Yeltsin regime. Everybody. Western people,
non-Western people. The first were the Russian people. But that was
OK. Russians elected him, and it was their business. But when
everybody else got sick and tired of him, it all began. It was the
last straw.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
