<HEADER>
A3483 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-REVIEW-CORRUPTION-OFP     09-15 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CORRUPTION-OFPOLITICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY THE WASHINGTON MACHINE IS BROKEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Corruption of American Politics: What Went Wrong and Why''
</P>
<P>
   By Elizabeth Drew
</P>
<P>
   Investigative journalism
</P>
<P>
   Birch Lane Press, $21.95
</P>
<P>
   American pundit Mark Twain once said, ``We have the best
Congress money can buy.'' After reading Elizabeth Drew's latest
book, ``The Corruption of American Politics: What Went Wrong and
Why,'' it looks like a million dollars doesn't buy what it used to.
</P>
<P>
   Drew, a seasoned Washington journalist, author and
Congress-watcher, looks at the pervasive, insidious role that the
all-mighty dollar plays in American politics. ``Corruption'' should
be required reading, not just for political wonks and editorial
writers, but for every voter and taxpayer in this country,
particularly as we get further into what is shaping up as the most
expensive presidential campaign ever. And that's saying plenty.
Total political spending just for TV ads during the '96 race was
$405 million, without counting the money paid to the people who
produced the ads.
</P>
<P>
   The entry fee into American politics is at an all-time high,
which means that men and women jockeying for the privilege of
serving the public spend an inordinate amount of time with their
hands out, palms up. The perception left in the public mind is that
the only citizens being served are the special-interest groups
anteing up the big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that Americans have grown cynical and apathetic
about politics.
</P>
<P>
   Even those weary few who attempt to address the ills of '90s
politics _ money, money and more money _ suffer at the hands of
their colleagues. Drew invites us to consider Fred Thompson. The
Tennessee Republican senator, tapped by Majority Leader Trent Lott
to conduct the hearings into the Clinton financial scandals of the
1996 election, never had a prayer. His desire to investigate how
campaign finance laws have been thwarted by folks on both sides of
the aisle was dead in the water before the echo of the convening
gavel rang through the Senate hearing room. Fellow Republican Lott
had a lot to do with torpedoing Thompson's effort.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem runs deeper than the pockets on a D.C. lobbyist.
According to Drew, civility, compromise, experience and a sense of
public purpose have evaporated from the halls of Congress. Drew
quotes one Senate aide: ``We don't have policy debates anymore.
Instead of voting on `the great issues of the day' _ whatever they
may be _ we haven't framed them very well. We go from skirmish to
skirmish until the next election. So much time is wasted on petty
issues instead of big ones.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Petty'' is also an accurate word to describe the relationships
that exist between policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marked decline in civility in both chambers in the past
few years has had an adverse effect on the job of doing the
people's business,'' Drew writes. ``Civility abetted the formation
of coalitions for large purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not uncommon, until sometime in the late '80s, for
senators and representatives to socialize across the aisle, go to
each other's homes. But now, serving in the Senate or the House is
an atomizing experience, what with the constant fund-raising
demands and the constituent demands.''
</P>
<P>
   The spate of 1996 retirements left ``a big hole in the center,
and a major hemorrhage of experience ... The collective departures
of, among others, Alan Simpson, William Cohen, Nancy Kassebaum, Sam
Nunn, David Pryor, Paul Simon, Mark Hatfield and Bob Dole removed a
substantial body of experience and judgment. A crucial core who
understood the point of compromising for the good of the whole was
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman members once looked to their elder statesmen for
guidance, deferring to their experience and knowledge in certain
fields; now they turn to their computers to try to become instant
experts on every subject. The world of an elected official consists
of the Internet, full-time campaigning and the latest polls showing
what folks back home are thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do everything they can do to avoid displeasing a
constituent or casting a controversial vote. They think in terms of
message rather than policy. The result isn't leadership,'' writes
Drew, a veteran political columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Drew's scrutiny of Washington insiders _ and outsiders who
desperately want in despite protests about how awful the place is _
has led to a string of books since 1994: ``On the Edge: The Clinton
Presidency; Showdown: The Struggle Between the Gingrich Congress
and the Clinton White House''; and ``Whatever It Takes: The Real
Struggle for Political Power in America''. This latest effort
paints perhaps the bleakest picture of the state of American
politics, but, unlike in some of her previous works, Drew does
offer seeds of hope for her readers. She just doesn't want them to
expect overnight miracles.
</P>
<P>
   Significant reform takes time, so Drew cautions Americans to be
prepared to hunker down for the long haul. But she firmly believes
that voters do care about campaign finance reform, and only need
the opportunity to focus on it. Evidence is available on the state
level; voters in several states have successfully adopted such
initiatives as public funding of state elections.
</P>
<P>
   Drew's look inside the halls of democracy gives readers an idea
of what they'll be up against in the fight to reform politics. In
any war, it's important to know how the enemy thinks.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist at
the Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
