<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SICKLE CELL PATIENT IS HOPEFUL DESPITE HER PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The worst part, perhaps, is not knowing when the pain will
strike.
</P>
<P>
   When it does, Kelley Lewis says, it is as if a truck ran over
her, backed up and rolled over her again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only way I know how to describe it,'' she says about
sickle cell disease. ``One day I'm feeling OK, and the next I may
be in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is where the 28-year-old Fort Worth woman was two weeks
ago. And a month or so before that. It is how her life is.
</P>
<P>
   It is enough to make you regret being born, because no amount of
time can erase the pain. There is no cure, so the debilitating pain
just keeps coming, like an uninvited guest banging on the door at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jones, executive director of the Sickle Cell Disease
Association of America/Greater Fort Worth, says that one in 12
people in Tarrant and Denton counties carries the sickle cell
trait. And contrary to popular belief, the disease is not limited
to African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sickle cell affects all of us,'' she says. ``It's not about
race, age, ethnicity, gender or social status.''
</P>
<P>
   But many contend that research funding would be more generous if
the disease did not primarily affect blacks and a small percentage
of people of Mediterranean, East Indian and Middle Eastern descent.
</P>
<P>
   In sickle cell disease, an inherited chronic anemia, blood cells
become sickle-shaped when deprived of oxygen. The results can
include pain, extreme fatigue and widespread, life-threatening
organ damage. The syndrome varies considerably in severity. Some
people live long and nearly normal lives; others, such as Lewis,
are plagued by strokes and painful ``crises.'' On average, sickle
cell patients die in their early 40s; 5 percent die before age 20.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' mother, Sandra, puts it this way: ``Sickle cell is a
disease that dominates the black Americans. It is a select killer
that needs to be eliminated in the worst way.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Lewis said she believes that isn't likely to happen
unless people, African-Americans especially, give more generously
to organizations such as the local association. If they don't, she
says, a cure may never come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need help,'' she says. ``Not pennies, real money.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that although about half the association's budget
comes from United Way, it must raise $108,000 this year alone just
to stay afloat. Donations help pay for testing, counseling and
education.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Lewis just tries to take one day at a time.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, when doctors thought she might die, Lewis
moved in with her mother. Two weeks ago, she returned to the
hospital after another painful episode.
</P>
<P>
   Because the episodes occur so often, she has never held a
full-time job, and even the part-time ones are only temporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, I'd get blood transfusions every month,''
she says. ``Now I only get them to bring me out of crisis. It's
hard, but you just live the best way you can. I have no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   But she does have hope that a cure will come. Not so much for
herself, but for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not in my life,'' she says. ``But it'll happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Star-Telegram. Send
e-mail to gstaples\Nstar-telegram.com.Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
