<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3487 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-DONNYMARIE16-COX     09-15 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DONNYMARIE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    They've had ups and downs, but Donny and Marie are once again on
top
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's 3 p.m. _ practically rush hour in traffic-snarled
metro Atlanta _ and even after the gleaming limousine has pushed
beyond the Perimeter and penetrated Mableton, problems loom.
</P>
<P>
   Pebblebrook High School's main parking lot is virtually
impossible to get into while school is letting out. And even when
the big car finds a parking spot, one of its two big star
passengers is nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to wake me up,'' Marie Osmond, 39, confesses several
minutes later, joining her brother, Donny, on the sidewalk outside
Pebblebrook's auditorium. ``I fell asleep on the way out.''
</P>
<P>
   As incredible as it sounds (could you nod off in Atlanta
traffic?), consider that the Osmonds are each operating on about
two hours of sleep. They've tacked this surprise visit to Cobb
County's performing arts magnet school (think ``Fame'') onto the
end of a long day near the end of an even longer, multi-city
promotional tour for their daytime talk show, their hosting duties
on Saturday night's Miss America Pageant, their ``Larry King Live''
appearance, their, well, you name it. They're so busy. So in
demand. So . I . I . dare we say it?
</P>
<P>
   So cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boys think I'm the bomb,'' Donny confirms.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old father of five sons winks while saying this,
which goes a long way toward explaining his and his sister's
resurgent appeal as a TV team. They know jaws drop whenever hip-hop
phrases like ``the bomb'' fall from their seemingly squeaky-clean
lips, or when _ as happened one memorable afternoon last year _
they welcome the likes of gangsta rapper Snoop Doggy Dogg to the
set of their show.
</P>
<P>
   ```In the best tradition of Donny and Marie, it's Snoop Doggy
Dogg!' '' Donny booms in a slightly incredulous tone moments before
the students arrive. ``That's why it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' begins its second season Monday _
which is something Howie Mandel and other, now canceled, talk show
hosts only wish they could say. More immediately, the Osmonds are
helping rescue Miss America from recent sagging TV ratings and a
series of less-than-successful host pairings that culminated in
last year's decidedly oddball coupling of ``Monday Night Football''
commentator Boomer Esiason and ``The View's'' Meredith Vieira.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing the Osmonds, pageant officials cited their family
image and youthful appeal. But that was before this week, when a
series of controversies hit the pageant. First, pageant organizers
revealed they would allow divorcees or women who'd had abortions to
compete for the crown; the resulting outcry was so immediate and
intense, the pageant now says it's reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   Another announcement, that Saturday's televised performances
would be limited to only the Top 5 talent finishers, elicited boos
from what is usually a fawning preliminary competition crowd
Tuesday night. And early Wednesday, more than 14,000 casino hotel
workers along Atlantic City's famed Boardwalk went out on strike.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly it seems like anything could happen during Saturday's
live telecast of a pageant long accused of being too staid and
anachronistic. A spokeswoman for the Osmonds said they were
traveling Wednesday and unavailable for comment on the pageant
controversies. No matter. The Osmonds seem to have been practically
prescient last month when they suggested during the Mableton
interview that their collective 60-plus years of show business
experience may have been the best reason to hire them as hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's three hours of live TV and there aren't many young people
who can do live TV,'' said Marie, a mother of seven (the youngest
is just 2 months old) and a veteran of numerous Children's Miracle
Network telethons and QVC appearances. ``I think they like the age
and the wisdom of the years!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think they went through many years of trying to find
people who can relate to each other and have chemistry,'' said
Donny. ``(People) who can on-the-fly handle things having to be cut
or extended because it's live television.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, nothing is ever as simple as it seems. Especially not
the devoutly Mormon Osmonds. Even before Marie's first marriage
ended in divorce when she was in her mid-20s, for instance, she'd
pretty much seen it all _ and then some.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, somebody said, `You know, you have this naive,
goody-goody image,''' she recalled, shaking her head. ``People are
naive to think that, that you can grow up in this business naive.
Most of the celebrity friends that I had growing up, my friends are
dead. And that's probably one of the reasons I stayed away from
some of that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, for a couple of supposed innocent naifs, these
two are pros. They've been up _ their wholesome variety show was
the top-rated program for several years in the mid-1970s. And
they've been down _ without a hint of self-pity, Donny will later
tell the Pebblebrook kids about having been declared a ``has-been''
at 20.
</P>
<P>
   They clearly like up better.
</P>
<P>
   They also think they know what it takes to get all the way back
there. Their talk show, which airs at 2 p.m. weekdays on WAGA,
started slowly last year, attracting a 2.2 rating locally (one
local ratings point equals 16,750 homes). By the end of last
season, however, ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' was averaging a 3.4 rating here
_ largely, the stars say, because it truly was Donny and Marie.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we tried too hard to be the perfect hosts and
memorize the scripts and say it exactly the way it should be
said,'' Donny explained. ``And Marie and I said to each other, `You
know what, this just isn't fun. We know what we've got to do, now
let's just throw it away and produce the show on the fly.'''
</P>
<P>
   For this season, that means more ``cutting edge'' musical
artists; they pride themselves on having given Britney Spears her
first national TV exposure last year. Monday's second-season
kickoff also will feature the duo's interview with the new Miss
America, taped Sunday night in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   But it also means doing what they've always done best, which is
talk. To guests, yes, but mostly to each other. And at each other,
about each other, around each other and occasionally even on top of
each other in a way more authentic than Regis and Kathie Lee, less
mean-spirited than Sonny and Cher.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to them on the traditional ``Miss America'' serenade, for
instance. Saturday night's crowning of Miss America 2000 will be
``completely different,'' they hint tantalizingly, but the old
chestnut ``There She Is'' won't disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Donny: ``The song has to stay, but it will be done in a very new
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie: ``We don't want to make it sound like it's something
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Donny (insistently): ``I won't be singing like Bert Parks, let's
put it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie (witheringly): ``Yes, he will.''
</P>
<P>
   They've been up, they've been down, and as the new millennium
beckons, Donny and Marie will be crowning Miss America.
</P>
<P>
   Donny: ``I think that says something.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess it says they're the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
