<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLERGY-ALERT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL MEANS THE RETURN OF SCHOOL _ AND ALLERGIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest bullies on the playground this fall may be grass and
ragweed.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny airborne pollens from these plants plague children,
causing them to sneeze, sniffle and cough their way through the
school day. And sometimes it's even worse: Some children with
allergies say they get teased for their watery-eyed appearance.
They feel left out, and they have problems paying attention in
school.
</P>
<P>
   Allergies, in short, are nothing to sneeze at: Twenty percent of
all children are allergic to something, and allergies account for 2
million missed school days each year. On any given school day, more
than 10,000 children stay home because of allergies, statistics
from the National Institutes of Health show.
</P>
<P>
   Allergic reactions can affect some children year-round or be
triggered by specific allergens, such as cat or dog hair. But many
allergies are seasonal. Ragweed season generally rages throughout
September, meaning that for many kids, back to school means back to
sneezing.
</P>
<P>
   What's a parent to do? Know thy enemy and its reaches, and arm
yourself with the best information on treatment. There's no cure
for allergic rhinitis, or hay fever as it's more popularly known,
but your child doesn't need to be miserable.
</P>
<P>
   KNOW THY ENEMY ALLERGENS
</P>
<P>
   Ragweed is the most common seasonal allergen in this country,
with 60 percentof all allergic people reacting to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of children are allergic to ragweed, and we always have
a lot of ragweed in this area at this time of the year,'' said Dr.
Susan Wynn, an allergist with Fort Worth Allergy and Asthma
Associates. Wynn is also a member of the national Pediatric Allergy
Collaborative, a panel of experts sponsored by the University of
Cincinnati College of Medicine. ``Ragweed season just happens to
coincide with the start of school each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ragweed might be the most obvious culprit, many other
pollens and particles can make kids sick. ``Mountain cedar, oak,
Bermuda grass, dust mites and ragweed, those are the biggies,''
Wynn says. ``Also outdoor mold spores _ especially on high-wind
days. It really depends on the person, but pollens _ trees, grasses
and weeds _ seem to cause hay fever-type symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   The physical symptoms of seasonal allergies _ sneezing, runny
nose, watery eyes, nasal congestion _ are more than just
irritations for children. They can lead to difficulty sleeping,
limited attention spans, decreased ability to concentrate, fatigue,
irritability and cognitive impairment. Symptoms can compromise a
child's performance in school, according to the Pediatric Allergy
Collaborative.
</P>
<P>
   Sneezing and wheezing can also be emotionally draining for kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disrupting class can be embarrassing and humiliating to the
child,'' Wynn says. ``I have heard of teachers making children
leave the class if they are sneezing and disrupting.''
</P>
<P>
   In a new survey by Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn, the maker of Children's
NasalCrom, 201 allergic children between the ages of 6 and 13 said
their allergies interfere with their studies. In fact, 29 percent
blame at least one poor test score on allergy symptoms; 11 percent
say they have trouble completing their homework. The survey also
found that 70 percent of the allergic kids are sometimes restricted
from participating in activities such as playing with friends
because of nasal allergies, and nearly half reported social
problems, such as an inability to make friends.
</P>
<P>
   TREAT THE SYMPTOMS
</P>
<P>
   Although a cure for allergies is still elusive, allergy shots
are an effective, long-lasting treatment for many kinds of
allergies, and medications that treat the symptoms have improved
significantly since today's parents were children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mom and Dad both had allergies, they may think it is normal
to have Kleenex in hand at all times and a box of Kleenex in every
room,'' Wynn says. ``That's not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have these good treatments when we were growing up.
Then it was, take a Benadryl and pass out, or just suffer. A lot of
people with allergies decided it was better to sneeze and blow your
nose than fall asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what parents need to know: Allergy testing is much
faster, less painful and more reliable than ever. Over-the-counter
antihistamines are the first line of defense against allergies,
especially when drowsiness is not an issue, such as bedtime.
Allergy shots are once again in favor as the best treatment for
many types of severe allergies. Prescription medication can also
offer relief for your child. For example, pediatric versions of the
minimally sedating oral antihistamines cetirizine (pediatric
Zyrtec) and loratadine (pediatric Claritin) have been approved by
the FDA for age 6 and older, and Tylenol offers children's Tylenol
Sinus and children's Tylenol Allergy-D (an antihistimine with a
decongestant and an analgesic). The FDA also approved Flonase nasal
spray for children 4 and up in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Cromolyn, best known under the brand name NasalCrom, has been
available over-the-counter the past couple of years to prevent
allergic reactions, and children's NasalCrom came onto the market
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Taken every four hours as a nasal spray, it works by stabilizing
mast cells, which release histamine in response to injury or
inflammation of tissue. It is the production of excess histamine
that causes itchy eyes, runny nose and itchy skin in an allergic
response. NasalCrom prevents the production of histamine rather
than neutralize it after it begins causing symptoms, so it is not
considered an antihistamine. It does not make users drowsy. What
parents should like about cromolyn is that it is safe and
nonaddicting. What they might like less is that it's a preventive
measure, which means you must use it before you come in contact
with an allergen. And the effects are not long-lasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big message,'' Wynn says, ``is pay attention to your
children's allergies. If over-the-counter antihistamines and
decongestants aren't helping, ask about prescription nasal spray.
Know that there are a lot of good, safe meds available to treat
your children without a lot of side effects.''
</P>
<P>
   DON'T TRIVIALIZE THE PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons a lot of children don't get the
treatment they need for allergies, Wynn says, is that society tends
to trivialize the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the media depicts a nerdy kid, you usually give him
allergies,'' Wynn says. ``You call him a snotty-nosed kid and think
of him as whiny, weak and inferior. You tend to not take allergy
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't buy into that thinking. If your child is having symptoms
on a daily basis _ sneezing, runny nose, itchy, watery eyes, if he
seems to be tired all the time or if symptoms seem to be disrupting
schoolwork because he is up getting a tissue every 20 minutes, he
needs help, Wynn says.
</P>
<P>
   Take your sneezing, wheezing child to an allergist whose
specialty is pediatrics, and get him or her the blood or skin tests
that will help identify the allergens that are causing the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Help him fight the bullies..MDBU/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
