<HEADER>
A3489 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BAPTISTS-GAYSREACT15-     09-15 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-GAYSREACT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptist group's stance on church with gays draws mixed reaction
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just as friends tend to choose sides in a divorce,
Christian leaders are rallying around the Georgia Baptist
Convention and Oakhurst Baptist Church as the two entities come to
a parting of the ways.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the executive committee of the convention voted to
sever its relationship with Oakhurst because of the church's
acceptance of homosexuality. The full state convention is expected
to ratify the decision in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for the prophetic people at Oakhurst!'' said Harry
Knox of Atlanta, director of the Georgia Equality Project, a
justice organization for gays and lesbians. ``I am so grateful to
them for giving leadership on this at great risk to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Knox, a United Methodist layman, was trained for the ministry
but has not been ordained because his denomination prohibits
practicing homosexuals from being clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Another United Methodist, Faye Short of Cornelia, praised the
Georgia Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand with them as they stand for the biblical standard
regarding homosexual practice,'' said Short, president of RENEW,
the women's branch of Good News, a conservative caucus within the
8.5-million member United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Short said her organization does not advocate mean-spiritedness
toward gays and lesbians. Rather, she said, she encourages ministry
to homosexuals that would help them change.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement prepared for the state convention, Oakhurst
members acknowledged that ``gay and lesbian Christians serve as
Sunday School teachers, choir members, deacons and preachers'' in
the church. Although the Oakhurst membership is not unanimous, the
statement said, ``we came to believe that the biblical references
to homosexual behaviors do not address the Christian commitments
and loving relationships of our gay and lesbian members.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakhurst is the first congregation to be removed from Georgia's
state convention rolls because of its stand on homosexuality, but
not the first nationally.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the North Carolina Baptist Convention dismissed Pullen
Memorial Baptist Church in Raleigh for sanctioning the blessing of
a homosexual couple and Binkley Memorial Baptist Church in Chapel
Hill for licensing a homosexual student to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some real grief involved,'' said the Rev. Randy Hall,
Pullen's youth minister. ``You've shared ministries together, built
relationships. To be kicked out is sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Pullen continues to bless same-sex unions, and as for
ordination, homosexuality ``is not a consideration anymore,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Removal from the state convention strengthened the 900-member
Pullen congregation in some ways, Hall said, ``because we took a
stand we felt we needed to take.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Faircloth, pastor of First Baptist Church in
Ashburn and a member of the Georgia Baptist executive committee,
would say the same thing applies to the Georgia Baptist convention.
He compared the Oakhurst decision to surgery, done cleanly and
precisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear everybody involved had been gracious and
conscientious,'' he said, ``but there comes a time when there has
to be a delineation.''
</P>
<P>
   But former Southern Baptist Bruce Garner of Atlanta, past
president of Integrity, an Episcopal organization for gays and
lesbians and their supporters, said, ``I think it's time everybody
learned it is not our business to sort and choose who belongs at
God's table. Everything I've seen indicates God's table is big
enough for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
