<HEADER>
A3490 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-SHOW16-COX     09-15 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SHOW16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guerrilla-ballerinas take the runways by storm
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you've ever stared quizzically at the apparel in
stores or magazines and wondered what designers were thinking when
they created them, read on for a glimpse into the minds of two of
Gotham's most glorified clothiers: John Bartlett and Cynthia
Rowley.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett unveiled warm-weather collections Tuesday that were
laden with light-colored leather. Bartlett's clothes for both sexes
bared a bounty of flesh. He winked at his jet-set clientele by
accessorizing outfits with flags-of-the-nations belts. Alternately,
the clothes looked militaristic, libidinously Latin, clubby and
equestrian.
</P>
<P>
   He dubbed his spring/summer styles ``Charo Meets Che.'' And the
collection, he said, ``incites a sensual revolution teeming with
guerrilla-ballerinas and deco-dent (sic) ex-patriot heiresses ...
the collection is a call for adventure, abandonment and a good
travel agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Phone home, John.
</P>
<P>
   After her womenswear presentation in the New Yorker Hotel's
ballroom, Rowley had to be dragged from backstage to take a bow by
one of her models. And she offered no pre-show explanation of her
design approach.
</P>
<P>
   But she did try to emphasize the whimsical nature of her
fashions by offering don't-take-this-so-seriously descriptions of
each outfit.
</P>
<P>
   She called one asymmetrically hemmed wrap sheath made from a
patchwork of handkerchief-weight floral fabrics her ``schizophrenic
dress with painted belt.'' Her titillating `` 3/4 of a swimsuit''
was just that, if not less. And the first in a series of eight
evening gowns with fiber optic lights woven into them was dubbed
``Black Out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowley really does design pretty, lighthearted clothes. But the
motives behind her merchandise still leave many in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kors: As aggravating as the all-Abba soundtrack to
Michael Kors' spring/summer preview on Wednesday was, the music
couldn't have been more fitting. Front-to-back and back-to-front,
Kors' collection was divine.
</P>
<P>
   The men's and women's outfits modeled were dedicated to his
moneyed South Florida constituency, which golfs, plays tennis,
hosts parties and lounges poolside. To Kors, spring signals the
time for sun worshipping; and his white, pale green, yellow,
tangerine and coral clothes were ideally suited for his skin-baring
silhouettes. Skirts were either short or slit sinfully high. Shorts
and bikini briefs were hard to distinguish from one another. Tops
showcased the models' chests, arms and shoulders. Cushy cashmeres,
translucent lace and luxuriant leathers were Kors' materials of
choice. Animal rights activists might protest the designer's
outlandish use of cowhide, but his laced leather pants and dresses
were still wonders to behold.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren: Any designer with a vision as resolute as Ralph
Lauren's should be forced to design collections with one eye closed
or an arm tied behind his back. The man may not experiment much,
but he's awfully darned good at what he does. Lauren doesn't design
so much as he refines; and his spring/
</P>
<P>
   summer 2000 womenswear collection further updates his great
American sportswear aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   This time, his aim was to simplify: Except for a few ruffled
skirts and fringed pants and jackets, everything looked slim, sleek
and oh-so-modern. To make wardrobing easier, he mainly restricted
his colorations to red, black, white and navy and his patterns to
checks, stripes and polka dots. There were lots of lavish leathers
in the form of bikinis, jeans, jackets and blouses. The crowd's
reaction to the collection was so enthusiastic that Lauren
high-fived his wife and children after the show.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta note: Jeffrey Kalinsky's latest emporium is the toast of
New York. Recently opened in the suddenly chic meatpacking
district, Jeffrey New York is getting plenty of fashion press ink
as the hot spot to shop. The designer responsible for Jil Sander,
Jeffrey Atlanta and Bob Ellis Shoes at Phipps Plaza has made his
store both a place to see and be seen. Celebs who have wandered
amid the finery since it opened in August include Luther Vandross,
Kevin Costner and Anthony Kiedis of the Red Hot Chili Peppers.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger goes patriotic and country-rock to boot
</P>
<P>
   By A. Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tommy Hilfiger described the men's and women's
clothes he previewed Tuesday night at Madison Square Garden as
``one part country and one part rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   That's apt, if only because all 70 of the spring/summer outfits
he unveiled _ to deafening, live accompaniment by the
alternative-rock band Bush _ were accessorized with red, white and
blue cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   But where within the rock-country continuum will his crucial (if
not core) constituency of hip-hop youth fit in? Only time, and
retail figures, will tell.
</P>
<P>
   After the extravagant, super model-studded show, actor Samuel L.
Jackson said of Hilfiger's wild, western-style jeans, ``I can't
wear stars on my (backside). People might think I was conceited.''
</P>
<P>
   The jeans _ rendered in leather, snakeskin and tropical weight
mohair _ were embroidered, lasered, studded, fringed and beaded to
the point of excess. Only Hilfiger's tube tops and cashmere
T-shirts escaped his ``Viva Las Vegas'' treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Flames shot up the legs of jeans held up by rodeo-buckled belts.
Cowpoke cross-stitching covered the seams of shirts, vests and
jackets. The lapels and shoulders of men's suits were top-stitched
in a way not seen since Roy Rogers ruled the movies. Some printed
silk skirts and dresses Hilfiger sent out bore an uncanny
resemblance to bandanas.
</P>
<P>
   On women, who are allowed more freedom to dress flamboyantly,
the clothes looked refreshing and realistic. On men, they tended to
look a bit costumey.
</P>
<P>
   It was at once a tribute to rockabilly culture and a cheer for
the cult of Tommy: tops, bottoms and accessories were all
emblazoned with his logos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The silhouettes in this collection, like the exaggerated boot
leg pant, could be Jim Morrison or they could be Lenny Kravitz,''
Hilfiger said. ``They were cool then and it's the new details and
the new fabrications that make them cool now.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the show if he thought hip-hoppers would hitch their
wagons to the rock-western look, three-piece-suited rapper-producer
Wyclef Jean replied: ``Well, I was looking at those white leather
pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the spirit of the collection,'' he added. ``It felt
like rock 'n' roll. Jimi Hendrix went for that look in his day. So
why shouldn't I?''
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton is Fashion Editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
