<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3499 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      09-15 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE QUESTIONS EVIDENCE GATHERING IN DRAGGING-DEATH TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ Attorneys defending a white supremacist accused
in last year's dragging death of a disabled black man in Jasper
tried Wednesday to cast doubt on how investigators collected
evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-examining a dozen Jasper County lawmen and FBI agents,
lawyers for capital murder defendant Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr.
questioned who picked up and bagged each piece of evidence, what
training and experience they had and why some of the investigators
failed to change their gloves after handling each item.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick, pick, pick,'' Jasper County District Attorney Guy James
Gray said during a break in the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   He said the defense was using a common tactic to make the jury
question whether the evidence could have been contaminated. But the
prosecutor insisted the evidence is solid and said the jury would
have to ignore the sworn testimony of several witnesses to conclude
that it was tampered with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cops make mistakes, lawyers make mistakes, everybody makes
mistakes. I wouldn't pretend every single thing is done
perfectly,'' he said when jurors were excused for the day. ``But
these guys were so thorough and they worked so hard picking all
this stuff up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real proud of our Jasper guys,'' he added. ``They picked
it up, labeled it, did a good job.``
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers Doug Barlow and Layne Walker of Beaumont have
declined to comment on their defense strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But for more than an hour Wednesday morning, Walked grilled
Jasper police detective Curtis Frame, seemingly questioning whether
a particular cigarette butt that Frame testified he recovered from
the crime scene could have instead come from a search of the
apartment of Brewer's co-defendant John William ``Bill'' King, or
from the search of another defendant's pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Frame insisted he had picked up the cigarette butt from a rural
logging road in the woods east of Jasper where prosecutors say
Brewer, King and Shawn Allen Berry beat and stripped James Byrd
Jr., chained him by his ankles to a pickup and then dragged him
more than two miles to his death early June 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, prosecutors plan to call a DNA expert from the FBI
to testify that Brewer's genetic blueprint was discovered on a
cigarette butt and a Bud Light bottle recovered from the crime
scene, and that Byrd's blood was on Brewer's tennis shoe found in
the apartment search.
</P>
<P>
   Frame remained calm and smiled at the jury as Walker repeatedly
pressed him to describe exactly how he picked up each piece of
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not that hard,'' Frame finally said. ``If you pick
an item up and put it in the bag, you've accomplished what you set
out to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Walker asked how Frame could presume that a certain
brown stain on the ground was blood, he answered: ``I've seen a lot
of blood, Layne. It's like if I ask you, is that water or not?''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Frame testified that when he arrived at Huff Creek Road
the morning Byrd's dismembered body was discovered outside a rural
black cemetery, it was obvious to him from marks in the road that
something had been dragged.
</P>
<P>
   A long trail of what appeared to be flesh and blood and drag
marks ``went back and forth on this asphalt road from side to side
to the point where the body had slung off to the side so it struck
a culvert and ripped its head off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frame also was the officer who was called to inspect Berry's
pickup after he was stopped on a traffic violation the night after
Byrd's killing.
</P>
<P>
   Frame said the truck appeared to be clean, but when he looked
beneath it he saw clumps of dirt and fresh grass stuck underneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I laid down under the truck and saw some red stains I
recognized as blood,'' he said, adding that he did a chemical test
to be certain. ``It showed positive.''
</P>
<P>
   In King's trial, DNA testing showed the blood belonged to Byrd,
49, whom witnesses said they saw riding in the back of the pickup
in the early morning hours of that day.
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying Wednesday were numerous investigators who
collected or transported evidence, a nurse from a Jasper hospital
who went to the jail to draw blood samples from the three
defendants and a mortician from the Jefferson County Morgue in
Beaumont, who took blood, bile and urine samples from Byrd's corpse
and turned them over to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of five women and nine men appeared attentive
throughout the day's slow, plodding testimony, as did Brewer, who
sat at the defense table, looking at the evidence and consulting
with his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boring, boring day,'' Gray said outside the courthouse. ``But
it's part of the law and you've got to do it. Pick up this little
piece of evidence and label it and carry it and who'd you give it
to or how'd you get it to the lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think the jury paid a whole lot of attention to
all that chain of custody stuff,'' he added. ``All they wanted to
know is somebody picked it up somewhere and it got to the lab.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of capital murder, Brewer, 32, would face life in
prison or death by injection.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, was convicted and sentenced to death earlier this
year. Berry, also 24, will be tried later in his home town of
Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
