<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-AMERICANS-ART-     09-15 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AMERICANS-ART-1300(TRIMS)(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPON RETURN, ALBANIAN-AMERICANS WHO FOUGHT IN KOSOVO ARE TREATED AS
HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers may make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By   BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Agim Selmanaj, 27, a construction worker, knows he
must go back to work soon. It has been two months since he returned
from war in Kosovo, and finding a job should be easy _ there are
plenty of grateful Albanian-American businessmen who would hire
him.
</P>
<P>
   But he is tired. ``I saw a lot of no-good things over there,''
he said. ``My friends tell me I look sad all the time. I feel good,
not killing anymore, not burning houses. I just want to relax a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Fadil Idrizi, a Manhattan restaurant manager, returned from
Kosovo a big man in the Albanian-American community. When he joined
the Kosovo Liberation Army, they made him a commander; he went on
to lead a battalion of 480 guerrillas during weeks of battle.
</P>
<P>
   Now everybody wants to talk to him. But he has been ducking
parties and avoiding acquaintances. He hates all the questions.
``They ask, What did I do over there?'' he said. ``But what they
want to know is, `How many Serbs did you kill?'''
</P>
<P>
   Every Albanian-American knows about Haxji Dervisholli, whose
right foot was blown off by a grenade. Many American volunteers saw
the explosion and remember it with horror. ``I was screaming, `Look
what they did to my friend!''' Selmanaj recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But Dervisholli himself sounds matter-of-fact. ``I got up and
stopped the blood,'' he said. ``I tied rags tightly. They carried
me up a sheer, straight cliff. Grenades were being thrown at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon he will be fitted with a permanent prosthesis. His plans,
he said, are firm. ``I want to go to Pristina. I want to see my
family. Maybe I stay forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Last April, these men were among 80 Albanian-Americans from the
New York area who volunteered to fight with the Kosovo Liberation
Army, flush with patriotism and dispatched with speeches, cheers
and weeping. ``I was very, very happy to go and serve in the army
for my country,'' said Selmanaj, echoing sentiments his fellow
soldiers expressed before embarking on their crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them have since returned, drifting home over the summer
after the Yugoslavians began withdrawing their troops in June. Some
are back in the Bronx, others in Brooklyn and Westchester _ all
heroes in the coffee shops, bars and living rooms of tight-knit
Albanian-American communities hungry for tales of bravado.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the transition has not been an easy one for a group that
went to war emboldened more with passion than military knowledge.
The group left with romantic visions of saving their homeland and
returned with troubling memories of killing and dead bodies, of
dodging shells and shots.
</P>
<P>
   As they go back to their old jobs, or are looking for new ones _
as waiters, doormen, stockbrokers, students _ many are finding it
hard to resettle into civilian life.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought war would be somewhat like the movies,'' Florim
Lajqi, a student at John Jay College who fought with the KLA, said
as he and other volunteers gathered in the Gurra Cafe in the
Belmont section of the Bronx. ``But you don't see people getting
shot up and blown up and grenaded around you in the movies. I had
never seen a dead body before. I realized, `Oh, my God, I could get
killed any minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other volunteers was a 16-year-old high-school girl
from Brooklyn and two men who were pushing 60. A third, Avdyl
Gashi, was 73, though he told the local KLA recruiter he was only
59. Most had never even handled a gun. And about 20 of them
eventually deserted the battalion, Idrizi said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   They were given a month to become soldiers. At the rebel
training camp in Albania, they were trained in basic combat
procedures _ how to load and shoot a gun, defuse a mine, take cover
from shelling. About 2,500 volunteers from many countries were
crowded into the camp, and for days the rations consisted of bread
and onions.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Abrahams, a researcher for the nonprofit Human Rights
Watch, encountered some of the volunteers in May, when he was in
Kosovo. ``Two things amazed me,'' he said recently. ``Their
willingness to put their lives on the line to _ in their words _
free their homeland. And their total lack of military experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were quickly pegged as spoiled, arrogant and out
of shape, said Florin Krasniqi, a Brooklyn businessman who raised
money to send the group overseas and who visited the training camp.
``They don't listen,'' he said. ``They want good food. They want a
shower.'' Idrizi, who had served in the Yugoslavian army for more
than a year and was trained as a sharpshooter, was one of the few
Americans who knew what he was getting into.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in with different things in their mind,'' he said.
``War works completely differently. You do not make a soldier in
two or three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Idrizi had his hands full with his recalcitrant colleagues. ``In
the army you have to walk in line,'' said Idrizi, who cajoled,
reasoned with and scolded the volunteers. ``These guys don't want
to walk in line. I say, `Get in line. Turn right. Turn left. Come
on, guys, you have to do it. You have to follow the rules.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The destination of the Atlantic Battalion, as the Americans and
other foreign volunteers under Idrizi were known, was Mount
Pashtrikut, a remote region on the border of southwest Kosovo.
According to the American volunteers, they camped there and fought
the Serbian forces for nearly a month. According to Idrizi, about
4,500 rebel guerrillas were stretched along a 10-mile range, facing
an unknown, but at least equal number of Serbians at close range.
</P>
<P>
   There were no journalists or other outside witnesses at the
Mount Pashtrikut battlefront. But Fatmir Lima, the senior KLA
commander who is now the deputy defense minister of the provisional
government, confirmed that the Americans were involved in combat
and, when the Serbians tried to take Mount Pashtrikut, participated
in a 10-day battle to hold it. The American volunteers, he added,
were better fighters than he had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought those boys and girls would find it very hard to
adapt to war conditions,'' said Lima. ``But I was pleasantly
surprised by their attitude and strong will. They adjusted very
fast to fighting conditions. They showed bravery on the
battlefield.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The mere presence of Americans on the battlefront boosted the
morale of the long-time guerrillas, he said. ``The first thing was
that they gave up everything they had on the other side of the
Atlantic to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the odds, nobody in the Atlantic battalion was killed,
according to Idrizi and other volunteers. The rebels took to
calling them ``the lucky Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Under fire, the Americans shaped up, said Idrizi. ``Our guys
learned so fast, so quick. There was lots of shooting. They saw the
wounded. They took it seriously. They kept their heads down.''
</P>
<P>
   The hike up Mount Pashtrikut took 8 hours. The bivouac, where
they remained for a month, was a rocky, treeless mountainside edged
by a forest. The volunteers had no tents. They dug trenches for
cover and bunkers _ stones piled in a circle _ to sleep in. It took
three hours to haul food and water from the storage side.
</P>
<P>
   Ilmi Berisha, a 29-year-old waiter from Brooklyn, said
volunteers boasted during boot camp about not being scared. ``But
when we get to the front,'' he said. ``I'm scared. Every time they
shell us, I'm scared.'' He actually felt safer as a spy on Serbian
territory, he said. ``No shelling.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Selmanaj said he had to force himself to shoot. ``I
saw something moving and I thought, `Oh, damn, let me just shoot
there.' Then they started shooting, too. I didn't really want to
kill somebody. But when I think what they do to us, torturing,
burning, I said, I have to do it. After two or three days. I didn't
really care.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the war's end, the volunteers made their way to Pristina
where NATO officials ordered them to hand in their weapons. Some
remained; other split off, searching for relatives and defusing
mines in rural areas. Lajqi said there were a few times he
protected Serbian residents from attacks by local rebels. But after
seeing the destruction of the house he was born he, he later
admitted torching the abandoned home of Serbian collaborators.
``I'd seen a lot of dead people and houses burned and I was going
crazy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to several Americans, Adrin Graatch, a volunteer from
the Bronx, was arrested by NATO for beating a Serbian man to death
in a Pristina restaurant but was just released.
</P>
<P>
   Ukaj said that as far as he knows, no other Americans were
involved in property destruction or attacks on Serbian civilians.
``We were busy trying to find our families,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they are home again, the volunteers are heroes to
Albanian-Americans. Troubling memories become jumbled with the
cries of praise and the kisses and exclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Some volunteers are trying to forget, but others love the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls,'' said Berisha, who is married, ``go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of ex-girlfriends are calling,'' concurred Lajqi, who is
single. He is making back-to-back dates in order to squeeze them
all in. At home, he said, he has had numerous visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty people are listening to you tell your stories,'' he
said. ``You're the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Idrizi wants to forget, but some of his men are not ready to let
him. Late one night a few weeks ago, he meet with some of them
during a regular weekly gathering over drinks and talk. When he
walked in, they rose and saluted. When they spoke, they called him
``commander.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said no,'' said Idrizi. ``Not here. I am one of you now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
