<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EAST-TIMOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PUSHES HUMANITARIAN AID FOR EAST TIMOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand _ Expressing fears that more East
Timorese could die of starvation, President Clinton pressed
Indonesia on Wednesday to allow humanitarian aid into the province
and to renew efforts to stop the continued violence against
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations early Wednesday approved plans for an
international force, led by Australia, to restore security in East
Timor, where pro-Indonesian militias have run amok since last
month's independence vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the Indonesian military, accused of supporting the militia
bloodshed, has been holding up plans to drop food and medical
supplies to East Timor residents forced from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he wanted to see the peacekeeping force move
into the Indonesian province within days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to receive reports of violence and intimidation,
which Indonesia has a responsibility to prevent. And also,
Indonesia has a responsibility to allow relief organizations access
to the refugees now,'' Clinton said during a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said many East Timorese are ``still vulnerable to
attack. Many have fled their homes; many are short of food _ not
only those who have left the country, but those who are displaced
within East Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters
that Pentagon officials were working with the White House on
details of the U.S. commitment to the peacekeeping force. Cohen
said information about specific units being deployed to East Timor
should emerge ``within the next day or so.''
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the troops _ possibly 7,000 _ likely will come from
the Australian and Malaysian militaries. France plans to send 500
soldiers, helicopters and an assault landing ship. Canada, New
Zealand, the Philippines, Portugal, Singapore and Thailand are
likely to contribute troops.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the United States will airlift 300,000 humanitarian
rations to Darwin, Australia, where food supplies will be stored
until Indonesian officials approve dropping the meals over East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Aid agencies estimate hundreds of civilians were killed by
pro-Jakarta militias upset after the East Timorese overwhelmingly
voted for independence Aug. 30. More than 200,000 people were
rousted from their homes as thousands were forced into West Timor
or into the mountains of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sited the international effort to assemble a
peacekeeping force for East Timor as one of the successes of the
Asia Pacific Economic Conference forum held in Auckland earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wrapped up a weeklong trip here with an official state
visit with Prime Minister Jenny Shipley. He will return to
Washington early Thursday &UR;  &LR; , cutting short a planned golf outing in
Hawaii because of Hurricane Floyd. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Australians, who have taken the lead in convening the
security troops, will provide the largest contribution, 2,000
soldiers for a force of 8,000. The United States will provide
troops for logistics such as airlifts, communications, intelligence
and engineering work.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials made the rounds of Capitol Hill Wednesday
to bolster support for the U.S. role. Richard Holbrooke, the U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations, met with Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., and several other senior lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution supporting the multinational force and commending
Australia for its role cleared the House International Relations
subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Shipley and Clinton praised the work of APEC, which
embraced a round of talks on global free trade that will begin in
Seattle in November. Clinton also said he was ``neither optimistic
nor pessimistic'' about a timetable for reaching an agreement with
China for its entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   China wants special concessions to protect some closed sectors
of its economy. The WTO would require China to play by
international trade rules. Clinton said the United States and China
had only a couple of issues outstanding but it was a decision China
must make if it wants WTO membership.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations renewed their WTO talks during the APEC session.
Negotiations had been suspended following the mistaken bombing of
Beijing's embassy in Yugoslavia by a U.S. warplane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
