<HEADER>
A3506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-SHELTERS-NC16     09-15 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-SHELTERS-NC16 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. residents seeking shelter
 &HT;    By Nancy McGillicuddy and Gene Metrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH CITY, N.C. _ As Hurricane Floyd tore into eastern
North Carolina, about 1,200 residents were expected to seek refuge
in shelters across the Twin Counties.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Lisa Richardson vacated her trailer Wednesday in
Nashville, N.C., and was among the first at the Red Cross shelter
at Northern Nash High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so nervous after Fran and Bonnie _ I didn't want to go
through the same thing,'' she said. ``They said 125 mph winds _
there was no way I was staying in the trailer.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, a 1983 graduate of the school, brought with her only
a bag of food, a blanket, water and her Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stay here until the storm blows over,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross began delivering supplies to shelter sites at 4
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first disaster,'' said volunteer Elizabeth Whitford
of Nashville while unloading cots and blankets from the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross officials said they were expecting several hundred
people at each of the shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to estimate just how many people will come,'' said
Diana Burger, a Red Cross volunteer who is helping operate the
shelters. ``Right now, we are prepared for 200-300 per shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash County has four shelters staffed by the Salvation Army and
the Red Cross _ Benvenue Elementary, Southern Nash Junior High,
Northern Nash Senior High and Southern Nash Senior High schools.
Edgecombe County has three Red Cross shelters set up at Parker
Middle School in Rocky Mount, Martin Middle School in Tarboro and
Carver Elementary School in Pinetops.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get more (people), we'll open up more shelters,'' Burger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 people had already arrived at Benvenue Elementary
School 30 minutes before the shelter was scheduled to open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get here early,'' said Pam Vick of Edgecombe
County, who came to the shelter with her husband, John, and two
daughters, Matilda, 15, and Lucy, 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seeing the news and watching all the cars leaving the
coast, we didn't want to get stuck in something like that here,''
John said. ``We thought we had better play it safe _ I don't want
to take any chances with the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick said he had received notice not to come in for his
third-shift job at Abbott Laboratories because the plant was
reportedly closing at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there for 22 years, and this is the first time I can
remember them shutting down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those taking refuge were told to bring a pillow, blanket, any
prescription medications and toys for small children. Babies should
have a three-day supply of diapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we are looking to stay open until Friday,''
Burger said. ``But it depends on what Floyd wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army's two shelters are preparing for 300 people
each.
</P>
<P>
   Cots and blankets will be sparse, but meals will be served, said
Maj. David Johnston, commander of the Salvation Army in the Twin
Counties.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve volunteers will be working throughout the night to
prepare the shelter and to cook and serve meals, which will be
served as long as the shelter is open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be there until they don't need us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
