<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Thursday, Sept.
16, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   GATES-GIFT (Seattle) _ The William H. Gates Foundation on
Thursday will give at least $1 billion and probably more in a major
inititative to help disadvantaged and minority students here in
Washington state and elsewhere in the country get a college
education.
</P>
<P>
   By Ruth Schubert and Kristin Dizon. (Story will move in the
``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ORPHANS (Seattle) _ About 25 years ago, Queen Anne resident
Betty Tisdale arranged for the evacuation of 210 young children
from the An Lac Orphanage weeks before Saigon fell. After the
children (all under 9) were adopted in the United States, Tisdale
kept in contact with them through the years when their parents sent
photos or letters. Now, many of the children will be meeting their
``Angel of Saigon'' for the first time as they fly in for a
Wednesday night banquet held in her honor.
</P>
<P>
   By Phuong Le. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WTO-PROTEST (Undated) _ They call it the perfect protest: a city
snarled. Traffic tied up. Banners hang from buildings. Protesters
have chained themselves to trees. Enter the The Ruckus Society,
which teaches these things, which espouses these methods, which
really wants to disrupt life in Seattle when the World Trade
Organization meets here later this year. This week, the Ruckus
Society is at the Pragtri Farm just outside of Arlington, Wash., to
teach 160 activists from around the world how to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   By Judd Slivka. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-ACTION (Undated) _ If ribaldry is not your scene, no need to
go in search of Fox TV's ``Action.'' But if intelligent comedy with
an adult slant doesn't make you dive under the bed, ``Action'' may
be the best thing to hit Thursday nights since ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
