<HEADLINE>
HACKERS CLAIM MARKET WEB SITES INVADED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mysterious Web site crakcers known as United Loan Gunmen
(ULG) has struck again &UR;  &LR; -- &UR;  &LR; maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ULG, which has claimed responsibility for defacing several of
the Internet's best-known sites, said Tuesday night it had posted a
mock news story at the Web site of the Nasdaq stock exchange. But
no sign of any break-in could be seen on Wednesday morning, and
Nasdaq has refused to confirm or deny that anything happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NASDAQ Web site is operational and secure, and we will
continue to monitor our sites to maintain their integrity,'' said
Nasdaq spokesman Scott Peterson. In addition, Peterson said that
even if the exchange's public Web site were attacked, this would
pose no threat to the computer systems that Nasdaq uses for stock
market trades.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the alleged attack is the latest indication of how
insecure many Web sites are. That's a problem because millions of
Americans now get their news and information from the Internet, and
even purchase goods and services there.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Martin, co-founder of Attrition.org, the computer security
organization that discovered the attack, points out that an
intruder could do a lot of damage by publishing plausible-looking
but false information on a financial Web site. ``Instead of making
a wild, outlandish front page, what if they had changed stock
prices, or changed an article?'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Such an incident happened in April, when an engineer at PairGain
Technologies Inc. was arrested for publishing rumors that his
company was about to be sold. The engineer, who held PairGain stock
options, published a message that simulated a report from the
Bloomberg financial news Web site. PairGain shares rose 32 percent
before the hoax was spotted.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin thinks ULG just wants to mock powerful institutions,
including Wall Street and the news media. Someone claiming to be
ULG has also taken responsibility for recent defacement of the
Drudge Report Web site, as well as the sites of the political TV
channel C-SPAN and the ABC television network. ``It seems like
they're trying to prove that these big institutions like media, are
not secure, and you can't trust the information coming from them,''
said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way of knowing if ULG is really a team or an
individual, or even if the ULG who claimed responsibility for the
Nasdaq attack is the same who performed the other intrusions.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged attack came to Martin's attention at about 11:25
p.m. Eastern time on Tuesday night. Martin says he was contacted
over Internet Relay Chat, a system that allows people to type
messages to each other over the Internet. Martin said that someone
using the nickname ULG told him that the Nasdaq site had been
attacked and urged him to take a look.
</P>
<P>
   Martin did, and found a mock news story on the front page. In
part it read, ``Just moments earlier, the Elite Computer Hacking
group ULG (United Loan Gunmen) uprooted the NASDAQ Stock Market Web
Site...Their goal was an attempt to make stocks rise drastically,
thus making all investors happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Martin made a copy of the page, it disappeared
from the Nasdaq site and no further problems have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Attrition spokesman B.K. DeLong believes that Nasdaq won't
confirm that its Web site was raided because the exchange doesn't
want to spook nervous investors. ``People who are not familiar with
technology are not going to know that the Web site and the trading
network are two entirely different entities,'' said DeLong.
``Obviously they don't want to send the market into a spiral.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq exchange fell anyway, though there's no evidence that
the attack had anything to do with it. The Nasdaq index closed at
2814.17, down 54.12 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
