<HEADER>
A3512 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-COMPOSERS-ONCASH-TEX     09-15 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPOSERS-ONCASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ONE MUSIC CRITIC WOULD CHANGE THE FACE OF CURRENCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British just pulled way ahead in the friendly competition
for cultural superiority with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it looked as if our side of the Atlantic was ahead,
at least in the classical music category. They gave the world
Elgar, Vaughan Williams, Britten and Tippett. We gave the world
Copland, Ives, Gerswhin and Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   They have the beleaguered Royal Opera at Covent Garden. We have
the wealthy, opulent Metropolitan Opera and a host of healthy
regional opera companies.
</P>
<P>
   They have the Philharmonia Orchestra, the BBC Symphony, the City
of Birmingham Symphony. We have the Chicago, Philadelphia, Boston
and Cleveland orchestras and other good orchestras, more than you
can count. They have Simon Rattle. We have James Levine.
</P>
<P>
   They have the Leeds. We have the Cliburn.
</P>
<P>
   But, in one gigantically significant move, our cousins on the
other side of the pond have demonstrated the superior position of
classical music in their culture, leaving us as embarrassed as if
we had had a coughing fit in the middle of Handel's ``Messiah.''
</P>
<P>
   They put their money where their mouth is, literally.
</P>
<P>
   They put a picture of a composer on the widely circulated
20-pound note.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Treasury currently produces seven varieties of paper
currency with pictures of famous Americans on them. All dead white
guys. All politicians. Three of them slave holders. Four of them
military men.
</P>
<P>
   One, Alexander Hamilton, was an avowed opponent of democracy
because he viewed it as a threat to private property, which he held
sacred. He died in a pistol duel.
</P>
<P>
   Although unquestionably significant in the formation of the
young United States, Hamilton is not exactly a role model.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Edward Elgar, however, who graces the 20-pound note in the
United Kingdom, was a devoted servant of the art of music _ besides
being an avowed patriot. Throughout his life, he continually
sacrificed his financial security to continue composing. A
self-trained genius, he produced two universally acknowledged
masterpieces (the ``Enigma'' Variations for orchestra and the Cello
Concerto) and two universally recognized melodies (the ``Pomp and
Circumstance'' March No. 1 and the ``Salut d'Amour.'') Connoisseurs
on both sides of the Atlantic contend that several other of his
works are equally significant, among them orchestral tone poems,
symphonies, a violin concerto and three monumental oratorios,
including the bold and radiant vision of the journey of the soul
after death, ``The Dream of Gerontius.''
</P>
<P>
   Let us hang our heads in shame, until the U.S. Treasury wakes up
and replaces Alexander Hamilton with one of our own great
composers.
</P>
<P>
   Which of our great composers should it be?
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin, Copland, Bernstein, Ives? Maybe. Any of the first
three would be the first Jewish person on our currency. Copland or
Bernstein would be the first homosexual on American currency _
which would at least trigger some healthy controversy and
discussion in the country, along with a good deal of opposition.
</P>
<P>
   However, passing over Scott Joplin, a sentimental favorite as an
African-American born in Texas, the ideal figure for the redesigned
$10 bill would be jazzman Edward Kennedy ``Duke'' Ellington.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ellington has everything going for him as a candidate
for currency. He's immensely well-respected by classical and jazz
musicians for his wide-ranging creativity, obvious genius and bold
innovations. He would be the first African-American to appear on
U.S. currency _ a long-overdue tribute.
</P>
<P>
   He never owned slaves and never fought a duel with deadly
weapons. He was not a politician or soldier, and he was
consistently the most popular musician in America in an era when he
was officially a second-class citizen because of the color of his
skin.
</P>
<P>
   America is more than dead presidents. Our contribution to the
artistic growth of humanity is equal to our military, financial and
political contributions. It's time we claimed that heritage on our
money.
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay covers classical music for the Star-Telegram.
Send e-mail to wlgay\Nstar-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
