<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MOB-DECISION-BOS &LR;      09-15 1591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-DECISION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REJECTS MOBSTERS' CLAIM OF FBI IMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- For decades, the FBI protected its prized informants,
reputed South Boston crime boss James J. ``Whitey'' Bulger and his
sidekick Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi, by tipping them to
investigations and ignoring their crimes, but they were never
promised they wouldn't be prosecuted, a federal judge concluded
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a long-awaited decision that threatened to derail a landmark
racketeering case against the region's top organized crime figures,
US District Judge Mark L. Wolf refused to drop any charges against
Flemmi, Bulger, reputed New England Mafia boss Francis P.
``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme, and two associates, or to toss out a
key piece of evidence -- a 1989 bugging of a Mafia induction
ceremony in suburban Medford.
</P>
<P>
   After 46 witnesses, 276 exhibits and 80 days of testimony that
stretched over most of last year, Wolf was unswayed by Flemmi's
central claim: He and Bulger were promised immunity from
prosecution for any crime short of murder in exchange for
information they fed the FBI on their Mafia rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In a one-inch thick, 661-page decision, Wolf concluded that the
FBI broke its own rules while handling Bulger and Flemmi, but that
any agreement with the pair did not rise to the level of a formal
deal not to prosecute them.
</P>
<P>
   While Wolf did not dismiss any charges, he did bar federal
prosecutors from using any evidence gathered against Bulger or
Flemmi during a series of buggings in the 1980s because they had
given the FBI information that it used in applications for the
bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, any victory for prosecutors may be shortlived. Wolf said
he plans to hold more hearings on whether information from four
bugging operations was presented to the grand jury that handed down
the racketeering indictment against Flemmi and the others in
January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   If it was, Wolf said he may throw out some or all of the charges
against the 65-year-old Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is it's very good news for Mr. Flemmi,'' said
his attorney, Kenneth J. Fishman. ``I certainly will be urging the
court that there really is no way for this indictment to survive as
a result of the evidence that is being excluded against Mr.
Flemmi.''
</P>
<P>
   Salemme's lawyer, Anthony Cardinale, said he will ask Wolf next
week to release Salemme on bail.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinale said it was Salemme and reputed Mafia solider Robert
DeLuca who pushed Flemmi to reveal that he was an FBI informant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for us, and certainly for my client, for the
world to know that this wasn't sleuthing that was going on,'' said
Cardinale. ``It was nothing but outright rat snitching and it was
accomplished by a guy who professed to be one of (Salemme's)
closest pals.''
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald K. Stern, whose office is prosecuting the
case, issued a statement saying he was ``pleased'' that Wolf denied
a request by defense attorneys to dismiss the indictment or
suppress FBI tapes of the induction ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, I am disappointed that the court is requiring
that further evidentiary hearings be held before it can make final
rulings on Flemmi's motions,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Stern and Barry Mawn, special-agent-in-charge of the FBI's
Boston office, said they are continuing to investigate allegations
of FBI misconduct that surfaced during the hearings before Wolf
last year and were chronicled in his lengthy decision.
</P>
<P>
   Although Flemmi became an FBI informant in 1965, followed by
Bulger a decade later, Wolf wrote that the FBI ``played a pivotal
role in forging a formidable enduring partnership between Flemmi
and Bulger. ... The FBI made Bulger and Flemmi, who were previously
acquainted but not close, a perfect match.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Flemmi testified that he had stopped meeting with the
FBI for a few years when Bulger arranged for him to meet his
handler, Special Agent John Connolly, in 1976. At the time both
Flemmi and Bulger were reputed members of the Winter Hill Gang,
based in Somerville, just outisde of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   They became a team, allegedly shaking down bookmakers and drug
dealers together, then rendezvousing with agents to provide
information on the criminal exploits of their Mafia rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arrangement offered (Flemmi) an opportunity to use the FBI
to disable his enemies, enhance his safety, and with the
competition diminished and the protection of the FBI, make his own
criminal activities more profitable,'' Wolf wrote.
</P>
<P>
   There was ample evidence that Bulger and Flemmi were protected
over the years by many agents, said Wolf, citing the testimony of a
parade of former FBI agents, prosecutors and underworld operatives.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said he was unable to rely on FBI records found in the
informant files of Bulger and Flemmi because there was
``substantial evidence that members of the FBI engaged in improper
if not illegal conduct'' and had a motive to tailor, omit or
distort the records.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Wolf said, he was drawing conclusions from some of
the testimony. Among his stunning findings: he believes that
Connolly, who retired in 1990, warned Bulger and Flemmi on the eve
of their January 1995 indicment so they could flee.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger left and remains a fugitive, named recently to the FBI's
Ten Most Wanted list.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said Flemmi's testimony that it was former FBI Supervisor
John Morris who warned Bulger to flee just wasn't ``credible.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday, Connolly said, ``I did not tip Bulger,
Flemmi or anyone else with repsect to the indictment returned by
the grand jury in 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   While Connolly refused to testify at the hearings last year
citing his Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination, Morris
was granted immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Morris admitted pocketing $7,000 in payoffs from Bulger and
Flemmi and claimed that Connolly delivered two of the payments,
each totaling $1,000. Connolly denies that.
</P>
<P>
   Morris also admitted tipping Bulger and Flemmi to an FBI
investigation of one of their associates, a Roxbury bookmaker, so
they would not be caught.
</P>
<P>
   Morris also claimed that he sent word to Bulger and Flemmi
through Connolly that another Winter Hill gang member, Brian
Halloran, was cooperating with the FBI and had implicated them in
the 1981 murder of Tulsa millionaire Roger Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran was murdered in 1982 and Morris said he suspected
Bulger and Flemmi were involved in the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly denies ever warning Bulger and Flemmi that Halloran was
cooperating against them.
</P>
<P>
   There were numerous instances of FBI protection detailed by Wolf
involving more than a half-dozen current and former FBI agents.
Wolf said it was the FBI's way of keeping two informants who were
providing critical information against the Mafia on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI agents primarily responsible for dealing with Flemmi,
by word and deed, for thirty years, promised Flemmi protection in
return for the valuable information that he was providing,'' Wolf
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Wolf said Flemmi had no expectation that he had immunity
from prosecution, nor was the term immunity used in any
conversation between him and FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather, he expected that the FBI would overlook some of his
criminal activity, provide him information concerning any
investigations that were conducted, and warn him of any imminent
charges against him of which it learned,'' Wolf wrote. ``The FBI
performed its part of the bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge concluded that Flemmi and Bulger were promised that
information they gave the FBI so it could get court approval to
install listening devices in Mafia hangouts would not be used
against them.
</P>
<P>
   In particular Wolf ruled that prosecutors were barred from using
any evidence gathered from the following ``bugs'' to obtain its
1995 racketeering indictment against Bulger and Flemmi:
</P>
<P>
   -- The 1981 bugging of the North End headquarters of Patriarca
family underboss Gennaro ``Jerry'' Angiulo.
</P>
<P>
   -- A 1984-85 bugging by the FBI and the US Drug Enforcement
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   -- The 1986-1987 bugging of Vanessa's Italian Food Shop in the
Prudential Center by the FBI and Massachusetts State Police.
</P>
<P>
   -- The infamous Mafia induction ceremony from Oct. 29, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said Flemmi was ``expressly and implicitly promised'' that
in exchange for his help on the Angiulo bugging that led to the
convictions of the Boston hierarchy of the mob, none of the
interceptions would be used against him.
</P>
<P>
   When the FBI enlisted Bulger and Flemmi to visit Angiulo's
headquarters, Bulger voiced concern that they might be killed and
both informants worried that the FBI might learn about criminal
wrongdoings by Bulger and Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   Those tapes did reveal bragging by Angiulo's consigliere, Ilario
Zannino, about the murders of three Boston brothers and how Salemme
and Flemmi had participated in them. The current racketeering
indictment charges Salemme and Flemmi with those murders.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi was among a group of informants who gave the FBI
information that led to the bugging in Medford in 1989, when four
aspiring mobsters -- including his co-defendant DeLuca -- took a
blood oath to join the Patriarca crime family.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said the FBI ``recklessly disregarded the government's
legal obligation of candor to the court'' when applying, along with
the DEA, to bug Bulger's car and apartment in nearby Quincy in 1984
and 1985 and failing to disclose he was an FBI informant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
