<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKING A FINE LINE ON MOB-FBI ARRANGEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was, in retrospect, a prescient moment.
</P>
<P>
   On January 6, 1997, the first day of hearings that would last 80
days and generate 17,000 pages of transcripts, US District Judge
Mark L. Wolf glanced down at the group of defense lawyers assembled
before him and warned that their prospects were ``not promising.''
</P>
<P>
   Others before them had failed to convince judges to dismiss
criminal charges because the government _ police officers, FBI
agents, federal prosecutors _ had acted outrageously in building
the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Wolf followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   While he hadn't considered that specific claim -- that
``outrageous government misconduct'' should result in the charges
being dismissed -- Wolf offered to consider that issue at further
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, defense lawyers will have a tough time clearing
that even higher bar, particularly if it means that career
criminals could walk free as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dismissing a case before the government has a chance to put on
evidence that a person has committed a crime is sort of like the
atomic bomb of judicial remedies,'' said David Rossman, professor
of law at Boston University Law School. ``And judges are about as
reluctant to put their fingers on the red button as presidents
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the legal landscape, some wondered why it had taken Wolf
so long to reach what seemed a foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was going to do nothing, he could have done that a year
ago,'' said Rosanna Cavallaro, an associate professor at Suffolk
University Law School. ``The fact that he took such care suggested
that he had in mind a bar that was achievable. He could have cut to
the chase much earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Others praised Wolf for not rushing to judgment, for
meticulously gathering evidence and holding hearings into
allegations that at first glance seemed fanciful: payoffs from
gangsters to an FBI supervisor, who in turn tipped off the
gangsters to wiretaps and investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Wolf has spent all the time in the world probing and
holding the government to close account,'' said Stanley Fisher, a
professor at BU Law School. ``He has been extremely meticulous and
fair . . . but you have to be extremely careful before you throw
out very serious charges against someone, much less someone who has
a history of very serious criminal behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   In refusing to dismiss extortion and racketeeering charges
against Winter Hill gangster Stephen Flemmi _ based on Flemmi's
claim that he was promised immunity from prosecution by the FBI _
Wolf walked a fine line. He acknowleded that Flemmi had been
promised ``protection'' by his FBI handlers and their superiors
during a 30-year span as an informant, but was not given formal
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI agents primarily responsible for dealing with Flemmi,
by word and deed, for thirty years, promised Flemmi protection in
return for his service as an informant,'' Wolf wrote. But, the
judge added, it wasn't the same as a formal immunity deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flemmi was not, however, explicitly or implicitly promised
immunity from prosecution,'' Wolf wrote. ``The term immunity was
never used.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Flemmi expected to be tipped off to investigations,
Wolf said, and the FBI ``performed its part of the bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   Cavallaro believes a case could be made that the bureau indeed
struck a formal immunity contract with its prized informants, based
on the sheer length of the relationship: the hundreds of meetings,
the dinner parties, the Christmas gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have thought at least some judge might be willing to
find that there was an agreement, based on the depth of these
contacts: the conversations, the contacts, the acknowledgment of
payoffs,'' she said. ``There is no written contract, but there is
an implied contract.''
</P>
<P>
   And, she added, ``I think there is law out there that you could
hang such a finding on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
