<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-RDP-ART-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE FLOYD TAKES AIM AT THE CAROLINAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Having already produced the greatest
evacuation in U.S. history, Hurricane Floyd skirted Florida and
Georgia on Wednesday and aimed itself directly at the low-lying
coastal border between the Carolinas, where its eye was expected to
come ashore early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although no widespread damage from hurricane force winds or
waves was yet reported on the East Coast, gusts exceeding 60 mph
began knocking down power lines and blowing billboards across
roadways on Wednesday evening along the South Carolina coast. And
with sustained winds of more than 40 mph, falling trees began
smashing windows and roofs at several houses northeast of
Charleston, according to the police. At least 86,000 homes were
without power in the Charleston region, and repair crews had no
plans to begin work until the storm passed.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, those homes were empty, as were all
others in dozens of counties from Jacksonville, Fla., to
Wilmington, N.C. Evacuation orders were in effect on Wednesday for
2.6 million people, and with the majority of those residents
obeying the orders, federal emergency officials said the evacuation
had now become the nation's largest.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 percent of Charleston's 87,000 residents had moved
inland, and Charleston County officials were amazed to report an 80
percent evacuation rate for the 230,000 people in the rest of the
county. The rate was far higher than for any previous hurricane,
and was attributed to the storm's enormous size and power, which by
evening appeared likely to spare the city. More than 90 percent of
neighboring Beaufort County was empty, according to county
officials, and 6,300 people were reported to be in shelters in a
three-county area.
</P>
<P>
   With the storm's eye moving to the north and east, residents of
North Carolina began adding to the exodus on Wednesday, filling up
hotels as far away as Alabama and Tennessee. The state government
ordered evacuations from the barrier islands around Wilmington, and
traffic began to clog the area just as heavy rains began falling at
midday. President Clinton declared coastal areas in the Carolinas
to be disaster areas, adding them to list of counties in Florida
and Georgia that were earlier made eligible for federal funds and
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Florida and Georgia at this point feel like
they've dodged a real bullet,'' said Richard Moore, the public
safety secretary for North Carolina. ``This thing is not going to
miss us.''
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation numbers were particularly high given the extreme
difficulty many residents had in leaving their homes on Tuesday,
because of massive congestion. South Carolina waited until
nightfall to make all lanes of the main interstate highway
westbound away from Charleston. Joseph P. Riley Jr., the mayor of
Charleston, charged the state with ``staggering incompetence,'' and
expressed concern that many of those who tried to leave wound up
returning, putting themselves in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Although Florida was spared the heaviest winds of the hurricane,
which weakened on Wednesday to 115 mph as the storm moved north,
areas around Daytona and Titusville reported numerous damaged roofs
and power lines. About 290,000 customers remained without
electrical power as many of the 1.3 million residents who followed
evacuation orders began returning to their homes. A popular pier in
Daytona collapsed when it was inundated by waves, but the state
insurance commissioner's office said there was no major damage
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   A 150-foot tugboat sank early Wednesday 345 miles off of
Jacksonville. The Coast Guard said that helicopters from the
aircraft carrier USS John F. Kennedy rescued three men, but the
other three crew members and their life raft were missing.
</P>
<P>
   The track of the storm left open the possibility that Floyd's
heavy winds and rain could continue north past the Carolinas into
Washington, D.C., New York City and even New England by the
weekend, even if it is not a hurricane at that point. Hurricane
force winds could reach the Chesapeake Bay by Thursday morning, and
federal emergency officials predicted significant tree damage in
Washington because of recent heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency told governors on
Wednesday afternoon that flooding as far north as New England
remains a high possibility through the rest of the week. Because so
much of the mid-Atlantic region is already saturated from Hurricane
Dennis, state agencies remain on high alert for inland river
flooding.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Already, an enormous swath of the country's East Coast was
virtually barren of visible human life. Charleston's historic
downtown was boarded up and deserted, the only movement the ominous
sway of trees and light poles. By 2 p.m., county police officers
had parked their cruisers and gone to shelters, and ambulances
stopped responding to any calls other than cardiac emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   In Horry County, the resort of Myrtle Beach had become an empty
stage set of abandoned hotels, seafood restaurants, waterslides and
miniature golf courses on Wednesday afternoon as the storm began to
produce significant swells in the Atlantic. Roads were empty and
gas stations, grocery stores and diners were boarded up and locked.
One facade of an old downtown building tumbled to the ground, and
police officers struggled to secure the exterior with plywood.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The usually animated beach town, a popular golf and retirement
destination, was projected to be very near the direct path of the
hurricane during the night, and though the storm's winds had
weakened to 115 mph from 140 mph the day before, officials were
still very worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in the path of some of the strongest winds and
largest storm surges,'' said Cheryl J. Henry, a county spokeswoman.
A curfew went into effect at 3 p.m., and similar restrictions were
imposed on Charleston after dark.
</P>
<P>
   Further north, in Wilmington, which has been affected by 16
hurricanes in the last decade, officials began preparing for the
serious flooding that occurred in storms such as Bertha, Bonnie and
Fran. Life jackets were placed on all fire trucks to assist in
water rescues. Having just gone through a weeklong pounding from
Hurricane Dennis, North Carolina officials predicted ruinous beach
erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to damage this beach like we have not seen since
Hazel,'' said Michael Stokes, a spokesman for Wrightsville Beach,
referring to the 1954 storm.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that it has been only a decade since Hurricane Hugo
came ashore in downtown Charleston, killing 13 people, producing a
17-foot surge, and costing South Carolina more than $6 billion,
city officials said they were amazed the state did not have a more
effective evacuation plan for the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Riley and other regional mayors were furious that the Department
of Transportation did not immediately allow fleeing residents to
use all lanes of I-26, as Georgia officials did with I-16 out of
Savannah. Some Charleston residents were on the road for 10 or 12
hours just to reach other parts of the small state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't rocket science,'' Riley said in an interview. ``What
the state Department of Transportation should have had in place and
could easily do is a system where you close lanes of traffic on one
part of the major highways and let people go out, because when you
have a major evacuation from a hurricane and you're requiring
people to leave, then that of a necessity means that people are not
coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hodges, who was blamed by most angry radio-show callers
for the snail's pace of the evacuation, said his transportation
advisers questioned the safety of reversing lanes on the
interstate, but said he finally overruled them at about 8 p.m.
Tuesday. Nonetheless, the issue was likely to remain a political
blow for him _ one handmade sign on a I-26 overpass read, ``Flog
Hodges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
