<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-INTERNET16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web provides instant updates on Floyd
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Who cares whether or not it's raining in Boise?''
sighed South Florida resident Linda Twersky while watching The
Weather Channel on Tuesday night. ``Somebody tell me if my house is
going to be oceanfront property in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   In the age of the Internet, television coverage often isn't
focused enough, specific enough or quick enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The personalization of the Web is what makes is work,'' said
Charlene Li, a senior analyst with Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   Twersky, like many residents of Florida, Georgia and South
Carolina, spent most of Tuesday night logging onto the Web and
watching in wonder as the gigantic multicolored radar swirl of
Hurricane Floyd moved toward the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   So did many other weather watchers, according to Li. ``It's so
annoying to wait for the media to come around for the news you
want,'' she said. ``It's insulting to have to wait eight minutes
for the next weather report. We've become used to having all this
information at our fingertips.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web is a great resource tool, Li said, because it allows
users to pinpoint the exact information they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want a lot more detail than just the weather report,''
added Lelia Lee, brand manager for The Weather Channel's Web site,
weather.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the latest information continuously updated.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather.com has a banner across the top of the page notifying
users it is in severe weather mode, meaning it's top priority is on
covering the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Weather was clearly on the minds of many Web surfers _ the site
recorded 23.5 million page views on Tuesday, setting an all-time
record for the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``In severe weather mode, we go in and strip anything that may
cause a slower download,'' she said. ``We take out some of the
graphics and other images. We show one really great map on the home
page and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the demand for instant information seems to overwhelm even
the best-prepared sites. Weather.com was ready to accommodate tens
of millions of users, but for many, pages were still slow to load
and at times the site was tough to access.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said the Web is a perfect place to collect information to
help users cope with weather emergencies. The site includes a
weather news section that's updated hourly and a section on weather
safety called Project Safe Side, which is done in conjunction with
the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Interactivity and exchange of information between the sites and
users is also key. Lee said she was surprised by the users'
response to the on-camera meteorologists' call for viewers to send
in e-mails to be read on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised that people were using their laptops to get
information, and there were lots of people from the Carolina coast
looking for information and updates. That's what's fantastic about
the Web,'' she said. ``You can serve up all kinds of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather.com will probably always be the first destination when
weather emergencies arise. Yahoo!'s weather section
(weather.yahoo.com) has a special storm section with huge radar
maps, storm tracking and bulletins from the National Weather
Service in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   As Yahoo! shifts away from being simply a search engine to being
a one-stop source of news and information, it becomes more valuable
to Web surfers who want as much news as they can find on a
particular topic conveniently located in one place.
</P>
<P>
   During a weather emergency, people not only want to see the path
of the storm, but find out what they should be doing to prepare for
it. The ABCNews.com site (www.abcnews.com) has comprehensive
coverage on the hurricane including a section called ``Help for
Hurricane-Hampered Travellers.'' The area offers tips and advice
for stranded vacationers, flight cancellations and updates from the
Florida, North Carolina and South Carolina tourism boards.
</P>
<P>
   While the Web can provide breaking information on a variety of
weather-related subjects, Forrester's Li pointed out that right now
the Web still isn't as portable as the old-fashioned transistor
radio. ``But there are advances in wireless communication that will
change this,'' she said. ``The fact is people want constant
updates. Broadcast is great for reaching all the masses, but it's
not personalized enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
