<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-TESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR NOT APOLOGETIC FOR MISTAKEN SUMMER-SCHOOL ASSIGNMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As school officials revised the number of students
mistakenly assigned to summer school upward to 8,500, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Board of Education officials argued Wednesday that
parents of those children should be grateful for the mixup because
the faltering children were given a chance at more schooling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a parent of one of the children, I would say, `Thank
you for having the child in summer school' because the child got
more education,'' the mayor said at a City Hall news conference.
``You've got to understand, the alleged error is an error with the
children at the lowest end of the score.'' He added, ``They are
children who, next year, when the standards are just a little bit
higher, would not be promoted. So, these are children very much in
need of additional educational help.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who had strongly pushed the summer school program as
a way of getting tough with failing students, spoke in response to
questions about the revelations by Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew
that thousands of students in the third and sixth grades were
erroneously required to attend summer school because of a scoring
mistake by CTB/McGraw-Hill, the Monterey, Calif., standardized
testing company. As a result of that error, hundreds of students
were forced to change vacation plans or compelled to sit in often
sweltering classrooms. The board on Wednesday raised the figure of
mistakenly assigned students to 8,500 _ far more than the 2,000 to
3,000 first indicated by school officials.
</P>
<P>
   But the board tried Wednesday to find a silver lining in the
situation. Recalculating reading scores to compensate for the
scoring error showed that test scores last spring for the school
system had sharply improved, not remained flat as was first
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The board said that 48.5 percent of students _ not 44.6 percent,
as previously reported _ scored at or above the national average.
With the statistical adjustment the board uses to allow for
comparisons with previous years _ the 1999 test was much different
from previous years _ scores improved by 4.9 percent over 1998, the
board said.
</P>
<P>
   The flawed test results, announced last June, were one of the
grimmest chapters in Crew's tenure, creating the impression that
Crew himself, who had put a high focus on literacy, was
ineffective. At the time, Crew said he was determined ``not to make
excuses'' and vowed to take strong action to overhaul the system.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, many of those actions _ from removing
superintendents to sending children to summer school _ turned out
to be based to a considerable extent on a fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see no reason even amidst the turbulence to abandon the
standards,'' Crew said before a meeting Wednesday of the Board of
Education at its Brooklyn headquarters, in which he and the board
members expressed both anger at the testing company mistakes and
pride in the new results. ``I don't think we made a mistake here at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   David Taggart, the president of CTB/McGraw-Hill, his voice
shaking, told Crew and the board that the company believed the new
test results to be valid. ``Maybe the word apology isn't enough,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Crew, who agreed with the mayor's assessment, said he would
advance all students who passed the spring exam, regardless of
their summer school performance, though he would encourage the
parents of borderline students to allow their children to be
retained.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants parents to think that ```I know my kid was
wrongly placed in summer school but, heck, I just know he or she is
not doing well enough yet to handle the fourth grade.' I want that
conversation to be had. But I also believe they are eligible for
promotion under the rules. Fair is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, just one week into the new school year, he predicted
confusion if many kids are moved around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it will be very disruptive and and I don't like to
do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The testing mistake elicited a range of emotion among school
officials, parents and students.
</P>
<P>
   Indira Baptise, whose son, Colin Bunbury, was promoted to the
fourth grade at Public School 41 in Brooklyn after attending summer
school there, said summer school got him so interested in reading
that he goes to the library after school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not mind him doing the extra work because he needed it,''
Ms. Baptise said. ``But I am upset that I sent him to school all
year long and he could not pass all the things he had to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town, outside a Bronx elementary school, Guillermo Rosado
offered a different view as he picked up his stepson, David, who
passed summer school and is now in the fourth grade at Public
School 69.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he didn't have to go to summer school we could have gone to
Florida as we planned,'' Rosado said. ``This definitely affected
our summer. We were going to go visit my mother and do all the
tourist things in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   David, for his part, did not seem to mind. ``I liked summer
school,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There was confusion Wednesday among schools administrators and
parents about what the revised scores may mean.
</P>
<P>
   The board began to focus in on the actual number affected by the
McGraw Hill miscalculation and found it was far larger than at
first believed. Board officials said that of the students
mistakenly assigned to summer school, more than 5,000 went and
passed a second test. But almost 3,500, the board said, either
never showed up for summer school or failed the second test by
scoring below the 15th percentile on a national curve.
</P>
<P>
   Those students will be promoted unless their parents request
they not be, Crew said.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake occurred through a miscalculation of the percentile
score that showed how the students compared to a national sample of
children across the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
