<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLFB-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRINGTON'S SPECIAL TREATMENT DOESN'T WASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's barely the middle of September, but Penn State's LaVar
Arrington has basically wrapped up the Butkus Award, given to the
nation's outstanding linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   If voters seek a reason to wait before crowning Arrington,
though, they should remember the disgraceful way Arrington played
in last week's victory over Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington drew two personal-foul penalties for knocking Pitt
punter Greg DeBolt down after punts and violently keeping him on
the ground. He wasn't ejected because one was a dead-ball penalty _
and because he's LeVar Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   If he were playing for Miami or Florida State, Arrington would
have been quickly tossed from the game for his blatant attacks on
the punter.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Arrington professed ignorance over the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my job,'' Arrington said. ``That's what we were
planning on doing all week. I was just playing. I'm not mad at the
call. I went over to the officials and apologized if I did anything
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Awfully noble, don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   But hey, this is State College, Pa., so let's see what demigod
Joe Paterno thought of the whole mess.
</P>
<P>
   Paterno said he hasn't looked at the special-teams game film. He
said he routinely watches only the offensive and defensive plays.
That's the slickest dodge Paterno has made in years, but when
gently pressed, he finally admitted that Arrington was out of line,
sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to LaVar about it,'' Paterno said. ``His job is to
make sure the punter punts the ball and then block him. If he did
anything beyond that, he's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami quarterback Kenny Kelly, who will face Arrington this
week, said he won't accept similar treatment during their game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a punter,'' Kelly said, ``but my reaction is that's
the last thing I'll put up with.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Lie of the week: In what could be a fixture in this column,
Ohio State coach John Cooper was once again caught lying to
reporters. This time, it was regarding his decision to insert
quarterback Steve Bellisari against UCLA immediately after
quarterback Austin Moherman led the Buckeyes to a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any kind of preconceived plan where we said,
`We're going to put this guy in after the third series,' '' Cooper
said. ``I think that would be a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Bellisari let slip Monday that quarterbacks coach Tim Salem told
him the day before the UCLA game he would be going in on the fourth
series.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mental warfare: Why did Baylor inexplicably go for a
touchdown with eight seconds left and the ball at the 8-yard line
against UNLV, which led to a fumble that Rebels defensive back
Kevin Thomas returned 99 yards for a touchdown and a 27-24 victory?
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of speculation around Baylor that coach Kevin
Steele was going for an in-your-face touchdown to punish Rebels
coach John Robinson for his pregame comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play Baylor, it's always a physical game. But they
always do something to screw things up,'' Robinson said. ``That's
been the history of their program.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele denied he was trying to teach Robinson a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a one-in-a-million play and we got burned,'' Steele
said. ``It was a safe play. We were simply trying to create an
attitude about lining up and getting after people.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Who's at home? When Idaho plays at Washington State on
Saturday, it will technically be a road game for the Cougars as the
Vandals are borrowing Martin Stadium this year in an attempt to
meet NCAA-attendance standards in order to become a Division I-A
program.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State will comply with the charade by wearing its
white road jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, we will not be giving up too much,''
Washington State coach Mike Price said. ``We've got our same seats,
our same sideline, our same locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   And same crummy team?
</P>
<P>
   __ Pro placement: Entering this season, Colorado, Texas A&AMP;M and
Nebraska had 32 players each on NFL rosters, best among Big 12
schools. Next were Oklahoma (18), Texas (16) and Oklahoma State
(14).
</P>
<P>
   __ Media circus: Oregon coach Mike Bellotti banned a reporter
from practices because the journalist, who works for a publication
devoted to covering Oregon sports, posted a report on the Internet
that the coach thought gave away some secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The report, posted on the Fighting Ducks Review Web Site on Aug.
31, discussed some new offensive sets the Ducks ran through in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Bellotti became aware of the so-called breach following the
27-20 loss at Michigan State. Apparently, a Michigan State
assistant mentioned the Internet report to an Oregon assistant
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Bellotti said, making it clear that he didn't
think the report cost Oregon the game, but adding, ``Who's to know
if they would be prepared, but certainly now we know they were
prepared for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   __ League expansion: Conference USA could offer TCU and SMU
invitations to join the league this week.
</P>
<P>
   But the schools might not accept if their admittance fees are
too high or if they face the 2000 season as independents if they
are kicked out of the Western Athletic Conference after this year.
</P>
<P>
   There is also resistance from Louisville, DePaul, Saint Louis,
Cincinnati and Marquette, who are against adding the schools
because they would give the league 14 schools that play basketball
(Army and East Carolina are members of C-USA in football only).
</P>
<P>
   __ Add releaguing: ACC presidents met in Tallahassee this week,
and expansion was again one of the topics. The idea of adding Miami
as a 10th member will not die, even though several schools are
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The schools that do not like the idea want to preserve the
tradition that every football team plays every conference opponent.
And some would suffer significant financial losses from a smaller
allotment of tickets for the ACC men's basketball tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
