<HEADER>
A3531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-TOWER-ART-2TAKE     09-15 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TOWER-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS REOPENS LANDMARK THAT SNIPER USED IN 1966 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There are two buildings that lord over this
city, the state Capitol and the Tower, and officials at the
University of Texas like to point out that the Tower stands two
feet higher. On special occasions, such as a celebration of a
championship football season, the limestone structure is
illuminated in school colors and transformed into an orange torch
that glows above the campus.
</P>
<P>
   But if, as officials say, the Tower symbolizes the university's
heart and its aspirations, it is also tainted by tragedy _ one that
the university hoped would be finally put to rest as the Tower's
observation deck reopened Wednesday for the first time in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 1, 1966, a student, Charles Whitman, dragged a foot
locker filled with hunting rifles onto the Tower's observation deck
and fired at people below as if they were deer, killing 14 and
wounding 31. His rampage lasted 96 minutes, but has reverberated
for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as shootings at schools and office buildings occur with
disturbing frequency, the Whitman incident is mostly a grim
historic footnote. But in the 1960s, it helped define the decade
and further shattered the nation's sense of well being. If the
assassination of John F. Kennedy proved that even a president could
be killed, the Whitman attack marked a new and different terror _
that anyone anywhere could be killed at random, and by an Eagle
Scout, no less.
</P>
<P>
   ``People essentially said, `Don't ask about it. Please don't ask
about it,' '' said Dr. Kenneth Foote, a geography professor at the
university since 1982, recalling attitudes on campus about the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   After four other people jumped from the Tower, the last in 1974,
the stain of death became too great and the university closed the
observation deck. Wednesday, morning, in marking the university's
116th birthday, university president Larry Faulkner stepped onto
the deck and declared it reopened.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Faulkner noted that a generation of students not
yet born in Whitman's era wanted to enjoy the majestic views of
central Texas. But for an older generation of Texans, Faulkner's
gesture meant finally reclaiming the University's most beloved
symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time for this university to move on and accept
the history that goes with this building and fully embrace the
positives,'' Faulkner said. Had he looked up, Faulkner could have
seen dark spots still marking where bullets had struck the stone.
</P>
<P>
   In reopening the deck at the request of student groups, Faulkner
faced skeptics who feared the Tower could again become a magnet for
suicides or a perch for a sniper. A stainless steel lattice was
erected to prevent jumpers and security checkpoints were built as
safeguards against weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lives of a lot of the survivors were terribly disturbed by
what happened,'' said Dr. Teresa Sullivan, the university's vice
president and graduate dean. ``We've still got people who can't
walk across the campus without looking over their shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 1, the 33rd anniversary of the shootings, university
officials dedicated a garden at the foot of the Tower to the memory
of the victims. Foote, who has written extensively about places
marred by violence, said that a sense of shame has often prevented
communities from publicly acknowledging heinous acts. He noted that
Salem, Mass., did not erect a memorial to the town's famous witch
trials for 300 years. Now, he said, events like the Oklahoma City
bombing or the Littleton, Colo., school shooting have changed
attitudes about how communities should deal with public grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing here is an attempt to come to terms with the
event,'' Foote said.
</P>
<P>
   Completed in 1937, the Tower is an architectural landmark, a
30-story beacon whose image is embossed on the university's logo.
Erected atop the central Main Building, the Tower has always served
as office space. In years past, students could ride the small
elevators to the 27th floor, then walk up a narrow stairwell to the
observation deck for a view that easily inspired wonder.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``That first morning,'' wrote the late Willie Morris in his
memoir, ``North Toward Home,'' reminiscing about his student days
in the 1950s, ``I took the elevator to the top, and looked out on
those majestic purple hills to the west, changing to lighter shades
of blue or a deeper purple as wisps of autumn clouds drifted around
the sun; this, they would tell me, was the Great Balconies Divide,
where the South ended and the West began.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, more than anyone or anything, shattered this serene
image.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Whitman was a married, 25-year-old ex-marine who was
studying architectural engineering. Shortly before noon on Aug. 1,
he carried a cache of weapons in his military foot locker up to the
deck. He killed a receptionist with the butt of his rifle, then
shot two tourists before barricading the deck.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Lavergne, author of ``A Sniper in the Tower,'' a
non-fiction account of the incident, said the entire campus lay
unaware below. Whitman had carried sandwiches, toilet paper and a
can of Spam, and as he took aim through his rifle scope, he fired
his first shot directly through the abdomen of a woman who was
eight months pregnant. When the unborn child's father bent over in
horror, Whitman killed him. The baby died, too, though the mother
survived.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Citizens rushed to the scene with hunting rifles and began
firing back as police officers armed with handguns were largely
helpless. Lavergne said the lessons of the Whitman case prompted
many police departments to develop the first SWAT teams. Until a
police officer finally broke through the barricade and killed him,
Whitman had been almost unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings horrified the nation. A television reporter, Neal
Spelce, broadcast a primitive audio feed to all three national
networks, foreshadowing today's all-encompassing media coverage of
such crimes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``White middle-class America was shocked,'' said Dr. Rosa
Eberly, an assistant professor of rhetoric who has taught a course
on the Whitman attack and Wednesday participated with Foote in a
symposium on the Tower. ``Whitman was the smiling Eagle Scout.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's motive remains in dispute. Police discovered that he
had killed both his mother and his wife the night before the
shootings to spare them ``the shame'' for what he planned to do. He
had suffered headaches, and had even fantasized about killing
people from the Tower to a psychiatrist, who did not believe he
would do it. He left a note asking that an autopsy be performed on
his body to ``see if there is any mental disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy revealed a pecan-sized tumor in his brain, but
Lavergne said doctors disputed the possibility that it caused his
behavior. Other theories speculate that Whitman wanted to embarrass
his father or that he was under the influence of amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Without a concrete explanation and with university officials
long loath to discuss the attack, Dr. Eberly said, Whitman became a
minor cultural anti-hero. Country music singer Kinky Friedman
wrote, ``The Ballad of Charles Whitman,'' with the famous line,
``There was a rumor about a tumor.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many of today's students, Whitman is little more than a
vague figure. Adriana Mendoza, a 19-year-old sophomore from El
Paso, said she learned about the shootings this summer from a
television news program. Sitting on the grass beneath the Tower
this week, she said she wanted to go to the top, but she also
wanted assurances that she would be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should be able to experience it and be safe when we
experience it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The first public visits will occur Thursday. More than 500
people have booked reservations, nearly selling out the first two
weeks. Belongings must be left downstairs, and each group will be
escorted by an armed campus police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No foot lockers are going to go back up to the Tower again,''
said Dr. Sullivan, the graduate dean.
</P>
<P>
   Noting what she hopes are positive results from the reopening,
she added, ``One of the best ways we can say we are open for
business for all of you is to open the Tower. It's just too
important of a symbol of who we are.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
