</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLATION IS MISSING DESPITE FOUR YEARS OF BOOM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The boom that has given such a strong lift to the U.S. economy
is four years old this quarter, but the much anticipated rise in
the inflation rate, which so often mars prosperous times, has
failed once again to make an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index rose in August by just 0.3 percent, the
Labor Department reported Wednesday. A spike in gasoline prices
accounted for most of the increase. Prices held pretty steady
otherwise, as they have month after month.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding food and energy, which tend to spike up in price and
then fall back, the so-called core inflation rate rose only 0.1
percent in August and 1.9 percent over the last year _ the lowest
yearlong rate in months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that appears to be going up in price on a
consistent basis,'' said Patrick Jackman, a senior economist at the
Labor Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics, who helps to
calculate the monthly CPI.
</P>
<P>
   By the standards of the last 25 years, mild inflation after so
many years of strong growth is an anomaly. Stock traders and
investors, uncertain how to interpret the low August inflation
rate, responded to the CPI report by driving up the Dow Jones
industrial average by more than 80 points in early trading, then
letting it fall by 108.91 points, to close at 10,801.42.
</P>
<P>
   The early run-up in stock prices suggested that Wall Street
initially interpreted the mild inflation number as reducing the
odds that the Federal Reserve's policy-makers would raise interest
rates at their Oct. 5 meeting. Higher rates tend to drive investors
out of stocks. And then later in the day, the initial
interpretation seemed to be reversed _ perhaps because of Tuesday's
report that retail sales had jumped in August. People are still
buying with abandon, which is potentially inflationary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are talking a big rise in consumer spending this year,''
said Donald Ratajczak, director of the Economic Forecasting Center
at Georgia State University. ``The Fed has to slow that down.''
</P>
<P>
   The mild CPI report is the last major economic statistic to be
released before the October Fed meeting. And with each month of
subdued inflation, despite the robust economy and the heavy
consumer spending, the Fed's top officials appear to be coming to
the conclusion that the economy has changed. The new view: Stronger
economic growth is possible without rising inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a general consensus within the Fed, between the hawks
and the doves, that you have this new higher speed limit on
economic growth,'' said David Jones, chief economist at Aubrey G.
Lanston &AMP; Co., a Wall Street firm.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Fed's top officials appear to be demonstrating a willingness
to tolerate an economy that grows at an annual rate of 3 percent,
or even a bit more. That is still not as much as the actual growth
over the last four years, far and away the strongest of the current
expansion. The growth since late 1995 has averaged 3.76 percent
annually. But the 3 percent is considerably above the 2 percent to
2.25 percent that the Fed in the mid-1990s considered the upper
limit on growth before inflation would inevitably accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, the Fed responded with higher rates to slow
growth, often acting ``pre-emptively'' before inflation actually
accelerated. Now the response is less aggressive. A quarter point
increase in short-term rates at the last Fed meeting, on Aug. 24,
came with the statement that the risk of rising inflation ``should
markedly diminish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed is sort of playing it by ear,'' said William Dudley,
director of domestic economic research at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve officials appear to increasingly accept the view
that the supply of goods and services, in this country and the rest
of the world, exceeds the demand and will most likely continue to
do so for months to come, eliminating inflationary shortages. Then,
too, a lower unemployment rate is possible without provoking
inflationary wage demands. And the productivity growth rate _
measuring the rising output of a worker for each hour on the job _
has gone to a higher level, if not permanently then for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
   ``An unanticipated increase in the rate of growth of
productivity is an example of a favorable supply shock, temporarily
lowering inflation,'' Lawrence H. Meyer, a Fed governor, said in a
recent speech.
</P>
<P>
   Measurement changes also play a role. Even with energy and food
included, the CPI has risen by only 2.3 percent for the 12-month
period ending with August. But changes in the way the CPI is
calculated, to improve accuracy, have reduced the CPI by
four-tenths of a percentage point a year since 1995. If the old
practices were still used, the 12-month average would be 2.7
percent, not 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other than price spikes for gasoline and for citrus
fruit, the August report was notably weak. Prices for new cars and
trucks fell. So did apparel prices, computer prices and airline
fares, thanks to discounting. Health care costs have plateaued
since last summer at an annual increase of 3.4 percent, less than
forecasters had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rising home prices, shelter costs were up 0.2 percent in
August and only 2.2 percent over the last 12 months. And while
gasoline prices rose 5.6 percent in August and citrus prices by 4.8
percent, both seem likely to increase by smaller amounts in
September, according to various estimates. Tobacco prices, however,
which had fallen by 1.3 percent in August, are expected to spike
upward this month as a result of price increases announced by the
cigarette companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
