<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-TAX-2TAKES(T     09-15 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAX-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS MAKES FINAL PUSH ON TAX CUT BILL 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in Congress paid their last respects
Wednesday to their cherished $792 billion tax-cutting bill, then
sent it to the White House for a certain veto by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At successive campaign-style events on Capitol Hill, Republicans
said sending a portion of excess government revenues back to
taxpayers was only fair, and Democrats said the plan would require
deep cuts in essential government services while risking the
country's economic health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know this is dead on arrival at the White
House,'' said Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The initial round in the battle over how to apportion the
projected federal budget surplus will thus go to Clinton, who says
the money the Republican majority in Congress wants to use for its
tax cut over the next 10 years should be split among spending
programs, debt reduction and a much smaller tax cut. Clinton, who
is scheduled to return to Washington early Thursday from a trip to
New Zealand, is expected to veto the tax bill within days if not
hours of arriving home.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans remain a bit bewildered as to why their tax cut _
the largest to pass Congress since 1981 _ generated relatively
little public enthusiasm. But they have decided to cut their losses
and move away from the tax-cut fight to what they consider firmer
ground, their effort to hold the line on government spending.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the Republicans are trying to leave open the
long-range question of what to do with the $3 trillion surplus
expected to accumulate over the next decade, hoping they can work
that out with a Republican president in a year and a half. Instead,
they are now focusing on passing the spending bills needed to run
the government in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, and saying they
are uninterested in negotiating a compromise with the White House
that would trade a smaller tax cut over the long run for additional
spending on Democratic priorities next year.
</P>
<P>
   Passing the spending bills is a prosaic task, and the focus on
doing so illustrates how the Republicans have scaled back their
agenda in the face of Clinton's opposition since taking control of
Congress in the 1994 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a job that Republicans believe will resonate
politically because it will revolve around the sensitive issue of
dipping into next year's projected surplus of $161 billion,
especially the $147 billion portion generated by excess Social
Security revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are still a long way from making their numbers add
up, Republicans say they can finance the government's operations
next year without dipping into Social Security. To do so,
Republicans will have to resort to an array of budget gimmicks and
use the $14 billion surplus expected to be generated next year by
general tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they are basically daring Clinton to prove he can do any
better, asserting that for the White House to make good on its
promises to spend more on education, health, the environment and
other areas would require one of two politically unacceptable
steps: raising taxes or raiding Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties for decades have routinely spent payroll tax
revenues earmarked to pay future Social Security benefits, simply
issuing government IOU's to Social Security in return. But with the
budget surplus swelling, Republicans and Democrats alike have
pledged to keep their hands off the Social Security money, in
effect designating that it be used to reduce the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say right now that we will not allow this president to
spend the Social Security trust fund dollars,'' said Sen. Trent
Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they can make their budget add up
without touching Social Security, albeit through steps like an
increase in tobacco taxes that Republicans say they will never
accept. White House officials are primarily interested in luring or
pressuring Republicans to come to the negotiating table to take up
not just next year's spending bills, but a broader agenda of issues
including Social Security, Medicare, reducing the national debt and
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we are going to reject this partisan, fictional
budget,'' Gore told the Democrats' rally on Capitol Hill. ``But in
the aftermath of its rejection, we want them to come back and work
out a reasonable solution so that we can avoid the kind of train
wreck that they have headed us toward.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the best forum for compromise may
prove to be the Senate Finance Committee, which is developing
legislation to deal with Medicare's long-term financial problems
and to add a prescription drug benefit to the program. The
committee is one of the few in Congress over the last few years to
have a record of bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Senate Finance Committee were to undertake Medicare in
a serious way,'' said Jacob J. Lew, the director of the White
House's Office of Management and Budget, ``one thing could lead to
another in ways that make it too soon to rule out having a broader,
more comprehensive set of outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There is also talk among Republicans of trying to use a routine
tax bill that is likely to come up for consideration in the next
few months as a vehicle to resuscitate some of the more popular
provisions of the much larger bill Clinton is about to veto, such
as a reduction in the so-called marriage penalty that hurts many
two-income couples. The routine bill would extend expiring tax
provisions like a research tax credit for business.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said he was not yet sure whether there was any chance of
getting a substantial tax cut signed into law this year.
</P>
<P>
   But like other Republicans, many of whom feel they have come out
second best in budget negotiations with Clinton over the last few
years, Archer said he was suspicious that the White House would
insist on gutting the ideological core of the Republican tax plan
to get a deal by emphasizing income redistribution over tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm concerned about is that if the White House gets into
a negotiating mode with us,'' Archer said in an interview, ``they
will want to give tax relief to people who don't pay any taxes.
That runs against what we're trying to do, which is giving a refund
to the people who are overpaying what the government needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer said Republicans should be proud of having passed a big
tax bill, and of ``stemming the tide of the aggressive left.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans said they were nervous about assuming that
reaching a standoff with Clinton on taxes and spending amounts to
an accomplishment that voters will reward in next year's
congressional elections, in which control of the House will be up
for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is a similar debate under way among Democrats in Congress
and within the White House, with opinion divided about the relative
merits of sticking to a defensive strategy of blocking Republican
initiatives and of seeking progress through compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are also gauging the risks that the fiscal standoff
could escalate into a conflict that leads to a shutdown of parts of
the federal government, as happened during a similar showdown in
1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   G. William Hoagland, staff director of the Senate Budget
Committee, said that in the context of a $1.7 trillion federal
budget there was relatively little money separating the two parties
in their dispute over the spending bills and that the chance of a
government shutdown was low.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanley E. Collender, managing director of the
Fleischman-Hillard federal budget consulting group, said that the
difficulty Republicans have had in holding together their slim
majority in the House made the outlook risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likelihood of a train wreck is not terrific,'' Collender
said, ``but an accident is much more likely to happen than people
are willing to admit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
