<HEADLINE>
PRICES OF TREASURIES REBOUND AS FEARS OF RATE INCREASE EASE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities rebounded somewhat on Wednesday
from their previous day's losses after tame consumer price data
eased investor fears that the Federal Reserve would raise
short-term interest rates again at its monetary policy meeting next
month.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day the 30-year bellweather Treasury bond was up
8/32, to a price of 100 11/32, pushing its yield, which moves in
the opposite direction, down to 6.10 percent, from 6.12 percent on
Tuesday. Traders said early sharp gains were erased, when the
dollar dropped against the yen and the euro in currency trading,
sapping foreign investors' demand for Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   A weakening dollar makes foreign investors cautious about owning
American securities because they could lose money when they convert
from dollars into their own currencies.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the core rate of the August Consumer Price Index
showed a lower-than-forecast 0.1 percent gain from July, while the
overall CPI rose 0.3 percent in August, following a similar rise in
July. Ballooning energy prices fueled the increases in both months.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation data are producing mixed signals, according to
some economists, as the overall CPI is slowly but steadily inching
upward on a trend basis, while at the same time the core rate,
which excludes food and energy, continues to creep downward.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management
said, ``Without question, the overall strength of the economy,
particularly the recent statistics for consumer spending, coupled
with the slowing trend in the CPI must be causing some dismay for
the preemptive-minded Fed committee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' he added, ``relatively benign wage
pressures and favorable core inflation trends certainly provide the
Fed with latitude to maintain its current policy stance.'' In
addition, Fine said, ``the usually prescient Treasury bond market
does not seem to be signaling an imminent Fed tightening, although
upcoming economic data releases between now and Oct. 5 that could
influence the FOMC decision process make this a fluid situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All things considered, another round of tightening seems
likely before the year is out, with the timing of the movement yet
to be determined,'' said Fine. ``Indeed, history shows that those
who ignore energy prices and their impact on overall inflation do
so at their own risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, strong gains were posted by corporate bonds, agencies
and other spread products that are priced off government bond
yields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
