<SLUG> BC-CAR-PETIT-LEMANS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Connell hits LeMans stride
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service ATLANTA _ The record 50 cars lining up
<TEXT>
for Saturday's Petit Le Mans will be a severe traffic jam.
<P>
   Maybe Panoz driver Johnny O'Connell, who lives 15 minutes away
in Flowery Branch, and his teammates will benefit from having to
drive in Atlanta traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be quite the show, especially with all the
traffic,'' O'Connell said. ``That's going to be the determining
factor to me, whose car is best in traffic, who can go through 10
hours without having a wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell is an Indy 500 veteran, a driver now in the top five
of the American Le Mans Series' 80 prototype drivers, a potential
champion with 20 years of experience at age 37.
</P>
<P>
   But he's had an up-and-down career. He won at Sebring in 1994;
was on A.J. Foyt's IRL team in 1997; ran as high as eighth in the
1996 Indy 500 before his car failed with fuel pump problems; and
won the ALMS race at Mosport this year.
</P>
<P>
   He also wiped out a Panoz GTR-1 during Petit Le Mans qualifying
last year when he hit an oil slick; had a debilitating injury
during the 1997 Indy 500 qualifications; and lost his job with
Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the points race indicates, O'Connell is on a roll coming
into Saturday's race.
</P>
<P>
   After winning Mosport, he and co-driver Jan Magnusson of
Denmark, who is tied with O'Connell in points, have finished third
at Sears Point and Portland. Their consistency is a surprise,
because they're driving a car so new that it didn't exist when
Sebring ran in March.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiled at the ALMS race April 18 at Road Atlanta, the Panoz
Roadster S wowed the crowd and scared the competition by starting
35th and finishing fifth, a feat equaled only by the race-winning
MKIII Riley &AMP; Scott Judd, which started 34th.
</P>
<P>
   The Panoz Roadster S, a front-engined upstart, turned in the
third-fastest speed in Le Mans qualifying. The two Panoz entries
finished eighth and 11th in the race, another surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans called the old Panoz GTR-1 ``The Batmobile.''. They'll
have to call the new Roadster S a ``clown's shoe.''
</P>
<P>
   Black, wide and low with front fenders rising out of the body
and a small cockpit way in back, it does look odd next to the
typical mid- or rear-engined LMP, but it's a screamer.
</P>
<P>
   They've done such a huge redesign,'' O'Connell said. ``Other
than the engine in front and the gear box in the back, it's all
new. It has transformed the car and it's much nicer to drive now.
It's such a well-behaved car.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
