<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTL-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    European underdogs rising
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The European Champions League was expanded to 32 teams
to help the big boys ensure a place in the first-round draw, but a
surprising batch of opening-week results has given the underdogs
plenty of hope for further upsets.
</P>
<P>
   Late rallies by Barcelona and Real Madrid prevented certain
losses, and defending champion Manchester United was held to a
scoreless draw at home.
</P>
<P>
   In the most dramatic contest, goals in the 86th minute by
Abelardo Fernandez and three minutes into injury time by Dani
lifted Barca to a 2-1 win over AIK Stockholm in Group B Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   United, missing eight players because of injury, was drawn 0-0
at Old Trafford on Tuesday by Croatia Zagreb in Group D. Bayern
Munich, last year's runner-up, got two goals from Paulo Sergio,
including the winner in the 69th minute, to beat PSV Eindhoven 2-1
in Group F. NK Maribor of Slovenia downed Dynamo Kyiv, a
semifinalist last year, by a 1-0 count in Group A.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Real Madrid finished with a 3-3 draw against Olympiakos
thanks to an 80th-minute strike by Raul Gonzalez in Group E, while
a penalty kick by Gheorghe Hagi with four minutes left gave Turkish
champions Galatasaray a 2-2 Group H draw at Hertha Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Two highly anticipated games didn't live up to the billing. In
Florence, Arsenal's Nwankwo Kanu attempted a weak penalty kick late
that Fiorentina keeper Francesco Toldo saved easily for a 0-0 Group
B draw. Chelsea dominated its first match in the Champions League,
vs. AC Milan in London, but settled for another 0-0 draw in Group
H.
</P>
<P>
   UEFA Cup: Parma to defend
</P>
<P>
   After elimination from Champions League qualifying, Parma today
begins its reign as champion of the UEFA Cup _ think of it as
European soccer's version of basketball's NIT tournament, only
twice as big and just as meaningless. Parma plays at home against
Ukrainian side Krivbas in the first leg of a first-round series.
The UEFA Cup, which absorbed the now-defunct Cup Winners Cup,
features 96 teams and has been won by Italian clubs six of the last
seven years. In Sofia, Bulgaria, on Tuesday, Montpellier won 1-0
over Crvena of Yugoslavia. Also on Tuesday, Leeds beat Partizan
Belgrade 3-1 in a match in Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: America tops Chivas
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Blanco had both goals as Club America bested Chivas
2-0 Sunday in the first major clash of the Invierno season. Blanco
leads the league with six goals in five games. The loss was the
first for Chivas, who host Toros Neza on Sunday seeking to keep
pace in Group 4 with leaders Necaxa, which romped over UAG 4-2.
Sergio Vazquez and Agustin Delgado had two goals each for the
winners, who have a league-high 13 points.... Struggling Cruz Azul
earned its first victory of the season in a 3-0 blanking of
Morelia.... Defending Verano champion Toluca surprisingly was tied
by Puebla 0-0 but still leads Group 1 by four points.... Atlas
remained tied with America at the top of Group 3 by routing Celaya
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   South America: Baring all
</P>
<P>
   Brazil: Sao Paulo club officials are unamused that goalkeeper
Roger is the current nude centerfold spread in G Magazine, a
national gay-men's glossy. He's not the first Brazilian league star
to pose for the publication.... Argentina: San Lorenzo stayed atop
the Apertura, but Boca Juniors kept pace with a 2-0 win over Ferro
Carril Oeste as Martin Palermo scored his eighth goal in six
games.... Uruguay: Antonio Pacheco had five goals to keep Penarol
ahead in the Clausura with a 6-1 win over River Plate.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Hamburg rolling
</P>
<P>
   Hamburg hasn't added a trophy since the Cup Winners' Cup in
1987, and it's too early to talk about a first Bundesliga title
since 1983, when it also won the European Cup. But Saturday's 5-0
throttling of Hertha Berlin, thanks to a hat trick by Roy Praeger
to keep them atop the league, has raised hopes.... Less than a week
after Kaiserslautern sweeper and captain Ciriaco Sforza was taken
off the starting lineup for criticizing coach Otto Rehhagel's
tactics, he was asked to return after a 5-0 loss to Werder Bremen.
</P>
<P>
   England: Wednesday reeling
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield Wednesday remained on the bottom of the Premier League
table after a 2-0 loss to Everton, increasing talk that manager
Danny Wilson is out soon... Liverpool's resurgence was short-lived,
thanks to defensive mistakes in a 3-2 loss to Manchester United at
Anfield. The Red Devils scored twice courtesy of own goals by Jamie
Carragher.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
