<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-FLORIDA-HNS &LR;      09-15 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The news hit close to home _ too close for comfort, in most cases.
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so nobody in college football tends to have much sympathy
for Steve Spurrier, the wisecracking, condescending,
beat-'em-as-badly-as-you-can head coach of the University of
Florida's Gators. In this instance, though, even a couple of
Spurrier's most bitter rivals were ready to offer tea and sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that terrifies you as a coach, because you
really can't control it,'' Florida State coach Bobby Bowden said.
``It's scary how they can get to these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Phillip Fulmer shares the fear. Volunteers fans may
smirk about a troubled offseason in Gainesville as the No. 2 Vols
and the No. 4 Gators get ready to meet again Saturday night at
``The Swamp,'' but the coach of the defending national champions
isn't smiling.
</P>
<P>
   (Well, not in public, at least.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely terrifying, from a coaching standpoint, to
even think about agents being on your campus,'' Fulmer said.
``We're trying all the time to educate our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Fulmer went to extreme measures to drive home the
message. Star linebacker and team leader Al Wilson agreed to
address a meeting, where he would offer a startling ``confession.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was almost in tears,'' Fulmer recalls. ``He told the team
he was real sorry, but he'd been involved with an agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer asked that his players turn in their 1997 Southeastern
Conference championship rings. The room fell silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dwayne Goodrich was about to cry,'' Fulmer said. ``His lip
started quivering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a set-up thing, but we wanted to make a point of how
big a deal the agents are.''
</P>
<P>
   That point has been made at Florida, where a disappointing 1998
season was made all the more dreary by revelations that several
players may have been receiving under-the-table payments from
agents before completing their eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the Orange Bowl, the school suspended Tim Beauchamp and
Dock Pollard for violations of university rules. The two later were
alleged to have received money from an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Later, three former players _ Johnny Rutledge, Reggie McGrew and
Jevon Kearse _ were linked to agent William ``Tank'' Black. In
affidavits, the three alleged that a representative for Black paid
them thousands of dollars while they were playing for the Gators.
Rutledge also said he had been told former players Ike Hilliard and
Fred Taylor had received cash from Black during their college days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do everything we can to teach the guys the rules, what's
right and what's wrong,'' Spurrier said earlier this summer. ``We
suspended two players before the Orange Bowl _ the two we found out
about. We would have suspended the others, too, if we'd known about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just bad choices by those players. The only thing we
can do as coaches and administrators is to show them you can't
break the rules and be a Gator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those players broke the rules willingly, and they're not going
to be welcomed back. They're not going to be able to use the weight
room. They sort of lost a home there.''
</P>
<P>
   While Florida endured most of the negative headlines, other
coaches who regularly make the polls and flirt with national titles
worry about what might be going undetected on their own campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the irregularities _ what they're driving, clothes,
expensive coats _ we ask the questions,'' Fulmer said. ``We're
trying. What it comes down to is that the kid has to do what's
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, we agree not to have any contact. We've had this
going on for four years now. They're going to talk to (agents)
after the bowl game. That's when they need an agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some peer pressure. We all agree it's not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   After a spring and summer of bad publicity, Florida tries to
make sure it doesn't happen again. In the meantime, the Gators also
hope to get back to the business of contending for the national
championship, a goal that went awry early last season when they
lost in overtime in Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   That game provided the springboard for Tennessee's national
title run. It also relegated Spurrier's team to second place in the
Southeastern Conference Eastern Division.
</P>
<P>
   A similar crossroads awaits Saturday night. Spurrier hopes his
team is more focused than the one that later lost to Florida State,
the other team that went on to play for the national championship
in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Galling? Not immediately, Spurrier says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was galling was when UCLA and Kansas State lost,'' he
recalls. ``After we lost to FSU (in Tallahassee), there was a
feeling of, `Well, gosh, we weren't in the big game anyway.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, bang, those teams lose .''
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, missing out on a trip to the desert would become a
lesser concern as tales of agents and runners and free-flowing cash
engulfed the program. Still, Spurrier regards the rout of Syracuse
in the Orange Bowl as a good starting point for 1999, and having a
younger, less-experienced team this season may come at just the
right time for all concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``These players are a little bit more fun to coach,'' he said.
``They look at you a little more like the coaches know what you're
doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the coaches they are looking at are different,
too. Defensive coordinator Bob Stoops left to become head man at
Oklahoma. Assistant offensive coordinator and running backs coach
Carl Franks moved on to run the show at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   So far, results in their absence have been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Gators are rolling. With Doug Johnson at
quarterback, Florida routed Western Michigan and Central Florida
and amassed 1,193 total yards in the two lopsided wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Doug has a better understanding and knowledge of our
offense,'' Spurrier said. ``He knows a little more what to check to
and what to get out of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early, but I really believe Doug's going to have a
big year.''
</P>
<P>
   He may need to do just that. The Florida defense, under new
coordinator Jon Hoke, has allowed 784 passing yards in two games,
405 of those against Western Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Gators put a 29-game home win streak on the line as
Tennessee tries to win in Gainesville for the first time since
1971. After owning the Vols for much of the '90s, Florida tries to
re-establish dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a bit of the swagger is returning to the tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we won't say more than we can back up,'' Spurrier
said. ``But I saw in the paper that we were favored by two points.
</P>
<P>
   ``So how are we supposed to act?''
</P>
<P>
   Like Florida, of course. With a chance to put an ugly 12 months
behind them, Spurrier and the Gators hope to see the skies finally
clearing in more ways than one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
