<HEADER>
A3545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-BAHAMAS-NYT     09-15 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BAHAMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAHAMIAN OFFICIALS ASSESS DAMAGE AND HOPE FOR THE BEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See HURRICANE-RDP, HURRICANE-FLORIDA, HURRICANE-BEACHES) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas _ Despite extensive damage to houses and land on
some of the islands east of here, Bahamian officials said Wednesday
they were cautiously optimistic that they survived a pummeling from
Hurricane Floyd with only one reported fatality.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after the hurricane lashed some of the
islands with 140-mph winds, officials were hampered in their damage
assessments by downed phone lines, blackouts, flooded runways and
insufficient aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Based on phone and radio reports received by disaster relief
officials, the worst hit islands were Abaco, Eleuthera, Cat and San
Salvador. There were reports of roofs being ripped off many homes,
extensive flooding, toppled utility poles and thousands of uprooted
trees.
</P>
<P>
   The only confirmed fatality was on Grand Bahama, where a man
driving along a flooded road was swept into the ocean and drowned,
Godwin Blyden, the national disaster coordinator, said.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial reconnaissance showed extensive damage on Little Abaco,
where Blyden said several people had been reported missing.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Coast Guard plane flying over Sandy Point on Little Abaco
observed large swaths of land covered with fallen trees whose thin,
brown limbs had been stripped bare of leaves. Almost every house
visible from the air had been damaged, from complete collapse of
walls that folded in on themselves, to roofs that were sent flying
across the road leaving behind concrete skeletons exposed to the
sky. Some roads were flooded, or covered with dirt and tree limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Though the winds were less severe on Nassau's New Providence
Island, blasts of up to 90 mph sent trees crashing to the ground,
while heavy rains inundated some roads. By late afternoon
Wednesday, most of the roads were passable, although trees and
pools of water limited passage to one lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were quite fortunate the damage was not more substantial
than it is,'' said Blyden, who has had to rely on sporadic phone
and radio contact with the most affected islands. ``Until we can do
a full assessment that may be different. It's difficult to say with
any degree of precision where the most serious damage occurred. We
have several reports of substantial damage, and I don't want to
minimize their losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach the affected areas Wednesday were delayed by a
lack of phone or radio service to the islands. While power and
phones have been restored to about 50 percent of capacity in
Nassau, service remains down on the other islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there was no communication we were not certain if
runways were open,'' Blyden said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Coast Guard dispatched several helicopters to transport
Bahamian and U.S. officials to assess the damage on the outlying
islands. The Coast Guard also sent several small jet planes to
conduct aerial reconnaissance. A team from the Office of Foreign
Disaster Assistance, from the U.S. Agency for International
Development, also arrived here Wednesday to assist the Bahamian
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Martinez, the public affairs officer at the American
Embassy, said some of the Coast Guard planes dispatched Wednesday
had to first check out reports of people needing assistance before
they could do a more general survey of the territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't find any people in distress or critically
injured,'' Ms. Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, a Coast Guard jet flying over Freeport circled
the skies as the crew tried to find the source of a distress signal
that buzzed repeatedly. It turned out to be from an airplane part
near the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Blyden said that there was substantial land erosion on
Eleuthera, leaving several houses teetering on their foundations.
He added that docks were seriously damaged and that wind and
flooding had damaged several farms. On San Salvador, he said, there
was extensive flooding of roads and a lot of roof damage.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were still signs of damage in Nassau, the airport
as well as government offices planned to resume normal operations
on Thursday. The weather was hot and sunny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely perfect now,'' Blyden said. ``The sea is calm.
You would not believe a hurricane went by yesterday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
