<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami game worries Penn State's Paterno
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No. 3 Penn State (3-0) has a lot to worry about when
it travels to No. 8 Miami (2-0) on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1, the Hurricanes are rested after a week off. Penn State
coach Joe Paterno says this Miami team is close to those of old.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids play with a lot of emotion,'' Paterno said.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2, there is concern in Happy Valley that the beginning of
this season is too similar to last season's.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Penn State started 3-0 by beating No. 21 Southern
Mississippi, routing Bowling Green and struggling to get by
Pittsburgh. In their fourth game, the Nittany Lions were trounced
by Ohio State 28-9. That game exposed their weaknesses and led to
an 8-3 regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State opened with an impressive victory against then-No. 4
_ but overrated _ Arizona, a blowout of Akron and a 20-17 victory
against Pitt on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Is history about to repeat?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important that we go down there this week
and come away with a 'W,' especially coming out of last year,''
fullback Mike Cerimele said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other pieces of history should worry Penn State fans: The
Nittany Lions have not beaten a top-10 team on the road since
beating No. 5 Michigan 31-24 on Oct. 15, 1994. They have not won a
game in the Orange Bowl, the site of Saturday's game, since 1976.
And the Hurricanes expect a rare sellout Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State leads the series 6-5, but the Hurricanes have won
four of the six games since 1979. In 1981, the Hurricanes and Jim
Kelly upset No. 1 Penn State in what some Miami fans called the
biggest win in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Paterno had one of his biggest wins, when Penn
State knocked off No. 1 Miami in the Fiesta Bowl for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Many people say this Penn State team could give Paterno his
third national championship. But Miami appears to be a dangerous
obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
