A3553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS16-COX     09-15 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons must find running game
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes, Falcons center Robbie Tobeck likes to joke
around, even when the subject matter is serious. Not Wednesday; not
with the mood offensive line coach Art Shell is in this week.
</P>
<P>
   The question: What does Atlanta need to do better to win Monday
at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Run for more than 80 yards, I'll tell you that,'' Tobeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobeck's point is crystal clear.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons are to have a realistic shot at getting back to
the Super Bowl, or, for that matter, at putting together
back-to-back winning seasons for the first time in the 34-year
history of the franchise, they've got to run the ball better.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons passed for 278 yards in a 17-14 loss to the Vikings,
66 more than they averaged while going 14-2 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But their 81 rushing yards were 21st in the league _ against a
defense that was supposed to be flimsy.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves said the Falcons were ``outworked'' up front,
as Viking defenders spun off blocks too easily. That's not a
function of power or technique; it's a matter of willpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about ... getting on guys, and finishing blocks ... going
until the whistle blows,'' Shell said.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Anderson rushed for franchise records last season of 1,846
yards and 14 touchdowns on an NFL-record 410 carries. Atlanta
averaged 131.4 rushing yards per game, sixth in the league last
year.
</P>
<P>
   There has been one change on his line. Bob Hallen, a
second-round pick and the backup guard last year, replaced Calvin
Collins at left guard. Collins is a backup guard and center.
</P>
<P>
   But the results were a lot different Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had 16 carries, almost 10 less than his average of last
year. That was partly because Atlanta fell behind 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   But other signs were ominous, too.
</P>
<P>
   Other than a 20-yard run where Anderson broke outside the
designed running lane, he had just 30 yards on 15 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you lose, it's because you got outworked,'' said right
guard Gene Williams. ``If we have everybody doing the right thing,
we make yards. It's that simple. But when we have eight or nine
people doing the right thing, it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings deserve some credit. All-Pro defensive tackle Randle
McDaniel, who often drew a double team, especially when he lined up
across from Hallen, was a pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hallen) did some good things,'' Reeves said. ``Randle caused
everybody some problems.'' Also, the Vikings were creeping strong
safety Robert Griffith and its cornerbacks toward the line,
reinforcing the run defense as they didn't seem to fear the deep
pass.
</P>
<P>
   And Anderson hinted that the excitement of facing the Vikings in
a rematch of the NFC Championship Game didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, you try to do too much. I have to be a little more
patient so things can develop,'' he said. ``I know I missed at
least two holes where, if I hit them, I think big runs could've
changed the complexion of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas will try to do a lot of what Minnesota did, try to make
us run laterally.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coaches would like to get speedy reserve running back
Byron Hanspard more involved. He had just three carries for 9 yards
against the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Cowboys' undersized, quick and young defensive
front seven would seem the good foil for a big back like Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Washington rushed for 135 yards against Dallas in the Cowboy's
41-35 overtime win, sixth-most in the NFL last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, we were getting on the right man and doing
the right thing, but we weren't always holding our blocks,'' Tobeck
said. ``We've got to get after `em.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
