<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ARAB-STORYTELLING-ART     09-15 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAB-STORYTELLING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TODAY'S DAMASCUS, LORE OF A GOLDEN ARAB PAST COMES TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ It is early twilight, and the muezzin's call
from the Umayyad Mosque has summoned the devout to the sunset
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost story time at Al Nawfara cafe. The television is
turned off. The tea drinkers wait expectantly.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, his prayers completed, the storyteller, in red fez-like
hat and patterned vest, takes his place on an elevated chair. He
finds his place in the text, and he begins to read.
</P>
<P>
   For precisely an hour, until the night is shattered again with
the day's final call to prayer, the story unfolds. It is the epic
tale of Antar and Abla, one that takes 300 nights to read. The
audience is transfixed. This is a story familiar to every Arab, but
in an era of uncertainty about Syria's future, it casts a powerful
spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stories represent courage, kindness and truthfulness,''
said Mohammed Jamil, 39, a businessman from northwestern Syria, who
listened intently as the familiar syllables rolled. ``When the
people fight, they fight nobly. There is no backstabbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Arab folklore has been spun by storytellers for hundreds and
hundreds of years, but in most cities the practice has long since
been supplanted by more modern forms of entertainment. In Damascus,
it disappeared for 15 years, beginning in 1975, so abruptly that
many people suspect the end was ordered by a government that had
embarked on a modernization campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But every night since 1990, the stories have been told again at
Al Nawfara, their traditional Damascus home. And there, just steps
from the eighth-century mosque, they have gained a following not
seen in any other modern Arab capital _ perhaps in part because
Damascus remains a city caught between old and new.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a return to the old history books, and how it was when
the Arabs were in their glory times,'' said Rashid Abu Shadi, 55, a
grocer by day and, by night, the storyteller, or hakawati, at Al
Nawfara, where he reads aloud seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with new hope budding for peace with Israel, no one in
Syria knows whether years of conflict might really be near an end.
For that conflict, the country has paid a heavy price. Its economic
development has been stalled, with mobile phones and the Internet
only now beginning to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Political discussion is so circumscribed that on the major
issues of the day, television, radio and newspapers offer little
more than slogans.
</P>
<P>
   At Al Nawfara, under fluorescent light, the institutional-yellow
halls hint at the yearning for a simpler past.
</P>
<P>
   There are the portraits, ubiquitous in Syria, of Hafez Assad,
the longtime president, and his son, Bashar, his apparent preferred
heir.
</P>
<P>
   But not far away are depictions of Antar and Abla, fictional
characters who would undoubtedly be judged, if there were a poll
among Arabs, as heroes by one and all.
</P>
<P>
   Antar Ibn Sheded, a brave and courageous warrior, is in love
with Abla, the embodiment of virtue and beauty. She loves him in
return, and is willing to be married.
</P>
<P>
   But Antar is cursed by his birth as the illegitimate son of an
Arab tribesmen and a black slave. To overcome repeated rebuff's
from Abla's family, he must repeatedly demonstrate his worthiness
through unimaginable feats of strength, kindness and bravery.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the oral tale was finally put to paper, under
Ottoman rule in the 18th century, the story ran to 3,000 pages.
Simpler tales have long been staples of Arab television and film,
but it is the unabridged version that Abu Shahdi has been reading
out loud every night for several months at Al Nawfara, with several
months to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The popular stories have meanings; they tell you the right
path of life,'' said Abu Shahdi, whose tenure at the cafe began
nine years ago, and revolves between Antar and Abla and two other
yearlong tales. ``They teach virtue, they teach sacrifice, and they
teach a love of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffering from the flu, Abu Shahdi cannot rely on the
storyteller's usual booming voice to drown out the tea-cup clatter.
But he makes up its absence with a flat sword, waving it in the air
for dramatic effect or slamming it against an iron table to
punctuate each turn in the story.
</P>
<P>
   A few tourists, and few women, are scattered among the 40 or so
people packed into the cafe.
</P>
<P>
   But most among the crowd are men, and many are regulars _
traders, businessmen and shopkeepers who, like Abu Shahdi, first
heard the stories at their fathers' sides, when they were small
boys. Over tea and narguila waterpipes, they listen as Abu Shahdi
picks up the classic tale.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, the story goes, Antar is preparing for a
dangerous journey over hundreds of miles of desert controlled by
hostile tribes. Only at that destination, in what is now Iraq, can
he find the 1,000 rare camels that Abla's father has so cruelly
demanded as her dowry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody besides Antar could get there,'' Mahmoud Jaffar, 35, a
trader who buys carpets from Iranian tourists, explained to a
visitor. ``They are just doing this to make things difficult for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Antar make it? And will he ever win Abla's hand?
</P>
<P>
   On this night, no one will find out. The muezzin's call rises
again from the minarets, and, with a smile, Abu Shahdi puts the
book aside.
</P>
<P>
   Men reach for a few small notes to pay a bill, and shuffle back
uphill toward the mosque. Soon, in the cafe, someone snaps the
television back on, to a Lebanese channel known for its relatively
racy fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best way these days,'' said Mahmoud Melhaan Abu
Marouf, 62, who remembers the old days at Al Nawfara, when the
storytelling would go on for hours. ``Now, everyone knows that it
will only take an hour; the story will last just from one prayer to
another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
