<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SENATORS NARROW CAMPAIGN FINANCE BILL TO DRAW SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
  ( Eds :  SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT, House passed bill on Tuesday,
sted Wed.; combines takes.) 
 (nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an attempt to break the long Senate stalemate on
campaign finance, the two senators sponsoring overhaul legislation
say they will strip down their bill to focus primarily on large,
unregulated donations to political parties that were at the center
of the controversy in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell
Feingold, D-Wis., to narrow their bill came after the House _ for
the second year in a row _ passed the original, more comprehensive
legislation Tuesday night, which put the issue of campaign finance
back before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not at all clear that the legislative tactic would
achieve the senators' aim, which is to somehow find enough votes to
prevail if senior Republicans once again mount a filibuster against
the effort to change the campaign law. Democrats who oppose scaling
back the comprehensive legislation likely will object to the new
language, and the most vociferous Republican critics of the bill
were showing no sign of being mollified.
</P>
<P>
   The two senators said in separate interviews Wednesday that the
new version of their bill would ban the unlimited, unregulated
donations to political parties known as ``soft money.'' But it
would no longer include new regulations on so-called issue advocacy
advertisements by outside groups within 60 days of an election.
Those commercials, critics say, purport to explain a policy issue
but are, in effect, thinly veiled campaign advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the more comprehensive legislation drew a 52-vote
majority in the Senate, but not the 60 votes needed to break a
filibuster mounted by Republican opponents who killed the bill.
With the Senate set to take up the issue again for a week in
October, the sponsors say they are trying to find a way to create a
new dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that there will be ample opportunities for senators
to amend their bare-bones bill, possibly building legislation that
can pass. That would get campaign finance legislation to a
House-Senate conference committee that would reconcile the
differences between the approaches of the two chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that we didn't see 60 votes if you reintroduced
McCain-Feingold,'' said McCain. ``I believe that by introducing
just the bare bones we can go through an amending process,'' he
added, `` hopefully approve a bill, get more votes and go to
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said the two had also considered the fact that
Sen.Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., and other chief opponents of the
overhaul legislation had long aimed most of their fire at the
provisions to regulate issue advocacy ads, arguing that they
amounted to an unconstitutional abridgment of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, they could not make that complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``This forces them to say that a ban on soft money is wrong,''
he said. ``I think that's hard because it's become essentially a
system of legalized bribery.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was far from clear Wednesday that the two men's move
would bolster their case. In fact it looked possible that it could
fracture their coalition since many Democrats argue that they are
often the targets of issue advocacy ad campaigns run by Republican
allies such as the National Rifle Association, the Christian
Coalition and anti-tax groups.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin T. Meehan , D-Mass., who is one of the chief
sponsors of the House companion bill, expressed doubts about the
maneuver by McCain and Feingold. ``We just had a great victory for
campaign finance reform and I hate to embrace the very next day a
weaker bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Nichols, a spokeswoman for Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House
Minority Leader, was more blunt. ``There's zero support among House
Democrats for a watered down campaign finance bill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the political spectrum, McConnell showed no
inclination to drop his opposition to even the rejiggered bill. He
argued that Republicans needed the large cash infusions that come
to the party in soft money to pay for television ads to counter
advertisements by organized labor, which usually backs Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want our political party to be able to defend our
candidates,'' said McConnell, who is head of the Senate
Republicans' re-election effort.
</P>
<P>
   Both Feingold and McCain conceded that they had no solid vote
counts and did not know whether their new approach could succeed.
They run the risk of gaining some new Republican supporters but
losing some of their Democratic support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Democrats will have concerns,'' Feingold admitted. But he
said he believed Democrats would be misguided to stand against a
soft money ban. ``I don't think Democrats either would on
philosophical grounds or should on practical grounds ever pretend
they will come out ahead if we continue with soft money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were some signs Wednesday that Democrats will still try to
fight for passage of the same bill that the House approved,
252-177.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really think it would be too bad if we had the chance to
get comprehensive reform and it somehow got undermined by a less
comprehensive bill,'' said Ranit Schmelzer, the press secretary for
Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the minority leader. She added, however,
that ``if that is not feasible we're committed to getting a bill
though the Senate that will go to conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides banning soft money, the new McCain-Feingold bill will
codify a Supreme Court decision that gave people who work in union
shops where they are required to pay dues the right to ask for the
return of the portion of the money that is used for political
activity.
</P>
<P>
   That stops far short of calls by Republicans to require labor
unions to receive prior written consent from all union members
before using dues for political activity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
