<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-GENERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA CONFIRMS IT WILL ACQUIRE GENERAL INSTRUMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa.)   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Motorola Inc. on Wednesday confirmed that it would
acquire General Instrument Corp., a leading maker of cable set-top
boxes, in a stock deal valued at nearly $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The move would make Motorola a key supplier of cable television
equipment and allow the company to develop what it calls a ``home
hub'' of products to offer broadband cable and Internet access to
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the deal gives it a passageway into the homes
of millions of consumers and that it plans to develop new set-top
boxes with cable modems that will enable consumers to surf the Web,
make telephone calls, access e-mail and even tune into interactive
video and pay-per-view digital television.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows us to participate in the fastest-growing segment
of the telecommunications industry,'' said Christopher Galvin, the
chairman and chief executive of Motorola, which is based in
Schaumburg, Ill. ``There's an insatiable demand for bandwidth into
the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Breen, the chairman and chief executive of General
Instrument, of Horsham, Pa., which has the dominant position in
set-top boxes, as well as a cable infrastructure, will head a new
unit of Motorola that combines his company with Motorola's
networking and Internet division to create a wired home that would
offer everything from burglar alarms to high-definition TV. General
Instrument had $2 billion in revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola agreed to offer 0.575 of a share of its own stock for
each share of General Instrument, which has 214 million shares
outstanding. Based on Wednesday's closing price for Motorola, the
deal would be valued at about $10.66 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Motorola, which skidded Monday on word of the deal,
tumbled again Wednesday, losing $6.5625, to close at $86.625 in
heavy trading. Shares of General Instrument also fell, closing at
$47.25, down $3.25.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have not reacted enthusiastically partly because
Motorola says the deal will dilute earnings in the first year
before bolstering them in later years. But Wall Street analysts say
the deal would give Motorola a dynamic new, high-growth component
and fit nicely with its fast-growing cable modem division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential of the combination is just huge,'' said Mona
Eraiba, an analyst at Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``It's going to open a huge
market that is considerably bigger than the current market.'' She
added, ``Everything is going to converge in the set top box.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire cable television industry is consolidating and
upgrading to offer high-speed Internet access, interactive video
and additional channels. Big cable operators, like AT&AMP;T, are
spending billions of dollars to upgrade their cable offerings and
buy set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   For Motorola, which has $29 billion in revenues and is
rebounding from a sharp slump, the new division and emphasis on the
Internet is expected to be a growth area that will complement its
strong positions in semiconductors and cellular telephones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
