<HEADER>
A3560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-BEACHES-(TR     09-15 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BEACHES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH AND GOVERNMENT COLLIDE IN CREATING A HAZARD 
</HEADLINE>
 (With HURRICANE-RDP, HURRICANE-FLORIDA, HURRICANE-BAHAMAS) 
(nk) 
 By CORNELIA DEAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The evacuations, disaster declarations and emergency
proclamations that are accompanying Hurricane Floyd along the
Atlantic coast are a small taste of worse to come, say coastal
scientists and policy makers worried about rising sea levels, more
intense storms and a ballooning coastal population.
</P>
<P>
   Weather forecasters at the National Hurricane Center and
elsewhere have gotten better and better at predicting when and
where storms will strike, helping officials to move residents and
tourists out of harm's way in time. But population growth along the
coast _ fueled in part, some experts say, by government policies
encouraging development _ is more than outpacing them. Within a few
years, some demographers predict, most Americans will live in
coastal counties.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, timely evacuations in some areas are already
becoming impossible.
</P>
<P>
   And if the earth is warming _ and mainstream scientists believe
it is _ the rise of sea levels will accelerate, leaving low-lying
areas ever more vulnerable to flooding. Plus, because hurricanes
draw their energy from ocean warmth, warmer seas may mean stronger
storms.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest burst of development on the coast has occurred since
the 1960s, a time of relatively few hurricanes. Some
climatologists, notably William M. Gray of Colorado State
University, say this quiet weather cannot last. They believe that
hurricane frequency varies in cycles, and that another period of
high hurricane frequency is beginning. If the nation returned to
the prevailing patterns of the 1930s, '40s and '50s, they say,
hurricanes costing tens of billions of dollars would become
routine.
</P>
<P>
   But policy makers are finding it difficult to limit building on
some of the nation's most desirable, but most hazardous, landscape.
In fact, some experts say, they are doing the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations and demand that the federal government be
extremely generous and supportive of disaster victims, and the
property rights movement nationally, have in a broad sense
intimidated federal, state and local officials from limiting
development and redevelopment,'' said Rutherford H. Platt, a
professor of geography at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst. His new book, ``Disasters and Democracy,'' deals with
disaster assistance and its effects on development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the rhetoric about mitigation,'' Platt said in an
interview Wednesday, ``the broad thrust of federal policy is to
provide disaster grants, loans and tax deductions that encourage
investment in hazardous areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Hurricane Floyd, President Clinton issued
pre-emptive disaster declarations from New Zealand and the
governors of Florida, Georgia, South Carolina, North Carolina,
Virginia, New Jersey, Delaware and Maryland all declared states of
emergency, hours before the storm made landfall.
</P>
<P>
   Like others who have studied coastal development, Platt says
programs like disaster assistance and the federal Flood Insurance
Program, which provides low-cost coverage in flood hazard areas,
can encourage unwise development. Some coastal scientists blame the
insurance program, in fact, for much of the unwise development that
has taken place on the coast since it went into effect in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   But many involved in coastal development issues maintain that
even if federal agencies halted their grants, infrastructure
support and other spending, people might still flock to build on
the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to be on the beach because they like to be on
the beach,'' said Gerry Stoddard, president of the Fire Island
Association, which represents homeowners on the island.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But as more and more people settle at the coast, getting them
out safely in the event of a storm is turning into a logistical
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, evacuations should be carried out well before a storm
hits, at low tide so low-lying coastal roads are not flooded, and
in daylight. Even then, coastal highways are not designed to carry
such a load. In fact, the prospect of throngs of residents trapped
in miles-long traffic jams is what most frightens many disaster
planners.
</P>
<P>
   There are few places more dangerous to be in a hurricane than in
an automobile. But that was exactly where many people were up and
down the coast as Hurricane Floyd approached. Evacuation traffic
clogged almost to a halt in Florida, and Interstate 40 in North
Carolina was choked with cars.
</P>
<P>
   As the hurricane neared Georgia, state workers were able to turn
Interstate 16 into a one-way avenue out of Savannah, with traffic
on both sides of the divided highway headed west, inland. But, as
in this case, most coastal highways were built before engineers
realized they might ever have to run only one way. So highway
officials in coastal jurisdictions must scramble to retrofit,
stationing portable signs, traffic cones and the like in strategic
locations.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, though, disaster officials are reconciling
themselves to the reality that it will not be possible to get
everyone out in time. That is particularly true in places like
Florida, with its low-lying barrier islands and its high proportion
of elderly residents, many in frail health.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in places like the Florida Keys and Sanibel Island, on
Florida's Gulf Coast, are designating ``refuges of last resort,''
places where people can shelter if they cannot escape a storm in
time.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, Americans' love for beach living serves to thwart
the coast's natural defense against extreme storms. Geologists know
that the more building there is on the coastal barrier islands that
line the East and the Gulf coasts, the more difficulty the islands
themselves seem to have in recovering from hurricanes and other
coastal storms.
</P>
<P>
   The geologists began studying the issue in detail more than 35
years ago, after the notorious Ash Wednesday northeaster of 1962.
That storm, which lasted for days, devastated much of the East
Coast. Undeveloped barrier islands recovered quickly; developed
stretches of coast were much slower to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this is because sand on these islands naturally shifts
from inland dunes to offshore sandbars, which form in storms and
then act as a kind of defense system, breaking waves before they
can crash more destructively on the beach. When calm weather
returns, gentle swells carry the sandbar sands back on shore.
</P>
<P>
   Platt and other experts on coastal planning say they wish
coastal officials knew more about this beach geology, and the
importance of keeping buildings off the beach. If they had acted on
that knowledge, these experts say, barrier islands might be better
able to survive storms, and there would be fewer people trying to
escape them.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as government assistance is available, it seems
likely that building in hazard areas will continue and disaster
declarations will follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
