u w BC-CELLPHONES-911-NYT &LR;      09-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONES-911-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LETS DISPATCHERS KNOW SOURCE OF CELLULAR CALLS TO 911 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reflecting rapid advances in technology, the
federal government on Wednesday announced new technical standards
that will enable emergency dispatchers to pinpoint the location of
cellular telephone calls to 911.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, which were approved unanimously by the
Federal Communications Commission on Wednesday and will begin to
take effect in 2001, dispatchers will be able to determine the
location of a caller to within an approximate range of 55 to 325
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision will save lives, it's as simple as that,''
William Kennard, the chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, said Wednesday. ``Locating people in threatening
situations is a life-and-death event. Right now, some 70 percent of
traffic deaths occur in the critical period two hours after the
accident. By giving public safety officials the ability to locate
callers, this will literally mean the difference between life and
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Most emergency dispatchers around the nation can already
determine the location of a call made from a conventional
telephone. But dispatchers and consumers have often complained of
the inability to locate a cellular phone caller in distress _ for
example, in a highway accident or in an unfamiliar neighborhood
where the caller has witnessed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is the second time in a month that the agency
has issued technical standards enabling the tracking of cellular
phone users. Three weeks ago, it announced standards to expand the
ability of law-enforcement agents to monitor conversations and
locate criminal suspects. Those rules, which were criticized by
privacy rights advocates, will enable federal and local agents who
obtain a warrant to identify the nearest cellular antenna that was
used by the phone company to transmit the beginning and end of any
call under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ruling last month, law-enforcement authorities would
be able to track a cellular phone user within a range of a few city
blocks to a few miles. Wednesday's decision would give far more
precision to locating a cellular phone user, and privacy advocates
said it was only a matter of time before law-enforcement officials
tried to use the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unrealistic to think there will be a generally deployed
tracking capability and that law enforcement will not seek access
to it,'' said David Sobel, the general counsel of the Electronic
Privacy Information Center in Washington. ``They already have their
foot in the door with last month's ruling, and it's a logical next
step for them to seek access to these emergency capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennard said that Wednesday's decision would protect
legitimate privacy interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer is in the driver's seat,'' he said, ``because the
location capability is only activated if you make a 911 call so you
choose when you will be subject to this technology. Most people in
an emergency are not as concerned about their privacy. They're
concerned about their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency gave the wireless telephone industry the choice of
how to comply with the requirements. The industry can make use of
its antennas and networks to calculate the location of the user
through such methods as trangulation, or using more than one cell
or signal sent by the same phone. It can rely on new technology
that will be embedded in the handsets, like circuitry that can be
used with the military's global positioning satellites system, to
determine the location of a caller. Or it can use a hybrid system
that uses the network in some places and technology in the handset
in others.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials applauded Wednesday's decision but said
difficult issues remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that the FCC has kept up with technology and that
the industry has beat the laws of physics and we can do this,''
said Tom Wheeler, president of the Cellular Telecommunications
Industry Association. ``Now we've got to deal with the laws of
human nature and politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the thorniest issue involves who will pay for the new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC is expected to decide that issue this year, although it
has largely left it to the states. About 30 states have adopted
legislation or regulations, many of which permit phone companies to
add a monthly charge of 50 cents to $1.25 to pay for the
technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
