<HEADER>
A3567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-OSU-MONEY16-COX     09-15 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSU-MONEY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friendly policy keeps Ohio State's coffers full while giving
other schools exposure
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ John Cooper knows what it's like to be on the
losing end of a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   As head coach at the University of Tulsa 20 years ago, Cooper
made annual trips to Oklahoma and Arkansas, where beatings were the
norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I was supposed to be happy about it,'' Cooper said.
``Everybody was happy but me.''
</P>
<P>
   As head football coach at powerhouse Ohio State, Cooper can
smile again because now the Tulsas of Ohio must come to him for the
poundings.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Ohio University (0-2) of the Mid-American
Conference visits Ohio Stadium to face the 13th-ranked Buckeyes.
Next week, the University of Cincinnati, whose football program has
been as bad lately as its nationally ranked basketball program has
been good, comes to town. Next year, its MAC member Miami (Ohio)
and in 2001, Akron.
</P>
<P>
   The games are part of a new neighborly effort by Ohio State to
help put some extra money in the pockets of smaller in-state
programs while keeping OSU's coffers full.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always understood that the Mid-American schools kind of
struggled financially and it just seemed to me to make sense to
keep the money (from nonconference OSU home games) in Ohio,'' said
OSU athletics director Andy Geiger, who pushed to get the Ohio
schools back on the Buckeyes' schedule after a 58-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State earns about $3million in total revenues from ticket
sales, parking, concessions, etc., from each home game, according
to Pete Hagen, the school's assistant athletics director for
finance.
</P>
<P>
   For visiting teams, the payoff is enticing, too. Ohio University
will make $350,000 from its visit to the Horseshoe this weekend,
``more money than we'd make from a home game,'' Ohio University
athletics director Thomas Boeh said.
</P>
<P>
   The big paydays suppliment the much-smaller budgets of the MAC
schools. OU for example has a budget of just under $10million as
compared to Ohio State's $68million budget.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeh said he did not agree to the meeting just for the cash.
If the Bobcats were in it only for the money, he said, they'd go to
Penn State or Florida or LSU where the payouts are $500,000 or
more.
</P>
<P>
   An Ohio State match-up allows Bobcat players from Ohio, of which
there are many, to play a televised game in their home state. This
exposure, Boeh said, helps both recruiting and the team's
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this game does for us is allows us to measure our program
a little bit,'' he said. ``It also gives us additional visibility
that we might not otherwise get.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the money isn't nice, too.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo athletics director Pete Liske said the $350,000 the
Rockets made from its game at OSU last year (a 49-0 loss) enabled
their football program to buy state-of-the-art video equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beating we took in that game was only in the score,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Liske said the blowout was disappointing because ``we
thought we were much more competitive.'' He admits winning-minded
coaches are probably less enthusiastic about playing OSU than the
money-conscious athletic directors.
</P>
<P>
   If Ohio coach Jim Grobe feels that way about Saturday's game,
he's not showing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was a no-brainer,'' he said. ``What a great
experience for our program and our kids.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
