<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ANTISMOKING-AD-COLUMN     09-15 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTISMOKING-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: ARNOLD COMMUNICATIONS LEADS BIG ANTI-SMOKING
CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Texas, Ill., Fla.)  (EDS: this replaces PRE-GAME-AD-COLUMN, which has been held) 
(bl) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team of agencies was selected Wednesday to create and produce
what is intended as the largest single national advertising,
marketing and public relations campaign to ``unsell'' cigarette
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The team, which includes two agencies with extensive experience
in developing anti-smoking campaigns for two large states, was
chosen after a three-month review by the American Legacy Foundation
in Washington. The foundation was funded by the recent $206 billion
settlement between 46 state attorneys general and the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will include television, radio, print and Internet
advertising with a particular focus on discouraging teen-agers from
starting to smoke cigarettes. The initial annual budget will be
$150 million to $255 million, or 50 to 85 percent of the $300
million the foundation is to receive each year under terms of the
settlement between Big Tobacco and the attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is emblematic of a trend that is reshaping the
attitudes of Madison Avenue. After decades of helping to persuade
Americans to smoke, agencies are now switching sides to assist the
anti-tobacco forces. That fundamental shift coincides with a
turnabout in societal perceptions about smoking as well as the
growing popularity of efforts to change behavior through so-called
social marketing campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, the change comes as increasing sums of money are
being devoted to a variety of campaigns to end smoking, under the
aegis of the foundation, states, pharmaceutical companies that sell
drugs meant to help smokers stop and even tobacco marketers like
Philip Morris Cos., seeking to improve their corporate image by
sponsoring anti-cigarette ads aimed at young people.
</P>
<P>
   The review began with the foundation soliciting agencies to take
part. The field was narrowed to nine teams, then four, then three
finalists.
</P>
<P>
   The lead agency on the winning team is Arnold Communications in
Boston, a unit of Snyder Communications that has created
anti-smoking ads for the Massachusetts Public Health Department.
Arnold's duties will include media buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity of a lifetime,'' said Francis Kelly,
managing partner and chief marketing officer at Arnold, in a
statement, ``to not only do great communications but to do it for a
great cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The other agency team member with a big state's anti-tobacco
work on its resume is Crispin Porter &AMP; Bogusky in Miami, which has
created anti-smoking ads for what is called the Florida Tobacco
Pilot Program. That campaign was centered on the concept of
promoting a brand named Truth that was intended to counter the
influence of cigarette advertising on teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Branding social change hasn't been done much before,'' said
Crispin Porter chairman and partner Charles Porter in a telephone
interview Wednesday. ``This is going to be exciting; we're very
eager for the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The tasks to be handled by Crispin Porter will include general
advertising and youth marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The Arnold-Crispin Porter team had been considered a
front-runner in the review not only because of its experience but
also because Chuck Wolfe, the executive vice president at the
foundation, ran a review in Florida that ended with the selection
of Crispin Porter as the agency for the anti-tobacco campaign
there.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the winning team are: Bromley, Aguilar &AMP;
Associates in San Antonio, Texas, a unit of MacManus Group, for
youth marketing and ads aimed at Spanish-speaking consumers;
Burrell Communications Group in Chicago, 49 percent owned by
Publicis SA, for youth marketing and ads aimed at blacks;
Circle.com in Boston, also part of Snyder, as the lead interactive
agency, and Nixon Group in Miami, for duties including promotions
and youth marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Porter Novelli in Washington, a unit of Omnicom Group, for
public relations and social marketing; Teen-age Research Unlimited
in Northbrook, Ill., for youth research, and Imada Wong
Communications Group in Los Angeles, an affiliate of the New
America Strategies Group of True North Communications, for tasks
that include ads aimed at Asian-American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two other finalist teams, one had as its lead agency
Messner Vetere Berger McNamee Schmetterer/Euro RSCG in New York,
part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas Advertising. Other
members included SFM Media in New York, also part of Havas, for
media buying, and Dan Klores Associates in New York, for public
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The other finalist team had at its lead agency Richards Group in
Dallas. Other members included the Los Angeles office of Western
Initiative Media Worldwide, a unit of Interpublic Group of Cos.,
for media buying, and the Golin/Harris International unit of
Interpublic, for public relations.
</P>
<P>
   The finalist team led by Arnold was chosen by the foundation
after a recommendation from a selection panel that included Lonnie
Bristow, a former president of the American Medical Association;
David Milenthal, chairman at HMS Partners in Columbus, Ohio, a
longtime opponent of Madison Avenue's handling of cigarette
accounts, and Wolfe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
