<SLUG> BC-STRAY911-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Page with a 911 invites cops to crack party
 &HT;    By Ralph Schusler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Like many people who want a prompt response,
Jay T. McCarty added a 911 after his phone number on the page he
sent his girlfriend near dawn on Aug. 29 on this wealthy island
community.
</P>
<P>
   The three digits somehow resulted in a phone call to the Palm
Beach Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Officers arriving at the ground-floor Hammon Avenue apartment
from which McCarty had called came upon a door presumably left open
for Hubbard. Announcing themselves and entering, they said, they
found McCarty with crack pipes and other drug paraphernalia, as
well as a 12-gauge shotgun and .22-caliber rifle, both loaded.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty has a felony conviction for aggravated drug trafficking,
and state law prohibits his possessing firearms. He was arrested
and faces a second felony charge that carries a mandatory minimum
three-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Local 911 operators speculated that after punching in his number
to Hubbard's pager, McCarty must have inadvertently disconnected
and unknowingly gotten a dial tone before hitting the 911 and
inviting the police to his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a new one for me,'' said Mark Adler, Palm Beach
County's 911 coordinator. ``It's so off the wall, it's
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Also disbelieving was McCarty's girlfriend, Kristen Hubbard, who
responded to his page by rushing in a cab to the apartment. Upon
arrival, she was arrested on an outstanding warrant. Police found a
crack pipe on her, too, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
