<HEADER>
A3572 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE LEFT'S NEW HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing ignominious defeat by Republicans in New
Hampshire _ a state whose primary he carried last time out _ Pat
Buchanan is now out to wreak vengeance as a spoiler. He can taste
the 13 million taxpayer dollars available to the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   A liberal former Democratic governor, hands clasped, tells me
fervently, ``Thank God for Pat Buchanan _ he could elect Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming the billionaire Ross Perot still owns the party
he formed and can dictate its nomination. Gov. Jesse Ventura of
Minnesota, Reform's electoral success, has pledged to complete his
term and hopes to run in 2004. But Ross the Boss, badly beaten last
time out, has a way to block Reform's reform and maintain his
personal platform.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, rejected by GOP rank and file, is his warhorse. Never
mind the libertarian, pro-choice instincts of most past Perot
followers; by putting his anti-choice choice atop his ticket, and
taking the vice presidential slot himself, Perot can legally add
tens of millions of his own money to the taxpayer's $13 million and
try to become a player again.
</P>
<P>
   But my old Nixon-Agnew speech-writing colleague (I did
``nattering nabobs''; Pat did ``pusillanimous pussyfooters'') has
this strategic problem: his only success has been based on the
politics of economic resentment. Blaming Asians and Mexicans for
taking away jobs works in hard times, but loses all traction during
full employment.
</P>
<P>
   Because neither abortion absolutism nor class warfare will help
him with what used to be called ``Perot's people,'' the bolting
Buchanan is giving new emphasis to his old fallback position:
cultural resentment, especially of the dire influence of Jewish
Americans, with anti-Castro Cuban Americans tossed in.
</P>
<P>
   His selling of sellout became apparent when David Broder asked
him on ``Meet the Press'' about assertions in his campaign book
that ``after World War II, Jewish influence over foreign policy
became almost an obsession with American leaders.'' And ``the
Israeli lobby is the most powerful of ethnic lobbies.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, advocate of ``Arab East Jerusalem'' as the Palestinian
capital, plunged in deeper: ``If Pat Buchanan becomes president of
the United States,'' he said, ``the foreign policy of this country
and the Middle East policy of this country will be made in the Oval
Office by the president of the United States alone.'' Implicit: And
not by those rich, pushy Jews who put Israel's interest ahead of
America's. He drove that dual-loyalty canard home with ``I know the
power of the Israeli lobby and the other lobbies, but we need a
foreign policy that puts our own country first.''
</P>
<P>
   Was this calculated to whip up resentment at Jews' political
participation, even at the cost of stimulating anti-Semitism? Of
course; he knows exactly what he's doing. To pose as fair, he also
imputes policy disloyalty to Americans with ties to Cuba, Greece,
Armenia and a dozen other places, and is careful to say ``Israeli
lobby'' rather than ``Jewish lobby.'' But you know what he means.
</P>
<P>
   The roots go deep. I went up against Pat on aid to Israel in
Nixon's '68 campaign on the issue of the sale of Phantom jets to
Israel. Buchanan argued it would get us no Jewish votes; although
Nixon agreed that Jewish Americans would oppose him overwhelmingly,
he urged the sale of the jets anyway because he thought the Israel
of Golda Meir was a strategic U.S. asset with admirable moxie. In
went a line promising a ``a qualitative edge,'' bipartisan policy
to this day.
</P>
<P>
   During the Persian Gulf War, Buchanan's bile spilled out. His
``amen corner'' crack displayed not just his isolationism, and his
deliberate leaving out of a Jewish name in a litany of expected
ethnic casualties led William F. Buckley, inventor of Goldwater
conservatism, to conclude regretfully that Buchanan's barbs could
well be taken as anti-Semitic. When I agreed in this space, my
White House comrade in arms ended our friendship.
</P>
<P>
   So now Democrats root for the nativist Buchanan to get the
Reform nomination just as Republicans root for the liberal Warren
Beatty. Neither major party would allow those would-be spoilers to
be part of the Presidential TV debates; the Reform Party would be
doomed to represent the resentful fringes of left or right. You
don't have to be Jewish to know that's not in America's interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
