u f BC-HEINZ-BESTFOODS-NYT     09-15 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEINZ-BESTFOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MERGER WITH HEINZ? BESTFOODS TAKES PAINS TO SAY IT ISN'T SO 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.J., N.Y.)  (af) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bestfoods, the maker of the childhood favorite Skippy peanut
butter and of Hellmann's mayonnaise, said Wednesday that it was in
``no significant acquisition or combination discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   A report in The Wall Street Journal Wednesday morning had said
that Bestfoods was in talks with H.J. Heinz Co. about a proposed
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods issued its disclaimer in a statement _ a rare, almost
unprecedented departure _ from a usual policy of no comment. And it
left many Wall Street analysts, executives and traders scratching
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Was the chairman of Bestfoods, Charles R. Shoemate, rebuffing
Heinz, but in the process telling Wall Street that his company was
willing to hook up with a partner? Was a merger wishful thinking on
the part of acquisition-hungry Heinz executives? And who was the
driving force behind a pairing? Perhaps the chairman of Heinz,
Anthony F.J. O'Reilly, who ran the company for two decades but has
seen his stock languish, hitting a 52-week low last week?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, Hurricane Tony blew into the United States
and created a stir by making some proposals,'' said John McMillan
of Prudential Securities. ``I sense that Tony has 12 months to go
as chairman, and he wants to get something going. If you know Tony,
he's a talkative guy. I'm not saying he is shopping Heinz, but this
might be a case where Tony wants to be hunted.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinz would not comment on the talks and refused requests for
interviews with executives. A Bestfoods spokeswoman would not
elaborate on her company's statement.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever heat was there though _ and people close to the two
companies say preliminary discussions ended Tuesday night _ seems
to have cooled. But it could signal that Heinz may be putting
itself on the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods, with its strong international business, is not as
vulnerable as other food companies, like Heinz, which are primarily
dependent on sales in the United States for revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some investment bankers spent part of Wednesday on the
phone trying to find other suitable partners for the two companies.
That is because it's unlikely that talks would revive in the near
future given Bestfoods' statement, industry experts said.
Regulators would question whether talks had really ended. And if
they had not, Bestfoods could be the target of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz had been thinking about the idea of merging with
Bestfoods, based in Englewood Cliffs, N.J., since early this year,
people close to those talks said _ an idea several investment banks
had promoted. But in an industry ripe for consolidation, analysts
said, Bestfoods was in a stronger position to negotiate because of
its profitable international operations.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising, Heinz executives were not shy about expressing
their interest early. Jaine Mehring, a senior food analyst at
Salomon Smith Barney, said executives from Heinz invited her to
breakfast last spring and told her of their interest in a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were interested in a combination and asked me about the
synergies,'' Ms. Mehring said, recalling the conversation. Still,
Ms. Mehring said she thought it was surprising that executives _ if
indeed there were talks going on then _ would be so open with an
analyst. ``I thought, `Why are you telling this to me?''' she said.
``My response was, `Don't tell me, tell Shoemate,''' referring to
Bestfoods' chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ms. Mehring said at the company's ``Heinz 57 Weekend''
conference in Dublin, Ireland, early in August, she joked about it
with a senior vice president, Michael J. Bertasso, and an executive
vice president, Malcolm Ritchie. When they started to talk about
Heinz's international operations, ``we teased them about merging
with Bestfoods,'' she said. ``They smiled but never said
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Heinz rose $1.4375 Wednesday, to $44.625, while
Bestfoods stock soared, up $4.1875, to $53.125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
