<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FLOYD-SOUTH-BOS &LR;      09-15 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-SOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHEASTERN COAST BRACED FOR FURY OF FLOYD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ After forcing nearly 3 million people out of
their homes, Hurricane Floyd last night ended its seaward rumble up
the southeastern coast and was poised to wallop the Carolinas with
a storm surge that could rival Hurricane Hugo's catastrophic strike
a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coastal residents who had yet to flee the storm were placed
under a dusk-to-dawn curfew, as police scurried from historic
Charleston to Wilmington, N.C., to clear the streets amid the
hurricane's howling advance.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters predicted the 600-mile-wide hurricane, spewing
sustained winds of 115 miles an hour, would crash ashore with
devastating force about 2 a.m. between Myrtle Beach, S.C., and Cape
Fear, N.C. Potentially disastrous flooding and wind damage were
expected throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Before it blows out over the North Atlantic this weekend, the
storm is expected to menace most of the East Coast with high winds
and drenching rains as it roars toward New England. The National
Weather Service predicted the hurricane's remnants would pound the
New England coast through Friday with heavy rains and surging
tides, but with far less fury than the storm's assault on the
Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Though Floyd's winds had diminished from their initial 155-mph
velocity, President Clinton issued preemptive disaster declarations
for North Carolina and South Carolina, and warned residents not to
defy orders to evacuate the low-lying coastal region. He said the
storm remained highly dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that every citizen will heed the warnings of the
officials and the recommendations to take every action to protect
their families and stay out of harm's way,'' Clinton said, as he
rushed back to Washington from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane-force winds began ripping apart oceanfront sections of
South Carolina, although the Charleston area appeared to escape a
repeat of the Hugo disaster, which caused 29 deaths and $6 billion
of damage in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Floyd spared several hundred of miles of coastline from
Miami to Savannah, Ga., from the kind of destruction the storm
wrought Monday in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Fears that Floyd would devastate the southeastern coast
triggered a full-scale exodus, which Vice President Al Gore
described as ''the largest peacetime evacuation of any disaster in
the history of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Floyd contributed to monumental traffic jams that
raised serious concern up and down the coast about the safety of
state and federal evacuation plans, the hurricane largely skirted
Florida and Georgia, causing far less damage than emergency
managers had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   At its worst in Florida, the hurricane washed out piers, knocked
out power to more than 200,000, and toppled streetlights. About 350
miles off the coast, the Coast Guard rescued three people from
18-foot seas in the hurricane's path, and the Navy was searching
for five crew members of a sinking tugboat.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was too soon to know just how badly the Carolinas
would be hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Florida and Georgia at this point feel like they've
dodged a real bullet,'' said Richard Moore, North Carolina's
secretary of public safety. ''This thing is not going to miss us.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the storm was as wide as Texas and one of the most
powerful to approach the Carolinas in recent years, authorities
left little to chance. The cobblestone streets of historic
Savannah, once considered to be situated in the hurricane's direct
path, were empty but for broken tree limbs and other debris.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hyatt Regency Hotel near the banks of the Savannah River,
nearly 200 police officers had moved in and were using the building
as an emergency staging area.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the river's churning waters battered a 103-year-old
wooden ship, the Barca Negra, as its captain and owner, Gerhard
Schwisow, 52, took last-minute precautions to try to save the
antique vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to turn it into a museum,'' Schisow said, as rain
pelted his yellow slicker and the river rose. ``But I'm afraid it
might end up in the parking lot,'' Schisow said, motioning toward a
paved lot on the river's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, boat owners trying to save their property filled a city
parking lot near the Charleston waterfront with their water crafts.
</P>
<P>
   As rain lashed the empty city streets, thousands of residents
were seeking refuge in shelters or hotels far inland. Similar
scenes were evident all along the coast, after South Carolina
Governor Jim Hodges ordered the entire coastal population _ about
800,000 residents _ to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This storm is so huge,'' said Charleston Mayor Joe Riley,
``it's very unlikely that this part of South Carolina can escape
without serious damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in North Carolina issued similar assessments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
