<P>
   (NYT43) SEATTLE -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- GATES-SCHOLARSHIP, 09-15 --
William Gates, Jr., father of Bill Gates, the latter being the
founder and chairman of the Microsoft Corporation, at his home in
Seattle's exclusive Laurelhurst neighborhood earlier this month.
The elder Gates is co-chairman of the Bill and Melinda Gates
Foundation, his son's $17 billion charity organization, which will
announce on Thursday that it is pledging at least $1 billion to
fund full scholarships over the next 20 years for minority students
in the fields of education, math, science and engineering. It is by
far the younger Gates' biggest philanthropic commitment to date.
(Dan Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- KOSOVO-AMERICANS, 09-15 --
Florim Lajqi, a student at John Jay College of Criminal Justice,
looks on as a friend shows photos of a colleague who was kidnapped
in Kosovo while they were fighting for the Kosovo Liberation Army.
Last April, Lajqi was among 80 Albanian-Americans from the New York
region who volunteered to fight with the KLA. The transition back
has not been an easy one for the group that left with romantic
vision of saving their homeland and returned with troubling
memories of death and destruction. (Barbara Alper/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) DAMASCUS, Syria -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- ARAB-STORYTELLING,
09-15 --Under Hafez al-Assad's portrait, a storyteller, Rashid Abu
Shadi, reads tales of Arab tradition every night to his loyal
Syrian audience. ``It's a return to the old history books, and how
it was when the Arabs were in their glory times,'' says Shadi, 55.
Tales told at the cafe, just steps from an eighth-century mosque,
have gained a following not seen in any other modern Arab capital.
(Courtney Kealy/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- NY-MRSCLINTON, 09-15 --
Hillary Rodham Clinton, left, and Fernando Ferrer, president of the
New York borough of the Bronx, one of the city's top Puerto Rican
officials, take part in a news conference denouncing the Republican
tax cut on Wednesday. Joining three other top city Democrats, Mrs.
Clinton and Ferrer stood shoulder to shoulder during the news
conference, an apparent symbol of her desire to mend fences with
the Puerto Rican community after she angered many of them by
opposing the clemency granted by President Clinton to a group of
FALN activists. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. -- Sept. 15, 1999 --
NJ-CASINO-STRIKE, 09-15 -- Members of the Local 54 of the Hotel
Employees and Restaurant Employees International Union picket
outside Ballys Hotel and Casino on Wednesday. Casino visitors found
themselves without room service and other amenities as thousands of
workers went on strike. Miss America Pageant organizers worried the
weekend event which will take place in a local hotel could be
disrupted. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) ST. AUGUSTINE, Fla. -- Sept. 15, 1999 --
HURRICANE-FLOYD-5, 09-15 -- Cynthia Hart, a volunteer with the
local emergency operations center, pauses for a smoke next to her
pickup truck which was damaged by a tree toppled by winds from
Hurricane Floyd on Wednesday. A weakened but still terrifying
Hurricane Floyd churned its way up the Atlantic coast on Wednesday,
heading on a collision course with the Carolinas after delivering
only a glancing blow to Florida. (John Moran/The Gainesville Sun)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) CHARLESTOWN, S.C. -- Sept. 15, 1999 --
HURRICANE-FLOYD-4, 09-15 -- A woman sleeps at the Charleston
Coliseum which was turned into a shelter for people fleeing
Hurricane Floyd on Wednesday. A weakened but still terrifying
Hurricane Floyd churned its way up the Atlantic coast on Wednesday,
heading on a collision course with the Carolinas after delivering
only a glancing blow to Florida. (Keith Meyers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- NY-NEGLECTED-THEATERS,
09-15 -- The 74-year-old Biltmore Theater is the focus of a real
estate tug of war. The battle, between a real estate developer, who
says he wants to restore and book the theater, and the Nederlander
Organization, which says it may try to more than double the house's
size, has cast a light on some of Broadway's most beautiful and
neglected two-balcony theaters that have fallen into disuse.
(Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- HEDWIG-SHEEDY-2, 09-15 --
Ally Sheedy is taking over as the drag queen in ``Hedwig and the
Angry Inch,'' a role originated by John Cameron Mitchell. It is a
risky move for both performer and production. ``I'm playing her as
straight as possible to begin with,'' Ms. Sheedy says. ``And seeing
how it goes over.'' (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- HEDWIG-SHEEDY-1, 09-15 --
Ally Sheedy is taking over as the drag queen in ``Hedwig and the
Angry Inch,'' a role originated by John Cameron Mitchell (shown).
The character, created by Mitchell and the composer Stephen Trask,
demands a mix of wit, wistfulness and vocal firepower in a
90-minute monologue spiced with 10 rock songs. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- GIANT-CANE-2, 09-15 -- Dr.
Charles Peters, an ecologist, in Japanese knotweed along the Bronx
River. As the natives die, these highly invasive species come in,
and say, 'Oh yeah, we can live here,' `` says Peters. ``Nature
itself is fixing this. These plants are photosynthesizing, they're
taking water up, they're cleaning the air.'' (J. Henson Scales/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) MADISON, N.J. -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- GIANT-CANE-1, 09-15
-- Dr. Sara L. Webb, a biologist at Drew University, amid thousands
of maple seedlings in the forest preserve in Madison, where Norway
maples are edging out sugar maples. Controlling invasive plants is
now on the presidential agenda. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) LONDON -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- HOUSE-LIGHTSHOW-2, 09-15 --
Andy Warhol prints by Alastair Thain hang in the stairwell of
Isabella and Detmar Blow's new house in London's Waterloo. ``It was
originally a hatter's house,'' says Ms. Blow, 40, who is an
influential stylist and fashion powerhouse. (Jonathan Player/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) LONDON -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- HOUSE-LIGHTSHOW-1, 09-15 --
In the Vampire Room in Isabella and Detmar Blow's new house in
London's Waterloo, a David Bartlett paper table and cardboard
chairs. ``It's called Excessive Sensual Indulgence,'' Ms. Blow
says, gleefully cranking up the electronic sequencer that regulates
the pulsating fountain-shaped light sculpture in the room.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- BOULEY-DANUBE-3, 09-15 --
The dining room in David Bouley's new 3,800-square-foot restaurant,
Danube, has a gold-mica ceiling and new Vienna-modern furniture.
The restaurant's Zsa-Zsa decor is the opening shot in the New York
restaurant world's Russian-Austro-Hungarian war. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- BOULEY-DANUBE-2, 09-15 --
The Orient-Express-like bar at David Bouley's new 3,800-square-foot
restaurant, Danube. The restaurant is Bouley's interpretation of a
high-water mark in 20th-century culture: the Austria of Gustav
Mahler and Josef Hoffmann, and the arts and cuisine of the Eastern
European countries along the river Danube. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- BOULEY-DANUBE-1, 09-15 --
A new version of Klimt's ``The Kiss,'' at David Bouley's new
3,800-square-foot restaurant, Danube. ``I don't know what I'm
doing, to tell you the truth,'' he says of his newly flexed
decorating skills. ``I wanted people to have a shock.'' (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
