   (NYT26) CHICAGO -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- TREE-STUDIOS-3, 09-15 -- An
ornamental detail from the facade of a building at Tree Studios in
Chicago: the face of Anna Tree, the wife of the studio's founder,
Judge Lambert Tree. The owners have been trying for 17 years to
sell the increasingly valuable property to developers. (Steve
Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CHICAGO -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- TREE-STUDIOS-2, 09-15 --
Barton Faist is a soft-spoken artist who is battling to save his
studio and home in Tree Studios, a wondrous amalgam of gables,
carved heads, stained-glass windows and chiseled aphorisms
orignially dreamt up by a turn-of-the-century philanthropist as a
haven for struggling artists. The owners have been trying for 17
years to sell the increasingly valuable property to developers.
(Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) CHICAGO -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- TREE-STUDIOS-1, 09-15 --
The fate of Chicago's Tree Studios, created in 1894 by Judge
Lambert Tree and the oldest such artists' enclave in the country,
is in limbo. The city, in cooperation with the Shriners, who have
owned it since 1959, has imposed a nine-month moratorium on just
about anything having to do with Tree Studios. (Steve Kagan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 09-15
-- Most people think of mold and mildew as minor household
annoyances. Large infestations, however, can become a serious
health hazard. Some environmental inspectors estimate that at least
10 percent of the houses in the United States have enough mold
contamination to make the occupants sick. (Edward R. Lipinski/New
York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- CIR-TETRIS, 09-15 --
Alexey Pajitnov, the creator of Tetris, visits the XS New York game
arcade in Times Square. ``Tetris is very nonviolent,'' he says.
``You fight against chaos.'' Pajitnov is hoping to strike gold
again with a new CD-ROM-based game called Pandora's Box. The game,
which is being released this month by Microsoft, is a collection of
10 visually dazzling puzzle types with more than 350 individual
variations. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- ROSSINI-OPERA-REVIEW,
09-15 -- In the New York City Opera's first new production of the
season, Rossini's ``Viaggio a Reims,'' Kevin Glavin, Peter Strummer
and Benjamin Brecher appear with Mary Dunleavy, as the Countess of
Folleville reviving on a table bearing a hotel name. For admirers
of the bel canto style, it was an occasion to celebrate the City
Opera's tradition of exploring rarities and neglected works. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) GILMANTON, N.H. -- Sept. 15, 1999 --
CIR-COMPUTER-REBATES-2, 09-15 -- Ann Marie Carpenter has been
frustrated by long waits and deadline problems in her attempts to
cash in on software rebates. ``I don't understand why they can't
just make the stuff cheaper off the bat,'' she says. Manufacturers
and retailers of computer-related products are relying more and
more on rebates to attract customers; but often, the experience of
redeeming them is not a pleasant one. (Michael Quan/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) COVINA, Calif. -- Sept. 15, 1999 --
CIR-COMPUTER-REBATES-1, 09-15 -- Though for many, the experience of
redeeming a computer-related rebate is not a pleasant one, Tim
Duffy, a consumer advocate in Covina, likes them and says they have
saved him $1,500. ``Most people procrastinate, and companies will
profit from that,'' he says. ``But if you work at it a little and
stay on top of the deadlines, you can really have fun with it.''
(Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN FRANCISCO -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- CIR-VISOR, 09-15 --
Clockwise from left, Ed Colligan, Jeff Hawkins and Donna Dubinsky
with a Palm cousin, the Visor. The Palm look-alike offers add-on
cartridges, or modules, that will eventually turn it into, among
other things, a wireless modem, a cell phone, an MP3 player, a
two-way pager or a game machine. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- CIR-NEW-VCR-B&AMP;W, 09-15 --
Panasonic is marketing the PV-HD1000, the first digital VCR that is
designed to work with high-definition television. At least three
different formats and technologies for recording high-definition
broadcasts are butting heads in research laboratories and product
development studios around the world. (New York Times Photo)
