SCOOTER-RIDERS-BOS, 09-15 -- Krissy Mendonca gives her brother,
Steve, a ride on her scooter. Outside of Boston, scooter
enthusiasts meet several times a month to go for daylong rides and
to share scooter stories and passions. (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PEPPERELL, Mass. -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- FOOD-TOMATOES-BOS,
08-15 -- At Kimball's Fruit Farm, owner Carl Hills surrounds
himself with his latest crop of ``heirloom'' tomatoes. The success
of his tomatoes at markets around Massachusetts is part of a
growing trend. ``Heirlooms are a big thing, because a lot of
consumers aren't happy with what they're finding on supermarket
shelves,'' explained Jaime Gooch, managing editor of American
Vegetable Grower. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- SWITCH-BILLIONAIRE-BOS,
09-15 -- Robert Madonna, 39, is one of the latest entrepreneurs to
hit what some now call ``the Lucent jackpot.'' Lucent Technologies
has offered to buy his small high-tech company for more than $1.4
billion. His company, Excel Switching Corp., is the maker of
versatile telecommunications equipment in Hyannis, Mass. (Wendy
Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MELBOURNE, Fla. -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- HURRICANE-BEACHES,
09-15 --Waves whipped up by the winds from Hurricane Floyd reach a
stairway leading from a pier to the beach on Tuesday. The
evacuations, disaster declarations and emergency proclamations that
are accompanying Hurricane Floyd along the Atlantic coast are a
small taste of the worse to come, say coastal scientists and policy
makers worried about rising sea levels, more intense storms and a
ballooning coastal population. (Ernst Peters/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- NY-HURRICANE, 09-15 --
Wasyl Mychajluk, left, and Scott Koen, secure an aircraft on the
flight deck of the aircraft carrier USS Intrepid, now a museum, on
Wednesday anticipating heaving winds and rain from Hurricane Floyd.
The hurricane is expected to make landfall late tonight or early
Thursday somewhere along the North Carolina coast. From there, the
storm was expected to weaken but make life miserable all the way up
the coast toward Canada's New Brunswick. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 15, 1999 --
HURRICANE-FLOYD-3, 09-15 -- Residents look at what is left of the
Main Street Pier on Daytona Beach after a 100-feet section was
washed away by powerful waves from Hurricane Floyd on Wednesday.
Although the hurricane stayed off Florida's Atlantic coast during
the night, parts of the state were raked by strong gusts. (Timothy
O. Davis/The Gainesville Sun)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WRIGHTSVILLE BEACH, N.C. -- Sept. 15, 1999 --
HURRICANE-FLOYD-2, 09-15 -- Messages on boards Wednesday covering
the windows of a house make reference to past hurricanes and
possible future ones such as Hurricane Gert, which is shadowing
Hurricane Floyd's early path across the Atlantic Ocean. Hurricane
Floyd is expected to make landfall late Wednesday night or early
Thursday somewhere in the area of Myrtle Beach and Wilmington, N.C.
(Ken Blevins/Wilmington Star News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- BOXER-DEATH-KAN, 09-15 --
Randie Carver with his NABF supermiddleweight championship belt
after his fight against William ``Bo'' James in May. Carver's
trainer George Smith is at right. Carver, 24, died Tuesday morning,
two days after going down in the 10th round of a 12-round fight
with Kabary Salem of Brooklyn, N.Y. (Courtesy of Carver family via
Kansas City Star)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) AUSTIN, Texas -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- TEXAS-TOWER-2, 09-15
-- The body of Charles Whitman is carried from the tower at the
University of Texas after he was shot by police in 1966. The
observation deck of the tower, closed since Whitman opened fire and
killed 14 people, reopened on Wednesday. (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) AUSTIN, Texas -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- TEXAS-TOWER-1, 09-15
-- A recent aerial view of the University of Texas campus with the
main tower. After 25 years, the observation deck of the tower,
scene of a shooting rampage in 1966 that left 14 dead, reopened.
(Larry Kolvoord/Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WILMINGTON, N.C. -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- HURRICANE-FLOYD-1,
09-15 --Last minute shoppers jam the checkout counters as Hurricane
Floyd approaches on Wednesday. The storm is expected to make
landfall late Wednesday night or early Thursday somewhere in the
area of Myrtle Beach and here in Wilmington. From there, the storm
was expected to weaken but make life miserable all the way up the
coast toward Canada's New Brunswick. (Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star
News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- SOUTH-FOOTE-COX, 09-15 --
Author and historian Shelby Foote speaks on the history of the
South. Foote, perhaps the world's best-known Southern historian,
was the first in a series of speakers who will address
congressional audiences on regionalism in the American culture at
the behest of William Ferris, chairman of the National Endowment
for the Humanities (NEH). (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ATLANTA, Ga. -- Sept. 15, 1999 -- KIDS-GARDENS-COX, 09-15
-- Kieran Maynard, 9, right, and his brother Pace Maynard, 7,
enjoys the Sunflower fountain at the new Children's Garden at the
Atlanta Botanical Gardens last Thursday. Public gardens around the
country are developing programs that not only expose future
generations to the joys of plants but, on a more practical level,
help the new gardens help generate more income from admissions.
(William Berry/New York Times Photo)
</P>
