<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BLACKS-MORTAGES-NYT &LR;      09-15 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-MORTAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIAS WORSENS FOR MINORITIES BUYING HOMES, STUDIES SAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa., N.Y.)  (rk) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Discrimination against black and Hispanic home
buyers has worsened as the economy has strengthened, two reports
released Wednesday by the Clinton administration show.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of ``a great economy, a great Dow Jones,
discrimination is getting worse, not just flourishing,'' said
Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo at a news conference where he
introduced the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks were twice as likely as whites, and Hispanic-Americans 1
1/2 times as likely, to be denied a conventional, 30-year home loan
last year, according to one of the two studies, by the Association
of Community Organizations for Reform Now, a housing advocacy group
with branches in most big cities. ACORN, as it is known, reported
that disparities in rejections have worsened since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The second study, by the Urban Institute, a nonpartisan research
organization here, showed that discrimination was the reason for
the disparity, said Cuomo, whose agency commissioned the study. The
institute dispatched pairs of white and minority group members,
each pair with the same incomes, assets and job, credit histories
and neighborhoods, to seek mortgages from lenders throughout the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, minorities were less likely to receive information
about loan products, received less time and information from loan
officers and were quoted higher interest rates in most of the
cities where tests were conducted,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the only difference is the color of their skin,'' said
Cuomo, who presented the studies as part of an effort to press his
case for increases in money to enforce the Fair Housing and Equal
Opportunity law, which Republicans in Congress propose to cut.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid, executive vice president of the Mortgage Bankers
Association of America, said, ``We'd be the first to admit that
there are some gaps to be closed in home ownership rates among
blacks and whites.'' The Census Bureau reports that 67 percent of
whites own homes, compared with 45 percent for both blacks and
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The figures also represent some closing of the gap, said Steven
Hornburg, director of research at the Research Institute for
Housing America, an affiliate of the mortgage bankers association.
Citing Census Bureau and other data, he said home ownership among
blacks has grown since 1994 by 7.8 percent, among Hispanics by 8.5
percent and among whites by 3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the ACORN study said, a survey of mortgage loans
granted by 11,029 banks in 41 cities showed that black applicants
were rejected 217 percent as often as whites last year, or more
than double the rate. In 1995, which the group called the peak year
for lending to blacks, the rejection rate was 184 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The disparities varied greatly among the cities that the group
studied. In Chicago, it said, the black applicants last year were
denied loans almost four times _ the rate was 363 percent _ as
often as whites. At the other extreme was Pittsburgh, where the
rate was 128 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the rejection rate for blacks was relatively high _
228 percent last year, an increase from 184 percent in 1995. The
rates there for Hispanics were 182 percent last year and 170
percent four years ago. ACORN said the number of conventional
mortgages made to blacks declined 2.8 percent over the three years,
rose 3.6 percent for Hispanics and rose 61.1 percent for whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``These findings are especially troubling,'' the group's study
concluded, ``in light of the fact that both the unemployment and
interest rates have been at their lowest in decades. Even with
these economic conditions, minorities were unable to gain much
ground, and black and Hispanic home-ownership rates are still less
than two-thirds the home-ownership rate of whites.''
</P>
</TEXT>
