<HEADLINE>
FIRM IN BANK SCANDAL MAY HAVE USED FLEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A shadowy New York company at the heart of a growing
probe into an alleged multibillion-dollar Russian money-laundering
scheme had accounts at New England's leading bank, sources familiar
with the matter said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Benex International Co., opened approximately four
accounts at Fleet Financial Group Inc. branches in New York and
Pennsylvania, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, unnamed US firms used their BankBoston corporate
accounts to wire money to accounts held by Benex and related firms
at other banks, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Boston-based banks transferred several million
dollars on behalf of Benex and related companies over the past 18
months, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in the midst of an extensive investigation that
surfaced last month say up to $10 billion tied to organized crime
and corporate fraud in Russia may have passed through accounts held
by Benex at the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators probing the Bank of New York, in what amounts to
the largest money-laundering inquiry in US history, suspect Benex,
a trading company, of having ties to alleged Russian mob boss
Semyon Mogilevich.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Bureau of Investigation, the Department of Justice,
and other investigators leading the inquiry have long suspected
that US and overseas banks have been used as ``revolving doors'' to
shift ill-gotten Russian gains into Western accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two major banks in Boston have been used for that
purpose,'' said one of the sources, adding that in contrast to the
Bank of New York, Fleet and BankBoston did not appear to be an
end-point for Benex-related money. In other words, the source said,
the Boston banks were conduits, rather than repositories, of
Benex-related finances, and transferred money to Benex accounts at
the Bank of New York. Still, sources said a dozen Fleet staffers
had been ``frantically'' combing through tens of thousands of
documents pertaining to Benex since the probe first came to light
Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of Fleet's and BankBoston's roles sheds new light
on what authorities suspect is a worldwide web of tainted money
flowing out of a corrupt and ailing Russia. Several European banks
recently notified regulators of suspicious activity.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston, which have merged, had not approached
regulators or authorities about their Benex-related activities and
had not been contacted by investigators, sources said. A Fleet
spokesman, James Mahoney, said Fleet had a policy of not discussing
individual accounts. BankBoston officials were not available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   It is uncertain how much of the money in question is linked to
organized crime, and how much is simply capital that fled Russia.
Money laundering _ the illegal shuffling of illicit gains through
shell companies and multiple bank accounts to make them appear
legitimate _ is difficult to track and even harder to prove. And it
is unclear whether Russian companies stashing profits abroad are
violating any laws other than their own.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Bank of New York probe has sparked fresh debate over
the West's political and economic support of Russia since the 1991
Soviet collapse. Investigators are exploring whether International
Monetary Fund aid to Russia was illegally diverted to Bank of New
York accounts, and whether Russian trading firms are using Western
banks to dodge tax inspectors back home.
</P>
<P>
   Benex, with operations in Queens, N.Y., and London, was headed
by Peter Berlin, a Russian emigre who is married to a former senior
Bank of New York executive, Lucy Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin and Edwards, a Leningrad-born emigre who set up Benex's
nine Bank of New York accounts and who was fired from her job after
the investigation surfaced, each held personal checking accounts at
Fleet, according to sources. The accounts were opened through Fleet
branches in New York and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and the Justice Department declined to comment on money
transfers made by or on the behalf of Benex through Fleet and
BankBoston. The Federal Reserve Bank of Boston and the Office of
the Comptroller of the Currency also declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sources did not know what had triggered Fleet's inquiry into its
Benex-related activities but said the bank was hampered by obsolete
computer systems that made it difficult to track quickly the tens
of thousands of electronic wire transfers it processes daily. The
OCC, an industry regulator, launched a special inquiry of Fleet's
technology and monitoring systems earlier this year, one source
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
