Charles Peters, an ecologist, in Japanese knotweed along the Bronx
River. As the natives die, these highly invasive species come in,
and say, 'Oh yeah, we can live here,' `` says Peters. ``Nature
itself is fixing this. These plants are photosynthesizing, they're
taking water up, they're cleaning the air.'' (J. Henson Scales/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
