<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3589 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-RUIZ-(TRIMS)-N     09-15 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-RUIZ-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S FORMER DRUG CHIEF, INDICTED IN U.S., FOUND DEAD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TIM GOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mario Ruiz Massieu, a volatile lawyer who was the most prominent
former Mexican official ever indicted on drug charges in the United
States, died Wednesday in New Jersey, an apparent suicide, his
lawyers and government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz Massieu, 48, who once headed anti-drug efforts under former
Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, had been scheduled to
travel to Houston on Thursday for his first appearance in federal
court on drug and money laundering charges that were filed against
him there late last month.
</P>
<P>
   One of his Mexican lawyers, Xavier Olea Pelaez, said that after
living under house arrest with his family in New Jersey for the
last four years, Ruiz Massieu feared that he would be unable to
make bail and would be sent immediately to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have the money and he believed that he was not going
to be able to post bond,'' Olea Pelaez said. ``He got desperate,
and he took that very difficult decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution of Ruiz Massieu had been a landmark in efforts
by the United States and Mexico to challenge the official
corruption that has helped the drug trade grow into what Mexican
officials call the most serious threat to their national security.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said his death shut the door on a case
that took years to build, and one in which they had hoped he might
yet agree to reveal the complicity of even more senior Mexican
officials with the traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Ruiz Massieu was found unconscious at his home in
Palisades Park, N.J., by his wife, Maria, who called 911 shortly
after 1:40 p.m. He was pronounced dead on arrival at Englewood
Hospital and Medical Center about 40 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz Massieu's principal lawyer in the United States, Cathy
Fleming, denied that he had been distraught over the legal case
against him, but noted that he had been treated for clinical
depression ``for a substantial period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   She said he had always insisted on his innocence and had done so
in a series of notes that he left behind for his family and
friends, as well as a public statement that was to be released at a
news conference on Thursday. Another person close to the Ruiz
Massieu family said the statement attacked the Mexican government
for what it characterized as malicious, unfounded attacks against
him.
</P>
<P>
   Two local officials in New Jersey speculated that Ruiz Massieu
had swallowed the contents of several bottles of prescription pills
that were found at his home. But an assistant prosecutor in the
Bergen County prosecutor's office, James Santulli, said the cause
of his death would have to be determined by an autopsy on Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The apparent suicide ends one of the more twisted political and
criminal sagas in recent Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz Massieu first gained wide notoriety in 1994, after Salinas
chose him to serve as deputy attorney general for the last seven
months of the administration. It was a period of political chaos in
Mexico, and a high point in the flow of South American cocaine
through the country to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Ruiz Massieu cast himself publicly as a crusader
against the drug trade and the corrupt officials who took bribes to
abet it. He also led a tumultuous investigation into the
assassination in that fall of his older brother, Jose Francisco, a
leading figure in the long-governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, though, U.S. law-enforcement and intelligence
officials were already concluding that Mario Ruiz Massieu was not
the man he claimed to be. Even before he left office in late 1994 _
railing at supposed efforts by other governing-party leaders to
block the investigation into his brother's murder _ American
diplomats asked secretly that he be barred from any senior position
in the new government.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1995, Salinas' elder brother, Raul Salinas, was
arrested on charges of ordering the death of Jose Francisco Ruiz
Massieu. The two men were said to have had some personal
differences stemming from Ruiz Massieu's one-time marriage to the
Salinas brothers' sister, Adriana, and Mexican officials also
claimed that Ruiz Massieu had emerged as a political rival of Raul
Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the arrest of Raul Salinas, Mario Ruiz Massieu
fled Mexico after being questioned by the authorities there. He was
intercepted by federal agents as he waited for a connecting flight
at Newark International Airport and was held initially on charges
of failing to declare all the currency he was bringing through the
country.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Customs agents, however, had already come upon $9 million
that Ruiz Massieu had deposited in a pair of Houston banks during
the last two years of his service to the Salinas administration.
Most of the deposits were made by one of his close aides, who
routinely walked into the banks with huge amounts of cash stuffed
into suitcases and cardboard boxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
