<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-TRADING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK NETWORKS AGREE TO SHARE TRADING DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to create a single market for after-hours stock
trading, eight electronic stock trading systems signed a letter of
intent Wednesday to share price information and other market data.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, while preliminary, could reduce the fragmentation
that has developed as the new electronic trading systems have
competed for customer orders, thereby helping to make a new and
rapidly growing venue for stock trading fairer and more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, customers of any one of the trading systems could be
able to see prices being bid and offered for stocks on each of the
other seven systems, known as electronic communications networks,
or ECNs. In addition, customers could be able to route their orders
to whichever market has the best price, an executive of one of the
participating companies said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a commitment to create an after-hours electronic
trading network that will be the future of what the markets are
going to look like,'' said Michael Satow, president of MarketXT
Inc., an electronic network that last month began offering an
after-hours trading session to individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   The eight electronic communications networks that signed the
letter of intent _ MarketXT, Archipelago, Tradebook, Brut,
Instinet, Redibook, Strike and Island _ have emerged in the last
year as the most virulent competitive threats to the New York Stock
Exchange and the NASDAQ stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But even as investors and regulators have embraced the concept
of greater competition in financial markets, many of them have
expressed fears that the rapid growth of new trading systems will
result in a fractured market that is less efficient and more costly
for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have contended that instead of promoting a national
market for stock trading, the electronic networks will breed chaos,
a disconnected system of independent clubs whose members will never
know whether or not they were getting good prices for their trades.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement to share price and other information addresses
those concerns, Satow said. ``All the competing players have come
together with a unified vision of what we want the market to look
like,'' he said. ``We believe it's in the interest of investors for
them to know they are able to get the best prices,'' whichever
network they use.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most of the networks have focused their efforts on
after-hours trading, which takes place outside normal market hours,
which on the East Coast last from 9:30 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. In
addition, some of the trading networks have begun offering trading
early in the morning, before the national markets open for
business.
</P>
<P>
   One of the attractions of after-hours trading is that it opens
markets later in the day for investors in the western United
States, who currently are all but unable to trade stocks much after
lunch time.
</P>
<P>
   Instinet, the largest of the networks, has long offered big
institutions like pension funds and insurance companies the ability
to trade stocks with each other after normal trading hours. But
until recently, individuals have been shut out of those efforts. In
the last month, several electronic networks as well as some
traditional brokerage firms have begun to offer after-hours trading
to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, both NASDAQ and the New York Stock Exchange
said they planned to expand their trading hours, but deferred the
efforts until next year, partly in response to questions raised
about the plans by securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Further details of the agreement among the networks are expected
to be announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The very existence of networks as viable threats to the
established structure of the nation's financial markets has come
about because of cheap and powerful technology and a loosening of
rules that kept the stock-trading business in the hands of a few
powerful institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest investors in some of the networks are several
major Wall Street firms, including Goldman, Sachs; J.P. Morgan, and
Merrill Lynch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
