<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON SCURRIES OVER FLOYD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The streets cleared. Grown men scurried out of
their Capitol Hill offices and rushed out the doors. The House went
home.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the nasty political fights and scandals. There is no
force that so instills fear into Washingtonians as weather _ any
kind of weather.
</P>
<P>
   This is a city that has closed schools at the threat of snow, a
place where children have been sent home from class because it was
too hot. Snow in Washington is treated as a space alien landing by
many skittish Washington drivers, even though there is some snow
nearly every winter.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise when Washington _ as of Wednesday night,
marred by only a mere drizzle of warm rain _ reacted Wednesday with
characteristic panic at the prospect of an unwelcome visit from
Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing, particularly when you're from New England,''
said Representative Martin T. Meehan, Democrat of Massachusetts.
``They are having an overreaction to the weather, definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   With tropical storm warnings for the metropolitan area, most
schools around Washington announced Wednesday afternoon that they
would be closed Thursday. District of Columbia employees were
offered ``liberal leave,'' meaning they can be late or not show up.
But federal employees in the nation's capital were expected to
arrive at work on time.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Anthony Williams warned of possible downed trees, power
outages, and flooding along the Potomac.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful that House members might not make it their home
districts in time for the weekend because of flight delays or
cancellations, House leaders closed up shop Wednesday afternoon,
recessing until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate remained in session, with votes still scheduled
through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional committees and political candidates frantically
faxed cancellation notices around town of previously scheduled
hearings and appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole postponed a
planned visit Thursday to Melrose, Mass., where she was set to
discuss education issues. The event has been rescheduled for next
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, stopping over in Hawaii on his way back from
New Zealand, dropped plans for a golf game to rush back to
Washington to monitor the weather emergency. He urged Americans to
``stay out of harm's way,'' and to leave affected areas if
necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
