A3597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-BAHAMAS16-COX     09-15 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-BAHAMAS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bahamas take beating from Floyd
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSH HARBOR, Bahamas _ The idyllic coves of the Abacos were
littered with sunken and beached boats and lined with hundreds of
homes heavily damaged from the 150 mph winds and sea surges of
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, 24 hours after the storm's eye passed over this
island, 170 miles east of Palm Beach, officials said damages would
run in the millions of dollars. It looked to be the hardest hit of
all the islands, according to the U.S. Coast Guard, which sent a
Falcon jet to survey the islands.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd's winds also did significant damage to Treasure Cay, San
Salvador and Grand Bahama.
</P>
<P>
   But only one death was reported, a drowning on Grand Bahama
Island, 55 miles east of Palm Beach, in swells reported up to 6
feet. Freeport resident Bobby Tinker disappeared west of town when
he tried to swim from a van that got stuck in storm surge.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of deaths in the Abacos, which officials
said was due to a forced evacuation that began Monday night. More
than 900 people weathered the storm in the St. Francis de Sales
school in Marsh Harbour.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Sawyer, assistant chief of Marsh Harbor's 20-member
volunteer fire department said, ``Every time we go out, we see more
and more destruction,'' he said. ``It will take weeks to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the costliest damage to Marsh Harbor was on the downtown
waterfront, where a floating bar called the Tiki Hut sank, and
sailboats, 60-foot lobster trawlers and cabin cruisers, were pushed
on shore by sea surges. Car-sized shipping containers were tossed
into the air, landing at the door of the Pizza Hut and in
neighbors' yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``My refrigerator is on the other side of the canal and I got a
TV set down the road,'' said Wendy Gwynn, whose Abaco Club condo
facing the eastern ocean filled with 5 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a disaster like this,'' said Angela Cash, a
20-year-resident of the island who also has a home in Haverhill
near West Palm Beach. ``There is not a person that hasn't lost
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest loss may have been on Hope Town, a key off the
eastern coast of the Abacos. The island was cut in half by the
storm, washing away seven homes and the Abaco Inn, said Silbert
Mills, mayor for the central Abacos. Ferry docks carrying
passengers to the key were destroyed by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   A central city shantytown called the Mud was knee-deep in water
and littered with tin and tarpaper from the homes occupied by the
island's Haitian residents.
</P>
<P>
   In Murphy Town just outside Marsh Harbour, several homes were
flattened by the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the end,'' said Wellington Davis, 46, who
rode out the storm in his concrete block home on a ridge
overlooking the sea. Davis said he was holding on his door knob
with both hands when he saw the roof being lifted by the 150 mph
winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the roof going, I jumped out the window and ran
down the street,'' said Davis, who sat on the rumble of his home
Wednesday wondering why he didn't obey evacuation orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time they say go, they won't have to tell me twice,''
said Davis, still shaken by the afternoon of terror. ``The Bible
says the Lord will not put more burden on you then you can bear _
but he sure tested me yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   The eye passed over about 2 p.m., giving the island an hour of
moderate winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very frightening,'' said Elizabeth Risberg, who spent
the night with her husband and three kids at a friend's house.
``The pressure was so bad it popped your ears as if you were on an
airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Seas surrounding the island looked like a muddy pond from silt
stirred up by the storm. Lobster fisherman Terrance Davis, 30, said
it would be about two months before the seas are clear enough to
set traps.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers John Pacenti and Cheryl Blackerby contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
