<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WGBH-DONOR-LISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CRITIC FAULTS WGBH ON USE OF CONSULTANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One month after WGBH-TV came under fire for sharing
donors' names with the Democratic Party, the station arranged a
series of focus groups to see how the public felt about the
controversy, station officials acknowledged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the station's choice of consultants that has aroused
WGBH's already energized critics.
</P>
<P>
   John Marttila, a Democratic consultant and pollster, was paid
approximately $20,000 by WGBH to gauge public sentiment toward
Boston's public television station in August, the chairman of the
House Telecommunications subcommittee said Wednesday.
Representative W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, a Republican of Louisiana,
called the action ethically questionable and demanded further
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has come to my attention that WGBH in Boston, which first
triggered the controvery over the sale, purchase, and rental of
donor lists between public broadcasters and political
organizations, has once again engaged in questionable ethical _ if
not legal _ practices,'' Tauzin wrote in letter to the inspector
general of the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, which oversees
funding for public stations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH officials had thought they finished defending themselves to
Congress last week, following the release of the inspector
general's report that detailed the station's list-swapping
practices. The station gave out donors' names twice, both times by
mistake, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement was something of a surprise to station
officials, who said they had conducted the focus groups in good
faith. Jeanne M. Hopkins, vice president of communications for
WGBH, said, ``If the implication is that we hired a Democratic
pollster, that's simply not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Marttila has worked for Democratic Senator John F. Kerry of
Massachusetts, as well as for Representative Edward J. Markey, the
Massachusetts Democrat who sits on the telecommunications
subcommittee that controls funding for public broadcasting. But
Hopkins said Marttila's political ties are irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Marttila is an opinion researcher, a well-respected
opinion researcher, who has been working in Boston for 20 years,''
Hopkins said. ``Is there supposed to be some kind of litmus test
for who you hire to do your work based on their personal
affiliation? I can't imagine it would be appropriate before you
hire somebody to ask whether they are a Democrat or a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, according to a spokesman for Tauzin, is not just
that Marttila has built a reputation on his success in helping
Democrats. It is that WGBH would do business with any political
entity, or perceived political entity, given the controversy over
the list-swapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't seem to get it,'' said Ken Johnson, Tauzin's
spokesman. ``We don't want any interaction at all between public
broadcasting and politicians and political parties. We are going to
put an end to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Marttila said the focus groups were not partisan. He called
Tauzin's allegations ``just disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was a shred of partisanship to it _ zero,
none, period,'' Marttila said of the focus groups. ``The WGBH
leadership conducted themselves in the most exemplary fashion. They
treated, I think, this entire issue seriously and appropriately.''
He said the use of the focus groups proved WGBH was ``extremely
responsive to its membership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really corporate concern at the highest level,''
Marttila said.
</P>
<P>
   Station officials did not disclose the amount paid to Marttila.
But Hopkins said he was not paid with federal funds. She also said
the focus groups helped shape new guidelines for WGBH, including a
provision that will clearly tell donors how to check off a box that
ensures their names are not swapped with other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped us understand what people viewed as important,''
Hopkins said. As for Tauzin's allegations, she said: ``I just don't
understand. We thought we were taking extra steps to be thorough
and responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Inspector General Kenneth A. Konz, Tauzin
requested an investigation to determine whether Marttila was paid
with federal funds. Konz did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
