<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE MUSICAL CHAIRS; QUESTIONS ABOUT BUCHANAN; DEMOCRATS
TAKE A CUE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Musical Chairs Time in Conservative Camp
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, the conservative advocate of family values, has been
riding high since he finished a solid fourth in last month's
Republican presidential straw poll in Iowa. The way he sees his
finish, though he was beaten by George W. Bush, Steve Forbes and
Elizabeth Dole, he nevertheless finished far enough ahead of the
rest of the 10-candidate field, especially other hard-core
conservatives like Pat Buchanan and Dan Quayle, to lay claim to the
title of new leader of the Christian right.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But that's not good enough for Charles Jarvis, an old
friend who worked with Bauer in the Reagan administration, who has
strong ties to Christian conservatives and who has been national
chairman of the Bauer campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday he quit. Worse, he signed on as a strategist with
Forbes, whose national poll numbers are a bit higher than Bauer's,
whose pockets are infinitely deeper and who has recently been
laboring mightily to persuade Christian right Republicans that he
is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Bauer, my friend and colleague for 16 years, cannot
win,'' Jarvis said. ``We waged a valiant effort in Iowa. But we
must be honest with ourselves. This is now a race between George W.
Bush and Steve Forbes. Steve Forbes is the only conservative who
can win. It is time for all conservatives to rally behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Who Gets Hurt if Buchanan Bolts
</P>
<P>
   So far, Pat Buchanan is only talking about bolting the
Republican Party to join the Reform Party. But suppose he actually
makes the leap, as seems more and more likely with each passing
Buchanan lament about how the Grand Old Party has lost its
conservative moorings?
</P>
<P>
   The widespread assumption among political pros has been that
should he switch and go on to win the Reform nomination, his
hard-right following would make the switch with him. In such a
case, the reasoning goes, the Republican nominee would be hurt more
in the fall by his defection than the Democratic nominee, even
though Buchanan might siphon a nice bit of Democratic votes by
adding some Reform reformism to his hard-right pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a poll that gives a bit of underpinning to that
assumptive scenario, including the part that assumes Buchanan has
no real shot at becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   Conducted last weekend by the nonpartisan Pew Research Center
for the People and the Press, the poll found that if the
presidential election were held now and the candidates were Bush
and Gore, Bush would win 54 percent to 39 percent, with 7 percent
undecided. But in a three-way contest between Bush, Gore and
Buchanan, Bush would win by 49 percent, with Gore finishing second
with 35 percent, Buchanan coming in third with 10 percent and 6
percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Buchanan would cut Bush's lead, albeit narrowly
_ but many presidential races are decided narrowly. In fact, when
the Pew people took a closer look at the results of the poll, which
covered 1,025 voters and had a sampling error margin of plus or
minus three percentage points, they found, ominously for Bush, that
of the voters who chose Buchanan in the three-way contest, two of
every three had been Bush supporters in the Bush-Gore matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this early state, Bush's big lead over Gore does not appear
vulnerable to a third party challenge from Pat Buchanan,'' Andrew
Kohut, the center's director, said. ``However, in a closer race, a
Reform Party bid by the conservative commentator might mean trouble
for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   UTAH: Democrats Learn A Republican Trick
</P>
<P>
   When Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah finally jumped into the Republican
presidential contest last summer, the leader, Bush, was somewhere
up in the 50s in the polls and somewhere around the $36 million
mark in raising campaign cash. The senator predicted his message of
solid conservatism would eventually enable him to overtake Bush in
the polls. As for catching up with the governor in the
money-raising business, well, he had this hot idea.
</P>
<P>
   All it would take, he said, was for one million people to give
him $36 each. ``George Bush has the fat cats,'' Hatch said. ``I
want the skinny cats.''
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on how much cash that scheme has brought in. But it
has given Utah Democrats an idea.
</P>
<P>
   For next year's Senate race, they say they will make 15,000
phone calls and mail out 10,000 letters in which they will ask for
donations of $36 to take on Hatch or whomever else the Republicans
put up.
</P>
<P>
   One catch, though.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats don't have a candidate yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
