<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOTOROLA CONFIRMS A DEAL TO BUY GENERAL INSTRUMENT
</P>
<P>
   Motorola confirmed that it would acquire General Instrument, a
maker of cable set-top boxes, in a stock deal valued at nearly $11
billion. The move would make Motorola a key supplier of cable
television equipment and allow the company to develop what it calls
a ``home hub'' of products.
</P>
<P>
   The company says that the deal gives it a passageway into the
homes of millions of consumers and that it plans to develop set-top
boxes with cable modems that will enable consumers to surf the Web,
make telephone calls, use e-mail and tune into interactive video.
Shares of Motorola fell $6.5625, to $86.625.
</P>
<P>
   EX-CBS EXECUTIVE HIRED BY REPLAY
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Replay Networks, a company offering a new video
recording device that some analysts think will revolutionize the
way viewers watch television, said it would name Kim LeMasters, a
former chief programmer for CBS, as its chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT IN A STOCK DEAL FOR VISIO
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is buying Visio, a maker of diagramming and technical
drawing software, in a $1.3 billion stock deal. Visio's products
let professionals like corporate administrators and designers make
flow and organizational charts and more technical drawings.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ LEADS OTHER GAUGES LOWER
</P>
<P>
   Stocks closed broadly lower as continued nervousness over
interest rates and the dollar dashed an early rally. The Dow Jones
industrial average tumbled 108.91 points, or 1 percent, to
10,801.42. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index dropped 18.32
points, or 1.4 percent, to 1,317.97, and the NASDAQ composite index
fell 54.12 points, or 1.9 percent, to 2,814.17.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices rebounded somewhat as the yield on the 30-year
Treasury fell to 6.10 percent from 6.12 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   MAYTAG TO REVAMP AND CUT COSTS
</P>
<P>
   Maytag, faced with slumping share prices on fears of a profit
slowdown, said it would realign its divisions, sharply cut costs
and try to shore up flagging sales of its discount appliances.
Lloyd Ward, Maytag's chairman and chief executive, said that the
company would cut more than $100 million in costs over the next two
years, develop an electronic commerce strategy and expand in
international markets.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACT REACHED AT TIRE FACTORY
</P>
<P>
   The United Steelworkers of America reached a tentative contract
at the Continental General Tire factory in Charlotte, N.C., ending
a nearly yearlong strike by 1,450 workers.
</P>
<P>
   TRADING AT ONLINE BROKERS SLUMPS
</P>
<P>
   The trading volume at online brokerage firms slumped far more
than expected in July and August. Still, some industry analysts are
sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   WAL-MART CLARIFIES PHARMACY POLICY
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores has instructed its pharmacists to fill all
prescriptions, and Planned Parenthood, which had criticized
Wal-Mart for not carrying a morning-after birth control pill,
praised the move.
</P>
<P>
   COLLECTING TAXES ON E-COMMERCE
</P>
<P>
   A panel of executives and politicians voted to push ahead to
develop a system to help Web-based businesses collect state and
local sales taxes on Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   BANK SCANDAL WORSENS IN INDONESIA
</P>
<P>
   A bank scandal in Indonesia appeared to worsen when the nation's
central bank assailed auditors working at the request of the
International Monetary Fund, who have implicated the central bank
in a questionable deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
