<SLUG> BC-SCI-VT-STARGAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN BACKS PRISON OVER UNTARNISHED SKY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (nk) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Vt. _ Amateur astronomers who cherish Vermont's
dark night skies suffered a blow on Tuesday when residents of this
economically depressed town voted to allow construction of a prison
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomy enthusiasts fear that the 350-bed prison's glaring
lights will spoil viewing from one of New England's main
star-gazing centers, Breezy Hill, which is 3.8 miles from the
prison site.
</P>
<P>
   Every August, amateur astronomers and telescope makers from
across the nation converge on the 80-acre Breezy Hill for a
gathering known as Stellafane, an annual event since 1926. It is
attended by thousands of star-gazing campers and others, many with
home-made telescopes the size of artillery pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Breezy Hill is also the site of a year-round observatory with
several research-caliber telescopes built by semiprofessional
astronomers. All of the work is carried out by volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Many organizers and participants in Stellafane have played
important roles in professional astronomy. Among Stellafane's
founders was Russell W. Porter, who was a major participant in the
design and construction of the 200-inch telescope on Mount Palomar,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Among Stellafane's most ardent partisans is David H. Levy,
co-discoverer with Dr. Eugene Shoemaker of a comet named for the
two that broke apart in 1994 as it was drawn toward Jupiter,
creating fireworks visible from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In a plea opposing the prison construction published in the
October issue of the magazine Sky &AMP; Telescope, Levy wrote:
``Stellafane is a magical place, a sanctuary to the stars. Steeped
in tradition, it is the birthplace of the hobby of amateur
telescope making.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the new prison, who include Gov. Howard Dean,
argued that the prison's lights would have a minimal effect on star
gazing.
</P>
<P>
   But Levy said: ``Its grounds will be as bright as day. I have
given astronomy lectures at prisons before, and I'm amazed at how
bright the sky glow can be, even if the lights are well shielded.''
</P>
<P>
   The balloting by Springfield residents on Tuesday was a re-vote.
The first, on June 29, was so close (1,633 in favor of the prison
and 1,564 opposed) that Stellafane supporters successfully
petitioned for a second vote. It went decisively against them, with
2,345 favoring the prison and 1,535 against.
</P>
<P>
   Springfield, once an important center of machine tool
manufacturing, has been economically depressed for many years, and
the state's offer of $7 million in incentives for allowing the
prison to be built nearby proved to be attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Maryann V. Arrien of Putnam Valley, N.Y., president of the
Vermont Amateur Telescope Makers Club and the spokeswoman for
Stellafane, said Wednesday that the group would continue to press
for light shielding and whatever measures might mitigate pollution
of the night sky when the prison is completed in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we know that the Vermont prison at Newport near the
Canadian border is so bright that objects on the prison grounds
cast shadows on the clouds above,'' Ms. Arrien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're deeply sorry,'' she said, ``but we respect the
democratic will of the people of Springfield.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
