<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-FLAECONOMY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floyd leaves shift in Fla. business
 &HT;    By Stephanie Smith
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Floyd flinched, but not before forcing
construction projects, restaurants, beer delivery trucks and
beachfront hotels to lose as much as two days of business.
</P>
<P>
   Barrier island hotels such as The Breakers in Palm Beach, the
Boca Raton Resort &AMP; Club and Sheraton Oceanfront Resort in Singer
Island bused patrons to safety, sending guests to hotels on
Florida's west coast or the Keys.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the inconvenience and fear, some guests such as a group
of vacationers from the United Kingdom found the thought of
impending disaster fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could sense they found it intriguing, they're eyes were wide
open like it was an adventure,'' said Stephen Kappeler, the
Sheraton Oceanfront's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-room hotel lost about $20,000, which includes
cancellations of 80 reservations because of Floyd, he said. The
hotel hired a bus to take 43 guests to a four-star resort in
Marathon Key on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, inland hotels did a banner business, with rooms
filled to capacity by residents forced to evacuate their homes or
stranded travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Taylor West, a professor at the University of Florida's
Bureau of Economics and Business Research, said Wednesday that it
would be difficult to gauge the storm's economic impact because
services and sales merely may have shifted from one business to
another or may have been postponed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't get my hair done for a day because of the
hurricane, it doesn't mean I'm not going to get it done at all for
the next two months,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   At William Thies &AMP; Sons in Fort Pierce, which typically makes
350 deliveries of Miller, Heineken, Molson and Samuel Adams beers
from the Palm Beach County line north to Indian River County, brisk
beer sales offset a delivery shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the week, it'll be a wash,'' said general
manager Pete Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants such as Howley's in West Palm Beach closed Tuesday,
anticipating the arrival of Floyd. The restaurant opened for
breakfast on Wednesday, but had to close at 2 p.m., because of a
shortage of food and staff.
</P>
<P>
   Many construction companies didn't bother to reopen Wednesday
because of the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Roberts, manager of Zeiger Crane Rental Inc. in West Palm
Beach, said the business was closed Tuesday and Wednesday because
construction projects stopped. The company typically handles 35
jobs a day, renting 180-foot cranes.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Home Depot, which shipped more than 580,000 sheets of
plywood to Florida stores Monday and Tuesday, compared to the
typical 13,000 sheets a day, it wasn't all good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't building decks or reseeding lawns when there's a
hurricane approaching,'' said Home Depot spokesman Don Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, those people were snapping up flashlights and
batteries. Every Home Depot from Marathon Key to Virginia Beach,
Va., sold a year's supply of those items on Monday alone.
</P>
<P>
   The company allows returns of unused storm supplies, such as
lumber and generators, but there weren't many returns Wednesday.
Hurricane Gert and concerns about year 2000 computer problems
probably have people holding onto their generators and plywood,
Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Even newspapers have to cope with losing business because of a
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Post's Advertising Operations Manager Gregg Harr
said that businesses typically pull their advertisements in advance
of a storm, although some of that loss is made up with unexpected
advertisers, such as insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, a lot of stores are preoccupied by being closed so
there's no use advertising,'' Harr said. ``And, a lot of
advertisers are concerned about how much time people are going to
spend reading their paper or even if the paper will be delivered,''
Harr said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Ava Van de Water contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
