<HEADLINE>
SEVEN REPORTED KILLED AT FORT WORTH CHURCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A gunman walked into a sanctuary full of
young people at a southwest Fort Worth Baptist church Wednesday
evening and began firing, killing seven, including himself,
officials said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred at Wedgwood Baptist Church about 7 p.m.
during a rally related to ``See You at The Pole,'' which attracted
hundreds of teen-agers from several area churches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the gunman entered the church, a number of teens thought it
was a skit, witnesses said. But members of Forty Days, the band
playing at the event, reportedly started ducking behind
amplifiers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports also indicated that a pipe bomb might have
exploded, sending shrapnel all the way into the balcony. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's cartridges, shrapnel and empty cart boxes and blood
splattered all over the wall,'' said Lt. David Ellis, a police
spokesman at the scene. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gunman was wearing a black leather jacket, bluejeans and a
bandanna when he walked into the church. A number of church members
said they did not recognize the man. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An off-duty police officer who lives near the church heard the
shots and called 911. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One man was reportedly taken into custody for questioning, but
police did not say why. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Dickens, 14, said she was sitting in the second pew in
the sanctuary when the gunman entered through the rear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had just finished singing and we were praying when he came
in,'' Dickens said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As many as 400 people may have been in the sanctuary, witnesses
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was a joke,'' Dickens said. ``We were singing,
and he told us to shut up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gunman then began shooting in different directions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was our pastor playing a joke on us. But then
Cassie got hit in the throat. She never got up,'' Dickens said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Rutledge and wife, Sundi, both 22, were in the fellowship
hall attending a prayer meeting when they heard a commotion
elsewhere in the church. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was hammering,'' said Kevin Rutledge, a
ministerial student at Dallas Baptist University. But minutes
later, he heard someone saying, ``I'm not joking, I'm shot.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The church's pastor, Al Meredith, was at home when the shooting
occurred and was notified when a reporter called him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A woman in the lobby of John Peter Smith Hospital, her clothes
splattered with blood, said her 17-year-old daughter, Heather
MacDonald, was saved by her best friend who was sitting next to
her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the gunman approached, the woman said, her daughter's friend
``laid on top of my daughter to protect her, and she got shot.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The injured teen-ager, believed to be 17, was not immediately
identified. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Brown said his wife, Jaynanne, was grazed in the head. His
wife was supposed to pick him up from work last night but instead
decided to take their children to a prayer meeting and concert at
the church, Brown said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said his wife was taken to Harris Methodist Hospital but that
his children were all right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank the Lord somebody protected her,'' Brown said. ``But
it's just a shame you can't go to church without something like
this happening.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
