<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3638 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-FLORIDA-HNS     09-15 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-FLORIDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDIANS EXPECTED TO JAM ROADS TO GET BACK HOME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TERRY KLIEWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ It promises to be a beautiful day in the
neighborhood all along Florida's upper east coast Thursday after
Hurricane Floyd spent most of Wednesday pushing northward toward
the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday morning also promised headaches for tens of
thousands of residents trying to get back to their storm-swept
neighborhoods along the coastline from Melbourne up to
Jacksonville, north Florida's biggest city.
</P>
<P>
   Fallen power lines, broken tree limbs, nonworking traffic
signals and wary cops patrolling beachfront roads combined to slow
the return of hurricane evacuees as officials reopened access
points along coast-hugging U.S. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problems stemmed from power lines snapped by the 60
mph wind gusts on Floyd's outer fringe. The hurricane itself passed
out of Florida waters with the eye never closer than 150 miles to
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the state had at least 100,000 homes without
power but expected 75 percent to be restored by Thursday afternoon.
Contractors from across the country worked with local utility
companies to do repairs. Meanwhile, traffic congestion grew
steadily through the day on the roads leading to beachfront
communities, starting just after noon EST Wednesday when
authorities began opening barrier island bridges to local-only
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Police continued into the evening to check identification for
drivers headed east, creating long lines at several chokepoints in
the Daytona Beach and St. Augustine areas.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers who waited up to two hours to get through were
philosophical, largely because officials repeatedly advised anxious
evacuees that beachfront housing generally appeared to be in good
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jim Raner, a retiree headed back to Neptune Beach after
spending a couple of days in an area hotel: ``I can stand to wait a
little while for good news. They say everything's probably OK.''
</P>
<P>
   His main worry were his two dogs, left behind inside his mobile
home. ``I got my own cleanup to do, I imagine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials were advising the 7,000 residents of Raner's
beachside hometown to boil their tap water as a precaution against
bacteria because water pressure had been lost briefly earlier
Wednesday. Most of the influx of evacuees was expected to come
Thursday morning under what weather forecasters said might actually
be the region's first sunshine and blue skies in three days.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville Mayor John Delaney urged the returning residents to
be patient, even to stay put at inland shelters, hotels, and
friends' and relatives' homes until Thursday to give work crews
time to restore power.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Friday we expect everything to be back to normal in
Jacksonville, Florida,'' he told reporters at a Wednesday afternoon
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the city's airport and public transportation
would be up and running again Thursday, and the port would resume
operations, too.
</P>
<P>
   The same scenario was replayed all along the upper Florida coast
Wednesday as the departing hurricane finished its long good-bye
here with continuing showers, drooping clouds and blustery winds.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses and homes remained boarded up in all north Florida
coastal towns apparently because, as one convenience store operator
put it, ``Why bother with it now? The weekend is soon enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees and customers alike promised to remain scarce until
Friday, and gasoline and grocery deliveries were slow to resume in
many places. The grungy weather had departed much of the south
Florida coastline by late Tuesday, and the homeward stampede of
residents there was winding down by Wednesday night. Although the
hurricane stayed well offshore and only grazed Florida's Atlantic
coastline with mostly tropical storm-force winds, its storm surge
and tumbling surf took a toll on beaches and ocean piers.
</P>
<P>
   A 100-foot section of Jacksonville Beach's oldest tourist pier
was toppled by heavy waves Wednesday. But those same waves were
already being eyed by local surfers, among them a young hotel desk
clerk here who said he expected to be on the water today ``when it
ought to be about perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning Gov. Jeb Bush told Floridians they had done
the right thing by departing coastal areas starting early in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to know'' what's in store with a hurricane, he
said. ``You have to prepare and you have to evacuate,'' and pointed
out that only a slight westward drift by Floyd could have brought
catastrophe to the state. Later in the day, Mayor Delaney spoke for
himself, Bush and probably everyone else on the coast when he
summed up the past few days for reporters:
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very, very, very, very lucky. Frankly, this was
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
