<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-COAST16-COX     09-15 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-COAST16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some evacuees say they'll ride out next storm
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Suzanne and Bill Mahrenholz, who returned to St.
Simons Island as soon as Glynn County officials sounded the
all-clear, survived Hurricane Floyd but were nearly done in by the
massive evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   The couple were among the multitude that fled coastal areas of
Florida, Georgia and South Carolina as the monster hurricane
menaced the lower Southeast coast. And they were among the first to
return late Wednesday, shortly after officials reopened the
causeway to St. Simons, the only way to drive to the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove 500 miles and never found a place to stay,'' said
Mahrenholz, a 69-year-old retiree. ``I don't think we'll do this
evacuation thing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those making it back home from their western flight had
to use secondary roads because eastbound Interstate 16 remained
closed between Savannah and the Swainsboro exit by order of the
Georgia Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Although Florida residents had been cleared to return home,
coastal Georgia counties were lifting the evacuation order one by
one. ``Although evacuation orders are issued by local officials,
the state will not approve any re-entry until the eye of Hurricane
Floyd passes the coastal counties of Georgia and South Carolina,''
said GEMA spokeswoman Pam Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the scenes and situations from across the
coastal South as Hurricane Floyd moved north:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach resident Jack Nee, 70, rode six hours Tuesday in
his Geo Metro to Ocala with his two toy poodles, Vinnie and
Squeaky. But when they arrived, hotel operators said the nearest
rooms available were in Alabama. ``I said to hell with that, I'm
coming back,'' said Nee, who got the last room available Tuesday
night at the Ramada Inn in Daytona Beach across from the speedway.
Nee lives five blocks west of the beach and doubts he'll evacuate
next time. ``I spent last night on route 40 and I'm not going to do
that again,'' Nee said. ``What a waste.''
</P>
<P>
   A skeleton staff was at work Wednesday at the Orange County
Convention Center, where exhibitors for the American Academy of
Family Physicians were allowed to set up. The annual meeting,
seminars and exhibition were delayed because of Hurricane Floyd.
``We still have no idea how many folks will or will not be able to
get here simply because of the storm,'' said Kathy Canning, the
center's marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd took a historic souvenir Wednesday before
leaving Daytona Beach and the Sunshine State. The storm's 15-foot
waves swallowed a 300-foot span of the landmark Main Street Pier,
built in the 1920s. Local television stations kept cameras trained
on the popular tourist destination throughout the day, making it
the image of the day for Florida's brush with Floyd. Just before
high tide at 12:32 p.m., a wave rolled underneath the Daytona Beach
pier and wiped out wooden pilings, crumpling the structure like it
stood on dominoes. Before bridges linking the mainland opened to
the public early Wednesday afternoon, locals gathered on the
boardwalk to watch the spectacle of the sea's violence. ``When
people come to Daytona Beach, this is where they come,'' said
resident Charles Beers, a timeshare marketer. GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   The governor's Office of Consumer Affairs in Atlanta reported
fielding about 50 complaints about price gouging, mostly for
high-priced gasoline and hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   That volume of calls is expected to grow substantially over the
next few days when people return to their homes and get the bills
for tree removal and home cleanup, said spokesman Bill Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite so far is a hotel in south Georgia that advertised
rooms for $12.95 on its billboard and is charging $130 a night,''
Cloud said. He said the report was unconfirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1995 law, it is a misdemeanor to take advantage of a
state of emergency by raising the price of items beyond prevailing
prices or beyond their cost plus a regular mark-up.
</P>
<P>
   Some coastal communities that were forced by Hurricane Floyd to
suspend candidate qualifying for municipal elections may extend the
qualifying deadline beyond 4:30 p.m. Friday, a spokesman for
Secretary of State Cathy Cox said Wednesday. Although the law
doesn't appear to require them to extend qualifying in these
circumstances, Savannah, Hinesville and Tybee Island are among the
municipalities that have asked Cox how they should go about doing
so. Cox said they must obtain both a court order from a Superior
Court judge and approval from the U.S. Justice Department. The
statewide qualifying period for municipal elections began Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By 5 p.m. _ hours before the hurricane's eye was expected to
pass 90 miles east of Savannah _ power was knocked out to about
50,000 homes throughout the county, said Billy Hair, chairman of
the Chatham County Commission. Sustained winds of 41 mph with 60
mph gusts were reported at the Savannah airport. By late afternoon,
tree limbs and dead palm branches were scattered on streets but
traffic lights still worked.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Rosenzweig considered Wednesday a nice day to go for a
swim at Tybee Island. ``I just wanted to see the beauty and power
and fury of Mother Nature,'' said Rosenzweig, a self-employed
tombstone cleaner in Savannah. ``I was swimming out here with
(Hurricane) Dennis a few weeks ago.'' Walter Strong ventured from
his Savannah home to Tybee Island with a friend, Dudley Stone, a
Savannah resident physician. ``It's fairly impressive,'' said
Strong, 26, wiping the driving rain from his eyes and his drenched
camera. ``I'm just a hurricane buff, I guess.'' The pair took
photos from the end of Tybee's pier, which was shaken by 8-foot
waves.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   Terry Hurley, who showed up Wednesday at a Wilmington shelter
with his wife and two young children, said his family stayed home
for Hurricanes Fran and Bertha in 1996, but not Floyd. ``They talk
like this one is going to be pretty mean. It's got everybody shook
up,'' he said. About 110 people were in the middle school shelter
an hour after it opened. At Wrightsville Beach, Pam Carroll and her
husband, Bernard, nailed plywood to the door of their King Neptune
Restaurant before leaving Wednesday afternoon. ``This is very
nerve-wracking. We're all stressed,'' she said, holding her
2-year-old son, Patterson, in her arms. Said her husband, ``My
son's not quite 3 years old and this is his third storm.''
</P>
<P>
   While the southern North Carolina coast braced for Floyd, the
Outer Banks took the storm in stride _ evacuating tourists but not
expecting much heavy weather. Emergency management spokeswoman
Martha Wickre said a mandatory evacuation, and Floyd's fierce
reputation, cleared most of the thousands of visitors out of Dare
County. Wickre said county officials expected high winds but
thought the storm, on an inland track, would clear out of the state
by this evening and largely miss this area. Just two weeks ago,
Hurricane Dennis dawdled off the Outer Banks for days, stirring up
a damaging surf before it backtracked and came ashore to the south
at Cedar Island in Carteret County. Cars streamed along U.S. 64 and
158, the two approaches to the county and its barrier islands,
during the day. By midafternoon, just a few vehicles moved along
the normally busy main road through Nags Head, Kill Devil Hills and
Kitty Hawk.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   With gale force-winds already upon them, Charleston officials
hoped that a northern shift in Hurricane Floyd would save them from
the devastation they remember from Hurricane Hugo. Still, 70 mph
winds whipped the city Wednesday evening and some feared they could
reach 115 mph. By 7 p.m. several roofs had blown off of homes on
the barrier islands and there was moderate flooding in some areas.
Before nightfall almost 200,000 people had lost power. Shelters
were filled with thousands of people. Christena Watkins, 59, moved
from Jones Island to the Econo Lodge with her sister and grandson.
She sat in her room watching a religious television show as the
storm raked the area. ``I just hope that everybody makes it
through, that nobody dies.'' But some people braved the slashing
rain. A soaking Curtis Chisolm, 26, didn't bother with an umbrella
as he walked down Rivers Avenue. ``This is the wrath of God. Who
ain't afraid of the wrath of God?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled from staff and wire service reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
