<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-15 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: BRITAIN, SPAIN, GERMANY, NETHERLANDS, FRANCE,
TURKEY, MEXICO, INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: 2 TORIES EYE MAYOR'S JOB
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Conservatives moved closer to choosing a
candidate in next May's election for a mayor of London. Lord
Jeffrey Archer, a millionaire writer and party stalwart, and Steven
Norris, a former transport minister, emerged as front-runners in a
vote among party members. The final choice will be made in a
broader, postal ballot. The Labor Party has not yet named a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: TEENS FIGHT JAIL TERMS
</P>
<P>
   Two teen-agers complained to the European Court of Human Rights
that their rights had been violated in a 1993 trial when, as
10-year-olds, they were jailed for beating a 2-year-old child to
death. Lawyers for Jon Venables and Robert Thompson, both
imprisoned in England, said the trial had been unfair. Lawyers also
said the prison terms, extended to 15 years from eight by a
government minister, had been arbitrarily set.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: FRANCO CONDEMNED
</P>
<P>
   A parliamentary commission for the first time officially
condemned Francisco Franco's rebellion in 1936 for starting the
civil war that ushered in his 36-year dictatorship. But the ruling
Popular Party, which has long downplayed the fact that some of its
members worked for the former regime, abstained from the vote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  GERMANY: EUROPEAN PANEL APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   The Parliament of the European Union approved the union's new
executive body, led by Prime Minister Romano Prodi of Italy. The
approval of the 20-member executive, known as the European
Commission, ends six months of uncertainty since the Parliament
forced the previous commission to resign after allegations of fraud
and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: U.N. PROSECUTOR TAKES OVER
</P>
<P>
   Carla del Ponte took office as the new chief prosecutor for the
U.N. war crimes tribunals for Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia,
replacing Louise Arbour, who was appointed to Canada's Supreme
Court. Mrs. del Ponte, 52, has been attorney general and chief
federal prosecutor of Switzerland since 1994, a post in which she
often challenged Swiss banking secrecy. In her new post she will
head an international staff of some 400 lawyers and investigators.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: MILITANTS SENTENCED
</P>
<P>
   An antiterrorism court sentenced 21 Muslim militants to prison
sentences of from six months to 10 years. They had all been charged
with organizing or playing a role in a terrorist network that
planted bombs in several French cities in 1995. Ten people were
killed and more than 170 wounded in the attacks, some of which were
claimed by Algerian insurgents known as the Armed Islamic Group.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: OCALAN TWIST
</P>
<P>
   A new file has surfaced in the case of the Kurdish rebel leader
Abdullah Ocalan, giving judges the opportunity to reopen the case
if they wish. All prosecutors were to have submitted their cases
before his trial, but a prosecutor in the eastern town of Sanliurfa
has reportedly found one he did not submit. Ocalan was sentenced to
death in June, but his case may now be judged still open.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: REBEL SYMPATHIZERS CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   The government has dropped charges against 37 sympathizers of
the Zapatista rebels in Chiapas who were indicted during army and
police operations last year to seize towns that the rebels
controlled. In what officials hoped would be seen as a conciliatory
gesture, 24 prisoners were released from jail or bail and 13 arrest
warrants were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: OPTIMISM FOR GOVERNING PARTY
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls show that the Bharatiya Janata Party is in line to
win 145 of the 268 parliamentary seats that were at stake during
the first two of five phases in the current elections, according to
state television. The same polls show that the Congress Party is
likely to win 105. The third phase will take place on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: GANDHI ON SPOT AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee has demanded that Sonia
Gandhi, the Italian-born leader of the Congress Party, explain why
she waited 15 years before becoming an Indian citizen. ``The
question is crying for proper answer,'' he said, further pushing
the ``foreigner issue'' in India's election campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
