<HEADER>
A3685 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:HOMEWORK-CLASSAC     09-15 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:HOMEWORK-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEWORK MUST-HAVES 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By ALYSON WARD 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's officially homework season again. No more summer slacking,
no more first-of-school light workloads.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to get down to business, whip out the sharpened No. 2
pencils _ or turn on the computer _ and do some real work.
</P>
<P>
   Here, some of the best ideas, products and resources for getting
out from under that pile of work:
</P>
<P>
   1. Start with basic organizers. Organize your study area with
two stationery musts: a calendar and an assignment book. Keep a
calendar by the homework area to keep track of projects and
long-term assignments. (That science fair can sneak up on you if
you don't see it approaching, circled in red.) Consider mounting a
reusable two-month or three-month wipe-off calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Students will also need a totable form of date-tracking: an
assignment book. They're crucial. Assignment notebooks come in all
forms, from the cheap and simple spiral notebook styles to the
personal organizers with leather covers and refillable pages.
</P>
<P>
   The key is to get into the habit of writing homework assignments
down. Remembering the homework assignment is half the battle. Well,
almost.
</P>
<P>
   2. Get a CD-ROM Encyclopedia. Time was, ``encyclopedia'' meant a
collection of heavy books that cost hundreds if not thousands of
dollars and were outdated within a couple of years. No more. These
days, encyclopedias come on CD-ROM and go for less than $100.
</P>
<P>
   The just-released Microsoft Encarta Reference Suite 2000
contains four major CD-ROM reference guides: the encyclopedia, the
Encarta Interactive World Atlas, the Encarta World English
Dictionary and Encarta Online Deluxe, an online version of the
encyclopedia. The set of four costs about $65 after a company
rebate _ the deluxe encyclopedia by itself is about $40 after the
rebate.
</P>
<P>
   One caveat: The ``Microsoft'' Encarta products run only on
Windows. A Mac version of the encyclopedia has been produced in
years past, but it's not known if one will be made for the 2000
edition.
</P>
<P>
   3. Turn to online homework helpers. There's more to the Internet
than junk e-mail and advertising _ it's probably the fastest,
easiest way to get information children might need to complete
homework assignments. Try these two exceptional Web sites that
specialize in getting students the homework help they need:
</P>
<P>
   The www.homeworkcentral.com site lets students pinpoint the
information they need by helping them narrow down their topics. The
site is divided into age groups, and the search engine is designed
to serve academic purposes. For instance, if you type in ``George
Washington,'' you'll get information about the first president _
NOT a list of every site with the word ``George'' or ``Washington''
in it.
</P>
<P>
   The www.schoolwork.org site offers numerous topic categories,
then provides a fairly comprehensive list of Web sites that contain
specialized information about each topic.
</P>
<P>
   4. Keep those papers in place. There's always that book that
won't stay open or that piece of paper that keeps disappearing.
Eliminate frustration with some products that keep flyaways in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Try an adjustable bookstand that props up your textbook _ and
keeps it open to the right page; The Container Store chain has a
version for $35.
</P>
<P>
   Or use a book weight that'll weigh down the page you need.
Levenger's Web site (www.levenger.com) offers really nice leather
book weights for $17.99 _ or find a cheaper one at bookstores or
office supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   5. Parents: provide practical inspiration. Sometimes the work
gets done faster when the right tools are also fun to look at.
Hence the Pokemon Study Kit, based on the Japanese animation game
that has taken over the lives of everybody younger than 12.
</P>
<P>
   These little desk-supply packs (ruler, eraser, pencil sharpener,
pencil pouch) cost less than $5 at toy stores that carry Pokemon
products.
</P>
<P>
   Or spring for the Deluxe Desktop Set, which includes a
Jigglypuff tape dispenser, a Bulbasaur pencil sharpener, a
Poliwhirl tape measure and a Pikachu stapler; it goes for about
$10. Not a bad investment if it helps get the homework done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
