<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: CD: JESSE CAMP'S ``JESSE AND THE 8TH STREET KIDZ'' 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By JANE AUSTIN, (High School) Student Reporter 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CD: ``Jesse and the 8th Street Kidz''
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Jesse Camp.
</P>
<P>
   Label: Hollywood Records.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Camp is like millions of other guys singing about girls,
hitchhiking and being a kid _ except that he has a record deal and
name recognition from being a VJ on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   He got the gig in April 1998 by winning the cable channel's
first VJ search contest. There were 4,000 other people who
auditioned.
</P>
<P>
   If Jesse is trying to send any profound messages, it's not
working, since his trademark voice is garbled when he's talking and
it's even harder to understand when he's singing. But the CD has a
good guitar sound, and there are a few catchy tunes, such as
``Crazy for You'' and ``Summertime Squatters.''
</P>
<P>
   I like the CD. Camp's brash personality comes through, and he's
not afraid to say what he thinks, though he doesn't have much to
say. It's just a cut above what you might hear the band next door
playing, but maybe that's part of the charm.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1 - 10 rating: 6.
</P>
