<SLUG> BC-KIDS:NEWS:YO-YOS-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID YOU KNOW ... ALL ABOUT YO-YOS? 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By JESSAMY BROWN 
 c. 1999 Compiled from reports by The Associated Press and Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did you know that yo-yos _ invented 2,500 years ago _ are more
than just toys to some kids? They can be serious competition.
</P>
<P>
   Picture 350 people spinning, looping, flipping and twisting
yo-yos for three days. That was the scene at the 1999 Bandai World
Yo-Yo Competition in Honolulu last month.
</P>
<P>
   Contestants came from countries around the world, including
Russia, Korea, Japan, Germany and Taiwan, but only a handful were
named World Champions.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve-year-old Takumi Nagasse of Japan won the World Champion
title in the double-handed division. American brothers, Joel and
Matt Zinc, came away victorious in the single-handed and
recreational divisions.
</P>
<P>
   FACTS: The word yo-yo apparently came from Tagalog, the native
language of the Philippines. It means ``come back'' or ``come
come.''
</P>
<P>
   For 400 years, the yo-yo was used as a weapon to fling at
enemies or animals. The early yo-yos had sharp edges and studs, and
were attached to thick, 20-foot ropes. Ancient Greeks made yo-yos
of wood, metal or clay.
</P>
<P>
   The yo-yo became popular as a toy in Europe in the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Today's versions are made of plastic and even Space-Age metals
developed by scientists at NASA.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about yo-yo tricks, types and competition,
log on to www.bandai.co.jp//yoyo//
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3695 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-WACO-TEX     09-15 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE POSTPONES BRANCH DAVIDIANS' WRONGFUL DEATH SUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter Smith Jr. postponed the Branch
Davidians' wrongful death lawsuit Wednesday because it's taking
longer than expected to move the physical evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Smith did not order a new trial date, but said he will not agree
to a previous proposal by the government to delay it until next
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Because the trial was already scheduled close to the holiday
season, it probably will be delayed until the first of the year,
one attorney involved in the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is presiding over a multimillion-dollar wrongful death
suit against the government for the 1993 Branch Davidian siege just
outside Waco, Texas. At the end of a 51-day standoff with the FBI,
Mount Carmel burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Religious leader David Koresh and about 80 of his followers were
found dead inside.
</P>
<P>
   Branch Davidian survivors, as well as relatives of Branch
Davidians who died in the fire, allege in their suit that the
government used excessive force during the ATF raid on the compound
Feb. 28, 1993. In addition, they say the government was negligent
for the April 19, 1993, fire at Mount Carmel and for not
extinguishing it.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent Lon Horiuchi also is named as a defendant, accused of
firing shots at the Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   Horiuchi is the only individual defendant named in the lawsuit,
mainly because he is the only one plaintiffs specifically accuse of
excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   Horiuchi and the United States now are the only defendants.
Jurors will decide if Horiuchi fired at the Branch Davidians and
Smith will hear the excessive force and negligence issues.
</P>
<P>
   Horiuchi, an FBI sharpshooter, fired the shot that killed Vicki
Weaver in August 1992, during the government siege in Ruby Ridge,
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno has appointed former Sen. John
Danforth to head an independent investigation into the events
surrounding the standoff, after recent revelations that the FBI
fired pyrotechnic tear gas grenades during the standoff. Reno and
FBI officials now admit the pyrotechnic canisters were used, an
about-face from six years of adamant denials.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Smith ordered that all evidence in the case be turned
over to the U.S. District Clerk's office, at the request of
officials at the Texas Department of Public Safety, who are storing
the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   DPS officials have said they are frustrated because requests to
review the evidence were being bounced back and forth between the
DPS, which had possession but no control over the evidence, and the
Justice Department, which had control, but not possession of the
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   DPS spokeswoman Tela Mange said DPS officials have been waiting
to find out if Smith wants the evidence taken to the U.S. District
Clerk's office in San Antonio, Texas, or the clerk's office in
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Once Smith decides, Mange said, it will take several weeks to
inventory the evidence. DPS officials couldn't inventory the
evidence while they waited for a decision, she said, because the
items will be moved as they are itemized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a while,'' Mange said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Michael Caddell, who represents most of the
plaintiffs in the wrongful death lawsuit, said the delay will give
attorneys on both sides time to prepare their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what he's done is very reasonable,'' Caddell said. The
trial can't just be delayed a few weeks, he said, because then it
would start in the middle of the holidays. With the trial expected
to last about a month, it's more likely for it to start at the
first of the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
