<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3699 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-MAIN16-COX     09-15 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-MAIN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carolinas in bull's eye today
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ And now it's the Carolinas' turn. Again.
</P>
<P>
   After threatening Florida and Georgia with much bluster but
little punch for the better part of two days, Hurricane Floyd
turned its menacing eye and potentially devastating 115-mph winds
toward North and South Carolina. Landfall was expected early today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to get ugly,'' said Huey Marshall, Brunswick
County attorney. ``It is going to hit at night, at near high
tide.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be the second hurricane to hit North Carolina in two
weeks and the fifth in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   With Floyd's center still 150 miles offshore, the storm's
leading edge had already knocked out power, flooded streets with
drenching rain and spun off tornadoes Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, hurricane-strength gusts of 79 mph were buffeting
Charleston, S.C., and 86,000 people in the area had lost electrical
power. One of several tornadoes near Wilmington destroyed one home
and damaged two others.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of strength and speed and force of the wind, it looks
to be a once-in-a-decade storm, or even longer,'' said Richard
Moore, North Carolina's public safety secretary. ``I know that
Florida and Georgia at this point feel like they've dodged a real
bullet. ...This thing is not going to miss us.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, one of the most powerful and largest hurricanes in
recorded history, had been headed toward Florida before veering to
the north Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively good fortune of Florida and Georgia caused no
small amount of chagrin for the 2.6 million people who fled their
homes. The fear of Floyd led to the largest peacetime evacuation in
U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Floyd caused mostly superficial damage along the
coast and knocked down trees in Orlando and other inland areas.
Some parking lots and portions of Florida's famous A1A highway were
awash with ocean water and sand.
</P>
<P>
   The storm gobbled a huge chunk of the famous Main Street Pier at
Daytona Beach and bit off a section of a large pier in
Jacksonville, leaving beams jutting from the surf.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's Kennedy Space Center and its four shuttles were largely
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials reported no injuries or fatalities related to
Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed the brunt of this monster storm, and we all feel
pretty blessed in that respect,'' said Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Florida attractions are expected to return to normal today.
Disney World and other theme parks near Orlando will reopen, after
closing Tuesday as the storm threatened to bear down on the state.
Orlando International Airport started operating early Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Orange County Commission Chairman Mel Martinez said the governor
called him Wednesday morning to ask when Disney World and the
airport would reopen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the main economic engine of the state, so it's
important to get those open,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney World suffered little damage except a few downed trees,
spokesman Bill Warren said. ``It's nothing we don't get in a
regular heavy rainstorm.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Bahamas were not so fortunate, with many of
them shoveling sand from homes and removing uprooted trees from
streets Wednesday. There were reports of widespread destruction on
distant islands raked by Floyd on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One man was missing on northern Grand Bahama Island after the
van in which he was riding got stuck in a storm surge and he tried
to swim to high ground.
</P>
<P>
   On the Great Abaco Islands, entire neighborhoods were flooded by
the storm surge. Homes, viewed from the air, looked as though they
had been randomly pushed together. In the island's Marsh Harbour,
some wooden homes were flattened and reduced to debris. Others were
left partially standing or turned on their sides.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was similar in northern Eleuthera, where winds reached
110 mph Tuesday. Homes were left without roofs, boats tossed like
toys onto the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Several people, including one who fell off a roof during the
storm, were treated for minor injuries in Nassau, the Bahamian
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, about 350 miles off the coast, the Coast Guard
rescued three people from 18-foot seas while five others who fled a
sinking tugboat in a life raft were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Now attention turns to the Carolina coast, where officials were
worried that Floyd's landfall would cause tidal surges that would
cover fragile barrier islands. It's a scene with which they're all
too familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Hurricane Dennis skirted along the North Carolina
coast and then backtracked as it passed the Outer Banks. On its
return trip, it washed out a half-mile stretch of N.C. 12, Hatteras
Island's main road, and soaked the coast with heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, Floyd was taking aim at North Carolina's
southeastern tip, which was battered by Hurricane Bonnie a year ago
and Fran and Bertha in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters are calling for another 10 to 15 inches of rain as
the weakened yet massive storm smacks coastal North Carolina towns,
which ordered evacuations and imposed curfews on residents who
refused to flee.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane is poised to unleash its most punishing
northeastern winds and storm surge on five Brunswick County beach
towns. Sunset Beach, Ocean Isle Beach, Holden Beach, Oak Island and
Caswell Beach jut eastward toward the sea between the South
Carolina line and the Cape Fear River.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared North Carolina, South Carolina and
Virginia federal disaster areas Wednesday in anticipation of storm
damage. He had already declared Florida and Georgia disaster areas
the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Officials opened additional shelters to handle evacuees. In a
minor replay of Tuesday's traffic jams that snarled Interstates 95
and 26 in South Carolina for hours _ and roads throughout Georgia
and Florida _ North Carolina motorists hit delays traveling inland
on rain-puddled highways.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd is spinning out hurricane-force winds 140 miles from the
eye. Its breadth prompted officials across eastern North Carolina
to close schools and set up emergency shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is moving fast, Floyd is so wide forecasters believe
it could pound North Carolina communities for 10 to 12 hours before
moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``A constant beating will play havoc on all of us,'' said Bobby
Greer, vice chairman of the New Hanover Board of Commissioners in
Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   One of the century's most devastating storms, Hurricane Hazel,
made landfall in 1954 in Brunswick County. Floyd is following a
similar course.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the folks who was around during Hazel left the island
today,'' said Bob Grant, assistant manager of Oak Island. ``He was
a barometer for a lot of other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant said most of Oak Island's 6,200 residents evacuated
Wednesday, in the hours before Floyd's outer bands hurled waves
across sand dunes and flooded streets. It also knocked the end off
the Long Beach pier.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters predicted a storm surge from 14 to 30 feet along
Brunswick County beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to cover a lot of the island with water,'' Grant
said. ''Those folks who chose not to leave, that is a major
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   On Bald Head Island, at North Carolina's extreme southeastern
tip, three of an estimated 1,000 residents refused to evacuate,
said Kent Brown, the island's emergency management director. ``I
wish that nobody had stayed on the island given the severity of the
storm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By noon Wednesday, ``absolutely monstrous'' waves had breached
ocean-front dunes, a stretch vulnerable in past storms, said Wayne
Kester.
</P>
<P>
   One of three people who stayed on Bald Head Island, 58-year-old
Kester is staying with his dog, Roux, in a house whose first floor
is 13 1/2 feet above sea level. Still, he said he's not worried by
forecasts for a huge wall of water hitting the beach several
hundred yards from his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just another rainy day,'' Kester said. ``I feel as safe
as I would anywhere on the island, except at the top of the Old
Baldy lighthouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Marlon Manuel and Shelia Poole contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
