<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ACTION-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX'S `ACTION' GETS DOWN AND DIRTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's dispense with weighty discussions about whether TV
reflects values or creates them, and simply note that a prostitute
holds the moral high ground in the new Fox comedy series
``Action.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone to the south of hooker Wendy Ward (Illeana Douglas) is
snared in the bowels of hell, the Mariana Trench of moral
turpitude, the ethical black hole from which the light of grace
cannot escape.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Hollywood entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action'' debuts Thursday night with two episodes, first the
stunner of a pilot at 9 p.m. and then an episode at 9:30 that
wasn't sent out for preview.
</P>
<P>
   There's little room for ambivalence on this one. ``Action''
carries the dreaded TVMA (mature adult) rating and wears it like a
badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   You will love ``Action'' as a scathingly funny satire of
moviemaking or hate it for its coarse language, sexual content and
insistence on shoving a scoundrel forward as the lead character.
</P>
<P>
   That's Jay Mohr as Peter Dragon, the divorced, dyspeptic,
Xanax-gobbling producer of big-screen action fare such as ``Slow
Torture'' and ``Beverly Hills Gun Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohr was in one of the lesser ``Saturday Night Live'' casts and
played Tom Cruise's obnoxious rival in ``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is more perfectly cast on TV this fall; Mohr projects
prickly anger lathered over a spot of vulnerability. He has about
six expressions each for contempt and disgust, and the role of
Peter Dragon requires them all.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Dragon? Not according to his ex-wife (Cindy Ambuehl), who
dumped him and entered into a show marriage with Bobby G. (Lee
Arenberg), the gay billionaire studio chief who distributes
Dragon's films.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby G. has the famous appendage that does all the draggin';
Peter Dragon, pleading with Bobby G. for his ``Show Torture''
sequel, glimpses it Thursday night and confesses afterward, ``I
folded. I completely collapsed under its majesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' Wendy Ward enters the picture as a sort of accidental
trick on the night of Dragon's ``Slow Torture'' premiere. In the
theater, she gets cozy with guest star Keanu Reeves, who plays
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter, I have some concerns,'' Reeves whispers to Dragon
during the movie. ``I'm a little concerned that your date has her
hand down my pants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan,'' says Wendy, who soon proves to be such an
astute judge of movie scripts that Dragon hires her as a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Watch Thursday night and you'll also see an agent pitching O.J.
Simpson to Dragon for a film role. Hey, even kids in Calcutta know
his face. He'll work for scale, and his recent acting lessons
included a moving scene from ``Raisin in the Sun.'' Still, not
Dragon's idea of a leading man.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about a villain?'' says the agent, not giving up. ``He'll
play a villain. C'mon, who's scarier?''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Hackett is in the cast as Dragon's uncle and chauffeur,
and Jarrad Paul plays a screenwriter named Adam Rafkin. He sold
Dragon the ``Beverly Hills Gun Club'' script for $250,000. Thing
is, Dragon meant to buy a script from someone named Alan Rifkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you telling me we spent a quarter of a million dollars and
we got the wrong Jew?'' an exasperated Dragon asks his production
lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   Created by veteran writer and producer Chris Thompson (``The
Naked Truth''), ``Action'' is the spotlighted front-runner in a TV
season that veers audaciously from the old ``honey, I'm home''
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Under chief programmer Doug Herzog, the Fox network in
particular seems to have come to a decision that in competing
against cable, the broadcast networks need to pander or perish. Fox
will pander.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action'' smashes the old rules about language; bleeps cover
Mohr's f-words about as effectively as a thong bikini covers its
wearer's behind. It treats sexual material as if there were no
children in the audience, and it dispenses with the cautionary veil
of political correctness. While that isn't all wonderful,
``Action'' comes with blessings, too.
</P>
<P>
   Think of all the TV shows that have been squeaky-clean and
thoroughly insipid. ``Action'' willingly dirties itself, but it
does have a brain. And one thing it doesn't have, refreshingly, is
a laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   It's taken a mere half century, but network TV finally has a
comedy show that's glaringly and exclusively tailored for adults,
in the same acidic way that HBO's ``The Larry Sanders Show'' was
for grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's double-dish premiere, ``Action'' will reside in
a 9:30 p.m. Thursday time slot on Fox, so it doesn't directly
collide with a certain acclaimed sitcom on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   See, you can have your fun and ``Frasier'' too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
