</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMBS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHEN MILITANTS RESPONSIBLE FOR MOSCOW BOMBINGS, RUSSIAN POLICE
SAY  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CORRECTS ``buildings'' to ``building'' in graf that begins: ``Some
of these bags...'') (See RUSSIA-BOMBS-POLITICS) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian police said Wednesday that Chechen militants
had shipped tons of explosives into Moscow disguised as bags of
sugar and used them to carry out recent attacks that killed more
than 210 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found out who carried out the explosions,'' Moscow's
deputy police chief, Aleksander Veldyayev, said Wednesday. ``The
terrorist attacks were carried out by Chechen fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Muscovites believed that the bombings, which sent waves of
anxiety through the city, were the work of Islamic militants who
invaded Dagestan from bases in Chechnya, and people from the
Caucasus already have felt the backlash.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the militants _ Shamil Basayev, the Chechen
warlord, and a Jordanian-born fighter known as Khattab _ insist
that they were not involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not like to be compared to those who kill sleeping
civilians with bombs and shells,' said Khattab, referring to
Russian airstrikes against Chechnya in the war there.
</P>
<P>
   The charges and denials have prompted an important question: If
the aim of the bombings is to pressure Russia to abandon Dagestan,
why would the Islamic rebels deny any involvement?
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the mystery, a previously unknown group, the Dagestan
Liberation Army, Wednesday called the semiofficial Itar-Tass news
agency and claimed it had organized the attacks. But some experts
said they doubted the group even existed.
</P>
<P>
   Assigning responsibility is important. Public sentiment here for
tough action against Chechnya _ and the Chechens who live in Moscow
_ is running high. Russia's prime minister, Vladimir Putin, has
said he planned to demand that Chechnya turn over the culprits
behind the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen government, however, asserts that Russian
conspirators carried out the attacks, possibly to provide a pretext
for the Yeltsin government to declare a state of emergency and
suspend the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one conclusion,'' said Chechnya's deputy prime
minister, Kazbek Makhashev. ``Russia needs a hot spot to solve its
own domestic political problems and its battle for power.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen authorities do not support the militants, who have
become a power to themselves near the Chechnya-Dagestan border. But
they also do not want Russia to continue its bombing raids against
rebel positions inside Chechnya or step up its offensive by,
perhaps, launching a ground attack.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said that 27 suspects had been detained as
part of a campaign to find the people responsible for the
explosions, but in their briefings Wednesday, Russian police and
intelligence officials did not name any suspects.
</P>
<P>
   They insisted, however, that they had evidence that confirmed
the involvement of Chechen militants, aided by people of Slavic
appearance, an important asset since dark-skinned Chechens often
are viewed suspiciously in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining their case, Russian officials said that Chechen
fighters had shipped explosives disguised as bags of sugar to
Moscow by truck.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these bags were later found in the basement of a house
in southern Moscow. But it is not clear whether they were being
stored there or were to be used to blow up the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 19 tons of explosives were delivered to Moscow disguised
as sugar,'' Veldyayev said. ``Most of it has been discovered and
seized.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleksandr Zdanovich, a spokesman for the Federal Security
Service, one of the successors to the Soviet KGB, said, ``It is not
that important whether it was this organization or another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing,'' Zdanovich said, ``is that these
acts of terrorism are connected with the developments in Dagestan
and were planned in Chechnya by associates of Basayev and
Khattab.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
