<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3715 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-COULTER-COULTER_SFCHR     09-15 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COULTER-COULTER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 New Job for Former BofA Chief
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
David Coulter, the Bank of America chief executive ousted a year
ago after North Carolina's NationsBank bought the San Francisco
bank, is about to take a new job.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter is near an agreement to become senior partner and a
private investment fund manager for Beacon Group, a New York buyout
and merger advisory firm, according to people familiar with his
plans. They said the former BofA chief would set up a West Coast
office for Beacon in San Francisco or Los Angeles, the &LR;  sources
said &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Joining a private investment partnership is a common step for
well-heeled refugees from the corporate world, especially when they
have large amounts of money to invest. Coulter's severance package
from BofA could be worth as much as $100 million over his lifetime,
providing him a large sum to contribute to Beacon's investment
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Private equity investment firms such as Beacon use their own
capital and money raised from outside investors to buy controlling
or minority stakes in corporations. Companies turn to such private
investors as alternatives to public stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   For the 52-year-old Coulter, the job would mark a new stage in
his gradual return to professional life after a humiliating
departure from the No.2 position at the merged BofA 11 months ago.
Earlier this year, he became a director of the San Francisco
investment bank Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh McColl, the NationsBank CEO who became chief of the
combined bank, fired Coulter 16 days after the takeover took
effect, blaming him for $372 million in losses in an investment
portfolio managed for the bank by the Wall Street firm D.E. Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter's high-profile ordeal didn't make him a pariah. People
familiar with Coulter's plans said he has been courted by several
U.S. and British investment banks and asset management firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In large organizations, people get outmaneuvered all the
time,'' said one executive search specialist. ``It's not a mortal
sin; it's a venial sin. After six months or so, you're free.``
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area investment professionals described Coulter as a
brilliant financial manager who didn't deserve the rough treatment
he got. If he had a flaw, they said, it was in his bargaining
skills, not his ability to understand how companies make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very smart man, and extremely personable,'' said Harlan
Kleiman, president of Shoreline Pacific Institutional Finance, a
Sausalito investment firm. ``If he is going to be managing a
private fund, he'll have an opportunity to show how good he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Coulter nor Geoffrey Boisi, Beacon's founder and chief,
returned telephone calls seeking comment. Coulter's discussions
with Beacon were first reported by the trade newspaper Investment
Dealers Digest.
</P>
<P>
   Boisi, who previously ran the merger advisory practice of the
prestigious investment bank Goldman Sachs, founded Beacon in 1993
to buy out public companies. Many of the firm's deals have been in
the energy industry, such as its purchase several years ago of the
coal operations of Mapco Inc.
</P>
<P>
   During his 21/2-year stint as BofA's CEO, Coulter developed a
keen interest in electronic commerce, and he has recently spoken of
possible ventures in computer-based payment systems. Several people
who know Coulter expect him to focus his investments in those
areas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
