<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-COMPUTING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTING Q&AMP;A/DAVID EINSTEIN 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Plugging In To Your Computer 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Q: The computer I got last year has two USB ports in the back, but
they're both being used, for a mouse and a Zip drive. I'm thinking
of adding a USB scanner, but as you can see, there's no place to
plug it in. Is it possible to ``split'` the USB ports so that I can
add more devices? Also, I have an older PC that doesn't have USB
ports. Is it possible to add them?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: First questions first. What you need is a USB hub, which lets
you attach multiple devices to a single USB port on your computer.
The most common hubs offer four connections and cost $50 to $60.
You should be able to find one at your local computer store.
Incidentally, by daisy chaining hubs together you can connect up to
127 USB devices to a single port. That's a lot of scanners.
</P>
<P>
   As to your second question, you should be able to add USB ports
to your computer if you have an empty PCI slot inside the case.
You'll need to buy a USB card (about $35) and plug it into the
slot. The card has two USB ports, which will be accessible through
the back of the PC once the thing is installed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Cable vs. DSL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm eager to get high-speed Internet access, but I'm not sure
which way to go. Cable modem and DSL are now available in my area.
Any suggestions about which one is faster, more convenient,
cheaper, etc.?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Both DSL and cable modems are ``always on,'' which means you
never have to dial up to get connected to the Internet. And both
offer speeds far faster than 56K modems.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's a tough comparison. On the one hand, DSL never slows
down, like cable modems can when too many people are online at the
same time. On the other hand, cable modem service usually costs
about $10 less per month than DSL.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the issue of technical support. Cable modem
companies aren't known for their fabulous service _ in fact, you
probably could get Boris Yeltsin on the line faster than you can
get someone to troubleshoot your modem. But phone companies are no
great shakes, either.
</P>
<P>
   What I'd do is seek out folks in my area who have DSL or cable,
get their opinions on the quality of the services and make my
choice based on that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Modem Musings &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently upgraded my PC from Windows 95 to Windows 98, and
now my modem doesn't work. It keeps asking for a TCP/ IP
connection. The PC once was connected to a network. Any
suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: I'd reinstall your modem driver. (That's the software that
lets the modem communicate with the PC). To do so, go to
Start/Settings/Control Panel and double-click the Modems icon.
Click Add, then follow the onscreen instructions to install the
modem driver. (You don't have to delete modems that currently are
installed. But after adding the new one, make sure to designate it
as the default for use with all Windows programs).
</P>
<P>
   As for the driver itself, it may be included with the Windows 98
disc. If it's not, you'll have to download it from the Web site of
either the modem manufacturer or the company that made your PC. And
there's the Catch-22 of the day because how can you download
something if your modem doesn't work? (Actually, you should be able
to use one of the generic drivers on the Windows disc until you can
find the specific driver for your modem.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; The Outlook on E-Mail &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: My situation is that I want to switch from Outlook Express to
Outlook 2000 for my e-mail. Is this an easy thing to do, or will I
have to go through the torture of setting up all my e-mail settings
again? And how do I transfer my stored messages into Outlook?
</P>
<P>
   A: Relax. When you start Outlook for the first time, it should
launch a dialog box that guides you through the whole thing. You'll
have the option of transferring your e-mail settings, stored mail
and address book into Outlook from Outlook Express.
</P>
<P>
   However, if all you plan to use Outlook for is e-mail, I'd stick
with Outlook Express. It's faster and, in my opinion, easier to
use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Here's a quick way to check on the formatting of any text in
Microsoft Word. Hold down the Shift key and press the F1 key.
Notice that the cursor turns into an arrow beside a question mark.
Place it anywhere in a paragraph and click. A window will pop up
showing the style format for both the paragraph and the type font.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Einstein is West Coast bureau chief of Forbes Digital
Tool. Got a question about computing? E-mail it to
computers &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
