u i BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-NY     09-15 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIST IS STRUGGLING FOR VOTES IN ARGENTINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MENDOZA, Argentina _ The campaign stop had much potential for
pizazz _ the inauguration of a glassy shopping mall, complete with
a brass band, a fashion show and mountains of caviar. But as
Domingo Cavallo climbed to the stage, his smile was a tad too
broad, his wave a tad too perky and long.
</P>
<P>
   If economics is the dismal science, then Cavallo, the former
economy minister credited with whipping Argentina's hyperinflation
in the early 1990s, is the dismal third-party candidate in the
presidential election in October.
</P>
<P>
   But as quixotic as his candidacy may be, Cavallo has the
potential of shaking up the two parties that have dominated
Argentine politics for most of this century.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at 9 percent in the polls, he is poised to win a
substantial bloc of congressional seats for his new conservative
Action for the Republic party. That will probably make Cavallo, now
a senator, a swing negotiator in Congress and an important player
in economic policy, no matter who is elected on Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for big things is there, although Cavallo's
campaign style could use polishing. And most often, Cavallo's
speeches are minilectures on ways to cut interest rates, increase
productivity and increase investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   His slogan is characteristically uncatchy _ ``Cavallo has a
plan.'' One can only wonder what television commercials would look
like, but the campaign cannot afford any.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two traditional parties are personality, sentimental
parties,'' Cavallo, 53, said in an interview. ``Argentines have
traditionally looked for the most sensitive and most affectionate
candidate, not for the best to govern. But every day the people are
thinking more carefully about their vote, and my candidacy is
reinforcing that process.''
</P>
<P>
   In a race in which the two leading candidates offer many vague
promises, Cavallo issues detailed position papers. Although his
true love is talking economics, he appears to be most effective
when he discusses the darker side of Argentine society.
</P>
<P>
   Organized crime, he said on a talk show, ``has infiltrated the
courts, all levels in government, in the police and in the
military.'' And he suggested that a three-year series of suicides
of people suspected of being witnesses to or actors in scandals
that involved the Menem administration was more than a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   But Cavallo keeps returning to his pet subject, the ins and outs
of monetary and fiscal policy. At one point, Cavallo drove an
interviewer to exasperation by refusing to let him take a break for
a commercial before he had completed a professorial critique of
International Monetary Fund policies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fullness of his oratory and the sparsity of his
campaign resources, Cavallo is receiving significant media
attention, in large part because he is recognized as the most
important cabinet member of the early years of President Carlos
Saul Menem's 10-year presidency.
</P>
<P>
   As Menem's first foreign finister, Cavallo restored ties with
Britain for the first time since the 1982 Falkland War. Then, as
economy minister, he engineered a plan that pegged the value of the
peso to the dollar, a policy that made him a hero on Wall Street
and the most acclaimed economist in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to resign in 1996, after describing to Congress an
expanding web of organized crime with links to the highest levels
of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cavallo is like a doctor,'' Joaquin Morales Sola, a columnist
for the newspaper La Nacion, said. ``You don't have to like him.
But you go to him for a cure when you are sick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3720 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HANDSPRING-HANDSPRING     09-15 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDSPRING-HANDSPRING </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 New Visor Organizer Thumbs Its Nose at Rival Palm
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Henry Norr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
With one bold leap, a startup called Handspring has catapulted
itself into the front ranks of the fast-growing market for
pocket-size digital devices.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain View company this week announced Visor, a new line
of handheld organizers, a.k.a. personal digital assistants or PDAs.
</P>
<P>
   The devices go on sale next month &LR;   &LR; but only online
(www.handspring.com); they won't get into retail stores until next
year. But when they do, I'm convinced they'll be big winners _ even
though I've had some serious problems with the prerelease unit I've
been trying out this week.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the Visors are just clones of the wildly
successful Palm PDAs from 3Com's Palm Computing division (soon to
be spun off into an independent company). Handspring's hardware
looks similar to Palm's, and its software is all but identical.
</P>
<P>
   But the Visors offer some compelling advantages over current
Palm models, not to mention competing devices from a variety of
vendors that use Microsoft's Windows CE software.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Handspring's products are cheaper, faster and easier
to hook up to a PC or Mac, at least if your desktop system is
relatively new. And by the end of this year, there likely will be
many more ways to add cool new capabilities to a Visor than to
other PDAs.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that the Visor is a lot like its Palm
predecessors. After all, Handspring was founded just over a year
ago by the people who created Palm Computing and designed its first
model, the Pilot, before a series of corporate buyouts made it a
part of networking giant 3Com. And when they left, instead of
attempting to reinvent the wheel, the Handspring team members opted
to license back much of the technology they had already created.
</P>
<P>
   Included in that license is the Palm OS _ not just the
underlying code that brings the handheld hardware to life, but also
the easy-to-use personal-information applications that have made
the Palm devices so popular: the electronic address book, calendar,
memo pad, to-do-list manager, expense tracker and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The Visors also come with Graffiti, the Palm software that lets
you enter information by writing on the screen in a simplified
alphabet with a plastic stylus; Palm Desktop for Windows or Mac,
programs for keeping your calendar and contacts on your desktop
computer; &UR;  &LR; and Palm's HotSync technology, which lets you share data
between the desktop and handheld systems at the touch of a button.
For those who use Microsoft Outlook on Windows, there's also
software for synchronizing between that application and the Visor.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when you fire up the Visor, the software environment is
so similar, you can hardly tell you're not using a Palm device.
According to Handspring, Visors also will run all of the thousands
of free, shareware and commercial software add-ons available for
the Palm products. I wasn't able to test that claim, but I have no
reason to doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few differences in the Visor software, though, and
while they're not earthshaking, they're all improvements.
Handspring's developers, for example, added some new features to
Palm's Date Book software: To-do items now appear in the calendar
and even roll over to the next day if not completed, and there are
several new views, including a biweekly one.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Handspring added an advanced mode, with an array of
new financial and other functions, to Palm's electronic Calculator.
And there's a new World Clock module that lets you simultaneously
see the time in five cities.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of hardware, the Visors are about the same size as the
Palm III, but at 5.4 ounces, the former are a shade lighter. The
standard unit's plastic is black rather than the gray of most Palm
models or the brushed aluminum of the slim and sleek Palm V, but
the Deluxe version will be available in your choice of five colors.
</P>
<P>
   All Visor models, like recent Palms, have infrared ports for
close-range wireless data exchange with other handhelds and some
printers. Handspring also borrowed a good idea from the Windows CE
world: Visors have built-in microphones.
</P>
<P>
   And like most Palm models, the devices run on two AAA alkaline
batteries; Handspring says a fresh pair will last six to eight
weeks in normal use.
</P>
<P>
   The viewable part of the Visor's monochrome screen, not counting
the Graffiti text-entry box at the bottom, measures about 2.25
inches square, with a resolution of 160 by 160 pixels. Like Palm's
screen, Handspring's is very readable in bright light, and there's
optional backlighting to help in darker environments, but it's
nowhere near as bright and crisp as the color displays on
more-expensive Windows CE devices.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, nothing I've mentioned so far sounds like a
breakthrough. So what's the big deal? Three things:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Price: Unless Palm responds to the new competition with sharp
price cuts, Visors will have an appreciable price advantage.
Handspring will offer three versions of the Visor, ranging from
$150 to $250, whereas Palm's comparable models start at $229 and go
up to $449. (The Palm VII costs even more _ $599 _ but includes a
wireless radio modem that Handspring doesn't yet offer and for now
still is sold only in the New York area.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Connectivity: The docking cradle included in Handspring's standard
Visor and Visor Deluxe packages connects to the PC or Mac via a
technology called Universal Serial Bus, which is significantly
faster and _ in principle _ less hassle-prone than the traditional
serial-port connection on which current Palm models rely.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, switching to USB also has its downsides. Most PCs
manufactured in the past two years and Macs built in the past year
have USB ports, but older computers don't. And even if your PC has
the requisite ports, you can't use them unless you're running
Windows 98, because older Microsoft operating systems don't fully
support USB. At The Chronicle, for example, I have a spanking new,
USB-equipped PC on my desk, but because our official OS standard is
still Windows 95, I couldn't use the cradle that came with my test
unit at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, even if your system meets all the requirements for
USB, it might not work. At least that was my experience when I
hooked up the Visor cradle to my year-old, Windows 98-based home
PC. Despite repeated software installations, countless tedious
restarts and more than an hour on the phone with a Handspring
support engineer, the Visor still reports that it can't make the
connection every time I press the HotSync button.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, Handspring has a solution for us suffering souls who,
for whatever reason, can't use USB: It's offering an alternative
cradle that exchanges data via a conventional serial port. But
that'll cost an extra $30, and it won't offer the speed and
convenience that USB promises.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Expansion: Handspring's biggest coup is the Springboard, an
expansion slot on the back of all three Visor models. Handspring
and a slew of other developers are creating an amazing array of
add-on modules that will plug into this opening, including extra
memory, games, reference works, voice recorders, GPS systems,
digital music players, pagers and both wired and wireless modems.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Handspring says it designed the Springboard
technology with users, not engineers, in mind. All modules are
supposed to start up automatically when plugged in _ you won't even
need to load drivers or configure the software.
</P>
<P>
   I did test one such module, a product called EA Sports Tiger
Woods PGA Tour Golf, which Handspring itself will sell for
$29.95. &UR;  &LR; It worked as advertised, though I can't say I find golf on
a 2-inch monochrome screen exhilarating. The other modules won't be
available until sometime this fall, if not later, and prices for
most of them haven't yet been set.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the idea of a PDA that easily can be configured to meet
different needs _ and even reconfigured repeatedly through the
course of a day _ is pretty exciting. Of course, it could be an
expensive habit, and I'm sure there soon will be users demanding a
way to run multiple modules at once _ something Handspring says is
technically quite feasible.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, despite my negative experience with USB, I found the
Visor an innovative and exciting product. If Palm and Microsoft's
Windows CE licensees respond as I hope they will _ with price cuts
and innovations of their own _ the already lively PDA market is
sure to see even more vitality in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   I just hope that Palm won't pull an Apple and change its mind
about licensing its OS after seeing an aggressive offspring
leapfrog its own products.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send feedback to Henry Norr at hnorr &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
