<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3721 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WHISPER-WHISPER_SFCHR     09-15 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHISPER-WHISPER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 How Whisper Estimates Can Affect Stocks
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Stein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
So-called whisper numbers are starting to speak volumes about
whether a company's stock soars _ or plummets.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle Corp. found that out the hard way. The company this week
posted earnings of 16 cents a share, which were in line with the
published consensus estimates of analysts. But that didn't stop
Oracle's stock from falling 6 percent yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   That's because whisper estimates _ the scuttlebutt floating
around Internet sites and chat rooms, which might come in part from
analysts' unpublished tips but also heavily relies on rumor _
predicted 19 cents a share. Oracle proceeded to drop $2.75
yesterday to close at $42.69, after trading as low as $39.88.
</P>
<P>
   More than 64 million shares changed hands, making it the most
active stock in U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   So why are investors disregarding the published reports of
respected analysts who cover companies like Oracle and instead
betting heavily on what might amount to little more than gossip?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whisper number more accurately reflects the true
expectations of analysts.'' said Shannon Puls, co-founder of
EarningsWhispers.com, a popular Web site that calculates and posts
whisper estimates. ``Analysts are taught to be conservative, so in
their reports they tend to publish lower estimates even though they
believe the numbers will be higher.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that some analysts give the juiciest bits of
information to select clients only but that this information often
leaks out and eventually gets incorporated in whisper estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Eisenbarth, an analyst with Collins and Co. in San
Francisco, said that for the most part, he does not know where
whisper numbers come from, but he believes that the whisper
phenomenon is directly related to the growth of the Internet. ``You
never heard about this whole whisper thing until a few years ago,
when the Internet got really popular.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it is not uncommon for an analyst to mention an
unpublished tidbit to a client and then see that nugget circulated
all over Yahoo and financial chat rooms. In the case of Oracle,
EarningsWhispers spoke to analysts off the record to gauge their
true feelings about the stock. It also factored in rumors it was
hearing that Oracle had closed several very big deals at the tail
end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But when those rumors did not pan out yesterday, Oracle paid the
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We attribute the whisper numbers to day traders and momentum
players who are looking for some excitement,'' said an Oracle
spokeswoman. ``Sure, the whisper numbers bother us, but we're not
going to change the way we do business to accommodate these
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies that recently have fallen prey to whisper
estimates include Dell Computer, whose fourth-quarter earnings
reported on February 16 jumped 55 percent but whose stock slumped 8
percent because it missed its whisper estimate by 2 cents a share;
Hewlett-Packard, whose shares fell nearly 6 percent in August after
it missed its ``unpublished forecasts'' by 6 cents; and Ethan Allen
Interiors, whose net income for the third quarter ended March 31
rose 40 percent but whose stock nose-dived about 9 percent after
the results missed its whisper numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the power of whisper numbers and their ability to
greatly impact the stock market, &UR;  &LR; Boston's First Call Corp. this
week started publishing what it calls ``hisper estimates,'' along
with its traditional consensus estimates based on analyst reports.
First Call compiles all analyst reports for a particular company to
create its estimates; until recently, those were the numbers by
which performance was judged.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Hill, director of research at First Call, said his hisper
numbers will be different from whisper numbers because ``they are
based on the historical performance of a company over at least the
last four quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   If a company consistently beats its published estimates by an
average of, say, 2 cents, the hisper number will reflect that
historical pattern. By contrast, adds Hill, ``whisper numbers are
based on who knows what.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he admits that analyst estimates, which typically are
published a month before a company reports earnings, are not always
the best gauge for investors because the numbers quickly get stale,
especially in today's highly volatile economy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a study of 101 high-tech companies' earnings reports by
Bloomberg News showed that estimates on EarningsWhispers.com and a
similar site called StreetIQ.com were off by 21 percent, while the
analyst estimates as aggregated by First Call missed by 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Market experts believe that companies themselves are encouraging
the proliferation of whisper numbers by being overly conservative
with their financial forecasts. Until yesterday, Oracle, for
instance, had trounced analyst estimates for the past six quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company has a pattern of beating the numbers, the
expectation is that it will continue to do so every quarter,'' said
First Call's Hill. ``But once you establish this pattern, it can
always come back and bite you in the rear.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
