<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3723 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA-MEDIA_SFCHRON &LR;      09-15 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-MEDIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Ethical Journalism in a Market-Mad World 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Media ethicists increasingly are posing a question: Can journalists
covering the stock market also trade stocks?
</P>
<P>
   MarketWatch.com Editor in Chief Thom Calandra poses a different
question: Can he fairly tell his reporters that they should give
readers information about stocks but not use any of that
information to trade themselves?
</P>
<P>
   The answer lies in the new MarketWatch stock ownership policy,
posted on the company Web site at
cbs.marketwatch.com/news/edpolicy.htx?sourcehtx/http2mw. (You also
can find it from the main page at cbs.marketwatch.com by clicking
on Site Map at the top of the page and then clicking on Editorial
Policy under the About Us heading.)
</P>
<P>
   The policy is harder to find than that of rival TheStreet.com,
which links its policy at the end of every story. And it's not
nearly as stringent: TheStreet prohibits reporters from owning
stocks, except through mutual funds and except in TheStreet itself.
(That doesn't go for columnists, however, such as co-founder James
Cramer, a walking conflict-of-interest case who writes about
everything, including firms in his hedge fund's portfolio, and then
discloses everything.)
</P>
<P>
   The expanded MarketWatch policy prohibits newsroom staffers from
trading securities of companies they regularly cover. If they write
about another company, they can't trade that stock until 48 hours
after their story is published. If they own stock in a company and
are assigned to write the story anyway, their interest will be
disclosed on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 53 full-time journalists; 49 of them said they did not
want to be excluded from the stock and bond markets,'' Calandra
said.
</P>
<P>
   Calandra reviewed proposals with his newest columnist, Marshall
Loeb, the former editor of Columbia Journalism Review, and picked
the two-day ban even though they figured that ``makes no sense,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, our journalists are not trading on news that they are
withholding, are they? Why should we trust their judgment when it
comes to the delivery of news, then devise some policy that in
effect says, `If you trade before 72 hours, or three weeks, or
three months, you're in deep doo-doo.' Our editorial trading
policies, which have worked very well for three years now, are to
guide our writers and editors, not penalize them or straitjacket
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a fine bunch of folks with the highest standards, and
that's the way they get treated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A NEW SALON: Salon.com is moving, but not too far. The online
magazine is leaving its home above the Rochester Big and Tall shop
on Mission Street and moving to new digs around the corner at 22
Fourth St.
</P>
<P>
   The move should happen by the end of November, and the company
will double the size of its quarters, from 10,000 square feet to
20,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the growing of a plant,'' said Chief Financial
Officer Todd Hagen. ``You put a plant in a small pot, it only grows
so big. lf you put it in a bigger pot, it grows bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon already is too big for its current space, but the new
offices will have room to grow further. It's part of Pacific
Resources PCX Development's $200 million project, Pacific Place,
which includes the new Hotel Palomar and the 102,000 square foot
Old Navy flagship store, opening in October.
</P>
<P>
   Salon is the last tenant in the 16-story office tower, which is
anchored by the advertising and media departments of Macy's,
according to Jeff Vance, Pacific's directing manager.
</P>
<P>
   It was tough to find space close to downtown, Hagen said, but
the company nailed down the new office with a 10-year lease that
over time will average $42.50 per square foot _ or $850,000 _ per
year.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, even a company in cyberspace needs some real estate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEWS? AD?: Talk about blurring the lines. Running alongside news
stories on the Forbes.com Web site is something headlined
``Microsoft Daily News.'' Beneath it are headlines and links that
look an awful lot like news _ even though it's all a paid promotion
from Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The Industry Standard first called the ads to the attention of
the Magazine Publishers Association, which now is investigating.
The association, which doles out prestigious National Magazine
Awards each year, can sanction members who violate the ad-editorial
wall.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes is comfortable that the ads don't violate guidelines,
which require that ads be clearly labeled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe it's an issue. We do our best not to mix
advertising and editorial issues,'' said David Churbuck, editor of
Forbes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spokeswoman Monie Begley said the site is ``absolutely in
compliance'' with APME's guidelines. The Microsoft ad is ``readily
identifiable'' as an ad, with no hint of it being editorial
content, she said. The Standard story represents ``the first time
any of this has been brought up. There hasn't been a phone call or
a complaint,'' Begley said.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Kahan, executive director of the American Society of
Magazine Editors, declined to comment, noting that an ASME
committee is reviewing the ads for any possible policy violations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SENSATIONAL SALE?: Tech publishing giant Ziff-Davis publicly denied
this week's report in the London Observer that media mogul Rupert
Murdoch's News Corp. was about to gobble up Ziff for $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Murdoch, who owns the Fox television network and the New
York Post, would have a hard time sensationalizing the bits and
bytes in PC Week or the geeks at ZDTV.
</P>
<P>
   But the price may look like a bargain. After all, Ziff _ which
is, indeed, on the block _ was sold in 1994 to New York's Forstmann
Little &AMP; Co. for $1.4 billion and then sold again to Japan's
Softbank for $2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to fostd &LR; sfgate.com, call (415) 777-6004 or
fax (415) 543-2482.
</P>
