<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 16
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MILITARY-POLITICS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Sept. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Sept.
8, about a study of opinion among civilian and military elites
misidentified the site of an October conference on the study. It
will be at the McCormick Tribune Foundation's Cantigny estate in
Wheaton, Ill.; there is no Caughny, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CONGRESS-SCENE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Sept. 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Sept. 14,
about the debate over campaign finance legislation misspelled the
middle name of the author of ``Tell-Tale Heart,'' to which a
Democrat compared the resilient measure. He was Edgar Allan Poe,
not Allen.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CREDIT-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Sept. 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Sept. 14,
about the daily performance of bond prices referred imprecisely to
the three lead managers of a $6 billion offering by Freddie Mac.
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter is a lead manager with Credit Suisse
First Boston and Merrill Lynch. Bear, Stearns is a co-manager, not
a lead manager.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-CORNED-BEEF-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Sept. 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Sept. 14,
about a search for a good corned beef sandwich in New York City
misspelled the surname of a professor of humanities at New York
University who recalled the heyday of what he called ``Jewish soul
food.'' He is Rabbi Arthur Hertzberg, not Herzberg.
</P>
<P>
   BC-WEB-HOME-FURNISHING-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Sept. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Sept.
8, about new home-furnishings Web sites, including
www.fiftie-fiftie.com, a Belgian Web site that gives prices in
euros and francs, misstated the dollar valuation for 100 Belgian
francs. It is $2.62, not $262.
</P>
