<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-HURRICANE-FLOYD-     09-15 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HURRICANE-FLOYD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STORM WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, Sept. 16: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To call the calm at the center of a hurricane an ``eye'' is a
metaphor, and a peculiarly disembodied one at that. The image is
barely anatomical, as the term ``eye wall,'' which has no
anatomical equivalent, suggests. The eye wall is the tight,
circular boundary of wind and cloud that separates the eye from the
swirling body of the storm. Sometimes it shapes itself into a
pantheon of clouds through which a lens of clear, blue daylight is
visible at the very top. The eye wall is also the most violent
region of the hurricane, the place where research aircraft flying
into the storm are most severely buffeted and where heaviest damage
is inflicted when a hurricane moves inland.
</P>
<P>
   What is striking about a hurricane like Floyd, which at this
writing is moving up the Atlantic coast at a four-minute-mile pace,
is the amount of information being drawn from it. Aircraft from the
53d Weather Reconnaissance Squadron have been flying into the
storm, clocking wind speeds and dropping weather-instrument
packages called dropsondes in the exact pressure center of the
vortex. Satellites have been tracking Floyd's movement from high
above, returning readings on every possible parameter. As Floyd
approaches and passes over them, weather buoys weigh in, as do
land-based weather-instrument stations. An astonishing amount of
this information _ gathered for the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration _ now makes its way promptly onto the
Internet, which has become something of a weather watcher's dream.
</P>
<P>
   It feels almost Olympian to look down on this hurricane from the
vantage of a weather satellite, the early sun catching the
symmetrical, flattened whorl of clouds as it scudded toward Florida
before turning northward Tuesday morning. From a satellite view,
the size of this storm, the extent to which it dwarfs Hurricane
Andrew, for instance, is immediately visible. Its nucleus alone _
the core mass of unbroken clouds _ is the size of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the sublime has almost vanished in this century. The
mountain scenes that so moved Goethe and many others in the late
18th century now seem ornamental at best. But a storm of this
magnitude still bears along with it the terrifying sublimity of the
winds and seas. To that we have added this serene, supernal vista.
It seems inevitable, by now, to personify a hurricane as the
National Weather Service has been doing since 1947, to call it
Floyd, to speak of its eye and its wrath. But to see a hurricane as
we do now, in its symmetrical wholeness as well as in its fury,
makes personification a little like an act of hubris. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
