<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-PEACEKEEPING-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RARE TALKS, U.S. AND JAKARTA OFFICERS WILL DISCUSS TROOP
SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Clinton administration discussed which U.S.
forces would take part in a peacekeeping mission to East Timor, a
senior U.S. military official met Wednesday at the United Nations
with an Indonesian counterpart and sought to ensure the full
cooperation of the Indonesian military, the White House announced.
</P>
<P>
   In an exception to a recent ban by the White House on military
contacts with Indonesia, Gen. Joseph Ralston, the vice chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, flew to New York Wednesday to meet Lt.
Gen. Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, who has been put in charge of
coordinating how Indonesian forces work with the Australian-led
peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress and Pentagon officials have insisted that
the mission include strong measures to protect all the forces
involved, and the United Nations is seeking assurances from
Yudhoyono that his troops will cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen said Wednesday that a
decision about specific U.S. units for the mission would be made
``within the next day or so.''
</P>
<P>
   The troops will provide transportation, logistics, communication
and intelligence, and the United States is likely to station only a
few hundred in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cargo planes, ships, tankers and specialists will be
drawn from bases in the Pacific command, according to Rear Adm.
Craig Quigley, a Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A team of 15 U.S. military experts from the Pacific command has
been working with the Australian military since Friday, drawing up
detailed plans for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is waiting for the United Nations to decide which
countries are going to take part and what they will need for
support.
</P>
<P>
   Washington expects to be asked to use its huge cargo planes to
help countries in the region bring in the jeeps, trucks and other
equipment that will be needed to support their troops in East
Timor.
</P>
</TEXT>
