<SLUG> BC-WACO-LAWSUIT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas talk show host to help build church at Mount Carmel
 &HT;    By Mark England and Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Austin talk show host Alex Jones, described by one
journalist as a man who ``never met a conspiracy he didn't like,''
plans to come to Waco this Sunday to start building a new church
for the Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you in three months they're going to have a
substantial church built on their original site _ unless tanks
drive up and stop us,'' said Jones, who hosts a radio program aimed
at the dark side on, appropriately, KJFK-FM.
</P>
<P>
   Jones plans to lead a convoy from the Capitol Plaza in Austin to
what's left of Mount Carmel, about 10 miles east of Waco. He's
using his radio program _ where he once accused the Federal
Emergency Management Agency of building concentration camps on
military bases _ to ask for volunteers from all the construction
trades as well as anyone wanting to donate materials and funds.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Lambert, a Waco bank auditor, heard the call. He's
already phoned the volunteer line (512-292-0070).
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been wishing this would happen since the compound
burned in 1993,'' Lambert said. ``And I called to see what I could
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert views the project as a form of protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is basically a peaceful protest to let the government know
that we are not going to take them coming down here and burning
churches for no reason at all,'' Lambert said. ``In addition, it is
just a good neighborly gesture. The Branch Davidians were wronged
by the government, and we are going to pull together as neighbors
to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone doesn't have to be as sure as Lambert as to the origin
of the fire at Mount Carmel to pitch in, according to Jones. He's
not looking to build Mount Carmel II, he said, just ``an old
country church.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea came up while talking to his friend, Mike Hanson, a
building contractor, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an endorsement of anyone,'' Jones said. ``It's not
even an attack on the government. It's act of defiance, if
anything. It's just saying you can't come here and spread
half-truths and wipe people out.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Jones, who got his start on Austin's public access
television, doesn't have a theory on Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was about heralding in a police state,'' Jones said.
``Clinton came to power and designated the right-wing groups as the
enemy. This little band in Texas was picked as a test case. For six
years, America has gotten an A-plus for reveling in the
establishment of a police state. It's wrong to allow the government
to paint people as evil and everyone join in on the barbecue.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidians are taking a wait-and-see approach to the offer of
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been very supportive,'' said Sheila Martin, who
lives in Waco. ``They want to help us get back on our feet. But
this is a situation where we're waiting on God to do what he thinks
he should do. That's the peace we have, knowing God will direct
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clive Doyle, who survived the fire that destroyed Mount Carmel,
said the offer to build the Davidians a church showed a ``kind
spirit.'' There are about 20 Davidians who still live in the Waco
area, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Doyle isn't getting his hopes up yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are willing to donate to a project when they
can see that it is up and running, but not so much if they can't
see anything going on,'' Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   As with most things dealing with the Davidians, the ownership of
Mount Carmel is not clear-cut. Surviving Davidians are not the only
ones claiming the property. Also making claims are Amo Roden Bishop
(ex-wife of George Roden, who lost a power struggle with David
Koresh) and Douglas Mitchell, who belonged to the pre-Koresh
Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   While ownership of the land is disputed, there's nothing to keep
a church from being built on the property, said Houston attorney
Percy Isgitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The latest ruling was that the land belongs to the church,''
said Isgitt, who represents Doyle. ``Now what is left to determine
is who are the representatives of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be the second building project this year for Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he organized an effort to build a home for disabled
World War II veteran Joe Campana, who refused to abandon a house
falling down on him.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' listeners built a small two-room house for Campana in two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, about 10 a.m., Jones hopes to stake out the church,
for which architectural plans have already been drawn, put down
rebar and get everything ready to pour the construction columns.
Besides volunteers to provide labor, Jones said he needs materials
such as concrete and rebar. He's also looking for a backhoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we'll really be trying to build back is the First
Amendment,'' Jones said. ``That's freedom of the press, the right
to freely assemble, freedom of religion and a lot of other things.
Basically, the freedom not to be bothered when you're not messing
with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
