<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-TRIALDELAYED16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge delays start of Branch Davidian civil trial
 &HT;    By Tommy Witherspoon and Mark England
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Delays in transferring custody of tons of evidence
related to the death of David Koresh and 75 followers at the Branch
Davidian compound near Waco have forced the postponement of the
wrongful-death civil lawsuit against the government set for next
month.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco, in an order
released Wednesday, stated the Oct. 18 trial date ``will be
impossible to maintain.'' Smith did not set a new trial date.
However, he said the government's proposed trial date of fall 2000
``is not realistic, and the trial date will not be postponed for
that length of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the government and the plaintiffs had motions pending with
Smith to postpone the trial. A court official, however, said
earlier this month that the judge was trying hard to stick with the
scheduled trial date.
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Mike Caddell of Houston, who represents some of the
plaintiffs, said he wasn't surprised by Smith's order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expected the judge to grant a continuance,'' Caddell
said. ``It's clear that the developments of the last few weeks have
raised a lot of issues that would make it very difficult to prepare
for trial by Oct. 18. I always believed Judge Smith would recognize
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said the continuance
was merited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the judge appropriately recognized the gathering of
materials would take longer than October 1,'' Marlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's order Wednesday also granted the plaintiffs' request for
a status conference on the case, although it did not set a date for
it. That will be done ``once the logistics of the evidence transfer
and storage have been resolved,'' according to Smith's order.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said both sides will benefit from the continuance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have more time to digest the evidence that has become
available in the last few weeks,'' Caddell said. ``It will also
give both sides an opportunity to prepare their case in a way that
the presentation of the evidence can be more efficient and focused.
You can sometimes do a better job and be quicker when you have time
to get ready than when you have to do things in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit stems from the the 1993 raid by the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms agents on Mount Carmel, the
Davidians' residence about 10 miles east of Waco. Four agents and
five Davidians died in a gun battle. Following a 51-day siege, a
fire consumed the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving Davidians and the relatives of the dead later sued,
challenging the government's conclusion that the Davidians shot
first during the raid and started the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's order defuses what had seemed like a growing conflict
over custody of the evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Smith was said to have been angered by the
apparent reluctance of government officials to comply with his
sweeping order to turn over all evidence related to the Branch
Davidian case, much of which has been stored for years by the
Department of Public Safety in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney William Blagg of San Antonio challenged Smith's
discovery order, saying it placed an ``unwarranted and substantial
burden'' on the government and hampered its preparations for the
wrongful-death lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In an order filed earlier this month, Smith countered by calling
the government's claims ``somewhat disingenuous since the
government has been in possession of the material for six years and
has been aware since 1994, when the civil suits were originally
filed, that this material could very well be subject to
discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith on Wednesday, however, granted a continuance after the
government made it known through informal channels that it would
bow to the court's authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court has been informed that the Justice Department
intends to comply with the court's order,'' Smith wrote. ``However,
the physical transfer of control of all of this evidence will take
longer than originally anticipated by the Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
