<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULGER-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING SETS GUIDES ON USE OF INFORMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (mk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a ruling on a case with unusually broad implications
for the murky world of criminal informers, a federal judge on
Wednesday rejected a claim by an informer that he deserved blanket
immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, Mark Wolf of U.S. District Court here, affirmed
specific assurances the defendant said he had received that he
would not suffer because of information gained from electronic
listening devices that the bureau planted with his help. The
defendant, Stephen Flemmi, is described by prosecutors as a career
criminal who was also a longtime informer for the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also ordered more hearings next month to determine if
the recorded conversations are so central to racketeering and
extortion charges against Flemmi that the case should be dismissed
altogether. Flemmi is said to have served as the sidekick-in-crime
to James Bulger, the black-sheep brother of the current president
of the University of Massachusetts, William Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   James Bulger was the sometime head of the closest thing to an
Irish mob in Boston, prosecutors say. Bulger, who had also been
recruited as a bureau informer, fled in 1995 when he was about to
be indicted in the case. He is now on the FBI's list of 10
most-wanted fugitives.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling, tangled, ever-so-Bostonian story of how Bulger
and Flemmi were recruited to inform for the bureau in the
anti-Mafia fever of a generation ago and the warm relationships
they formed with their FBI handlers, seem so much the stuff of
books and movies that several are reportedly in the works.
</P>
<P>
   But the trial of Flemmi and other defendants has been hung up by
pretrial hearings largely focused on the questionable ties between
FBI agents and their informants.
</P>
<P>
   One unsettling aspect of the case that has emerged is that such
confidential informers, in exchange for the information they
provide the bureau, are allowed to commit certain crimes and
promised the agency's protection if other law-enforcement branches
come after them. Flemmi testified that an FBI supervisor told him
and Bulger they would not have to worry about their crimes as long
as they did not kill someone, quoting the agent as saying, ``You
can do whatever you want, just don't clip anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's ruling, Wolf noted that deals with criminals must
sometimes be struck and that ``informants are valuable, if not
vital, assets in combating serious crime.'' But he also took the
FBI to task on some aspects of its relationship with Flemmi, noting
at one point that it had ``routinely ignored'' guidelines requiring
it to report informers' crimes to the Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The case has prompted the Department of Justice to review and
tighten its rules on how such informers are handled.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, both sides in the case declared themselves at least
partly happy with the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Stern, the U.S. attorney here, said in a statement that
he was pleased that Wolf had ``flatly rejected Flemmi's claim that
he was provided immunity from prosecution.'' But he said he was
disappointed by the judge's call for further hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Fishman, Flemmi's lawyer, called the ruling ``a major
victory,'' saying the judge had believed most of what Flemmi said.
Fishman predicted that the government's case against Flemmi would
be substantially weakened by the new strictures on the material it
can use.
</P>
<P>
   In broader terms, Fishman said, ``I think this decision will
become a standard for the all-important concept that when the
government makes a bargain, they need to live by it.''
</P>
<P>
   However the current trial turns out, Flemmi's troubles are far
from over. Federal prosecutors here announced last week that they
had cemented a plea deal with a confessed hit man, John Martorano,
who is expected to testify against Flemmi and Bulger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0467 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-CAROLINAS-H     09-15 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-CAROLINAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAROLINAS BRACE FOR DANGEROUS FLOYD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
and STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ After spawning the biggest peacetime
evacuation in U.S. history, a weakened but still dangerous
Hurricane Floyd headed for landfall on the Carolina coast
Wednesday, bringing with it the threat of high winds and torrential
rains as far north as Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people were ordered out of their homes as
Floyd, with winds of 115 miles per hour, churned toward a landing
somewhere between here and Myrtle Beach, S.C., early Thursday
morning. As its eye approached late Wednesday, Floyd was already
causing extensive street flooding and power outages as far south as
Charleston, S.C. which was experiencing hurricane force wind gusts.
</P>
<P>
   Wilmington had already received more than a foot of rain and a
tornado had been reported on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day Wednesday, residents in the Carolinas
streamed away from their coastal communities, jamming freeways as
they headed inland for shelter. In all, 2.6 million people from
Florida to North Carolina were ordered evacuated in what officials
described as the largest evacuation for a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, Floyd was considered one of the biggest storms ever
to threaten the United States. While it tore up the Bahamas on
Tuesday, it was about 600 miles wide and carried winds in excess of
150 miles per hour. But after delivering a glancing blow to Florida
on Tuesday night, it steadily weakened as it took aim at the
Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, because of its enormous size, forecasters warned
Floyd could still drop copious rain as it moved inland on its
predicted track up the Eastern Seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, where about 1.3 million people were ordered out of
their homes, squalls in the outer bands of Floyd were strong enough
to knock down trees and power lines and churn up waves big enough
to consume a 100-foot section of a pier at Daytona Beach. At NASA's
Kennedy Space Center, gusts of wind up to 81 miles per hour were
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   And about 350 miles off the coast of Jacksonville, Fla., U.S.
Navy helicopters rescued eight crewmen from a tug bout that had
floundered in 30-feet seas kicked up by the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   But while Florida and Georgia were breathing collective sighs of
relief, authorities in the Carolinas were bracing for the full
impact and officials in states as far north as New York were
expecting heavy rains, high winds and high tides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Florida and Georgia at this point feel like
they've dodged a real bullet,'' said North Carolina's public safety
secretary Richard Moore. ``This thing is not going to miss us.''
</P>
<P>
   While significantly weaker than the Category 4 monster it was 36
hours ago, Floyd was still a 300-mile wide system with hurricane
force winds extending as far as 140 miles from its center on its
northeast flank, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the damage Floyd could inflict on the coast,
President Clinton on Wednesday extended an emergency declaration to
include North and South Carolina. On Wednesday, the president, in
what he called an ``unprecedented'' action, declared emergencies in
Florida and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of Hurricane Floyd prompted Clinton to abandon a day
of golf in Hawaii during a refueling stop on his way back from a
trip to New Zealand and head directly to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've done everything we know to do,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of residents evacuated the North Carolina coast
Wednesday, clogging interstate highways and main roads leading
inland. One official estimated traffic along I-40 west stretched
100 miles as people fled Floyd as it approached the shore near
Wilmington. At 4 p.m. CST vehicles were at a virtual stand still on
I-40 for the last 50 miles heading into the Raleigh-Durham area.
</P>
<P>
   Coastal counties were under a mandatory evacuation, especially
those living in mobile or manufactured homes and along the beaches.
David Paynter with the Wilmington emergency operations center said
tens of thousands had evacuated New Hanover and Pender counties.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuations were also ordered for the barrier islands off the
coast near Wilmington, as well as for the ecologically fragile
Outer Banks that were severely damaged by Hurricane Dennis only a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Four shelters were set up at area schools in Wilmington where
150,000 people live, Paynter said. By evening, all but one were
filled to capacity. Each could hold 200 to 250 people.
</P>
<P>
   While several streets in Wilmington already were flooding by
Wednesday evening, Paynter said many still were passable. Power
outages, he said, were increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty calm right now,'' Paynter said. ``We've had a few
slight gusts of wind but that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has been preparing for the storm for several days, said
Cam Griffin, with the emergency operations center. ``We are as
prepared as you can be for a storm. We are ready for it to hit.``
</P>
<P>
   In Charleston, where the memory of Hurricane Hugo, which scored
a direct hit on the city almost exactly 10 years ago, is still
fresh, authorities expressed relief that Floyd appeared to be
moving north of the city, but were still concerned about winds in
excess of 110 miles per hour, heavy rains and flooding caused by a
storm surge which could be as high as 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Slater, a spokeswoman for the Charleston County Emergency
Operations Center, said that at least 75 percent of the county's
316,000 residents heeded warnings to evacuate on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very fortunate that it has drifted a little bit north
of us,'' Slater said.
</P>
<P>
   In this city of historic houses and handsome boulevards,
comparisons to Hugo _ which killed 49 and caused damage worth $8.4
billion _ are inevitable when talking hurricanes and one resident
scoffed at the idea that Floyd was a more powerful storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can be worse than Hugo,'' said Bobby Drainer, a
longtime Charleston-area resident who stopped by a local motel to
seek out a cup of coffee and said he was going to ride out the
storm in the city. ``If it was worse than that, I'd be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Others weren't taking chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got insurance on the house,'' one man declared, as he bought
a pack of smokes. ``I don't need to stick around here.''
</P>
<P>
   After avoiding the full wrath of Floyd, many of the 1.3 million
people in Florida who had been told to evacuate began returning to
their homes to find tree limbs and power lines down.
</P>
<P>
   By late Wednesday, at least 100,000 people in Florida remained
without power, which was expected to be restored to at least 75
percent of the customers by this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In Jacksonville, Mayor John Delaney urged returning residents to
be patient, even to stay put at inland shelters, hotels, and
friends' and relatives' homes until Thursday to give work crews
time to restore power.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Friday we expect everything to be back to normal in
Jacksonville, Florida,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Gov. Jeb Bush praised the citizens of his state for
heeding calls to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to know'' what's in store with a hurricane, he
said. ``You have to prepare and you have to evacuate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
