<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-NY-ART-710&AMP;     09-15 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-NY-ART-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRACING FOR FLOYD, NO MATTER HOW BIG
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Ill.)  (With HURRICANE-RDP, HURRICANE-FLORIDA, HURRICANE-BEACHES,
HURRICANE-BAHAMAS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In New Jersey, Gov. Christie Whitman declared a state
of emergency because of concern about major coastal flooding.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, stepping into his
familiar role as the city's top crisis counselor, said he would
open 20 shelters Thursday _ just in case.
</P>
<P>
   And on Long Island, the Suffolk County executive, Robert J.
Gaffney, urged residents of Fire Island to evacuate before wind and
rain made it impossible to escape by ferry.
</P>
<P>
   All over the region Wednesday, local officials and emergency
personnel scrambled to prepare for Hurricane Floyd, which, by the
time it passes through Thursday night, could have weakened to
Tropical Storm Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said Wednesday night that it was still too early
to predict the path the storm would follow or what kind of wallop
it might pack, but they were preparing for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service was predicting that Hurricane Floyd
would make landfall in the Carolinas and whip through the New York
metropolitan area by late Thursday, bringing up to 8 inches of
rain, winds of at least 40 mph, widespread coastal flooding and
major beach erosion.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of a torrential downpour that crippled New York City's
transportation network three weeks ago, when just three inches of
rain fell in a short period, officials said Wednesday that they
were concerned about flooding.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Giuliani said that he would open 20
shelters Thursday at noon for people who might need to evacuate
low-lying areas.
</P>
<P>
   The shelters will be able to hold up to 70,000 people, although,
the mayor said, ``I highly doubt we will need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Reuter, president of New York City Transit, said storm
drains had been cleaned, flood-prone areas had been fortified with
sandbags and water pumps had been checked to ensure optimal
service. ``We plan to run service through the storm as long as we
are able,'' Reuter said.
</P>
<P>
   New York City schools are expected to close at 6 p.m. Thursday,
cancelling all evening programs and classes, Giuliani said. But it
was still not clear Wednesday night whether those cancellations
would extend into Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   And while city officials have distributed 50,000 brochures in
the last two days offering tips on handling the storm, Giuliani
also urged people to remove from yards and balconies any items _
such as gas-grill tanks and folding chairs _ that could become
projectiles in furious winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have things out on a balcony, if they have things on a
roof, if they have things even on their lawn or on the sidewalk
that could easily blow away, you know that, remove it, put it
inside, secure it and you'll be protecting yourself and protecting
others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the city will have a better idea later Thursday
what measures are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer we can get to the event and therefore have to take
action, the more intelligent the action is going to be,'' he said.
``So the best thing to do is for people to be warned.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Whitman declared a kind of pre-emptive state of
emergency, warning against the danger of coastal flooding coupled
with high winds. And she said she would decide early Thursday
morning whether to close the state's schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Moore, New Jersey's chief coastal engineer, said his
inspectors spent most of Wednesday checking the state's 127 miles
of Atlantic coastline, particularly beachfronts in Cape May County.
At the moment, Moore said, he was taking a ``wait and see''
approach.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, Gaffney, the county executive, said he might
convert the voluntary evacuation of Fire Island into a mandatory
one, depending on the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In the coastal city of Long Beach, officials had already checked
and fueled emergency vehicles, primed their power generators and
prepared to deal with fallen trees and windblown objects, said
Eugene C. Cammarato, the city's director of operations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city handed out 4,000 sandbags to people,
businesses and local institutions to wall off the rising tide,
which meteorologists said may climb to eight feet above normal.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time since 1995, Cammarato said, that the city
had distributed sandbags.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The region's utility companies were busy Wednesday , too.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Edison has alerted its tree-trimming contractors to
be on standby, to help crews fix fallen power lines if necessary.
The utility said it plans to provide dry ice to customers to help
preserve food if the power fails.
</P>
<P>
   Keyspan, the holding company for the union of Brooklyn Union Gas
and the Long Island Lighting Co., has canceled training classes
Thursday at its Coney Island center because that area is prone to
floods, said Robert Mahoney, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   And Public Service Energy and Gas has recruited 50 workers from
Illinois Power to join its crews in New Jersey to assist with any
electrical failures, said Beth Derin, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   It may turn out that the bark of Floyd is worse than the bite,
that Floyd will turn out to be more a lesson in preparation than an
exercise in emergency management. Still, many area residents, like
the officials, were preparing for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricane Floyd may still be a long way off, but everyone's
afraid of it. Nobody wants to see it hit,'' said Joe Matlaga, 36,
who was battening down the hatches of his 25-foot fishing boat, the
Phoenix, at the Covesail Marina in Sea Bright, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at the gathering gloom, then added: ``I went fishing
yesterday, because I figured I may not have a boat left after this
storm hits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
