<HEADER>
A3819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-WRESTLING-CAMP16-COX     09-15 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-CAMP16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Readin', writin' and rasslin'
 &HT;    By Frank W. Rabey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, N.C. _ Fame drives the dream: A young man swaggers
through swirling smoke into the big ring, a bikini-clad babe on
each arm. The crowd boos. The man destroys all who oppose him. The
crowd cheers. The bank account grows.
</P>
<P>
   But for the thousands of youngsters dreaming the dream, only a
small handful will make the big time. That's why the wrestling
industry has its version of the wakeup call _ the indy leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Many would-be wrestlers get a cold dose of reality in the
independent training centers that are cropping up all over. From
there, if you get a gig, it's in the local community center, where
crowds can be tiny. If you get paid, it may be little better than
squat. Broken bones are routine. The blood is very real.
</P>
<P>
   One such place is the Great American Wrestling Federation
Training Center in this small town just west of Asheville where
wrestlers named Pain and the World's Strongest Teenager dream of
the big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job to smack 'em with reality,'' says J.D. Sullivan,
37, GAWF's principal trainer and current heavyweight champion who
works by day at a furniture factory. ``Not every guy is gonna get a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the big schools don't do that,'' he adds. ``They just
take a young kid's money, beat the crap out of him for six months,
and if they like him, they keep him; and if they don't, they send
him on his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some small schools have their own problems, too, according to
GAWF owner Bill Hagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of little fly-by-night organizations have people in the
ring that are not ready to be there, and they get hurt,'' Hagan
says. ``We just don't let 'em in the ring if they're not trained.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't break into the big time anymore without wrestling
school, Sullivan says. A young wrestler may have years of
indy-circuit experience, but if he wants to get picked up by the
World Wrestling Federation, World Championship Wrestling or Extreme
Championship Wrestling, he's probably going to have to school with
one of the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Big-league wrestling schools like the WCW's Power Plant and
those of the WWF and ECW fuel big-league dreams, but have
big-league fees.
</P>
<P>
   Indy schools tend to be much cheaper, and maybe more honest.
Sullivan and Chris Wright, who runs a wrestling-training program in
Smithfield, N.C., tell their young wrestlers up front: This is a
hard road you're starting, bub.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I can guarantee,'' Wright says, ``is that you're
not going to come out of my school until you're ready. I'm not
going to put a kid out on the mat and let him hurt somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety is one thing you can train, but the biggest hurdle for
some neophyte wrestlers comes in putting on their game faces.
Believe it or not, they're shy. Sullivan says that the majority of
the guys he's trained over the years have battled shyness.
</P>
<P>
   Wright tries to offset those initial jitters by letting some of
his students go into the ring for the first time with masks on.
They get a cautious taste of the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence takes time, but finding your own identity as a
wrestler is something else entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charisma's something you can't teach,'' Wright says. ``Some
kids have it, some kids don't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got several guys here now that you'd swear are eating
some type of drug or something,'' Sullivan laughs. ``They lose
their minds from time to time. They scare me.''
</P>
<P>
   The eternal teenager
</P>
<P>
   The World's Strongest Teenager turns 20 in October. What will we
call him then? He'll still be the World's Strongest Teenager.
</P>
<P>
   The title was won at a 1997 powerlifting event in Blackpool,
England. ``I'll hold it until somebody breaks it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of wrestling, even on the indy circuit, you can
call yourself anything you want, so long as you're winning.
</P>
<P>
   But even if he loses the title, he'll probably keep the name,
which has a certain poetry to it: Wrestling is where grown men
extend those testosterone-addled teen years indefinitely. They
dress up scarier than the rock group KISS. They shout in each
other's faces. They puff up their chests like fighting cocks,
pushing and pulling and whacking and slamming each other between
boastful sashays around the ring.
</P>
<P>
   The WST has another name, too: Steve Crowe. By that one, he
lives with his dad, a truck driver, in Statham, Ga., just outside
Athens. And he lays floor covering. ``Until the 'rasslin' takes
off,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Like other young hopefuls, Crowe is ready to ditch the day job _
just as soon as he doesn't need it to finance his road trips. And
his training.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe trains in Athens, Ga., with ``Fast Track'' John Aaron and
``Outlaw'' Tommy James, affiliates of GAWF.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe's instructors have taught him ``a lot about life,'' he
says. ``They taught me from becoming a boy into a man. They taught
me a lot about business, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He was trained hard, the old-school way. ``It's real rough, what
I had to go through. A lot of it's mental. You've got to be able to
block pain out. If you get hurt, you've got to keep on going.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowe vividly recalls his first day at GAWF. It began with
running. Then there were squats _ 1,000, without stopping.
Push-ups. Sit-ups. Step-ups. A short break. And more running _
``constant, nonstop running.''
</P>
<P>
   Before wrapping up, he practiced some basic moves, which mainly
involved Crowe getting knocked around. GAWF owner Hagan calls it
``taking bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next few months, training sessions remained heavier on
physical conditioning than wrestling technique.
</P>
<P>
   Once that was over, Crowe would say to people he knew who'd been
through military boot camp, ``Man, you ain't did nothin' with what
I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, he's wrestling in venues throughout Georgia and
across the Carolinas. He loves it, especially the crowd. ``How they
react when you do a move,'' he explains. ``Or how they react when
you get hit. It's awesome, how it goes on like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Crowe, like thousands of other young wannabe ringmasters,
has his sights set far above the high school gymnasiums, bingo
halls and National Guard armories where most indy matches are
fought in front of anywhere from a handful of people to a couple
thousand. He has the dream bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to get up there with the big boys in a few more
months,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF. The WCW. The guys on TV.
</P>
<P>
   `He's a monster'
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling may be a youthful pursuit, but it isn't just a young
man's game: Old-school dynamo Ric Flair, 50, is still working, as
bottle-blond as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Wright's students are kids. But the average age of guys
in training at GAWF is between 25 and 28, Sullivan says.
</P>
<P>
   John Boyer is 33.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer lives in Swannanoa, just east of Asheville. At 6-foot-8,
he's almost as big as the mountains he lives in. ``In my wrestlin'
boots, they put me at 6-foot-10.''
</P>
<P>
   And he weighs 400 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a monster,'' Sullivan says.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the bigger guys can't take the rigors of training,
Hagan says. ``I've had some train for an hour and go get a drink of
water, and I've never seen them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyer is another story. He's determined and eager.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wrestle,'' he says, ``it'll be against two or three
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyer's past is as colorful as he's trying to make his future:
Bouncer. Bodyguard for the Rolling Stones. Bodyguard for a Saudi
prince.
</P>
<P>
   He left the Middle East for Asheville more than a year ago to be
with his wife, whom he'd met on a Stones tour stop in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most wrestlers are usually family people with kids and regular
jobs,'' Boyer says.
</P>
<P>
   In the ring, he's Pain. Out of the ring, he drives a milk truck
and owns his own ice cream truck.
</P>
<P>
   One of his customers told him about the GAWF school. ``I just
said, 'Yeah, yeah. Sure, sure.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Boyer did a little investigating anyway, and liked what he
found out about Hagan and the GAWF organization. His training began
a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing they taught him, he says, ``was how not to hurt
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After being taught for his whole life that falling down was to
be avoided, now he was being told to throw his arms and feet up in
the air and land squarely on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your brain just doesn't want to let your body do that,''
Sullivan says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   On Boyer's first day, he and his brain disagreed, and he nearly
broke an ankle when he unconsciously tucked one of his legs in
during a staged fall.
</P>
<P>
   He's also learned to watch out for his opponent's safety. At his
size, if he hits somebody hard enough, he could kill them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to worry about that,'' he says. ``Safety's the
number one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the risks are part of the show. And Boyer really digs the
show. He's got the dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead and pay me a couple hundred thousand dollars a
year,'' he says, ``and you can beat me with a baseball bat, I don't
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
