<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grapevine: Eric Bischoff's rise and fall
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eric Bischoff's rise was also his fall.
</P>
<P>
   In making his organization the biggest in the sports
entertainment business, the WCW president, who was fired Sept. 10,
had hooked his star to Hulk Hogan and a new Monday night program
called ``Nitro.'' In the end, a weaker Hogan could no longer carry
WCW, and Bischoff was killed with his own weapon _ the rival Monday
show from the World Wrestling Federation that has destroyed WCW in
the ratings this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bischoff was replaced by Bill Busch, formerly the senior vice
president for strategic planning. Busch, who's been with WCW for 10
years, now holds the title of executive vice president of WCW,
supervising all day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive spending on wrestling talent, coupled with falling
ratings, was the main reason for Bischoff's ouster. In trying to
combat WWF's raunchier and more creative offerings, WCW seemed to
get sloppy in the losing cause.
</P>
<P>
   Bischoff's ouster on Friday came two days before the ``Fall
Brawl'' pay-per-view, which suffered from the the same symptoms as
other WCW efforts lately. Slow ticket sales and weak story lines
were rumored. For years ``Fall Brawl'' has featured War Games, a
trio of concurrent tag-team matches, but not this year _ perhaps a
factor of a lack of story lines to support the action.
</P>
<P>
   The pinnacle for Bischoff and WCW began in 1996. Bischoff made a
bold move by signing two of the WWF's biggest stars _ Kevin Nash
and Scott Hall. Nash, Hall and Hogan formed a new organization _
the New World Order _ that battled the WCW stars. The new group was
a phenomenon and made ``Nitro'' and WCW pay-per-views the most
popular wrestling shows.
</P>
<P>
   After a year, the WWF hit back, signing some smaller WCW stars
and including more sex and violence in its story lines. The WWF
caught and passed the WCW in the Monday night television wars, then
grabbed a lot of the merchandising and pay-per-view money.
Eventually the WWF doubled its ratings.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Bischoff got Hogan back in the ring, along with the
Hulkster character of the late '80s and early '90s. The results
were less than spectacular. Recent problems, including wrestlers
leaving the WCW fold and high-priced wrestlers who weren't
wrestling (such as Bret Hart, Hall and Nash), spelled the end for
Bischoff.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of his tenuous situation were reflected in a story line
that brought Bischoff into the ring this winter. According to the
story line, he lost control of the WCW to Ric Flair and had been
scheming to regain the reins. Reality has intruded, and Bischoff's
fate is sealed, both in the ring and in reality.
</P>
<P>
   So where does WCW go now? Expect a lot of changes.
</P>
<P>
   In the ring, Sunday night's heel turn of Sting, the WCW's
constant face, was a dramatic and popular move. The return of Bret
Hart to the ring to join Hulk Hogan is also interesting.
</P>
<P>
   For Busch's part, he's 35 with a finance degree from Louisiana
State University. He reportedly has a reputation for the bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
