<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARTRAND MADE IMPACT IN EXHIBITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ When they are growing up and dreaming of
reaching the NHL, players don't dream of such unglamorous roles as
checking forward or defensive specialist.
</P>
<P>
   But as he sized up his chances of reaching the big-time, Brad
Chartrand realized he wasn't going to fool anyone into thinking he
was the next Jaromir Jagr, Pavel Bure or Paul Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 24-year-old Chartrand is trying to make the Los
Angeles Kings as center on the team's third line, the ``stopper''
unit, to borrow the terminology used by coach Andy Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Chartrand was more than a defensive specialist,
assisting on Garry Galley's overtime goal as the Kings beat the
Colorado Avalanche 3-2 before an announced crowd of 7,216 at the
Forum. The Kings improved to 2-0 in the exhibition season and
dropped the Avalanche to 0-2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, I look at myself as an underdog,'' Chartrand
said when asked to evaluate his chances of winning a spot on the
Kings' opening-night roster. ``At the same time, I think I've shown
the coaching staff that, `Wow, this kid is for real.' All you're
looking for is an opportunity and to try to seize the moment, and I
don't want to give them a reason to send me down.''
</P>
<P>
   The assist provided one more reason for the Kings to let
Chartrand stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good as a player,'' Chartrand said of the opportunity
he is getting to try to win a spot. ``It doesn't come without hard
work. That's what I try to stress in my game _ work ethic and
commitment to defense. When you do that, you get rewarded. I think
I earned the chance to be out there (in overtime).''
</P>
<P>
   Murray is well aware of Chartrand's abilities. Chartrand played
for Murray's Canadian national teams for two seasons, captaining
the squad in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   Chartrand said he's getting a much better chance to make the
Kings' roster than he got a year ago when he was in Toronto's camp.
On Murray's recommendation, the Kings signed him as a free agent
this summer after he spent last season with the Maple Leafs'
American Hockey League affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rule helps:With the teams testing the NHL's new 4-on-4
overtime rule, Galley scored the game-winner with five seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely opens up the ice,'' Galley said of the new rule.
``The league wants to see more wins and to make the game more
exciting for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rule, if the game had been played in the regular
season, the Kings would have gotten two points in the standings,
the Avalanche one for a regulation tie.
</P>
<P>
   __ Roster trims: The Kings assigned defensemen Trevor Gillies,
Richard Seeley and Kevin Bolibruck and right wing Kevin Baker to
their Lowell affiliate in the American Hockey League and sent left
wing Kip Brennan back to his junior team in the Ontario Hockey
League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
