<DOCNO> NYT19990915.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-FLA16-COX     09-15 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-FLA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floyd brushes by Florida
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Having spared Florida the full force of its
fury, Hurricane Floyd tore into the Carolinas early today, its
winds weakened but its destructive potential still formidable.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation from Floyd's path became the largest in peacetime
in U.S. history. Some 3.5 million people in four states have fled
the storm that now is on track for landfall between Charleston,
S.C. and Wilmington. At 10 p.m., the storm was about 120 miles
southwest of the line between the states and blowing at 115 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters warned that Floyd's huge area of influence, roughly
the size of Texas, could inflict damage far into the interior and
cause problems over a broad region. Washington, D.C., Mayor Anthony
Williams ordered public schools there closed because major flooding
is expected from the hurricane's outer bands. The rain could reach
into Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Floridians spent Wednesday counting their blessings and
recalling their hurricane experience for what did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression really is how fortunate we were as a state to
have had Floyd brush by us but not really impact us,'' Gov. Jeb
Bush said. ``By and large, it was pretty remarkable how close we
got to having serious, serious property damage and perhaps loss of
life. And yet it looks as though we escaped quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   The toll in Palm Beach County and along the Treasure Coast was
limited mostly to uprooted trees, power blackouts, beach erosion
and a half-dozen sunken sailboats off Peanut Island in Riviera
Beach. A wind gust on Hutchinson Island in Martin County was
clocked at 80 mph as Floyd scurried by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people don't think they've lived through a hurricane,''
said John Bonde, administrator of the Indian Trail Improvement
District in The Acreage. ``We've gotten afternoon storms worse than
this. Don't become complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd sideswiped the northern Florida coast Wednesday. A weather
buoy more than 20 miles off Cape Canaveral measured a 54-foot wave,
but Cape Kennedy NASA's space compound, with its four shuttles, was
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred miles off the Jacksonville coast, a tugboat sank
in 30-foot seas. Its eight crew members were rescued by the Coast
Guard and Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The thrashing ocean swallowed about 100 feet of the century-old
Daytona Beach pier and sheared off the end of the Jacksonville
Beach pier.
</P>
<P>
   Floridians prepared for their encounter with Floyd as they had
never done before. The Home Depot said it shipped 580,000 pieces of
plywood to Florida, 25 times the usual amount, on Monday and
Tuesday. Laid end-to-end, that's enough sheets to run from West
Palm Beach to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Along Interstate 10, rest stops became makeshift shelters where
motorists spent the night in their cars. The Salvation Army
provided breakfast to about 1,500 people at rest stops from
Tallahassee through the Panhandle. Traffic backed up 30 miles or
more as people headed inland from the east coast. One motorist
reported taking five hours for what usually is a 30-minute drive
across Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel rooms and many shelters were packed, leaving some people
with hours-long searching for a safe place.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's 15-year-old son, Jebbie, told his father it took him
eight hours to get from Jacksonville Beach, where he attends
private school, to Tallahassee. That's about twice as long as
normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave people enough advance notice and their lives were not
in jeopardy,'' Jeb Bush said. ``That's the most important thing.
They evacuated. There were lines. It took a while, but people got
out of harm's way. That's the ultimate objective here.''
</P>
<P>
   No fatalities or injuries have been attributed to Floyd in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The most compelling evidence of Floyd's power came from the
Bahamas where hundreds of wooden homes lost their roofs and dozens
of small boats were thrown onto the shore. Electricity and
telephones remained down throughout the 700-mile long archipelago
Wednesday. Despite the direct hit, no deaths there have been
confirmed, though one man is reported missing.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd's winds reached 150 mph on Abaco, Eleuthera, San Salvador
and Cat Islands, where damage was not yet assessed but feared
extensive.
</P>
<P>
   The mass exodus from the Carolinas left eerie scenes behind it
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate 26 into Charleston was dotted with empty vehicles,
cars that died or ran out of gas waiting to inch closer to safety
the night before.
</P>
<P>
   On talk radio, evacuees told of three-hour trips that took 14
hours instead. Frustrated travelers walked their dogs in the
median.
</P>
<P>
   Mayors from across the coast vented as well, angered that it
took so long for South Carolina Gov. Jim Hodges to turn the
interstate into a one-way exit.
</P>
<P>
   The last time South Carolina took a direct hit from a major
hurricane was almost exactly 10 years ago, when Hugo struck near
Charleston with 135 mph winds. The storm killed 29 people and
caused $5.9 billion in damage, the most costly hurricane to hit the
U.S. mainland until Hurricane Andrew hit Florida in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Florida and Georgia at this point feel like
they've dodged a real bullet,'' said North Carolina's Public Safety
Secretary Richard Moore. ``This thing is not going to miss us.''
</P>
<P>
   Myrtle Beach, a usually bustling resort, was a virtual ghost
town as people fled or stayed indoors, and highways were jammed
around Wilmington. In both Carolinas, many hurricane-hardened
people who rode out earlier storms left this time.
</P>
<P>
   Myrtle Beach authorities imposed a 3 p.m. curfew and turned off
the water supply. The hospital sent its patients inland but kept a
doctor and three nurses on emergency duty.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina officials banned price gouging on essential
items, threatening fines up to $100 or 30 days in jail.
</P>
<P>
   In Beaufort County, at South Carolina's southern tip, an
estimated 90 percent of its nearly 120,000 residents heeded the
call to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a tomb out here now,'' said Bud Boyne, a county
emergency spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina authorities issued evacuation orders for the
barrier islands outside Wilmington and for the Outer Banks, the
fragile line of islands that were battered by a lingering Hurricane
Dennis last week.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, hurrying back from New Zealand to deal with
the hurricane, pre-emptively declared federal disaster areas in
South Carolina and North Carolina. He had issued similar
declarations Tuesday for Florida and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've done everything we know to do,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney World remained closed Wednesday, the second day of
its first weather-related shutdown in its 28-year history. But
SeaWorld reopened and scheduled a ``Farewell to Floyd'' fireworks
show.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville, a sprawling city of 1 million, looked deserted
Wednesday morning, with funnel clouds visible and dark clouds
circling overhead. Three downtown bridges across the St. Johns
River were closed after a police car flipped over on one of them.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA Director James Lee Witt expected the unprecedented
evacuation to grow as the storm turns inland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot think of another evacuation that's on the scale of
this one, and as it moves up the coast there's going to be more
people displaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd's early strength had raised fears of a repeat of Hurricane
Andrew, which smashed into South Florida with 145 mph winds,
killing 26 people and causing an estimated $25 billion in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Sonja Isger, Jenny Staletovich, Joe Brogan, Brian
Crecente, Robert P. King, Eliot Kleinberg, Chuck McGinness, Susan
Spencer-Wendel and Julie Waresh, and the Associated Press
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
