<SLUG> BC-TEN-WILLIAMS-GIBSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERENA WILLIAMS HAS TIE TO A LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEIL AMDUR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even before she won the U.S. Open on Sunday, Serena Williams had
a connection to former tennis great Althea Gibson, the only other
African-American woman ever to win a Grand Slam singles title.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the 17-year-old Williams faxed Gibson a
letter with a list of questions for a school project.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very curious about Althea,'' said Fran Gray, Gibson's
spokeswoman, on Wednesday, as she fielded calls to discuss Gibson's
reaction to Williams' accomplishment. ``Serena has been kind of
curious and sought out common links with Althea. That gave us a
good feeling about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Venus Williams, Serena's older sister, recalled that
Gibson had been the ``back cover'' of a newsletter the girls had
published in connection with ``Black History Month'' earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the Williams sisters at the U.S. Open and the
semifinal showing of Alexandra Stevenson at Wimbledon earlier in
the summer have rekindled interest in Gibson, who won five Grand
Slam titles during her career before turning professional.
</P>
<P>
   A photo of Gibson appeared with American Express ads during this
year's Open, a fund-raiser in August for the Althea Gibson
Foundation was a financial success, and the first recipient of a
scholarship from the foundation was awarded this fall to Timi
Solomon, a black member of the tennis team at Fairleigh Dickinson
University.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, who lives in East Orange, N.J., recently celebrated her
72nd birthday, is alert, listens to music, watches television, is a
voracious reader and is paying attention to the new wave of
American women, who will play Russia in the Federation Cup final
this weekend in Palo Alto, Calif. But after a stroke several years
ago, she has withdrawn publicly and prefers to communicate through
her foundation and her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She followed what happened at the Open,'' Gray said of the
success of Venus and Serena Williams, who are now third and fourth,
respectively, in the tour rankings and pocketed $1.29 million from
the Open, including the women's doubles title. ``She's happy about
how well they did. It's kind of a relief, something we all wanted
to see, and we're hopeful that Serena will continue on.''
</P>
<P>
   The power-hitting style of the Williams sisters and Stevenson
was a trademark of Gibson when she became the first black to win
Wimbledon and U.S. singles titles (1957 and '58) after taking the
French championships in 1956. Gray said Jeanne Moutoussamy Ashe,
the widow of Arthur Ashe, phoned her and said that American Express
was interested in Gibson as part of an advertising campaign for the
Open that included past and present players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent me the original picture to approve,'' Gray said.
``The money from the ads was given to the Althea Gibson
Foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray, a co-founder of the foundation, said American Express,
Coca Cola, Johnson and Johnson, Ethicon, Public Service Electric &AMP;
Gas, PNC Bank, Florida A&AMP;M University, Summit Bank and the U.S.
Tennis Association were major contributors to the Gibson
fund-raiser, which grossed $83,000.
</P>
<P>
   Besides scholarships, the foundation is involved with urban
tennis and golf programs and is developing a mentoring program for
former athletes to link up with urban youth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
