<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOYA-TRINIDAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDADS, FATHER AND SON, PREPARE FOR DE LA HOYA BOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Felix Trinidad Jr. has been here for almost two
weeks, training for his welterweight showdown against Oscar De La
Hoya on Saturday night. He has not been seduced by neon lights or
tempted by casinos. Don Felix Trinidad, his father and trainer, has
made sure there are no distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad spends his time either in the gym, working out in
private, or in his hotel suite, which has a pool table,
video-arcade games and two large-screen televisions. The elder
Trinidad says his son's priority is training, not giving
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's scared,'' said Trinidad's promoter, Don King, of Don
Felix. ``Tito is his whole life and future in boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere here has the electric charge of a heavyweight
championship bout. With TVKO projecting close to a million buys,
and the Mandalay Bay Casino's 12,000-seat arena sold out (a $14
million gate), it could be the richest nonheavyweight championship
bout in history. Each fighter is guaranteed to draw the largest
paycheck of his career. Trinidad (35-0), the IBF champion, will
earn $8.5 million and De La Hoya (31-0), the WBC champion, $15
million.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, at the final news conference before the bout,
Trinidad appeared loose and confident. He plans to knock De La Hoya
out. ``We feel he is over-popularized,'' Trinidad said. ``I'm going
to put him at the level we feel he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Felix does not share his son's bravado, though he predicts a
sixth- round knockout over De La Hoya. He is wary of those not in
his inner circle. As Trinidad faced reporters, Don Felix sat
nearby, along with an interpreter. Occasionally, when questions
were asked of Trinidad his father would whisper answers that his
son would repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the bout nears, De La Hoya paranoia has creeped into the
Trinidad camp. Concerned about the possibility of De La Hoya spies,
Don Felix has closed all of Trinidad's workouts. Trinidad's
training center is in a resort 45 miles from here. His workouts
took place in an open tent. But it was several yards from public
view.
</P>
<P>
   The media-savvy De La Hoya, who fights here so often that it
could be considered a hometown fight, is accustomed to the madness.
Trinidad, who loves nothing more than spending time with his family
and raising horses at his home in Cupey Alto, Puerto Rico, is not
used to the crush. And Don Felix doesn't want to use this occasion
to learn whether Trinidad will like it.
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest fight of Trinidad's career, the elder Trinidad is
merely doing what he thinks is best for his son. But as a trainer
and manager, is he doing what is best for his fighter? No one will
know until fight night. Typically, father and son relationships in
boxing are full of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday afternoon, De La Hoya talked about his
strained relationship with his father, Joel. De La Hoya said he had
always sought the approval of his father in the ring, but his
father had never given it to him. During his three months of
training at Big Bear, De La Hoya was visited three times by his
father and each time Joel showed up, De La Hoya cringed.
</P>
<P>
   Joel De La Hoya did praise his son's workouts, telling the
trainer Robert Alcazar that it is the best shape he has ever seen
his son in. ``I read it in the newspaper,'' De La Hoya said. ``I
want to hear it from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad says he doesn't have problems getting approval from his
father and that their personal and working relationship is fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is the first one to teach me to throw my first
punch, and the second and the third and every punch that I am
throwing today,'' Trinidad said. ``As my father, my manager and my
trainer, he has to be with me. After Sept. 18 we will celebrate
together.''
</P>
<P>
   While De La Hoya will carry the weight of expectations from his
promoter, Bob Arum, and his many sponsors, Trinidad will be
carrying the weight of all of Puerto Rico. Parishioners have been
asked to light candles at their churches for him on fight night. In
four of Puerto Rico's 32 prisons, 1,600 inmates will watch the
fight on pay-per-view television as a reward for good behavior.
Baseball games in a season-ending tournament have been postponed
because they conflict with fight night.
</P>
<P>
   A victory over De La Hoya could catapult Trinidad into the
position of being more popular than other former Puerto Rican
champions like Wilfredo Gomez and Wilfredo Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   ``No pressure,'' Trinidad said of the weight he bears heading
into the ring on Saturday night. ``It makes me more happy to be
representing all of Puerto Rico.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
