<SLUG> BC-WALMART-PHARMACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICY ON PRESCRIPTION ORDERS AT WAL-MART DRAWS PRAISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that was praised by a family planning organization,
Wal-Mart Stores Inc. recently instructed its pharmacists to fill
all prescriptions or refer customers to another store if they had
an objection about dispensing a drug.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores, one of the nation's leading sellers of
prescription drugs, was criticized by Planned Parenthood in May for
not carrying Preven, a high-dose birth control medication to
prevent pregnancy up to 72 hours after unprotected sex. It was
approved for sale in the United States last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Wal-Mart still refuses to sell Preven, Planned
Parenthood was encouraged by the company's missive to its
pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this, the pharmacists won't unload his or her religious
beliefs on their customers,'' said Alexander Sanger, president of
Planned Parenthood of New York City. ``When customers come in to
get emergency contraceptives, either the pharmacy must fill it or
refer them to another store, even if it's to a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wal-Mart stressing compliance from its pharmacists,
proponents of emergency contraception hope that the company will
reconsider its decision not to carry Preven and will eventually
carry a recently approved similar product called Plan B.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that Wal-Mart will stock Preven and Plan B,'' said
Sanger. ``We hope this policy may make them re-evaluate their
business decision. Hopefully, we won't have to fight this battle
every time a contraceptive comes on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Planned Parenthood was encouraged by Wal-Mart's
pharmacy policy, the company expressed confusion about the
attention it was getting. Jessica Moser, a Wal-Mart spokeswoman,
said Wednesday that the company's pharmacists had operated under
that policy for several years and that it was reaffirmed as part of
a routine employee meeting in August. Wal-Mart's pharmacy business
trails only CVS, Walgreen, Eckerd and Rite Aid, according to Drug
Store News.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moser also noted that doctors sometimes prescribed birth
control pills at higher doses that may work as emergency
contraceptives and that Wal-Mart pharmacists had always filled
those prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to figure out what the news is here,'' Ms.
Moser said. ``As far as we're concerned, there wasn't any.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has yet to make a decision on whether to carry Plan B,
Ms. Moser said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
