<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYTAG-REALIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARS OF PROFIT SLOWDOWN STIR MAYTAG TO REVAMPING
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Iowa)  (nk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just days after its shares plummeted on fears of a profit
slowdown, the Maytag Corp. said it would realign its divisions,
sharply cut costs and try to shore up flagging sales of its
discount appliances.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of spectacular growth, Maytag executives say
the company is now grappling with eroding market share for its
discount products, such as the Magic Chef refrigerator, and a
slowdown in the sales of its new Gemini ovens, despite evidence
that the economy remains healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd D. Ward, the chairman and chief executive of Maytag, said
in a conference call Wednesday with Wall Street analysts that the
company would cut more than $100 million in costs over the next two
years, develop an electronic commerce strategy, and expand into
international markets, where it has just a small presence now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The realignment will make us faster, smarter and better at
innovation,'' Ward said, referring to a plan to create four
divisions in the hopes of strengthening the company's marketing and
brand strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Maytag rose 43.75 cents, to $38.375, on the New York
Stock Exchange after dropping more than 40 percent in the last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said that although the company seemed to be
addressing its problems, company executives offered few specifics
and did not fully explain how they planned to turn around a
business whose growth is slowing at a time when competitors like
Whirlpool are gaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are confused. There's a lot of uncertainty out
there,'' said Justin Maurer, an analyst at McDonald Investments.
``I think we all have to get a sense of what this redesigned end of
the strategy is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiatives come just days after Maytag, which is based in
Newton, Iowa, surprised Wall Street by warning that third- and
fourth-quarter profits would be flat from a year ago, disappointing
analysts who had expected another season of double digit profits.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn was largely attributed to eroding market share in
the company's sale of low-end or discount ovens, washing machines
and refrigerators, an area Maytag had once all but ignored in favor
of upgrading its more sophisticated, higher-priced products. Now,
the company says it needs to recapture market share in the low-end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing an erosion of the value brands and quite frankly
at a slightly increased pace,'' Ward said. ``But we will not
concede value brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Maytag made the announcement last Friday, its stock
had plunged in heavy trading, suggesting that some large investors
had received advance notice of the company's downturn, though the
company strongly denies that anyone was tipped off. Few insiders at
Maytag have sold stock in recent months, though Leonard A. Hadley,
the former chief executive who recently stepped down, sold about
20,000 shares, or about 10 percent of his holdings, worth $1.7
million in April, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. Wall
Street analysts, who had been assured on Sept. 9 that everything
was fine, were shocked to learn early Friday of the company's
turnabout. Several analysts said that the company failed to give
them adequate or timely notice, but Ward said Wednesday that his
first obligation was to the company.
</P>
<P>
   When an analyst asked Ward about the timing of the announcement,
he replied: ``Our job is not to report, but to try and mitigate
that _ not to give guidance to analysts.''
</P>
<P>
   Maytag has also come under fire from some analysts who have
questioned its recent accounting practices. Nicholas P. Heymann, an
analyst at Prudential and a former auditor, issued a report this
week that said that Maytag executives appear to have overstated
their sales projections and understated overhead costs in the first
half of the year. The result was that earnings in the first half of
the year appeared more robust, while second half of the year
adjustments appear to have hurt profits.
</P>
<P>
   Ward did not fully address accounting issues Wednesday, but said
the company's financial practices were sound. ``I am confident with
our internal controls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To regain its footing, Ward said that Maytag would become a
leaner operation, cutting about $100 million in costs, and then
re-investing much of that money in ``innovative'' products and
strategies. He said the company would also create a more flexible
system so that inventory doesn't build up the way it has recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
