<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-REPLAY-NETWORKS-NY     09-15 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REPLAY-NETWORKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPLAY NETWORKS TO APPOINT EX-CBS PROGRAMMER AS CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officials at Replay Networks Inc., a company offering a new
video recording device that some analysts believe will
revolutionize the way viewers watch television, said it would name
Kim LeMasters, a former chief programmer for CBS, as its chairman
and chief executive Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Replay, of Palo Alto, Calif., is one of two companies offering
the device; the other is Tivo Inc., of Sunnyvale, Calif. The
appointment of LeMasters, perhaps best known for scheduling
``Murphy Brown'' on CBS, underscores how closely the two new
companies are associating themselves with long-established entities
in the TV industry.
</P>
<P>
   Replay executive vice president Layne Britton said, ``The hiring
of Kim reflects our continuing evolution into becoming a
broadcasting company that will support existing broadcasters and
media companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Replay and Tivo have created electronic recorders not unlike
videocassette recorders except that they use digital compression
and videodiscs to create much greater capacity and flexibility in
recording and watching television shows.
</P>
<P>
   With these devices, called personal video recorders, viewers can
store many hours of programs, delivered overnight to programming
guides on the machines, making it possible to create personal menus
of shows _ for example, mysteries, ``Seinfeld'' reruns, old war
movies.
</P>
<P>
   The machines also make it possible to pause and rewind programs
that are being broadcast live, and to replay part of a show while
the rest of it is still being recorded.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several months, Replay and Tivo have secured
partnerships with companies that own networks and production
studios. Tivo has made deals with CBS, NBC, Discovery Networks and
News Corp.; last week, it said that Sony Corp. of America will
manufacture its machines. Sony also made clear its intention to use
the Tivo platform to promote its movies and television shows.
</P>
<P>
   Replay has made partnership deals with Time Warner, Walt Disney,
NBC, Showtime Networks and Liberty Media, among others. Kevin
Bohren, a member of Replay's board, said, ``As we have added these
organizations as investors, we have come to realize we need a
different set of skills, more than just hardware skills. We have to
be able to serve the entertainment community. The bottom line is
we're in the entertainment business.''
</P>
<P>
   Replay and Tivo have assured partners like the networks that
they do not intend to steal advertisers or make it easy to
eliminate commercials from recordings, though both devices can
accomplish that.
</P>
<P>
   Several senior television executives who have used the machines
have said that if they achieve significant penetration in
households, they could drastically alter the way TV is watched
because of the increased freedom to watch favored shows whenever a
viewer wants to instead of merely when a network broadcasts them.
</P>
<P>
   Replay turned to LeMasters, Bohren said, because of his
programming background, his relationships with many entertainment
companies, and what Bohren called ``his vision for what we might be
able to do in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   LeMasters said he would work closely with Replay's
entertainment-industry investors to devise schedule formats for
Replay that ``best serve the needs of our partners.''
</P>
<P>
   LeMasters said his first priority would be ``getting the machine
into the hands of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that Replay had selected him based on his
experience in TV programming. ``Down the line there are some
exciting possibilities from programming formats that we maybe could
do without displacing any of our partners.''
</P>
<P>
   LeMasters worked as CBS' chief programmer at a low point for
that network, taking the job just as many hit shows began to
collapse. The network was third in the ratings when he was forced
out in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling those days, LeMasters said, ``One other thing I think
I bring to this job: After the gunfire I was under at CBS, it'll be
real hard to panic me.''
</P>
<P>
   After he left CBS, LeMasters formed his own production company.
In 1992, he took a job as president of Stephen J. Cannell
Productions, a TV production company. After that company was sold
in 1995 to New World Television, he pursued a goal of becoming a
writer himself, taking charge of the USA Network cable drama series
``Silk Stalkings,'' on which he served as both executive producer
and head writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
