<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-FASHION-I-ART-NYT &LR;      09-15 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-I-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WOMEN DRESS GIRLISH AND GIRLS DRESS SULTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long before there ever was a television show called
``Sex and the City,'' Nicole Miller seemed to exist for the woman
who had written the script for it in her head.
</P>
<P>
   Such a woman may never have come into contact with an
heirloom-tomato salad or a man who owned half of Anguilla, but she
dreamed of the life. In a glaring I-won't-let-you-forget-me Miller
print, perhaps she would have a shot at attaining it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller showed her spring collection on Tuesday, hours before
Cynthia Rowley, whose clothes have always been intended for a far
less manipulative approach to love and mating. At the end of the
day, though, there seemed to be little difference in the kind of
life styles both women were now serving up.
</P>
<P>
   The 1950s-inspired silk print and ruffled dresses, the white
daisy organza blouses, the knee-length beaded skirts _ nearly
everything that Ms. Miller sent down her runway would not have
seemed out of place later, in the ballroom of the New Yorker Hotel,
where Ms. Rowley unveiled her line.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller's clothes now seem to be meant for dates that end
long before breakfast. They are clothes without a big agenda, just
a stitch or two short of being mundane.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rowley, on the other hand, generally seems incapable of the
mundane. She trotted out a pair of white-haired ballroom dancers
before she got down to the business of sending out models in floral
embroidered snakeskin dresses, printed cashmere sweaters, pajama
pants and for the finale, little dresses that appeared to be
lighted from the inside by Christmas lights. In fact, they were
model-train lights, and Ms. Rowley intends to sell these garments
despite the problem of overheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I was thinking,'' she joked after the show.
Nothing ever seems to shake Ms. Rowley's love of romance. It's
almost disorienting to attend one of her shows knowing that outside
there are movies with titles like ``Love Stinks'' playing.
</P>
<P>
   An appreciation for things innocent would certainly have been
welcome at the Girls Rule show, which featured the work of five
different labels, all aimed at teen-agers. One outfit consisted of
a tiger-print miniskirt over tight crocheted pants with a
midriff-bearing top.
</P>
<P>
   It was called Heavenly Harlot, presumably not something one
would put on for a Vassar interview. More significantly, it's
unlike anything that would even be seen on ``Dawson's Creek,'' the
mirror of teen-age life.
</P>
<P>
   The collection had a fair number of actual teen-agers attending,
and one didn't know what to make of the fact that in the front row
a small child, years away from getting into ``Cruel Intentions,''
kept whispering ``I like it'' every time something in parachute
cloth went by. Shouldn't she have been wondering why nothing had a
Furby on it?
</P>
<P>
   The Jeffrey Lee show seemed absent of such style mavens. Held in
a small room at St. Bartholomew's Church on Park Avenue, it didn't
attract the fashion editors' sorority. Not a pony-skin handbag or
Jimmy Cho shoe was in sight. In a sense those who missed, missed
out.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is not a New Yorker; he lives in Dallas, so perhaps he
hasn't mastered the art of getting plugged in.
</P>
<P>
   He's mastered other things though. He turned out rough,
full-length wool skirts, all in white and beige. He used belts and
armbands of blond wood. At times the models looked as though they
were standing inside a sake box, but Lee did manage to present a
collection that didn't resemble anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   There was a stark beauty to his clothes that transcended the use
of rather unusual accessories. Would a woman, even an artist, ever
go to dinner in a strapless dress with a corset and wooden side
pockets? Probably not, but she'd be memorable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
