<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLS' LEWIS IS BACK AND READY FOR GATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Tee Martin doesn't remember his teammate
Jamal Lewis' standing on the Fiesta Bowl sideline last January as
the pink skies of Arizona turned black. He doesn't remember
uttering a word to him in the bowels of Sun Devil Stadium in the
jubilant hours after his team captured a national title.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, the Tennessee quarterback, is embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled and confessed the other day that he never gave a
thought to Lewis on the night the Volunteers beat Florida State,
23-16, to cap a perfect 13-0 season. ``Now I think about him all
the time,'' Martin said sheepishly. ``I hear him in the huddle. I
watch him blow through holes. It's real comfortable having him back
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, Tennessee's 6-foot, 225-pound running back, shrugs off
the Fiesta Bowl oversight. Yes, he was there _ in street clothes,
because he had torn the lateral collateral ligament in his right
knee in the fourth game of the Vols' championship season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long, boring, tiresome,'' is how Lewis remembers his spring
and summer of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty good start,'' he said recently, referring to
his freshman season in 1997, in which he gained 1,364 yards and
averaged 5.9 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Martin remembers and appreciates him, Lewis gets a
chance to reintroduce himself to the nation and to the Florida
Gators (2-0) on Saturday, when Tennessee (1-0) travels to
Gainesville and a raucous stadium known as the Swamp, where they
haven't won since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunshine State has sent more than Hurricane Floyd to other
regions in the South, as some Gators, befitting a bitter rivalry,
have unleashed high winds of insults through the newspapers. Most
have been of the weak tropical storm variety.
</P>
<P>
   Florida coach Steve Spurrier, of course, made the most stinging
dig at the Vols by pointing out that his No. 4-ranked Gators were
favored over the No. 2-ranked defending national champions.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis isn't biting after hearing all the insults. He prefers the
dramatic gesture over words. In the preseason, he asked coach
Phillip Fulmer to list him third on the depth chart behind Travis
Henry and Travis Stephens, who combined for 1,447 yards last year
in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to come in and take something,'' Lewis explained.
``I want to earn it. They played great last year and helped get us
a championship. I wanted to keep it in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Tennessee opened the season two weeks ago with a
42-17 victory over Wyoming, however, Lewis was the lead tailback.
He had 159 yards and three touchdowns, reaching 2,000 yards in his
17th game _ faster than any Volunteer in school history.
</P>
<P>
   His return has emboldened the already confident Martin to try to
out-Gator the Gators and predict a victory. With the Tennessee
legend of Peyton Manning all but buried by Martin's undefeated
record (14-0) as a starter, Martin has turned into a steady
metronome that keeps a better beat than Tennessee's unofficial
anthem, ``Rocky Top.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Wyoming here, Martin was 14 of 21 for 264 yards, threw
two touchdowns and ran for 36 yards to account for nearly 60
percent of Tennessee's 522 yards. In his last 200 pass attempts, he
has thrown only two interceptions and has become the Tony Robbins
of his team's success-breeds-success mantra, which they vow will
carry them to another championship.
</P>
<P>
   Martin led the Volunteers through informal summer workouts. He
reminded his teammates that he was a better quarterback and that
they were a better team than last year. In the weight room, or on
the track for sprints, he kept reminding them that last season was
a gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miles; I've come miles,'' Martin said. ``Last year, I felt
like I was the caboose, and the rest of the offense was the train
in front of me. And believe it or not, we are hungrier than we were
last year. We weren't supposed to win the title. We were replacing
12 guys and this was supposed to be our year. I'm telling you we
haven't skipped a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers were supposed to have a weak receiving corps with
the departure of Peerless Price to the National Football League.
But in the opener, Cedrick Wilson caught seven passes for 183 yards
and two touchdowns. Their defense was supposed to be leaderless
with the departure of linebacker Al Wilson, yet they held Wyoming
to just 203 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful motivation Martin has ticked off for his team
is the one most familiar to each and every Volunteer: they get no
respect. The national championship has been conceded to Florida
State. He and Lewis are merely long shot Heisman Trophy candidates.
No preseason poll gave the Vols a shot to join Nebraska and become
the second team in 19 years to repeat as national champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're flukes,'' Martin said, repeating what the naysayers have
said about his team. ``Last year was a fluke. We've heard it every
way. But the thing I know and my teammates know is that once the
game starts, everything said in interviews and all the trash talk
is forgotten. The final score counts. And I like our record
there.''
</P>
<P>
   If it holds, Martin will have something to say to Lewis this
January at the Sugar Bowl in New Orleans. His running back would
like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``By then people should know that I'm back,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
