<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAP ON THE FIELD? PHELAN STEPS IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Senior Matt Phelan is the Mr. Fix-it of UCLA's
offensive line. Suspension at left guard? No problem. Fatigue at
center? Got it covered. Injury at right guard? He's there.
</P>
<P>
   Phelan, a senior from Leona Valley, has played every offensive
line position but left tackle, and Saturday he'll make his third
start of the season at his second position.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always been my role,'' he said. ``I pride myself on
being a renaissance lineman. I like knowing what everyone's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelan played sparingly for three years and doesn't foresee an
NFL career, but his talent (i.e., versatility) has been critical
this season. He started two games at left guard for the suspended
Oscar Cabrera and now he's sliding to right guard for the injured
Mike Saffer. In previous seasons, he also played right tackle and
center.
</P>
<P>
   Although Phelan's favorite position is center _ ``It appeals to
the intelligent side,'' he said _ he isn't complaining about his
current role. With nine (or 10) games left in his career, he's
happy to be on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' he said. ``It's the first time I've been in
the rotation legitimately. I come to practice and I know I'm going
to start or play a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   __ How they stand: The Bruins lost one lineman and gained two
this week with Saffer's sprained ankle _ he's out 2-4 weeks _ and
the return of Cabrera and Jim Ghezzi. The shuffle leaves them with
10 healthy linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Polak and Blake Worley are the starting tackles, with
Micah Webb and true freshman Bryce Bohlander in reserve. Cabrera
and Phelan are the starting guards, with Ghezzi and Ed Anderson off
the bench. (Saffer will start for Phelan when he returns.) Troy
Danoff and reserve Tony Ippolito are the centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tackles are all right,'' coach Bob Toledo said. ``We're
struggling at guard.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Defensive tackle Pete Holland might not play
Saturday because of lower-back pain. Anthony Fletcher will start in
his place.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Danny Farmer tweaked his sprained left ankle making a
cut _ his cleat got caught in the dirt _ and is questionable for
the Fresno State game. There's growing concern at Spaulding Field
that Farmer won't be at full strength all season. Such is the
nature of high (above the ankle bone) sprains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to go on forever,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Clamping down: The Bruins were more concerned with Ohio
State's running game than its passing attack. As a result, they
committed eight defenders to the line of scrimmage and had their
cornerbacks play a few yards off the receivers. The Buckeyes
responded with a slew of short sideline passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think their quarterbacks were good enough to beat
us,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins won't give Fresno State's receivers the same cushion
this week. Freshman cornerbacks Ricky Manning Jr. and Joe Hunter
will play tight man-to-man against Rodney Wright and Charles Smith
in what should be the best matchup of the game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Taken aback: Safety Ryan Roques said his father, Burnell,
received a piece of hate mail after Roques was charged in the
disabled-parking scam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `What is this?' I wasn't expecting anything like
that,'' Roques said. ``Whoever sent it, I guess their kids have
never sinned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
