<HEADLINE>
LOAIZA EXCELS FOR RANGERS IN VICTORY OVER TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The only berths guaranteed in the Rangers'
rotation if they reach the playoffs belong to Rick Helling and
Aaron Sele, manager Johnny Oates has said.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be long before Oates guarantees a third.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won for the eighth time in Esteban Loaiza's past 11
starts, and the pitcher's doghouse-to-penthouse season continued
with yesterday's 8-3 victory against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza held the Twins to three runs (two earned) 6 1/3 innings,
and Roberto Kelly and Rafael Palmeiro supplied the offensive
firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly drove in four runs with the fifth two-homer game of his
career, and Palmeiro ensured the victory with his three-run,
opposite-field homer off Brad Radke (12-14) in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Rangers a 12-game, season sweep of the
Twins and reduced their magic number to 10. The Rangers would
capture their third American League West title in four years with
any combination of their victories and/or losses by second-place
Oakland that total 10.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Rangers can begin to discuss their postseason plans
without disclaimers such as ``if we make the make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza (8-4) continued to make a case for his inclusion in the
postseason rotation by allowing only six hits and one walk, and
only a two-run, seventh-inning homer by Terry Steinbach marred his
latest performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw the ball very well,'' Oates said. ``He threw some
fastballs by people. He had a little giddy-up out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza is 7-3 with a 3.62 earned-run average in 11 starts since
joining the rotation July 24, but thoughts of starting in the
postseason remain the furthest thing from his mind, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to finish the season strong and keep
winning,'' he said. ``I'm not really thinking about anything else.
I just want to keep performing the way I'm performing and continue
to throw the ball the way I'm throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's seventh-inning home run gave the Rangers a 6-1 lead
and gave Palmeiro a personal-best 44th home run. Oates
congratulated Palmeiro after the home run, and the left-handed
power hitter responded in typical fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not finished yet,'' Palmeiro told Oates. ``We've still
got work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's afternoon kept him in contention for a Triple Crown
season. Palmeiro entered yesterday's games ranked no worse than
fourth in batting average, home runs and runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wins the Triple Crown, we've got a pretty good chance of
winning this division,'' Oates said. ``I'd love for him to win the
Triple Crown. Raffy has had a very special year.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
