<HEADLINE>
HOW TO HELP HANDLE THE AFTERMATH OF VIOLENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KRISTIN N. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As survivors of Wednesday's Fort Worth
church shooting gathered and grieved, a cadre of counselors,
psychologists and ministers prepared to guide witnesses through the
stress of witnessing violence firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   Experts who have counseled survivors of shootings from
Jonesboro, Ark., to Littleton, Colo., have said those victims may
suffer post-traumatic stress disorder, an affliction more commonly
associated with shell-shocked soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Stress disorder symptoms include flashbacks, nightmares and
intrusive images of the event that may flood back. Survivors also
may feel anxiety. Victims can become alternately withdrawn and
aggressive in the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Adults may react to traumatic events by becoming overprotective
of their children and fearful. People may also feel intense anger,
fear that they have lost control, hurt and guilt, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists and counselors have recommended these strategies
to help young people deal with the trauma that follows violence.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to their fears. Encourage them to talk openly about them,
mental health professionals said Wednesday. Kids respond better
when they're heard first. Family therapists recommend starting by
asking children, ``What do you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Reassure children who are afraid and let them know that their
feelings are normal. Counselors say that it is common for children
to react to such a situation by becoming worried that they could be
harmed at a place they once considered safe. Parents should stay
calm and let children talk through their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   If possible, parents should shield their children from traumatic
news, because it is frightening. But if children do hear about it
from friends or on television, do not try to sweep the subject
under the rug. Parents should encourage the children to talk about
what frightens them by asking questions such as, ``What do you
think about that?'' or telling them, ``That scares me; tell me what
you think?''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
