<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS COACH HOLDING FIRM WHEN BUMPING EGOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chan Gailey did it first with Emmitt Smith, and he did it next
with Michael Irvin. Frankly, I wondered with each case if Gailey
hadn't bumped up against something that would either bump him back
or even knock him down.
</P>
<P>
   That ``something'' would be defined in many ways, including
massive egos, Hall-of-Fame credentials, Lombardi trophies,
worldwide household sports names and local legends. Gailey had
bumped up against all that.
</P>
<P>
   An Emmitt or an Irvin represents all of the above. Better yet,
those two ``earned'' the right to have their names represent all of
the above.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the reputations of Emmitt and Michael, not to
mention Troy and Deion, and yes, Mr. Jerry Jones himself, it was 19
months ago when Gailey came to Valley Ranch as Coach Nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Chan was Jones' handpicked man. So, of course, was Gunsmoke
Switzer, meaning there was ample room for error in Jerry's judgment
of what was best for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   There is no tougher coaching/managerial job in America at any
sport at any level. That includes managing the Yankees for George
Steinbrenner, which is a close second. This is the toughest because
of Jones, because of recent world championships, because of the
aging core of high profile players remaining from the title teams,
because of the absolute mess Gunsmoke left behind, because of the
poor drafts in the mid-90s, because most of the fandom is waiting
on the next Jimmy Johnson, and mainly because the Cowboys ain't
even close to what they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, as we've learned, is not the next Jimmy Johnson, nor
does he strive to be, except for the part about being the architect
of a Super Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   But like Jimmy, Gailey is tough. A totally different kind of
tough, but still ...
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Gailey tells Emmitt there will be a change in the
way he had been used. The very last thing Emmitt wanted was to be
used less. Enter Chris Warren. There would be less carries for
Emmitt.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who says today they didn't believe Emmitt was a running
back in total decline, well, he or she is lying. But Emmitt bounced
back with a huge season in 1998, even though Warren ended up
injured. Whatever, that was a renewed Emmitt last season, and there
is no sign thus far of that changing.
</P>
<P>
   For this season, it was Irvin, a true football warrior, who got
the Gailey ``treatment.'' Fewer snaps for Michael will equal more
production, believed the coach. And such was the case last week
against Washington _ fewer snaps, more production from Irvin, who
yapped-yapped-yapped about it, but did-did-did it.
</P>
<P>
   And Gailey will be doing it again this week, and next week, and
every week. But without even a hint of ``I am the coach''
chest-pounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tough? What is a tough coach? Define that for me,'' Gailey
said yesterday at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   OK, how about Lombardi, how about the Jimster, how about
Parcells?
</P>
<P>
   ``You still haven't defined tough for me,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   And then Gailey explained that bumping up against all that
``something'' was not what he had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only about me making decisions I consider best for the
team,'' Gailey said. ``But when it involves individual careers,
then I want those players personally involved in the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if there's a total disagreement by players with the
stature of Emmitt or Irvin?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we will continue to have discussions until there is a
common ground. It becomes my fault if there can't be a common
ground because I didn't do a good enough job selling the player on
what is best for the team,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   The answer from my man The Jimster would have been a smile and a
wink, signifying the tough-coach code of ``My way or the highway.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not Gailey's style, obviously. But once he charts a
course, and once the ship sets sail, then it becomes Gailey's boat.
</P>
<P>
   About his off-season conversation with Gailey: ``I didn't agree
or disagree at the time,'' Irvin said yesterday. ``I didn't know
what to think.''
</P>
<P>
   At times in the Washington game, when his butt was on the bench,
Irvin knew what he was thinking, and it's not printable. But an
amazing comeback victory in which Irvin was a late fourth-quarter
star, meant Michael was a happy soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Lose a game under the same circumstances, or lose under any
other circumstances and, well, we'll see.
</P>
<P>
   But by now, we also know enough about Gailey to know he isn't
changing. He is the boss on a team in desperate need of a boss
because of Jerry's previous choice of human Jello to lead the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I found here are players willing to put the team at the
forefront,'' Gailey said. ``I found people willing to buy into the
team philosophy, and I don't mean 100 percent of the time _ no team
has that. But for the most part, it's true. And that's what will
eventually make it all work.''
</P>
<P>
   But everything has to start with a strong team leader on a team
of strong individuals. Until further notice, consider that the
strength of Chan Gailey.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
