<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS REUNION: MANY HAPPY RETURNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Suspended together, they suffered apart. UCLA
fullback Durell Price watched the Ohio State game with friends.
Linebacker Ryan Nece was with his family in San Bernardino. Guard
Oscar Cabrera barbequed with relatives at his home near the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Their emotions paralleled UCLA's performance _ first-quarter
thrills giving way to fourth-quarter reality, as the outmanned
Bruins wilted in Ohio Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurting inside,'' Price said. ``Those guys did a great
job, but depth was a problem. We were so thin in numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. The reinforcements have arrived.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's second season begins this week with a new quarterback
(Cory Paus) and the return of 10 players who served two-game
suspensions for the disabled-parking scam. Among them are six
starters and six seniors who will provide desperately needed
leadership. Together, they account for 13 percent of UCLA's roster
and a chunk of its spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're starting the season over,'' guard Matt Phelan
said. ``This is how it's supposed to be. It's how we imagined it
would be. A lot of our best players finally have a chance to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Assimilating the suspended players before Saturday's game
against Fresno State should not be difficult, either
psychologically or strategically. During a series of summer
meetings, the guilty players apologized to their teammates and
coaching staff. Captains Danny Farmer and Pete Holland accepted and
the matter was dropped. Incensed coach Bob Toledo also accepted the
apologies, but he banned the suspended players from contact with
the team during games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest moment for me was during the Boise State game,''
Nece said. ``I was in the stands, and at kickoff I felt separated
for the first time. It was the first time I felt divided from the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Although punished severely _ $1,485 fines, 200 hours of
community service, two-game suspensions and additional penalties by
the dean of students _ the guilty players were, in the end, allowed
to practice. They stayed in shape physically, they attended
meetings, learned new plays and refined fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   Once game preparation began, they were relegated to the dreaded
scout team, which mimics the opponent's offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it actually didn't suck,'' Price said. ``I just put
it in my mind that we were contributing to the team winning games.
When you're young, the scout team sucks. When you're older, you
realize you can help the young guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Had they been banned from practice, the suspended players would
have been a month behind their teammates. They'd have needed time
to get in shape and find their rhythm, time to adjust to contact
and familiarize themselves with the system. Instead, they were
ready for action Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people say, `Welcome back,' I want to say, `I never
left,' '' safety Ryan Roques said. ``I've been here the whole time.
I've been practicing with the team, doing everything I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Their impact will be greatest on defense. Roques, a senior,
takes over at the troublesome strong-safety position, where
sophomore Jason Stephens struggled. Nece, Robert Thomas and Tony
White replace an inexperienced group of linebackers. Safety Eric
Whitfield and linebacker Ali Abdul Azziz will bolster the depth.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, junior Oscar Cabrera returns to his starting spot at
left guard, and senior lineman Jim Ghezzi becomes the top reserve.
Price is the No. 1 fullback _ a move based on leadership as much as
talent _ and reserve tailback Keith Brown's return should give
weary starter DeShaun Foster some rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll make an immediate impact, whether it's because
the talent is back or the leadership and experience we're
gaining,'' Roques said. ``There will be an impact one way or
another.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence has energized the Bruins, who blamed fatigue and
a depleted roster, not talent, for the loss at Ohio State. The
numbers agree: The Bruins scored the first 14 points of the game
and scored the first points of the second half but were outscored
by a combined 42-3 in the remainder of the two halves.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a full roster, an influx of senior leadership and a
starting quarterback, their spirits are soaring. It's a new season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to a lot of the guys and they're still excited
despite that loss,'' Nece said. ``We're confident we can be a big
force in the Pac-10.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
