<HEADER>
A3930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-LEAKS-LAW-NYT &LR;      09-15 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LEAKS-LAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LEAKS AND THE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, Sept. 16: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court in Washington has ruled against undue
secrecy, and for the public's right to know, in a case arising from
the investigation by Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, of
President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky. The court
ruled that Starr's office did not violate the confidentiality of
grand jury proceedings by speaking to reporters about its own
internal deliberations over whether to indict Clinton. The decision
overturned an order by Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, the federal
trial judge who oversaw the grand jury that heard evidence about
the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was an article that appeared in The New York Times last
January, at the tail end of the impeachment trial in the Senate. It
reported that Starr had concluded that he had the constitutional
authority to seek a grand jury indictment of Clinton before he
leaves office in January 2001. The appellate panel did not say it
approved of any leaks of information or the timing of the article.
What the panel did say _ quite valuably _ is that grand jury
secrecy covers only those statements by prosecutors that
``directly'' reveal grand jury matters. The court's previous
decisions on grand jury secrecy, the panel said, were not meant to
require that a ``veil of secrecy be drawn over all matters
occurring in the world that happens to be investigated by a grand
jury.''
</P>
<P>
   This expansive approach to what prosecutors may discuss publicly
with reporters shows due respect for the tradition of openness in
American law and the strong public interest in having grand jury
rules that allow for informed debate of public issues. It is a
refreshing departure from the devotion to secrecy that saw the same
appeals court uphold press lockouts when Starr and the White House
sparred over executive privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's private lawyer, David Kendall, has indicated he plans
to appeal the latest ruling. But at this point it is hard to see
what Clinton stands to gain by seeking to overturn a sound decision
on grand jury secrecy _ except to add to his pile of unpaid legal
fees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-99 2353EDT &QL; 
