r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-OFFICI     09-15 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-OFFICIALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, OTHER OFFICIALS SHOCKED AT MULTIPLE SLAYINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER and JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Calling it a tragic event in a ``house of
hope and love,'' Texas Gov. George W. Bush, along with other
officials expressed shock and dismay at the multiple slayings in a
Fort Worth Baptist church Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr, in Toluca, Mexico, for a Sister
Cities event, said, ``We are prayerful for the individuals who have
been shot and their families, and mournful for the families of the
deceased.''
</P>
<P>
   But, added Barr, who was planning a hasty return to the city,
``this is Fort Worth, and we'll be united as a city in our strength
to see clear through the fog of this tragic criminal act.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in Detroit Wednesday campaigning for president, said
through a spokeswoman: ``This is a terrible tragedy, made worse by
the fact that it took place in a house of hope and love.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thoughts and prayers are with the victims, their families
and the congregation,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Some elected officials and gun control advocates called for a
review of the need for legislation to limit access to weapons and
possibly make it more difficult for such shootings to occur.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the shooting must have been done by some ``deranged
person,'' state Rep. Glenn Lewis, D-Fort Worth, said something must
be done about the proliferation of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The details are a little sketchy right now as to who did what
or why,'' Lewis said. ``Obviously, we need to curb the
proliferation of weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Texas Legislature convened earlier this year, Lewis
pre-filed a bill making it mandatory for any gun owner to have a
trigger lock when purchasing a gun. A similar bill is being
considered in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas lawmakers, who earlier in the decade passed
legislation allowing residents to carry concealed weapons if they
obtained qualification, did not look favorably on Lewis' proposal.
The Legislature did pass a bill this year protecting gun
manufacturers from lawsuits filed by local governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even get a hearing in committee,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   He challenged the notion put forward by advocates of a concealed
weapons law that allowing more people to carry weapons would reduce
crime. ``Obviously, that's not true,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Elfant, a Travis County constable and head of Austin-based
Texans Against Gun Violence, called the carnage the latest in what
has become ``a terrible year for high-profile shootings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know a lot more about this, like where he got the
gun and what his mental condition was,'' Elfant said. ``But one
thing we do know is that one of the things the Legislature did this
year was to take away the prohibition of guns in churches. Churches
are no place for guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of questions that need answers. Some of these
shootings by deranged people are never going to be prevented. But
we have to make sure that only law-abiding citizens have access to
guns.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barr urged caution, saying, ``I think we need to dedicate
ourselves to understanding the tragedy, and then to figuring out
how to make the changes to keep this from happeining again. It's
not unique to Fort Worth, but we can start in Fort Worth, and we
will.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
